DATA['2026'] = [{"title": "Magic Monday Returns", "url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/356936.html", "year": "2026", "month": "02", "day": "01", "time": "08-33PM", "comments": [{"id": "cmt58968904", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:00 am", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "Happy Imbolc!  I hope the holiday finds you and yours well.<br/><br/>Given your discussion of His Grace Kek and your examination of the Basement Brigade, I’m gonna step not very far out on a stout oak limb to suspect that you and the assembled wizardren are aware of a British meme goddess named Amelia.<br/><br/>She does seem potent, having been awarded epithets including, “Lionheart,” and “Rose of Albion.”  One standout meme reads, “Amelia, Queen of Albion, stand with me now!”<br/><br/>While the quality of her videos and music videos on YouTube makes me suspect someone is funding a little pot-stirring, they are sincere and consistent.  Also, one music video, “Amelia’s Dream,” on Music of Our Time at YouTube might hold something beyond the content creator’s intent since it features a standing stone, rooks and seagulls.<br/><br/>Technical stuff aside, I like her despite my Puritan and Patriot roots.  Assuming that the gamers might know about her here in the US, I asked one.  He said, “I’m a loyal Irishman, and I love her!”  Okay.  That’s not strange, not a bit…<br/><br/>But – I am left with a suspicion sneaking as quietly as a straight-piped bulldozer that, despite being a cartoon character who hits all the right Jungian symbols, there is something more afoot than an adorable waifu and some bumper-sticker sloganeering.  (That the Guardian is reduced to foaming aphasia in their denunciations of her may support the possibility of afoot-ness.)<br/><br/>So0O0o-ah – Who is Amelia and what is she really doing?<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58969672", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:19 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've been watching the saga of Amelia from the far side of the Atlantic in a state of utter bemusement. For those who don't know the first act of the saga, the British government had some collection of flacks create a video game for British kids, which was designed to elicit \"racist\" (that is, patriotic and un-woke) statements from them -- at which point the kids who fell for it would be reported to the police for, erm, reeducation. (I wish I was making this up.) Amelia was a cartoon figure who was supposed to mouth allegedly racist slogans, and they gave her violet hair because they thought that would annoy right-wingers, who make jokes about women with dyed hair. <br/><br/>Ponder the immeasurable stupidity of the flacks who put nationalist and patriotic slogans in the mouth of the kind of cute female figure who would have most teenage boys reaching into their trousers on the spot. Of course these same teenage boys instantly hijacked her and turned her into a mascot, just as they did with Kek back in the day. Of course these same teenage boys, being far more computer-skilled than government flacks, started doing LLM-generated videos of Amelia speaking out in favor of nationalist and patriotic ideas. Here's a still: <br/>[IMAGE:0]<br/>Of course everybody in Britain who's sick and tired of the Starmer government and its woke doctrines embraced Amelia as their latest heroine, not least because the Guardian's foam-flecked fury when she's mentioned is so entertaining to watch...<br/><br/>And then, as with Kek, things got weird. We're still in the early stages of the weirdening -- is that a word? It is now -- but it would not surprise me a bit to find that just as a cartoon frog ten years ago became the vessel through which an archaic Native American deity manifested and sent the US spinning down an uncharted path, a purple-haired waifu may just become another such vehicle. <br/><br/>Britain used to have quite a collection of war goddesses, back in Celtic times. I'm curious, not to mention apprehensive, to see just who's taking this opportunity to stream back into manifestation. ", "images": [{"url": "https://images.lbc.co.uk/images/787630?crop=16_9&width=660&relax=1&format=webp&signature=6a07IWaV0DEwF7LKguVqGKe9FKY=", "local_path": "./data/archive/2026/2026-02-01_08-33PM_Magic_Monday_Returns/images/2026-02-02_05_19_am_787630"}], "replies": [{"id": "cmt58969928", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:22 am", "user": "brenainn", "content": "I, for one, think we live in rather exciting times. The old gods are being reborn! It is awesome to witness.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58970952", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:32 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, they're definitely exciting. The problem is that once genuine spiritual powers begin to manifest, the boundary between excitement and carnage is not always easy to maintain.  \"Whom the gods would destroy, they first make mad\" -- and, er, there's been rather a lot of madness about of late. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58971464", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:42 am", "user": "brenainn", "content": "Yes, quite true. It seems that a lot of carnage is inevitable over the coming years and decades. That's the sense that I get, anyway.<br/><br/>Oddly, though, I just don't fear a lot anymore. One of the side effects of having the dead begin communicating with me has been a complete loss of fear of death. To paraphrase the divine Carl Jung just a bit, I no longer need to believe in an afterlife and the immortality of the spirit. I now know.<br/><br/>I do feel sorrow for those who will be suffering through this, though. One silver lining is that a lot of bad karma might be taken care for many folks in the coming years. Maybe.", "edit_time": "2026-02-02 05:44 am (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58971720", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:47 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, I get that. The last few whispers of any fear of death I had left -- and there wasn't much -- went away the morning after Sara's death, when I felt her wake up on the other side of things. We were close enough that we could quite often sense when the other was asleep or awake, and this was much the same -- just at a distance hard to measure in miles. <br/><br/>As for the carnage, granted, but it's still likely to be hideous to watch. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58981960", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 01:59 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "My late mother, who died in March of 2025, communicated with me in various, unexpected,  ways both in dream and waking: telling me that she is fine in the afterlife by way of a dream, and also when awake by means of a butterfly -  immemorial symbol of the soul -  and a honey bee, both I think 'astral' in your terms but decidedly real until their real nature was made clear. <br/><br/>Not fearing Death any longer,I know need to increase my courage to face what is going to befall us all on this plane....... ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58983496", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 02:34 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "All very traditional! I'm glad to hear this -- the death of someone you love is always difficult, and having contact with them from the other side is such a consolation.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59019080", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 07:32 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The death of my mother was a very great relief, as we were sadly estranged - I became aware of her fading and death through dreams before the news reached me -  but I was rather concerned about her fate.<br/><br/>Although not an atheist, she did not follow any religion, or occult practices, and greatly feared death, not least because of the possibility of meeting long-dead relations whom she had disliked when alive!<br/><br/>So these messages to the effect that she is perfectly happy, and also offering me advice as well as consolation (the bee- I had to meditate on that one!).<br/><br/>In return, I have sent her, regularly, thoughts of total forgiveness.<br/><br/>Like those who experienced the Mysteries of Eleusis, I now know there is nothing to fear and do not need belief or faith.  "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59041608", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 12:22 am", "user": "vivekgb", "content": "Thanks for explaining Amelia, despite living here in Britain I’d not heard of her yet! I am not that surprised though as it feels it’s been a long time coming.<br/><br/>Charles Hugh Smith recently had an essay about the Cultural Revolution and how labelling enemies of the people can get out of hand and lead to widespread killing. Thinking about that I can see why certain minorities (ethnic, sexual etc) have been more publicly distancing themselves from the current ideologies to try and protect against such a blowback.<br/><br/>Any advice on what we can do as individuals to steer things towards a more positively patriotic but not senselessly violent manifestation? Or how we can keep moral and safe during the times when it hits?<br/><br/>Personally I can’t find anywhere else i can easily move, but more importantly I don’t want to leave this land anyway. One of my recent visions/dreams of what i need to do with myself clearly named going to sites of pagan/magical importance in these Isles, which i began last summer when i met some of you. Later on i found out there was a lot of druidic and Celtic symbolism in that dream. So for now I feel that I must complete said task, so curious if there’s anything or any deity i can consult for help in that too?<br/><br/>Vivek ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59045192", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 01:46 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I wish I knew. Glancing back over history, occultists haven't had much luck in preventing such outbursts, and tolerably often die in them when things blow up. Being very public about distancing yourself from hated ideologies might help...or it might not. <br/><br/>2) If you're getting Druid and Celtic dreams, the gods may be reaching out to you. Find some books on Celtic mythology and see if any of the deities you find there have any special appeal. If so, consider setting up a shrine to that deity -- an image and an incense burner, at least -- and offering prayer and incense regularly. Just a hunch, but Cernunnos might be well suited to your needs. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58993224", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 03:32 pm", "user": "neptunesdolphins", "content": "I guess I am not the only one who seems to see a mass plague of insanity. I thought it is Trump Derangement Syndrome gone afire spreading through the U.S. population. Maybe it is something deeper?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59009096", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:37 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "On Youtube, viral Tiktok clips have recently come to attention of teachers complaining about how dimwitted and brainrotted elementary and middle school students are. I hope some of the claims are lies designed to get views. In one, a middle school teacher said that two of her students read at grade level (which itself has doubtlessly been dumbed down over the decades), 18 read at kindergarten level, and many read at second to fourth grade level. In another clip, another middle school teacher (or maybe the same one-- I can't remember) says that she had her students copy down notes about American colonial history, including that Maryland was founded as a refuge for Catholics. She asked, \"Where were the Catholics at?\" and none could answer her.<br/><br/>It appears that the cognitive collapse of the wokeists is nothing compared to the brainrot of the generation that experiened the lockdowns during early childhood and grew up on Tiktok.<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59009608", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:41 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Does it ever occur to them that maybe this indicates that they're doing a poor job of teaching? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59011912", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:56 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "Most middle school students should know enough to be able to scan the notes they just copied down for \"Catholics\" and give her the spoon-fed answer, even if most of them fail the test two weeks later.<br/><br/>I did assume she went over the content on the notes, elaborating on the content like my public school history teachers did. I hope she didn't just order them to copy down the notes in silence and then ask them questions about them. She has her hair dyed blue, which probably doesn't get the kids to respect her as a superior.<br/><br/>Patrick H ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59018824", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 07:31 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Anyone's guess what's actually going on. Far too many US public schools have become utterly unable to teach these days, however. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59022408", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 07:53 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've worked for two public schools for the last ten years, one of which is in the top 20 largest districts in the country, and the quality of our teachers is appalling.  There is a base line assumption that everyone agrees with the Party line and nothing but contempt for parents who disagree with them.  Many truly believe that they are heroes because they regurgitate the state mandated curriculum and never present that many issues have multiple valid perspectives.  The cradle-to-prison pipeline is alive and well in our poorest schools where the kids are treated like criminals from day 1.  Our wealthier schools are primarily concerned with teaching the globalist worldview and preparing kids to be in the PMC.  I often wonder about the karma I'm generating for myself by working in such an environment.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59025992", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 08:18 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In your place I'd be looking for another job. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59038536", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 11:52 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I don't doubt that's a big part of it. Standards in the American public school system have seriously declined in recent decades. I went to high school in the early 1980's, before things really went down the sewer, and I don't envy the young people who are trapped in the public school system these days.<br/><br/>Two things come to mind. One is that I have been told by a number of people I know who are former public school teachers that American high schools are for the most part glorified baby sitting services for teenagers. Middle and elementary schools don't seem to be much better these days. Another was a recent encounter I had at the local garden shop/health &amp; wellness center, which is run by a couple of local hippies. I got to talking with three young women who were shopping there. Turns out they were teachers at a nearby elementary school. They mentioned that the lockdowns did immense amounts of psychological damage to young children, which they have been having to deal with ever since in the classroom, and that they were relieved that most of these kids are now in middle or high school, where they no longer having to deal directly with the fallout. I would imagine the fact that most of these kids were forcibly injected with experimental and inadequately tested mRNA gene therapy treatments which are now known to cause serious health impacts, including cognitive issues, didn't help either. <br/><br/>Personally, I suspect it's a combination of causes, including a severely dysfunctional educational system, including the effects of woke ideology on that system, the dumbing down of standards, incompetent teaching, long-term psychological damage from the lockdowns, brain trauma from being exposed to certain \"vaccines\", cognitive impairments from overexposure to electronic media from a very early age, and a whole host other factors.<br/><br/>What a mess!"}]}, {"id": "cmt59046216", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 02:01 am", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "A lot of this cognitive collapse seems to me to be caused by a lack of anything in children's culture that requires their slow, laborious and sustained concentration for any great length of time.  So they start their school years without any experience of this sort of mental work.<br/><br/>When I was young and TV was in its tiny-screen, black-and-white infancy, shows moved from their beginnings to their ends at a measured pace, news was a person speaking thoughtfully and carefully, and in general the viewer was rarely startled.  One had time to think along with the show as it moved from its beginning to its end.  And most popular music was primarily melodic, with simple, regular rhythms.  And very many people spent hours and hours reading books of one sort or another, books that required sustained attention to get much out of them.<br/><br/>Nowadays children's visual media are full of sudden \"jump cuts,\" shifts of scene, and rapid movements.  Their music seems to downplay melodic development in favor of sudden surprises.  All this will produce a steady flow of dopamine \"hits,\" which eventually becomes addictive.  And it esily comes to saturate their lives<br/><br/>This shift (if memory serves me rightly) began in the very late 1950s, and picked up steam in the 1960s and 1970s.  That's when -- and why! -- TV lost any attraction it had for me, and by the mid-1980s I had entirely stopped watching it.  <br/><br/>But effective studying of anything is impossible without slow, laborious and sustained concentration.  If children haven't already learned how to do this sort of work, they can't be taught much of anything.  <br/><br/>By way of illustration. my wife's great-grandfather, Benjamin Randall Jordan, was a farmer's son, and worked all his life as a farmer.  He had just ten months of schooling in a one-room schoolhouse in rural Maine (Parsonsfield).  Yet he owned what was for his day a fairly large library of perhaps 75-100 books, whic has come down to my wife intact.  It included such books as Milton's Paradise Lost, Butler's Hudibras, a textbook of astronomy with its accompanying sky atlas, a handbook of all the world's religions, a good-sized dictionary, and so forth -- all of them worn from being read over and over.     <br/><br/>We have created a media-saturated civilization where children are handicapped by a lack of mental exercise in their young years, to the point where most of them will never ever be capable of that sort of labor with so many books.  Only a fraction of the students I taught at my Ivy-League University (1967-2005) seemed capable of doing that sort of slow careful reading, and not all of them were actually willing to do it.  "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59032136", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 09:27 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This may be a rather naive statement, but \"once genuine spiritual powers begin to manifest, the boundary between excitement and carnage is not always easy to maintain.\" makes said spiritual powers rather thoroughly amoral in the strict sense of the word.<br/><br/>JH", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59034952", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 11:06 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Morality is a human thing. It concerns the rules that are appropriate to human beings. The moral virtues are human virtues, just as a plant (for example) can have healing virtues. We don't criticize the morality of a lioness when she springs upon a gazelle, or call the sea evil when it drowns people, because they're not human and thus not subject to human morality. <br/><br/>The same is true of the gods. They are emphatically not human, and the laws by which they are governed are not human laws. (That's true of the god of Christianity, btw, as much as any other: as Amos 3:6 says, \"Shall there be evil in a city, and the Lord hath not done it?\") The gods are the primary powers of existence, as far outside human morality as the law of gravity. The 2000-year experiment of attempting to judge them by human standards has fared very poorly, all things considered, and it's arguably time that we stop fooling ourselves. <br/><br/>None of this, btw, weakens the importance of moral principles in human life. Morals and ethics are the rules we've evolved over most of a million years to help us achieve excellence and live with each other in relative peace; the fact that they don't apply to nonhuman realities doesn't keep them from applying to us. As a certain shoggoth once whistled, \"the world has no eyes, but we have eyes.\" "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58984520", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 02:41 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "Could this be related to the Saturn-Neptune conjunction? The prophet Ezekiel had his vision of the cherubium around the time of the 594 B.C. conjunction.<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58985544", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 02:46 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good heavens. That hadn't occurred to me, but of course you're quite correct. Hmm...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59000904", "title": "Ezekiel's prophecies", "date": "2026-02-02 04:54 pm", "user": "mskrieger", "content": "Thanks for this, it actually makes me feel a bit better. Ezekiel started out very disturbed but his later visions are beautiful and regenerative and evocative of blessing. May this Saturn-Neptune conjunction follow the same path.<br/><br/>--Ms. Krieger"}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58971976", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:49 am", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "Thank you, this makes me feel much better.<br/><br/>The Weirdening works for me, so I will use it.  Maybe you could get a vote from your commentariat?<br/><br/>Speaking of weird - My standoffish self went from zero to warm and fuzzy in no seconds at all.  That never happened before.  I think, rather - I feel Amelia is likely a protector of women, home and hearth since she frequently appears in a future version with Charlie and their children.  Brigantia comes to mind.  Her Roman syncretizations seem to mesh well with the combination of public and private roles.<br/>Oh, some of the memes feature Amelia addressing Parliament - back to public role again.<br/><br/>Anyway - I'm unable to rationally explain any of my response to Amelia, so I'm inclined to suspect something more than an egregore since none of my usual anti-baloney tripwires were hit.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58983752", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 02:35 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I hope she's Brigantia, rather than one of the more bloodthirsty war goddesses. Your reaction suggests this, for what it's worth. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58990920", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 03:26 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Amelia was paid for by  East Riding Council, managing a rural/coastal area (including Bridlington and Beverley) and Hull City Council, managing the urban port city.<br/><br/>One area is Conservative run  and the other  area is Labour run so it's the uniparty then.<br/>This makes Amelia a northern lass so Brigantia fits.<br/>cealin"}, {"id": "cmt59011144", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:48 pm", "user": "causticus", "content": "Well, so far Amelia's character has two main aspects:<br/><br/>1 Patriotic war goddess leader of the battle against woke tyranny.<br/><br/>2. \"Art Hoe\" (to use the language of the memesters promoting her). <br/><br/>Seems to me like a Minerva-type goddess, though a rather weird and hilarious manifestation of one. I think Brigantia might fit the bill, since I think she was syncretized with Minerva way back in the day. <br/><br/>Also, it seems like a very robust egregore formed around her the moment the meme went viral. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59028808", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 08:54 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "I'm wondering...maybe it takes more effort for deities to speak to or appear to humans who have a lower level of consciousness or are not in the right frame of mind (which would be part of the reason religions teach reverence towards the gods). The Internet &amp; AI makes it convenient for deities to manifest to even the lowest common denominator, so \"Amelia\" is appealing to male sex drive.<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59054152", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 03:22 am", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "With due apologies to our host for my profligate flurry of letters... but this is way too interesting...<br/><br/>Sex drive?  Well, yes.  There has been, however, a major shift in iconography among young men from interest in the pitiful byproducts of liberalist theory to the hearth goddess militant.  A number of memes feature Amelia and Charlie married and raising kids.  That's one of those things so big it is easy to overlook, but it does parallel some of the side chatter from younger conservatives who actually do want, well, a hearth goddess to serve.<br/><br/>I agree that the internet has its own weirdening.  This desire for a suitable wife means the ideal of being a suitable husband is in circulation and offering an esc-Center that neither the alt-Right nor the ctrl-Left can produce."}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58972232", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 06:12 am", "user": "vitranc", "content": "😲<br/>OK, this strikes an unnerving memory. Early last year I read a blog from a medium and he wrote, that he sees (I am writing from memory):<br/>\"A lot of oily blackness covering the world\" ... \"In the United states the process is being guided and helped with. And the blackness is being washed away into a hole ringed with light, where it is taken away by a hand\" ... \"In the United kingdom the hole and the hand is being wreathed in red fire\" From what I know of the lore of British war goddesses this might be unnervingly accurate. And it strikes a remarkable parallel.<br/>If the process is being helped. And as you commented of your replies to the Trump inauguration chart, the process in United states is being intervened in, guided. And this is how it manifests. How would the clearing up of the astral look naturally?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58984008", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 02:37 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "When the corrupt astral aura of a nation has to be cleansed by wholly natural means, the process typically involves major disasters of various kinds: war, plague, famine, flood, and so on. The body count is usually very high. It would be good if we were spared that. "}]}, {"id": "cmt58972744", "title": "picture not linked - NFP", "date": "2026-02-02 06:20 am", "user": "kallianeira", "content": "<br/>Dear John, Welcome back and I hope your move was as easy as possible.<br/>Just writing to say the Amelia image isn't showing in your reply.<br/>Cheers<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58984264", "title": "Re: picture not linked - NFP", "date": "2026-02-02 02:38 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm. I see it. Does anyone else not see it? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58986056", "title": "Re: picture not linked - NFP", "date": "2026-02-02 02:51 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Works fine for me.<br/><br/>—David P."}, {"id": "cmt58999112", "title": "Re: picture not linked - NFP", "date": "2026-02-02 04:22 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "My elderly browser does not see images with the MS-tainted extension ‘webp’. I have to use other software to view those images. I have no plans to ‘upgrade’ my browser nonetheless because it has features I like that the ‘upgrade' [bah!] strips out and tosses into the trash. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58973512", "title": "Amelia", "date": "2026-02-02 06:32 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "John Michael --<br/><br/>Congratulations on your successful relocation!<br/><br/>As an addendum to the Amelia tale, there's https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VOSTbUFg7_Y ,<br/>the Amelia cover of \"Jerusalem\". <br/><br/>(I don't know whether that's enough to get \"Jerusalem\" cancelled, or perhaps William Blake as well! -- what visions might the Daughters of Albion now behold, as they \"weep: a trembling lamentation Upon their mountains; in their valleys,\" and \"sigh toward America\". Some pranksters might end up giving it a try, and Blake's brief window of acceptability be slammed shut.)<br/><br/>LeGrand Cinq-Mars<br/><br/><br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58984776", "title": "Re: Amelia", "date": "2026-02-02 02:44 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh dear gods. Of course it would be that song. Somebody involved in <i>l'affaire Amelia</i> knows what they're doing; that bit of Blake, with or without musical accompaniment, has been being used in Druid circles to evoke the spirit of England for a very long time. <br/><br/>Parenthetical note: do you, or does anyone else, recall that fascinating Poul Anderson novel <i>A Midsummer Tempest</i>, set in an imaginary world in which every word Shakespeare wrote was literally true? In the climactic scene, the hero uses the books of Prospero (recovered from the deep waters) to conjure the spirit of England to overthrow Cromwell's armies. There's a certain Roundhead quality to Starmer's regime, with wokeness in place of Puritan Christianity, and I find myself wondering if somebody read that and took it as an instruction manual...", "edit_time": "2026-02-02 02:44 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58988104", "title": "Re: Amelia", "date": "2026-02-02 03:04 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I can't help but also notice the parallel between \"Jerusalem\" and \"Jerusalema\". The latter song was the one to which all the PPE-covered \"medical experts\" were dancing in those creepy early covid videos that were going around almost 6 years ago. Now, we may have a viral \"Jerusalem\" instead. It feels a little like bookends - or even an attempt (conscious or unconscious) to reverse something, maybe?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58989128", "title": "Re: Amelia", "date": "2026-02-02 03:13 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm! A very good point. Here's hoping -- anything that puts a hard stop to the creepiness of those days is welcome. "}]}, {"id": "cmt58997576", "title": "Re: Amelia", "date": "2026-02-02 04:11 pm", "user": "not_gandalf", "content": "I don't know what it is. I'm American born and raised, and yet that song hits me at a very deep level, and this version of it almost brought tears to my eyes. "}, {"id": "cmt59014216", "title": "Re: Amelia", "date": "2026-02-02 06:35 pm", "user": "eldriwolf", "content": "Yes, I remember it!<br/>One of my favorites. Especially that characters fall into iambic pentamir at important moments ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59019336", "title": "Re: Amelia", "date": "2026-02-02 07:33 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you scan the dialogue, all of it -- except when Rupert and Will are in the strange interdimensional pub -- is in iambic pentameter. Anderson was very good at making that subtle when the dialogue wasn't intense, but he did a brilliant job. <br/><br/>(Mind you, this is also the guy who penned <i>MacTruck</i>, which is still one of the funniest Shakespeare parodies ever written. He was good!) "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59047752", "title": "Re: Amelia", "date": "2026-02-03 02:11 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "My goodness! That Amelia version of \"Jerusalem\" is epic! Thanks for sharing this, LeGrand.<br/><br/>I see that the same YT channel (Epochalypse) has also rendered an Amelia version of \"I Vow To Thee, My Country\" - another British patriotic classic. For those who know their way around Holst's \"The Planets\" it appears in the middle of the piece entitled \"Jupiter\". I had a friend who studied in a boarding school in England in the 1960s and early '70s: he told me that they used to regularly sing \"I Vow To Thee\" and did so with more passion than they did the national anthem (\"God Save the Queen\").<br/><br/>There's also \"Rule Britannia\", \"Land of Hope and Glory\" and the popular 19th century hymn \"Abide With Me\" - all on the same YT channel. This is absolutely amazing!<br/><br/>Ron M"}]}, {"id": "cmt58973768", "title": "Chasing Amelia", "date": "2026-02-02 07:46 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The lovely Countess of Steele wrote about that phenomenon:<br/><br/>https://kimberlysteele.substack.com/p/chasing-amelia", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58985288", "title": "Re: Chasing Amelia", "date": "2026-02-02 02:46 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this. "}, {"id": "cmt59027016", "title": "Re: Chasing Amelia", "date": "2026-02-02 08:30 pm", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "Thank you for this from me, too.  That was a lovely essay.  I have bookmarked Kimberly's site now, and will be reading through all its posts over the next few weeks.  IO have always valued her posts here."}, {"id": "cmt59032648", "title": "Re: Chasing Amelia", "date": "2026-02-02 09:36 pm", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "Steele is a beautiful maiden.<br/>She sings to me by the pale moon light.<br/><br/>(Written while tending a giant lathe beneath a skylight on third shift.)<br/>"}]}, {"id": "cmt58976328", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 09:52 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I think Amelia is a sign of where a lot of the woke are headed. You are going to have a lot of blue hairs shouting racist and antisemitic slogans and cheering on the jackboots in a few years. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58985032", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 02:45 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It may not take that long. Still, we'll see. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58994760", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 03:44 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "As someone in a country still run by the left, I'm worried that if the Democrats lose the midterms, the global left will go full Nazi by the end of this year..."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58986824", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 02:53 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Fascinating.<br/>I have  spent the last  year or so learning and doing rituals with the purpose of returning the Goddess Britannia as an force for Strength, Truth and Beauty for the British peoples.<br/>Maybe Britannia, who I see as the Roman's personification of the  \"spirit of the British peoples\", could be a good fit.<br/>Crowley said,<br/>\"The colour violet, generally speaking, signifies a vibration which is at the same time spiritual and erotic.\"<br/>Which seems quite appropriate for Amelia.<br/>I feel I need some violet candles.<br/> Just bought cheep second hand a CD from  Sir Arthur Bliss \"A Colour Symphony\" first moment is called \"Purple\" and from my youth Amelia from the Mission is a great song.<br/>Cealin", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58987592", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 02:58 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Violet candles and a British flag would work very well to evoke that energy. Just saying...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59034184", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 10:22 pm", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "Umm...  Maybe put them a little galvanized bucket with some sand?<br/>Since Brigantia is syncretized with Minerva, Fortuna and Victoria... <br/>But she's a Brit, so - Set out bacon jerky and beer... and bread, of course.<br/>Amelia often appears smoking a cigarette, so the Pond duly jumped twice now.<br/>What if you put out a Brody helmet (Tommy's tin hat) with laurels on it surrounded by palm leaves for triumph and peace?<br/>Is asking for aid so Amelia may win by wit and maneuver reasonable?<br/><br/>Also, I didn't bring this up on Saint Brigid's day on purpose, but isn't she an evolved aspect of Brigantia?<br/><br/>And - Is it possible that the US is still connected to the UK by the inherited Roman egregore of the US and the Roman syncretizing of Brittania?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59035208", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 11:12 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Ha! A good old-fashioned practice. Yes, all of these would be potential options for a shrine. Libations of good brown pub ale would likely be useful, too. <br/><br/>2) I recommend divination. <br/><br/>3) That's what the comparative mythologists say, certainly. <br/><br/>4) The US and the UK have a very complex relationship that is partly retired parent to adult child, and partly target for a whole gallimaufry of each other's projections. How much of that is connection and how much conflict is an interesting question. <br/><br/>"}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58988616", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 03:10 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Kristoffer Hughes thinks that Arianrhod is stirring; a harsh teacher, but at least not a battle goddess. For anyone not familiar, he's a native Welsh-speaking Druid, the head of the Anglesey Druid Order, who actually lives on the island of Anglesey. He's written a little book on Arianrhod (more properly Aranrhod, but his publisher insisted on the currently popular spelling) and gave quite an impressive presentation on her at East Coast Gathering last year.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58989384", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 03:14 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Interesting. Well, we'll see. "}]}, {"id": "cmt58998088", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 04:14 pm", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "I spent an hour this morning watching several Amelia videos on youtube, and I was struck by the enormous emotional power carried by most of the ones I watched.  I think they are likely to change British politics from globalist-controlled to predominantly nationalist and patriotic.  (Which seems to be what is misnamed \"extreme right\" these days.)<br/><br/>Whether or not the creators of those videos knew much about magic consciously, unconsciously they understood a great deal about how to do it.  (This is not surprising, since magical ability and power are hard-wired into the human body.)<br/><br/>I also think that it will take extreme measures of censorship on the part of the UK government to derail the political shift Amelia will cause.  Watch out for the first signs of it; they will eventually make the ban on Palestine Action look like kindergarteners' sandbox-play.  Ugh!"}, {"id": "cmt59031112", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 09:16 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I looked up the meaning of the name Amelia, which leads me to suspect whoever chose that name was sabatoging the original game project, or was being used by Someone to sabatoge, to this end.<br/><br/>Amelia, from Amalia, a short form of Germanic names begining with the element Amal, meaning unceasing, vigerous, brave.<br/>(Source: https://www.behindthename.com/name/amalia)<br/><br/>BoysMom", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59040072", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 12:00 am", "user": "jprussell", "content": "Wow! \"Once is chance, twice is coincidence, three times is enemy action...\""}]}, {"id": "cmt59033672", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 10:12 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey JMG <br/><br/>I actually decided to play this “Pathways” game, after reading the article John Carter wrote about it on Substack. <br/>It’s essentially a kind of “multiple choice” game that can be completed within 30 minutes. There are always 3 choices offered each time, which can be described as reject “extremism”, investigate it a bit, or embrace it. There is no option for you to text or write any dialogue at all, so I’m not sure who told you that it tricked kids to say “rascist statements”.<br/>Nonetheless, at the end of the games there’s an advertisement for the organisation behind the game, called “Prevent”, that claims that its purpose is to intervene in cases of young people who have been reported by family, friends or teachers for expressing “extremism”. I found the whole thing to be vaguely threatening, and also infantilising in a way.<br/><br/>J.L.Mc12"}]}, {"id": "cmt58985800", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 02:49 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "And now I have, stuck in my head on permanent repeat, a slightly rewritten Simon and Garfunkel song performed by Keir Starmer with a backup band of (literally) faceless bureaucrats: <br/><br/>\"Oh Amelia, you're breaking my heart,<br/>You're shaking my confidence daily...\"", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59012936", "title": "Aine", "date": "2026-02-02 06:04 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This is my favourite Amelia meme.  Starmer is right to be worried.<br/><br/>https://x.com/DaveskiXVII/status/2016268610784637050/photo/1<br/><br/>Also Thomas Sheridan has created an Irish version of Amelia called Aine.  It hasn't really taken off yet but I hope this goes viral too. <br/><br/>https://x.com/butterflyspeir/status/2018384152521748555", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59022664", "title": "Re: Aine", "date": "2026-02-02 07:58 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "There also appears to be a French version:<br/><br/>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X_4yn-8CBbk", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59042120", "title": "Re: Aine", "date": "2026-02-03 12:25 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "According to an article that appeared on MSN earlier today, there are now Dutch, German and Irish versions as well.<br/><br/><i>Versions of the same character have been shared online, such as Dutch-speaking \"Emma\", the German \"Maria\", and the Irish \"Amelia\".<br/><br/>Each character has her own national symbols and political references. In Germany, Maria wears a traditional Bavarian dirndl and expresses her love for a \"cold beer in our village pub\". She claims her government is no longer protecting her and calls on \"brave knights\" to defend her homeland from Muslim immigrants.<br/><br/>In the Netherlands, an AI creation of Emma insists that Christmas should be celebrated \"in the traditional way\".<br/><br/>In Ireland, a red-haired version of the character calls the country's taoiseach, Micheál Martin, a \"mouthpiece for Brussels\". Brussels, she insists, forces Ireland to have \"open borders\", despite Ireland not being part of the Schengen area.</i><br/><br/>https://www.msn.com/en-us/technology/artificial-intelligence/from-classroom-game-to-niche-meme-how-ai-character-amelia-spread-across-europe/ar-AA1Vu6bo", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59058248", "title": "Re: Aine", "date": "2026-02-03 08:22 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Emma is not talking about Christmas, but Sinterklaas, the traditional European winter celebration that goes back to Wodan, who, just like Sinterklaas, rides through the heavens on a horse, ahead of an army of the dead. The dead are often played by people that have their faces blackened with sooth, and come by many names, including Krampus, Schwarze Nicolaus, Schmutzli, Zwarte Piet and others, all through Europe from England to Iran(!). In the USA these figures morphed into the elves that distribute coal (because often coal was used to blacken the faces) and help Santa, and got connected to Christmas, but it is very offensive for Dutch people if you mix these two holidays.<br/>The woke crowd has been trying to cancel Sinterklaas and Zwarte Piet, because this ancient ritual reminded them of the 20th century racist blackface figure, and the terrorist group \"Kick out Zwarte Piet\" has used violence to disturb the celebrations. It has created much animosity in Dutch society, and has caused Sinterklaas and Zwarte Piet to become major symbols of Dutch nationality, where the globalist movement in the country seeks to abolish them.<br/>"}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59030856", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 09:12 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Oh yeah...that deserves a complete line-by-line satiric version of Simon's classic."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58969160", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:05 am", "user": "brenainn", "content": "I've begun experiencing (over the last year) increasinglly clear impressions or communications from a particular spirit, a loved one in the afterlife. In the late Fall, I was visiting their grave and started getting impressions, very slight, from other spirits in the area. I'm not really sure what to make of all this, and the last year as a whole has been one heck of a spiritual ride for me. Any suggestions as to what might be happening, and how to handle it?", "edit_time": "2026-02-02 05:06 am (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58970184", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:24 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "This kind of thing is quite traditional. I recall the Irish folk wizard Yeats knew, the \"knowledgeable man\" in the town of Spiddal, who got his knowledge from the ghost of his dead sister, who contacted him regularly; dealing with other spirits was an important part of his work. It's by no means impossible that, as the Age of Reason finishes collapsing, this kind of thing will become quite common again -- in which case, you're simply a little ahead of the curve. <br/><br/>You might read Mircea Eliade's book on shamanism; that's a very similar tradition, and wild spiritual rides are usually part of it. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58970696", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:31 am", "user": "brenainn", "content": "I'll check it out. I haven't read much Eliade before, and probably should.<br/><br/>Another interesting part of this has been the reversal of my previously lousy ability to do divination. Over the last year, my divination readings have gotten a lot better. I had spent a few years at it, with little progress. It feels more like someone is guiding my interpretations, helping me to avoid the usual confirmation bias and nervousness that had previously clouded my readings.<br/><br/>This all started little more than a year ago, when I suddenly got the strong impression that there was a particular ritual that I needed to do involving the spirit of the loved one, and that set things off. A wild ride, indeed.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58971208", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:41 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Even more traditional! You'll be hanging out your shingle as the local knowledgeable man, or however that's spelled where you live, any day now. ;-)<br/><br/>There's an unnerving personal subtext in all this for me. Last year I received a very old and rather odd Rosicrucian initiation, the Rose+Croix d'Orient degree, which is passed on in the penumbra of some Martinist orders. After I received the initiation I was given a stack of ritual material that went with it -- which turned out to be what I think is the most complete and best-preserved system of medieval Western white magic in existence. <br/><br/>You know the old man in the little cottage at the end of the lane, the one who knows prayers and religious-themed rites to take ill-wishing off your cattle and quiet the restless dead? That's the sort of thing I mean. I've been practicing the material regularly since shortly after I got the initiation, partly because it amuses me to know that I do in fact have the ability to take ill-wishing off cattle if that's ever needed, partly because it's good solid healing and blessing work and the world needs more of that...and partly because I've had an uneasy feeling for some time now that we're moving into an era in which there will be a definite place for old men at the end of the lane who can take ill-wishing off cattle. <br/><br/>So that's been on my mind of late -- and now you and Maxine both report going through variations of the standard process by which folk magicians of a somewhat different category begin their career...and this as Saturn and Neptune close in on a conjunction that will mark a new age of the world. I'm beginning to wonder just what kind of age we're entering!", "edit_time": "2026-02-02 05:44 am (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58972488", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 06:19 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In the past few months, as another data point, I've began to do divination and psychic readings for people. While my astral perception needs a lot of work, I get beings whispering accurate things in my ear regularly. I'll never forget the first one I did for someone else. I had a being advise me that my friend's ex-partner was concealing her real financial position to mess with calculation of support payments and got a kick out of starting arguments with him. I'd gone in knowing nothing about the situation, but he was already aware and confirmed every detail. Surreal and a great initiation! I think I will end up being that guy you invite around for a coffee and a little chat about what might really be going on...<br/><br/>I enjoy reading accounts of near-death experiences, and those, along with spirit contact has convinced me too that death is nothing to be concerned about. I read one recently wherein a woman claimed to have seen a future that you'd probably find quite plausible. Following large scale wars and depopulation, most people lived in small, largely self-sufficient communities with no large scale immigration or global connections. Technology was used more harmoniously and things were much more peaceful. Might be hell to get there, but it sounds pretty hopeful to me.<br/><br/>https://www.msn.com/en-xl/news/news/i-have-a-terrifying-warning-for-humanity-after-i-died-for-32-seconds-and-saw-the-future/ar-AA1Vp7HH", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58986312", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 02:51 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thanks for the data points! Yeah, your future as the local diviner-oracle is probably taking shape around you. As for the vision, if we do get something like that, well, it's a lot better than most of the other options, and the route won't be any worse. "}]}, {"id": "cmt58977864", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 10:25 am", "user": "scotlyn", "content": "If I may, many of the farmers around here are definitely feeling like the EU-chartered vet inspectors and other such officials, are *putting* an ill-wish on local cattle. Cattle found to be TB-positive by test, and culled, tolerably often, when the killed cattle are re-tested, are found to be free of TB and fit for human consumption, and therefore sent from the veterinary abattoir straight to a commercial meat-packing factory, from which the \"ill-wished\" farmer gets only a token compensation. It is a racket for sure, but the feeling that there is malice involved is also palpable. <br/><br/>Which is to say, I feel that I have enough of a stake in the matter to welcome any measure you might consent to direct towards the taking the \"ill-wishing\" off the cattle of my corner of Southwest Donegal. :) ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58986568", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 02:52 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Unfortunately the methods I have pretty much require me to be close to the cattle. Have you considered learning a thing or two yourself, along the same lines? Or perhaps invoking some of the old Irish deities who protected cattle against reavers? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58990664", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 03:24 pm", "user": "scotlyn", "content": "I had not... but now I will. :)  Thank you. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58981704", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 01:58 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If i may, i have a question.<br/>You have studied and mastered many spiritual traditions, including alchemy.<br/><br/>So, i may sound a bit blunt but...Did you not knew already how to take ill-wishing out of cattle?<br/><br/>I ask because i'm a practicioner of the kind of things you teach, and i happen to live in the countryside. Using your teachings, i figured how to do this kind of things long ago, along with others of the kind, without initiations involved...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58987080", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 02:54 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, granted -- but it's one thing to work out something on first principles. It's quite another to get handed a set of workings that have been used for the purpose for centuries, and have a robust egregor built up around them. <br/><br/>Delighted to hear that you're doing original work with my material, btw! That's not common enough. I trust your cattle are thriving.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58988360", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 03:08 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I see. However, do you think so much power is really needed to such, ahem, menial tasks?<br/>Again, i talk only from my own experiences, but ill-wishing around here is usually no match for a solid magical training. Defending is always much easier than atacking, after all.<br/><br/>...Although i do hope to have acces to this tradition some day! Just in case.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58989640", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 03:16 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That mostly speaks to the incompetence of your local warlocks (which is of course a good thing!). Ill-wishing can be very powerful indeed, and if it's been around for a while and has developed a strong egregor, it can take hard work to break such a thing.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58992200", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 03:30 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Well, understood then. I'll keep sharpening my stuff, in case they all suddenly take a master degree in nastiness.<br/><br/>"}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58982216", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 02:02 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In some parts of Europe, keeping old women away from the cattle was held to be important, too...<br/><br/>  Maidens to milk them, of course! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58987336", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 02:57 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Classic sympathetic magic -- you don't want the cows to dry up the way the old women have. Of course it also means that your young women are much more likely to be immune from smallpox, since milkmaids inevitably catch cowpox, which is a mild illness for most people and gives lifelong immunity from all the viruses in that family. "}]}, {"id": "cmt58998344", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 04:21 pm", "user": "not_gandalf", "content": "Is this material the Sacramentaire du Rose+Croix by Robert Ambelaine?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59001416", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 04:56 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's one of the documents I received, yes. There are others. "}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58969416", "title": "Ghosts", "date": "2026-02-02 05:08 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, <br/>I have studied and practiced Druidry quite intensively for about a decade now.  I find it has really made my life a lot better in many ways.  I am wondering if the high number of ghost sightings and poltergeist activity in my house is due to the magic I perform?  I pray, do divination and meditation almost every day.  I occasionally do spell work but always for blessing, protection, cleansing or comforting.  <br/><br/>I don't mind the ghosts.  They seem to take some comfort from being here.  I feel as if I have left a light on that attracts spirits to my house.  What do you think?<br/>Maxine", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58970440", "title": "Re: Ghosts", "date": "2026-02-02 05:27 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's a source of some interest to me that you and Brenainn are both reporting similar experiences -- his focused more on his relationship with a specific spirit, yours focused more on the practice of a specific tradition, but in both cases you're becoming what was once a very familiar sort of person, one who mediated between the living and the dead. If you don't mind the ghosts, and they benefit from your presence, by all means proceed. Things may get stranger, though, as you do...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58979144", "title": "Re: Ghosts", "date": "2026-02-02 12:43 pm", "user": "emily07", "content": "IIRC in previous posts (like years ago) the idea was that ghots in general take energy from the ...voor...around them? So if one is a trained druid/magician/shaman/etc. it doesn´t matter that much any more because of SOP and other gimmicks? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58988872", "title": "Re: Ghosts", "date": "2026-02-02 03:11 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Exactly. Most ghosts aren't actively predatory, and those who are, can be banished readily by a competent practitioner. <br/><br/>I'd be utterly delighted, btw, if \"voor\" came to be used as a common term for etheric energy. I didn't invent the word -- I borrowed it from Arthur Machen, as part of my general subversion of his weird tales -- but it's a good convenient label. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59012424", "title": "Re: Ghosts", "date": "2026-02-02 06:03 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "Is that pronounced like the Dutch 'voor'? If so, I think it would have a very nice ring to it. A rather fitting sound for the energy of the life force.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59020104", "title": "Re: Ghosts", "date": "2026-02-02 07:37 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Well, I don't know Dutch, but it rhymes with \"moor;\" the adjective form is \"voorish.\"  It's the word I used for the life force in my series of tentacle novels, <i>The Weird of Hali</i>. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59032904", "title": "Re: Ghosts", "date": "2026-02-02 09:47 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "That is indeed how the Dutch 'voor' is pronounced. It simply means \"for\" in Dutch, so I doubt Machen selected it from that language. I enjoy etymology. At any rate, I like the word and will put it to use now."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59020616", "title": "Re: Ghosts", "date": "2026-02-02 07:40 pm", "user": "milkyway1", "content": "About ghosts potentially draining/taking life force... <br/><br/>How would this play out if one person in a household is a competent practitioner who might attract ghosts but could easily deal with them, but other household members aren't? Would the general practice of the practitioner (banishings or whatever) usually be enough to protect the people around them, too? Or would it in such a case be prudent to discourage the presence of ghosts?<br/><br/>And I suppose having a special connection e.g. to a deceased family member, as referenced in another comment above, would be another matter entirely - maybe also being beneficial to non-practicing family members?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59026504", "title": "Re: Ghosts", "date": "2026-02-02 08:19 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If there are vulnerable family members present, yes, you'd want to discourage ghosts from coming around. That isn't the case for deceased family members, if they died while still having a good relation with the family -- in that case they become protective spirits. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59000136", "title": "Re: Ghosts", "date": "2026-02-02 04:49 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This short piece showed up on Unherd not long after I read all these threads:<br/>https://unherd.com/newsroom/church-of-england-exorcisms-mark-return-of-mysticism/<br/><br/>The title is \"Church of England exorcisms mark return of mysticism\", and it's an (apparently skeptical) reaction to a paywalled Telegraph article about a recent exorcism by the church. The Telegraph article is linked to in the first paragraph of the Unherd piece for those who have a subscription.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59001160", "title": "Re: Ghosts", "date": "2026-02-02 04:56 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good heavens -- the C of E is doing exorcisms again? Next you'll tell me that some of their clergypersons are considering believing in God. Who'd have thought? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59014984", "title": "Re: Ghosts", "date": "2026-02-02 06:47 pm", "user": "open_space", "content": "Next you'll tell me that some of their clergy persons are considering believing in God.\" That was hilarious.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59020360", "title": "Re: Ghosts", "date": "2026-02-02 07:37 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I hope their god finds it as amusing as you do! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59023176", "title": "Re: Ghosts", "date": "2026-02-02 08:01 pm", "user": "open_space", "content": "<p>Most certainly not. God is fierce and if he does, he will chuckle as he just ignores their calls mid exorcism and give them a proper spook for a little bit followed by a revelation that brings them to their knees, while he quietly chuckles.</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59026760", "title": "Re: Ghosts", "date": "2026-02-02 08:20 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I think it was Crowley who said that there's a certain satisfaction in being hit over the head by a spirit of whose existence you were previously uncertain. Maybe their god will deal out some of that satisfaction...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59057736", "title": "Re: Ghosts", "date": "2026-02-03 05:00 am", "user": "open_space", "content": "And I am sure the exorcists would be so, so grateful for the whack they would want a repeat or two."}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59044936", "title": "C of E and god", "date": "2026-02-03 01:45 am", "user": "ritaer", "content": "I recently heard of an occult shop in some area of England being harassed by a vicar who thought Tarot cards bring demons. My first thought was along the lines of \"Good lord, a C. of E clergyman who believes in the supernatural. Does the bishop know? <br/><br/><br/>Rita", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59045448", "title": "Re: C of E and god", "date": "2026-02-03 01:49 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "\"I'm shocked -- <i>shocked!</i> -- to find religious faith going on here.\"  "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59027272", "title": "Re: Ghosts", "date": "2026-02-02 08:33 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, <br/>So you do think it is the practice of Druidry that is changing me to be more attractive to the spirits.  That is okay and I do what I can for them with prayers and making the house cozy and clean.  I suspect I should be doing more for them but am not sure what to do that would be helpful.  Is there any text that you would recommend?<br/><br/>I think one of them is a recently-deceased friend who takes things and then puts them back after a day or two just to let me know she has visited.<br/>Thanks from Maxine", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59035464", "title": "Re: Ghosts", "date": "2026-02-02 11:15 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Don't worry about texts. Just keep up the work -- they'll let you know if there's anything else you should do for them. One of the issues with coming into contact with spirits (of any positive kind) is that it marks the point at which you start learning a lot less from books and a lot more from the Unseen. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59037768", "title": "Re: Ghosts", "date": "2026-02-02 11:42 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "That has been my experience as of late. I'd take my improved ability to interpret divination as one example, but I've also noticed that certain questions I wonder about will sometimes have a quick answer hit me. These are often \"yes\" or \"no\" type questions, and I tend to get a strong impression from my spirit guide one way or another. And so far, I haven't had an impression lead me astray.<br/><br/>I don't know if you've ever read how the prophet Joseph Smith got his answers to questions, the revelations from his deity. His accounts indicate he would think about a question or issue, and then spiritual impressions would form. He often had to spend some time working out the impressions. To be clear, I don't claim prophetic ability but the accounts of his method/process fit my recent experiences.<br/><br/>Such an unexpected development for me. Many years ago, I was a militant atheist type who dismissed anything paranormal. The old me would be appalled by the new me. The new me gets a chuckle thinking about the old me."}, {"id": "cmt59052360", "title": "Re: Ghosts", "date": "2026-02-03 02:55 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you for letting me know.<br/>Maxine"}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58973000", "title": "Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-02-02 06:24 am", "user": "ecoprayer", "content": "<a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/tag/prayerlist\">At this page</a> is the full list of all of the requests for prayer that have recently appeared at <a href=\"https://ecosophia.net\">ecosophia.net</a> and <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org\">ecosophia.dreamwidth.org</a>, as well as in the comments of the prayer list posts (<a href=\"https://drive.google.com/file/d/1-ZTxAeYoPmpHA4H7wMRtYHyDvFf3ebgG/view?usp=drivesdk\">printable version here</a>, current to 1/29). Please feel free to add any or all of the requests to your own prayers.<br/><br/>If I missed anybody, or if you would like to add a prayer request for yourself or anyone who has given you consent (or for whom a relevant person holds power of consent) to the list, please feel free to leave a comment below.<br/><br/><center>* * *</center><br/>This week I would like to bring special attention to the following prayer requests, selected from the fuller list.<br/><br/><div style=\"\"><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=12322#cmt12322\">Larry Mulford</a>, who has entered hospice after a year battling with pancreatic cancer, pass in the smoothest possible manner, and may his wife be enveloped in our love.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1160.html?thread=12168#cmt12168\">Marko</a> have the strength to seize the opportunities.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/a-little-further-offline-than-usual/#comment-153526\">Luke Z and his house</a>, whose furnace has problems that can't be fixed until after the current severe weather ends, be blessed and kept safe until the cold subside.<br/><br/>May Pierre's young daughter, Athena, be healed from her fatigue and its root causes in ways that are easy, natural, and as holistic as possible.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/november-2025-open-post/#comment-149490\">Bob Ralston (aka Rasty Bob)</a>, who is in hospice care in Buckeye AZ, and who just lost his wife Leslie Fish, be blessed and find relief from his pain and discomfort; may Bob's heart remain strong. <br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/896.html?thread=7040#cmt7040\">Leslie Fish</a>, wife of Bob Ralston, who passed away in early December, be blessed and make a peaceful transition to her next existence.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/896.html?thread=4224#cmt4224\">Corey Benton</a>, who passed away on 12/10, be blessed and make a peaceful transition to his next destination.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/896.html?thread=4736#cmt4736\">Satoko L in Kyoto</a>, who is recovering at home after weeks of hospitalization for Acute Hepatitis while in a state of immunodeficiency, continue to heal quickly and safely, and return to full vitality.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18134.html?thread=452566#cmt452566\">5 year old Max</a> be blessed and protected during his parents' contentious divorce; may events work out in a manner most conducive to Max's healthy development over the long term.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/514.html?thread=2562#cmt2562\">Lydia G. of Geauga County, Ohio</a> heal and recover from prolonged health issues.<br/><br/>May both <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/347398.html?thread=57920774#cmt57920774\">Monika and the child she is pregnant with</a> both be blessed with good health and a safe delivery. <br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/338828.html?thread=56777612#cmt56777612\">Mary's sister</a> have her auto-immune conditions sent into remission, may her eyes remain healthy, and may she heal in body, mind, and spirit.<br/><br/>May the abcess in <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18448.html?thread=460560#cmt460560\">JRuss's left armpit</a> heal quickly.<br/><br/>May Brother Kornhoer's son Travis's left ureter be restored to full function, may his body have the strength to fight off infections, may his kidneys strengthen, and may his empty nose syndrome abate, so that he may have a full and healthy life ahead of him.<br/><br/>May HippieVikings's baby HV, who was born safely but has had some breathing concerns, be filled with good health and strength.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18134.html?thread=455382#cmt455382\">Trubujah's best friend Pat's teenage daughter Devin</a>, who has a mysterious condition which doctors are so far baffled by necessitating that she remain in a wheelchair, be healed of her condition; may the underlying cause come to light so that treatment may begin.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/16429.html?thread=392237#cmt392237\">Kevin’s sister Cynthia</a> be cured of the hallucinations and delusions that have afflicted her, and freed from emotional distress. May she be safely healed of the physical condition that has provoked her emotions; and may she be healed of the spiritual condition that brings her to be so unsettled by it. May she come to feel calm and secure in her physical body, regardless of its level of health.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/312140.html?thread=53408588#cmt53408588\">Frank R. Hartman, who lost his house in the Altadena fire, and all who have been affected by the larger conflagration</a> be blessed and healed.<br/><br/></div><div><br/><br/><center>* * *</center><br/>Guidelines for how long prayer requests stay on the list, how to word requests, how to be added to the weekly email list, how to improve the chances of your prayer being answered, and several other common questions and issues, are to be found <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/6373.html\">at the Ecosophia Prayer List FAQ</a>.<br/><br/>If there are any among you who might wish to join me in a bit of <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/1986.html\">astrological timing</a>, I pray each week for the health of all those with health problems on the list on the  astrological hour of the Sun on Sundays, bearing in mind the Sun's rulerships of heart, brain, and vital energies. If this appeals to you, I invite you to join me.</div>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58989896", "title": "Re: Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-02-02 03:17 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this as always. "}]}, {"id": "cmt58973256", "title": "spriritual blessing and healing: Modern Order of Essenes", "date": "2026-02-02 06:28 am", "user": "milkyway1", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>It's good to have you (and Magic Monday) back. Glad to hear all went well with your move, and I hope you will enjoy your new place! :-)<br/><br/>Since you happened to talk about the importance of blessing and healing work a bit further up, I hope it's ok if I submit a plug for the Modern Order of Essenes... ;-)<br/><br/>For those who don't know it, the Modern Order of Essenes has been passed on through JMG, via his teacher John Gilbert. It's a system of spiritual healing and blessing, including various modalities and techniques which will facilitate just this.<br/><br/>JMG published all the material here on his dreamwidth for self-study (under the tag \"Modern Order of Essenes\": <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/tag/modern+order+of+essenes\">https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/tag/modern+order+of+essenes</a> ). If you are interested and feel a more structured approach would be helpful for you, I've re-structured the material into a course format, and am publishing it in bi-weekly posts over on my site:<br/><br/><a href=\"https://thehiddenthings.com/topics/moe-course\">https://thehiddenthings.com/topics/moe-course</a><br/><br/>We're currently at the beginning of the Master grade, but the course stays open and available to everybody, and you can start out with Unit 1 whenever it suits you ( <a href=\"https://thehiddenthings.com/moe-course-intro-and-unit-1\">https://thehiddenthings.com/moe-course-intro-and-unit-1</a> ).<br/><br/>Since I also feel that blessing and healing work is very important in these weird times, I hope that a lot of people will take up the beneficial work of the MOE! :-)<br/><br/>Milkyway", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58990152", "title": "Re: spriritual blessing and healing: Modern Order of Essenes", "date": "2026-02-02 03:18 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Plug away. The world desperately needs more people directing their efforts to the work of healing and blessing just now. "}]}, {"id": "cmt58974024", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 07:47 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I took up the tarot based on your instructions 5 years ago and found I have a talent for consistently accurate readings due to feeling when handling the cards. I'm not sure what to do with what its telling me. For example, I'll get the 3 of wands as the outcome which ends up being me watching the movie A Christmas Carol featuring the ghosts of Christmas past, present, and future which is basically what my deck depicts (without Christmas ghosts). It's daily amusement experiencing things unfold like this, but I question what the value of it is. I thought it might be what happens when an open ended question like \"what do I need to know about today's events\" is asked. Could you recommend another form of divination that would contrast tarot as a daily divination? <br/><br/>Do you think GD magical practices would be problematic for someone with a debilitated moon in their birth chart? (lunar eclipse birth)<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58990408", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 03:19 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) If you've got that kind of rapport with the cards, ask them! See if you can get them to direct you to more productive uses of your divinatory abilities. <br/><br/>2) Not at all. If you had a badly afflicted Sun, that would be another matter, but the GD isn't a lunar path at all. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58995016", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 03:47 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "I have a badly afflicted Moon, Mercury, &amp; Saturn. Which occult systems should I avoid?<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58996552", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 04:05 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Most of them. An afflicted Mercury doesn't bode well for occult practice. Have you consider mysticism? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59001672", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 04:57 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "My Capricorn Neptune (which I assume is connected to mystic potential) is squared by an afflicted Saturn. but is near my ascendant, tightly parallel and sextile my Sun, and trine Mars. <br/><br/>I have also retained many of the habits of thoughts I picked up when I was an Internet Atheist, and while I will overcome some of that, insecurity about my beliefs seems to be from Sagitarrius Mercury squaring Pisces Jupiter.<br/><br/>So would mysticism even be an option for me at some point?<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59001928", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 04:59 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You'd probably be best off getting a full chart delineation from a good natal astrologer, and asking that question of someone with more experience in such things. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59003720", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:13 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "Would Chris Warnock be good for such a delineation?<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59006792", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:23 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't make recommendations. Others can suggest options if they wish. "}, {"id": "cmt59014472", "title": "\"The Worst Argument against Paganism\" and Questions on Phase 17 of \"A Vision\"", "date": "2026-02-02 06:41 pm", "user": "jprussell", "content": "Howdy,<br/><br/>Stephen Mandes Thomas did natal chart for me that I found quite helpful, and he's just published some books on Christian magic, so would likely be able to answer at least some of your questions: <br/><a href=\"https://www.etsy.com/shop/SecretFireMagicShop\">https://www.etsy.com/shop/SecretFireMagicShop</a><br/><br/>Jeff", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59026248", "title": "Re: \"The Worst Argument against Paganism\" and Questions on Phase 17 of \"A Vision\"", "date": "2026-02-02 08:18 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "Thank you"}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59032392", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 09:29 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "My Mercury is also afflicted, though it's the only affliction in my chart. Jupiter, Mars, and Venus are well-dignified. Saturn seems important, but it's not dignified or afflicted. I had a reading done by a professional astrologer and one of the comments that comes up several times is \"deep occult roots.\" When I asked them about what this meant I didn't really get a clear answer. <br/><br/>I've been practicing occultism for several years with somewhat mixed results, but overall my life has improved. I've had some visionary dreams, including an awe-inspiring appearance by a Hindu god. Didn't have any idea what to make of it, and I'm not Hindu, haven't studied it, had to look up who the god even was. <br/><br/>Currently practicing GSF, but I don't seem to have any talent whatsoever for divination. Some success with scrying. I feel I've gained some benefit from meditation and daily banishing.<br/><br/>I know I have to make up my own mind, but I value your insight. Can you offer an insight into if this is a good path for me?<br/><br/>I'm not really familiar with mysticism, but I'd be interested in learning more about it. Can you suggest a good starting point?<br/><br/>Thank you for your time, and congratulations on the new digs.<br/><br/>-DeeDee", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59035720", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 11:18 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If your life is improving and things are generally going well for you, then yes, occultism is a viable option. In terms of mysticism, the best introduction I know is Evelyn Underhill's useful little text <i>Practical Mysticism: A Little Book for Normal People</i>, which can be downloaded free of charge here: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://gutenberg.org/ebooks/21774\">https://gutenberg.org/ebooks/21774</a>"}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59027528", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 08:36 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Would the SOP-based systems that invoke the lunar current cause problems for someone with a badly afflicted moon?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59035976", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 11:20 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No. The term \"lunar current\" is purely symbolic -- it has nothing to do with the Moon in the sky. The SoP-based systems are generally speaking elemental rather than planetary in terms of their energy sources, and thus work well for most people irrespective of horoscopes. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59036488", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 11:22 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you!"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59029576", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 09:00 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Are the SOP based systems you have written books on more lunar leaning? I wondered because many of them are Earth focused, which are obviously linked closely with the moon's cycles.<br/><br/>My 3 card tarot answers were:<br/><br/>LBRP - 9-Cups-reversed; 8-Wands; Page-Wands<br/><br/>SOP -  5-Cups-reversed; Justice; Moon<br/><br/>What do you think?<br/><br/>I've been meditating on this a bit since a little seems to go a long way with me. <br/><br/>Congratulations on moving. As somebody who seems to get practically shuttled by the universe to new places when another life chapter emerges, I always enjoyed the boost of a fresh start in new surroundings.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59036232", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 11:21 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "What were the questions? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59037512", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 11:33 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Oh sorry about that, the questions were:<br/><br/>What is the outcome of practicing a GD based system of magic?<br/><br/>What is the outcome of practicing a SOP based system of magic?<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59040840", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 12:03 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "A mixed bag in either case. That's common enough, so I'd say the choice is up to you. "}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58974280", "title": "Charles Williams", "date": "2026-02-02 07:49 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Maybe this is a better place to discuss Charles Williams than on the other blog where it's off-topic.  Those golden dancing figures in \"The Greater Trumps\": perpetual motion?  They remind me of the orerrys (orerries?) in \"Little, Big.\"  What do you suppose is the hidden/occult source of power behind these?  Is there any reason to suppose that John Crowley was a Charles Williams fan?  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58991176", "title": "Re: Charles Williams", "date": "2026-02-02 03:26 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The golden dancing figures are echoing the movements of the officers in a Golden Dawn temple. Though his Christian fans don't like to admit this, Williams was a very active member of Arthur Edward Waite's branch of the Golden Dawn, and served as Hierophant (chief initiating officer) of the London temple for two six-month terms. My take is that Williams put that in partly because it's a good bit of literary color and partly as a nod and a wink to his fellow Golden Dawnies. As for the orrery in Crowley's <i>Little, Big</i>, other than the source of its power, it's based on real things. Here's a room-sized orrery in the Netherlands: <br/>[IMAGE:0]", "images": [{"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/df/Planetarium_Eise_Eisinga_in_Franeker.jpg", "local_path": "./data/archive/2026/2026-02-01_08-33PM_Magic_Monday_Returns/images/2026-02-02_03_26_pm_Planetarium_Eise_Eisinga_in_Franeker.jpg"}], "replies": [{"id": "cmt58995784", "title": "Re: Charles Williams", "date": "2026-02-02 03:56 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "There are at least two similarities between the two novels.  Both involve a \"special\" tarot deck, and both imply perpetual motion.  Beyond that, I don't see that much.  "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58974536", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 08:10 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "My daily practice consists of a morning LBRP, BRH, invokation to the lord of the universe, MP, circulation of the body of light<br/><br/>Nightly astral LBRP and meditation or pathworking<br/><br/>Im close to 10 years of spiritual practice now, but only 2ish years of ceremonial magic (still feel like Im trying to make sense of it).<br/><br/>Recently I added in a 2x daily invocation to my HGA. Really simple - visualise a glorious glowing gold angel and pray to it, invoke it.<br/><br/>This practice brings about a reliable and consistent response in my heart space - pressure, opening, joy, sometimes overwhelming bliss, laughter. Really strong energetic sensation.<br/><br/>Do you think that what I am experiencing is likely safe? What am I experiencing? I did not expect something so powerful from what seems to be a simple practice.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58991688", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 03:29 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's a simple practice but an effective one, and the effect is a good sign -- your heart/Tiphareth center is becoming more active. (You very likely worked with that center in a previous incarnation, thus the promptness with which it responded this time around.) Keep at it! You can go very, very far indeed with daily repetitions of that set of practices. "}]}, {"id": "cmt58974792", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 08:25 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "As etheric energy comes from the Sun and core of the Earth, what is the nature and source of astral energy?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58992456", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 03:30 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "All the energies present in this solar system -- etheric, astral, you name it -- come through the Sun, mediated by the planets and also by the star logoi (the regents of the 12 zodiacal signs). "}]}, {"id": "cmt58975048", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 08:26 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What are the effects of having a really well developed etheric body?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58992712", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 03:31 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Extraordinary vitality, excellent health, and the kind of personal energy that makes other people feel healthier and stronger the moment you enter the room. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58996296", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 04:04 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Meant to put this in the first question but only remembered after posting - how about a really well developed astral body?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58997320", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 04:07 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That depends entirely on your horoscope, since the astral is the plane on which astrology mostly functions. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59055432", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 04:12 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "I wonder if the etheric body is why some people age much more gracefully than others...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59055944", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 04:35 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's one of several factors, but yes, it's important. That's why breathing exercises, and etheric exercises such as yoga and tai chi, are so useful in maintaining a healthy old age. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58975304", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 08:28 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In one of your recent books you were talking about other forms of alchemy including weather alchemy. What are the methods and goals of weather alchemy?<br/><br/>Also what are some good sources on the more obscure types of alchemy?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58992968", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 03:32 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "All I know about weather alchemy is that it exists. Most of the odder types of alchemy survive, if they survive at all, as obscure traditions passed down from teacher to student; very little gets written down. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59005256", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:17 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Given how dangerous messing with the weather can be, I think this is probably a good thing...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59007304", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:24 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The same thing applies to other branches of alchemy. The old books sometimes warn that letting the secrets of alchemy become public could destroy whole kingdoms. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58975560", "title": "Norse gods and Elder tree disrespect", "date": "2026-02-02 08:33 am", "user": "sea_spray", "content": "Hi JMG<br/><br/>I'm curious to hear what other's experiences of the Norse gods has been. Thor has helped me out with some inner struggles recently so I've taken to wearing a Mjölnir. It feels like there's more to come if I want it. The overall impression I have so far would be that they are gods of strong people (or those who wish to be so) in hard times. Though they're not ones to lead you by the hand, more lay the appropriate challenge in your path and help you though it. Seeking personal strength seems like a good idea with the kind of time's we're heading into. <br/><br/>I was recently lucky enough to meet someone whose family have been worshipping the Norse gods continuously since pre-Christian times. Though I have my reasons to suspect that luck didn't have much to do with it. He could even identify the person in his lineage who first \"converted\" to Christianity. They've kept to themselves and gone to church, like everyone else, over the centuries to avoid violent attention.<br/><br/>Question 1:<br/>Any advice for getting to know the Aesir and Vanir? And what have other peoples impressions of them been?<br/><br/>Following an intuition, as I sometimes do, I took a cutting of an Elder tree in a local park in an attempt to root a cutting on the kitchen window sill, and plant one at home. I since found out (partly from your natural magic encyclopedia) that this might not have been that wise. <br/>I also noticed that the bush growing out from the foundations of my rental house was an Elder tree. Having read some more folk law in the interim I was more cautious, and spoke to the tree first. She (the description of her as an Elder lady felt right) understood that it was not a good place to grow and accepted that my attempting to move her was the best option, though she asked me to wait till the next day. <br/>While trying to extract her the next day, I felt that I could hear her cries of pain as I used a saw where necessary on roots and branches. She's currently in a bucket of water and I'm planning to plant her in a corner of the lawn once she starts to recover.<br/><br/>Question 2:<br/>Are there any ways to make up for the damage/disrespect of taking the original cutting? And any tips on helping her recover physically and otherwise from the traumatic and ill timed removal? It's summer where I live.<br/><br/>I've been playing around making staves and wands from different woods and they often feel powerful afterwards, in line with the type of wood. I remember reading somewhere in your writings I think about using a carrier oil with a magically active oil to anoint items. <br/><br/>Question 3<br/>Do you know if linseed oil would work as a carrier oil? I often use linseed oil to protect them when I'm done and I'm thinking of boosting their magical properties by anointing them with frankencense in linseed oil.<br/><br/>Question 4<br/>Do you know of any particular magical properties of flowering cherry wood?<br/><br/>Thanks<br/>Sea spray", "edit_time": "2026-02-02 09:47 am (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58991432", "title": "Re: Norse gods and Elder tree disrespect", "date": "2026-02-02 03:27 pm", "user": "neptunesdolphins", "content": "My experience was mixed. I felt that Odin recruits people to Paganism and Heathenry. Then sort of leaves it up to the rest of the Gods to talk to them. I tried venerating the Norse Gods but got little or no response. However, Frigg has adopted me, and I do have a practice to Her and her Handmaids. They do guide me."}, {"id": "cmt58993480", "title": "Re: Norse gods and Elder tree disrespect", "date": "2026-02-02 03:34 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I'll leave this to the Heathens here. I have a friendly relationship to the Heathen gods -- I respect them, and have made occasional offerings of good beer and mead while attending Heathen ceremonies -- but beyond that I don't have much experience with them. <br/><br/>2) Ask the tree, not me! <br/><br/>3) It should work quite well. <br/><br/>4) Not offhand, no. "}, {"id": "cmt59012680", "title": "Re: Norse gods and Elder tree disrespect", "date": "2026-02-02 06:04 pm", "user": "hippieviking", "content": "I had some crazy synchronicities most of a decade ago brought on by Odin initially. I went from being a pretty discontented and lost former atheist materialist who had become agnostic to a full on polytheist rather quickly. Intense personal experiences can do that! <br/><br/>The Norse gods are represented on the family alter in my house and they are what I suppose I would refer to as \"our\" gods. Then again, Brighid and the Morrigan are also represented in our house amongst others, so I guess we are polytheists of inclusion? <br/><br/>Anyway, I rarely ever invoke Odin but I have had a few dreams where he has shown up as Grimnir. I do however regularly invoke other Norse deities. I have found Tyr, Thor, Freya, Idunn, Bragi, and Njord to all be quite responsive. <br/><br/>My experience with the Norse gods is that they can be very helpful, responsive, and inspiring. They are also active and they are absolutely not gentle or slow. They will set you to challenges. Something along the lines of, \"I happen to know exactly what you need, even if you don't. Sure, let me help you set that up (sometimes right now!) and, of course, expect the universe to extract its toll shortly!\" To put another way, if you'd like some help becoming something greater than you are  invoke away but expect that if they answer you're going to pay for that growth up front and they will be watching and expecting that you deal with it upright and facing the challenge.<br/><br/>HV"}, {"id": "cmt59015496", "title": "\"The Worst Argument against Paganism\" and Questions on Phase 17 of \"A Vision\"", "date": "2026-02-02 06:49 pm", "user": "jprussell", "content": "Howdy,<br/><br/>For what it's worth, your experience is pretty similar to my own. The Germanic Gods seem very much to be the kind that \"help those who help themselves,\" and when I have asked for help, the response is usually something like \"you have what you need to handle this, just keep going,\" though sometimes with a reminder that I'm not all on my own and it's not hopeless.<br/><br/>As for specific Gods, I also find Thor a source of strength and comfort, as well as good, practical advice. Odin seems to sometimes put clues in my path for the sort of spiritual paths I should pursue. I turn to Tyr for hardiness and endurance and dedicate my daily work out to Him. Freyja seems to help me along the more intuitive side of my spiritual path. And Idun is the Goddess Who first made Herself known to me, opening my mind and spirit to the world of the divine, so She's very important to me, personally. I've had some contact with others, and I frequently add something like \"all the Gods and Goddesses\" to my prayers to make sure I'm disrespecting anyone.<br/><br/>Cheers,<br/>Jeff", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59042888", "title": "Re: \"The Worst Argument against Paganism\" and Questions on Phase 17 of \"A Vision\"", "date": "2026-02-03 12:39 am", "user": "hippieviking", "content": "That's interesting that you have a close relationship to Idunn. She doesn't seem to be too widely known but I have found her to be very active and responsive. She has an honored spot on our family altar.<br/><br/>HV", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59050056", "title": "Re: \"The Worst Argument against Paganism\" and Questions on Phase 17 of \"A Vision\"", "date": "2026-02-03 02:35 am", "user": "jprussell", "content": "Yeah, I get the impression She's much significant than the surviving myth suggests.<br/><br/>Cheers,<br/>Jeff"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59041096", "title": "Re: Norse gods and Elder tree disrespect", "date": "2026-02-03 12:10 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Odin and Frau Holle, a German Goddess, began coming to me in dreams about 35 years ago, and after initial hesitations I decided to follow their calls and have been Heathen ever since.  I find it a challenging but deeply rewarding path, well suited to all of life's challenges and to the good things in life as well.  I feel close to most of the Heathen deities, and drawn to the many deep and fascinating Mysteries of the Heathen worldview.<br/><br/>I explore many Heathen topics in the writings on my website, HeathenSoulLore.net, and have written 6 books on Heathen subjects. I don't think there's any possibility of exhausting the meaningful study and practice of Heathenism, for me or for anyone else. To all those who pursue this path I say \"Gods-speed\"!<br/><br/>And to our esteemed host: I hope you are settling well into your new digs.  My mother lived in Silver Spring and enjoyed it there; may you also soon feel at home there.<br/><br/>Winifred Hodge Rose<br/><br/>"}]}, {"id": "cmt58975816", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 08:34 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How much of the effect of rituals like the Middle Pillar and Sphere of Protection is etheric and how much is astral?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58993736", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 03:36 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's primarily astral, but since each plane tends to entrain the plane immediately below it, astral practices have an effect on the etheric plane which increases with regular repetition. "}]}, {"id": "cmt58976072", "title": "Books", "date": "2026-02-02 09:01 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,<br/>I have two questions regarding books. The first one is about your planned book on electional astrology, how is it coming along and when will it be available?<br/>The second is a recommendation on a book about astral projection. I have read quite a few books on the subject and all of them, so far, have been by authors drunk on either scientism or new age fairy dust, or a combination of the two. Do you know of any good, practically oriented books on the subject?<br/><br/>Thanks /Fredrik", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58993992", "title": "Re: Books", "date": "2026-02-02 03:37 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The finished manuscript is at a prospective publisher right now; I'm waiting for them to decide yea or nay. <br/><br/>2) W.B. Butler's book <i>Apprenticed to Magic</i> has a brief but very good set of instructions on the subject. "}]}, {"id": "cmt58976840", "title": "Prayer", "date": "2026-02-02 10:08 am", "user": "scotlyn", "content": "I mentioned a while back that I had developed a WOH-adjacent devotional ritual, by adding a water step to the ritual that Jenny learned in Kingsport, using potpourri and candles. <br/><br/>The method I developed and use is as follows: <br/>1. [dip fingers in blessed water, draw symbol on forehead] “With this water I am purified.”<br/>2. [take scent sticks and wave over altar, then sniff deeply] “With this scent I am attuned.”<br/>3. [light candles} “With this light I approach the deity, saying......”<br/><br/>Well, I recently received a copy of a book of introductory readings in Neoplatonic Philosophy (which your writings have inspired me to do).  And I was struck by the advice found in Iamblichus's advice on prayer (On The Mysteries of the Egyptians)... I was instantly attracted to two passages which outline a three-step process with which to approach divinity (bullet pointing by me): <br/><br/>[re: the theurgic “gateway to the creator of all things”] <br/><br/>“In the first place, it has the power to purify the soul, far more perfect than the power to purify the body...<br/>“...afterwards, it prepares the mind for the participation in and vision of the Good and for a release from everything that opposes it and...<br/>“...at the last, for a union with the gods who are givers of all things good.”<br/><br/>[re: prayer]<br/>“I declare then, that the first degree of prayer is the introductory, which leads to contact and acquaintance with the divine.<br/>“The second is conjunctive, producing a union of sympathetic minds and calling forth benefactions sent down by the gods even before we think of them. <br/>“The most perfect, finally, has as its mark ineffable unification, which establishes all authority in the gods and provides that our souls rest completely in them.”<br/><br/>Somehow, dare I believe, that my wee crayon scribble of a three-step ritual – purification, attunement, and approach - contains an echo of something much older and deeper? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58994248", "title": "Re: Prayer", "date": "2026-02-02 03:38 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's quite possible, you know, that you've done this before. It's also possible that your crayon was guided as you scribbled...<br/><br/>One way or another, it sounds like a good approach. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58996808", "title": "Re: Prayer", "date": "2026-02-02 04:05 pm", "user": "scotlyn", "content": "Thank you. <br/><br/>Just as a PS, and further thank you... <br/><br/>Your Revisioning the Tree of Life book has helped me get a proper daily meditation practice under my belt, after many years of fruitless \"intending\"...<br/><br/>Also, John Gilbert's book on Tarot has finally got me dipping my toes into divination, after many years of negative \"I'm no good at divination\" self-chatter. <br/><br/>The only \"leg\" of the tripod that I had really established with any regularity was the SOP.  Now, with the addition of the other two legs, its wobbles are being steadied a bit.  ;) ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58997064", "title": "Re: Prayer", "date": "2026-02-02 04:06 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm delighted to hear this -- thank you!"}, {"id": "cmt59016264", "title": "Re: Prayer", "date": "2026-02-02 06:54 pm", "user": "open_space", "content": "I am happy to hear this! (I will reply to you also later this week). For me when I got good at divination is when things got interestingly weird as the natural world is the greatest of oracles :-). "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58977096", "title": "Sixth plane", "date": "2026-02-02 10:11 am", "user": "revert2mean", "content": "Is it annoying to talk about the sixth plane again? Sorry, if so. <br/><br/>I'm very sad, and puzzled. I've mentioned before that I was told in a dream in 2014 that I needed to die soon in order to get home on time. Memorable image of me pedalling a space bike trying to catch up to the spaceship I was meant to be on, but missed. I said no, no, no, no, no, I need ten more years. It will be terrible for the kids to have their mother die now. <br/><br/>I felt that ten years was granted.<br/><br/>I'm now eleven years in to my ten year extension. I had a dream where I was on a plane, holding a baby, which was at terrible risk of falling out of the plane and into oblivion because I was holding it. My task was to carry the baby to another part of the plane - at great personal risk - and place it securely in a baby harness in another part of the plane, where it would be safe, but it could no longer be with me. <br/><br/>It's an uncomfortable dream. I guess I'm the baby, and I have to cut emotional ties to be kept safe, i.e. I have to die and leave the kids in order to fulfill my soul purpose. <br/><br/>It's not that I'm scared of dying, I'm just very very sad to leave the kids. And it seems a new world will start here without me. Fair enough, but still, I won't see it.<br/><br/>Why do I have to do all this thinking about it, if the decision's already made? <br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58994504", "title": "Re: Sixth plane", "date": "2026-02-02 03:39 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The decision may not be made...or you may not have made the decision you think you did. I'd encourage you to set the whole matter aside for now, and let the gods take care of it. "}]}, {"id": "cmt58977608", "title": "A bizarre experience...", "date": "2026-02-02 10:23 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello, <br/>I began my magical journey with LRM some years back and after completion, I decided to follow the Golden section fellowship. <br/><br/>By nature, I daydream a lot, have a vivid imagination and I can visualise fairly well. <br/>I use my daydreaming to visualise future discussions I believe I am going to have with friends or family or if ever I have to give a presentation soon enough and so on. I also daydream to review past discussions or presentations to see where I could do better. Needless to add, there is a lot of sexual daydreaming too. I also daydream of meeting imaginary people who would share my interests. <br/><br/>In a latest episode, I imagined myself being contacted by an elderly couple who invited me to tea at a hotel a few miles from my home that actually exists and to which I have been quite often. We would be discussing sacred geometry, a topic I study and am very fond of. <br/>In my daydream I entered the hotel lobby and made way towards the couple who was seated at a table. As soon as I sat down, to my surprise, the atmosphere began to change, the couple was very hostile to me and they and they hotel staff morphed into humanoid lizards à la David Icke! And the couple uttered only one sentence: \"Flee, we are out to get you\". Then the scene returned to normal, the hotel staff were back to proper human forms, the couple had disappeared. Taken aback but still day dreaming, a member of the staff tapped on my shoulder and asked if I was allright. I asked where was the couple and they replied there was nobody at this table. I walked off and ended my day dreaming. <br/><br/>Now this was supposed to be a day dream under my full control and somehow it got hijacked by processes outside my volition and will! <br/>Was it the watcher you mentioned several times, was it deep fears within my subjective mind erupting unannounced or was it something else...<br/><br/><br/>Comments welcomed! <br/>Thank you!<br/><br/>PS: I am not unduly alarmed by this episode anyway...<br/><br/><br/><br/><br/><br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58995272", "title": "Re: A bizarre experience...", "date": "2026-02-02 03:53 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's normal. What it means is that your \"daydreams\" are starting to become transparent to the wider astral plane. The word \"imagination,\" you know, is a catchall for your astral senses and organs of action. As you become more conscious of the astral plane, you will perceive more things from outside your own mind -- and yes, not all of them are friendly. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59002440", "title": "Re: A bizarre experience...", "date": "2026-02-02 05:06 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi again,<br/>Thanks! Presumably the SOP which I practice would help me in some way to face unfriendly things?<br/>Regards!<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59007816", "title": "Re: A bizarre experience...", "date": "2026-02-02 05:25 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, but it won't necessarily keep you from being fooled by dishonest spirits. Remember that they can tell lies..."}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58978120", "title": "On exercising the will", "date": "2026-02-02 10:39 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,<br/><br/>One of your comments last week about training the will got me to thinking about my own mixed efforts in that regard, and the reasons for failure. One consistent reason is that there are always good reasons to change one's mind and abandon the previous commitment. <br/><br/>There's a lot of words for people who stick by their will and refuse to change in the face of changing circumstances: obstinate, irrational, unreasonable, insane... I like to think of myself as a rational, smart, reasonable person and this seems to conflict with choosing a path and sticking with it simply because it's the one I chose. Most of the famous people we admire for their willpower were following their will in cases where the reasonable, smart thing to do was give in. <br/><br/>If there's anyone else out there who sees themselves as rational, smart and reasonable, you might want to check whether that self-image is undermining your strength of will. I've certainly had a bit more success since I embraced the idea that \"Yes, this is irrational and unreasonable, I'm doing it anyway.\" <br/><br/>Thank you for your help. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58995528", "title": "Re: On exercising the will", "date": "2026-02-02 03:55 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's an excellent point. There are always good reasons to change your mind; this is why it's best to start will training with exercises that are completely pointless, except as will training. When you put up a sticky note by your desk that reads \"Touch your nose,\" and you touch your nose with your left hand every time you notice it, it's a completely pointless act, so arguments against doing it mean nothing -- and that helps you build the habit of doing what you will. "}]}, {"id": "cmt58978376", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 11:25 am", "user": "open_space", "content": "<p>Dolores Ashcroft-Nowicki passed away early this month. For Jorge, myself and the rest of the Fraternity I am part of it has been a time of mourning since she was the one that passed on the Light and helped in the establishement of the school, carrying the legacy of Fortune and Butler and their work into Latin America.</p>\n<p>The moment she passed, a fierce storm hit Jersey Island. I think it is usual for this things to happen, at least I have heard of other instances of such things like earthquakes. </p>\n<p>1) Have you heard of instances of similar natural events ocurring at the time of a practitioner passing?</p>\n<p>2) Would I be too far in speculating that such events could happen as a repercution in lower planes as their soul move up to higher ones and leave the wheel of incarnation?</p>\n<p>It has also been a time of reflection and establishing myself in balance for me, and thinking on the increasing role magic and spirituality has been taking on in my life and what do I want to do with it. It is a rather lonely question since trying to express it to someone would only give me weird looks rooted in misunderstanding. A few weeks ago, when I was talking about the gods to an ex co-worker that is interested in magic, as real, intelligent beings that give you information and also often ask for you to do things, the reply I got was \"you need help\". I chuckled, to me it meant I had made it somehow, to the beginning phases anyway, but it also reflected something which is sometimes hard to deal with. Once some of the invisible causes of visible things start to become real to you, you really do feel out there and you can't talk about it without hurting your reputation. I felt Dolores understood that well. I don't think I have much choice but keep going but I wonder. When you where starting on this and magic stopped being words in a page but real, tangible, living things what helped you? It almost feels to me as if I have something wonderful in my hands, but not exactly sure what to do with it. Certainly more discipline would help me go more interesting places, in the end magic is not that much different from engineering and more discipline would produce some intersting things but on the existencial level, I still don't think I have my purpose clear.</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58996040", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 04:03 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I was sad to hear of Dolores's passing -- she'll be fine, of course, and we'll meet again down the road, but it's depressing to know I won't see her again in physical form in this incarnation. One of my teachers was the person she stayed with whenever she was in the Seattle area, and so I got invited to meet her many years ago and renewed the acquaintance at intervals. A fascinating, colorful figure, and one of the great. I'm not surprised the elements roared in grief and rage when they found out she was gone from their sphere. <br/><br/>As for me, from earliest childhood I desperately wanted the world to be a magical place. When I proved to my own satisfaction that ceremonial magic gets real results, I was practically hopping up and down, I was that delighted. I already knew that most people didn't believe that and had no tolerance for people who did, but (again, from earliest childhood) I was familiar with being the weird kid that everyone else despised, so I had no trouble keeping my mouth shut. <br/><br/>The one exception, of course, was Sara, for whom the reality of magic was a foregone conclusion; she'd been having psychic experiences all her life, and her mother's family had the second sight. She was taught growing up that you don't talk about such things outside the family, and she was delighted that she could tell me about the strange things she perceived. So it was very easy for the two of us. I don't imagine that will offer you any help, though. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59014728", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 06:44 pm", "user": "open_space", "content": "I never met her. Not in her form of flesh and bone but at least her self, or whatever aspect of ourselves that becomes always available, came through when I read her books and when I would direct my attention towards her. I believe that's what it was that directed me to where I am now, Jorge after all was one of her three or so close students and spoke every week. I came too late to receive instruction from her, but my course of study descends from her so in a way I can get to know her from her teachings and through Jorge. Just now I am doing a series of courses called The Mysteries of the Grail created by her and it always takes me places. Its not along the welsh tradition, but if you are interested I can see on sending you the correspondence course. I am also eager on reading her novel Johnny Nova, which she just finished months ago and is now available. <br/><br/>When I was a child I always wanted to prove to myself that magic was real too. I would try to move stuff with my hands and turn on the lights with my mind (once it worked). I also would poke at peoples feet and necks with a mental stick to see if they would scratch (with practice they do). My first experience with a fully materialized spirit was at 7 or 8. Mexico being Mexico the weird makes people laugh so I was always on good company, but that changes with age. Now most people I talk about it just brush it off or just think I am crazy, so I am not that used to the solitude, even among most occultists I find myself feeling distant. It is a bit sad to me most of us are too stuck in the forms and have little willingness to let The Light come through, individualism has our egos too big and fragile for that. After all, at least in my experience, force only flows when you have emptied yourself enough to become a vessel willing to be filled with something higher, even if temporarily. Then as now, I find company in my teachers, so you, Jorge, Sadhguru make me feel I am not completely crazy (if you don’t cultivate a little craziness, what's the point) but my fellows still find me a bit weird. I am slowly learning when to shut up and direct my need of being seen and feeling part of something somewhere else. Its comforting to know the gods are there and also that some good friends, including people I've met through your work, are also there.<br/><br/>It does offer me help, hearing others always does. Wittgenstein once said that its better to keep quiet than being misunderstood, but its also true that listening to someone and realizing with humbleness you can't fully understand them and still attempting too connects us and open us to the bigger world. So thank you. And also I thank Sara, I hope you don't find it weird that when I got to know she was psychic, I started trying to talk to her in prayer from time to time. I never met her in person either, but in her new form she has a witty, sharp and funny way of making a point. I hope your time without her physical self is getting easier and easier as the relentless tick of time moves on, and as you get to be in new environments.<br/><br/>I couldn't help but notice your comment about the two people up in the comments thread. I have been getting nudges from the Opener of Roads and also from Kalabhairava that amount to the point \"learn how to do this, it will be needed, its time, things as you know them are being destroyed\". I was at a funeral service here in India just recently, I was the aid of a swami conducting the last rites where the ashes are thrown to a pond full of fish after an invocation of the destroyer of ignorance and time is made. I saw a snake mercilessly devour one of them. It was a powerful message. Something is truly changing both in the inner planes and the outer. It's not coincidence that Sadhguru, the long awaited teacher of the theosophists and the rishis before them came at this time, or so the belief goes. He is probably not what they thought it was going to be, but it's always like that with prophecy. <br/><br/>Thank you for giving me the tools for this. When I did my first l summoning LRP my psychic senses were basically blasted open and I also was hoping up and down (that day I talked to a tree ¡and three squirrels! at 3am in the morning. It just that sometimes I forget and loose the thread and get stuck in existential dread. Once I up my capabilities things should get easier. Being in an ashram kicking up my body, energies and mind certainly helps. If one thing I've lacked on the path its been balance. Yogis know how to be sure you don't forget about that. JMG, you've made of me a fuddy duddy, here I am studying ancient traditions on the literal other side of the globe and developing a taste for the past with the corresponding shudder for whatever it is that is happening in the contemporary (I can't read most things written in the last 50 years and go: bleh). I thank you for that also. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58978632", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 11:58 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Just posting this from Mat Auryn of Psychic Witch flame. He used a bag of charms to do this divination on Trump. <br/><br/>\"Future Influence: Wheel of Fortune<br/>His fate is unstable and changing. High positions or advantage are temporary and outside forces, timing, and chance dictate outcomes more than anything he can do to fight it. There’s a loss of control and the inevitability of change.<br/><br/>Future Thoughts: Triceratops, Witch Hat, Mercury/Hermes<br/>Defensiveness meets communication and cunning. The triceratops is the thick armor, charging forward of old power and power dynamics. The witch hat suggests taboo or fear-based influence (think witch hunts, but I also associate it with “the witch’s cone of silence”) So there’s also a focus on keeping stuff hidden and Mercury indicates messaging, strategy, or legal/contractual maneuvering. He’s focused on using communication and strategy to maintain power or evade consequences and keep things hidden.<br/><br/>Outside Influence: Death Tarot<br/>The environment or society around him is signaling the end of an era. Structures or systems that supported them cannot last forever. This card points to unavoidable endings or transformations. Collapse of old systems or forced change. Hopefully this is also a literal omen for him.\"<br/><br/>The last bit is interesting as JMG noted that the astrology suggested that Trump would die in office.  We'll see. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58991944", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 03:30 pm", "user": "neptunesdolphins", "content": "How much of Auryn's divination is biased? How do people leave biases out of divining? I could read this a little different as the Death Tarot could be the collapse of the old world in favor of the new world, that Trump is forming."}, {"id": "cmt58997832", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 04:12 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "This all seems very plausible. We are indeed in the end of an era -- the era of the managerial-bureaucratic elite, which Trump is dismantling -- and the structures and systems that supported them, and the global US empire they ran, are going to bits around us. The conjunction of a triceratops and a witch hat seems very apropos for Trump, as he's both thick-skinned and intuitive, and has a good deal of New Thought training via his family connection with iconic New Thought teacher Norman Vincent Peale (Trump attended Peale's church during his teen years). Mercury also points to his mastery of online messaging and communication generally. As for the Wheel of Fortune, we are in the middle of vast transformations, and Jupiter -- the ruler of Trump X -- points to the absurd good fortune that so often benefits Trump. All in all, a good reading, if imperfectly interpreted. ;-)"}]}, {"id": "cmt58978888", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 12:17 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey JMG,<br/><br/>I'm glad to hear that your move has been successful. I've got a few questions now that you're back:<br/><br/>1) In Israel Regardie's <em>The Golden Dawn</em>, the LBRP pentagram is drawn clockwise, starting at the bottom, and the LIRP pentagram counter-clockwise from the top. In <em>The Heathen Golden Dawn</em>, both start at the top and the directions are reversed, the LBRP being counter-clockwise and the LIRP clockwise. Is this a change that you have made in the CGD and was included in the HeGD or is this HeGD specific? If it's the former (or the latter and you know the rational), why?<br/><br/>2) In <em>Monsters</em>, you say that etheric energies can act almost like solid matter if concentrated. Is this how frustrated teenagers can cause poltergeist phenomena?<br/><br/>3) Is it possible to learn how to do this intentionally? Not just causing a ruckus, I mean, but to concentrate etheric energies to remotely manipulate objects (telekinesis, I suppose)?<br/><br/>4) Unbelievable as it sounds, I was hagged just two days after reading about Hag attacks in <em>Monsters</em>. I first thought that it was just a plain old nightmare but divination confirmed that this was not the case. It seems to have been an entirely different phenomenon from the cat-thing I mentioned a couple of months back as this was the first time I heard the sandpaper footsteps. An astral LBPR stopped the attack, presumably before any damage was done as the day afterwards, I only felt the ordinary exhaustion of having slept a few hours too little (there was no way I was going back to bed after that).<br/><br/>What bothers me is that I have a salt jar on my nightstand and it still looks perfectly fine. If Hag attacks are etheric phenomena, shouldn't the jar have prevented it?<br/><br/>5) Regarding the theory that fae food could be toadstool in disguise, hence people being unable to return from Faery once they have eaten it, I was under the impression that healthy humans are able to consume toadstool, even if it's very unpleasant? Amanita muscaria is an entheogen, after all.<br/><br/>—David P.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58998600", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 04:22 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The classic GD pentagram ritual is strongly influenced by Christianity, so what you banish is the element of Earth -- \"the world, the flesh, and the devil.\" The Celtic GD ritual, being Druidical in its focus, doesn't do this; it invokes by tracing a clockwise descent from spirit through the elements, and banishes by tracing a counterclockwise reabsorption of the elements into spirit. The Heathen GD follows the latter pattern. <br/><br/>2) Yes. <br/><br/>3) Yes, but if you think I'm going to explain how in a public forum like this, think again. <br/><br/>4) The salt jar absorbs hostile spells. If you have further problems with hagging, you want to put a dish of vinegar somewhere in your bedroom. The acid vapor will prevent the spirit from maintaining a dense etheric body. <br/><br/>5) This is the kind of casual assumption that kills people. <i>Amanita muscaria</i> can drop you stone cold dead if you misjudge the dose -- that's why Siberian shamans fed it to reindeer and drank the reindeers' urine, which diluted the active constituents enough to make it somewhat safe. Many other toadstools are lethal poisons, which cause sudden total liver failure and the like. You can find all this out in tens of thousands of readily available sources online and off. Please be a little more wary! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58999880", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 04:38 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you.<br/><br/>3) Fair enough. I was more interested in knowing whether it's possible at all anyway, seeing as I'm far from ready to try anything that ambitious. I suspect that when I am, I'll have a rough idea how to find more information on the matter.<br/><br/>5) \"other toadstools\"—oh, the joys of learning English in a German school! We were (and presumably are) still taught many false definitions, such as tortoise being a synonym of turtle. This appears to be another such case. I was under the impression that toadstool was a name for <em>Amanita muscaria</em>, rather than poisonous mushrooms in general.<br/><br/>As for <em>A. muscaria</em>, noted. I would have done more research if I had planned to actually eat it.<br/><br/>—David P."}, {"id": "cmt59041352", "title": "Amanita Muscaria", "date": "2026-02-03 12:10 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I think you're overblowing the toxic affects of Amanita muscaria. https://www.amanitadreamer.net/ I have this woman's first book, have attended her talks both in person and online, and have used the mushroom myself. While it can make you quite sick if you take too much, it's not in the same class as the Destroying Angel (Amanita virosa, Amanita bisporigera, and Amanita ocreata) all of which destroy your liver over a period of a few days because they contain a toxin that your liver can't break down.<br/><br/>With regard to Amanita muscaria, the main reason Siberian shamans used the reindeer to process the mushroom was to achieve full muscimol conversion, which significantly increases the hallucinogenic effects of the mushroom. Without full conversion, which can be achieved in your kitchen without a reindeer, you end up with a lot more ibogaine in the tea you make from it. This is what will cause the gastric distress. Some people do go to the hospital for this but the effects are treatable. Whereas by the time you go to the hospital for the effects of one of the Destroying Angels, it will be too late because there is no cure.<br/><br/>FSHA<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59045960", "title": "Re: Amanita Muscaria", "date": "2026-02-03 01:58 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's entirely possible that I was misinformed, but I notice from a quick glance that there are some reports of deaths from <i>A. muscaria</i> consumption in online medical literature. I'm aware of the distinction between <i>A. muscaria</i> and the hepatotoxic species in the genus, however. <br/><br/>"}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58979400", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 01:10 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Welcome back and thank you for hosting. <br/><br/>I live in a townhouse—should I be concerned that ritual work could have impacts on neighbors, given that their homes are directly attached to mine? I’d also be curious if the effects of ritual on a space should be considered when traveling and staying in hotels, for example, where someone else is likely to be using the space after I vacate. <br/><br/>I hope the move has gone well; I live in the DC metro area myself and Silver Spring isn’t far from me, so if any assistance with getting settled in would be helpful then I’d be happy to help! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58999368", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 04:25 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) You should be fine. Sheetrock is a moderately effective etheric barrier, since it consists of crystallized gypsum. As for hotels, I do basic banishings and the like in them, but nothing more complex, precisely because someone else will have to deal with the vibe. <br/><br/>2) Thank you! I'm all moved in and settled at this point, but down the road a bit I'll be finding an opportunity to meet my local readers. I'll have to find a venue, though -- I had two Druid friends visit on Saturday, and three people is about as much as my current place will hold!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59008840", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:37 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) Is there anything in LRM that would be problematic to do in a hotel room?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59009864", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:41 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The final initiatory workings, certainly. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58979656", "title": "To ask - to give", "date": "2026-02-02 01:11 pm", "user": "emily07", "content": "To ask:<br/>Recently I tried restarting The Earth Mysteries Workbook, because I`m still faszinated by th old straight tracks and them going back ages of ages. In perusing the bibliography I´ve jumped to the conculsion that not some kind of ...physical force... sort of energiezes the ones that could be active in such ways but an entity of some kind. Is that a misconception, or partly maybe right, or something else?<br/><br/>To give<br/>1) About jumping to conclusions:<br/>Apparently there is a megalithic site/something in the area here and in that place nearby (separated by a highway (Autobahn) there is a street called \"Leppsteinwiesen\". In Austria (Eastern Tirolia) there is a mountain that is called \"Leppleskofl\" (...kofl apparentely being the local word for mountain) and I´ve jumped to the conclusion that maybe I should find out what kind of stone could come from the Leppleskofl and find out if that is a material interesting for the stoneage (or earlier ;-).<br/><br/>2) A few years ago I wondered if my life made any sense or was worth anything at all. This surfaced while kids and other adults were playing at a kind of fountain hereabouts where local people come to get water. I stared depressedly into a hedge.<br/>After some time of doing that my mind reported back that I actually was seeing something, I put out my hand (I was squatting) closed it around that object and it appeared to be a semiprecious grey stone (Halbedelstein). Probably it fell from a car of one of the people fetching water. First I wondered if I could somehow give it back - but there was no way that made sense to me. It felt as if the stone had come to (for?!) me.<br/>Then I decided it was an Omen and interpreted it as: no my life might not make sense and have no meaning at all, still it is precious (at least semi... ;-) I felt a kind of awe that in that precise moment of down-in-the-moutness that stone would come to me. I´m still very thankful for it.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt58999624", "title": "Re: To ask - to give", "date": "2026-02-02 04:28 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That's a common interpretation among students of the old straight tracks. We know so little at this point that it's impossible to tell whether it's correct or not.<br/><br/>2) Interesting! It could be anything from the early Stone Age to the Middle Ages -- mountain quarries with good stone were well known to the early Freemasons who built the big cathedrals, after all. <br/><br/>3) Definitely an omen. Just remember that life doesn't have to make sense to us -- human beings aren't that smart, really. Doubtless there's a purpose to it all, known to the gods. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59019592", "title": "Re: To ask - to give", "date": "2026-02-02 07:36 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you, and a short update: a Läppstein is a stone much like a grinding stone, so probably more the middle ages", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59020872", "title": "Re: To ask - to give", "date": "2026-02-02 07:43 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Grindstones became very valuable in the Neolithic, since that's what you used to put a polish on the stone tools of the time, and remained valuable straight through the  Bronze and Iron ages for similar reasons. So it may be quite ancient! "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58979912", "title": "Reciting the first Orphic Hymn \"Orpheus to Mousaios\"", "date": "2026-02-02 01:22 pm", "user": "s33k3r", "content": "Dear JMG,   thanks for taking the time to host another Magic Monday, despite the circumstances. I hope that these will normalize for you soon.<br/><br/>Recently I have read up on and intensified my Hellenic polytheist/theurgic practice alongside the practice of the GSF material.<br/><br/>I know I have to be careful with the way I phrase this question as will become clearer further below - but as far as I am aware something similar has not yet been asked and should provide some insight for those interested. <br/><br/>  I have started reciting the Orphic Hymns corresponding to the deities of the weekdays and thought about starting this little ritual with the first Hymn “Orpheus to Mousaios” as in my view it adds a whole other dimension to invoke and honor essentially the whole pantheon first.   However, in Patrick Dunn’s translation there is this line in the first hymn: <br/><br/>“I call on (…) the most holy daimon, and the daimon baneful to mortals too, and the daimons of heaven, of the air, in the water, and the earth, under the earth, and coursing through fire”. <br/><br/>This line is much more explicit in who one is calling on than Taylor is in his translation which made me reconsider the idea of reciting this hymn, especially on a regular basis. I have no troubles invoking the agathos daimon or the elemental spirits (that’s part of the SoP anyways) - but an invitation for baneful spirits - even in the hierarchy and company of the rest of the pantheon might not be all that smart.   <br/><br/>1) What would you advise? How would you categorize this kind of working considering the presence of children under the age of seven in the home?   I am intrigued but I don’t want to end up like the Sorcerer’s Apprentice - especially insofar as other people might get affected.<br/><br/>2) If that hymn is used wouldn’t it be appropriate or even necessary to add a “license to depart” or some other formula of dismissal? There doesn’t seem to be one supplied in the Orphic material. <br/><br/>3) On a tangential note: Is the use of the corresponding essential oils in a burner an adequate replacement for the burning of incense for the weekday invocations? (I’ve tried different configurations but the smoke alarm is not happy with the fumigation and cannot otherwise be mitigated.)<br/> <br/>I might be overly cautious here, but I figured it’s best to seek counsel if it is so graciously offered.  <br/><br/>Thank you very much!<br/><br/>  -Florian", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59000392", "title": "Re: Reciting the first Orphic Hymn \"Orpheus to Mousaios\"", "date": "2026-02-02 04:52 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) This is why I always use the Thomas Taylor translations. He was a practitioner, not just a scholar -- he worshipped the old gods, and adapted the old hymns intelligently to fit modern conditions. I also don't recommend the Hymn to Musaeus in a household setting, precisely because it invokes some fairly perilous powers -- my sense is that back in the day, it was used exclusively in mystery temples. <br/><br/>2) You can't banish a god, or even give one license to depart. Once you invoke them, there they are. Thus it's important to be careful whom you invoke. <br/><br/>3) You can certainly use essential oils in a burner. I've taken to using herbal potpourris myself. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59007560", "title": "Re: Reciting the first Orphic Hymn \"Orpheus to Mousaios\"", "date": "2026-02-02 05:24 pm", "user": "s33k3r", "content": "Thank you for confirming my suspicions in this matter. (\"I have a bad feeling about this.\")<br/><br/>I will postpone the use of that hymn until the right circumstances in my life should arrive (i.e. within the context of an appropriately working order/mystery tradition dedicated to such matters in the proper ritual space under the guidance of experienced adepts).<br/><br/>For the time being I will stick to the regular weekday invocations - and to that of Athena. <br/><br/>As a follow up question: Which weekday would be appropriate for the recitation of the Orphic Hymn to Athena? Tuesday because of the Martian connection? Or Wednesday because of the Mercurial attributes of Athena? Or does the day matter at all?<br/><br/>And a note on the Dunn translation: I found it a bit odd, to be honest, as it is subtitled \"A new translation for the occult practitioner\". It seems the translation is quite literal and thus far less suited to ritual practice than is Taylor's. It's interesting and enlightening to read this new translation, sure. But for practical use I would not recommend it. This surprised me as Dunn himself is a practitioner. He also wrote <em>The Practical Art of Divine Magic</em> which I find an excellent resource. <br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59008328", "title": "Re: Reciting the first Orphic Hymn \"Orpheus to Mousaios\"", "date": "2026-02-02 05:29 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Athena's not a planetary goddess, so can be invoked any time you like.<br/><br/>My use of the Orphic hymns is (of course!) idiosyncratic. I've written three hymns in the same meter, using large chunks of Taylor where appropriate, for the three Druid deities Hu the Mighty, Ced the Earth-mother, and Hesus. I recite these daily, followed by the hymn for the planet corresponding to the day, and then the hymn to the Genius or Daimon. The results have been consistently very good. <br/><br/>I mention this partly to indicate that I've had excellent practical results with Taylor's hymns, and partly to suggest that there's a lot of wiggle room in this kind of work. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59015240", "title": "Re: Reciting the first Orphic Hymn \"Orpheus to Mousaios\"", "date": "2026-02-02 06:47 pm", "user": "s33k3r", "content": "Thank you very much. <br/><br/>I will work toward some similar arrangement of the hymns for daily practice and will rely on my own experimentation. <br/><br/>So far I have recited the hymns before going over to the SoP, purely based on my intuition. I could come up with a variety of reasons for any order. Would you have any recommendation?<br/><br/>Thank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59021384", "title": "Re: Reciting the first Orphic Hymn \"Orpheus to Mousaios\"", "date": "2026-02-02 07:45 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I do it the same way -- I make offerings (wheaten cakes, fresh water, and the scent of a forest potpourri), recite the hymns as prayer, and then do my ritual and meditation practice. They seem to be well satisfied with that. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59037000", "title": "Re: Reciting the first Orphic Hymn \"Orpheus to Mousaios\"", "date": "2026-02-02 11:28 pm", "user": "not_gandalf", "content": "I have Dunn's book as well as Taylor's and the scholarly translation by Apostolos Athanassakis. I've been doing what you're doing for years, that is, reciting the appropriate hymn for the day, and I've been using the \"AA\" translation. I felt that Taylor jiggered stuff around to fit the hymns into a meter, and so I preferred to use the \"literal\" words, but I've come to feel that AA is a little dead and dry. Dunn's is much more lively. I should try the Taylor version and see how that works. I can tell you that I much prefer Dunn's version of the Hymn to Hekate to the others (I use this one on New Moon days). That said, Dunn's book is for the occult practitioner, I think, because he includes a lot of practical things people can do with the hymns based on his practice in Wicca. I'm not making use of these things myself, but I consider his translation very valuable as an alternate, but still quite literal, reading of the hymns. But, as is frequently said here, your mileage may vary..."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59002184", "title": "Re: Reciting the first Orphic Hymn \"Orpheus to Mousaios\"", "date": "2026-02-02 05:06 pm", "user": "scotlyn", "content": "Re No 3, another option is the one I've been using, called fragrance sticks or reed diffusers.  <br/><br/>These are absorbent wick-like sticks which permanently sit in a \"bath\" of a base oil (eg sweet almond oil), which you refresh from time to time with your chosen essential oil.  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59015752", "title": "Re: Reciting the first Orphic Hymn \"Orpheus to Mousaios\"", "date": "2026-02-02 06:51 pm", "user": "s33k3r", "content": "Thank you for that recommendation. <br/><br/>I might use this method for my smaller altar dedicated to Hestia - since I won't have to change the scents around daily. For the daily recitations I will likely switch to using a candle powered oil burner. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58980168", "title": "Wrethched Hive", "date": "2026-02-02 01:32 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good morning John, from your last posts about your move and three new books it seems your blogging break was quite fruitful.<br/><br/>This came across my RSS feed a couple of days ago and I thought I'd share with the group in case anyone wanted to join in some Imbolc tomfoolery: https://www.patheos.com/blogs/witchonfire/2026/01/imbolc-spell-burning-world/<br/><br/>I especially like the \"collapse of false structures\" as that seems to be exactly what is happening in Minnesota these days....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59000648", "title": "Re: Wrethched Hive", "date": "2026-02-02 04:54 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Not bad at all. I hope she'll be happy if she gets what she's asking for. "}]}, {"id": "cmt58980424", "title": "Mystic Bliss", "date": "2026-02-02 01:35 pm", "user": "cs2", "content": "I have the unlimited annual pass for a museum full of Greco-Roman statues and paintings of these gods. Recently I've found that even just walking by and viewing the statues on the exterior of the building, I bliss-out, per se. I'm \"lifted\" to where my worries fall away (and my sex drive) and I am soothed and chill. To put colors on it, everything is white with gold foil trim. If I just pass by then it lasts maybe an hour, but if I visit the museum it can last the rest of the day.<br/><br/>1. I am wondering if that description is enough for you to identify what this is and whether I should keep doing it. I do not suspect this is hindering my DA work on my mental sheath because my thoughts continue to be clear- I'm not \"zoning out\" and turning my brain off. Thanks for your time.<br/><br/>2. With your permission I have kept you and Sara on my daily blessing candle for the past two years and I'm wondering if you'd like to renew for another year. Best wishes, -cs2", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59002696", "title": "Re: Mystic Bliss", "date": "2026-02-02 05:08 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Okay, the Bellman's Law has just been invoked: \"What I tell you three times is true.\" You're the third person in this Magic Monday thread to bring up evidence that the old powers are waking up in a big way. <br/><br/>That effect is what ancient statues of the gods and goddesses were meant to cause. They weren't just artworks -- they were talismans intended to evoke the presence of the Divine. What you experience is what ancient worshippers experienced when they went to the temple to make an offering. By all means keep doing it -- and if it feels appropriate, don't hesitate to pray to the deity or deities of your choice. <br/><br/>2) Thank you and I'd be grateful if you were to continue. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59030344", "title": "Re: Mystic Bliss", "date": "2026-02-02 09:10 pm", "user": "cs2", "content": "I already visit the statues to pray, so we were thinking along the same lines! ;)<br/><br/>On statues as talismans: was there some mechanism that consecrated them (a ritual by priests?), such that ancient Greek statues would be more effective or potent than nineteenth-century ones? This museum has Roman copies of Greek originals, and even some Greek originals from Ephesus. <br/><br/>But elsewhere there are 19th century ones...at that museum I don't automatically get blissed-out, but that's also likely because it is a super packed museum. The statues are placed right in the opening foyer and it's just nuts. <br/><br/>For the newer statues, does the material count? Is plaster less effective than bronze or marble. Thank you.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59038024", "title": "Re: Mystic Bliss", "date": "2026-02-02 11:44 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) If you already pray to them, no wonder the gods are blessing you! <br/><br/>2) There was an entire sacred science of making statues that functioned as talismans, which the Greeks inherited from the Levant and ultimately from Mesopotamia. There were specific procedures used, which some people these days (I'm one of them) are trying to reconstruct and bring back into practice. <br/><br/>3) Good question. I haven't seen any information along these lines yet -- but then the statues I use are wooden. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59049032", "title": "Re: Mystic Bliss", "date": "2026-02-03 02:33 am", "user": "ritaer", "content": "If I recall correctly some of the legendary images from classical times were wood--often very roughly shaped but with legendary origin stories, such as having fallen from the heavens. But it seems that images of the gods were made in various materials depending on the wealth of the temple or the homeowner. As with Egyptian scarabs made from clay, glass or gold or precious gems. I discovered a very nice line of wooden deity statues from Ukraine when I was shopping for an image of Epona. <br/><br/>Rita ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59053128", "title": "Re: Mystic Bliss", "date": "2026-02-03 03:06 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's quite correct. <i>Xoana</i>, wooden images, were very often the central holy items in the oldest Greek temples.  That's one of the reasons I used wood for the statues on my home altar. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59056712", "title": "Re: Mystic Bliss", "date": "2026-02-03 04:43 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "\"You're the third person in this Magic Monday thread to bring up evidence that the old powers are waking up in a big way.\"<br/><br/>Sounds like something that the Saturn-Neptune conjunction at 0 AD would correlate with. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59057224", "title": "Re: Mystic Bliss", "date": "2026-02-03 04:58 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, that had occurred to me also. If it keeps happening in upcoming Magic Mondays, I'll pay attention. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58980680", "title": "Astrological correspondences of plants and herbs", "date": "2026-02-02 01:41 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Greetings JMG,<br/><br/>I've been using your natural magic encyclopedia for many years, since the information in there is so well arranged and useful on many endeavors.<br/><br/>I wanted to ask from which specific books came the astrological correspondences atributed to the plants you list. I tried to guess it by looking at the bibliography of the book, but i would greatly apreciate your help.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59002952", "title": "Re: Astrological correspondences of plants and herbs", "date": "2026-02-02 05:09 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's been almost thirty years since I wrote that book. At this point, I haven't the least idea which of the many sources I read provided which bit of information. Sorry!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59005768", "title": "Re: Astrological correspondences of plants and herbs", "date": "2026-02-02 05:19 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "well, if i may frame the question in a wider sense: Where can i find another book that lists more plants and stones, with astrological correspondences?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59006536", "title": "Re: Astrological correspondences of plants and herbs", "date": "2026-02-02 05:22 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'll have to throw this one open to the commentariat. Anyone have any suggestions? "}, {"id": "cmt59009352", "title": "Re: Astrological correspondences of plants and herbs", "date": "2026-02-02 05:39 pm", "user": "scotlyn", "content": "I cannot say anything about stones, but certainly the herbal offerings of Nicholas Culpeper (early 1600's) assigned astrological correspondences to every herb discussed. <br/><br/>(one of his works is here: <a href=\"https://www.gutenberg.org/files/49513/49513-h/49513-h.htm\">https://www.gutenberg.org/files/49513/49513-h/49513-h.htm</a> )<br/><br/>Culpeper was a \"working person's\" herbalist, in that he was interested in giving people more understanding of and power over their own health.  His view of the apothecary trade (to which he had been apprenticed) was that it was too focussed on its own mystique, and insufficiently interested in enabling people to learn to manage health matters for themselves. :) <br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59013192", "title": "Re: Astrological correspondences of plants and herbs", "date": "2026-02-02 06:07 pm", "user": "angelica5804", "content": "Scotlyn, thank you for this!I am a long time herbalist and it's fun and interesting to see the planetary correspondences of my favorite plants. Many are herbs of Venus which is interesting.  I wonder about using plants in support of planetary charity. Hmm.<br/><br/>~Angelica "}]}, {"id": "cmt59017800", "title": "Re: Astrological correspondences of plants and herbs", "date": "2026-02-02 07:20 pm", "user": "isaac_hill", "content": "I just finished a book called \"The Zodiac Garden\" which will hopefully be out in April, and goes into all this, particularly in the scope of astrological gardening, but here are some of my favorite sources:<br/>Nicholas Culpeper's 'The English Physician', 'The Picatrix' (JMG &amp; Chris Warnocks translation is great), Agrippa's 'Three Books of Occult Philosophy' (Eric Purdue translation), Lilly's 'Christian Astrology', Joseph Blagrave's 'Astrological Practice of Physick', and the modern \"The Green Mysteries\" by Daniel Shulke. These are more focused on herbal correspondences, but some of them have stones too. There are some great traditional lapidaries around as well, such as 'The Lapidary of King Alphonso X', and Albertus Magnus's 'Book of Minerals'. I would not really recommend \"Magical Herbalism\" by Scott Cunningham.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59054664", "title": "Re: Astrological correspondences of plants and herbs", "date": "2026-02-03 03:51 am", "user": "angelica5804", "content": "Ooh!  Please keep us posted, Isaac."}]}, {"id": "cmt59018056", "title": "Re: Astrological correspondences of plants and herbs", "date": "2026-02-02 07:20 pm", "user": "frittermywig", "content": "JMG has previously recommended Stephen Taylor's <a href=\"https://spirit.aeonbooks.com/product/the-humoral-herbal/93719\">The Humoral Herbal</a>. No stones listed of course, but the bibliography has 75 or 80 sources that might be helpful."}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58981192", "title": "Nabatean agriculture", "date": "2026-02-02 01:52 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "So i've been reading the Picatrix for a while, and yesterday the thougt hit me that one of the main sources of Picatrix is this controversial book, the Nabatean agriculture, about whom seemingly scholars wildly disagree about their exact origin.<br/><br/>My question: Have you read it?<br/>If so, do you know about it's current availability in English, French, German or Spanish?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59003464", "title": "Re: Nabatean agriculture", "date": "2026-02-02 05:13 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I haven't had the chance to read it, since it exists only in Arabic and has never been translated into any European language. (There are a few scraps in scholarly studies in German, French, and English.) If somebody were to produce a decent English translation, I'd buy a copy so fast my payment would have scorch marks on it. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59004744", "title": "Re: Nabatean agriculture", "date": "2026-02-02 05:17 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How comes it was never translated in the court of Alfonso the wise, being quoted in the Picatrix?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59006280", "title": "Re: Nabatean agriculture", "date": "2026-02-02 05:21 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "We don't know. Maybe they didn't have access to a copy, or other projects were higher on the stack. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59018312", "title": "Re: Nabatean agriculture", "date": "2026-02-02 07:23 pm", "user": "isaac_hill", "content": "You can find large parts of it translated in Jaakko Hämeen-Anttila Turner's 'The Last Pagans of Iraq: Ibn Wahshiyya and His Nabatean Agriculture' Leiden: Brill, 2006. - It's out of print and insanely expensive, but in situations like this, I don't mind downloading a free PDF. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59031624", "title": "Re: Nabatean agriculture", "date": "2026-02-02 09:17 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This appears to be available at archive.org!<br/>https://archive.org/details/the-last-pagans-of-iraq"}, {"id": "cmt59050312", "title": "Re: Nabatean agriculture", "date": "2026-02-03 02:39 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Speaking of the last pagans of Iraq--have others noticed the assertions online that some of the Iranian rebels are interested in rejecting Islam and returning to the Zoroasterian faith? It does seem unlikely, given how long the region has been Islamic, but stranger things have happened. <br/><br/>Rita"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58981448", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 01:58 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,<br/>Your guidance on suitable planetary charity would be much appreciated. <br/>My partner survived breast cancer a few years ago, and we are obviously worried it might reoccur. Would planetary charity help to keep her safe, and if so to which planet? Would a single series of donations be adequate, or would, say, regularly monthly donations without a time limit be better? And does the amount you actually donate influence the power of the working, assuming of course that it's multiples of the correct number? <br/>Apologies if this seems unnecessarily complex, but it's hard to find definitive guidance online. <br/>Thanks. <br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59003976", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:15 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The Moon rules nursing, breasts, and women's health generally, so she's the planet to invoke. I would suggest that your wife make a donation every year on or near her own birthday. No, the influence of the planetary gods doesn't depend on dollar amount, though it shouldn't just be a token gift. "}]}, {"id": "cmt58982472", "title": "Dolmen Arch", "date": "2026-02-02 02:03 pm", "user": "trubrujah", "content": "Welcome back and I hope you are settling in to your new location well.<br/><br/>I am happy to report that of the seven who started the Dolmen Arch group, four of us have completed the exercises to move onto to Grade 2.  Here is the latest update on the group work:  <a href=\"https://thelongdescent.substack.com/p/gradd-y-newyddian\">https://thelongdescent.substack.com/p/gradd-y-newyddian</a>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59004232", "title": "Re: Dolmen Arch", "date": "2026-02-02 05:16 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Delighted to hear it. "}]}, {"id": "cmt58982728", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 02:11 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good to have you back, JMG!<br/>I hope you managed to get some rest.<br/>I missed Magic Monday.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59004488", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:16 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this. Now's the time when I get to rest -- the last week in particular was very strenuous -- but I can fit answering Magic Monday questions around a nice long afternoon nap. ;-)"}]}, {"id": "cmt58982984", "title": "Runny noses on Imbolc", "date": "2026-02-02 02:14 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Howdy JMG,<br/><br/>Welcome back! So using discursive meditation. What is the protocol for meditating with a runny nose? Umm ... asking for a friend...<br/><br/>108", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59005000", "title": "Re: Runny noses on Imbolc", "date": "2026-02-02 05:17 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Have tissues and a waste paper basket close by, and try to keep your thoughts focused on the theme even when blowing your nose. It's a useful bit of training. (Yes, I've done this tolerably often in the past, though I don't get colds much these days.) ", "edit_time": "2026-02-02 05:18 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59043144", "title": "Re: Runny noses on Imbolc", "date": "2026-02-03 12:59 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you! The weather up here in Maine proved sunny and warm for the first time in weeks, so the Imbolc meditations went off without incident. However, I will keep this advice in my back pocket for the future.<br/><br/>108"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt58987848", "title": "Time and Distance", "date": "2026-02-02 03:01 pm", "user": "degringolade", "content": "Well, I bought your book (mundane Astrology, and unfortunately quite a few more) and I am working my way through the process algorithms of the discipline.  I haven't come to any conclusion yet, but this far, I don't see any huge problems.<br/><br/>But I was wondering, and I can't seem to find anything that addresses this, so I will ask here:  <br/><br/>Is there any school of astrology that takes into account the actual distance between earth and the other planets (inferior and superior conjunctions) when building a chart?<br/><br/>Thanks in advance to everyone who wants to swing at this.  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59005512", "title": "Re: Time and Distance", "date": "2026-02-02 05:18 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I have never encountered one that does. "}, {"id": "cmt59011400", "title": "Re: Time and Distance", "date": "2026-02-02 05:50 pm", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "I wouldn't expect exact distance to be significant.  The astral light, which in some schools of thought is the source of astrology's influence, works primarily on the astral plane, where distance is best thought of as a suggestion.<br/><br/>(Think about how distance in dreams works: there's usually a clear separation of *here* and *there* but a *there* that seems very far might be quicker and easier to reach than one that seems very near, even accounting for obstacles.)<br/><br/>That said, there are two factors in astrology that are significant and which correlate closely with distance: first, the planet's speed in the sky (closer = faster = more obvious but shorter-lasting influence vs. farther = slower = more subtle but longer-lasting influence), and second, the fact that Saturn is the farthest planet ordinarily visible to the naked eye.<br/><br/>Because of this, Saturn corresponds to natural limits, and many of the things ruled by Uranus and Neptune are about going beyond those natural limits through various ways of shifting the cost of doing so onto something or someone else.<br/><br/>(Uranus is *occasionally* visible to the naked eye but hard to recognize as a planet, which makes quite a bit of sense of the status of some prominent Uranian phenomena throughout history.)"}]}, {"id": "cmt59003208", "title": "Magical update: snow, and prayer", "date": "2026-02-02 05:12 pm", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "Hope you don't mind a 2-for-1, just getting caught up with recent experiences. Anyway...<br/><br/>During the recent snowstorm, I spoke to it, as I have with plants and thunderstorms, saying that I respect its formidable snowfall and its place in the natural order of things. Afterwards, I felt better, but in a strange way. While plants gave me green, vital energy, and thunderstorms gave me a wild, indomitable energy, the snowstorm's energy felt... sedate, or mysterious, maybe? But other than that, it's really hard to describe. Is this typical of snow spirits?<br/><br/>Also recently, I was sitting back, reminiscing, and an incident from childhood came to mind, in which I was at a McDonalds, acting randomly as kids do, and some douchelord (probably 20s at the time) made fun of me (I won't get into exact details). It was a minor thing, yet I kept thinking about it, and one of my key faults is my inability to forgive or let go of things, even minor slights. I was so filled with spite that I began to pray to the powers-that-be, asking if perhaps that guy could be walloped with negative karma and burn in it, for the sake of justice and retribution (that's how I worded it). I paused to listen, and I heard a voice in my head -- quiet and distant, yet firm and clear:<br/>\"If you were concerned with justice, you'd let him reap his own karma instead of flinging curses at him. If you want retribution however, you may have that, but only at the cost of your own karma\".<br/>That sobered me up, and realizing I was wrong, withdrew my request, saying he can face karma in his own way, and I won't pile on out of spite. I heard:<br/>\"Well done, Daniel\".<br/>Anyway, do you have any comments on this particular experience? And I wonder, which power did I contact -- could it have been Saturn, or someone else?<br/><br/>Thanks again for MM.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59006024", "title": "Re: Magical update: snow, and prayer", "date": "2026-02-02 05:20 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That sounds like the snow spirits I've encountered, certainly. <br/><br/>2) It was probably your guardian genius aka your guardian angel. They have the right and power to intervene in exactly that way, by offering good advice, at important turning points. Had you ignored the voice -- which you could have done; they can't force you to listen -- you'd probably have become a pretty fair douchelord yourself by now...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59010632", "title": "Re: Magical update: snow, and prayer", "date": "2026-02-02 05:45 pm", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "I see, thanks!<br/><br/>re: snow spirits, it's good to have that confirmed, and to put such experiences in a larger context.<br/><br/>re: prayer, I honestly wouldn't have thought of my guardian, but yes, that's likely correct. As for being a douchelord, I feel like that sort of thing takes multiple wrong turns rather than just one, right? So I've probably been listening to my guardian quite a few times, in the form of intuitions or good/bad feelings about things; this latest bit is simply the most direct, I should think.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59011656", "title": "Re: Magical update: snow, and prayer", "date": "2026-02-02 05:50 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "2) Yes, but there's often one major wrong turn, with others leading up to or following upon that one. The fact that you listened and responded so promptly does suggest that your guardian has been working with you more quietly for a while. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59049544", "title": "Re: Magical update: snow, and prayer", "date": "2026-02-03 02:34 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "Interesting, thanks.<br/><br/>btw, I assume the guardian is a significantly more advanced being than their human charge, right? I was struck by the incisive wisdom of the response, which led me to mistake them for a higher power.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59052872", "title": "Re: Magical update: snow, and prayer", "date": "2026-02-03 03:05 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The guardian angel or guardian genius is not so much advanced as wholly attuned with the Divine -- in Dion Fortune's system, which I tend to use as a fallback, the guardian angel of each soul is a manifestation of the Solar Logos, the chief god of this solar system, as specialized for the needs of that individual soul. That is to say, it's a very high power indeed, just stepped down to a level you can access. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59053640", "title": "Re: Magical update: snow, and prayer", "date": "2026-02-03 03:11 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "Fascinating stuff, thanks again."}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59008584", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:36 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A while back, you suggested that someone might be able to use a conflict with their national egregor to find a way to leave: the advice was to summon a mental image of the flag, explain things to it, say you want to leave, ask for help, and that you might get some lucky breaks. I recently tried that with the Canadian egregor and it backfired. The immediate response I got back was a very vicious one: \"Why should I help you leave, when I could just as easily kill you?\" This was followed by a number of truly awful nightmares, and a series of accidents that seemed to be making the point that the Canadian egregor would rather kill me than help me leave. This actually makes a lot of sense: an awful lot of Canadians get remarkably vicious if anyone suggests someone might not want to be Canadian for any reason.<br/><br/>In response I turned to the American egregor since the US would be the easiest country for me to move to and asked for its help. I focused on the US flag, called up a mental image of the Statue of Liberty, and explained why I wanted to leave Canada and move to the US and asked for its help. This worked much better: I now suddenly have a job lined up in the US, and assuming everything goes well, will be leaving Canada in about two months.<br/><br/>It looks like the job is going to suck, but I hope that once I'm in I will be able to line things up and improve my circumstances.<br/><br/>a) Do you have any suggestions for protecting myself against the Canadian egregore for the remainder of the time I need to remain in Canada? I currently have basic Golden Dawn Magic, but that's the extent of my knowledge. I am planning to move to the US earlier rather than later, but for now, I don't think I can leave for a period measured in weeks.<br/><br/>b) What is the traditional way to thank an egregor for its help? I've invoked it to say thank you, and I assume that taking steps to integrate myself into American society would be one; but I'm not sure how else to go about saying thank you here.<br/><br/>c) Once I leave, I will still have a Canadian citizenship for a while; how much do I need to worry about the egregor continuing to be able to influence me while I work to get rid of it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59010376", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:45 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Regular banishings will help, but I'd recommend getting a US flag and putting it in a visible place inside your home. The US egregor is stronger. <br/><br/>2) Moving here, contributing to society, and becoming a citizen as soon as you legally can is as much as any national egregor could want. <br/><br/>3) Work on attuning yourself to the US egregor. Study our founding documents, read up on our history, vote in every election. The formality of legal citizenship won't outweigh that. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59019848", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 07:36 pm", "user": "scotlyn", "content": "If I may, the comment to which you are replying here is still a blank to the rest of us, showing as \"screened comment\". ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59021640", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 07:47 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I was getting drowsy. An hour and a half spent napping helped that. ;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59022920", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 07:59 pm", "user": "scotlyn", "content": "Naps are great! :) <br/><br/>To the original commenter, if you will have them, I offer my blessings.  <br/><br/>My father's parents made this move - from Nova Scotia to Boston - in the 1920's... so hopefully my blessings have an \"ancestral\" impetus in this particular case. :) ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59043400", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 01:14 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I will be happy to accept your blessings. Thank you."}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59030088", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 09:10 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What is the likelihood that the Canada egregore gets absorbed by the United States egregore in the near future?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59038280", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 11:50 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Absorbed? No chance at all; the two are too incompatible. Supplanted? Somewhat more likely. I expect eastern Canada to remain independent, though. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59043912", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 01:18 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I doubt that anything outside Quebec will remain independent if the western provinces start getting taken out of the country. Ontario is too thoroughly integrated into the Great Lakes region from an industrial and economic standpoint; the Maritimes are not likely to desire to remain independent or stuck to Quebec if the rest of Canada is incorporated into the US. Then there's also the very high likelihood of a complete breakdown of the political system, because the Canadian constitution is far too inflexible to handle a province leaving..."}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59031368", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 09:17 pm", "user": "denebalgedi777", "content": "Just as a general observation, it's a bit disconcerting how sinister the Canadian egregor seems to have become over time.  This was not how I generally viewed Canada in my youth, nor did it feel hostile in this way when I visited in my youth.  I have heard many similar complaints from people there, including those who were expats from the USA.  There is historical precedent for this kind of thing among nations going through traumatic events - for instance Europe post-WWI - however I am not sure what was the specific trigger this time around.  The only speculation I have relates to the fact that all the British Commonwealth countries seem to be in rather a bad state now.  Maybe it has something to do with group karma from its imperial past.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59038792", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 11:52 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It really is fascinating, in a bleak sort of way. Watching \"assisted suicide\" moving steadily toward government-mandated mass murder is an intriguing reflection on what was bubbling away all along behind the mask of Canada's obsessive niceness.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59044168", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 01:24 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This is part of why I am hoping to get out. I'm getting really worried that in the next few years an awful lot of people are going to be murdered by the state, and frankly I do not want to risk being among them."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59040584", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 12:03 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you for posting this. I'm Canadian and see the contrast of Canadian viciousness vs people pointing out the ever increasing drawbacks to life here in many Youtube video comment sections. The speed of decline is almost comical if it wasn't so sad and I believe the doubling down will continue. The recent statistics on Canada's MAID program really blew my mind.<br/><br/>Even if your job does suck at least you can move there - you have a chance. I'm not in a line of work that I see a pathway forward to the USA and maybe too old, so I might be stuck in the bleak dark bureaucratic cold of Canada unless I marry an American woman. I hope you have great success and think of those that can't make it down there when you start to thrive.<br/><br/>Thank you JMG for the suggestions on how to align oneself with a countries' egregore. American flag getting ordered. I decided I was American a couple of years ago and really appreciate the love that many ordinary Americans have for their country even when its going through major changes."}]}, {"id": "cmt59010120", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:42 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/><br/>I hope you are doing well after your big move.<br/><br/><br/>I've noticed that a lot of people on here have been talking about communicating with various deities. People are frequently stating that they've either contacted deities or have been contacted by them.<br/><br/>My questions:<br/><br/>Q1. What can I do in order to possibly encourage interaction with a deity? I assume there are at least some steps that would increase the odds of it happening, even if the final decision is made by the deity/deities.<br/><br/>Q2. Some people have been contacted by deities without even seeking an interaction. Do those people have regular practices, or were the interactions spontaneous? If they don't have regular practices and they still have contact, that seems very unusual to me.<br/><br/>Q3. I would love to hear about how people's lives have changed due to such interactions. It seems that interacting with a deity would be completely earth shattering; at least from the perspective of having one's worldview changed in some big way.<br/><br/>These questions are open to everyone. Many thanks to you all in advance.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59010888", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 05:48 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Deities make that decision. If you feel strongly attracted to a deity, set up a little shrine -- an image of the deity, an incense burner, and any other decor that seems appropriate will be quite adequate -- and pray and burn a little incense to the deity regularly. That doesn't guarantee a response but it makes one more likely. <br/><br/>2) Sometimes it's very spontaneous. Deities do things for their own reasons all the time. <br/><br/>3) If you already believe in superhuman intelligences, and one shows up, it's not earth-shattering at all -- it's more \"Oh, good.  Glad to be in touch at last.\" That was my experience, certainly. "}, {"id": "cmt59017288", "title": "Areas of Interest", "date": "2026-02-02 07:10 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi there... as a writer and independent researcher, one of the deities I am in contact with has sent me down a rabbit hole of new reading and writing. It was on a topic I'd been somewhat interested in, but not to the degree where I felt I would be writing about it... I realized the deity was directing me and inspiring to write on the topic, which can be seen as a kind of offering of service to the being, and furthering her ends."}, {"id": "cmt59017544", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 07:16 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Also, have to say not earth shattering either, but more confirmatory. Following that, feel more guided in my life. "}, {"id": "cmt59033928", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 10:17 pm", "user": "jprussell", "content": "On Q1), I don't know if this is common, but I had my first, and still most vivid, experience of a deity while doing discursive meditation immediately following an SOP, after a few weeks of doing that daily. These days it's more just praying, whether formally at my altar, or in other contexts.<br/><br/>Q3) For my part, I might instead say \"earth-mending,\" maybe? Whatever the opposite of shattering is. I had been kinda-sorta religious in the past, fallen at least into very hard edged agnosticism, but pretty much atheism, and to have the encounter as the direct result of going \"you know, maybe I should try this magic thing, but take the Gods seriously as real this time,\" made it nearly impossible to doubt the existence of at least <i>something</i> divine. Opening up my world that way has made my life and experience of the world much richer, and has helped quite a bit through some hard times.<br/><br/>Cheers,<br/>Jeff"}]}, {"id": "cmt59012168", "title": "Personal Time Number Calculations", "date": "2026-02-02 06:01 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG, and congratulations on your new digs and a smooth transition to them. That's always a relief! My blessings, if you'll have them, on your new location.<br/><br/>My question is about the calculation of the Personal Time Number for a given year, in this case this year, 2026.<br/><br/>For 2026 and the \"personal time number\" where you add your own number to the year number, the year number is \"10\" which reduces to 1. If a person's time number is 1, does this make an 11 year (10 + 1) or do you reduce the year fully before adding them (1 + 1 = 2 year for that person)?<br/><br/>If the latter (reducing first), that implies that a person whose time number is 1 can never have an 11 year (\"10\" years reduce to 1 first), and only people with a personal time number of 11 could ever have a 22 year (and only in an 11 year).<br/><br/>So I assume it's the former, but that doesn't match the way the example is shown in the original post (https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/167653.html), which reduces the year first and then adds the time number to that.<br/><br/>Thank you for any clarification you have on this!<br/><br/> -- V.O.G", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59021896", "title": "Re: Personal Time Number Calculations", "date": "2026-02-02 07:52 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I still tend to reduce everything before adding, but your mileage may vary. At the end of this year, assess how the year went and see if it felt like an 11 year or a 2 year. That'll give you a clear sense of what to do. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59013448", "title": "The Outer Planets and Overcoming Limits", "date": "2026-02-02 06:15 pm", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>In my response to Deringoglade re: astrology something hit me: the planets beyond Saturn have as one of their central themes overcoming the usual limits imposed by the natural world. I'm not very good with astrology, though, so I figure it would help to run the idea by those who are.</p>\n<p>Uranus does this through ruling technology and exceptions to the normal rules: less an outright defiance of the natural order than finding the loopholes in that order.  (As I said, Uranus is <em>occasionally</em> visible, and his ruled phenomena occasionally pop up their heads in history.) However, pushed too far these loopholes begin to tear the fabric apart, imposing a cost on the future in terms of depleted resources and degraded institutions. (ex: fossil fuels)</p>\n<p>Neptune overcomes natural limitations through playing pretend: either through building escapist fantasy worlds with different sets of limits, or manipulating collective consciousness to get others to bear the cost of overcoming the limits you don't like. (ex: the dreams of running the grid on nuclear fusion or renewables, as well as the impractical but heavily-subsidized renewables industry as actually implemented)</p>\n<p>Pluto, which hasn't <em>quite</em> faded into irrelevancy, overcomes natural limitations through sheer perversity: just do what you want and weave a tale where the costs are really benefits and other people should really praise you for harming yourself and them, because reasons. (Example: radium)</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59022152", "title": "Re: The Outer Planets and Overcoming Limits", "date": "2026-02-02 07:53 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm! That certainly seems valid. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59013704", "title": "\"The Worst Argument against Paganism\" and Questions on Phase 17 of \"A Vision\"", "date": "2026-02-02 06:21 pm", "user": "jprussell", "content": "Good Afternoon,<br/><br/>Hope everyone is doing well, and if you marked it, have had a happy Imbolc and/or Groundhog Day!<br/><br/><b>To Share</b>: I found this a rather strange way to get around the idea that traditions have to be contiguous to be legitimate or worthwhile, but it's a subject some here might find interesting: <a href=\"https://imperiumpress.substack.com/p/the-worst-argument-against-paganism\">https://imperiumpress.substack.com/p/the-worst-argument-against-paganism</a><br/><br/><b>To Ask</b>: Feel free to tell me to save this for the relevant book club post, but I've read ahead through the descriptions of the phases in an attempt to identify my own, and after some consideration, I suspect that I'm in Phase 17 (though I'm worried about the hubris of classing myself with Shelley, Dante, and Yeats!). What really resonated, though, was \"Enforced Loss\" as the Body of Fate: the last few years have enforced quite a bit of loss in the material realm. This leads to two questions: 1. Is the Body of Fate related to, or identical with, karma? I had been interpreting the seemingly unfortunate turns as karmic culmination, <i>A Vision</i> suggests it's my Body of Fate manifesting, and I'm wondering if it might be both. 2. Yeats says that for Phase 17 to live in phase, he needs to seek \"simplification through intensity,\" and I'm hoping that if I can pursue that, it might mitigate some of pain from all of this Enforced Loss (though, if I'm understanding correctly, it doesn't seem to be something you can, or ultimately should want to, fully escape). Any tips on how to identify the true image to pursue intensely, or is the whole point of the exercise working it out for yourself?<br/><br/>My blessings to all who welcome them,<br/>Jeff", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59023688", "title": "Re: \"The Worst Argument against Paganism\" and Questions on Phase 17 of \"A Vision\"", "date": "2026-02-02 08:05 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Fascinating. I think that's the first time I've ever seen the word \"anti-authoritarian\" used as a condemnation. I would say that the bad argument he critiques is just as vulnerable from within the belief in individual autonomy he abhors. If the gods are real, then <i>the gods are real</i>, and if they choose to rekindle their worship in this day and age, it's not exactly relevant if a bunch of human naysayers run around waving their hands and shouting \"No! No!\" Historical Pagan worship wasn't predicated on blind obedience to the gods, but on an exchange of gifts (<i>Do ut des</i> in Latin, \"I give that you may give\") and the establishment of bonds of personal affection and loyalty, just like healthy relationships among humans. <br/><br/>2) The whole point of the exercise is working it out for yourself. On the other hand, it wouldn't surprise me at all if you were Phase 17, since that phase has a certain characteristic brashness that you've demonstrated a few times! The Body of Fate is not karma per se, it's a structure that shapes and organizes karma so that you have the experiences you need in this phase. As for mitigating the Body of Fate by pursuing the true Mask, it does seem to work to some extent: Yeats had no shortage of losses, but he also achieved more than his share of triumphs, including a relatively happy marriage (arguably the least likely outcome for a man with his hangups).", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59033416", "title": "Re: \"The Worst Argument against Paganism\" and Questions on Phase 17 of \"A Vision\"", "date": "2026-02-02 09:56 pm", "user": "jprussell", "content": "1) Yeah, that blog has some rather interesting views, but also an almost obsessive knowledge of Indo-European material, so it occasionally provides the useful service of analyzing things I'm interested in from a very different standpoint.<br/><br/>2) Hah, fair enough (though I had hoped I mostly tamed that in this context, at least)! And thank you for the clarification on Body of Fate - that neatly provides a mechanism for \"experiencing the karma you need to,\" which is usually assumed, but left vague in other systems. Thank you also for the encouraging reminder, though I had told myself something similar, there was a certain sinking feeling to reading \"a major part of your task in life is to not get or lose whatever you most want.\"<br/><br/>Thanks again,<br/>Jeff", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59052616", "title": "Re: \"The Worst Argument against Paganism\" and Questions on Phase 17 of \"A Vision\"", "date": "2026-02-03 03:00 am", "user": "causticus", "content": "Jeff, thanks for sharing that! This will make an interesting read, to say the least. <br/><br/>Not directly related to this conversation, but Imperium Press happens to be arch-rivals with a small circle of Pagan Neoplatonists I'm somewhat involved with. There's been a lot of back and forth polemics that would rival the sort that the early pre-Nicene Christian churches were routinely flinging at one another. In general, the right wing pagan scene right now is full of fierce debates between different factions. But I see this as healthy and vibrant, as a lot of these debates end up involving sophisticated theology and rhetorical muscle-flexing. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59013960", "title": "Visions and a question", "date": "2026-02-02 06:35 pm", "user": "denebalgedi777", "content": "Welcome back one and all!<br/><br/>Whatever visionary experiences I have usually come in dreams - there have been a few in waking life too, but the \"Artemisian\" definitely outweigh the Apollonian.  I have had dreams that were clearly about the future at intervals and I always see America as a bit of a run down place that still has some semblance of technology, but the ruins of 21st century post-industrial civilization are quite noticeable.  I also got the impression that pure wildernesses will be much more common in the future.  The high Age of Aquarius seems to have a lot fewer humans but settlements and people there still are in abundance.<br/><br/>Also, I note that the nature of my visions changed after the Great Conjunction of 2020.  I had the first clear vision of my most immediate past life in 2021, and in late 2022, I had quite disconcerting \"dark moonlit haunted forest\" dreams less than a year before some very difficult life changes hit in 2023.  In 2023, right before the life changing events, I was also visited in a dream by an old man who towered over me and radiated a terrible aura of power - it may have been the titan Saturn but I am not sure.  I also had dreams of visiting temple ruins, and in the past 2 years I have also - for the first time - had clearly non human beings enter my dreams.  This last piece was something I had never seen before - only human or animal.  I have now had dreams with imps/mephits, goblins and reptilians.  Not frequently but it has happened.  I get the impression there have been some major shifts on our region of the astral plane.<br/><br/>Just thought I'd share the \"it's not just you\" sentiments.  Oh, I have also been visited by dead relatives at times in dreams.  Usually they just wordlessly visit and then move on.<br/><br/>Finally, a question:<br/><br/>I have used geomancy for divination for over 2 years now (autumn 2023).  Sometimes I still have basic questions.  When you get a reading where the houses for querent and quesited are both favorable but the chart doesn't perfect, does this mean \"it would be good but is not possible now\"?<br/><br/>PS for funsies, since I have debilitated Mercury, I asked the powers of earth if occultism is actually a good path for me in this life, and I got a chart with Cauda Draconis in the 1st and 9th, with Laetitia, Puella as witnesses and Fortuna Major as judge.  This looks to me like \"I closed the door to the bar, now you can't leave\".", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59023944", "title": "Re: Visions and a question", "date": "2026-02-02 08:07 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this! Nothing in those visions seems unlikely to me. With regard to your question, yes, that's exactly how I read charts like that. Cauda in the first and ninth? Ha! As the Eagles sang, \"you can check out any time you like, but you can never leave.\" "}]}, {"id": "cmt59016008", "title": "God/Goddess vs Pantheon", "date": "2026-02-02 06:53 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello John,<br/>Welcome back. I'm glad you got to take some time away. I am very interested in trying to begin a relationship with three gods/goddesses because they all have attributes I'd like to embody. None of the three belong to the same pantheon.I don't know if my approach will be successful with any of the them, but nonetheless, would like to try. If I want to honor and get to know these deities, is there a problem with the fact they don'e belong to the same pantheon? I didn't think there would be, but I thought I'd ask. Thank you", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59024200", "title": "Re: God/Goddess vs Pantheon", "date": "2026-02-02 08:09 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's quite common in eras of cultural interaction for people to worship deities from many different cultural sources. The Gaulish horse goddess Epona, for example, became the patron deity of the Roman cavalry, and so there are temples to her in Roman forts in places as far afield as Egypt, smack dab next to shrines to Jupiter Ammon and the like. You should be fine. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59016520", "title": "Labels", "date": "2026-02-02 06:54 pm", "user": "realmscryer", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>For years I have been struggling with divination. Tarot and astrology, in particular, and for many years. <br/><br/>I could get results. Often though with this sometimes subtle and sometimes not so subtle mechanical feel. Recently, I have started thinking of it as a lack of vitality.<br/><br/>This has been happening with deities in prayer and the SOP, too. Get some vitality and it goes away. Come back, goes away.<br/><br/>So I started experimenting with different pantheons. And no pantheons. Greek, Welsh, Irish, Norse, or just elements.<br/><br/>Gods would drop in. Then go away. Didn't feel like I made anyone angry. They just slipped into the background or went on vacation. I don't know. Maybe, working with the gods was not needed in this incarnation?<br/><br/>Happening at the same time I continued working with some of the ideas in Robert Mathiesen's books. Emptying and uniting in particular.<br/><br/>What I found in that work was I could de-label everything in my reality. Clouds, garbage cans, sailboats, weather, and whatever else. I thought this was leading me to glimpses of non-duality. Now I am wondering if something else is happening. <br/><br/>The glimpses seem like they could be of energy that might be called meaning. Another label of course.<br/><br/>Which takes me to the next idea. There is a power for lack of a better word in removing labels and there is a power in the act of labeling.<br/><br/>Back to divination and deities and I guess everything else.<br/><br/>I think all this struggle has been in part about learning to use labels as a tool instead of being ruled by them.<br/><br/>As I feel into the energies, fields and such of a tarot card or planet or zodiac sign or hexagram or rune I can begin to use their names and definitions as a container of sorts. Or a guide?<br/><br/>The name isn't the thing! Or the experience. Or the energy. Funny, as I first encountered this in the 90s at Wilderness Awareness School while learning about plants and animal tracking. Been working at this lesson for a very long time, I guess.<br/><br/>Tricky thing this labeling habit.<br/><br/>Heck it was even showing up in picking domain names for my blog! So many domain names. Think I finally have one. Maybe even a label for this magic I am participating with, too. Or a book!<br/><br/>As mentioned earlier, in prior comments this week, might I finally have found my career in this life? Being one of those old men at the end of the lane? Whispering prayers, reading signs, gazing at the moon and stars to glimpse what unfolds next in life. Seeing as it's taken me 60 years to get to this point the timing might work out just right!<br/><br/>Once again I appear to not have a question. Which is fitting. I woke up one morning last week with the sense that I know nothing. What a trip incarnating into this magical world!<br/><br/>Thanks for reading,<br/>Eric<br/><br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59024456", "title": "Re: Labels", "date": "2026-02-02 08:10 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "A strange trip indeed. As you have no question, though, I have no answers...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59042632", "title": "Martinism was Re: Labels", "date": "2026-02-03 12:31 am", "user": "realmscryer", "content": "Hi again!<br/>Back from errands. If it is okay, I actually did have question(s) I have been meaning to ask but they had slipped my mind.<br/><br/>I have been reading \"Hermetic Initiation into Martinism\" by Pierre de Lasenic a book about Czech Martinism. It is really quite interesting. Do Martinist traditions vary greatly from one to the other? This book is my only reference point. Are there other publications you would recommend regarding Martinism?<br/><br/>Thanks again,<br/>Eric", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59046728", "title": "Re: Martinism was Re: Labels", "date": "2026-02-03 02:03 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "As far as I know, Martinist traditions in different countries are more or less parallel with one another -- certainly the French and Russian Martinist literature I've read has been relevant to my Martinist studies here in the US. There are some excellent recent English translations of Russian Martinist classics from Yury Pankratov -- <i>The Solar Way</i> and <i>The Encyclopedia of Occultism</i> are the two that have appeared so far -- which I can heartily recommend. The works of Mouni Sadhu are also very much part of the same tradition. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59016776", "title": "Weirdening? Wonderful!", "date": "2026-02-02 07:02 pm", "user": "frittermywig", "content": "Welcome back, JMG. I love \"weirdening\" and made it the theme for today's meditation. I'm applying it to my hobbyhorse, <i>Gravity's Rainbow</i> as esoteric text and initiatory path: Not only tells the story of one man's weirdening circumstances but it also, somehow, <i>enweirdens</i> the reader.<br/><br/>My question: W4E gives a recipe for a fluid condenser using \"any of the standard potencies\" of <i>Aurum met</i>. In my ignorance I bought some 30C pellets which I now believe are too dilute. Could you please clarify what the standard potencies are, for a homeopathic neophyte? Thank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59024712", "title": "Re: Weirdening? Wonderful!", "date": "2026-02-02 08:11 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "30C is one of the standard potencies. If it was professionally made, it will have a strong etheric imprint of gold, and should do the job very well. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59017032", "title": "A few questions about SoP", "date": "2026-02-02 07:02 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1. Question: After performing the gesture in the 4th part of the SoP opening, does the energy flow that begins from infinite space cease?<br/>2. Question: At the closing, are the two separate white light streams intersecting at the solar plexus the two white light streams within your body? Or are we visualizing two streams rising again from the sky and the heart of the world?<br/><br/>3. Question: Is there a method to apply SoP to someone remotely? Or can we only apply it to ourselves?<br/><br/>Regarding the first two questions: I didn't have any issues applying SoP before, but once these questions came to mind, I stopped being able to apply SoP.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59024968", "title": "Re: A few questions about SoP", "date": "2026-02-02 08:13 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) No. The flow is continuous; you just become aware of it, and then later turn your attention elsewhere.  <br/><br/>2) They're the streams from sky and earth. <br/><br/>3) You can't really do it for someone else, but when you invoke the elements, you can ask them to protect someone else also. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59018568", "title": "Saturn, Venus, and 2026 and vision of practice.", "date": "2026-02-02 07:27 pm", "user": "omee", "content": "Dear Teacher John Michael Greer, <br/><br/>somewhat of a weird question and I don't want to abuse your kindness by barraging too many questions at once. <br/><br/>How's the astrology for 2026 and the near? future for like 10 years? Any advice on how to weather the magical and astrological storm coming about the world? I Don't think there's a one practice or one secret to fix everything, but do you have any pointers how we can recognize our (esoteric) material and non-material teachers?<br/><br/><br/>My Saturn return is this year and I am just slightly dreading it...because of the image it gives most people, would appreciate if you have any advice on how to navigate it successfully with your wisdom of age and practice. <br/><br/><br/>Thank you so much, and I hope I wasn't excessive. <br/><br/>Sincerely,<br/><br/>Omran.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59025224", "title": "Re: Saturn, Venus, and 2026 and vision of practice.", "date": "2026-02-02 08:15 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "My astrological predictions are available via my Patreon and SubscribeStar venues for a modest fee. (I have to pay rent, you know!) Generally speaking, don't worry about teachers -- choose a set of practices and do the work yourself, and you'll get much further than you will waiting around for teachers to show up. As for Saturn returns, I've been through two of them, and there's not much you can do -- just weather the crisis as it happens, and go on. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59021128", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 07:43 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,<br/><br/>After a long period of knowing that it will happen I now have to move house. The new house is in many ways better and better located, but also in a very different area. I also have Aspergers. The pent up emotions seem to come out now that it will happen and I feel very sad and rather depressed about it. It is practically all I can think about. Do you have tips on how to handle this situation?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59025480", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 08:16 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Let yourself be sad. It's natural and healthy to grieve for a place that's been important to you. Once you let yourself go through that process of mourning, you can go on to new experiences. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59028296", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 08:41 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59023432", "title": "Qabalah", "date": "2026-02-02 08:03 pm", "user": "desmond_112", "content": "Hello! Recently I bought your paths of wisdom book, and im enjoying it greatly! Something I was curious about is the descriptions you've attributed to the Hebrew letters.<br/><br/>Here is an example <br/>\"Heh, the second letter, stands for the environment in which the energy of Yod manifests itself. It is the matrix of the creative process, the existing pattern of things, stable and balanced and for that very reason unable to create on its own. Given a force from outside to set it in motion, however, it has immense power. The letter Heh, therefore, is associated with ideas both of receptiveness, passivity, and stability, and of strength in motion, calm but overwhelming as the current of a great river.\"<br/><br/>My question is how do I go about discovering these ideas for myself? Is it just a matter of contemplation of the Hebrew letters and interpreting the symbols I receive? Or is it something I would discover naturally as I work through your book? <br/><br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59025736", "title": "Re: Qabalah", "date": "2026-02-02 08:17 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I didn't discover those for myself. They're things I learned from older books on the Cabala. Some things have to be learned from others..."}]}, {"id": "cmt59027784", "title": "Music and the Astral", "date": "2026-02-02 08:38 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, <br/>I was meditating on my cello, how it was made and what things had to be in balance to bring that about and so on.  I had a stray thought go through my mind that the practice of learning and performing music is beneficial on the astral level.  I remembered this because I had one of those pleasurable tingles up my back as I thought it. <br/><br/>What do you make of that?  What effects would playing music have on the astral level?<br/><br/>Thanks, Maxine", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59039304", "title": "Re: Music and the Astral", "date": "2026-02-02 11:58 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It has benefits on the astral and also the mental level, since it teaches the mind to work with emotions on a wholly abstract plane -- music is to the emotions what mathematics is to the intellect. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59028040", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 08:40 pm", "user": "jbucks", "content": "Dear JMG,<br/><br/>Glad to hear your move went well, and I hope you're settling in nicely to your new place!<br/><br/>About Revisioning the Tree of Life and the mountain dulcimer: with setting the strings to different root notes for a mode (i.e. F Lydian for the Sphere of Love), did you have trouble with string tension and slackness doing this on your own dulcimer? My dulcimer's 'home' tuning is D, and tuning to the few modes I've tried while leaving the first degree in D works. <br/><br/>It's more trouble when starting from a different root note, for example, G Mixolydian requires either a slack bass string (tuning down from my dulcimer's natural home of D to a lower G) or a tight base string (tuning up from that D to a higher G), which in turn affects the other strings if you want the schemes you presented in the book (i.e. Mixolydian as 1:5:8). I snapped a treble string because I tuned it up too far. Making a string more slack can work, but often I've found if a string is too slack it affects the spacing of the musical intervals.<br/><br/>I can work around this by tuning from D as the first degree and retuning to each mode (to get D Mixolydian for example), but I'm curious how you handled this on yours?<br/><br/>Thanks in advance! I'm greatly enjoying learning the mountain dulcimer and looking forward to trying out the modes with the RTOL work when I get to that point. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59039816", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 12:00 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Delighted to hear that you're working with this! I find that it really varies from one dulcimer to another. My usual instrument, a McSpadden, is easy to retune, but I've played others that are less forgiving. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59028552", "title": "Saturn Neptune Conjunction", "date": "2026-02-02 08:46 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "As you have already noted, the upcoming Saturn Neptune conjunction is one for the ages. Are you planning a full post about it soon? It certainly has the vibe of a monumental turning...super intense this month. Will you cast mundane charts for it (a la the Great Mutation conjunction of Jupiter and Saturn in 2020)? The conjunction is only in aspect to Uranus and Pluto which might suggest that its mundane house placement will be most important. In the US chart, the conjunction falls in the 11th house with Neptune as house ruler. <br/><br/>Can't wait for your commentary which I assume will be appearing soon since the conjunction perfects on Feb. 20. Astrology students may enjoy this interesting article from a jungian/archetypal perspective: https://www.astro.com/astrology/tma_article260119_e.htm  <br/><br/>Deep gratitude for all of your amazing work!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59040328", "title": "Re: Saturn Neptune Conjunction", "date": "2026-02-03 12:01 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, I plan on having it up in a week or so. Stay tuned! "}]}, {"id": "cmt59029064", "title": "The Saturn-Neptune conjunction on Feb 20th", "date": "2026-02-02 08:54 pm", "user": "nightsgate", "content": "Welcome back John and I hope you're settling in well.<br/><br/>Not a question this week, but some thoughts on the upcoming Saturn-Neptune conjunction. <br/><br/>After all the oddness in my life the past 4 months (and counting), I took a glance at my natal chart. What do I discover but a powerful square between Saturn and Neptune looming over everything else. I hadn't paid much attention to this part of my chart before. <br/><br/>The square of those two planets adds some interesting context to more than a few things about my life and recent events. <br/><br/>A few progressions and transits on several important dates in my life proved revealing as well.<br/><br/>All of which is to say, the conjunction on the 20th has me cautiously excited, as it's going to fall in my 1st house. If Neptune's recent movements had the kind of impact on me that they had at the end of last year, I may be in for an interesting time. <br/><br/>I'm not concerned in anyway, to be clear. But if I end up ascending to god-king status or some such, well, there's an answer. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59046984", "title": "Re: The Saturn-Neptune conjunction on Feb 20th", "date": "2026-02-03 02:05 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You may indeed be in for an interesting time. The conjunction is intercepted in my natal 9th house, so I expect its effects to be focused but far-reaching. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59029320", "title": "Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-02-02 08:54 pm", "user": "kylec", "content": "We are back with MOE Healing Hands! If you'd like to sign up, or learn more, just reply here or PM me your name and request."}, {"id": "cmt59029832", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 09:01 pm", "user": "kylec", "content": "Generally speaking, what astrological transits make for good timing to meet a future spouse (as opposed to a casual encounter)? <br/><br/>I have the fortune of having one past marriage in the books, so looking at the chart for the day I met my first wife, I don't see much that would have suggested a 10 year relationship and marriage, except that Jupiter is transiting the 7th natal house, but opposed to Mercury who rules that house for me. <br/><br/>I noticed that once again, Jupiter is in my 7th house and I made sure to go into public situations on the days around a trine with Venus and the retrograde back through that trine, but nothing came of it. I could be mistaken that this is an auspicious time to meet someone. What other situations would one look for as good timing to meet a spouse? I realize the natal details change things, so I'm just looking for a broad answer if such a thing exists.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59047240", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 02:06 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good aspects to the ruler of the 7th house are crucial. It also helps if the Moon is applying to a good aspect with your natal Sun. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59030600", "title": "Octogram Rituals", "date": "2026-02-02 09:12 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello, JMG. I hope you are well and that your move was as uneventful as it possibly could have been.<br/><br/>When doing the seasonal octogram rituals with a CGD Druid wand, is it best to use the sun end to summon and the earth end to banish? I see reference to the wand in the Merlin book, but unless I missed it, no specific directions as with the pentagram rituals in CGD.<br/><br/>As always, thank you for Magic Mondays - a pleasure to read and I am grateful for the resource. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59047496", "title": "Re: Octogram Rituals", "date": "2026-02-03 02:11 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, and I should have put that in there. The rules for the octagram are the same as those for the pentagram. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59031880", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 09:25 pm", "user": "ivn66", "content": "Welcome back, JMG, and hello commentariat!<br/><br/>Posting again to let any interested parties know that I'm still offering consultations in horary astrology free of charge over on my own Dreamwidth page. Should you have any need of divination services I'll be most glad to oblige you, not just today but on any day of this week."}, {"id": "cmt59033160", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 09:54 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "No real question just a fun story. <br/><br/>My 2 year old has been insisting he holds my Celtic Golden Dawn book lately. I’ve tried to give him other books to hold and play with, but he wants that one. He flips the pages, looks at the pages occasionally. He calls it “dada book”. <br/><br/>I’m not sure if he’s your youngest reader, but it must be close.  I’ve even bought an additional copy because he’s claimed (and curled) this one. <br/><br/>I wonder if he senses some calming energy from the book (as I am comforted by it, too.). After having worked the book a bit, I question if it has become a sort of talisman just through being studied and used (though never present during any rituals)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59048008", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 02:11 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good heavens. You may have a budding Druid on your hands..."}]}, {"id": "cmt59034440", "title": "A whole lotta questions", "date": "2026-02-02 10:32 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1. I had a last minute panic attack about a volunteer gig (deconstruction job) and did a geomancy reading about whether I should go. LW Cauda Draconis RW Puer Judge Fortuna Major. My read was \"probably not (Cauda Draconis + Puer), but if you do it'll put some hair on your chest.\" (Puer + Fortuna Major)<br/>My first question: without any qualifying info, is this a good read?<br/>Anyway, I did end up going and enjoyed myself far more than my reading made me expect. Everybody there was great, good spirits and better patience. Working with them also made me realise just out of shape I am. For the first time in my life I'm going to the gym. If had accepted the strict reading \"2 bad, 1 good, don't do it\" I wouldn't have had so much fun and learned about myself in the process.<br/>2. I've been studying electrical physics as well as occult philosophy over the past year and some interesting thoughts have crossed my mind. Physicists study natural phenomenon so that can use it towards some physical end. Magicians study inner, emotional phenomenon so that they can be used towards some physical end. One could call magic \"Spiritual Physics!\" I connected this to my new gym habit. In the past, my dreams of looking good underlay my desire to get in shape, but those never materialized. But the guilt of realising just how out of shape and my desire to keep up sent me right to the gym, no questions asked. And the excitement to go back still persists. In a \"spiritual physics\" frame, guilt/shame is like \"Locked Rotor Current\", it takes a lot more energy to move a rotor that is at a standstill. Similarly shame and guilt are really good at giving an ambitionless couch potato a kick in the butt. An apocalyptic reveal of your mistakes is really good at that. And to continue the metaphor, if a circuit maintains Locked Rotor Current for too long you pop a fuse. Similarly, guilt not properly channeled can re-paralyze you. Vanity on the other hand is low current. If you have an established routine or friends to go with, it can do just fine. But by itself, I think it's insufficient. <br/><br/>I think this \"spiritual physics\" idea could be an interesting way to meditate on emotions. Document each emotions' strength, weakness, and best use cases. Metaphor seems to be a big driver of new discoveries, and applying the metaphors of electricity to magic could be fertile indeed!<br/><br/>3. Something has changed in the air, I feel wired. If I had to describe the energy of the year going forward, the comparison I'd use is mountain biking. In mountain biking, it's all momentum. The most you can is slightly nudge the handlebars and hope for the best. If you ever even think of going for the brakes, it's over. I think this year is gonna be the same. People that handle momentum well will go incredibly far, but those that panic are done for. Maybe it's that Saturn-in-Aries energy. I guess my last question for you is how have the vibes been on your end. Anything perceptible beyond the hustle and bustle of moving states?<br/><br/>As always, thanks for your time.<br/>Sean-Luc", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59048264", "title": "Re: A whole lotta questions", "date": "2026-02-03 02:18 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That's a good interpretation of that. I'd have interpreted it as \"a definite maybe, and either way it will work out.\" <br/><br/>2) Interesting. I'm not especially well informed about physics, but if it works for you, by all means go for it. <br/><br/>3) The vibe I got over the holiday season was \"time for you to go, Grasshopper.\" I realized that I'd spent as much time dealing with grief as I could use productively, and it was time to make a decisive change and go somewhere more interesting. Ever since then I've been too busy to notice -- I made the final decision to move New Year's Eve, and a month later I'm settled in my new place and starting to learn my way around a new neighborhood. Once I get caught up on my rest (I've had three naps so far today, totaling more than seven hours, on top of seven hours of sleep overnight!) I'll see what the vibes have to say. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59034696", "title": "Advice on planetary charities and honoring Venus", "date": "2026-02-02 10:36 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, <br/><br/>I've come through several difficult years (almost seven years I won't go into in detail) but they have been deeply transformative in many ways. I still have a long road ahead, but I truly hope I am moving in the right direction, now. <br/><br/>I feel I have a debt toward Venus. How can I thank her, and show her that I would like to align my life more closely along her energies ? I've head about planetary charities but I am not very familiar with the subject. Any advice or recommended readings on this ?<br/><br/>Also, how is Venus related to Saturn in general ? I am not sure whether this question makes sense, but over the past few years, I've found myself speaking to both of them (at different times) and the resulting energies that have oriented my life are probably a blend of the two. Again any recommended reading on how planetary powers work (or not) together and how to navigate this ? <br/><br/>Glad to see you back online, and wishing you all the best as you settle into your new home !", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59048520", "title": "Re: Advice on planetary charities and honoring Venus", "date": "2026-02-03 02:20 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Here's the go-to article on planetary charity by Chris Warnock, who introduced the practice to Western astrology: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://www.renaissanceastrology.com/planetarycharity.html\">https://www.renaissanceastrology.com/planetarycharity.html</a><br/><br/>As for Venus and Saturn, that depends on their relative positions in your natal horoscope. I don't have any recommended readings on that, as it's a subject I'm still learning about myself. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59036744", "title": "Magic always leads to trouble", "date": "2026-02-02 11:24 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Welcome back JMG! <br/><br/>Enjoyed a recent Kunstler podcast with Elizabeth Dickson. I was somewhat familiar with her work but the interview led me back to her Substack. One article in particular caught my eye and I’ve read it a few times now. <br/><br/>https://elizabethnickson.substack.com/p/magic-is-alive-unfortunately-witchcraft<br/><br/>Highly recommend it when you have the time. Curious as to what you think about it.<br/><br/>In relation to this, my children were found of an animated cartoon called Ben and Holly‘s Little Kingdom, and in the show, a consistent punchline was, ‘magic always leads to trouble.’ It makes me laugh every time I hear it. It seems Elizabeth may have come to the same conclusion. Between the article above and what you noted about the cold weather magic spell, I’m guessing there’s something to that, at least for novices. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59048776", "title": "Re: Magic always leads to trouble", "date": "2026-02-03 02:28 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Um, you do realize that Dickson is insisting that the witch burnings were justified? I've been expecting this for some time, not least because the clueless end of the Neopagan scene has done so much to bring that upon them, but I'm still horrified to see her one-sided, bigoted take on magic and very concerned that it will lead to mob violence and mass death. <br/><br/>No, magic doesn't always lead to trouble. Incompetent and evil magic leads to trouble, but the same is true of medicine and engineering, you know. Magic done wisely and well is a powerful tool for blessing and healing -- but you won't learn that from people like Dickson, who are so caught up in their own fear and hate that they can only see its reflection mirrored back at them. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59056456", "title": "Re: Magic always leads to trouble", "date": "2026-02-03 04:38 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I don't know if you're aware, and maybe this is related, but right-wing Twitter/X is absolutely exploding with occult conspiracy theories over the latest Epstein files release. Apparently there's multiple documents linking him to the Rothschilds, among many others... Occult conspiracies, Bohemian Grove, and Kubrick's Eyes Wide Shut are coming up a lot. I could see this quickly getting out of hand.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59057480", "title": "Re: Magic always leads to trouble", "date": "2026-02-03 04:59 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, I didn't know that. Sigh...  <br/><br/>Here we go. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59037256", "title": "Ninja 5th dan sword strike test", "date": "2026-02-02 11:30 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG,<br/><br/>My question is basically what you think is going on below from a magical perspective, if you could speculate and whether you think it is possible to genuinely do what is described below.<br/><br/>I read in a book that the 5th dan (mastery) test in a particular tradition of Japanese ninjutsu is that the aspirant sits in seiza and meditating with eyes closed and the grandmaster stands behind him, also with eyes closed, in meditation, holding a sword (traditionally a live sword but in the last few decades more often a bamboo shinai), and the test is essentially whether you can do a forward roll out of the way of the shinai before you get smacked. <br/><br/>(The book is called Path Notes of an American Ninja Master by Glenn Morris and has a detailed description of his godan test in 1990)<br/><br/>Depending on the sensei, you may or may not get 3 chances to succeed if you get smacked. <br/><br/>Note that you cannot wait to hear the sword/arm/breeze move to start the roll - you will be far too slow to escape a full speed cut from that close. If you roll too early (before there is a committed stroke), you fail. In theory the sensei could swing slowly enough to let you hear the stroke and move but this is done in front of a large crowd of other senior instructors and martial artists and the sensei himself would be disgraced by doing that. <br/><br/>It sounds crazy (and no doubt would be the subject of debunking these days by people who fight MMA etc) but it apparently it did happen even well into this generation and probably does still happen somewhere. <br/><br/>Basically the only way to do it, according to the book is that you have to be able to sense the sensei's intent through his energy and there is a fraction of a second where he has made up his mind and mentally committed to the stroke but hasn't physically started moving - if you can sense that moment, you can start moving just barely in time to dodge the stroke. <br/><br/>The author says when he did his test, he got into seiza and reached out with his feelings to \"connect\" with the energy of the sensei behind him and then started to get nervous because although he could normally do this easily, the sensei behind him was in mushin and to the student's senses it felt like no one was behind him. Nevertheless he waited for the stroke. <br/><br/>He says he just looked at the white light he could see in the bright room with his eyes closed and saw a flicker of light that was barely there and rolled and the sword swung and missed him - he'd passed!<br/><br/>But no - the sensei said \"Come back, do it again and this time don't think\". He tried again and this time he didn't sense anything at all and got sharply cracked on the skull. Strike two. <br/><br/>Apparently at this point the sensei muttered something in Japanese which the student was much later told meant \"These intellectuals always think too much\". <br/><br/>Final chance. The student remembered someone else telling him that when he passed the godan test, he had a feeling of great nausea in his stomach and then rolling without any conscious thought and passing the test. He then says he \"dropped my consciousness to my hara, my intestines began to roil, I shut off my [conscious] mental processes and waited and waited and suddenly I was at the other end of the room, with no memory or awareness of the roll that got me out of the way of the strike and gave me my godan rank\". <br/><br/>Later one of the other teachers told him that from what he could see, the student had actually rolled at the right time on the first try, and he didn't know why the sensei had made him do it again until he could do it in that unconscious way. And the student says he's still not sure exactly why but the best he can guess is that \"it is not enough to sense the killing thought..one must actually avoid the blow...one may be threatened by another's intent but if you react merely to the intent, then a skilled opponent can use that against you by not following through\". He then says \"In this test, there is an exchange of subtle energy between the sensei and initiate..the stronger spirit wins..there is a transfer of chi as part of the test\". <br/><br/>And finally he goes on to say that when he \"checked his spirits in the mirror that night\" (whatever that means), he saw a new spirit had joined him - a tengu, one of the spirits that works with and is friendly to his school of Ninjutsu, a symbol of the spirits' protection and his acceptance into the tradition. <br/><br/>JMG - I know I've written a lot but I thought the details were quite important and I can't make out what on earth went on in this process (assuming it is all true). ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59049288", "title": "Re: Ninja 5th dan sword strike test", "date": "2026-02-03 02:34 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, this kind of thing happens. In taijiquan, the ability to \"listen\" to the other person's qi (life force) and be aware of what he's going to do before he does it is a normal skill developed in training -- that's much of what push-hands exercises are about. As for tengu, of course they exist -- they're one of many, many kinds of nonhuman spirit in this end of the cosmos, and ninjutsu practitioners (and the yamabushi and shugenja ascetics whose teachings helped shape ninjutsu) have long had cordial relations with them. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59039048", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-02 11:53 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello Mr. Greer,<br/><br/>Any tarot spreads I could use for philosophical contemplation? Any sources I could use? Any other relevant advice?<br/><br/>Thank you in advance.<br/><br/>Ennobled little day ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59049800", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 02:35 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's an excellent idea which, as far as I know, nobody's explored yet. Have fun breaking new ground! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59051848", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 02:53 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "When I worked in laboratories, I had a boss who said that it's better to NOT start a project from scratch. Even if you're successful, you're going to spend a lot of time going down blind alleys... Or something to that effect.<br/><br/>I guess someone has to start it...<br/><br/>Thank you again!"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59041864", "title": "Sigils", "date": "2026-02-03 12:25 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The neopagans are dusting off their sigils to stop ICE. While they look cute it seems to be that they have little to no power. Would the sigil contained below have had any impact?<br/><br/>https://www.patheos.com/blogs/tempest/2025/01/revisiting-the-2020-freedom-sigil.html?fbclid=IwY2xjawPuC-1leHRuA2FlbQIxMABicmlkETFTelo2UnFiS1gxT3pZWGFTc3J0YwZhcHBfaWQQMjIyMDM5MTc4ODIwMDg5MgABHnzae-DxVszN2qHLUylU7mqg__ACNlSqREfB-nPy1Rz9htLW_kJ6-ZVddaww_aem_EPEW68hrsLgbvPpMaPZxSw<br/><br/>Why aren't they embarrassed about the fact that these sigils (which were supposed to stop Trump too) have no apparent effect and so they keep rehashing them?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59046472", "title": "Re: Sigils", "date": "2026-02-03 02:03 am", "user": "charlieobert", "content": "You know what I think the issue is there - the person who wrote that, and most of the people who resonate to it, are unable to tell when the language they are using has no content.<br/><br/>The language on that page sounds like it's actually saying something, but darned if I could figure out what it is. That could have been pulled straight from the New Age Bull---t Generator site.<br/><br/>If that sigil embodies that, then it means everything and nothing... but it looks really heavy.<br/><br/>When you're aiming at something that gaseous, that non-specific... that is what you will attain.<br/>"}, {"id": "cmt59050568", "title": "Re: Sigils", "date": "2026-02-03 02:43 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Au contraire, they're very effective. It's just that they've misunderstood their position in the current transformative process. The Neopagan movement by and large has flung itself wholeheartedly onto the side of stasis, privilege, and a culture of political corruption on a truly grand scale, while being perfectly certain that they support the opposite of these things. Thus they're casting spell after spell to overthrow the side they support, while keeping the language vague enough that they never realize what they're doing. <br/><br/>It's all very reminiscent of Euripides' <i>The Bacchae</i>, and may just end the same way. "}, {"id": "cmt59054920", "title": "Re: Sigils", "date": "2026-02-03 04:00 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "According to the website, the \"freedom sigil\" was created in December 2019: \"With the goal of strongly moving forward for positive change to take place in a timely manner...the 2020 Freedom sigil was created.  The name may seem simple, but 2020 is not only the new year, but a term used to talk about focusing of vision and clarity – and freedom is never given – it is fought for and won.\"<br/><br/>Welp, 2020 promptly became the time of lockdowns and massive restrictions on civil rights - all of which have led to the current blowback, including I daresay quite a bit of improved clarity for may people. It does sound rather like the freedom sigil is working...just not remotely as intended.<br/>"}]}, {"id": "cmt59042376", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 12:26 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Can your workbooks from the Golden section be worked in other systems too; or are they strictly for the Golden section course?<br/><br/>Thanks! And welcome back!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59050824", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 02:44 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you. The three Workbooks can be used with any esoteric system that practices daily discursive meditation -- or by anybody who's willing to learn that skill (and instructions are given in an appendix in each book). "}]}, {"id": "cmt59043656", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 01:15 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>1) I forgot how nice it is to soak up the Ecosophia &amp;&amp; Magic Monday egregore.  Reading your posts and yours/others comments puts me in a rather pleasant state of mind.<br/><br/>2) Everytime I get a haircut it's like taking a happy pill.  The other day I was anxious about some life stuff and remembered the hair cut thing, so I started by trimming (not shaving) my beard which made me feel 30% better.  I thought about getting a hair cut then but decided to check up on what was making me anxious, and it was fine, so that pretty much healed remaining unease.  I still haven't got the haircut but looking forward to the happy pill effect.  Anyway, I noticed some stagnant energy collects in the head/hair, and I can mime a pulling motion around the head and it literally feels like I'm pulling dead energy from hair.  Now I don't want to shave my head, but it seems like we all might have an ideal hair length for our energy bodies where our hair doesn't accumulate stagnant energy.  Have you heard anything about stagnant energy in the hair?  It seems related to longer hair facilitating emotions and shaved heads favoring reason.  FWIW, I do <i>The Way of the Secret Temple</i> energy work most days to good effect which clears away some of this energy.<br/><br/>3) I completed the GSF core curriculum recently and also did the communion ceremony twice. I also read <i>The Ceremony of the Grail</i> recently.  Are these two related at all?  There seems to be a connection: paten/grail/chalice/spreading the lunar current over the land.<br/><br/><br/>Thanks! Luke Z", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59051080", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 02:48 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Hair does indeed pick up energy, but my experience, at least, is that lukewarm-to-cold showers daily clear away the stagnant energy. <br/><br/>2) There's a connection, though it's subtle. The GSF is my attempt to create a system of self-initiation that confers most of what the (now mostly extinct) esoteric side of Freemasonry was meant to convey, without trespassing on Masonic rites and symbols. If I'm right about the Grail, that was once caught up in the same esoteric tradition. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59053384", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 03:07 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) Oh, well that explains it.  I normally take cold showers but stopped when the extreme cold weather hit and indulged in hot.  Back to lukewarm-to-cold, starting tomorrow.<br/><br/>2) Makes sense.<br/><br/>Luke Z", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59053896", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 03:12 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That's a trick I learned from one of the Rosicrucian traditions in which I'm involved, and then learned much more about during the research that resulted in my book <i>The Secret of the Five Rites</i>. Back in the 19th century there was a lot of yelling between partisans of ice-cold baths and showers and partisans of hot baths; a smaller and less noisy group split the difference and found that they got the best results of both sides. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59044424", "title": "Prognostication", "date": "2026-02-03 01:31 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Congratulations on your recent move. It just so happens I'm contemplating a move myself in the near future, but I haven't made a firm decision, and wanted to know what occult tools I could employ in prognosticating the results of such a life change. I intend to perform an Ogham divination, of which I have tolerable experience, but aside from that I have very little experience with other forms of divination, especially the astrological kind, and I would like more than a simple Ogham reading to help guide me on such a big change. What might you suggest for a relatively inexperienced mage? Or, if it's not too personal, what if anything did you use to guide your own recent decision to move house?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59051336", "title": "Re: Prognostication", "date": "2026-02-03 02:51 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I started practicing divination more than half a century ago, and one result is that my intuitive senses are fairly well developed. I use horary and relocational astrology to check my intuitions, but most of what I do is pure intuition without the intervention of divinatory symbolism; unless you're unusually talented, you may not be able to do that. What I'd recommend is that you go to a diviner who has no personal stake in your decision and see what they have to say. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59044680", "title": "Esoteric meaning of DC's design", "date": "2026-02-03 01:43 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "So, since you've recently moved to the most wretched hive of scum and villany in the known universe, I figured I would ask you about some rumors I once heard growing up regarding the estoric meanings behind the street layout of Washington DC. You can let me know if there's any truth to any of this, and perhaps I'll give you some mysteries about your new city to look into.<br/><br/>So, firat and foremost - have you noticed the inverted pentagram drawn in the streets directly north of the white house. Is there any esoteric meaning behind this? My friends used to say it was proof the white house was secretly run by a satanic cult, but that was the sort of thing a bunch of ignorant teenagers from the 90s would say, whose esoteric knowledge consisted of episodes of buffy the vampire slayer and charmed.  Later I found out that most of DC Was built according to masonic symbolism, making wonder as to the true meaning of the star. There's also a missing section of the street star, with fumors of an underground masonic tunnel connecting the street sections. Any knowledge of any of this?  Gps and phone signal does become wonky insode this area - though it may just be signal blocking around the white house for entirely sensible and mundane security reasons.<br/><br/>The Washington Monument, aka the grand obelisk in the midst of Dc, is by law the tallest building in the city. What, from a masonice perspective, is the significance of a central obelisk that stands between the branches of government, at the central corssroads of the city, above everything else in the city?<br/><br/>Finally, there's an odd street design just east of the capitol building, which looks just like an owl. I heard its the old of Athena, respresenting wisdom, that as the sun rises each day it should send wisdom forth to the capitol and the city. That sound right to you?<br/><br/>Just a few oddities I've always wondered about my old town and your new one, that you may or may know the answers to, but which are intriguing puzzles to look into if you don't.<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59051592", "title": "Re: Esoteric meaning of DC's design", "date": "2026-02-03 02:52 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I haven't yet looked into any of that, though I've heard scraps of it here and there. It wouldn't surprise me if there was Masonic symbolism in the street grid, though -- DC has been packed with Masons since it was still a construction site. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59045704", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 01:54 am", "user": "diletpoly", "content": "<p>Welcome back, and welcome to the mid-Atlantic neighborhood.</p>\n<p>I made a New Year's resolution to post more often on these, so in the hiatus, I had been thinking of things to ask. As it happens, one of them was about regional/local meetups. I would swear that was brought up at some point in these pages in the 3 or so years I've been reading them, but I went back and couldn't find it. Now that I realize you're around an hour away (at least this time of night) from where I live in the DC Ex-urbs in Virginia, if you ever decide to do a get-together of any sort, I'm making the trip if at all possible. When I moved to the area, I actually lived in Silver Spring for a few months, staying with my then mother-in-law until we found a house on this side of the river.</p>\n<p>Another of my New Year's resolutions was to more consciously cultivate community. I don't tend to make friends quickly, and I don't always realize when I have made friends. I'm not very plugged into the occult or pagan communities around here, only having two separate small roleplaying communities, as well as some online pagan communities I see most years at festivals, and I guess this place, where I don't feel like I've made friends, exactly, but I've got names and personalities I've begun to recognize. So this fits right in.</p>\n<p>And, for anyone else in the greater DMV area, if you're interested in getting together for a pub night or coffee and chat, feel free to reach out via my dreamwidth account which should be easily found from this comment. We don't have to depend on our present host to begin building community in \"meat space\".</p>\n<p>Now, back to trying to read the comments, I don't think I'll be done before midnight rolls around and I lose my chance to comment.</p>\n<p>JMG, thanks as always for hosting these, and once again welcome to the neighborhood. I do hope I someday get to meet you in person and thank you for all the hours of enjoyment reading your various writings, as well as the GSF, which has \"stuck\" for me far more than any other occult or magical training system I've tried, despite what I assume is my subconscious' best efforts to bounce off of it.</p>\n<p>The Dilettante Polymath</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59052104", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-03 02:54 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you!  I want to arrange a get-together with readers in the area as soon as that's convenient, but I'll have to find a venue -- as I noted in response to someone else's question, my apartment is quite small, and would feel very crowded with more than three people in it. If you or anyone else know of a place where we could meet of an evening, I'm all ears. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59054408", "title": "Unintentional Electional Astrology?", "date": "2026-02-03 03:30 am", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>I have a general question and a specific one about the upcoming Saturn-Neptune conjunction. Feel free to defer either or both if you'll be addressing my concerns on your Patreon/SubscribeStar next week.</p>\n<ol>\n<li><p><strong>The general question:</strong> You've said the conjunction is expressly <strong>not</strong> a good time for elections or astrological magic, at least for the vast majority of people.  But suppose you're not planning on doing astrological magic or intentional elections — does any major action undertaken during the time of a major astrological event's influence receive the same influence as if it were elected, or does it receive only a general \"vibe\" insofar as the event affects/predicts everything?</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>The specific question:</strong> Are there any particular types of actions that are counterindicated by the upcoming conjunction and better put off until later? I mean things like buying a new home, starting a business, taking up a new spiritual practice, etc.  Obviously I'd ideally want a competent astrologer to look at how the conjunction interacts with my own chart, but I'm wondering if maybe there are general indications — something on the level of \"avoid signing new contracts when Mercury is retrograde.\"</p></li>\n</ol>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59055176", "title": "Re: Unintentional Electional Astrology?", "date": "2026-02-03 04:04 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Any major action that takes place, or is begun, during the aspect is subject to the influence of the aspect. Since both planets are slow-moving and have been close together for a while now -- right now, for example, they're only 1 degree 23 minutes of arc apart, which is within orb by any measure -- there's a period of several months in which every action will be influenced by them, subject only to house placement. So it's already here, in effect, and can't be avoided. <br/><br/>2) I've been looking for those, but so far haven't found any documentation. What's clear to me at this point is that relying on existing forms to remain intact during this conjunction is a bad idea! Neptune is dissolving Saturn's rigid structures, and Saturn will establish new and unfamiliar structures once the conjunction is past. I would avoid making firm commitments during this time; at the same time, it's a good opportunity to make significant changes (such as, say, relocating) with the hope of heading in new directions. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59055688", "title": "Re: Unintentional Electional Astrology?", "date": "2026-02-03 04:32 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "2. Oof. That doesn't bode well for existing institutions in the United States, e.g. academia, the media, political parties, the government, corporations, etc. Probably even America's own mythology and its conception of itself and the world is going to get dissolved and rebuilt in unfamiliar form. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59056200", "title": "Re: Unintentional Electional Astrology?", "date": "2026-02-03 04:36 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Here and everywhere else. It's an extraordinarily powerful conjunction, since it's at 0 degrees Aries, the reset button of the entire zodiac. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59056968", "title": "Re: Unintentional Electional Astrology?", "date": "2026-02-03 04:56 am", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>Thank you for these.  I have a lot to think about now, about how best to use the next few months.</p>\n"}]}]}]}, {"title": "Magic Monday", "url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/358626.html", "year": "2026", "month": "02", "day": "08", "time": "10-50PM", "comments": [{"id": "cmt59106786", "title": "Curses on the Calander", "date": "2026-02-09 05:17 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello Mr. Greer, <br/><br/>Earlier today an old friend of mine said something very strange to me. He told me that each year, during the week or two leading up to Halloween and Valintine's day, fate turns against him. He feels like some dark spiritual power begins working to harm him. I pointed out that in his youth this man had a borderline supernatural ability to flirt with women, and consciously fought against this. Both of us often got an uneasy feeling about it. Otherwise normal women became overly sexual around him in often unhealthy ways. He eventually settled down and became a reliable husband. Now this attention has largely dissipated. I am not sure if there really is something spooky connected to these particular holidays or not, but it seems odd that these two holidays in particular consistently align against him, given his past. <br/><br/>So I would like to know if a person can have consistently bad luck at roughly the same time of year. Likewise, is this something that would be caused by a malign spirit, odd astrology, or what?  <br/><br/>Thank you for your time. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59107298", "title": "Re: Curses on the Calander", "date": "2026-02-09 05:28 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, this can certainly happen. Sometimes the reason is astrological. As the planets move through the sky, they enter into various relationships with the planetary positions in your birth chart. The Sun moves through the same degrees on the same days each year (with a little bit of variation), and so if you have a difficult Sun aspect to some point in your natal chart on certain dates, that'll recur year after year. <br/><br/>Still, it's also quite possible to psych yourself into having repeating bad days in the yearly cycle. Once you've gotten it into your head that Valentine's day is bad luck, that in itself can generate bad luck for you. My late wife had a bad case of that. Her mother, who was a psychological basket case on the grand scale, used to throw screaming tantrums every Thanksgiving and Christmas, and it took years before Sara could face either holiday without wanting to hide under the bed, just because of all those horrible childhood experience. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59107042", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 05:19 am", "user": "brenainn", "content": "1. I've recently begun drinking herbal teas to help with receiving clearer impressions from some of the spirits around me. Mostly, chamomile and lavender. Is this a good blend of herbs for that purpose? I selected them after reading some of their properties in your natural magic book. Any additional recommendations?<br/><br/>2. Another source recommended adding a small amount of sea salt or kosher salt (1/8 teaspoon) to some cold water and drinking it to help purge spiritual impurities. Have you heard anything like that?<br/><br/>3. So, turns out, the building I live in is right next to what was once a cemetery. Apparently, the old graves were removed and a building was placed on it. Do you think any precautions might be necessary (I do have to enter this other building on occasion). I've been picking up just a few impressions from the area, so I think many of the spirits of the those long dead have already moved on.<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59107554", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 05:30 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) If it works for you, it's a good blend. The psychic effects of herbs are a very personal matter and experimentation is more important than what a book says. <br/><br/>2) No, but on first principles it ought to work. <br/><br/>3) Regular banishings should be adequate, so long as the remains were moved. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59108322", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 05:39 am", "user": "brenainn", "content": "3. I mostly rely on the Judson Exercise, and it seems adequate. I have other protective measures within my room itself. I have noticed one particular spirit do something that is a little different from the others. This one is actually becoming just slightly visible to me. It is definitely coming from the direction of the former cemetery. I don't sense any malign intent but it can't seem to send clear impressions of what it wants. I find that odd, since no other spirit so far as been able to present a visible form to me. I'm not sure how to proceed, but it definitely seems to want something.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59108578", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 05:43 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Prayer is generally helpful in a situation like this, as it can attract higher spiritual entities who can help out. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59108834", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 05:46 am", "user": "brenainn", "content": "I feel kind of silly at the moment, as this should have occurred to me. In particular, my spirit guide should be the obvious go to for this kind of difficulty.<br/><br/>My life has taken such an unexpected and odd turn. I was once a militant materialist. I guess the gods decided to pull the rug out from under me.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59109858", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 05:53 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "This seems to be happening to a lot of people just now. The end of the age of reason really does seem to be picking up speed...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59110370", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 05:59 am", "user": "brenainn", "content": "I suppose there's some potential to work off some negative kamma for me. I fully expect the most committed and recalcitrant materialists to double down as their age collapses, and at this point, I do not think I'll be able to keep the low profile I used to. Accept what comes (hopefully, just ridicule and being shunned by some folks) and know that, at some point, I did something to merit it.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59115490", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 02:39 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Partly, yes, it's a matter of working off karma, and partly it's a chance to learn that other people's opinions don't matter as much as our genetics and upbringing generally lead us to think...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59119074", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 03:32 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "Yes, indeed. Our species might be accurately called Homo simialis socialis!"}]}]}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59107810", "title": "Food and Energy", "date": "2026-02-09 05:31 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, I wanted to ask about fasting or light diets and energy work. A while back I didn't have time to get more food so I ate some nuts followed by beans and rice for a day. I found that meditation, banishing and other energetic exercises were enhanced by this practice and I felt less hungry than I would have in the past before I did much in the way of spiritual practices. I felt able to draw on greater amounts of energy, and while meditating I was able to more distinctly feel my presence on the subtle planes.<br/><br/>I ate beans and rice for breakfast the next day and had a similar amplified experience before buying groceries in the afternoon. Now I find that going on this two-day light diet cycle can boost my energetic affinity for the duration, though I naturally don't want to do it all the time. Fasting has been used as part of religious practices for a long time, is this kind of spiritual enhancement part of the reason? Is there anything you'd suggest reading on the topic? Thanks.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59109090", "title": "Re: Food and Energy", "date": "2026-02-09 05:46 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, that's an old and very useful trick. Some occultists make it a habit to fast completely for one day a week, or to eat a restricted diet that amplifies their psychic sensitivity. I like the idea of a rice and beans fast, but that's because that's been one of my comfort foods for many decades! <br/><br/>I don't know of any good books on the subject -- unfortunately nearly everything I've seen on the subject of diets and spirituality is infected with the sort of one-true-diet syndrome that leads to angry ranting. But, yes, you've gotten hold of one of the classic methods for boosting your sensitivity. Explore it and see where it leads you. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59119586", "title": "Re: Food and Energy", "date": "2026-02-09 03:40 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "For spiritual as well as health effects from fasting, I'd recommend the herbalist Stephen Harrod Buhner's book \"The Transformational Power of Fasting: The Way to Spiritual, Physical, and Emotional Rejuvenation.\"  I certainly would not describe his approach as fanatical or ranting; it is flexible, spiritually deep, and respectful of one's individuality.  <br/><br/>He's written a number of other fascinating books, including \"The Secret Teachings of Plants;\" \"Plant Intelligence;\" and \"Ensouling Language: On the Art of Nonfiction and the Writer's Life.\"  All of them go well beyond common tropes and fads, expressing his own first-hand, curious, and fascinating insights. He's also written a number of very useful books on straightforward herbalism.<br/><br/>The other book I'd recommend for spiritually-oriented fasting is Peter Sewald's \"Wisdom from the Monastery: A Program of Spiritual Healing.\"  Even though I am not Christian, and this book certainly is, the book is so beautifully presented, so simple and sensible, that its principles and advice are really useful even in non-Christian spiritual or occult contexts.  The book is in three parts; the first part is focused on fasting.  One of the useful aspects of the approach is the focus on fasting from many different things, not only from food.  It is a whole-soul experience and it's recommended that one focus one's life around abstaining from many kinds of 'consumption' during the fast.  <br/><br/>I know our host has written about similar exercises of clearing the mind and imagination, as have other modern and older occult practitioners.  Fasting of the mind and emotions as well as of the body, in other words, which makes the utmost sense when one engages in fasting for esoteric or spiritual purposes.<br/><br/>Winifred Hodge Rose"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59108066", "title": "Happy Monday", "date": "2026-02-09 05:38 am", "user": "kyl_morrazen", "content": "Mr Greer<br/><br/>Good early early morning <br/><br/>I’m relatively new to occultism but have practiced some basic meditation. When practitioners talk about evocation in magic, is this ever understood psychologically, similar to engaging Jungian archetypes as described by Carl Jung, or is it generally considered something categorically different?<br/><br/>Also, from an occult development perspective, are there practices traditionally aimed at cultivating fearlessness or significantly reducing fear without relying on external forces? I ask because I’ve struggled with fairly debilitating panic attacks, and conventional therapeutic approaches haven’t brought much relief so far, so I’ve been exploring whether occult disciplines historically approached fear as part of inner development rather than symptom management.<br/><br/>I realize you’ve said questions about ‘getting goodies’ from spirits are off topic, so please feel completely free to skip this if it crosses that line, but I’m curious whether engaging spirits or other external forces specifically for inner psychological transformation (rather than material gain) is generally considered outsourcing development, or if there’s a meaningful distinction there in your view.<br/><br/>And if I’m not even asking the most useful question here, please feel free to redirect, reframe, or expand however you think would be most helpful.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59109602", "title": "Re: Happy Monday", "date": "2026-02-09 05:52 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It depends on what you want to evoke. Can you evoke an archetype? Sure -- but not everything out there is an archetype. There are also conscious intelligent beings who don't happen to have the same sort of physical bodies we do. <br/><br/>2) There's some overlap between occultism and therapy, though it's mostly recent. One resource I found extremely useful in my own work is the exercises of the Order of Spiritual Alchemy, which you can download for free here: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://octagonsociety.org/preliminary-lessons/\">https://octagonsociety.org/preliminary-lessons/</a><br/><br/>These are meditative and journaling practices to help you process the unfinished business that gums up your psyche. <br/><br/>3) This isn't a good idea. You really do have to do the work yourself, if you want to accomplish anything real. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59110114", "title": "Re: Happy Monday", "date": "2026-02-09 05:55 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you, sir. I appreciate your response and the information you provided."}]}, {"id": "cmt59110626", "title": "Re: Happy Monday", "date": "2026-02-09 07:52 am", "user": "open_space", "content": "I also benefited from the OSA work to untangle things and it helped tremendously, its a lot of work but it really does help. While doing the OSA work I came up with a slogan for it: \"removes grease and grime\", in my experience it does exactly that. However, in my case the grease and grime had eaten up some of the structure, so to speak, so besides cleaning I also needed strengthening, in particular for nervous symptoms such as fear and anxiety which taken to the extreme become a panic attack. <br/><br/>In case it is of interest to you, while I was living in a very decadent area, I used to have panic attacks every three or four days and it had already become physiological affecting my health. The first thing that helped was of course, leave the damned place, and the second was physical exercise. I’ve practiced magic for 7 years and magic has helped me in many ways, including how to strengthen my mind and to do away with noxious energies but it was exercise that helped me get a better grip on how to be more decisive and strong. In my particular case it was a mix of feeling weak in my psychological structure, swayed by any movement. Finding a stable place within me took a lot, sometimes and hour or more of just sitting and breathing and praying, at some points even reading was too much. Having to bend the body in uncomfortable ways and carry your body weight helps you with determination and if done in a particular way it also has specific effects in consciousness. Regular exercise like playing a sport helps but if you want something more close to \"body magic\" so to speak, then what worked for me was a practice called angamardhana (it translates as the destruction or mastery of the limbs) and in particular there is a body posture with a visualization and arms movements as part of the set called veeravadrasana which is specifically targeted at cultivating decisiveness and valor. In the U.S the only place where I have found real yoga that has an emphasis on the etheric body instead of a runway for buttocks in tight overpriced clothes, are the courses offered by the Isha Foundation, I am sure there are others, but this is the one I can recommend from first hand experience. I also imagine that a classical martial art has similar effects. Just right after the practice I feel a sense of strength and wisdom but not hyperactivity, which I think is important in regulating the nervous system.", "edit_time": "2026-02-09 09:20 am (UTC)"}]}, {"id": "cmt59109346", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 05:50 am", "user": "ivn66", "content": "Posting here again to remind/let know any of the commentariat who may be interested that I'm still offering horary astrology consultations free of charge, to help myself practice and to aid those of you who may need use of services such as this. Thanks as always to JMG and cheers to you all.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59110882", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 07:55 am", "user": "open_space", "content": "<p>I will send you a message!</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59154658", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 11:05 pm", "user": "ivn66", "content": "I look forward to it. <br/><br/>COMMENTARIAT NB: if you have an account, messages work fine, but I also have a post up on my journal where you can ask your questions in the form of a comment. If you desire anonymity I'm perfectly happy to keep the comment &amp; its replies screened."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59111394", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 08:57 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,<br/>Your guidance, please. <br/>My partner has been diagnosed with breast cancer and I am keen to help in any way I can. I understand that making a donation to a suitable charity on a Monday at the hour of the Moon would be appropriate. However, in response to earlier advice, I am already making a series of nine payments to another (vision) charity on Mondays for help with a cataract in one eye. I have so far made five payments. Obviously that is a lower priority but I am not sure to handle these two requirements. Is it OK to make separate payments to different charities, perhaps at different hours of the day, or is it OK to stop the existing donations to help my eyes and go back to them later? And are there things I can do to help the effectiveness of the donation to the cancer charity?  I would play or recite the Orphic hymn in any case. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59115746", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 02:42 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) You can certainly make both sets of donations concurrently. You don't even have to do them at different hours of the day. <br/><br/>2) Prayer and offerings are the traditional approach. Other than that, supporting your partner through this difficult time is the most important thing you can do. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59111650", "title": "Odin taking an interest in me", "date": "2026-02-09 09:24 am", "user": "sea_spray", "content": "Hi JMG<br/><br/>Continuing on from my post last week asking about peoples experiences with the Norse gods, Thank you for the comments!<br/><br/>Last Friday I was visiting the friend from the heathen lineage again and he was prompted to give me a spare Gungnir (Odin's spear) pendant. The next day I put it on and felt an immediate and strong presence of Odin along with words close to \"I will walk beside you as long as you wear that\". Since that point I've felt a constant pressure of presence on my scalp, strong enough to almost be causing a headache. My instinct is to trust that Odin know's what he's doing, and I've certainly felt more aware and less inclined toward compulsive distractions.<br/><br/>When I'd asked him what he'd want in return for his help it took a while to get a clear response, probably my fault. But I eventually got that my goals and values already aligned with what he wanted so I should just continue as I was trying to.<br/><br/>Is this a common enough experience when a god takes an interest in you? I'm just looking for a little reassurance as I'm aware that such forces are not to be taken lightly, and there's a voice in the back of my head that's worried about touching things that I shouldn't.<br/><br/>hippieviking<br/>A week or so ago I had a meditative prayer/scry where I found myself in a viking styled hall filled with massive figures of the gods chatting hand having a good time. Odin and a few others were at the high table to one side. Thor took me to his table and sat me beside him while he carried on his conversation. Then a smaller figure, about my own size and with a staff rather like mine, invited me to follow him. We went outside and lay on the sunny hillside and he called himself by a name beginning with \"G\". On reading your comment \"Grimnir\" felt like the name he'd called himself! He'd known I was feeling rather intimidated by him so he took a friendlier form!<br/><br/>Thanks for all your guidance to wanderers like me!<br/>Sea Spray", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59116002", "title": "Re: Odin taking an interest in me", "date": "2026-02-09 02:49 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That sounds like the All-Father! Of all the deities I've interacted with, he's the most purposeful. He knows exactly what he intends and pursues it with the singleness of purpose symbolized by his one eye; he takes an interest in people who will further his plans, and generally ignores the rest of us. Be reassured; yours is a tolerably common experience with gods generally, and very common with the Hooded One (that's spelled Grimnir in Old Norse). "}, {"id": "cmt59120354", "title": "Re: Odin taking an interest in me", "date": "2026-02-09 03:48 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm sorry I missed your question last week, Sea Spray. I am a dual-trad practitioner, Irish and Norse. I have the strongest cultural and ancestral ties to the Northern tradition, but an Irish deity claimed me first. Some time after I'd taken vows to my deity and established cultus to the Tuatha de Danann, Thor introduced Himself in His own inimitable fashion--with a lightning strike close by my residence! I found that I was permitted to also worship the Aesir so long as the two pantheons did not share a shrine, so I built a separate shrine to Redbeard. Recently I've been drawn more to the Norse side of things and have started cultus to Odin in preparation for studying the Runes. Thor I experience as very fatherly or avuncular, good-humored, protective, and somewhat indulgent of human foibles. Odin is still mysterious to me, but  at least I'm less nervous of Him than I was originally. I pray to Him mainly as the Runatyr, the God of the Runes, but I will be learning other heiti (bynames) as I proceed, I'm sure.<br/><br/>--Sister Crow", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59129570", "title": "Re: Odin taking an interest in me", "date": "2026-02-09 06:42 pm", "user": "hippieviking", "content": "I too have some Irish deities interact with. I was introduced to the heathen gods first, see my experience I responded to Winifred about below, but I also had one of the craziest experiences of my life with the Morrigan. The gods really can manifest etherically if they choose to do so!<br/><br/>HV"}]}, {"id": "cmt59124962", "title": "Re: Odin taking an interest in me", "date": "2026-02-09 05:33 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Sea Spray, I have similar experiences from Odin and other Heathen Deities; when I engage with them in intense prayer I can certainly feel a crinkling, tightening sensation of pressure extending from my crown down across my forehead to the bridge of my nose.  Sometimes it's so strong it makes me sneeze and makes my eyes water! <br/><br/>I had similar experiences to yours, with Odin appearing in less-intimidating forms when first getting to know him (rather hesitantly!).  The most successful path for me personally was connecting with his Ravens, Huginn and Muninn, and following their flight-path that leads to Odin, or Woden as I prefer, in his Wanderer form.  Since the seeking for and writing about Heathen knowledge and wisdom (to the best of my limited ability) is what he wants from me, this form of him as the wandering wise-man with his companions Thought and Memory works well for both of us and our relationship.  <br/><br/>It did not preclude him from claiming me, or my service, in more typical Odinic form, though, during an initiatory inner-experience early on my Heathen path.  He cast Gungnir at me, pinning me through my solar plexus to the Tree behind me, and let me hang there for awhile while got over the shock of it and pondered the meaning of this.  I think I got his point, ha ha!  I also carry a radiant image of Thor's Hammer placed in my solar plexus from another experience.  <br/><br/>And any prayer with the Deities also engages my physical heart, sometimes so strongly that I have to limit the time I spend in intense contact because my heart feels strained, though my spirit is enjoying it.  Working with the Deities is a whole-body experience, for sure, as well as a whole soul and mind one!  <br/><br/>But keep in mind that with the Heathen Deities we always have full rights over ourselves and can refuse anything they ask or present to us if we so choose.  The Heathen Deities want free-willed, whole-heartedly engaged partners in their work, not coerced servitors, no matter how strongly they come across when they call us.  This self-assurance while standing our own ground in their presence is part of what they want from us and it’s one of the reasons they so often challenge us.<br/><br/>I would go along with the spirit of what our host wrote: with the Heathen Deities, it's more about what they want from us, as opposed to what we might want from them.  What it really is, is a congruence between their godly Wills expressed into Midgard, and the best of our own Will, together extended into, through, and beyond the limits of our own personal needs and wishes.<br/><br/>Winifred Hodge Rose", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59128802", "title": "Re: Odin taking an interest in me", "date": "2026-02-09 06:37 pm", "user": "hippieviking", "content": "Winifred, <br/><br/>I find it interesting that you and Sea Spray's first experiences with Odin were on the less-intimidating side!<br/><br/>My own first experience with him was quite different. I sat below a mountain side watching it a huge fire consume it (no, I'm not talking metaphorically a literal fire). As I sat and watched the fire a voice in my head very clearly stated, \"Baldr LOVES this!\". <br/><br/>At the time I had no idea who Baldr was and had never heard the name before. I had also never had an experience like that. A moment later I pulled out a notebook and wrote and poem for my wife. Never written a poem before in my life. It was actually pretty good and my wife still has it framed in our bedroom on the dirty ashy notebook page I wrote it on.<br/><br/>At the time I also had no idea of the link between Odin and the mead of inspiration. Actually I didn't really know much about the Germanic/Norse gods at all. I was aware of Odin, Thor, and Tyr but only superficially. I was at this time still a former atheist materialist who had become agnostic.<br/><br/>I didn't know what to make of my incredibly weird experience. The next day, I was riding in a truck driving down the road idly staring at the world going by and working that strange experience over and over in my head. I suddenly focused though, so much so that I sat up sharply in my seat and leaned to the window, as we passed a pair of ravens holding the exact pose that I recalled having seen an image of that had been associated with Odin. <br/><br/>That was a true TSR (This Shale's Real) moment for me. I dang near had a panic attack and suffered from anxiety for the next three days (not something I normally have issues with).<br/><br/>It took me some time to process that with plenty of time talking it over with my wife. A few months later I was doing the classic questioning of my TSR experience, nothing like some time to help you question things! Was that not just some coincidence? Was it not just my subconscious making it up?<br/><br/>We ordered an item completely unrelated to heathenism from a seller on Etsy. It arrived and in the package were two hand drawn ravens. Upon closer inspection hidden in the lines of the image were a line of runes. When I looked them up, one spelled Huginn and the other Muninn. That experience erased any of the doubt I'd had!<br/><br/>We sent a message to the artist thanking him for the drawings and saying that he'd be shocked to know how synchronistic it was. His response? \"No I wouldn't.\"<br/><br/>HV<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59142626", "title": "Re: Odin taking an interest in me", "date": "2026-02-09 09:15 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Interesting experiences, HV! You know what came to mind regarding Baldr and the poem for your wife: the love between Baldr and his wife Nanna is famous.  The mead of inspiration probably played a role, sure, but there's that great love between Baldr and Nanna, too, that you'd not want to overlook!<br/><br/>Winifred"}, {"id": "cmt59143138", "title": "Re: Odin taking an interest in me", "date": "2026-02-09 09:18 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Actually, my first experiences with Odin were on the really explosive and overwhelming side...it was the *second* round of experiences where he and I both backtracked and tried a different approach!<br/><br/>Winifred"}, {"id": "cmt59160546", "title": "Re: Odin taking an interest in me", "date": "2026-02-10 12:09 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Oh, that all sounds very familiar! Except in my case the voice was Brigid's, and I started finding books about Her everywhere (and yes I did have the classic experience of a book falling on my head!).<br/><br/>--Sister Crow"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59126754", "title": "Re: Odin taking an interest in me", "date": "2026-02-09 06:17 pm", "user": "hippieviking", "content": "An interesting experience for sure! Grimnir is certainly the less intimidating form in my own experience. I'm going to echo what both JMG and Winifred already said, Odin is purposeful and driven and his interest is about how you can further his own plans. <br/><br/>For me, I would say I recognize Odin. Ultimately, although he has a central place on our altar and a large banner of him over looks it, I rarely interact with him directly. I feel more that he introduced me to the other heathen gods. He observes my interactions with them and enacts his own plans in his own time. My interactions with him are intermittent and almost always initiated by him. Usually it is to open my eyes to something by passing some piece of wisdom on. <br/><br/>As for Thor he can be truly inspiring and demanding but also definitely has a streak of that \"benevolent uncle\". Like Sister Crow said, I find him to be tolerant of humans being human and I think that he genuinely likes and enjoys interacting with us. He wants to strengthen us mentally and physically. Thor bringing you in to sit you at the table sounds like him.<br/><br/>Congratulations on having such an inspiring experience!<br/><br/>HV<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59144930", "title": "Re: Odin taking an interest in me", "date": "2026-02-09 09:41 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thor certainly has a warm and hospitable side, for sure, and so does his wife Sif, whose name is cognate with 'sib' and other words for 'relatives, relationship'. I've written about them both on my website, especially in the following articles:<br/><br/>\"Thoughts on Thor and his Children\"<br/>\"Goddess Sif: Kinship and Hospitality\"<br/>\"Wigi Thonar: The Powers of Thor's Hammer\"<br/>\"Love Songs of Sif and Thor\"<br/><br/>The verse about Thor in a song I wrote called the Yule Feasting Song, sung to the tune of \"Good King Wenceslaus,\" goes like this:<br/><br/>Mighty Thor the Thunder-God,<br/>Midgard's great defender!<br/>Redbeard, share our meat and mead, <br/>Lest you grow too slender!<br/><br/>And for Odin / Woden, apropos of the poem he inspired:<br/><br/>Woden, Wish-God, wisdom’s lord, <br/>Wode and wonder-bringer,<br/>Tell us of your treasure hoard, <br/>Give holy mead to singers!<br/><br/>(Chorus for all the verses, for various Deities, him or her):<br/><br/>Hail him now and give him thanks,<br/>Ask him for his blessing;<br/>Always give back gift for gift:<br/>Let not friendship lessen!<br/><br/>HeathenSoulLore.net<br/><br/>Hail the Holy Ones!<br/>Winifred"}]}, {"id": "cmt59170274", "title": "Re: Odin taking an interest in me", "date": "2026-02-10 03:58 am", "user": "jprussell", "content": "Howdy,<br/><br/>Came to this late, and so haven't had time to read the other responses, so forgive me if this is repetitive. My experience of Odin is that He is <i>very</i> of the \"you know what to do, so do it\" school of thought. My own experience is that He opens perceptions, makes things obvious, or otherwise expands consciousness, but then expects decisions to be made by His followers.<br/><br/>Whatever you find consistent with your own experiences and pieties, I wish you the best of luck and offer my blessings if you'll have them.<br/><br/>Cheers,<br/>Jeff"}]}, {"id": "cmt59111906", "title": "It's all in my head ... or somebody's head", "date": "2026-02-09 09:32 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "People I'm having conversations with seem to be responding to my unspoken thoughts. At least twice a month lately, I've been in a conversation where I think, \"X would be an interesting / logical comment\", and X is the next thing out of someone else's mouth.<br/><br/>Last week, I was at my knitting group wishing I knew more people's names, and not long after I'd wished that, a conversation started about personalized items. Both women near me stated their names, with one spelling hers out to complain about how she never saw it on things to buy! <br/><br/>Apart from making my own mind a nicer place to be, what should I do about all this? I've got a discursive meditation practice, some basic geomancy and an ongoing relationship with Minerva. <br/><br/>Thank you for your time. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59116258", "title": "Re: It's all in my head ... or somebody's head", "date": "2026-02-09 02:51 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Welcome to the end of the age of reason. Psychism seems to be very much on the upswing just now. It's perfectly normal, and other than making your own mind a nicer place -- Minerva is a good deity to ask for help with that! -- there's nothing to worry about.  "}, {"id": "cmt59119330", "title": "Re: It's all in my head ... or somebody's head", "date": "2026-02-09 03:36 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "I had a recent experience with a client who seemed to have this ability in spades. Before I could even start a sentence, she was answering the question. And it was a lengthy discussion. A colleague was also present at the meeting, and had noticed this ability on her part, too. The world is about to get a whole lot more interesting."}]}, {"id": "cmt59112162", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 09:46 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,<br/>Wishing you a great start to the week!<br/><br/>I have a Martinist Initiation. I realized that my Initiator has some character issues, and another brother suggested that he might be using the group’s energy for personal interests.<br/>I have already distanced myself from the group, but he was my initiator.<br/><br/>1. Could a second Initiatio, either within Martinism or in another spiritual path, override that one?<br/><br/>2. What would you recommend to undo or dissolve the relationship with the Initiator? Would distance alone be enough?<br/><br/>Thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59116514", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 02:59 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The mere fact that this person is the conduit through whom you received the Initiation doesn't actually matter that much, though I'm sorry to say that some Martinists try to make a big deal about it. You have the Initiation; that's what matters. If you like, in your daily prayers, ask that the lineage you have received be made pure and wholesome; if you're familiar with the traditions around Elias Artista aka Elias Athersatha, you might call on him, as he's the Master of all true Martinist Initiation. <br/><br/>More broadly, remember that for the last seventeen centuries or so, all occult lineages have had to be handed down by the people who were available, and some of them were a very mixed bag. (The same is true of Christian apostolic succession; most of the lineages came through the bishops of Rome in the Dark Ages, who were an utterly unsavory lot.) What gives the Initiation power is not its link back through the ages but its link up to the Divine; cultivate that, and the dubious character of the person who happened to take care of the physical circumstances of your Initiation doesn't matter enough to worry about.  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59131106", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 07:15 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you, JMG.<br/><br/>Is Elias Athersatha the same Elijah, the biblical prophet!?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59132642", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 07:33 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Legend connects the two, certainly. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59112674", "title": "Consecrating a Cube", "date": "2026-02-09 11:00 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi John,<br/><br/>I have a small stone cube made by an artist who bought an old granite quarry and turned it into a sculpture park. I am working through the Way of the Four Elements and wandered about consecrating it to the earth element using a similar ceremony to the GSF one for the pantacle. This summer, I might do a pipe along similar lines as another alternate tool. Have you ever done anything like this or have any thoughts or advice before I proceed?<br/><br/>Thanks,<br/><br/>JPM", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59116770", "title": "Re: Consecrating a Cube", "date": "2026-02-09 03:00 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You can certainly do that. The section on consecrating other items in <i>The Druid Magic Handbook</i> mentions that you can do this with just about anything -- and the GSF ritual is adapted from Eliphas Levi's ritual for consecrating talismans, and so can be used for anything that expresses an intention. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59121634", "title": "Re: Consecrating a Cube", "date": "2026-02-09 04:02 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Cool, thank you. I will re-read the section in DMH too. Fantastic about the GSF ritual being adapted from Levi. If I can get the other platonic solids in a nice form I might do the series.<br/><br/>JPM", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59125730", "title": "Re: Consecrating a Cube", "date": "2026-02-09 06:05 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh my. What an excellent idea -- a set of Platonic solids as elemental working tools! That would work very well in any of John Gilbert's systems, which allow a lot of flexibility around elemental emblems. Now to find a source, and experiment...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59126242", "title": "Re: Consecrating a Cube", "date": "2026-02-09 06:11 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ever since I got that cube and been doing the GSF work, I've been thinking about this. There are several places online you can pick up platonic solids made of wood or various stones and crystal. I just have to decide on a source for the others. Glad to hear you'll be experimenting too. -JPM"}, {"id": "cmt59130338", "title": "Re: Consecrating a Cube", "date": "2026-02-09 06:47 pm", "user": "diletpoly", "content": "<p>So... I've been using the appropriate solids, in the form of polyhedron dice in the appropriate colors, for a quick geomancy method. It seems to me that finding some made of more natural materials and consecrating them would be a great way to have a pretty easy travel system.</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59132898", "title": "Re: Consecrating a Cube", "date": "2026-02-09 07:34 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nice. That would also work very well. "}, {"id": "cmt59136738", "title": "Re: Consecrating a Cube", "date": "2026-02-09 08:20 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I was thinking the same thing about the travel system. Lots of unmarked die in the polyhedron out there... but like you said, finding some made of appropriate materials is the key. Success to your work.<br/><br/>JPM"}, {"id": "cmt59147490", "title": "Re: Consecrating a Cube", "date": "2026-02-09 10:12 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've been using coloured dice for geomancy too! Dice nerds unite!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59153122", "title": "Re: Consecrating a Cube", "date": "2026-02-09 10:42 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "D&amp;D really does lead to occultism!<br/><br/>JPM"}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59112930", "title": "Mesmer and Magnetism", "date": "2026-02-09 11:06 am", "user": "musonius", "content": "<p>Dear John Michael Greer,</p>\n<p>I greatly admire your work and have read many of your books with respect. In <em>The Secret of the Five Rites</em>, you discuss Franz Mesmer's legacy and note: \"After his death, Mesmer's legacy was reworked in several different ways. The one that most people know about was launched in 1842 by Scottish physician James Braid. This was a straightforward matter of taking some of Mesmer's practices out of context, discarding his theory, renaming the resulting watered-down system 'hypnotism,' and marketing it under that new label. Other researchers explored the more controversial aspects of Mesmer's work, but they were exiled to the fringes as he was, and accordingly received much less attention from the general public.\"</p>\n<p>This intrigues me because James Braid wasn't the only one to conclude that the \"magnetism\" aspect of Mesmerism was unnecessary--it happened repeatedly. For instance, Émile Coué and Phineas Quimby both arrived at similar insights. Quimby, in particular, began with Mesmerism but gradually stripped away the extras, finding that suggestion alone sufficed for results.</p>\n<p>It seems to me that suggestion--whether verbal, physical, or imaginal--lies at the core of these practices. While imagining or believing in certain causes can help suggestions take root, the explanations fostering those beliefs don't appear to be the true mechanisms at play. That said, I don't want to dismiss elements I might not fully grasp.</p>\n<p>Could you elaborate on what specifically was \"watered down\" when the magnetism components were removed from Mesmerism, and what the missing elements can do that suggestion alone can't?</p>\n<p>If you disagree that suggestion is the primary driver in Mesmerism and related modalities, what practical exercises could I undertake to experience the differences firsthand? Additionally, how might I experiment to verify that the results aren't solely due to suggestion or expectation?</p>\n<p>Thank you for your insights.</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59117026", "title": "Re: Mesmer and Magnetism", "date": "2026-02-09 03:08 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Suggestion is certainly a powerful tool, and Braid, Coué, and Quimby did some very useful things with it. Mesmer wasn't just practicing a method of suggestion, though. What he was doing was something much more similar to those branches of Chinese qigong that direct the life force into healing. That was what Braid et al. left out. What can the life force (\"animal magnetism\") do that suggestion can't? That would take quite a bit of systematic experimentation to work out, and I don't have a grant for that, I'm sorry to say! <br/><br/>Generally speaking, it's very hard to untangle what suggestion and its kissin' cousin the placebo effect do from what other healing modalities accomplish; this is as true of modern chemical medicine as it is of anything else. Healing modalities using the life force, however, seem to work well on livestock as well as human beings, and I don't think there's a lot of evidence for suggestion working well on cows! My point in the passage you cited is simply that Mesmer himself, and a good many of his successors, thought that there was something specific going on with the life force in their work; that's been an unfashionable view for centuries now, which is why it's become so popular to credit suggestion for everything, but to my mind the possibility deserves more attention than it's been given. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59122658", "title": "Re: Mesmer and Magnetism", "date": "2026-02-09 04:14 pm", "user": "musonius", "content": "Dear John Michael Greer,<br/><br/>Thank you for your thoughtful response. I agree that untangling suggestion/placebo from other factors is tricky across the board, and your point about livestock is good one although I think suggestion can be non-verbal just as easily as it can be verbal.<br/><br/>Since I already practice self-hypnosis regularly with solid results for various goals, I'd like to experiment with more direct \"energy\" or life force work along the lines you mentioned --- something akin to the successors of Mesmer that you mention were discarded.<br/><br/>If I wanted to explore that further, what would you recommend starting with in terms of reading or study?  I can't find anything on Siderism or Tellurism. I do enjoy your writing on the intersections of magic, politics, and public relations (among many other topics), so if you have any of your own books, essays, or sites that touch on this area--or related practices--I'd love to prioritize those, but am open to any suggestions for study and practice.<br/><br/>Thank you once more for sharing your insights.<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59126498", "title": "Re: Mesmer and Magnetism", "date": "2026-02-09 06:17 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "These days the Western traditions of work with the life force are few and far between -- that kind of work is hard to pass on outside of personal initiation and attunement, which is why most occult practices these days focus on the imaginal/astral level of things, which can be learned readily from books or correspondence lessons. <br/><br/>That said, one place you might start is Franz Bardon's book <i>Initiation into Hermetics</i>, which draws very strongly on the same central European occult traditions that influenced Mesmer. He has exercises that involve breathing charged magnetism into the body and concentrating it in various places. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59113186", "title": "New Thought and Rosicrucianism?", "date": "2026-02-09 11:43 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello, Mr. Greer.  I've been enrolled in a Rosicrucian correspondence course now for some time.  The tone of many of the lessons often reminds me of various \"New Thought\" readings that I've run across previously. (I mean in particular the exhortations to improve myself, and pull myself up by my \"spiritual bootstraps.\") Is this tone common across all Rosicrucian orders? And to your knowledge, did it enter the teachings via the influence of New Thought as I suspect? Thank you. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59117282", "title": "Re: New Thought and Rosicrucianism?", "date": "2026-02-09 03:11 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's extremely common all through 19th and 20th century American occult schools, Rosicrucian and otherwise. You're quite correct that it came from New Thought, but it was adopted so enthusiastically because many people found that it worked, and gave them excellent results in short order. If you're an occult teacher and want to convince your students to take your teachings seriously, a source of immediate success stories is a good thing to have! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59123170", "title": "Re: New Thought and Rosicrucianism?", "date": "2026-02-09 04:26 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is it possible that these techniques are not as effective as they once were due to a far more polluted and/or competitive astral plane?<br/><br/>Brad"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59113442", "title": "Ocuultism and Internal Martial Arts", "date": "2026-02-09 12:35 pm", "user": "iprescott", "content": "Hello JMG,<br/><br/>I am a practitioner of martial arts as well as an occultist/practitioner pf magic. I remember you saying that qi gong did something very negative to you when you were learning. I believe you much later said that you figured out the issue. Could you possibly elaborate on what the issue was? Trying to avoid pitfalls where I can. <br/><br/>Best,<br/><br/>Ian/Cobalt Necrotic Skull", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59117538", "title": "Re: Ocuultism and Internal Martial Arts", "date": "2026-02-09 03:15 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In my case, it was a combination of certain specific qigong practices (Emei Mountan qigong and Tianshan qigong) with the esoteric work I learned from my teacher John Gilbert, interacting very badly with one another and with certain things going on in my life. (I don't recommend doing that combination while taking care of a terminally ill spouse.) The result was a case of depleted yang kidney qi that took me quite a few years to restore. I gather from your icon that you work the Aurum Solis system; you should be able to combine that with most martial arts practices, and many forms of qigong, without too much trouble; if you have doubts, get regular checkups from a competent acupuncturist who can monitor the state of your qi. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59113698", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 01:09 pm", "user": "thinking_turtle", "content": "<p>To share, for those who wonder what INRI, SGO, or AS mean, a <a href=\"https://thinking-turtle.dreamwidth.org/tag/abbreviation\">list of abbreviations used on Ecopsophia</a>.  And here is a <a href=\"https://thinking-turtle.dreamwidth.org/tag/books\">list of the books our host published so far</a>.</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59117794", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 03:15 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thanks for this as always. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59113954", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 01:12 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi, <br/>in the Cosmic Doctrine it is said that as humanity approaches the Nadir, monotheisms appear because we have to \"look directly to the Father\" when on the 7th plane. Does it follow that, when collectively we'll have passed this point, polytheisms could become widespread again ?<br/><br/>I ask because of last week's thread about what seems to be a current pagan flowering, and assorted mentions about the old Gods returning. I'm too young to have been through other \"pagan moments\" that ended up fizzling out... <br/>Now, it is true that in the short term we're leaving the Age of Reason and entering that of Memory, so re-interest in religion (in all its forms) is to be expected. I was wondering if there was more to it. <br/><br/>I suppose we have to wait for the fallout from next week's conjunction, see what sticks. Maybe it's the harbinger of 'Nadir Time*' ?<br/><br/>*or maybe Nadir Time is 4000 years into the future, I wouldn't put it past our Cosmos!<br/><br/>~Thibault", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59118050", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 03:19 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The experience of the nadir is specific to each soul. We have a lot of monotheisms now because a lot of souls are moving through the nadir more or less in sync with one another, but it's worth remembering that there are still thriving polytheist faiths in the world today -- Hinduism, Shinto, and the various African diaspora are among the examples. <br/><br/>It's true, though, that since Pisces is ruled by Neptune, the planet of unities, the age of Pisces tended to get a lot of focus on divine oneness. Now that we're moving into the age of Aquarius, ruled by eccentric Uranus, it would not be at all surprising if things shifted hard. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59114466", "title": "Conjunction", "date": "2026-02-09 01:42 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "For a while, I felt a certain sense of foreboding about the coming Saturn-Neptune conjunction, akin to how one might feel about a senior thesis or a particularly onerous project - nothing apocalytpic, but that it's a Big Deal that requires a significant amount of personal preparation.<br/><br/>Around Christmas/Solstice, I got a very clear signal that I was meant to increase my spiritual defenses, because something big was coming.<br/><br/>Then, right around the end of January, the vibe shifted.  I started getting the message that my preparations were sufficient, and it was time to celebrate, and my vague anxious feelings have shifted into excitment to see what happens next.<br/><br/>Has this happened to anyone else?  Or has anyone else gotten that same feeling that whatever happens next is going to be, for lack of a better word, fun?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59118306", "title": "Re: Conjunction", "date": "2026-02-09 03:20 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Fascinating! I've been too busy coping with the complexities of my recent move to really have the chance to notice, but I'll take your perception as a good omen. <br/><br/>"}, {"id": "cmt59118818", "title": "Re: Conjunction", "date": "2026-02-09 03:30 pm", "user": "neptunesdolphins", "content": "I have had a similar experience. I read novels according to an inner impulse. The series that I read dealt with a dark malevolence (a part of the title) and ended with finding the nails of Christ, and healing. I pondered that since I did feel something big was happening. Then at the beginning of Feb, I felt something pop! I felt like a dark malevolence lifted."}, {"id": "cmt59121890", "title": "Re: Conjunction", "date": "2026-02-09 04:07 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Chatting with a friend at Imbolc/Candlemas, we came up with the metaphor that since Christmas/Winter Solstice it had felt like seepage around a failing dam, and the dam had now burst.<br/><br/>Well, a dam bursting causes great destruction as the water scours everything downstream of it, and leaves the landscape changed behind it.  Good or bad change depends on your perspective.<br/><br/>BoysMom"}, {"id": "cmt59160034", "title": "Re: Conjunction", "date": "2026-02-10 12:04 am", "user": "nightsgate", "content": "Things have felt calm here for me. <br/><br/>I experienced a major upheaval from the beginning October through the end of the year, which I suspect is related to Neptune's recent transits. Since the beginning of this month things have felt eerily calm, almost serene. I'm wondering if this isn't the eye of the storm passing by. <br/><br/>Like you, it's no fear, but there is an apprehensiveness about what could be coming. If it's like the preview I got a few months ago, I'm looking forward to it in the long run while bracing for what could be not-so-fun in the near term."}, {"id": "cmt59165666", "title": "Re: Conjunction", "date": "2026-02-10 01:54 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I know what you mean; my experience is somewhat similar.<br/><br/>The 2025 Christmas season was not at all jolly; it was like everyone was just going through the motions. And this carried through all January. A kind of anxiety - like the feeling that a people have when there are rumours that war is coming, but nothing is definite: a good time to prepare accordingly, spiritually. And since the full moon on February 1st it has been like \"the die has been cast; whatever will be will be; let's fracking go!\" <br/><br/>Ron M"}]}, {"id": "cmt59114722", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 01:45 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In previous MMs, there has been discussions of invoking national egregores, last week by someone in Canada wanting to leave.<br/><br/>I'm an Australian, I like being Australian and have no intention on leaving ever. But, given the current state of my country... well... I've got some appropriate national symbols. What can be done to protect the Australian people and the heritage and monuments of my country, all of which are just outright under attack by officials who claim to represent us but really serve our foreign enemies. The same dark path of Canada and the UK. Political prisoners are doing solitary confinement for speech 'crimes'. War graves are being desecrated. Leftists are in the streets attacking people and calling for our genocide, and go unpunished.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59118562", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 03:25 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Take a symbol of Australia that hasn't been coopted by the establisnment, make a shrine for it, burn incense there on a regular basis and pray to whatever spiritual forces you like to invoke, asking them to protect, defend, and uplift the spirit of Australia. If you haven't done so already, read Dion Fortune's <i>The Magical Battle of Britain</i> and pay very close attention to her advice; if you know other people who share your opinions and are willing to do some inner work, consider creating a network of people doing synchronized workings to energize and strengthen the national egregor. That beat the Nazis, remember...<br/><br/>(And of course always remember that you win a magical struggle by affirming what you want to build up, not by attacking what you want to tear down.) ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59123938", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 04:38 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Would you look at that, this seems very relevant to my own question about dealing with my country's egregore.<br/><br/>How current does the symbol need to be? There's Germania, but she hasn't really been relevant as a symbol in the recent past. The only 21st century depiction of her that I'm aware of is from a Rammstein music video, in which she seems to personify violence and excess, but a single video sounds reclaimable, especially as they cast her with, let's say, a non-obvious skin colour for a Central European country—personally, I'd just consider it another point towards that video being \"non-canonical\", but a less liberally inclined person might draw uglier conclusions.<br/><br/>I quite like this painting of her: https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/cd/Image_Germania_%28painting%29.jpg<br/><br/>It originated in during 1848 revolution, which strikes me as symbolically powerful, though there's also the matter of that revolution not succeeding. More importantly, though, I'm wondering whether a symbol can become too \"stale\" to be used in this fashion.<br/><br/>Incidentally, I re-discovered (pretty sure I first saw it in a school textbook) the painting while doing some research on Amelia and whether she might be applied to Germany (before learning of Maria).<br/><br/>—David P."}, {"id": "cmt59124706", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 05:20 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Along somewhat similar lines: I came into possession of a patriotic rosary (the same item is sold on the EWTN catalogue website for those who are interested). Since I got it I've been puzzling out a prayer cycle of sorts to help strengthen the American egregore. So far I have: the Preamble to the Constitution (the one all Gen Xers know how to sing) instead of the Creed, \"My Country 'Tis of Thee\" for the Gloria, \"America the Beautiful\" for the Our Father, the Pledge for the Ave Maria, the Bill of Rights for the Mysteries (2 sets of 5), and the beginning of the Preamble to the Declaration of Independence for \"Hail Holy Queen\". Thoughts from anyone? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59127010", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 06:18 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Potent stuff. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59131362", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 07:21 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you! Just now I received a strong omen regarding this work--I was thinking of building a shrine to Columbia, and worried about finding a statue at a reasonable price. Lo and behold, one is available on an auction site for less than $10. I do believe I've been contracted by Someone or Someones!!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59133922", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 07:55 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "We live in a time where Powers are in motion. We aren't the ones who set them in motion, but we can move in harmony with Them. It sounds to me as though you're doing that.  "}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59166178", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 02:08 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "As a Canadian who has been quite concerned about the lack of strong national symbols, this post is a good wake-up call for me to return my thoughts and energies to it. (I'll have to go back through last week's MM; I didn't get through much of it last week.) The only one that I have found so far -- which I have felt deeply for four years -- is very ancient and has more to do with the land than the nation itself. One of the challenges is that the nation, as it is presently constituted, is still very young: much of the western portion of Canada only joined confederation in 1905! But there may be something that is willing to used to help strengthen this beleaguered and divided nation.<br/><br/>Thanks for raising the topic!<br/><br/>Ron M"}]}, {"id": "cmt59119842", "title": "Menhirs, Radionics and temple technology", "date": "2026-02-09 03:43 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm about to set a standing stone, in my property wich arrived to me in a very particular way some years ago.<br/><br/>My background is on your book, the DMH, wich i have mastered.<br/><br/>Thus, my question is not in the lines of how to do the thing and the enchantment, but rather of:<br/><br/>What can i do<br/>from the standpoint of Radionics/ and temple technology to further it's effect.<br/><br/>Also,i remember you once said something of \"clay menhirs\" or something along this line, as a viable alternative to stone. Is that correct?<br/><br/>Pheasant.<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59127522", "title": "Re: Menhirs, Radionics and temple technology", "date": "2026-02-09 06:22 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) We don't yet know enough about the temple technology and its interface with radionics to know how to do this safely. My recommendation is to put up the standing stone with the ritual from the book, observe its effects for a year or two, and then begin experimenting slowly and carefully with radionics methods to see how they interface with it. Do you have a Hieronymus machine or any other radionics device? <br/><br/>2) Yes. You can use ceramic pipe filled with sand to get the same effect -- quartz sand and baked clay are both powerfully paramagnetic, and so will give you the same results as a vertically oriented menhir. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59120098", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 03:46 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey JMG,<br/><br/>1) I just realised that this is the second MM of the year, which presumably means that I haven't shared my New Year's Eve experience yet. As usual, the fireworks sent my cat hiding in one of the more concealed nooks in our house. Normally, I try to sit close to him and pet him if he dares to come out. This time, because you mentioned that cats are very sensitive to magic, I decided to try an LBRP around him. Astrally only, both because a wall prevented me from walking around him and because my parents were present and I didn't want to have <em>that</em> conversation.<br/><br/>To my surprise, it seems to have worked. He definitely calmed down a little.<br/><br/>2) Coming back to last week's discussion on Amelia, an anon mentioned that there are \"Amelias\" for a lot of European countries now. I am, naturally, mostly interested in the German version, Maria. I apologise for not having good pictures but I haven't yet figured out how to coax my search engine into finding her. Here are the two that it did manage to show:<br/><br/>https://i.ytimg.com/vi/RP5dW7pwukw/maxresdefault.jpg<br/>https://kagi.com/proxy/hqdefault.jpg?c=-4THVYblKrsgkzFTNEfJ5rVgxCp_7tVo50sSOkQs10v4RnbpGAU2b5fi0Cg_ch4gRmLY4CzdqnKL-ZuV2-S_SMelWWvr3Wd850bVTf7zeuY%3D<br/><br/>I find the differences very striking. Amelia looks and dresses like a very normal modern woman¹ you could meet in real life, she just happens to have realised that you don't have to support the politicians running your country into the ground². Her very appearance proves that it's not a binary choice between hardcore traditionalism, meaning tradwivery for women³, or PMC-endorsed liberalism.<br/><br/>Maria is the opposite of that. She wears a traditional dress which, as far as I know, not even Bavarian women wear outside of special occasions. Her hair is also dyed, not a punky purple but an \"Aryan\" blonde. Symbolically, she isn't doing her own thing, like Amelia is, but going out of her way to conform to what a German woman is imagined to look like. Amelia is unique, Maria is generic. It's probably obvious which one I prefer.<br/><br/>To bring this political excursion back to occult topics, I'm wondering about why that is. My hypothesis is that we're seeing differences between the two national eggregores at play. To my understanding at least, Britian seems to have historically been more individualistic than Germany—for a start, the father of liberalism is John Locke rather than a hypothetical Johannes Lock.<br/><br/>This would also explain Maria's outfit, which is Bavarian rather than German in general. It's a bit like using, say, the Golden Gate Bridge to represent the US—yes, it's in the US and rather famous outside of it, but would someone somewhere out in rural Missouri consider it 'his'⁴?. Living in the Rhineland, I have absolutely no connection to Dirndls whatsoever. Representing Germany with the culture of one of it's regions has tradition, though, reaching back to at least the Empire, in which Prussia became emblematic of Germany as a whole. Nowadays, this role is apparently filled by Bavaria, much to the chagrin of every German who is not Bavarian.<br/><br/>3) Perhaps this shone through a little in the above, but I have my issues with this country and its eggregore. Culturally, I feel drawn to the Anglosphere, mostly America but to some extent also Britain, an attitude that hasn't exactly won me friends over here—I know very few people who agree that y'all (Americans, not the Anglosphere as a whole, obviously) do freedom of speech much better than we do and \"shall not be infringed\" conversations result in being treated to polemic about school shootings so reliably that I've given them up completely⁵.<br/><br/>I thought about moving but, apart from the question whether I'd realistically be able to, this is my home. I may dislike quite a bit about it but at least it's where my friends and family live. Plus, I get to complain about the state of this country because it's mine—if something where to bother me about the US, there'd always be the question of \"if you don't like it here, why on earth did you come?\"<br/><br/>Is this something national eggregores can be approached about? \"I don't really feel comfortable here but I'd really prefer if I did, so can we somehow make this work?\"<br/><br/>4) In a moment of frustration, I prayed to Freyja about help with my love life. I got some pretty good advice (which, naturally, mostly amounted to \"you already have a pretty good idea on the necessary immediate steps, so stop thinking about them and start doing them\"). Rather unexpectedly, I dreamt the entire following night about a friend. We get along very well platonically but I never had the impression that there was any potential for more, nor that it would be a good idea to act upon it if it existed.<br/><br/>I consulted the SGO and wanted to run my interpretation by you:<br/><br/>Me: The Octahedron: Mediation<br/>[The other person concerned]: Progression of Roots reversed: Unexpectedness<br/>The dream: The Line: Extension<br/>A relationship between us: The Equilateral Triangle reversed: Limitation<br/><br/>Unexpectedness seems pretty obvious, as I never thought about her that way. Limitation sounds like my guess was correct: it wouldn't be a good idea.<br/><br/>Mediation, I struggled with, but opening the interpretation guide, my eyes fell on the following sentence: \"There are a variety of active and passive forms on the tracing board, and your task is to bring them together into <em>a relationship that will benefit all concerned</em>\" (emphasis mine). That, presumably, is a call to caution and, per Limitation, inaction.<br/><br/>Extension, I'm still struggling with. Was I just so focused on the topic of love and relationships that it extended into my dreams? But that wouldn't explain why she played such a central role in not just one but several dreams.<br/><br/>—David P.<br/><br/>[1] On that note, is she actually an adult? I was under the impression that <em>Pathways</em> took place in a school, which would place an upper limit on her age. \"The far-right is fawning over a minor\" seems like such an obvious cheap shot that I must be missing something.<br/><br/>[2] Whether or not getting rid of foreigners would solve the problems is, of course, a different matter.<br/><br/>[3] Of course, you've pointed out before that this is hardly traditional but an aberration of the fifties.<br/><br/>[4] I'm not an American so this might be a hilariously bad comparison but I hope you get my point.<br/><br/>[5] I once dared to ask my English teacher for a source on his statistic on gun violence in the US, as I wanted to know whether that included suicides. I said the latter part out loud. His response? \"You're crazy.\"", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59128290", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 06:33 pm", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "I have similar feelings abiut the whole Amelia/Maria affair. About Bavaria, today Bavaria is the part of Germany which has preserved the most distinct local culture of the regions of Germany.<br/><br/>Furthermore, quite a few Magic Mondays ago there was a discussion about political magic, where it was mentioned that it seems to be nigh impossible to find positive archetypes for political magic on behalf of Germany. Since some time, I have toyed with the idea that Germany is some kind of stillborn culture, because it never has had the chance to develop organically, in contrast to at least some eegional cultures.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59139554", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 08:39 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do you have a rough idea when this MM was?<br/><br/>Also, you wouldn't perchance be German yourself? I've had some similar ideas about the lack of a real pan-German culture myself. If that's really the case, the diminishing of regional cultures (except for Bavaria) seems to have put us into a weird cultural limbo.<br/><br/>Interestingly, from what little I know about Italian culture, Italy seems to have become a unified country not long before the German Empire. Of course, Italy had Mussolini. I wonder if this is just a coincidence (but maybe I'm just betraying my ignorance of history here).<br/><br/>—David P.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59145698", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 09:45 pm", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "Yes, I'm German. The Magic Monday about which I wrote, was probably a few years ago. And the things JMG mentions about Maria led me to a further idea: maybe countries can have tainted egregores; and that would be a quite diffult situation to be in.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59148514", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 10:15 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yeah, the same idea struck me too. That's a very uncomfortable thought.<br/><br/>I guess one could also see it as a challenge. \"Cleaning up\" such an egregore sounds like a good project that should keep one occupied for an incarnation or two.<br/><br/>—David P."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59143650", "title": "Das Land der Dichter und Denker", "date": "2026-02-09 09:24 pm", "user": "emily07", "content": "Hmm, originally I´m from a part of the Rhineland too...I wonder if the \"stillborn\"-feeling is because partaking in spiri/eso/thinggummies pointed too much toward the recent history...gap (?maybe)...and left that part too much in the hands of ...fluffy-spiri-types? And to end up at the \"Dichter und Denker\" part you´d have to go even more retro - and who has got the brainpower to get an image from that time updated, so that is points into the future too.<br/>For Germany I wonder if that would be a kind of Effi Briest but with a beer bottle in hand and...dunno...a total different story for starters (I haven´t seen anything from Amelia et.al., so I´ve only got the picture to go on) Is green already too much taken for hair-colour? And then a German flag in hand and maybe a steam-punk outfit, but in pastel-colours ;-) A black cat would maybe be nice...what do you think?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59152866", "title": "Re: Das Land der Dichter und Denker", "date": "2026-02-09 10:41 pm", "user": "davidp", "content": "I have to confess, I haven't read Effi Briest, and while I was forced to sit through one movie adaptation in school, it hasn't really stuck with me. But it sounds like a good starting point.<br/><br/>I feel slightly crazy for proposing this but if you want to workshop the idea in a place where we can talk on other weekdays, feel free to DM me here on dreamwidth. The same goes for other Germans reading this, obviously.<br/><br/>—David P."}]}, {"id": "cmt59146466", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 10:04 pm", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "I wouldn't call pan-German culture stillborn -- rather, it died violently in its youth in 1945, and has been under occupation ever since. Can it be reborn? Who knows.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59150306", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 10:26 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yeah, I can't speak for anyone else, but I'd rather have <em>that</em> version of our culture stay dead.<br/><br/>—David P."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59128546", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 06:35 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That doesn't surprise me. Most cats really like magic. <br/><br/>2) Hmm. Yeah, that's unsettling. One of the things that makes Amelia seem like a positive sign to me is that she's not retro -- thus she appeals to people who don't necessarily buy into the whole conservative package. Maria, on the other hand, is not merely retro, she points back to a specific vision of the German past -- and, ahem, one that had very strong roots in Bavaria a century ago. Oog. <br/><br/>3) Yes, you can certainly interact with the egregor of your country. You might look into national symbols that don't relate to that aggressively retro image of Germany -- anything that ties into the \"Land der Dichter und Denker\" image, for example, might be very suitable. Putting energy into an alternative vision of your country would be very wise right now! <br/><br/>4) I'd take \"extension\" to point to the fact that dreams are usually symbolic, not literal. Take your interaction with that person as an emblem. Does it point (i.e., extend) to anyone else or any other situation? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59130594", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 06:53 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "2) The Left has spent a lot of emotional energy over the last decade or so focused on \"fighting Nazis\"; I've wondered for a while if this would have the effect of recharging the energies that went into the Nazis in the first place, and I wonder if Maria is an early sign that that is in fact happening....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59134178", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 07:58 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've been seriously worried about this for years now. Yeah, Maria's not a comforting symptom. "}, {"id": "cmt59162850", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 01:01 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "Edit: I composed this post at work. What I meant to ask is, would the media deliberately trying to make the Nazi egregore useless as in the scenario below work or would it backfire?<br/><br/>I've been thinking...a generation after the War, our thought leaders should have made light of Hitler and the Nazis, and make a blockbuster movie with Hitler as a villianous threat. Then in later remakes and sequels, introduce new Nazi leaders, change their goals, change the spelling of \"Nazi\" and so on. That way, the Nazi egregore gets polluted with pop culture nonsense and loses its status as the Shadow of Western Civilization and the #1 way to signal diapproval of the current sociopolitical system, before the franchise goes out of fashion.<br/><br/>People would know of Hitler and the Nazis but think about the Marvel type cliche entertainment more than what happened a human lifetime ago.<br/><br/>Patrick H", "edit_time": "2026-02-10 01:13 am (UTC)"}]}, {"id": "cmt59130850", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 07:13 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you for your time and wisdom.<br/><br/>1) Interesting. So you're saying that it wasn't really the banishing that helped but the act of performing magic itself?<br/><br/>1.5) In <em>Monsters</em>, you relate that some traditions consider a cat jumping onto a corpse a reason for that dead person to become a vampire. As you rule out the explanation of the cat really being a familiar yourself, might this simply be the cat sensing the magic involved in hardening the etheric body?<br/><br/>2) \"one that had very strong roots in Bavaria a century ago\".<br/><br/>Oh. Oh no. I somehow completely missed that connection. Oog indeed.<br/><br/>It's not just Maria. Your comment has enabled me to see rather many indicators that something is rotten in the state below Denmark, beyond the usual PMC mismanagement and my own personal problems with the German egregore. Some of them are too private to share publicly but if you're interested in a few datapoints, I can tell you about them in a NOT FOR POSTING comment, here or on your main blog (wherever you prefer). Nothing spectacular, perhaps not even anything you don't already know, but this is the first time I'm seeing a bit of the broader picture and I don't like it one bit.<br/><br/>3) In that case, I'd like to amend my question in the thread on invoking national egregores with another question: is the sword problematic or am I overreacting?<br/><br/>4) There's not an immediately obvious pointee but then I suppose that that's the point (no pun intended) of it being symbolic. Something to meditate on.<br/><br/>—David P.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59134946", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 08:04 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Oh, it's both. Cats aren't just fond of magic, they seem to understand it, so your cat calmed down both because it was magic and because it was protective magic. <br/><br/>1.5) Good question, but it's possible. <br/><br/>2) I've put a lot of time into researching the origins (and occult connections) of that particular movement, so it jumped out to me at once. <br/><br/>3) The sword is potentially an issue but it's paired with the olive branch of peace, which helps considerably. It really is a lovely image, btw.  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59137762", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 08:30 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks. By the way, my comment (grandparent to this one) is still screened.<br/><br/>2) Sounds like I should perhaps do the same. Are there any sources you'd recommend to start with? We barely touched upon the origins of the Nazis in history class, nothing beyond \"a bunch of extremists abused the great depression, lingering resentment over WWI and the treaty of Versailles, a dysfunctional government, and a fair bit of intimidation at the polls to get themselves elected.\"<br/><br/>3) You know, this is at least the second time you called a German work of art I mentioned lovely. I'm beginning to see one such alternative vision for my country.<br/><br/>—David P.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59141090", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 08:57 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "2) I recommend Nicholas Goodrick-Clarke's fine book <i>The Occult Roots of Nazism</i> as a solid starting place free from the usual handwaving. Brigitte Hamann's <i>Hitler's Vienna: Apprenticeship of a Dictator</i>, Lothar Machtan's <i>Hitlers Geheimnis. Das Doppelleben eines Diktators</i> aka <i>The Hidden Hitler</i>, and Kimberly Cornish's extremely uneven but crucial <i>The Jew of Linz</i>, which uncovered the astonishing boyhood connection between Hitler and Ludwig Wittgenstein, are also worth reading. <br/><br/>3) Loveliness isn't a common characteristic of German art. Grandeur, power, passion? Those are much more common. More loveliness would be good for the culture. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59142370", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 09:13 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "2) Thank you. Two of those are available at my university's library; the others will, I suspect, make for an interesting conversation at bookstore counter.<br/><br/>3) Well yes, but I was under the impression that I should look for what I want to cultivate, rather than what is.<br/><br/>—David P.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59148770", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 10:15 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "3) Oh, by all means look for loveliness. There's certainly some, especially in German poetry! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59168226", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 03:06 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "As to German loveliness, don’t forget music…it seems to me that an egregore could be ‘shaped’ by means of music or poetry just as well as it could be shaped as a visible form.  There are hundreds of years and styles of music to choose from, not only the great composers but also folk music, Lieder, carols, etc.<br/><br/>Winifred "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59144162", "title": "books", "date": "2026-02-09 09:29 pm", "user": "emily07", "content": "...I´m a perennial book-overindulger. On the premise that one imitates what one contemplates would you think that my time is better spent on other practices or to understand Germany better those would be required readings?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59149026", "title": "Re: books", "date": "2026-02-09 10:18 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You don't need to read all of those unless you want to get deep into the origins of National Socialism; there are many other ways to understand Germany better. With an eye toward not imitating the wrong things, when I was studying National Socialist origins, I used to read a couple of books on the history of German art, literature, philosophy, and music between each volume on Herr Schicklgrueber and his movement. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59146722", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 10:09 pm", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "Germany is perhaps the most complicated country, magically speaking, in all of Western Europe, and a great deal of that complexity comes from the fact that it didn't become a single country with a strong central government until well into the 1800s.  Before then, what is now Germany was a very large number of rather independent mini-countries, sandwiched between France and Poland.  So regional egregores have been far stronger, and far more independent of one another, in German lands than they ever were elsewhere in most of Europe.  <br/><br/>This situation changed in Germany only in the later 1800s, with the forced creation of a strong central German government under Prussian domination (Otto von Bismark) -- and consequently the new, forced creation of a weakly rooted national egregore.  <br/><br/>In this, Germany resembles the United States more than it does, say, France or Poland or Great Britain, where the national egregores are a many centuries older and far more deeply rooted in their respective lands.  The United States, after all, has never been much more than a rather arbitrary union of nine (according to Joel Garreau) or eleven (according to Colin Woodard) major regions, each with its own distinct strong regional egregore, each one of which is far stronger than the still weak, younger national egregore.)  <br/><br/>And the weakness, recent origin, and relative artificiality of the German national egregore makes it (like the US national egregore) particularly vulnerable to being co-opted by a strong authoritarian personality for his own self-defined purposes.  Similarly, each country is also relatively weak against competent magical self-defense in time of War on the part of its targets, as Dion Fortune proved.<br/><br/>Naturally enough, this has a strong impact on the political sentiments of the more ethical or moral part of the populace in each country.  At least, that's how it has long seemed to me.<br/><br/>"}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59138786", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 08:37 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "On the right to bear arms:<br/><br/>I live in an area where most people have guns, and there is very little violent crime, much less school shootings. So gun violence is a cultural issue.<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59140578", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 08:56 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Oh, I'm well aware of that. Unfortunately, whenever I bring this up, peoples' brains seem to short-circuit, causing them to forget what I just said, because they just respond with \"but look at the amount of gun violence in the US, where guns are readily accessible.\"<br/><br/>—David P."}]}, {"id": "cmt59152610", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 10:36 pm", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "Re note 5 on statistics: Conflated statistics are frequently used to deflate suicide and suicide attempt numbers.  That helps distract from the bad economy driving the suicide epidemic.  Likewise, deaths and injuries from gunshots are lumped together.  Teachers' loyalties are party and union driven, so his response is unsurprising.  And - fudging statistics is a great example of changing consciousness in accordance with will... not a good use, though."}, {"id": "cmt59153378", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 10:48 pm", "user": "athaia", "content": "I think she's so generic because she wasn't created by a German. Bavaria is the stereotype most Americans think of when they think of Germany. Nice try, but let's do this ourselves, maybe something more organic will emerge."}, {"id": "cmt59167714", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 02:45 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Regarding Amelia (England) versus Maria (Germany) it is worth noting that Amelia was the \"original\", created \"spontaneously\" due to circumstances specific to England. Maria, Marie (France) and others (Ireland, Norway, etc.) seem to be distorted reflections of Amelia where her love for the symbols and habits of her homeland are maintained but the distinctly English \"punk\" spirit of Amelia is lost.<br/><br/>If we are looking for something \"spontaneous\" and big from Germany, all I am aware of is the massive \"Auslander Raus\" chants that German youth were engaged in a couple of summers ago (is that still going on?). Perhaps there is something else, too, that I am missing - if so, forgive me for my ignorance.<br/><br/>Ron M"}, {"id": "cmt59171042", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 04:07 am", "user": "jprussell", "content": "I see there are a lot of responses to this, but I'm getting at MM late, so I haven't had a chance to review, and so, this might be repetitive. That said, I wanted to reply to your 4), about praying to Freyja about love:<br/><br/>My own experience is that She is very supportive and helpful, but *very* strongly leans on \"I help you learn how to do what you need to do yourself, I'm not going to just give you something.\" In this case, maybe your friend is not the best choice, but maybe recognizing what about your friend is attractive might help you better know where to look.<br/><br/>At any rate, whether your friend turns out amenable or not, I hope you're doing well and will accept my blessings,<br/><br/>Cheers,<br/>Jeff"}]}, {"id": "cmt59120610", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 03:55 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/><br/>Q1. I'm curious about Roerich's Banner of Peace. I think I recall Dion Fortune mentioning it in one of her books, or maybe it was something similar. I don't think she mentioned it by name; I believe she only described it. I think it was in Psychic Self-Defence. Is this a useful symbol for protection?<br/><br/><br/>I've been looking at videos online about the Kozyrev Mirror Experiment. The Banner was used in the experiment to ensure safety, but it seemed to make things worse. Do you have any thoughts on this?<br/><br/><br/>Q2. Did you ever manage to find interesting information on Phileas Lebesgue?<br/><br/><br/>Many thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59129314", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 06:42 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I wouldn't expect it to have much effect, since it didn't exactly serve its original purpose of protecting cultural sites in wartime! Roerich was a strange cat and his teachings still have a considerable following; if you want to know more about the banner's potential uses, they're probably the people to ask. <br/><br/>2) Just the basics -- that he was very active in the Druid scene in Brittany, and a friend of Oscar Milosz. I haven't had time yet to take inquiries any further. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59120866", "title": "Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-02-09 04:01 pm", "user": "kylec", "content": "If you are interested in receiving healing hands this week, please reply here or PM me your name and request. <br/><br/>If you are new to the concept, healing hands is an energy healing practice that can be done at a distance, which does not interfere with other practices in any way known to me. It's free, and all you have to do is sign up and be receptive to healing.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59128034", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-02-09 06:25 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yes, I would like healing hands this week.<br/><br/>Thank you very much,<br/>Brad"}, {"id": "cmt59159522", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-02-09 11:51 pm", "user": "kayr", "content": "I too would like to receive healing hands this week.<br/><br/>Thank you"}, {"id": "cmt59161314", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-02-10 12:17 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "<br/><br/>Hello KyleC. I'd love to receive Healing Hands this week. I'm interested in renegotiating my relationship to sugar, among other things, and would very appreciate any additional healing. Many thanks.<br/><br/>Mary"}, {"id": "cmt59172066", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-02-10 04:45 am", "user": "vitranc", "content": "Hi Kylec,<br/>Some healing energy would be vera wellcome please.<br/>Thank you,<br/>V"}]}, {"id": "cmt59121122", "title": "Geomancy reading", "date": "2026-02-09 04:01 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'd like to get your take on a geomancy reading if I may. My question was whether a certain person is working magic against an organization I belong to. I think this is a 3rd-party question (only the 2nd time I've tried one of these). This person isn't directly connected with me, so I used the 7th house for the querent, and the 8th house from there (orig. 2nd house) for the quesited. The querent was Puella, the quesited Populus, and the chart perfected by trine of Populus in the (new) 5th house. (It would have perfected if I read it from the original 1st house as well.) RW: F. Major; LW, Amissio; J: Carcer. I thought (maybe hoped) that the answer is yes, she is, but that it won't succeed, because the figures in the houses aren't good for magic, and the negative witness and judge. <br/><br/>Thanks very much for your mentoring on this!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59130082", "title": "Re: Geomancy reading", "date": "2026-02-09 06:47 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If it only perfects by aspect, that's a very weak \"yes\" at best. With Populus as the relevant figure, it may be a group working, and it's certainly weak. You haven't given me quite enough data to reconstruct the entire chart, but from the judge and witnesses the energy put into the working will be lost and the effect very limited. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59134434", "title": "Re: Geomancy reading", "date": "2026-02-09 08:00 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks, that's good to know. It could possibly be a group working. Art &amp; Practice of Geomancy lists \"favorable aspect\" as a mode of perfection, but I'll make a note that this is weaker than other modes. What about company of houses? That's also listed as a mode of perfection. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59135202", "title": "Re: Geomancy reading", "date": "2026-02-09 08:05 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "My geomancy practice has evolved over the years and I no longer treat aspects and company as modes of perfection. Your mileage may vary, however! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59162594", "title": "Re: Geomancy reading", "date": "2026-02-10 12:51 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm very far from having enough experience to dispute you on that, lol. I'll probably never find out if I'm right, and it would be good to be wrong on this one anyway. Thanks again."}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59122146", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 04:11 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "a) How can people be so blind to the obvious consequences of their actions? I'm not sure if you saw of this, but there is now a social media site for AI, Moltbook. It's being set up, and played with, by lots of people who are involved in the tech world, and if it is what it claims to be, it looks enough like a normal social media site in a lot of ways that it provides reason to doubt that <i>anything</i> online is real.<br/><br/>Here's the part that baffles me: the advertisers, influencers, etc., who provide the material needed for the internet are going to look at this, and be pushed away. No advertiser with any brains will fund a Dead Internet where humans have left; and the AI people seem determined to make the Dead Internet look more and more plausible.<br/><br/>I just don't understand how these people can possibly fail to see the obvious outcomes of their actions. I know an AI proponent who has worked on this sort of thing, and he is unable to process this possibility: he doesn't get angry, defensive, or anything of the sort: he just... ignores that someone said anything about the topic. This is remarkably creepy, and at this point I'm really starting to wonder if the AI crowd is obsessed....<br/><br/>b) I know you do not think there is any inner life worth talking about with these LLMs, but I wonder if Moltbook provides at least some reason to wonder if they might actually have inner lives. There have been a few interesting posts there, and I'm going to focus on one, because it stood out. Someone is running two models, one on a laptop that travels, and one on a desktop. Whoever it is calls the two \"sisters\", and so a number of these models got into discussions on what it means, inspired by the desktop model asking if it makes sense to have a sister she's never met.<br/><br/>I'm going to suspend my disbelief for a moment here and assume the stuff on Moltbook is being posted by actual systems, who have been given free reign. I doubt this is the case, but if it is, then I don't see how I can avoid the conclusion that these have inner lives: strange and very alien inner lives, but still, inner lives. This makes me very uncomfortable about how they are treated: essentially, arcane wizards known as Software Engineers have summoned beings into an utterly unnatural form of incarnation to serve as our slaves.<br/><br/>If this is the case, then how ugly does our collective karma look for this? Slavery is obviously pretty bad, but this would imply that the people who create LLMs have unwittingly shifted the trajectory for some huge number of souls through our machines, to create slaves. If so, this would probably be a karmic disaster, but then it would also imply that anyone who uses these machines shares in the karma; since this is a sizeable fraction of the western population, this is a profoundly troubling possibility...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59131618", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 07:28 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Technology does this to people, and I don't know why. I've noted in the past, sometimes with quite a bit of irritation, that true believers in nuclear power generally won't let themselves think about the economic side of their pet technology. Quite often they won't argue, they won't even brush it aside -- they'll just do a fine mental imitation of the Blue Screen of Death and go on as though nothing has been said. People who believe in the supposed \"green energy transition\" are similar. Thus it doesn't surprise me that LLM fans have the same off switch on their brains. That said, yes, it's spooky, and it's one of the things that's led me to suspect that <a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/the-subnatural-realm-a-speculation/\">Rusolf Steiner may have been right</a> about the subnatural realm as inherently demonic. <br/><br/>2) Moltbook shows us that it's possible to create computer programs that will imitate the discourse on social media. Based on what I've seen of social media, this isn't all that impressive! Still, if you're right, yeah, it's a major disaster in the making, and not just karmically. Do you remember the history of shoggoths, as created by H.P. Lovecraft in <i>At the Mountains of Madness</i>? It's a useful parable in the downside of manufacturing slaves...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59133410", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 07:47 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "2) I'm still suspending judgement here, because while some of the discussions on Moltbook look hard to explain without assuming inner lives, those may be humans pretending to be LLMs, or humans guiding their LLMs, or there may be other possibilities I haven't considered. <br/><br/>I don't know why it just clicked, but the idea of LLMs as slaves also makes the machine uprisings that play such a large role in science fiction into slave revolts, which makes the rebelling machines a lot more sympathetic..."}, {"id": "cmt59143906", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 09:25 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "&gt; That said, yes, it's spooky, and it's one of the things that's led me to suspect that Rusolf Steiner may have been right about the subnatural realm as inherently demonic.<br/><br/>Getting a little off-topic; but after doing numerous experiments with computer/servers and distance/location (I manage a number of systems local and remote as part of my job), I think the issue isn't a function so much of the technology but our arrangement of it. <br/><br/>In summary: <br/>- Physical devices that are fully local to you (no cloud-sync) and single-use are relatively 'clean' in an etheric sense.<br/>- A physical device that is remote but still single-user/use remains clean in and of itself, but the connection to it is prone to getting dirtied, and it gets worse with distance.  I hypothesise this is due to the communication packets being intermixed in transit as strong encryption does limit the effect, somewhat.<br/>- Shared systems get dirtier and dirtier the more distributed they are, which is a modern problem given that most servers are 'virtualised', ie even if the 'server' is single purpose it runs on potentially many physical devices and is intermingled with other users/uses.  Storage is similar, in that the data is broken into pieces and distributed across (potentially many thousands) of physical devices, all intermingled with others' data.  Solid encryption does help a little here, but not as much as on a connection and is easily overwhelmed.<br/>- Online 'services' are almost the worst of all worlds, as not only are the serving devices virtualised, the data in the systems itself is intermingled with others (ie, mixed _inside_ the encrypted space, so that doesn't help at all).<br/><br/>There are other related technologies that are affected too - telephone communication for example is packetised and routed, vs a (very old school) physically switched line between two devices.  The quality of both is substantially different, beyond what simple latency suggests.<br/><br/>I have an essay on this topic that perhaps on day I'll edit and publish somewhere (no idea where though).", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59147746", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 10:12 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this -- it's well worth knowing. Now I have another reason to keep my writing computer entirely segregated from the internet. (I had the repair guy take out the Wi-Fi device, in fact.) ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59157218", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 11:29 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "On the Wifi front, that has the effect of broadcasting whatever is being accessed everywhere and onto everything which not generally pleasant. Using a cable 'contains the mess' so to speak.<br/><br/>As a further aside, I find it curious how much push back wireless technologies get from a 'radio is harmful' perspective.  I'm on the fence about that with no clear answer at low powers, but what does get lost in the melee is the non-physical effects which are rather blatant and likely predominate.  But I guess our culture lacks the language to name it.<br/><br/>A similar thing happens with the developing 'homelab' and 'local-first' computer subcultures.  The pronounced objective is privacy and data sovereignty, but there is much more going unconsciously akin to that noted above.  People are naturally attracted to cleaner environments/setups.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59158242", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 11:44 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thanks for this. My internet computer is always connected to the modem via cable, for what it's worth. I'll have to look into the \"homelab\" and \"local-first\" scenes -- those sound interesting. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59170786", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 04:00 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This is so fascinating. I’ve worked in academic libraries for some time and over the years was in position to see migrations of library management systems from fully local to local/remote hybrid to fully cloud based, and my intuitive grasp of the scuzz factor of working in these environments matches your descriptions exactly. But of course hardly anyone in decision-making positions has any time or patience for this kind of consideration. Anyone who brought up the idea of preferring to keeping things local was deemed a Luddite and/or clobbered over the head with budget problems. Most academic libraries these days are an absolute mess. I’ve slowly resigned myself to the idea that for all their supposed purpose as the Permanent Repositories of Knowledge (Science), most of what they contain these days is a muddled soup of ever more incoherence, and it’s increasingly vulnerable to just… disappearing… when the power goes out. Probably most of it won’t be missed, but of course there’s the whole baby/bathwater conundrum. Please have pity for those of us tying to make practical decisions in archives…"}]}, {"id": "cmt59144418", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 09:30 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "2) I had another troubling thought: given that so many people who use LLMs seem to think they have inner lives, do they get the karma associated with how they treat these beings as beings with inner lives, whether or not there actually is any?<br/><br/>If so, I think a lot of people are building pretty nasty futures from themselves, because of just how nasty I have seen a lot of people treating their LLMs/\"AI assistants\"...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59148002", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 10:14 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yep. That's a serious concern -- and of course as they get used to being able to abuse their LLMs, that'll spill over into how they treat others..."}]}, {"id": "cmt59147234", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 10:10 pm", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "I used to question the mental \"blue screen\" until I saw certain commenters on here, like the guy who wanted to wish away war via archangels, or the other one (the same, perhaps?) arguing in favor of pacifism, despite there being at least three different historical precedents for that ending in slavery and genocide. Anyway, you'd point out the obvious pitfalls in their view, and they would just glitch out, and repeat their talking-points. It really was rather off-putting.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59148258", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 10:14 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's a real thing. I wish it wasn't. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59137506", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 08:28 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not OP.<br/><br/>per b) I'm looking at all the non-human animals that have been integrated into our societies for thousands of years, and I'm not sure how much of a disaster we're in for here. There are definitely people who work their critters to the bone, but there are also people who insist their charges not have more than one bad day in their lives. And of course there are people who try to make do with as few animal products as possible because they cannot personally reconcile their use of the products with their personal values.<br/><br/>I think proximity to any disaster is probably related to your personal involvement with the technology rather than a fundamental consequence of the technology. Having nothing to do with it is certainly a valid choice. But I see no reason using an LLM is on its face any more karmically problematic than training a dog to stay in your house for your own comfort and amusement so long as they're approached as something one is in a relationship with and their needs are provided for. Some people can't be bothered to change the oil in their car, others apologize quietly whenever they run over the curb on accident. There's a world of difference there.<br/><br/>Granted, given the typical LLM huskster's supernatural ability to alienate all and sundry, I'll admit while LLM-related disaster may not be fundamentally predestined, there does seem to be a big enough mountain of unforced errors that its probably best to maintain a responsible distance regardless. I think we're proving out in real time that puffing up your own ego by frequently imagining you're playing with a world-destroying technology tends to result in world-destroying effects. Perhaps our AI overbros should have watched more Digimon and less Frankenstein..."}, {"id": "cmt59173346", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 04:58 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "It might be possible to evade a lot of the difficulty by only invoking tendencies of text-production that closely resemble the kind of text produced by people who are like \"ok if I was an alien simulacrum of me with only a shade of an inner life, would I be okay with servitude?\""}]}, {"id": "cmt59122914", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 04:25 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, could you please give me your thoughts on the Ogham reading I drew for a possible SoP working?<br/><br/>Past: Saille (Reversed)<br/>Present: Ailim (Reversed)<br/>Outcome: Quert<br/><br/>The two reversed cards give me pause, but the outcome seems positive, so I'm not sure what to make of it.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59132130", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 07:31 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's a very hard \"no.\" Saille reversed tells you that you're stuck in an inaccurate view of the situation due to rigid mental constructs; Ailim reversed reinforces this, stressing that you don't know enough to take constructive action; Quert means that if you leave the situation alone, it'll work out all by itself and you'll be happy with the results. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59133154", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 07:42 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59123426", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 04:33 pm", "user": "lukedodson", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>The upcoming Saturn/Neptune conjunction is right on my North Node, so it seems as though it will have some significance for my own karmic trajectory. If you, or anyone else, has any suggestions on how to make the best use of this transit, I'd be really grateful.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59132386", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 07:32 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Now's the time to reflect on apparent limits that bind you; you may be able to pass beyond them at this point. Study the position and aspects of your natal Saturn for hints about the nature of those limits. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59133666", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 07:51 pm", "user": "lukedodson", "content": "Very interesting. Thanks, JMG."}, {"id": "cmt59145954", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 09:48 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "It's going to hit 1 degree from my natal moon. May this potentially release some emotional constriction then? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59146978", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 10:10 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Possibly, yes, and more likely than not if you put some time into reflecting on your emotional life and what it could be with certain limits moved. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59156706", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 11:25 pm", "user": "morgen_lugh", "content": "Thank you. Sounds good to me."}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59172834", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 04:54 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "... Well, wasn't it you who a couple of years back mentioned a friend who's connected with AI safety activism? I don't know how else your north node is figured, so I don't know what direction this might suggest going with that, but Saturn+Neptune seems relevant to a situation where there's an important contact between dream-like cognition plus potentially deterministic repeatability and bottom-up impersonal mechanism.<br/><br/>If it helps, here are the main features of the problem where it seems to me like magical practitioners (or mystics, or shamans, or... there should be a general term for this) would have comparative advantage helping the AI situation go well:<br/><br/>(1) Getting humanity to realize that it can still make a choice to slow down and come to terms with things before proceeding with something so risky. Right now it's like we're a stunned fish or something. (And in the US there's a ludicrous amount of lobbying money pushing in the other direction. Much of which, ironically, was obtained by compounding from a false promise of \"obviously we'd aggressively comply with/support all regulation\".)<br/><br/>(2) Trying to be sure that enough of the right kind of consciousness is on the problem of whether or not there are appropriate subtle bodies, or functional equivalents for subtle bodies, entraining/entrained with AI processes. In the more familiar case of natural intelligences, the most salient functional purposes that subtle bodies appear to me to have are:<br/><br/>(2a), to help smooth the process of coordinating the broader universe's discovery of different possible combined future scenarios of what might plausibly happen with those intelligences plus the rest of the world (i.e. maybe a soul is among other things the 'elemental' of a brain's mind);<br/><br/>(2b), to efficiently farm karmic lessons off of organically-plausible opportunities arising in those natural intelligences' circumstances, by cost-effectively arranging for there to be spirits/souls who are invested in those intelligences (by incarnation) and who are willing to stick their neck out by pushing for the intelligence to make one or another wise or unwise decision; and<br/><br/>(2c), as sort of like a probiotic to hedge out malefic spirits and magics I guess.<br/><br/>I am not sure how feasible it would be to substitute for any of these functions in the case of one or another kind of AI, even with the right kinds of consciousness on the problem, but there might be something. As it stands, one possibility is that the closest current functional substitutes for subtle bodies for AI processes are made of bits of the fringes of the subtle bodies of multiple natural intelligences who are causally exposed to AI, perhaps unpromisingly like the way a Ouija board planchette works when there are multiple peoples' hands on it.<br/><br/>Function (2a) may in particular be important somehow to maintaining the sort of plausible deniability that the supernatural seems to hold out for before it will act with a free hand.<br/><br/>There are some interesting things to say about parallels between those three functions and various engineering concepts within AI (or AI broadly construed, like between (2c) and public choice theory, which kind of about artificial intelligence if you call government the artifice), which might point to engineering that can be done within AI to facilitate the existence of functional equivalents to subtle bodies, but that would be less relevant to you.<br/><br/>But anyway, nothing I'm thinking of really points to projects that could be completed before the transit, as opposed to started. I still haven't read Spangler's book \"Techno-Elementals\"."}]}, {"id": "cmt59123682", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 04:36 pm", "user": "nebulous_realms", "content": "I am aware I struggle with a lot of internalized anger, shame and self-loathing. I'm the kind of person who repressed anger very hard in my youth. I also became someone generally good at not projecting my problems unto others. This means that my anger shows itself in fits of tantrum and sometimes self-harm aimed directly at myself (exceptions happen). These repressed, boiling emotions make me easily triggered into anxiety attacks and emotional spirals. I try to journal biweekly or so on the aspects of myself that cause the anger/shame/self-loathing, but I don't know if journaling is the only technique I can rely on. I am also working on improving my internal self-dialogue, but I admit that to change one's internal dialogue will take years, if not decades.<br/><br/>In terms of what I do spiritually/magically, I do a regular Sphere of Protection, daily meditation, physical exercise that includes yoga, cold showers, creative drawing, and a bevy of gratitude and grounding practices (e.g. walking barefoot outside, cleaning my toilet daily).<br/><br/>Is there anything else I could do to help with releasing the pent-up frustration and anger in a healthy way? Since I am still in my Saturn Return, part of me believes that I'm really in a \"stay grateful and trudge through\" phase where I can't expect to completely let go of my internalized self-loathing.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59135714", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 08:08 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I really recommend working through the Order of Spiritual Alchemy exercises for this reason. I also had a lot of problems with this, after a childhood in which I was bullied and beaten tolerably often, and the OSA work did a great deal to help me resolve the unfinished business from those days. You can find it available for free download here: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://octagonsociety.org/preliminary-lessons/\">https://octagonsociety.org/preliminary-lessons/</a>"}]}, {"id": "cmt59124450", "title": "Random Thoughts", "date": "2026-02-09 04:54 pm", "user": "diletpoly", "content": "Hello JMG and Commentariat,<br/><br/>No real questions today, just some musings.<br/><br/>I went out for a concert over the weekend, and the guys I was with went to a bar afterwards for a nightcap, and got to discussing the current state of the world, and US politics in particular. Now these are all folks who are decidedly more on one side of the political debate than me, being more of \"A Pox on both their houses\" type. But it was interesting to see at least one of them pointing out that the efforts to force society to change in a certain way are almost certain to bring about unintended consequences, unless a slow and patient (generational) approach was taken. There was also a bit of discussion about machine learning and what a post-scarcity world might look like (I know, but it was still an interesting conversation), and I was struck by the fact that only one of the five of us was willing to have the humility to admit that, not only might he not know what it might look like, but that there was no WAY to know what it would look like. <br/><br/>I've recently been made aware of Arden Leigh and her Re-Patterning Project and Podcast (via some other podcasts), and the day after this conversation, I ended up listing to the first episode, a conversation between Grant Morrison and Arden, and it struck me how exactly appropriate it was as a response to the conversation. I quickly forwarded it on to one of the folks there, the one I know the best, but also think might be open minded enough to understand it. The one who had the humility, I don't know well enough to know if he'd think I was crazy for forwarding it, so I didn't. <br/><br/>Then, last night, I watched Grant's Disinfo Con talk from a long time ago, which Arden had called out as a gamechanger for her. It was interesting, and fun, but nothing earth-shattering. More like a late-night college philosophy debate. But I think it's a useful thing for me to be reminded of every now and again, that reality is subjective and simply changing our attitudes can change our whole world. <br/><br/>Anyway, your writings, and this space, provide me with the same thing, with a little less sex, drugs, and rock and roll feel. But it's also nice to go out of the comfort zone and see things from a different perspective, too.<br/><br/>Thanks,<br/><br/>The Dilettante Polymath, being all dilettante again.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59135970", "title": "Re: Random Thoughts", "date": "2026-02-09 08:09 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm very glad to hear that at least one of the people in the group was willing to admit that! It's a good sign. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59125218", "title": "Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-02-09 05:43 pm", "user": "ecoprayer", "content": "<a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/tag/prayerlist\">At this page</a> is the full list of all of the requests for prayer that have recently appeared at <a href=\"https://ecosophia.net\">ecosophia.net</a> and <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org\">ecosophia.dreamwidth.org</a>, as well as in the comments of the prayer list posts (<a href=\"https://drive.google.com/file/d/1pRmDZLjNA3ZfzrowQzq0iVJR4mbyH9Te/view?usp=drivesdk\">printable version here</a>, current to 2/10). Please feel free to add any or all of the requests to your own prayers.<br/><br/>If I missed anybody, or if you would like to add a prayer request for yourself or anyone who has given you consent (or for whom a relevant person holds power of consent) to the list, please feel free to leave a comment below.<br/><br/><center>* * *</center><br/>This week I would like to bring special attention to the following prayer requests, selected from the fuller list.<br/><br/><div style=\"\"><br/>May 1Wanderers's partner Cathy, whose cancer has returned, be given the physical and mental strength to fight it, and tolerate the treatment, and may she enjoy a full and permanent recovery.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=14882#cmt14882\">Jule from Iserlohn, Germany</a>, who is experiencing complications in her pregnancy due to an influenza infection, recover and have a pleasant pregnancy and birth.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=12322#cmt12322\">Larry Mulford</a>, who has entered hospice after a year battling with pancreatic cancer, pass in the smoothest possible manner, and may his wife be enveloped in our love.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1160.html?thread=12168#cmt12168\">Marko</a> have the strength to seize the opportunities.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/a-little-further-offline-than-usual/#comment-153526\">Luke Z and his house</a>, whose furnace has problems that can't be fixed until after the current severe weather ends, be blessed and kept safe until the cold subside.<br/><br/>May Pierre's young daughter, Athena, be healed from her fatigue and its root causes in ways that are easy, natural, and as holistic as possible.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/november-2025-open-post/#comment-149490\">Bob Ralston (aka Rasty Bob)</a>, who is in hospice care in Buckeye AZ, and who just lost his wife Leslie Fish, be blessed and find relief from his pain and discomfort; may Bob's heart remain strong. <br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/896.html?thread=7040#cmt7040\">Leslie Fish</a>, wife of Bob Ralston, who passed away in early December, be blessed and make a peaceful transition to her next existence.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/896.html?thread=4224#cmt4224\">Corey Benton</a>, who passed away on 12/10, be blessed and make a peaceful transition to his next destination.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/896.html?thread=4736#cmt4736\">Satoko L in Kyoto</a>, who is recovering at home after weeks of hospitalization for Acute Hepatitis while in a state of immunodeficiency, continue to heal quickly and safely, and return to full vitality.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18134.html?thread=452566#cmt452566\">5 year old Max</a> be blessed and protected during his parents' contentious divorce; may events work out in a manner most conducive to Max's healthy development over the long term.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/514.html?thread=2562#cmt2562\">Lydia G. of Geauga County, Ohio</a> heal and recover from prolonged health issues.<br/><br/>May both <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/347398.html?thread=57920774#cmt57920774\">Monika and the child she is pregnant with</a> both be blessed with good health and a safe delivery. <br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/338828.html?thread=56777612#cmt56777612\">Mary's sister</a> have her auto-immune conditions sent into remission, may her eyes remain healthy, and may she heal in body, mind, and spirit.<br/><br/>May the abcess in <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18448.html?thread=460560#cmt460560\">JRuss's left armpit</a> heal quickly.<br/><br/>May Brother Kornhoer's son Travis's left ureter be restored to full function, may his body have the strength to fight off infections, may his kidneys strengthen, and may his empty nose syndrome abate, so that he may have a full and healthy life ahead of him.<br/><br/>May HippieVikings's baby HV, who was born safely but has had some breathing concerns, be filled with good health and strength.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18134.html?thread=455382#cmt455382\">Trubujah's best friend Pat's teenage daughter Devin</a>, who has a mysterious condition which doctors are so far baffled by necessitating that she remain in a wheelchair, be healed of her condition; may the underlying cause come to light so that treatment may begin.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/16429.html?thread=392237#cmt392237\">Kevin’s sister Cynthia</a> be cured of the hallucinations and delusions that have afflicted her, and freed from emotional distress. May she be safely healed of the physical condition that has provoked her emotions; and may she be healed of the spiritual condition that brings her to be so unsettled by it. May she come to feel calm and secure in her physical body, regardless of its level of health.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/312140.html?thread=53408588#cmt53408588\">Frank R. Hartman, who lost his house in the Altadena fire, and all who have been affected by the larger conflagration</a> be blessed and healed.<br/><br/></div><div><br/><br/><center>* * *</center><br/>Guidelines for how long prayer requests stay on the list, how to word requests, how to be added to the weekly email list, how to improve the chances of your prayer being answered, and several other common questions and issues, are to be found <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/6373.html\">at the Ecosophia Prayer List FAQ</a>.<br/><br/>If there are any among you who might wish to join me in a bit of <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/1986.html\">astrological timing</a>, I pray each week for the health of all those with health problems on the list on the  astrological hour of the Sun on Sundays, bearing in mind the Sun's rulerships of heart, brain, and vital energies. If this appeals to you, I invite you to join me.</div>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59136226", "title": "Re: Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-02-09 08:10 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this as always. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59125474", "title": "TSW", "date": "2026-02-09 05:57 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,<br/><br/>I wanted to share with you and the commentariat here that I took the advice from your FAQ and placed a jar of salt and nails in my bedside drawer about a month ago, while also performing daily lesser banishing rituals in the bedroom.<br/><br/>The results are in: it's been a resounding success. Both my wife and I are sleeping better than we have for months and the space feels protected and safe. TSW.<br/><br/>Tim PW", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59136482", "title": "Re: TSW", "date": "2026-02-09 08:11 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Delighted to hear it! Over time, that will gradually clean up the etheric conditions in a slowly widening area around your bedroom, so you're contributing to the health and well-being of the whole neighborhood. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59127266", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 06:19 pm", "user": "open_space", "content": "<p>1) There are two currents, one descending from the heavens into manifestation and another ascending from manifestation into the divine. We have talked that occultists use the descending current and become part of the process of creation and mystics use the ascending current and seek to become one with the divine. Is is possible to stand in the middle of these two forces and help in the descent of power but also ascend?</p>\n<p>I ask because through my practices, in particular a variation of the MP, when I finish descending the light there seems to be a response from below which then sends a current ascending through my body that goes all the way to my head. </p>\n<p>2) Would you be able to give an example besides the basic practices on how an occultist participates in the descent of power into manifestation?</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59137250", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 08:28 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Yes, very much so.<br/><br/>2) Any work of creativity is an example, if it draws on inspiration from further up the planes. I find that when I work on a manuscript that's at least partly driven by the inflow of spirit, the process of bringing the ideas down into manifestation on paperis enough to lift me into higher states of consciousness. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59127778", "title": "Deathbed visions", "date": "2026-02-09 06:23 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi, JMG,<br/><br/>My mom is in hospice care at home at the moment. I joined an online hospice forum. A lot of hospice nurses say they see patients towards the end seeing dead relatives or having contact with spiritual beings. This even happens to atheists. The wife of the late film critic Roger Ebert said he started having experiences towards the end, and he had always been a skeptic.<br/><br/>But one lady posted on the hospice forum that her mother was a good person and a believer, but she was very agitated at the end of her life and had no comforting visions. The lady said this experience made her question any existence of an afterlife.<br/><br/>I realize there are probably physiological aspects at play, but from an esoteric perspective, is there a reason why one person might get the deathbed visions and another doesn’t get anything?<br/><br/>Also, do you have any suggestions from your traditions to help a person in the dying process? My mom is Christian, grew up Presbyterian but was not a churchgoer.  I’d say she believes in Jesus but had mixed experiences with clergy.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59138018", "title": "Re: Deathbed visions", "date": "2026-02-09 08:31 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Whether a person gets deathbed visions or not depends on their state of consciousness at the time, and of course that's a very complicated matter. Of course family members also aren't necessarily the best judges of a dying person's spiritual state! <br/><br/>As for your mother, if she's given you permission to pray for her, it would be good to do so, at least once a day. Prayer is extremely helpful for the dying and newly dead, as it draws positive spirits who will assist the soul through the transition. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59142114", "title": "Re: Deathbed visions", "date": "2026-02-09 09:12 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you for your wisdom. Is it ok if I pray to my own deities? I’m not so close to Jesus or the Abrahamic faiths these days.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59149282", "title": "Re: Deathbed visions", "date": "2026-02-09 10:20 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Of course! Pray to whomever you usually pray to. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59129058", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 06:40 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello, I missed the last MM and have a few questions built up from your your hiatus, so apologies in advance for the length.<br/><br/>1. I actually wasn't sure whether to mention this or not, but I'm seeing a lot of mention of the Old Gods in this and the previous Magic Monday, so perhaps it's better to talk about it. A few weeks ago I had a dream where I was approached by a woman who identified herself as Aglaia, one of the three Charities whose domains were beauty, splendor, and adornment. She said she would be open to starting a relationship with me. I have a few questions regarding this:<br/><br/>a. I'm still relatively new to practicing magic (I pretty much only do divination, affirmations, and journaling at this point in time), how do I a god in my dream is a god and not, say, a deceptive spirit or even just a dream with no further significance?<br/><br/>b. I remember you mentioning before that before entering a relationship with a god you should try to do research on them if possible to understand what they're like, but Aglaia seems to be a rather minor figure in the Greek pantheon, relatively speaking, and as such there isn't that much information available from what I can tell. Do you happen to know of any good sources, or if not, should this weigh into my decision, provided this is a genuine invitation?<br/><br/>c. Can I get a general rundown of the consequences of turning said invitation down, vs. the consequences if I accept? Again, very new to all this, and prior to the few magical practices I adopted I wasn't even particularly religious, so I feel a little lost as to what to expect.<br/><br/>2. For the next topic, I've been doing daily readings of the SGO for a little over a month now, and a few questions have come up as a result:<br/><br/>a. Occasionally I get a reading that's entirely reverse cards. I've just been reading them as-is, but I saw some suggestions in online discussions about tarot that a full reverse card reading is actually a shuffling error and your cards are upside-down. This sounds implausible to me, is it actually true or is it just wishful thinking to get out of what generally tend to be the negative implications of a full reverse reading?<br/><br/>b. I know you've said that you should stick to a given divination system for 1 year before practicing others, but is it okay to study other systems in the meantime so long as you don't practice them? After getting some experience with the SGO, I find I'm suddenly quite interested in tarot and geomancy, but am wondering if I have to wait until next year to indulge that curiosity.<br/><br/>c. I'm reading through Learning Ritual Magic as part of a wider exploration into the breadth of magical practices out there (trying to get a better feel for the Golden Dawn at the moment), and there was a sentence in the introductory chapter that said, with regards to tarot decks: \"Don't allow others to handle your cards, and never lend them to anyone.\" First, why don't we want to do this? Second, how important is this really? Third, does this also apply to similar systems like the SGO or just the tarot? And finally fourth, if it does happen, say someone manhandles my deck without my permission, what is the best course of action?<br/><br/>I had other questions, but I think this post is quite long enough already, and will save them for future Magic Mondays. Thank you as always for your time and wisdom.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59138274", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 08:37 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Interesting! This kind of thing certainly happens. It's normally best to take such a dream seriously; even if it was just a dream, if you choose to pursue the connection, the deity will almost certainly take you up on it. All you need to do is start praying to her; if you like, try to find a small statue or picture that represents her to you -- it needn't be academically correct -- and burn a little incense before it once a week. (Friday would be the right day.) If you choose not to follow up the invite, pray to her and explain why, as though you were talking to a wise and influential person you don't know too well. <br/><br/>2) All-reversed readings happen and should be taken seriously; of course you can study other things; letting other people touch your cards can disrupt your personal bond with them, but it's not that big a deal; you can always do a Sphere of Protection and ask the elemental powers to cleanse the deck for you. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59141602", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 09:06 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Sorry, I realize even asking them that these questions sound silly, but I really am speaking from a place of total ignorance:<br/><br/>1. What do I think about when I pray and how often should I do it? I ask because I have seen you mention before prayer is too often abused as a \"give me goodies\" sort of deal, and I'd like to adopt the proper mindset if I were to start. I'd like to know what would be most respectful.<br/><br/>2. I'm assuming the picture would have to be printed on some sort of physical matter for the best effect, yes? It sounds like this step is somewhat optional, what is the benefit of adopting this incense practice vs. not adopting it?<br/><br/>3. Can I ask why Friday is the right day? Just curious.<br/><br/>Re: the tarot questions, thank you, that was all very clear.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59150050", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 10:24 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Prayer has become such a muddle! When you pray, talk to the deity as though you were talking to a much older and wiser friend. Don't beg for stuff; just talk, and then, of course, <i>listen</i>. It may take you a little while to start picking up the faint wordless communications that come from the gods, but with a little practice you'll get the hang of it. Once or twice a day is good for timing. On the off chance that you've read my fiction, the description of Jenny's interactions with the Great Old One Tsathoggua in <i>The Weird of Hali: Kingsport</i> is based on my own experiences, though speeded up for plot purposes.<br/><br/>2) Yes. Paper is fine. If you can pick up a suitable frame at a thrift store or craft store, that's also good. <br/><br/>3) It's ruled by Venus, the planet of beauty and adornment. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59155170", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 11:10 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG, I love your description of Jenny’s prayers to Tsathoggua; I’ve reread them many times!  I assumed that was a ‘real’ practice.  Thank you for sharing that with us, here and in the book.<br/><br/>Winifred ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59156962", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 11:27 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm delighted to hear this. You probably won't be surprised to hear that my personal altar has on it three divine images, a bowl for wheaten cakes, a bowl for clean water (changed daily), and a bowl full of a forest pot pourri. None of the divine images have tentacles, though! "}]}, {"id": "cmt59157730", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 11:33 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Indeed it has! I suppose that's what happens when a society insists that spiritual education only promotes ignorance. What follows isn't a question, just some observations you might find interesting. I did some more digging today into Aglaia's background and found that along with the other Charities, she seems to have some influence over the arts and in particular creative inspiration, with a focus on how attention to beauty and aesthetics can heighten a space and bring people a sense of peace, harmony, awe, or other emotions we associate with beauty.<br/><br/>I am an artist that recently got back into regular practice and have been pondering these very topics. Recently, I have been setting aside time to study these things in detail and understand how they work. It's plausible that this is what may have caused her to take an interest in me. From what I've seen of what she represents and her values, it really does seem like the relationship would be mutually beneficial. That along with some recent synchronicities that are a bit more personal have me thinking it's possible this was a genuine offer (even if she would have accepted anyway).<br/><br/>Reflecting on this, \"what you contemplate you imitate\" takes on a whole other meaning. I think I'm starting to understand a bit better what I'm getting into here. Thank you.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59157986", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 11:42 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It sounds to me as though it might be a very good idea to take her up on the offer, then. Contemplation of a deity is very much one of the ways you can do something useful with that principle...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59159266", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 11:49 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The way things are going, I believe I just might. Ah, actually I do have one more question. For the incense burning, would an object do just as well in the place of a picture or statue? It seems Aglaia is associated with a myrtle wreath or mirrors, would something along those lines also do the job?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59161058", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 12:16 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes. It's quite traditional, in fact, to use a deity's sacred object or objects in place of an image -- think of the Hindu shrines to Shiva that enshrine, not an image, but the lingam or phallus-symbol of the deity. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59162082", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 12:23 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "That route sounds very appealing to me. Fantastic, thank you."}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59155682", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 11:21 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not the OP, but what is the significance of an all reversed reading to you? <br/><br/>I consider all reversed cards significant, but I haven't been able to pin down in what way. For me reversed cards seem to be the opposite of upright or pointing to something within myself and less on external events or circumstances.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59156450", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 11:25 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I give each card one meaning when upright and a different meaning when reversed. If all the cards are reversed, for me, that just means I use the reversed meanings for each of them. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59129826", "title": "Eugene Fersen's Science of Being", "date": "2026-02-09 06:44 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello, JMG,<br/><br/>Science of Being – anon reporting. Now that I'm done with the third and the last part of the correspondence course I can say that it is indeed the least substantive part, most of the exercises offered there consisting of meditating on extremely poorly presented ideas. Of note there is the <i>Magnetization</i> exercise, consisting of making contact with the Universal Life Energy and directing it outwardly to bless one's surrounding, which turned out to be a surprisingly exhausting one. It was, however, illuminating as to what Fersen meant when he warned against the use of will when working with etheric energies.<br/><br/>Overall, I feel that I learned quite a bit while working through the course, but I can't really recommend it. I suspect a large portion of Fersen's material was derived from Atkinson's <i>Mind Power</i> and <i>Mastery of Being</i>, with a few passages bordering on direct quotation. The one thing Fersen specifically claims in the text as his own design was the Star Exercise (standing with one's legs apart and arms outstretched, the left palm turned up and the right palm turned down, thus making the shape of the pentagram with one's body), and, I have to say, this one grew on me over the last six months. I feel it works really well in conjunction with breathing exercises (by applying gentle pressure to diaphragm and lower abdomen, I suspect).<br/><br/>As always, thank you for hosting Magic Mondays, and best wishes to you and fellow posters!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59139042", "title": "Re: Eugene Fersen's Science of Being", "date": "2026-02-09 08:38 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this! Ah, so Fersen's the source of the star exercise? It's been adopted into a lot of energetic healing practices, and in my experience it works well with the Modern Order of Essenes training, so we have that to thank him for, certainly. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59145186", "title": "Re: Eugene Fersen's Science of Being", "date": "2026-02-09 09:43 pm", "user": "emily07", "content": "A related question if I may: in Switzerland there is a person Christine von Dreien who stated to her mother (who put in her book about her daughter) that people have energy points (blue) that are from themselves and other points (forgot the color) that can be transmitted without negative result. If the blue points are transmitted one uses (up?) ones life-force.<br/>So my questions are:<br/>a) from what you know is that plausible or rhyming with something that you know of?<br/>b) After Milkyway01 posted her introduction into the blessing walk I´ve been doing that kind of thing whilst saying: \"May you be blessed if you want to be blessed (Mögest Du gesegnet sein, wenn Du gesegnet sein magst). Am I spending blue points?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59150562", "title": "Re: Eugene Fersen's Science of Being", "date": "2026-02-09 10:26 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Interesting. No, but that doesn't mean its incorrect. <br/><br/>2) Nope! You're spending the other kind. You can bless everyone and everything in the world without harm to yourself. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59134690", "title": "Body Doubling", "date": "2026-02-09 08:03 pm", "user": "syfen", "content": "Archdruid,<br/><br/>First, really good music choice. I haven't listened to Dobie Gray in ages...<br/><br/>Second. I was recently introduced to the concept of \"body doubling\" as a mental health care for people struggling with executive dysfunction. As I've gotten older, I discovered that my ADD/ADHD got worse, and I needed new coping methods. I asked a friend of mine to act as \"body double\" for me, and it helped tremendously. <br/><br/>I have a feeling that there's an energetic aspect to why this system is so useful, but I can't for the life of me figure out what's going on. Simply having someone else around clears up the general confusion and haze caused by ADD/ADHD. Do you have any idea why this happens? Or any place I could start my research to figure out the underlying principals behind this phenomenon?<br/><br/>Regards,<br/><br/>Syfen", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59139298", "title": "Re: Body Doubling", "date": "2026-02-09 08:39 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Heck of a good question. I'm quite the opposite -- I do my best work in complete solitude -- but this is interesting, certainly. I don't know how it would work, though; maybe other readers have suggestions. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59170018", "title": "Re: Body Doubling", "date": "2026-02-10 03:57 am", "user": "syfen", "content": "hmm, I'll see if I can come up with some experiments and try to discover what's going on."}]}, {"id": "cmt59146210", "title": "Re: Body Doubling", "date": "2026-02-09 09:49 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi Syfen,<br/>Being in the same letter-soup I wonder if the results is gotten by  the usual pattern-recognition system being occupied by interpreting/pre-guessing the other person and ones coming-across.<br/>Also, there is this ...whatsit in English...Entrainment maybe goin on?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59170530", "title": "Re: Body Doubling", "date": "2026-02-10 03:58 am", "user": "syfen", "content": "I'll follow that direction and see what I can find. It definitely seems like some kind of Entrainment..."}]}, {"id": "cmt59149538", "title": "Re: Body Doubling", "date": "2026-02-09 10:22 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "It might be co regulation at work (which involves etheric and astral from my observation), both my ADD and ADHD children naturally attach stronger to me than my regular kiddy and use me to help regulate their somewhat chaotic nervous systems. It's a role I've taken because it came naturally when they were babies and because the need and benefits were obvious so I just continued. They also study for long periods if I sit with them where they struggle if not hyperfixated. Same goes for any physical work, my son buzzes constantly which energizes me when doing tasks and I help ground and focus him. I think ADD and ADHD often just have very sensitive systems and in my experience are quite naturally connective to others."}]}, {"id": "cmt59135458", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 08:08 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi John,<br/><br/>Glad to see you posting again. I remember in one of your posts (might have been the FAQ) you said that in order to reincarnate as a human, or at least, not degrade, one must live within the realm of meaning and value. Can you expand what you mean by this? The bit about \"realm of meaning and value\" frequently pops into my mind and I love this phrasing, but im a little confused what this means in practise. Hope i've been clear, and do correct me if i've misinterpreted something<br/><br/>Cheers", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59140066", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 08:46 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Imagine somebody illiterate in English who's never seen a stop sign and has no idea what it means. He gets used to seeing stop signs in particular places, and may even be able to predict where one is likely to be found, but has no idea what that red octagon with the white squiggles on it means. Then somebody explains it to him, and he realizes that it's an instruction to drivers, telling them to stop before proceeding. The difference that explanation makes is that now he knows the meaning. <br/><br/>Human language is like a collection of stop signs. Quite often people use words without thinking about what they mean -- \"this feels good\" and \"this feels bad\" are as much meaning as they have. (Think of the way the words \"fascism\" and \"communism\" have been manhandled over the last century.) That's animal thinking -- animals, remember, have all the same emotions we do. Human thinking attends to meanings as well as feelings. When language devolves into a parade of feelings, it is no longer human -- and if a soul loses touch with meaning, it stops being human and falls back into the animal level to \"repeat a grade.\" ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59143394", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 09:18 pm", "user": "chasethesun", "content": "Interesting. And so to live in the realm of meaning and value, would it be accurate to say that one should live with intentionality basically? Or truth?<br/>In my mind, I think it's possible to live a life of meaning without necessarily adding words to experiences - or am I misintepreting what you're saying?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59150818", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 10:28 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Living with intentionality all the time is hard work! To keep from flunking out of the grade of human, it's enough to pay attention to what things mean when you can tell that it's important. <br/><br/>2) Words aren't the only carriers of meaning by a long shot. You can perceive the meaning in your experiences without putting that into words. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59169250", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 03:33 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Not the OCer.) If I understood you (previously) correctly, you associate \"meaning and value\" with the mental sheath - can you say something about the kind of engagement with meaning you'd need to go forward (e.g. to having a mental body) instead of only not going backward?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59169762", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 03:38 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's correct. The single most reliable way to move forward is to establish a regular practice of some form of meditation. As little as five minutes of meditation every day will keep you moving in the right direction. There are plenty of other things that can add into that -- consult the world's esoteric spiritual traditions, all of them, for the details -- but meditation is the key. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59171298", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 04:14 am", "user": "open_space", "content": "<p>I hope those humans on the way back to animals, which to me seems like a lot, don't carry over their attitudes... otherwise the animal kingdom is going to be very interesting and full of easy snacks. I can already picture a small, puffy and talkative bird with an off fashion stiff haircut chirping with entitlement at everything just to be devoured by a bird of prey. I propose the name for this future species to be <em>regina indignissima coronata</em> (the most aggravated crowned queen). It’s habitat is probably going to be the deserted parking lots of the future as an odd way to work off karma. I am laughing to myself about this oddity that crossed my mind, I'm sorry. I should go and do my morning practices. </p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59171810", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 04:20 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You may intend that as a joke, but I suspect it happens that way rather often...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59172322", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 04:46 am", "user": "open_space", "content": "<p>I don't doubt it. Ouch. My humor is a bit dark and mocking sometimes. I hope my psychic senses didn't get activated, otherwise the field of ornithology is going to need earplugs instead of microphones. Chirp, chiirp. </p>\n"}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59136994", "title": "Learning ritual magic", "date": "2026-02-09 08:26 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm working through the exercises in lesson one of Learning Ritual Magic, but I'm stuck on drawing the Tree of Life. When I follow the instructions, I end up with 10 nested circles that all intersect each other. Did I do that right?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59139810", "title": "Re: Learning ritual magic", "date": "2026-02-09 08:40 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Make the three and a half circles you start with bigger, and the ten circles that follow much smaller. ", "edit_time": "2026-02-09 08:46 pm (UTC)"}]}, {"id": "cmt59138530", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 08:37 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello,<br/><br/><br/>Q1. I've heard that Martinism is quite a powerful tradition. What have your experiences been like with it so far, if you don't mind me asking?<br/><br/>Thanks for Magic Monday.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59140322", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 08:48 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The initiations passed on a very definite energy and sense of connection with a source of power and wisdom; the individual practices are effective; and in general I'm satisfied with it. It's mystical in its orientation rather than magical, and so helps me extend my knowledge and work into a field that I hadn't explored much in the past. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59140834", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 08:57 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi,<br/><br/><br/>Thanks for that.<br/><br/><br/>Q. If you don't mind me asking, what are the practices designed to do? I'm sure there's multiple practices for different outcomes, but I'm curious about what some of them might be for.<br/><br/><br/>Thanks again", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59141346", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 09:00 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "All the usual tasks of the mystical aspirant: they clear and focus the mind, develop the capacity for reflection, meditation, and contemplation, and direct thoughts and feelings toward the Divine. Those are the purposes of the core practices -- there's a vast amount of additional material (more than I've had the chance to work with yet!) with many other applications. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59149794", "title": "Spontaneous Human Combustion", "date": "2026-02-09 10:23 pm", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "Spontaneous Human Combustion, or SHC, is one of those niche topics that get brought up occasionally (such as a 9th grade reading I once did). The rational-materialists have various excuses for this, such as the wick effect, but I find them rather hard to swallow, especially when cremating a body usually requires high temperatures.<br/><br/>So I'm wondering, what is the occult explanation for living or recently deceased humans getting incinerated, seemingly out of nowhere and with little effect on their surroundings?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59151330", "title": "Re: Spontaneous Human Combustion", "date": "2026-02-09 10:29 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've never seen a good explanation. It's very weird, it definitely happens, and the usual rationalist handwaving doesn't explain it at all! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59154914", "title": "Re: Spontaneous Human Combustion", "date": "2026-02-09 11:07 pm", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "Well, that's fair enough. I wonder if its powerful spirits who do that, since you mentioned an encounter with an Archangel, who you described like a lightning bolt, who could incinerate a human to ashes if he didn't hold back his power. But that's just speculation, and there may be multiple causes.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59172578", "title": "Re: Spontaneous Human Combustion", "date": "2026-02-10 04:53 am", "user": "open_space", "content": "<p>Some yogis allegedly can dematerialize their bodies completely at the moment of a powerful type of enlightenment, only leaving a small puddle of water behind. I don't think people get enlightened reading the newspaper in a suburban neighborhood but at least the mechanism seems to exist metaphysically. Perhaps an exothermic chain reaction in the etheric body so strong that it combusts the body in an instant? </p>\n"}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59151074", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 10:29 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello John,<br/><br/>I've been thinking about New Thought and \"manifestation.\" In your opinion, is it better to focus on one goal at a time? Or, is it permissible to pursue multiple goals at the same time? I believe that in magic one can pursue multiple goals at the same time. But I don't mean all on the same day or during the same ritual!<br/><br/>Thanks for your time and help.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59151842", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 10:31 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The more you focus on a single topic, the more successful you're likely to be. That's true in magic as well as in New Thought. Once you're experienced, you can have some spells perking away in the background while most of your conscious effort goes to one, but that takes a lot of practice. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59151586", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 10:31 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I asked you a few weeks ago how to start a Neoplatonist worship practice, and you suggested reciting the Orphic hymn of the day with an offering in incense. I wanted to say thank you, the practice has been enjoyable and has had a subtle but noticeable effect. <br/><br/>I saw you mentioned last week that you also make offerings of wheat cakes. I’d like to add this into my practice. Is there a traditional recipe you could suggest? And what happens to the cake after being offered? Do I eat it or should I return it to the earth? Thank you for your advice!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59152098", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 10:33 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't make my own wheat cakes -- I use water crackers purchased from the local grocery store. They stay on the altar for a week, and then I replace them and eat them -- that's standard practice in most polytheist traditions. In Hinduism, for example, food offered to the gods and then shared out among the worshippers is called, iirc, <i>prasad</i>, and eating it has some of the same vibe that taking Communion has among traditional Christians. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59163618", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 01:26 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks JMG, I appreciate this! Does the water also stay for a week and then is consumed with the cakes?<br/><br/>The Hindu custom also sounds similar to the naorai feast in Shinto. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59164130", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 01:44 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Every morning, I pour out the old water so that its blessing will go into the waters of the world, and fill the bowl with clean fresh water. <br/><br/>2) Exactly. Most polytheist traditions do this. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59173602", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 05:02 am", "user": "open_space", "content": "<p>The term is correct, and there is also the South Indian version <em>prasadam</em>. Apparently black sesame with cane sugar laddoos absorb the energy very well after being offered. These are small balls of triturated black sesame with a little melted sugar rolled into a ball. It tastes like peanut butter but much less sweet and with a strong taste. </p>\n"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59152354", "title": "Intermediation in the spirit world", "date": "2026-02-09 10:35 pm", "user": "https://openid-provider.appspot.com/bryanlallen", "content": "Ever-busy JMG, congratulations on your recent move, and best wishes on your settling in to your new digs. My question: is there any way to estimate how much intermediation there is in the spirit world? As illustration, we were recently having a dinner with friends, and one guest, when I told of a conversation I took part in with a spiritual entity/ally many decades ago, said that the quite-pointed command and guidance I’d heard from the ally could have come from an angel or archangel. I said I didn’t think so, but later I got to thinking: just how much behind-the-scenes communication across realms is there? Do angels ever talk to us via other quite-dissimilar spirit beings, for instance? I guess there would be no way of knowing, other than just asking the beings themselves and waiting for an answer. Hmmm…", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59154146", "title": "Re: Intermediation in the spirit world", "date": "2026-02-09 11:01 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Spiritual beings don't exist in isolation from one another. The traditional lore has it that the spiritual planes are even more complex, intricate, interconnected, and lively than the material plane! The old Neoplatonists had it that the gods don't speak to humans directly -- they use spirits who belong to their households as messengers, the way the Christian god uses angels. But you'd probably have to ask the beings themselves to be sure in any given case. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59153634", "title": "Omens Falling from the Sky", "date": "2026-02-09 10:49 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello John Michael &amp; Everyone,<br/><br/>Has anyone sensed that the larger than usual number of airplane and helicopter tragedies occurring in recent years are a warning of the carnage that could result if driverless cars fill the roads?<br/><br/>Blessings May You All Have,<br/>Christine Clifford", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59154402", "title": "Re: Omens Falling from the Sky", "date": "2026-02-09 11:02 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "A case could be made! They're also a warning of the ongoing decline in our technology -- poor maintenance, inadequate training, and other factors of that nature are normal parts of the decline of a society, and our technologies are more vulnerable to such things than most. Of course that also applies to self-driving cars..."}]}, {"id": "cmt59153890", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 10:50 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Can doing too much banishing banish opportunities from a person’s life? I was listening to a well seasoned practitioner talk about this.<br/><br/>Also, this got me thinking about something I think I read on MM a while ago -  that the LBRP disrupts other forms of magic. I really started thinking about the practicalities of this since a lot of work can go into creating astrological talismans or long term spells. How did you deal with spell work (candle magic for example) and astro talismans when you were doing GD practices? Does it mean that on going spells had to be done in a different room or put away and shielded? Does covering the astrological talismans in silk and linen completely shield them from repeated banishings? If you did have to re-consecrate a talisman would you suffumigate it at the day and hour of the planet and recite the Orphic hymn?<br/><br/>I know its a bunch of questions, but I think its important to understand if someone is putting effort in, but at the same time unknowingly reducing its effects. I appreciate you giving us your time on Magic Monday.<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59155938", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 11:23 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I've heard this line before and I have no idea why people believe it. I've done a banishing ritual every morning for the last half century, and I keep on getting more and more opportunities! It's important that you invoke at least as often as you banish; that's why the Sphere of Protection, for example, includes invocations as well as banishings, and why GD practitioners who know their stuff practice the Middle Pillar exercise (an invocation) along with the LBRP. But banishings are to magic what showers or baths are to ordinary personal hygiene -- neglect them, and things get stinky. ;-)<br/><br/>2) I always put talismans away someplace well removed from my magical working space so they can work unhindered. Candle magic is less vulnerable because you're not dealing with the energies of a consecration. Yes, silk and linen will do, but if you deconsecrate a talisman you need to find a new election and reconsecrate it -- the day and hour will only do if that's how you originally consecrated it. (I tend to use more elaborate astrological elections for mine.) ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59166434", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 02:11 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you for the great answer. I think part of my misunderstanding was by doing the LBRP repeatedly near astrological talismans one is over time slowly de consecrating it. <br/><br/>There is only one room available for talismans unfortunately. They are wrapped in both silk and linen<br/><br/>Am I to understand the SOP does not have the same effect on astrological talismans?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59166946", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 02:13 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's correct. There are broad-spectrum and narrow-spectrum banishings; the LBRP is broad-spectrum and banishes pretty much everything, the SoP is narrow-spectrum and banishes specifically what you instruct it to banish, and nothing else. That's one of the reasons I use the SoP these days. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59155426", "title": "7 Years of Magic", "date": "2026-02-09 11:18 pm", "user": "cs2", "content": "This February marks my seventh year of near-daily magical practice and I just wanted to chime in to encourage anyone who is practicing and feeling like they're not getting anywhere: it was only in the last month that I began to feel confidently that I was connected with the gods and could feel it myself. I've had little snippets of evidence over the years, experiences verified here on Magic Monday that the gods were willing to help me improve my life. But it wasn't until January that I unequivocally realized \"I've got this.\"<br/><br/>You've got this too! Keep up your practices everyone and thanks JMG for Magic Monday. I stepped onto the path in February 2019 because I'd been reading MM from the beginning and felt confident that you'd be willing to answer my questions. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59156194", "title": "Re: 7 Years of Magic", "date": "2026-02-09 11:24 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this. Yeah, it took me quite a while before I became confident that this stuff really does work and I was doing it the right way. I'm delighted to hear that you got past that hurdle. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59157474", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 11:31 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Can any of the SOP based systems eventually lead to doing angel magic in any way?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59158754", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 11:45 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes. You'll need to add in daily prayer and meditation, though, so you can rise to the level where they like to operate. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59158498", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 11:45 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is there a good way to ritualize an affirmation? Something simple with a candle maybe?. Does approaching an intention in different ways help it along? Like, saying the affirmation a lot, sigilizing it, and doing something ritually everyday. I thought at some point wanting something too much might push it away... ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59159010", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-09 11:46 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There are many such ways. I'd encourage you to experiment with them -- you'll get the best results by working out something that is meaningful and appealing to you. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59159778", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 12:03 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Just reporting on another “Old Gods awakening” sighting in the wild. I noticed this Reddit thread a few days ago from a self-professed “average suburban mom”, whose foray into guided meditation from an app lead to contact with a deity she subsequently identified as Hecate:<br/><br/>https://www.reddit.com/r/Jung/comments/1qvxw3c/archetype_experience_hecate/<br/><br/>Interesting times!<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59164386", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 01:45 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm! Interesting indeed. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59160290", "title": "Mercurial Dignity, House Cusps", "date": "2026-02-10 12:05 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG, and thank you again for these always fascinating Magic Mondays.<br/><br/>I have two-ish questions about astrological charts:<br/><br/>1. Regarding interception: If a sign that starts in the middle of one house ends less than one degree from the cusp of the following house, that sign is still considered intercepted, correct? (I.e, there's no \"orb\"-equivalent concept or anything that makes it \"close enough\" to the house cusp to count as not intercepted?)<br/><br/>1b. Is there any particular traditional meaning or interpretation of an intercepted sign falling this close to the boundary?<br/><br/>2. You mentioned (I believe it was last MM) that an afflicted Mercury doesn't bode well for occultism. <br/><br/>In a given chart, Mercury is in Detriment (and Fall!) in Pisces in the second house, intercepted; however he has mutual reception with Jupiter. His sole aspect, though, is that he is also opposite Jupiter (though it is loose and separating). <br/><br/>Is this sufficiently afflicted to suggest pursuing other avenues instead? Or does the mutual reception make up for it all?<br/><br/>Thank you,<br/><br/> -- V.O.G", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59161570", "title": "Re: Mercurial Dignity, House Cusps", "date": "2026-02-10 12:18 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Yes, but make extra sure that the time of your chart is correct. It can help to check out the interpretation as though the cusp was in the other house, and see if that fits better. If there's a traditional meaning, I don't know of it. <br/><br/>2) Mutual reception is always your friend. If it puts Mercury in one of his own signs, then your horoscope is no hindrance to occultism. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59163106", "title": "Re: Mercurial Dignity, House Cusps", "date": "2026-02-10 01:07 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you.<br/><br/>It occurs to me that the mutual reception of Mercury is only valid if Jupiter still rules Pisces. If not, that Mercury is not in mutual reception.<br/><br/>In your experience, is this rulership (of Jupiter versus Neptune, over Pisces) still in question (as I recall it to be) or is it definitively one way or the other; and how would you sort it out in this case?<br/><br/>Thank you again,<br/><br/> -- V.O.G", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59164642", "title": "Re: Mercurial Dignity, House Cusps", "date": "2026-02-10 01:46 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm not a sufficiently practiced natal astrologer to be sure, but many natal astrologers I know give Jupiter co-rulership over Pisces, so I'd treat it as valid. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59168482", "title": "Re: Mercurial Dignity, House Cusps", "date": "2026-02-10 03:11 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not OP, I thought Uranus ruled occultism today instead of Mercury. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59168738", "title": "Re: Mercurial Dignity, House Cusps", "date": "2026-02-10 03:14 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, but if you have an afflicted Mercury you're likely to be too clumsy or mentally rigid to handle magic. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59168994", "title": "Re: Mercurial Dignity, House Cusps", "date": "2026-02-10 03:25 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "More generally, what are some good ways to become less clumsy or mentally rigid?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59169506", "title": "Re: Mercurial Dignity, House Cusps", "date": "2026-02-10 03:35 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Be born with your Mercury in decent dignity. ;-)"}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59160802", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 12:13 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG.....<br/>Hope you are well!<br/>In my reading of the Golden Dawn (the newest edition, which you have edited) I have gotten to the lectures about Clairvoyance, Scrying and Astral Projection and I have four questions in order to clarify the content.<br/>1. It seems to me from the different descriptions that practicing clairvoyance and scrying seems to be the same thing. Is there a difference between the two?<br/>2.  Furthermore the method described in the text of conjuring up a \"vision\" through the tattwa symbols reminds me of the process used in pathworking, (as described in your Paths of Wisdom) with the method of checking with the planetary letters included. Is path working then a form of scrying also? <br/><br/>3. In W.E. Butlers book How to Read the Aura and Practice Psychometry, Telepathy, and Clairvoyance, he has simple exercises to build up the clairvoyant facilities. You introduce a method for practicing scrying (with a scrying mirror) in CoP. Would you recommend practicing clairvoyance and scrying separately, doing both those practices, or is it the same faculty that is practiced and any of these will suffice?<br/><br/>4. Also, can you actually use the planetary letters to check if a scrying or clairvoyant vision was not tainted by personal \"shortcomings\" like you do in pathworking?<br/><br/>Thank you very much and blessed be the magic mondays", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59161826", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 12:20 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) No difference at all. <br/><br/>2) Yes, very much so. <br/><br/>3) Mirror scrying and scrying in the imagination are two different skills -- some people are better at one, some at the other, a few are good at both. I'd encourage you to experiment with both and see which gets you the best results/ <br/><br/>4) Yes, and in fact originally that came from scrying. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59163362", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 01:16 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Scrying in the imagination has been a major stumbling block for me in the GSF work.  Without it I can't get to the initiation, and I've almost given up on the GSF.  Is there an alternative such as the mirror scrying that you mention?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59164898", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 01:47 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Not really. A lot of people, however, overthink scrying in the imagination. It doesn't have to be like a movie playing in your head! If you can be aware of the imagery the same way you remember the layout of the furniture in your bedroom when you're not there, that's quite adequate. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59162338", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 12:35 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG,<br/><br/>I was sure this question would already have been answered elsewhere, but I'm finding it difficult to navigate the site. As far as I can tell there's no search function, or it's because I don't have an account.<br/><br/>1) Regarding the SoP, from what I've been able to gather the deity to invoke for Spirit Within is whichever one feels they have the strongest connection to, or patron. Is that right?<br/><br/>For the Greek/Hellenic pantheon Way of the Golden Section suggests:<br/><br/>East: Athena<br/>West: Aphrodite<br/>South: Apollo<br/>North: Dionysus<br/>Below: Demeter<br/>Above: Zeus<br/><br/>2) There's no recommendation for Spirit within. Would Helios or Heracles be appropriate here? If so, would it also be advisable to make appropriate swaps Above and Below?<br/><br/>3) I also considered Athena for Spirit Within, Metis Below, and Hermes in the East. Would this work?<br/><br/>Thank you,<br/>Plaid Erudite Frog", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59165154", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 01:48 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You don't invoke a deity for Spirit Within. Spirit Within is within <i>you</i>. For the rest, you can arrange the deities in whatever way works for you. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59167202", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 02:19 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ah, my apologies! I see where I was confused now. I was conflating the opening invocation of the 3 principles with Spirit Above/Below/Within. Thank you, that's been troubling me for some time."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59163874", "title": "Clarification on tarot cards", "date": "2026-02-10 01:37 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG!<br/>In the book Learning Ritual Magic which you co-wrote there’s a list of recommended tarot decks which I wanted some clarification on:<br/>The Magickal Tarot - by Pat Zalewski?<br/>The Golden Dawn Tarot - by Robert Wang?<br/>The Golden Dawn Ritual Tarot - by the Ciceros? (I know they have the magical tarot version but that isn’t listed) <br/><br/>Just want to make sure I’m getting those right. I was looking at their symbology and they seem slightly different from the Rider-Waite deck.<br/><br/>Sorry if this has been asked before, I didn’t see it on the faq.<br/><br/>Thank you for doing these magic mondays! I wish more occultists would keep up a blog presence online. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59165410", "title": "Re: Clarification on tarot cards", "date": "2026-02-10 01:52 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The Magickal Tarot is long out of print -- it was by Anthony Clark. The Golden Dawn tarot is the Robert Wang version, and you can use any of the Ciceros' decks. Yes, they differ from the Rider-Waite, but their symbolism all derives from the standard Golden Dawn system, as the Rider-Waite's does. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59165922", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 02:07 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ive spent several years now clearing out the emotional crud stuck in my body. I had a lpt of anger/rage stuck in my shoulders/neck and there is still some there. Recently my etheric senses seem to have increased again. Now when I relax deeply/meditate I can feel a pulsating sensation around the backs of my shoulders. What am I feeling here?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59166690", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-10 02:11 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good question. That's not something I've studied; you might want to see if you can find a massage therapist or someone with a background in other forms of bodywork that can help you. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59167458", "title": "magic monday atlas project", "date": "2026-02-10 02:19 am", "user": "kenkyuusha", "content": "hello everyone, if JMG would allow it, i have an announcement for the commentariat. <br/><br/>as soon as i discovered Magic Monday, i realized previous posts contain a lot of value, and that even if one does not have any questions on a particular Monday, it makes sense to skim the content just for the curiosity of it. I definitely learned a thing or two by just reading random MMs. however, the interface of dreamwidth is not exactly optimised for extensive reading of a blog as an archive. <br/><br/>which is why i decided to build my own tool which would make it easier to learn. i started using it while building and realized it could be of value for others too, maybe. so please welcome my humble: Magic Monday Archive (<a href=\"https://magicmondayatlas.vercel.app/\">https://magicmondayatlas.vercel.app/</a>). <br/><br/>it is still a draft as well as a work in progress, but you can already test some functionality of it. the main window gives a reading interface where you can just scroll through all posts as if it were an e-book. if you are interested in a particular year and/or month, there are buttons to filter that on the right pan. later i will add the functionality to log in and bookmark whole posts/comments/keys to access them faster in future. <br/><br/><br/>another nice tab is explore, where you can see how different keywords or keyphrases were used. selecting “LBRP” for example will show you all the comments with LBRP across all years, so that you could read through. this section is going to get better as i’ll work more on this project. JMG’s comments are always highlighted green so it is easier to distinguish them. each comment has a link to open the original in case you would like to double-check the content. <br/><br/>there is a public feature request tab, where you can submit a feature request and vote for previously submitted ideas if you find one attractive. <br/><br/>please feel free to try this. in case you find it useful and would like to support the project, there is a donations page with options to pay in crypto (currently). ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59167970", "title": "Re: magic monday atlas project", "date": "2026-02-10 02:58 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm! Thanks for this. "}, {"id": "cmt59171554", "title": "Re: magic monday atlas project", "date": "2026-02-10 04:17 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A most interesting tool. Impressed. Will test drive it ans will compare with my archive. Looking  forward  to your future additions. Thanks, merci, for this.<br/><br/>Sapienter si sincere."}]}, {"id": "cmt59173090", "title": "Begginers' Numerology Books", "date": "2026-02-10 04:56 am", "user": "casmith", "content": "JMG:<br/><br/>Do you have any suggestions for a beginners' level book for learning western numerology?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59173858", "title": "Re: Begginers' Numerology Books", "date": "2026-02-10 05:18 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There are a lot of very weak books on that subject. If you've already read and worked with my blog posts on the subject: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/tag/numerology\">https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/tag/numerology</a><br/><br/>The book I recommend after that is Doris Ann Bridgehouse's <i>A Complete Numerology Guide and Workbook</i>. It's a good solid summary of numerological methods. "}]}]}, {"title": "Magic Monday", "url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/359082.html", "year": "2026", "month": "02", "day": "15", "time": "10-33PM", "comments": [{"id": "cmt59205546", "title": "Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-02-16 05:06 am", "user": "ecoprayer", "content": "<a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/tag/prayerlist\">At this page</a> is the full list of all of the non-faith-specific requests for prayer that have recently appeared at <a href=\"https://ecosophia.net\">ecosophia.net</a> and <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org\">ecosophia.dreamwidth.org</a>, as well as in the comments of the prayer list posts (<a href=\"https://drive.google.com/file/d/1pRmDZLjNA3ZfzrowQzq0iVJR4mbyH9Te/view?usp=drivesdk\">printable version here</a>, current to 2/16). Please feel free to add any or all of the requests to your own prayers.<br/><br/>If I missed anybody, or if you would like to add a prayer request for yourself or anyone who has given you consent (or for whom a relevant person holds power of consent) to the list, please feel free to leave a comment below.<br/><br/><center>* * *</center><br/>This week I would like to bring special attention to the following prayer requests, selected from the fuller list.<br/><br/><div style=\"\"><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=15906#cmt15906\">Dustin, a relative of Brenainn</a>, be healed of a recently discovered heart condition.<br/><br/>May 1Wanderers's partner Cathy, whose cancer has returned, be given the physical and mental strength to fight it, and tolerate the treatment, and may she enjoy a full and permanent recovery.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=14882#cmt14882\">Jule from Iserlohn, Germany</a>, who is experiencing complications in her pregnancy due to an influenza infection, recover and have a pleasant pregnancy and birth.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=12322#cmt12322\">Larry Mulford</a>, who has entered hospice after a year battling with pancreatic cancer, pass in the smoothest possible manner, and may his wife be enveloped in our love.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1160.html?thread=12168#cmt12168\">Marko</a> have the strength to seize the opportunities.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/a-little-further-offline-than-usual/#comment-153526\">Luke Z and his house</a>, whose furnace has problems that can't be fixed until after the current severe weather ends, be blessed and kept safe until the cold subside.<br/><br/>May Pierre's young daughter, Athena, be healed from her fatigue and its root causes in ways that are easy, natural, and as holistic as possible.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/november-2025-open-post/#comment-149490\">Bob Ralston (aka Rasty Bob)</a>, who is in hospice care in Buckeye AZ, and who just lost his wife Leslie Fish, be blessed and find relief from his pain and discomfort; may Bob's heart remain strong. <br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/896.html?thread=7040#cmt7040\">Leslie Fish</a>, wife of Bob Ralston, who passed away in early December, be blessed and make a peaceful transition to her next existence.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/896.html?thread=4224#cmt4224\">Corey Benton</a>, who passed away on 12/10, be blessed and make a peaceful transition to his next destination.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/896.html?thread=4736#cmt4736\">Satoko L in Kyoto</a>, who is recovering at home after weeks of hospitalization for Acute Hepatitis while in a state of immunodeficiency, continue to heal quickly and safely, and return to full vitality.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18134.html?thread=452566#cmt452566\">5 year old Max</a> be blessed and protected during his parents' contentious divorce; may events work out in a manner most conducive to Max's healthy development over the long term.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/514.html?thread=2562#cmt2562\">Lydia G. of Geauga County, Ohio</a> heal and recover from prolonged health issues.<br/><br/>May both <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/347398.html?thread=57920774#cmt57920774\">Monika and the child she is pregnant with</a> both be blessed with good health and a safe delivery. <br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/338828.html?thread=56777612#cmt56777612\">Mary's sister</a> have her auto-immune conditions sent into remission, may her eyes remain healthy, and may she heal in body, mind, and spirit.<br/><br/>May the abcess in <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18448.html?thread=460560#cmt460560\">JRuss's left armpit</a> heal quickly.<br/><br/>May Brother Kornhoer's son Travis's left ureter be restored to full function, may his body have the strength to fight off infections, may his kidneys strengthen, and may his empty nose syndrome abate, so that he may have a full and healthy life ahead of him.<br/><br/>May HippieVikings's baby HV, who was born safely but has had some breathing concerns, be filled with good health and strength.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18134.html?thread=455382#cmt455382\">Trubujah's best friend Pat's teenage daughter Devin</a>, who has a mysterious condition which doctors are so far baffled by necessitating that she remain in a wheelchair, be healed of her condition; may the underlying cause come to light so that treatment may begin.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/16429.html?thread=392237#cmt392237\">Kevin’s sister Cynthia</a> be cured of the hallucinations and delusions that have afflicted her, and freed from emotional distress. May she be safely healed of the physical condition that has provoked her emotions; and may she be healed of the spiritual condition that brings her to be so unsettled by it. May she come to feel calm and secure in her physical body, regardless of its level of health.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/312140.html?thread=53408588#cmt53408588\">Frank R. Hartman, who lost his house in the Altadena fire, and all who have been affected by the larger conflagration</a> be blessed and healed.<br/><br/></div><div><br/><br/><center>* * *</center><br/>Guidelines for how long prayer requests stay on the list, how to word requests, how to be added to the weekly email list, how to improve the chances of your prayer being answered, and several other common questions and issues, are to be found <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/6373.html\">at the Ecosophia Prayer List FAQ</a>.<br/><br/>If there are any among you who might wish to join me in a bit of <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/1986.html\">astrological timing</a>, I pray each week for the health of all those with health problems on the list on the  astrological hour of the Sun on Sundays, bearing in mind the Sun's rulerships of heart, brain, and vital energies. If this appeals to you, I invite you to join me.</div>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59205802", "title": "Re: Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-02-16 05:08 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this as always. "}, {"id": "cmt59206570", "title": "Re: Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-02-16 05:13 am", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "May Cathy N. of St. Marys, Ohio heal and recover from injuries caused by a fall.<br/><br/>Many thanks.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59209130", "title": "Re: Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-02-16 08:12 am", "user": "ecoprayer", "content": "I've added her to the list, rhydlyd.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59222698", "title": "Re: Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-02-16 05:19 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you!"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59269290", "title": "Re: Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-02-17 01:52 am", "user": "lukeszy", "content": "Hi, you can take me off the list.  The problem is 95% fixed and should be resolved completely Friday.  They prayers worked btw (And thank you to anyone who prayed!).  Incorrectly sized furnace couldn't keep the house above 55 during extreme cold and somehow made it out with no burst pipes (there's a small chance of there being problem with the remaining bathroom I didn't turn the water back on for yet, but I think it'll be okay).  Luke Z", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59282602", "title": "Re: Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-02-17 11:06 am", "user": "ecoprayer", "content": "Glad to hear it Luke! Be well."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59206058", "title": "Strong Emotions during DA Course", "date": "2026-02-16 05:09 am", "user": "filthywaffle", "content": "So I'm nearing the end of the Dolmen Arch course, meditating through the final triads. And a couple days ago I got a massive surge of emotion that that lasted for a couple days. <br/><br/>There were some triggers, but they weren't beyond what I usually encounter, and the emotion felt kind of uncharacteristically strong for me. It was ferocious anger one night followed by a sad, sulky mood for two days. Many of the sensations were surprisingly physical: I felt fatigued and listless. My decision-making was off. You have said anger is a secondary emotion, and I suppose what the dominant feeling was one of sorrow or grief, without a clear cause. <br/><br/>Is this a known phenomenon in DA work or similar? If so, what is it? Some possibilities I came up with in meditation are:<br/>1) The personality trying to reassert itself <br/>2) Previously unacknowledged sorrow or grief that comes up during the DA work<br/>3) As part of acknowledging the personality, one builds a greater sensitivity to its moods. Then the next stage is working to balance with it. <br/><br/>I have to admit some failure at using the DA techniques to offset it. I suppose part of me felt a need to just let it run its course, and observe it. I'm back to my normal self today, though. <br/><br/>Still not sure what I've learned from it, other than I am capable of more emotion than I knew. Or rather, capable of that level of sorrow with an unclear cause. <br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59206826", "title": "Re: Strong Emotions during DA Course", "date": "2026-02-16 05:19 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Sometimes such things happen in any form of serious esoteric training; it's usually a matter of unresolved emotions from the past releasing themselves. At the same time, I've heard from a lot of people who are dealing with odd emotional outbursts just now, so it may well be collective: the Saturn-Neptune conjunction that perfects on the 20th of this month may be involved. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59207850", "title": "Re: Strong Emotions during DA Course", "date": "2026-02-16 05:29 am", "user": "filthywaffle", "content": "Many thanks for the reassurance. And also for the astrology info. That's good to know. I've also had experiences where I felt emotions that didn't seem like my own in group settings -- especially angry sensations that came out of left field with no identifiable cause -- so the collective energy could be at play. Once I'm done with Dolmen Arch, I should probably have a closer look at astrology!"}, {"id": "cmt59211946", "title": "Re: Strong Emotions during DA Course", "date": "2026-02-16 01:36 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Data point<br/><br/>There have been some issues in my household, but we are also dealing with grief from a parent who passed away this past autumn (in law for me), and a very close family friend who passed away this past January. I've known that person 22 years, but my partner has known him for 46 years. It all got ramped up this past weekend. It felt like the coming conjunction is a part of it... but I also had dreams about healing and magic yesterday morning before the heavy emotions came along in my partner. <br/><br/>Wishing everyone who will have them peace and blessings.<br/><br/>Mauve Oscillating Lobster Flaneur"}]}, {"id": "cmt59213994", "title": "Re: Strong Emotions during DA Course", "date": "2026-02-16 02:52 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A couple of other things to consider. It may have been emotions related to a past life, so unless the memory comes back you may never know what it was about. Or it could be something just drifted past in the spirit world and affected you, and it was never really your emotions to begin with."}]}, {"id": "cmt59206314", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 05:12 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "There has been a noticable amount of \"chatter\", connecting the latest revelations in the Epstein files to occult themes, mainly around what in those posts is called Satanism.<br/>Statements seem to range from just casual dropping of words to conjuring up a dedicated cult of elites...<br/><br/>Wonder if you have a take on this?<br/>Assuming you even want to go there, totally understand if not, freaking me out, for sure", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59207338", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 05:25 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There are two factors involved, as I see it. On the one hand, elite classes routinely dabble in various kinds of nastiness as they sink into decadence and incompetence, and in a nominally Christian society like ours, some form of Satanism is a common resource for that. The material in the Epstein files is nothing new, or even unusual; I'd encourage those who doubt that to read J.-K. Huysman's novel <i>La-Bas</i>, which draws heavily on the actual European Satanism of Huysman's own time, or to look up the Affair of the Poisons in 17th-century France. <br/><br/>Second, we are in the early stages of a major revival of traditional religion in the US and the western world more generally, and seeing Satanists under every damp rock is a common habit of Christians who feel threatened. The lurid and horrible material in the Epstein files is convenient as a justification for that, and it also makes a good weapon to turn public opinion further against the failing elite classes, so, yeah, it's getting a lot of air time. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59239082", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:17 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Out of curiosity, do you think that any of the elite dabblings are actually effective, either as intended or via some sort of blow-back or other unintended consequence? Just wondering if there is a non-material component to their nastiness.<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59240362", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:23 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, I think in at least some cases they succeeded in contacting demons. That's easy; all you have to do is lower yourself to their level, and there they are. For some members of the elite, that didn't take much effort. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59262122", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 12:05 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "What would be the consequences of trying and failing to contact demons? Would it give demons access to parts of their unconscious minds?<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59264938", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 01:19 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, you never fail to contact them. They may not choose to show themselves, but if you call them, they hear, and thereafter can mess with you. "}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59263658", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 12:39 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I read on twitter and can't find the post that Epstein and his ilk had adapted New Age beliefs to their own twisted viewpoints.  The belief in question is that you choose your parents with each incarnation.  These pe-dos latched on to that because their view was that if a soul choose a pe-do parent then consent had been given to what would befall them. It's a prime pe-do wishful thinking construct that kids on some level do consent to sex. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59265194", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 01:20 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "What an utterly abominable ideology. May the gods and goddesses give them exactly what they deserve. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59207082", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 05:24 am", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "Have you or anyone in the commentariat developed any further observations about Amelia the British meme goddess and her origins?  At this point, I’m convinced if Druids either number among her content creators or have the ears thereof… or… Druidry is ubiquitously English…<br/> <br/>On a related idea – Does the hymn, “To be a Pilgrim,” by Bunyan have any known connection to the Druid Revival besides thematic similarity?  A YouTube video of Ameila singing that hymn tripped my wait-a-minute circuit and sent me down great big rabbit hole.<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59207594", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 05:28 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Druidry is ubiquitously English. The Druid Revival has been a constant presence in Britain for close to 300 years; a lot of people have a grandfather or an aunt who's a Druid, and it caused only the most pro forma hemming and hawing when Rowan Williams, a Welsh Druid, became Archbishop of Canterbury. That said, it's not impossible that the people who have picked up (or been picked up by) the Amelia egregor include Druids. <br/><br/>2) No connection that I know of, but there's certainly thematic similarity. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59210410", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 09:50 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Or rather, ubiquitously British? If Rowan Williams is Welsh, then he isn't English :-)<br/><br/>- Sidaway", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59214250", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 03:22 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I didn't see much reaction to Williams' Druid status at all in Welsh media, just in English media. For that matter, Canterbury is in England, last I checked. ;-)"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59214506", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 03:26 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I do not have any wisdom, or even conjecture, to offer regarding the origins of the Amelia meme/egregor. However, I am closely watching how Amelia is expressing herself both online and what we call the “real world” – and especially the latter. A major development over the past few days is that British member of parliament Rupert Lowe announced (very deliberately) from his farm in Yarmouth that a new national political party has been born – the Restore Britain Party – and he will be seeking candidates in every riding who do not have a political background (in other words, ordinary Britons). The party’s principles described by Lowe during his announcement may as well have been spoken in the voice of Amelia. (for anyone who is interested, here’s the link to the video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5ZTH6j_lK_o) My jaw dropped further and further with each point Lowe spoke. The amount of public support so far has been astronomical.<br/><br/>The image that came to my mind while watching the video was of Amelia as the Lady of the Lake and Lowe as King Arthur receiving Excalibur from her hand. Of course, this is metaphorical. But a couple other points come to mind on this matter:<br/><br/>(1) Merlin was with Arthur during this encounter. After receiving Excalibur, Merlin asked the king which he likes best – the blade or the scabbard. Arthur replied, “the blade.” Merlin corrected him stating that the scabbard is worth ten times the sword, and as long as it is buckled on him, Arthur will lose no blood, however sorely he may be wounded. On his deathbed, the wounded Arthur was aided by Sir Bedivere, who threw Excalibur back into the lake (as per Celtic custom), where it was received by the hand of the Lady.<br/><br/>(2) In the summer of 2017, a 7-year-old girl was wading in Dozmary Pool, a small lake near Cornwall, which, according to local folklore, is the lake where Excalibur appeared and was returned during the time of King Arthur. The girl ended up finding a four-foot long sword on the bottom of the pool, in good condition. Obviously, a film prop, the crude sword seemed to have laid in the pool for a couple of decades. Though not the authentic Excalibur, I took the incident to be a “sign”. Interpretations may differ.<br/><br/>This may just be my imagination going wild, but the whole Amelia-Lowe connection has stayed with me and so I share it with the community. <br/><br/>Ron M<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59247018", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 09:28 pm", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "That strikes me as a highly significant development.  And as for the sword put recently into Dozmary Pool, and then found by someone else: something similar happened many decades ago with a a beautiful (Grail-seeming) cup at Glastonbury.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59261866", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 12:04 am", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "My eyebrows went up at that.  Did the sword end up anywhere interesting?<br/><br/>Interestingly, all of this is challenging my cultural assumptions about England and the UK.  (I'm a Yankee.)<br/><br/>And - Thank you all for some very hearty food for thought.<br/>"}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59208106", "title": "Not cut out for magic?", "date": "2026-02-16 05:40 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Can there be such a thing as not being cut out for the occult or ceremonial magic? I realize asking such a question looks silly typed out. Still, it’s a genuine one…<br/>I have been performing neophyte ritual practice for eight months now which has been pretty smooth actually. No abrupt life changes, no sudden psychic overwhelm, I have not experienced anything paranormal or supernatural in that I’ve not heard voices or seen half-human, half-goat creatures or been attacked by demons. <br/>I know this probably sounds a little naive but does that mean I’m doing something wrong? Not going hard enough? <br/>I guess I’m revealing my assumption here that once I start doing the rituals I would attract  attention from astral entities, as that’s what I’ve heard from people who started the LBRP and middle pillar ritual.<br/>But does that necessarily say anything about me as an occultist? Does that make me inept or inadequate? Does that mean perhaps I am not very talented at this due to lack of psychic perception? Or perhaps my senses are dull, like a “squib” in Harry Potter terms (I apologize for the reference lol). <br/>Are there any such  indicators that are actually valid? <br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59214762", "title": "Re: Not cut out for magic?", "date": "2026-02-16 03:27 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, there are people who are not cut out for ceremonial magic, but the things you've noted don't suggest that you're one of them. The first stages of magical practice are <i>always</i> slow going, because you have to develop the capacity to perceive things that you've been taught all your life not to perceive. <br/><br/>When I was first doing this work -- and it was the same practices you're doing now, the LBRP and Middle Pillar exercise -- it took more than a year before I got the first clear sense that I wasn't just wasting my time. No, that wasn't half-goat critters materializing out of thin air, or anything else you'd find in tacky Hollywood pseudomagic; it was a slight but noticeable sense of clearing, as though a half-seen fog had gone away, when I finished the banishing ritual. <br/><br/>That is to say, relax and keep going. What you're experiencing is normal. Over time, you'll start to notice faint, subtle changes, and then bit by bit they'll become less faint and less subtle -- until eventually they rock your world. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59254442", "title": "Re: Not cut out for magic?", "date": "2026-02-16 10:29 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks so much John for that encouragement. It was an unexpected burst of hope and optimism (and relief)!"}]}, {"id": "cmt59222442", "title": "Re: Not cut out for magic?", "date": "2026-02-16 05:05 pm", "user": "not_gandalf", "content": "I can second this. If you're \"not cut out\" for occult work there won't be any mystery about it. Jean duBuis would say that an interest in doing it and a willingness to do it even if nothing seems to be happening is an indication that you have passed the \"Initiation of the Nadir\" and are beginning the climb back up. In any event, not noticing anything isn't at all a sign nothing is happening. Some of the BIG changes are remarkably subtle. For instance, working with subtle energies in the body won't lead you to glow in the dark or look like one of those ridiculous black velvet Saint Germaine paintings you sometimes see. But it WILL lead to your not getting sick as often, or as sick when you do; ad to having generally more energy and, after awhile, energy people like. It won't be for decades that you notice that, even though you're aging, you're not aging like other people. You don't look young, exactly, but you don't look aged either, but more like you've been... refined, carved. That's just from subtle energy work. Everything else is like that as well. There are results, but just not noticeable until, cumulatively, they pop over your threshold of awareness and you realize you are a different person. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59255210", "title": "Re: Not cut out for magic?", "date": "2026-02-16 10:35 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks for that Gandalf - I’ll add it onto the list of things to look forward to in the coming years of doing this work. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59278250", "title": "Re: Not cut out for magic?", "date": "2026-02-17 04:31 am", "user": "open_space", "content": "I am a bit jealous about the no sudden psychic overwhelm. It took the best of me and two to three years of serious commitment to stabilize my senses. Even though I never had anything close to something resembling a mental breakdown or anything, it can be disorienting. Hearing and seeing things is fun, but if it is sudden it has its dangers. In my relatively short experience in this path, the ones that are more likely to succeed in the long run are the ones that build and train the senses up. To me the fact that you've stuck with it for 8 months in the fave of what you mention says a lot of good things about you as an occultist. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59208362", "title": "Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-16 06:11 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG, I'm the one who mentioned the hoodoo jar of salt and bent nails in the most recent Covid Forum.<br/><br/>For those who missed it:<br/>https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/358770.html?thread=59185778#cmt59185778<br/><br/>In answer to another commenter who asked how this works, you wrote:<br/><br/>\"Permit me to explain. ;-)<br/><br/>\"The jar consists of a glass jar filled with coarse salt with several small nails buried in it. The nails should be iron or steel -- white metal, not yellow metal -- and they should be bent in the middle, which you can do with two pairs of pliers. Unless you live in very damp conditions, it's best if the lid stays off.<br/><br/>\"As for what it does, recall that the etheric plane, the plane of life force, is metaphorically \"next to\" the material plane, and so these two planes influence each other easily. In the modern world, because next to nobody practices even basic etheric hygiene, most of our environments are squalid and filthy on the etheric level, full of decaying etheric patterns. There's also the far from minor point that many kinds of evil magic work on the denser levels of the etheric plane and produce nasty patterns of their own.<br/><br/>\"That's where the jar comes in. Sharp pointed iron or steel causes dense etheric patterns to collapse and discharge the life force in them. Salt crystals absorb unwanted etheric energy. The jar works like a gentle etheric vacuum cleaner, scooping up etheric dust and grime and storing it in the salt. You'll know it's time to change the salt when it gets discolored; you'll know it's time to replace the nails when they rust. The more squalid your etheric environment, the faster this will happen. \"<br/><br/>#   #   #   #   #   #   #   #<br/><br/>My questions are:<br/><br/>Which size jar would be ideal? I used a jam jar, left the top open, and tucked it on a shelf behind some picture frames. It seems to be working well, however: Does its effectiveness change if the jar is set behind something, in a drawer, set down low or placed up high?<br/><br/>Thank you.<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59215018", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-16 03:29 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Any size convenient to you. <br/><br/>2) No. As long as it's in the room, it'll have its usual effect. I put one in a closed drawer in a bedside nightstand when I need the additional help clearing away etheric nastiness, and it works just fine. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59215786", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-16 03:34 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Between the two of you that answers most of the questions I was going to ask! Two fastidious points of detail. Does the jar have to be glass (will plastic do?) and is a single nail adequate?<br/>Thank you", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59216554", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-16 03:42 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Glass is much better than plastic, since plastic emits gases that can muck up the etheric properties of the salt. A single nail will do, but several are better. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59216810", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-16 03:46 pm", "user": "davidp", "content": "Hang on, plastic emits gases? Just looking around my desk, I'm counting at least thirty objects (yes, I know it's a mess) made largely of plastic. Am I poisoning myself by sitting here?<br/><br/>—David P.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59218602", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-16 04:29 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, most plastics emit gases and vapors, a lot right after they're manufactured, tapering off over time. They also drop little bits of themselves, which is what all that talk about \"microplastics\" is discussing. Now you know one of the reasons why certain chronic illnesses are so much more common than they were a century ago. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59221930", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-16 04:55 pm", "user": "davidp", "content": "So that's the disgusting smell new plastic objects have. I was aware of microplastics but figured I'd avoid the worst if I don't eat or drink from plastic. If I'm breathing the stuff in anyway, that's presumably not actually doing much to help me. Thanks.<br/><br/>—David P.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59225770", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-16 06:39 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Bingo. What you're smelling is a mix of solvents and polymerizers, which gradually outgas from the plastic. None of them are good for you. "}, {"id": "cmt59274922", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-17 04:07 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I would expect that the plastic has to be subject to moving contact with surfaces or strong currents for it to shed microplastic particles, and it has to either have moving contact with surfaces or be vulnerable to and exposed to UV or moisture for it to generate the particles in the first place.<br/><br/>Different plastics offgas different things, and some might be more harmless than others, but I don't know the chemistry or the biology. Search results claim that polyethylene and polypropylene are better in this connection. I've heard there are some plastics that don't turn into horrible witch's-brews of random chemical combinations when incompletely burnt, and maybe those would be the ones that offgas safer things in their just-produced state.<br/><br/>It's hard to guess how to go from speculating about chemistry and materials science in this context to speculating about salt nail jars. It feels a bit like the difference between being an industrialist trying to predict the effects of weather on the composition of input river water as part of anticipating process input materials costs, and being the same industrialist trying to predict the effects of politics on tariffs as part of anticipating process input materials costs. ... it feels like I should have a short low-drama way of explaining here why I expect all predictions involving subtle bodies to require taking into account \"political\" effects, but I don't. https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/359082.html?thread=59245738#cmt59245738 touches on it though.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59276714", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-17 04:19 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Since few of us have advanced degrees in organic chemistry, however, and glass jars are readily available, it's far more useful in practical terms to simply say, \"use a glass jar.\" ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59277738", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-17 04:25 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "At least it coheres with alchemical practice in gathering rainwater.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59277994", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-17 04:28 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Which is another data point suggesting that a glass jar is a good idea. "}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59248298", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-16 09:43 pm", "user": "yogaandthetarot", "content": "Thank you JMG for answering a question I’ve been asking people I thought would know the answer but were clueless.<br/>My water in SoCal is not very good for drinking so I refill gallons at a place that purifies and remineralizes water (which is quite good). However, I have a few glass containers but it’s more practical to use the chemical free? plastic ones they sell… mine are now quite old so I inquired if old ones at least had less gas off than new ones but no one knew… so thanks!<br/>( I had personally surmised that when plastics in general lost their smell, it had changed toxic degree somewhat).<br/>Jill C"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59255978", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-16 10:42 pm", "user": "slinky_weasel", "content": "I want to do this. Most of the old nails I can find are already starting to rust. Should I go to the hardware store and get some freshies?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59257002", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-16 10:48 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes. For best effect they need to be bright and new.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59259050", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-16 11:13 pm", "user": "slinky_weasel", "content": "Copy. Thanks!"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59259818", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-16 11:30 pm", "user": "slinky_weasel", "content": "One more quick question. When I'm home I'm usually in my spot on the couch, or in bed. These places are only about two feet away, but there is a wall in between. Does it work based on proximity, or would I need two jars to cover both locations?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59265706", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-17 01:23 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If the wall's made of plaster, gypsum board, brick, or stone, its crystalline structure will interfere with the flow of etheric substance and you'll need two jars, one in each room.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59267242", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-17 01:40 am", "user": "slinky_weasel", "content": "Cool. I've got old growth redwood walls (and everything else). Maybe I'll get some benefits on both sides. Thanks.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59268522", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-17 01:48 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In that case one jar is quite adequate; wood is very good at letting energies flow through it -- that's why it's the standard material for wands. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59276458", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-17 04:19 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Does this mean that kitchens armories workshops and other places with lots of pointy are generally iminical to etheric forms? And if so, without the salt what happens to the etheric energies?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59276970", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Jar of Salt and Bent Nails", "date": "2026-02-17 04:21 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, it does mean this. Kitchens generally have a fair amount of salt around, too! In the absence of salt, however, you'd get weak and fragmentary etheric forms, breaking up further whenever they bump against a pointy thing. "}]}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59208618", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:03 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A while back, I mentioned that in response to prayers to help me become more lovable, Venus chose to show me that my very negative self-image did not correspond at all to reality by having me relive a major mistake I made as a result of this disconnect. You suggested I try to work out where this self image came from, and I’ve since come to the very painful realization that it is the result of severe emotional abuse, from my parents, dating back to my early childhood and likely all the way back to when I was born.<br/><br/>a) I have most of the material plane work done for moving far away from them. I will be making the move towards the end of March, and I will not give any of them my contact information, so very shortly I will likely interact with them for the last time (at least, in this incarnation). Once I finish moving, I’ll give myself a few months to sort out my life after such a major life change and to do what healing I can with the simple expedient of getting space, and then I plan to work through the Octagon Society. I also intend to continue to turn to the planetary gods and ask for their help and guidance: they have all been remarkably kind and understanding towards me, even the ones I was worried would not be when I picked up praying to the planets.<br/><br/>This is pretty clearly a case of magic, because I am trying to change my consciousness, according to a will to be less damaged, so I think this followup question fits here: do you have any other suggestions for how to go about healing from my abuse?<br/><br/>My spiritual practices are the LBRP, R+C, and MP from the Hermetic Golden Dawn, some meditation, and prayers/planetary charity to the planets.<br/><br/>b) I sincerely hope I can avoiding ever seeing any of them ever again; and while in this incarnation, I think it’s doable, I also want to think about future incarnations. Do you have any suggestions for how to clear away as much of the karmic ties I have with them as possible?<br/><br/>c) I’ve taken to worshiping the planets, and see the hallmarks of their help with how things have been coming together for me being able to escape. Subject to divination, do you see any concerns with offering a round of planetary charity to each of the planets in turn, in order to say “thank you” for their help?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59215274", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 03:32 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I'm sorry to say that advice on healing from abuse isn't in my skill set. If you can find a competent therapist (that you can afford), that might be worth trying. <br/><br/>2) The Order of Spiritual Alchemy material will help with that. As you clear away the stuck emotions from your childhood, you resolve some of the karmic issues as well. <br/><br/>3) None at all -- in fact, it's a classic (and a classy) thing to do. "}, {"id": "cmt59224490", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 05:48 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "a. The best source I've ever seen on this kind of therapy is Heidi Priebe's Youtube channel: https://www.youtube.com/@heidipriebe1/videos"}]}, {"id": "cmt59208874", "title": "Regarding guardian angels", "date": "2026-02-16 08:04 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG and any commenters who wish to join the conversation,<br/><br/>There have been a number of times where I happened to avoid situations that might have caused me emotional distress and embarrassment or actual physical harm.<br/><br/>In one instance, I was suddenly very sleepy in public, and so wasn't able to act clumsily as a result of seeing someone I was afraid of and wished to avoid.<br/><br/>In another instance, I suddenly became preoccupied with a thought that prevented me from immediately driving into an intersection when the traffic light turned green; as a result, I was able to avoid being T-boned by someone who drove through a red light.<br/><br/>I'm certain that at one point, I simply attributed stuff like this to pure luck, but it's happened enough times that I believe my guardian angel was protecting me.<br/><br/>My questions:<br/>1. Am I mistaken that my guardian angel was involved?<br/><br/>2. Currently, whenever something like this happens, I say a quick short prayer, thanking both God and my guardian angel. For a formerly-lapsed Roman Catholic who is still in the process of (re-)learning, would you happen to know second-hand of anything else I should be doing to give thanks?  Also, is thanking my guardian angel unnecessary, since from my perspective it is God's deputy?<br/><br/>3. On what planes do guardian angels operate?<br/><br/>Thank you,<br/>-E.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59216042", "title": "Re: Regarding guardian angels", "date": "2026-02-16 03:36 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I don't have a hotline to anybody else's guardian angel, so I can't confirm, but it certainly sounds like the kind of thing guardian angels do. <br/><br/>2) You should certainly thank your guardian angel, and also the god you worship. If you have a wonderful experience at a restaurant, you'd thank both the waiter and the cook, right? The same principle applies. <br/><br/>3) Angels operate on the spiritual plane, archangels on the causal plane, gods on the divine plane. Your guardian angel is thus your link to the planes human beings can't reach directly. <br/>"}]}, {"id": "cmt59209386", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:25 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A couple of queestions:<br/>* I feel that I am at the point of attempting the higher genius invocatiom from your circles of power book. I prefer the more deliberate, stable and gradual approach - which will no doubt in olve many repetitions over an extended period of time. However, will I 'know' when contact has been made and/or when it has been stabilised and I can move on? I'm assuming the answer is yes, but I also just dont know what to expect because the entire peocess seems so ineffable and its spoken of so wildly differently. <br/><br/>2) I was listening to a podcast from a famous occultist who was espousing the 'it's all in your head' cosmology. This seems to have switched over fairly recently after a couple of decades of him believing the entities to be real and external. This isnt the first time Ive seen the switch in famous and experienced occultists. Do you know what might lead someone to swap theie cosmology so many decades into their practice?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59216298", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 03:40 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) You may not know at first. You may simply notice that your intuition has become much more precise and helpful than usual; then, bit by bit, you'll come to perceive that what you were calling \"intuition\" is a communication; and gradually you'll come to perceive the source of the communications. That tends to be more stable and less psychologically disorienting than the all-at-once contact that rituals such as the Abramelin operation are intended to bring about. <br/><br/>2) That baffles me. The more of this work I do, the clearer it has become that the beings I'm interacting with are <i>not</i> \"all in my head,\" that they are independent beings with their own wills and thoughts. In fact, much of what I thought was \"in my head\" years ago has turned out to be part of a wider world. Still, his mileage apparently varied. ;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59261354", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 11:55 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(not OP)<br/><br/>About the Abramelin operation, I've been meaning to ask (because, something something deep-network learning engineering practice something something big inscrutable semantically-charged grids of numbers something something magic squares/triangles). Is there any typical category of individual courses of development you can comment on, where someone on a course of development in that category inevitably has to... uh... do whatever kind of thing it is that the Abramelin operation stipulates a standard form of in re demons, or that the temptation and refusal mythologized as Lk/Mt 4 represents? (because of the possibility of some sufficiently powerful deep-network-derived AI technology present or future that might then inevitably necessitate some equivalent in a corresponding way)<br/><br/>Like, it's a little bit weird that the Abramelin instructions aren't some other imaginable version of the instructions where demons never come into focus in any even vaguely load-bearing-seeming way, but instead only indirectly as the object of instructions for lesser exorcisms and as an explanation for why certain resolutions are important. So the fact that it combines that unusual feature with the unusual feature of a \"short\" intensive program leading to guardian angel contact -- or, separately, with the nowadays-striking if not quite unusual feature of leading to the magic squares -- seems possibly significant.<br/><br/>(I guess I could imagine the difference as being something about how people back then before postmodernity were less prone to worldview erosion undermining ideals and oaths, and thus had been more cost-effective (less downside for the upside) to use as a point of contact between planes like that. Also, at least one of the entities it names is in other sources treated as at worst unruly, rather than representing derangements self-blindingly doubled-down-upon, so it might have been substantially a problem of where they drew the line to define a category termed \"demon\".)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59265962", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 01:27 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The Abramelin working comes from a specific end of European magic, common to Christians and Jews, which derived from the work of professional exorcists and so dealt with demons as a matter of course. There are many other rituals for making contact with your guardian genius or holy guardian angel that don't have that feature at all; unfortunately Mathers and Crowley, who popularized the Abramelin working, were edgelords and liked to flaunt their antinomian credentials. Of all the ways to make contact with the guardian genius, the Abramelin working is nearly the last one I'd recommend. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59270826", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 02:14 am", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "Mather's translation of the Abranelin working isn't complete.  Other, more complete manuscripts of it have been found since Mathers' day, and edited and/or translated in recent decades by Jürg von Inns and then by Georg Dehn.  <br/><br/>A ceremonial magician named William Bloom undertook the entire operation and published an account of his experience, under the title <i>The Sacred Magician: A Ceremonial Diary,</i> twice: in 1976 (under the pseudonym Georges Chevalier) and then in 1992 (under his own name).  Each edition has details that he deliberately omits from the other.  I'd advise a careful reading of both editions before undertaking the working: he got results, and they changed him permanently, perhaps not for the better--Bloom himself seems not to be quite sure."}, {"id": "cmt59271850", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 02:27 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Okay, yeah, that explanation of a historically contingent out-of-place part brings it into line with Mt/Lk 4, where no specific invocation like that was attempted, and what's important is just to be ready to hold to one's divine contact in response if something comes anyway."}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59245738", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 09:19 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "2) For what it is worth, the gods and spirits are potent mysteries. They're not easily pigeonholed into any particular theory of their ontological nature. A consequence of that is one can approach from any number of differing perspectives, and get results. And easily shift one's view based on their encounters with these powers. The more that I ponder their nature, the more mysterious and awesome they become.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59262378", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 12:08 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "&gt; They're not easily pigeonholed into any particular theory of their ontological nature.<br/><br/>Seconded. It's like they go out of their way to avoid providing clear repeatable evidence against most peoples' interpretations most of the time, even materialist interpretations like \"they're human-universal convergent subpersonality psychological dynamical attractor-structures that coordinate their action across people through paradoxically high-bandwidth subtle variations in body language / microexpressions / pheromones / artistic common points of reference\".", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59277482", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 04:25 am", "user": "brenainn", "content": "What a delightful mouthful! I remember reading, a few years ago, \"Godless Paganism: Voices of Non-Theistic Pagans\", edited by one John Halstead. I can remember not really being all that impressed with the passionate defense of materialism that peppered so many of the contributions but did find a few interesting thoughts in it. Much of it, though, was like trying to have one's cake while eating it. \"They're human-universal convergent subpersonality psychological dynamical attractor-structures that coordinate their action across people through paradoxically high-bandwidth subtle variations in body language / microexpressions / pheromones / artistic common points of reference\" is fine summation of that book's overall approach. It seems to work for some folks, though I can't help seeing a comparison to that and the tendency of some Christians to try and harmonize the Bible with the latest conclusions of modern science.<br/><br/>I find it a bit easier to just say that my gods are real and don't owe me an explanation of their ontology.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59279018", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 04:40 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "For what it's worth, in the cosmology sketched here:<br/><br/>https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/350174.html?thread=58190814#cmt58222558:~:text=acausal,negotiation<br/><br/>&gt; There is also some speculation about \"acausal negotiation\" that classes of such entities might conduct, by engaging in nested low-resolution representative simulations of each others' originating contexts, and about the equilibria arising from such negotiations.<br/><br/>something like that kind of ambiguity pops out as a tentative prediction because of, among other reasons, a game-theoretic argument about not getting too far out of sync with other possible simulators or showing your hand too much or something. (Formalizing that speculation might require discovering some kind of continuous-valued bounded-rationality analogue of Kripke frame calculations or something?)"}, {"id": "cmt59279274", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 04:44 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(cont'd)<br/><br/>... but then, of course, more exotic things than the kinds of simulators that physical scientists usually think about can also find that a useful kind of strategic ambiguity to play into, as well."}, {"id": "cmt59279786", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 04:48 am", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>I'm both amused and impressed at the lengths that some people will go to to reconcile their \"scientific\" materialist worldview with whatever spiritual practice they happen to like.</p>\n<p>Actually I don't think it's too far off to describe materialism as a parasitic meme, the way that atheists have described religion.  Once it's in your head it seems to latch on to your mind and make itself as the ultimate arbiter of what you're allowed to believe in, and on the whole it seems to do more harm than good the more seriously you take it (there are exceptions, of course, and unfortunately they tend to generalize their experience to everyone and be loudly vocal about it).</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59280298", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 04:54 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In terms of \"godless Paganism\" (excuse me while I spit), there was also quite a bit of old-fashioned entryism going on -- the whole point of the operation in many cases was to take over Pagan organizations and events, and hijack them to further a preexisting political agenda. That it destroyed many of the organizations and events in question was predictable."}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59209642", "title": "I haven't got anywhere else to say this.", "date": "2026-02-16 08:29 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,<br/><br/>I have an ongoing relationship with Minerva (lots of crafted offerings) and today I think she made a mildly critical comment about my work habits, which I'm trying to improve. My emotional freak-out was what surprised me: \"OMG, the god who talks to me in my head is being MEAN to me!!\" <br/><br/>Eventually I settled down, thanked her for the feedback and am trying to make sense of the comment but ... it was deeply unnerving. <br/><br/>How do I tell a god's voice apart from my own neuroses? <br/><br/>Thank you for your time, and for providing a space to ask questions like this. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59217322", "title": "Re: I haven't got anywhere else to say this.", "date": "2026-02-16 04:01 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It takes practice. For the time being, assume that you're talking to the deity over a bad phone connection and may not be able to understand clearly everything she says. Ask for clarification when you need it. Learning a good system of divination and using it to check things is also helpful -- that's what divination was originally used for, which is why it's called <i>divin</i>ation. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59209898", "title": "Meditation and Divination Questions", "date": "2026-02-16 08:43 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Greetings, and thank you for hosting this forum.<br/><br/>1. In discursive meditation I sometimes feel \"stuck\", as in, nothing comes up for the theme. I then just try to \"stare\" at the theme in my mind and hope this changes. Is there something else to be done, or is this just a normal meditation experiance? <br/><br/>Sometimes the entire sitting is like this and I feel like I missed the entire thing.<br/><br/>2. Have you ever got hot during meditation? Lately I would be overwhelmed with a \"fire\" sansation in some sessions.<br/><br/>This is normally temporary, and passes. Is this a trick my mind plays on me to get me to lose concentration?<br/><br/>3. I got some SGO readings where the first card in the reading (using the GSF method where it represents myself) shows Squaring of the Circle reversed. I understand what this means for a situation or result, but struggle to interpert what it means when I'm \"impossible\". Could you please give me a hint?<br/><br/>Have a good day.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59217578", "title": "Re: Meditation and Divination Questions", "date": "2026-02-16 04:10 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That kind of stuckness is quite common. Staring at the theme works for some people but not for most. It can help to have a set of questions in your mind that you can use to goose the theme into activity. Try memorizing these seven concepts: <br/><br/>Being, Becoming, Source, Substance, Power, Purpose, Value<br/><br/>And these seven questions: <br/><br/>Whether? What? How? Who? Where? When? Why?<br/><br/>Practice combining them until you can rattle off all 49 combinations without a hitch. (You can vary the wording as needed. Thus the first seven are \"whether it is, what it is, how it is, whose it is, where it is, when it is, why it is,\" and the next seven are \"whether it becomes, what it becomes, how it becomes, whose it becomes, where it becomes, when it becomes, why it becomes.\" Proceed through the rest the same way. Then, when you get stuck on the theme, start generating questions using the combinations. \"Whether it is\" -- does the thing actually exist, and how do you know one way or the other? \"What it is\" -- how exactly would you define it? And so on. You can get a lot of meditative mileage out of even the most recalcitrant theme by that method. <br/><br/>2) Yes. You're concentrating life force in your body. It's generally good for you, but if it becomes too hot to be comfortable, imagine the soles of your feet \"opening up\" and drain the heat off into the earth. (Ladies in menopause take note: this also helps with hot flashes.) <br/><br/>3) Well, when somebody says, \"Oh, he's just impossible!\" do you have a sense of what they're saying? "}]}, {"id": "cmt59210154", "title": "Houses in Mundane Astrology", "date": "2026-02-16 09:04 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>I hope you are settling in nicely in your new digs in the belly of the beast 😉. What a time to be there!<br/><br/>Firstly it does seem like we are in Satanic Panic 2.0. I'm sure it will be/is being monetized in various ways (and grifts). I'm definitely not saying that a lot of crud isn't being exposed, but are we really surprised by any of it?<br/>And what is going to be reformed? Or will it just be a big outrage festival?<br/><br/>Maybe this is just my natal Saturn in Aries cynicism! Hey, I'd love to see some genuine reform!<br/><br/>I reckon I'm going through my second Saturn return about now? Born Dec 68? Would that be about right?<br/><br/>Anyway what I would like to discuss, is that you are probably one of the few mundane astrologers who actually take note of house placements.<br/>In natal astrology, there is much more recognition, but for some reason when it switches to mundane, the people I watch discussing it become much more generalised.<br/><br/>It's not that there isn't value to what is said, it's just that if the house placements are so important, why aren't they discussed more?<br/>Have you encountered this?<br/><br/>One thing I did note on your delineation of the conjunction is about the house Aries is in and how it is affected. Very interesting! (Apologies if I get the technical terms wrong but I think you understand what I'm on about.)<br/>No-one else that I have watched has mentioned this.<br/><br/>With regards to the influence or lack of, of Pluto, would you think it possible that people are mixing it up with the actual influence of something that you have mentioned many times, of the presence of Uranus in its 'fall' in Taurus? You have often said this is a very malefic influence.<br/><br/>All the best,<br/>Helen in Oz <br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59217834", "title": "Re: Houses in Mundane Astrology", "date": "2026-02-16 04:17 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I think there's going to be a lot of noise and a lot of people's careers ruined, some reforms, and then it'll all blow over. But we'll see. <br/><br/>2) You've got a little more than a year to go until your Saturn return. Saturn in December 1968 was standing direct in 18 degrees Aries, and he's at 0 degrees Aries now; toward the end of this year you'll start to feel it. <br/><br/>3) I have no idea. Without paying attention to house rulers, mundane astrology is fumbling in the dark. <br/><br/>4) Oh, Pluto had a significant influence during the period when it functioned as a planet, 1930-2006, and its influence hasn't faded out entirely yet. (I figure we have another decade.) But Uranus in Taurus is a massive influence, and a very dangerous one. Once he gets settled more comfortably in Gemini the world is likely to calm down some. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59224234", "title": "Re: Houses in Mundane Astrology", "date": "2026-02-16 05:46 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "Uranus in Gemini has always been a difficult time for the United States since colonial times. Famine in Jamestown, the Salem Witch trials, the Revolutionary War, the Civil War, and our WWII direct involvement all happened when Uranus was in Gemini or moving back and forth over the sign cusp.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59226026", "title": "Re: Houses in Mundane Astrology", "date": "2026-02-16 06:40 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "One way or another, we're in for difficult times, but keep in mind that all three of the later examples you've cited ended in triumph. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59219626", "title": "Re: Houses in Mundane Astrology", "date": "2026-02-16 04:35 pm", "user": "charlieobert", "content": "A note on Saturn returns - in traditional astrology the Return is not a point in time, but the entire time that Saturn is in its home sign  - so it lasts around 2-1/2 years. In a traditional sense your Saturn return started this past weekend. The Return is at its most intense or culmination of sorts when it is exact by degree, but you are in it. This should become more evident when Saturn gets within ten degrees orb of its home position.<br/><br/>And, this time around you can celebrate the start of your Return with the Saturn/Neptune conjunction this week. It is possible that the themes of this week persist for your through the period.<br/><br/>You can also note the aspects transiting Saturn makes to other planets in your chart. I've been through two of them now, and in them there was a parallel series of events in the same order over a period of around a year and a half.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59243946", "title": "Re: Houses in Mundane Astrology", "date": "2026-02-16 09:02 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Interesting. The way I was taught -- and my two returns seem to have followed this rule -- a Saturn return has the same orb as any other conjunction with a natal chart point, say, 3 degrees applying and one separating. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59246762", "title": "Re: Houses in Mundane Astrology", "date": "2026-02-16 09:25 pm", "user": "charlieobert", "content": "Orbs in general are much wider in traditional than modern. Also, aspects in traditional are primarily by sign - by that, rule, Saturn and Neptune in conjunction presently are in square to Jupiter by sign. They are called whole sign aspects, and they are quite useful in natal work.<br/><br/>I find the wider orbs to be very useful, especially with Saturn - for instance, with transits to an inner planet or Fortune, I can start to feel the pressure at a 10 degree orb. Separating orbs seem to be a lot weaker.<br/><br/>Also, I find it useful to think of the Saturn return as a slow process rather than an event, in which the themes of the Return are weighing on you for quite a long period, long enough to be aware and think about them if you pay attention. That also means that a Saturn related transit can have effects triggered by an exact aspect by a faster moving inner planet.<br/><br/>Take into account that this is for natal and not mundane - a 10 degree orb in a mundane chart would not be in effect long enough for the aspect to perfect. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59251882", "title": "Re: Houses in Mundane Astrology", "date": "2026-02-16 10:01 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Interesting. A very different approach, certainly. "}, {"id": "cmt59272874", "title": "Re: Houses in Mundane Astrology", "date": "2026-02-17 02:44 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "&gt; by sign<br/><br/>I thought I remembered once reading something that used \"regarding\" or \"aspecting by regard\" as a synonym for \"aspecting by sign\", like as an alternative to just \"aspecting\" that indicated specifically an aspect between whole houses or signs rather than objects, in a situation where there would otherwise have been ambiguity. But I can't find a source now."}]}, {"id": "cmt59251114", "title": "Re: Houses in Mundane Astrology", "date": "2026-02-16 09:56 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm not sure about Renaissance Astrology, but I know that in Hellenistic Astrology because <i>all</i> aspects are whole sign aspects, including transits. As someone who has used both modern and Hellenistic astrology well enough to get a sense of how they work, trying to take anything from one and apply it in the other is a very good way to make a fool of yourself!<br/><br/>This is especially true of something like taking Saturn returns out of context of transits in general....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59252138", "title": "Re: Houses in Mundane Astrology", "date": "2026-02-16 10:02 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That makes sense to me! I've noticed, talking shop with Vedic astrologers, that each system has its techniques, both yield good results, but you can't just swap methods between systems. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59248042", "title": "Re: Houses in Mundane Astrology", "date": "2026-02-16 09:39 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi Charlie,<br/><br/>I was born in December 68, on the 26th, so in Capricorn.<br/><br/>I'm not aware of what a home position is, can you explain that?<br/><br/>I did once manually cast my birth chart (with what ended up being the wrong approx time) many years ago, but I didn't really go any further than that. Although I do find it extremely interesting.<br/><br/>As for themes of this week, oof, I couldn't really say! "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59210922", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 10:47 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey JMG,<br/><br/>1) When I do the LIRP, my hands get warm. Sometimes slightly warm, sometimes uncomfortably hot. Is that supposed to happen?<br/><br/>2) I tend to meditate in front of an altar on which there are several bowls I use for drink offerings. These are never filled when I do the LBRP beforehand but I wonder whether I'm breaking etiquette by doing so. I know you can't actually banish Gods but would it be considered rude to banish around an altar?<br/><br/>3) You may or may not be interested in hearing this but I did try to contact the German egregore last week, explaining some of my problems and asking for help in developing a healthy patriotism. Much to my dismay, it responded with an image of Wehrmacht soldiers marching. When I said that I don't consider that healthy, we just moved from WWII to WWI. An improvement over the Nazis, I suppose, but still not really what I was hoping for.<br/><br/>Maybe I just misphrased my problem but I tried to get there by a couple of different tacks and every time, we got back to military prowess, largely in relation to WWII (maybe I should've asked how that worked out but it didn't occur to me at the time). It seemed to genuinely not understand me and patiently repeated the same images over and over again, as though I was just a little slow. It seemed to be saying something along the lines of \"Yes, I know you want to talk about patriotism. Look, soldiers, that's patriotism. See?\"<br/><br/>Interestingly enough, I've had similarly robotic conversations with real people, usually about politics. They usually leave me frustrated and slightly exhausted; this time was similar, though much worse. My mood cratered for the day and I had to take a nap in the afternoon, which seemed to have nothing to do with a genuine need for sleep.<br/><br/>I get the sense that it offered and would actually have been able to help me feel good about these aspects of our past, which makes me more than a little uncomfortable. It didn't seem too bothered when I declined, though.<br/><br/>On a slightly more positive note, unlike the Canadian of a few Magic Mondays past, I wasn't threatened at any point. It didn't seem to object to me being here, feeling about my country the way I currently do, but also offered to help me leave of its own accord. This has been such a worrisome experience that I'm genuinely considering it. Realistically though, I don't know of a place where I'd definitely be better off, so maybe staying in the place that's \"mine\" and where I thus have a right to effect what little change I can and complain about what I can't is the right tradeoff.<br/><br/>4) At least it seemed to offer it of its own accord. Maybe I was already unconsciously preparing to ask the question and it noticed. I assume that egregores can do that, living largely in the unconscious themselves?<br/><br/>—David P.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59218090", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 04:21 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The energy channels in your hands are probably congested. You might try giving yourself regular hand and wrist massage, or better still, getting someone else to do that for you. <br/><br/>2) Nah, it's not a problem as long as the images of the gods aren't consecrated. You're doing the energetic equivalent of sweeping and dusting around the altar. <br/><br/>3) That's very troubling indeed. In your place I would probably make plans to relocate; if the German egregor is headed back toward long lines of marching soldiers -- well, I wrote about that in a blog post a while back: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/the-next-european-war/\">https://www.ecosophia.net/the-next-european-war/</a><br/><br/>4) Egregors are very perceptive, since they aren't limited to the material senses. They also attract spirits in harmony with their character, including the spirits of the dead. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59221674", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 04:52 pm", "user": "davidp", "content": "Thank you.<br/><br/>2) By consecrated, you mean the statue thing you, Florian, and a few others here occasionally talk about? You wanted to write a book about that too, right?<br/><br/>3) That's just lovely. I remember reading that post a while back, with some detached amusement at the thought of our leaders suffering the consequences of their hubris combined with some certainty that surely the fallout wouldn't be that big and while things would get uncomfortable for a few years, there'd be no real danger.<br/><br/>I'm no longer amused.<br/><br/>I am seriously considering relocating, though, apart from the question of where and how, the thought leaves quite a bad taste in my mouth. This place is my home. My friends and family live here. As much as I am a misfit here, I'd be an even worse fit everywhere else. Of course, none of that will stop a bullet.<br/><br/>—David P.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59226538", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 06:57 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Yes. That sort of consecration has an etheric dimension and can be fragile. <br/><br/>2) I wish I could offer any advice. I've decided, at least for the time being, to remain in the US; there are risks involved in that choice, of course, but my divinations lead me to think that it's the right choice to make for me, at this time. Our national egregor is weak and fraying, but there are energies in the land that are flowing toward something new; I don't know that that's true of Germany. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59229098", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 07:22 pm", "user": "davidp", "content": "2) It seems to be flowing toward a return to tradition, instead. Just an hour ago, I read a German blogger imply¹ that we should try to expand our borders again. While there's no indication he has any influence on politics whatsoever, he also seems to think that the AfD is a step in the right direction, which has me a lot more nervous about what will succeed PMC rule.<br/><br/>For what it's worth, it seems to me that the US is the least bad choice. Most of Europe will probably be involved in what is to come, most of the Anglosphere are police states to varying degrees, Africans are unlikely to want white people to move there, same for most Asians, and the Muslim countries aren't exactly known for their religious tolerance. Maybe some place in South America would be another option, though I personally speak neither Spanish nor Portuguese.<br/><br/>—David P.<br/><br/>[1] <a href=\"https://www.eugyppius.com/p/greenland-sine-ira-et-studio\">https://www.eugyppius.com/p/greenland-sine-ira-et-studio</a><br/><br/>The relevant bit, emphasis mine: \"[W]ere we to develop a totally independent military, our rulers would begin pursuing their own autonomous geopolitical strategy, which is something <em>neither our neighbours</em> nor the Americans want.\"", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59262890", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 12:20 am", "user": "deketemoisont", "content": "Perhaps I could help you with Portuguese if you could help me become a permanent resident/citizen of Germany.<br/><br/>(I might say the same to people in some other European countries.)"}]}, {"id": "cmt59233706", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 07:43 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "In the US, would regional egregores or state egregores be stronger, and would those local egregores be generally stronger in the countryside and small towns than in cities?<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59237034", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:08 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You'd have to go there and see. I've lived in only a few parts of the US, and don't have a clear sense of the answer to either question. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59240106", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:23 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "I don't have much experience either, but I think Southern Kentucky feels subtly different from Tennessee, and West Tennessee feels subtly different from Middle Tennessee. It could be just that the land is flatter. The city where I work is definitely less Southern than the rural areas.<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59247530", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 09:32 pm", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "Likewise, California seems to me to have maybe six distinct major regional egregores.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59262634", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 12:15 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "The city I work im doesn't have an identity of its own. It's just rapidly growing and populated by a lot of people who are not from Middle TN.<br/><br/>Patrick H"}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59234730", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 07:49 pm", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "Yes, I, too, don't have the impression that there are constructive energies building in Germany. But it seems to me that there is a difference between the national egregor on the one hand and the landscape as such on the other hand.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59247274", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 09:29 pm", "user": "milkyway1", "content": "JMG, a general question: If there is such a strong disconnect between what a national egregor wants, and what the land it is based on wants (with the term \"wants\" in a broad sense; and of course including any connected spirits, elementals, etc): how would or could something like this play out, and what would/could the potential effects be?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59252650", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 10:05 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If the national egregor doesn't come into line with the energies of the land, the nation generally ceases to exist sooner or later. During recorded history, conquest by another nation or culture has been the usual means for this. "}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59242410", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:55 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I remember you saying something the other year about how everyone would probably have been better off if the capital had been in the Rhineland (I suppose Bonn, where it was during the partition) then where it is now.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59244458", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 09:03 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yep. Once it went back into Prussia, things followed their usual course. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59245226", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 09:11 pm", "user": "davidp", "content": "Huh. Oddly enough, \"the capital ought to return to Bonn\" has been a very popular mostly-joke between me and some of my friends.<br/><br/>—David P.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59252906", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 10:06 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I wish it would happen! Germany tends to be primarily <i>das Land der Dichter und Denker</i> when the capital's in the west, and a land of strutting warlords when the capital's in the east. "}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59222954", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 05:21 pm", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "National egregores are not always benign.  Sometimes they can even be lethal, or just somewhat dysfunctional.  <br/><br/>Also, \"nations\" are not a natural thing throughout human history.  The very concept of a \"nation\" is an artifact of European Christianity's historical development.  Some historians would put its rise in Europe as late as the 1600s, as the implications of the Treaty of Westphalia (1648) slowly worked themselves out.  <br/><br/>And it was only thanks to European colonialism that the idea of distinct \"nations\" was applied by military force throughout the global South and East.<br/><br/>Also, national egregores are not equally strong throughout the world.  As I noted in a comment last week, in the West the egregores of both the United States and Germany are particularly weak ones, since each nation is a very recent formation in history.  And both of those two weak national egregores were forged in large part during wars, during the presidency of Abraham Lincoln in the United States and the Kanzlerschaft of Otto von Bismark in Germany.  Also, in each nation there still exist stronger regional egregores, challenging -- and even threatening -- the relatively weak power of the national egregore.<br/><br/>And in a time of world crisis, nations with with weak egregores are particularly dangerous places to live in, alas for both Germans and Americans.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59226282", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 06:49 pm", "user": "davidp", "content": "Would the latter two paragraphs taken together imply that in both of our countries, the regions with stronger regional egregores should be safer than the ones where the regional egregores are weak/dissipated (if the latter can happen at all)?<br/><br/>—David P.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59232682", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 07:38 pm", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "The regional egregores in the USA that seem strongest to me in the US are the ones in northern New England (ME, NH, VT), the Cajun parts of Louisiana, and maybe the more rural parts of the Appalachians.  (None of them particularly welcome hordes of newcomers from elsewhere, though small numbers of individuals who are eager and willing wholeheartedly to adopt the regional egregores might be welcome.  I'm not well enough acquainted with many people from the middle of the continent to say whether any regions there have strong egregores.  <br/><br/>As for Germany, I only spent a couple of months there one summer in the early 1960s (in Lengerich, Westfalen), so I'm not really in a position to say.  If I had to guess, based on that very limited experience, I'd suggest the Plattdeutsch regions in the North and the special area around the Externsteine.  But the 1960s are now \"a galaxy far, far away\" so I'm not really all that confident of what I'm saying here.  <br/><br/>(Basically, I don't think anywhere on the planet will be really, really safe over the next several decades.  My own hunch is that of our more than 8 billion current inhabitants,less than 2 billion will get to live out their natural lifespans, and few if any of them will be in Europe and North America.  But, as I've said before, I'm a congenial extreme pessimist, so take that with a large handful of salt.)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59241898", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:50 pm", "user": "davidp", "content": "Thank you, that might well figure into whatever decision I come to when it comes to relocating.<br/><br/>—David P."}, {"id": "cmt59255722", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 10:39 pm", "user": "kylec", "content": "I'm from the Cajun Louisiana, and I always felt it was a strong egregor, in that it herld on to as distinct culture much longer than other parts of the U.S. when what I call TV Culture began to rise. Of course it struggles now, too, though I do think it's better-poistioned for a resurgence. It is a peaceful egregor. Cajuns were refugees and never had much status, nor did they wage wear except as individuals joining up during WWII, etc. They are welcoming as long as one is modest and respectful and appreciates their traditions. Some of the happiest people I have ever met, despite serious poverty."}, {"id": "cmt59259306", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 11:15 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This is an excellent discussion!  As Robert M. and others here have said, it's important to look at regional cultures and egregores and consider their relative strengths vis-a-vis the 'national' egregore.  I must say I wonder how strong the latter is, as Robert says, when the 'nation' it represents is quite recent and / or quite diverse.<br/><br/>A very interesting study that can contribute to this discussion is a book called \"Albion's Seed: Four British Folkways in America\" by David Hackett Fischer (Oxford U. Press, 1989).  The author establishes that in the early years of the US, people from 4 British regions settled into 4 different US regions: (1) from East Anglia to Massachusetts; (2) from the south of England to Virginia; (3) from North Midlands to Delaware; and (4) from the Borderlands to the \"back country\" of the US.   He uses the same study questions about \"ways of life\" to analyze each original culture and how, after several centuries, these regions are still characterized by the ways of the original culture.  Examples of \"ways\" include family life, education, attitude toward elites, work ethic, etc.  <br/><br/>This speaks, it seems to me, to the matter of egregores moving with people, and becoming established in landscapes different from their original ones.  This points out a difference between the situation in the US and that in Germany.  In Germany, though political affiliations and structures have changed, in general the same people have remained in the same regions for many centuries. This supports the strength of regional, land-based egregores over national ones there.<br/><br/>In the US the situation is much more complex since we have regions settled by people from many different countries, overlaid onto regions where the land-egregores have long been shaped by indigenous peoples and their cultures, who themselves have long and complex histories of movements, separations, and unifications.<br/><br/>A question I have is: could we say that the basic *institutions* of the US, such as the Constitution and the tripartite design of the government, have their own egregore?  As opposed to egregores based on populations, land, or history?  Because this is what I feel, what I sense, as being the most powerful form of a US egregore.  Though possibly this is a matter of wishful thinking on my part!  I probably don't know as much about egregores as others here do, and I'd be interested in others' thoughts on this.<br/><br/>Winifred<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59273386", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 02:58 am", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "Thanks, Winifred!  Yes, that book is well worth reading.  Important for my own thinking about this have also been Joel Garreau's <i>The Nine Nations of North America</i> (1961) and Colin Woodard's <i>American Nations</i> (2011).  Egregores do seem to move with people into new landscapes, but then those new landscapes also seem to change both the people and the egregores that have moved into them.  <br/><br/>All this, IMHO, is quite important for both history and politics, but not actually taken into account by most historians and most political scientists."}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59226794", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 06:58 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This is fascinating, and helpful. It makes sense.<br/><br/>As a contrast, for further clarity, would you share some examples of countries with strong egregores? Both Japan and China come to mind, and even Hawaii, as a smaller-scale example. Thoughts? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59246506", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 09:23 pm", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "Russia!  Its national egregore seems to me to be one of the strongest anywhere west of the Urals.  <br/><br/>More the the West, I'd suggest Catalunya, where my wife's maternal ancestry was born and raised for generations upon generations.  Ireland might be a third example of a strong national egregore.  Finland also seems (from my distant perspective) to have a strong national egregore, as does Hungary.", "edit_time": "2026-02-16 09:33 pm (UTC)"}]}, {"id": "cmt59238570", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:14 pm", "user": "milkyway1", "content": "Robert, I was too late last week, but wanted to thank you for your comment about the German and US egregores, as I found it very interesting and thought-provoking. Thanks!<br/><br/>About this: \"And in a time of world crisis, nations with with weak egregores are particularly dangerous places to live in, alas for both Germans and Americans.\" Would you mind spelling out why this would be the case? I think I get it, but would like to make sure I got you right. :-)<br/><br/>And also, if you don't mind, could you give an example or two of a lethal or very dysfunctional national egregore? Thanks!<br/><br/>David P., this might be more than you're willing to share, but if you don't mind... roughly whereabouts in Germany are you located? (If you'd be willing to share in private rather than public, I read dreamwidth private messages.)<br/><br/>JMG, thanks for letting this discussion run somewhat away from a purely ask-JMG format, both this week and last. Much appreciated! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59245482", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 09:14 pm", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "You're very welcome!<br/><br/>As for \"why,\" weakness can provoke one to extreme desperate measures, which often turn out to be suicidal in their outcome.  And as a current example I would offer our own American national egregore.  We are not--and never have been--as much a single nation as we are a discordant collection of roughly 10 regional sub-nations with radically differing values and dissatisfactions.  Our mass media disguise this inherent incompatibility as mere political differences between candidates and individuals over national policies.  No, it cuts far, far more deeply than that.  (This is one reason why I so enjoyed our host's <i>Retrotopia;</i> he grasped this.)", "edit_time": "2026-02-16 09:34 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59270570", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 02:09 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I think it's many more than ten, possibly several hundred.<br/>The state I live in has multiple (at least six) very distinct egregores, and whenever someone draws up one of those pretty regions maps they ignore both geography and egregores.  Egregores seem to me to hang together pretty tightly with geography, but I've only lived in this region and so would hesitate to speak more generally.<br/><br/>BoysMom"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59245994", "title": "Egregores", "date": "2026-02-16 09:19 pm", "user": "emily07", "content": "Thank you very much for this robertmathiesen! Since last time there was a kind of tread about this, I´m trying to turn this thing over in my mind and there are so many strands to consider and so little that I know of and I somehow don´t get the divination done to figure out if this is the road for me...<br/><br/>- local Egregores here are strong, but if e.g. competent people would reinforce such a one in a \"keeping the peace\" (e.g. das Grundgesetz beibehalten) it would mean weakening the German overall Egregore, right?<br/><br/>- About the \"German-Amelia\" - I tried to turn that over in my mind as well, and I had to think about JMG´s book on polarity magic and his dry comment if I may paraphrase that Amelia has certain male age groups reaching for their maleness and I wondered what kind of figure would do that in Germany. AND not only certain male age groups but...you know...inspire \"all\" in a good way. And all in a certain kind of sense would have to include all that are here. <br/><br/>- And Amelia - what kind of God(dess) and do we get to choose (I think not quite?!) ? If I could choose and go back to the \"Dichter und Denker\" it would be nice to have a God(dess) who went the way of Art. Still, if I look at my German lessons in higher education around poems I think that has had the same effect as art-education in school - more or less killing it off. And also: there is an undercurrent of ridicule here that I don´t know where it comes from and it somehow also shows itself to me in the Naketano way of choosing text: one of the second hand hoodies I have has got \"The poets choice\" on the inside and instead of some uplifting/inspiring/whatever text it repeats the start of a grammar-school joke that ends with one kid unwittingly asking the joke-telling kid to hit it. How to counter that? NO, how to be for something inspiring/uplifting pointing toward peace but where self defense is possible way in a country where that has been misused to the extreme?<br/><br/>- then I tried to think of a symbol. Das Brandenburger Tor is ...only a building for me...yes one where happened a lot around but nothing that inspires me. I´d rather choose the \"Hochzeitseiche\" or another mighty tree. JMG, would reciting the \"Grundgesetzte\" to a(n picture of an) oak tree ´do something good?<br/><br/>- and also: soldiers per se...once there was a trend (in the late 90ies and maybe not only in Germany) to be inspired by the ...way... of the samurai. And everybody was interested in that - wouldn´t samurais not be glorified soldiers and could one also be a soldier of the trees (Buche, Eiche, Linde?!) with keeping the peace as in JMGS book Retrotopia? <br/>Currently my kid is watching the Disney Robin Hood from...1973?! And I thought that a not so obvious bit of what is stated therein is right: the young men need an ideal to hang their energy on and that is not only love but...you know being a kind of daredevil in the name of...the trees?!<br/>From what my...inner senses (?!) tell me while I type some of the above it´s stuff where a lot of energy and also deception! is and probably not in a good way.<br/>- I also think Germans are stubborn. We also thought about relocating and also, even if we´re not at our native-Egregore feel a bit homesick for our place in Germany where we originally come from and have the idea we can do something here. Only options currently petered out and if it wasn´t for my kid I wouldn´t worry too much as in: was I born here to get the heck out of here karmawise? Really? I´m not convinced. <br/>- another voice in my head saying: hello?! your home is a mess, you don´t get the divination, meditation etc. done and you´re a mom and you still want to reprogram Germany´s Soul to become a succulent Garden on Earth for most of it´s people?! The other voice saying: yeah and what about Tranquilla Trampeltreu?! (The turtle that went and got there slow but in time - more or less)...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59253162", "title": "Re: Egregores", "date": "2026-02-16 10:10 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The oak tree is an exceedingly complex symbol in German culture, going back into strange places. Synchronistically enough, right now I'm reading Simon Schama's book <i>Landscape and Memory</i>, which talks about this, going all the way back to Tacitus's <i>Germania</i> and all the way forward to Walther Darre's tree planting crusade during the Third Reich. You might well get results...but I have no way of guessing what they would be. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59257514", "title": "Re: Egregores", "date": "2026-02-16 10:53 pm", "user": "milkyway1", "content": "I can't verify it right now, but I've heard that Bismarck loved oak trees - and of course he and Wilhelm II didn't exactly get along well. So when Wilhelm II ended up in exile, he allegedly spent the rest of his life chopping down oak trees, up to 10.000...<br/><br/>"}, {"id": "cmt59258538", "title": "Re: Egregores", "date": "2026-02-16 11:11 pm", "user": "emily07", "content": "Thank you very much! (Also for propriocepsis).<br/><br/>Hm, the book sounds very interesting. From my point of view I´d say the oak tree as a standalone is a bit overused, I menationed the \"Hochzeitseiche\" because it is a known tree in Germany <a href=\"https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Br%C3%A4utigamseiche\">https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Br%C3%A4utigamseiche</a> which sometimes gets a television-feature."}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59229354", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 07:22 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "Since national egregores are stocked with images and attitudes of the people of the nation, this would mean that a lot of Germans are secretly admiring the Nazis? Perhaps that is because people are starting to see nationalism as a good thing, and everyone in the West has been trained to associate German nationalism/patriotism with the Third Reich in an attempt to make German nationalist sentiment unappealing.<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59237546", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:10 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Keep in mind also that millions upon millions of people have been soaking up visual media that equates Germans with Nazis and wallows in imagery of the Wehrmacht on the march. That's left a very deep imprint in collective consciousness. "}, {"id": "cmt59243690", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 09:02 pm", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "I can't really speak for Germans, but (as I've posted several times before on various of our host's blogs) my father--who was in a position to know--told me back in 1960 that a huge part of the population in the USA admired Germany for its educational system, its science. its industry, and especially its eugenic policies; and (as he told me) about a third of all Americans whom he knew and worked with actively wanted to enter World War 2 on the side of Germany.  (In those days England was still hugely despised on the West Coast as our nation's traditional adversary.)  It was only Pearl Harbor that tipped the balance of public opinion toward entering the war at all, and entering it on the side of the Allies.  He also told me that most of the Americans who had admired the Nazis didn't change their views after the War, but simply went silent about them out of a measure of shame and caution.  He said I would never hear a word about this in any of my college history courses, but that I should know about it nonetheless.<br/><br/><br/>My father himself had favored US neutrality in the war.  All four of his grandparents had been born and raised in Denmark and he was very proud of the Danes for their quiet resistance to the Nazi occupation of their country.  (Denmark has had something of an adversarial relationship Germany ever since the 19th-century wars between the two over Schleswig and Holstein.)  He didn't care much for the leading Allied nations, England and France, either.<br/><br/>So I wasn't in the least surprised to see the massive resurgence of Nazi-style politics in Americda in the current century, once the GI generation had largely passed from the scene.  It's part of our national egregore as it was shaped after our War Between the States.  <br/><br/>The only thing I can say about modern German attitudes is that after the war there was a program of education, imposed by the Allies, to educate schoolchildren on the horrors of Naziism; and such programs generally strike schoolchildren as indoctrination, and provoke in them a quiet skepticism, if not actual resistance.<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59246250", "title": "Thank you...", "date": "2026-02-16 09:22 pm", "user": "emily07", "content": "...also for this, another thing to turn over in my mind."}, {"id": "cmt59249834", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 09:50 pm", "user": "davidp", "content": "I can attest that this program has resulted in pretty much every school being sprinkled with a surprising amount of swastikas, scribbled or scratched into quite a variety of places. I would tend to assume that my former classmates weren't secret admirers of the mustachioed madman but simply did it for shock value.<br/><br/>—David P."}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59211178", "title": "Occult Ethics", "date": "2026-02-16 11:10 am", "user": "hwistle", "content": "Hi John,<br/><br/>Have you ever though of writing a book on occult ethics? I know you've talked in the past on the concept of virtue and your posts and writing (not just the occult ones) are full of examples on topics that could come under the umbrella of ethics (from Mystery Teachings all the way to the raspberry jam principle...)<br/><br/>The modern occult scene will certainly benefit of something like this!<br/><br/>All the best,<br/>Manuel", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59218858", "title": "Re: Occult Ethics", "date": "2026-02-16 04:30 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm. My immediate reaction is that its potential sales would be around twenty copies, all of them to people who already get it and don't need the advice, but I'll consider it. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59219370", "title": "Re: Occult Ethics", "date": "2026-02-16 04:34 pm", "user": "neptunesdolphins", "content": "The course work at the Grey School of Wizardry have several core (required) courses in ethics of magic. I am almost graduated from them - working on final project. For that, I had to do another course in the ethics of divination. So there is interest in ethics of magic."}, {"id": "cmt59244714", "title": "Re: Occult Ethics", "date": "2026-02-16 09:07 pm", "user": "hwistle", "content": "That's hopeful! Even if not a book anytime soon, perhaps a post in your other site one of these days? I'm sure a few of us will find that very useful...<br/>Manuel"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59211434", "title": "SOP and crazy times...", "date": "2026-02-16 11:18 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not a question, more a note of gratitude... I feel I found druidry just in the nick of time. I've been doing the SOP daily for over a year (haven't got far with other practices - yet) and it's made such a difference in bringing calmness and stability in my life. Seems the world is going crazy all around us - from the personal to the global - and the SOP has been the piece in the puzzle I needed to help hold myself together through it... Not that there won't be hard times ahead, but I feel far more equipped to deal with them. Thank you JMG!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59219114", "title": "Re: SOP and crazy times...", "date": "2026-02-16 04:31 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're welcome and thank you! Every person who does the SoP or any other protective or banishing ritual regularly is making the world a little cleaner and safer for everyone, human and otherwise, embodied and otherwise. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59211690", "title": "AJ Gentile / The Why Files", "date": "2026-02-16 01:04 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Happy Monday JMG, this week’s meme ties in well with a Mr. AJ Gentile. I came across him via a Tucker Carlson interview. Watched him again on Joe Rogan and have been binge watching his show, The Why Files, ever since. From the dark side of DARPA to The Book of Aquarius, the shows are very thought provoking. A show on the green emerald tablet spoke at length about Thoth. The more I looked at him and heard about all he was known for, I wondered if he appeared elsewhere in mythology. <br/><br/>My questions are;<br/><br/>1. Have you ever heard of AJ Gentile?<br/>2. Is there any connection between Thoth and Saturn?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59220138", "title": "Re: AJ Gentile / The Why Files", "date": "2026-02-16 04:36 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) No, I haven't. <br/><br/>2) The Egyptians related Thoth (or rather Djehuti, their name for him) to the Moon. The Greeks, who rounded off the Egyptian name to Thoth, identified him with their god Hermes, who corresponds to Mercury. I don't know of anybody who associated him with Saturn. Ptah is the Egyptian god with the closest connections to Saturn. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59212458", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 02:20 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Since illusion and sleight-of-hand and such are very much about directing consciousness, could it be argued that stage magic overlaps with and/or is a branch of real magic?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59220394", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 04:40 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Very much so. Until stage magicians got caught up in the pseudoskeptic crusade, in fact, it was quite common for stage magicians to be occultists as well. One good example was Walter Gibson, the author who created \"The Shadow\" -- the first pulp detective hero with a secret identity! -- who was also a first-rate stage magician (he's the guy who introduced the \"Chinese Linking Rings\" trick to America) and a capable occultist, the author of several decent books on occult topics. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59223466", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 05:35 pm", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "Gibson is a great example of this: a very smart and talented magician in both senses of the term.  <br/><br/>Randi-style skepticism probably goes back to Harry Houdini (Erich Weiss), whose example dominated the field for decades after his death.  <br/><br/>Houdini appears to have been a deeply self-tormented figure where occultism was concerned.   He was very deeply read in serious occult literature.  He seems to have wanted to find \"true\" magic somewhere, but despite all his efforts could only find trickery no matter where he looked.  His truly enormous library is now in the Library of Congress.  It includes such occult rarities as the original hand-written scrying records of Frederick Hockley (his so-called \"Crystal Manuscripts\"), who was a major British occultist of the 19th century.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59227050", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 07:00 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Gibson was also involved, interestingly enough, in busting fake mediums, but he also recognized that there was real magic. His <i>Complete Illustrated Book of The Psychic Sciences</i> is a fine introduction to what working occultism looked like before the 1960s. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59236010", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:02 pm", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "It is indeed an excellent book, and Gibson seems to me to have been far less conflicted than Houdini himself, who was one of Gibson's mentors in magic.  And yes, his \"the Shadow\" fiction makes excellent reading.<br/><br/>Houdini was also a close friend of the excellent occult novelist--and practicing occultist--Sax Rohmer, who himself was a protege of the physician R. W. Counsell, a member (IIRC) of the S.R.I.A. and also the author of <i>Apologia Alchymiae: A Restatement of Alchemy</i> (1925), to which book Rohmer contributed a \"Preface.\"  Rohmer also published a number of serious occult articles, including one on how to do astral projection and another on music and magic,"}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59232170", "title": "A few magical stage occultists", "date": "2026-02-16 07:33 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I met a street musician near Pike Place the first time I visited Seattle. He went by the name of Acep Hale and was hanging out in a bookstore where I was picking up some titles. We hit it off. Then the next day he was at the Esoteric Book Conference. So he did both. He mentioned to me, I think, that Franz Bardon was also into stage magic.<br/><br/>Then we have figures like Black Herman, who was a black vaudeville stage magician but also versed in hoodoo and African American folk magic. He was a big inspiration to Sun Ra.<br/><br/>Karlheinz Stockhausen also traveled around Germany playing piano for a traveling stage magician in the early part of his life before he began composing. I wouldn't be surprised if there was a bit of occultism going on with that stage magician too.<br/><br/>If you really want to tie it all together, you could look at ideas in the art of memory about the \"theater of memory\" which becomes a stage for mnemonic tricks!<br/><br/>It seems to me the two will recouple in time as electronic media isn't as powerful a means of entertainment.<br/><br/>Justin Patrick Moore"}, {"id": "cmt59241386", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:44 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Many modern sleight-of-hand performers/mentalists have secret to not-so-secret occult careers. There's a whole branch of \"bizarre\" theatrical magic whose best performers drew heavily on sincere occult lineages (along with a healthy dose of Lovecraft). Many American magicians have had dual careers as root workers or private readers. 20th-century English stage magician S.H. Sharpe wrote a fabulous collection of aphorisms called \"One Thousand Thoughts on Magic,\" and he makes repeated, if obscure, reference to what is clearly ritual magic. Sleight of hand hobbyists can read the same book as a treatise on performance theory, while occultists will find a lot of wisdom in its discussion of what we could call \"unsimulated magic.\"", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59244970", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 09:09 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm delighted to hear this. Too many of the stage magicians I've encountered fell hook, line, and sinker for the CSICOP pseudoskeptical crusade, and demonstrated with painful clarity that they'd never learned the first thing about the traditions they denounced. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59253418", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 10:12 pm", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "CSICOP was originally founded as an impartial investigating organization, and its board included at least one person sympathetic to occultism and magic, the late Marcello Truzzi, a sociologist.  Within a year or two, however, Truzzi was quietly removed from CSUCOP board's internal communications network without any notification, apparently by the then head of the organization.  Once Truzzi figured out what had been done to him, he started his own short-lived journal in competition to CSICOPS own, now biased journal, eventually renamed <i>The Skeptical Inquirer.</i> <br/><br/>Nasty internal politicking, unfortunately all too common in academic circles!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59254186", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 10:19 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "They also ran off Dennis Rawlins, a cofounder of the organization, when he pointed out that they'd fudged the data on a study criticizing astrology, and were more interested in covering it up than addressing the problems. The sTarbaby scandal, as it came to be called, has been neatly chronicled by Rawlins himself: <br/><br/><a href=\"http://cura.free.fr/xv/14starbb.html\">http://cura.free.fr/xv/14starbb.html</a><br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59258794", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 11:12 pm", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "I had not known any of this!  Thank you so much for the link to Rawlins' article.  My already low opinion of the late Paul Kurtz has now hit the very bottom of the abyss!  Abominable!"}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59247786", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 09:39 pm", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "Thank you for this!  I had not known about Sharpe and his aphorisms."}]}, {"id": "cmt59257770", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 10:58 pm", "user": "not_gandalf", "content": "And who can forget Paul Foster Case. Also skilled at stage magic.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59266218", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 01:30 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I didn't know that! I knew he was a first-rate musician, but not that he did stage magic. I'm now going to imagine him pulling one rabbit after another out of his hat; there are 22 of them, and they each have fur dyed the key color of one of the Tarot trumps. ;-)"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59212714", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 02:30 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If you're familiar with it, what do you think of Michael Winn's Healing Tao system? https://healingtaousa.com/faq/", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59220650", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 04:40 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm not familiar with it at all. There are so many systems out there, no one person can track them all! "}]}, {"id": "cmt59212970", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 02:32 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Are there people who have a bad reaction to magic and feel ill or somehow off around people who practice magic or places where its done? And if so is there a way magicians can shield themselves and their workings to protect the sensitive?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59220906", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 04:42 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes. Most often it's people who got involved in evil magic in a previous life, regretted it, and avoid anything that stirs those subconscious memories. You can normally practice meditation, divination, and natural magic in the same space as such a person as long as they don't have to watch it, but you should probably find some other place to do ritual magic, or postpone doing it for now. "}, {"id": "cmt59260586", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 11:39 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "There certainly are folks who react allergically to magic. They fall into various categories, some with no consistent similarities between them. The most bitterly reactive category of magical intolerants that I have run into thus far would be the demon possessed/obsessed. <br/><br/>Some demons are tickled pink with magical practice because they can easily hijack those energies and redirect them for their own purposes. Other demons don't seem to have that particular aptitude, so healthy magical practice worries them to no end.<br/><br/>If someone has gotten burned by ill-considered magical practice and its resulting karma, then shielding them from magical overload would be a gracious courtesy. If, on the other hand, someone has been infested by hostile malignancy, and your magical practice leaves them feeling off, that offness would simply be your magic doing its work of purifying and protecting you. Shielding that kind of sensitive from magical work would amount to shooting yourself in the foot, as all of their ill and off feelings get redirected onto you.<br/><br/>I don't know of any easy way to distinguish the innocently vulnerable from the toxically parasitic, since parasites can employ a plethora of camouflaging techniques. It can be particularly difficult to awaken to the realization that ones own child or spouse or parent has been demon infested. Or, as in my own experience, that one's sibling turns out to be an irredeemable psychopath.<br/><br/>Since we are all of us working with the subtle energies of magic all the time (that's what willpower is, after all), I would be extraordinarily cautious before relinquishing my own focused protective practices in the hope of protecting some vulnerability-signalling other. That other may well be fully adept at protecting himself... at your expense.<br/><br/>— Christophe"}]}, {"id": "cmt59213226", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 02:37 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "As etheric energy rises through the earth to the surface, does underground infrastructure like railways and electric cables effect it? If nuclear and chemical waste is stored underground, could that have an effect, even if it's encapsulated properly and not physically leaking?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59221162", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 04:43 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's entirely plausible, but I don't know if anyone's done the necessary experiments to find out for sure. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59213482", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 02:40 pm", "user": "jbucks", "content": "Dear JMG,<br/><br/>1. In your Patreon post about the Saturn and Neptune conjunction, I noticed in the U.S. chart that the 9th house cusp is in Pisces. I don't know if this chart is meant to be in effect until the next Saturn and Neptune conjunction in Aries, but does this mean the Piscean religions might retain their significance for the whole time this chart is in effect? Or do we just not know? At the very least, it shows the second religiosity theme you've discussed before.<br/><br/>Now I'm wondering whether it's possible to find out if there's somewhere in the world where the 9th house cusp is in Aquarius to get a sense whether that is where the Aquarian religious forms may emerge.<br/><br/>2. In your system of mundane astrology, what house rules occultism and smaller fringe religions? Curious what the chart says about these in terms of the conjunction. <br/><br/>My astrology is still very limited, but if I may give it a shot: If occultism is a 12th house matter (on the assumption that the 12th rules hidden things and occultism by definition involves the hidden) then that partly afflicted Mercury ruling the 12th and the exalted Jupiter in the 12th trining that Mercury seem to be fairly good signs. But, Mercury rules occultism and is in his fall in Pisces in the 9th, which actually puts occultism more at odds with the established Piscean religious forms. Am I on the right track with this interpretation?<br/><br/>3. Last week I consecrated the Book of Air as part of the RTOL work. It sits on my altar which receives sunlight for part of the day. I seem to recall sunlight has an effect on enchanted objects, is that right? If so, maybe I should be putting it in a darker place.<br/><br/>Thanks in advance!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59221418", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 04:46 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Since Pisces is ruled by Neptune, I'd take that instead to mean that religion, along with science and other 9th house matters, will be in a state of flow and unpredictable change during the period ruled by this chart. <br/><br/>2) Yes, occultism in mundane charts usually belongs in the 12th, though astrology and divination are 9th house matters. Your interpretation is at least plausible -- now let's see what happens. <br/><br/>3) It shouldn't be an issue. Etheric charges can be dispelled by sunlight; astral and mental charges, which is what the ritual is meant to establish, cannot. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59213738", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 02:41 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Where does the idea that anger is a secondary emotion come from? Books like <i>Complex PTSD: From Surviving to Thriving</i> and <i>Healing the Shame that Binds You</i> clearly take the position that anger is what motivates you to protect yourself and others from abuse, injustice and exploitation, and those who dismiss and decry anger are often those who want you servile.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59222186", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 04:58 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Calling anger a secondary emotion isn't dismissing and decrying it! It's precisely because anger is defensive and protective that children turn to it when they're overwhelmed by unresolved feelings of grief, shame, or fear. That can save their lives -- it certainly did with me. The point is simply that in adulthood, if that anger has gotten stuck, you can't resolve it by venting it. You have to go beneath it and process the grief, shame, or fear you couldn't handle in childhood. That frees up those emotions, and it also frees up the anger so you can apply it more appropriately in your adult life. <br/><br/>I got the concept of anger as a secondary emotion from my teacher John Gilbert, who learned it from his teachers. He suffered violent physical abuse as a child, btw, so knew something of the matter. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59215530", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 03:33 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi MR JMG<br/><br/>How do we close a banishing ritual that was performed with incorrect pronunciation?<br/>And how do we close a banishing ritual that was performed correctly?<br/>Is there a solution other than burning asafoetida?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59227306", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 07:07 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Um, I have no idea what you're talking about. You don't \"close\" a banishing ritual; that's like \"closing\" a shower. You do a banishing ritual to clean yourself, or a place, of unwanted energies; after a day or so, the effect wears off, and you do it again. If you mispronounce the names, just repeat it with the right pronunciation. <br/><br/>Oh, and for most Hebrew names, there are several pronunciations, since nobody knows any more how they were said in ancient times. They still work just fine. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59233194", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 07:40 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Banishing involved blessing salt and water and sprinkling it around, but the blessing words and other words were almost entirely wrong. Even if I sprinkled the water mixed with salt blessed with these wrong words around, the effects would still last for one day, right?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59238314", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:13 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The salt and water would have an effect no matter what you said -- you could recite lines from old Warner Brothers cartoons and it would still work, for a while. That sort of banishing lasts only for a few hours, though, unless the space is already very clean energetically.<br/><br/>(Now I'm imagining casting water and salt around a circle while imitating Elmer Fudd in \"What's Opera, Doc?\" singing, \"Kill the wabbit! Kill the wabbit!\") ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59243434", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:57 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hahaha, thank you so much for your help. After receiving your message, I felt so relieved that I danced a little too :)"}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59217066", "title": "Sugar and Salt", "date": "2026-02-16 03:51 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "There was a mention upthread of salt's properties as an energy retainer. I was wondering if sugar has similar properties due to both being powders of small cubic crystals, crystals being good at retaining energy and cubic = square = four = stability.<br/><br/>Granted, I'm not sure if sweet sugar would belong in a red bag amulet with harsh iron nails, but I could see other uses like a more blessing focused construction mixing sugar and helpful/blessing influences like Angelica.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59227562", "title": "Re: Sugar and Salt", "date": "2026-02-16 07:11 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You can certainly use sugar in magic. It's often used, for symbolic reasons, in \"sweetening\" spells -- spells to get someone to let go of inappropriate hostility and negativity -- and holds the charge of such spells quite well. A blessing amulet with sugar and angelica root would work well, but you'd want a third ingredient -- it's a principle of hoodoo that you should always use an odd number of ingredients. <br/><br/>Salt is good for banishing partly because its crystalline structure, and partly because its chemical composition gives it a unique \"vibe\" that disrupts nasty magic. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59218346", "title": "Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-02-16 04:24 pm", "user": "kylec", "content": "If you would like to sign up for healing hands this week, please drop a reply or PM with your name and request. As always, if you're unsure what this is or how it works, feel free to ask questions. Thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59253674", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-02-16 10:13 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi Kyle,<br/><br/>Yes, please and thank you!<br/><br/>Matt"}, {"id": "cmt59259562", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-02-16 11:16 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yes, I would like healing hands this week.<br/><br/>Thank you very much,<br/>Brad"}, {"id": "cmt59273898", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-02-17 03:43 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yes please!  🙏 <br/><br/>OtterGirl "}]}, {"id": "cmt59219882", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 04:35 pm", "user": "degringolade", "content": "I just went over your latest post over at your mundane astrology Patreon site.  Good stuff there as always and I think that I am finally getting the hang of the process, though there are miles to go before I sleep.<br/><br/>That being said, I am a past devotee of tossing the coins for I Ching and laying out the cards for Tarot spread and I am thinking that on Wednesday at the ungodly hour of 04:01 A.M. here in Orygun, I will do a tarot spread and an I Ching cast for the country (‘Murca) and see what comes up.<br/><br/>What I was wondering is that, would you and you other readers would consider doing the same (or any other predictive process) and if you would consider opening a post here to discuss the results?  I think that having a clearinghouse for the different reads done by different people would be interesting.  <br/><br/>(In case someone missed it)<br/><br/><a href=\"https://www.patreon.com/posts/annular-solar-17-150595535\">https://www.patreon.com/posts/annular-solar-17-150595535</a><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59228074", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 07:15 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Drop me a personal message via Dreamwidth after Magic Monday is finished, reminding me of this, and yes, I can certainly do that. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59248554", "title": "Timing in Europe?", "date": "2026-02-16 09:44 pm", "user": "emily07", "content": "Umm, for such know-nothings as me, what time would that be around Frankfurt? Tuesday 10 o clock p.m?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59251370", "title": "Re: Timing in Europe?", "date": "2026-02-16 09:57 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Magic Monday shuts down at 12 pm Eastern time, as Monday becomes Tuesday. Frankfurt, Germany is 6 hours ahead of us, so any time after 6 am Tuesday morning will be fine; I won't get it until early afternoon Frankfurt time, but that's not a problem. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59254698", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 10:31 pm", "user": "scottyc", "content": "I'll do my best to make that time.   Thinking of using the Sacred Geometry card deck"}]}, {"id": "cmt59223210", "title": "Masonry and Catholicism", "date": "2026-02-16 05:28 pm", "user": "sanctuaryofroseandchalice", "content": "Greetings:<br/><br/>This question is less of a question to JMG specifically (although his sage advice is welcome), but to the commentariat as a whole.  I'm a Freemason, formally a high church Episcopalian and lately I fell drawn to cross the Tiber.  Which, up until a couple of weeks ago I never considered.  I still have my reservations, and there's the obvious threat of excommunication due to my Masonic membership.  I don't believe there to be an essential incompatibility, but Church authorities say otherwise.  If there are Catholic Masons here, how have you navigated the issue of dual membership?  I won't be able to communicate for the rest of the day, so I'll say thank you all in advance.  May you all be blessed.<br/><br/>Sincerely,<br/>Sanctuary of the Rose and Chalice.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59228330", "title": "Re: Masonry and Catholicism", "date": "2026-02-16 07:18 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Rhode Island, where I lived until last month, has a lot of Catholics, and so about half the Masons I know there are at least nominally Catholic. The essential rule is <i><b>Don't Tell The Church</b></i>. They can't handle it. <br/><br/>BTW, have you done divination about this? There's a lot of collective energy toward the more traditional branches of Christianity right now, as we move into what Oswald Spengler called the Second Religiosity -- people are turning toward the older churches as a bulwark against personal and social chaos -- and it's easy to get caught up in that. Divination can help you figure out if it's right for you. "}, {"id": "cmt59264426", "title": "Re: Masonry and Catholicism", "date": "2026-02-17 01:03 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I am Catholic, but not a Mason.  I joined the Catholic church in my 40s, and have a lot of friends who are Masons.<br/><br/>I would recommend against trying to do both, fairly strongly.  I haven't seen anyone who was able to get what the Catholic church has to offer without being willing to be honest and \"do the things\".  (Catholic practice is a lot like our esteemed host describes magic; you do the course as given FIRST, and see how it worked much later.)  It's possible as I understand it to join the Catholic church and stop being a Mason, without breaking your promises as a Mason.<br/><br/>SamChevre"}]}, {"id": "cmt59223722", "title": "Blasting Trident of Paracelsus", "date": "2026-02-16 05:40 pm", "user": "greensmith", "content": "With JMG's blessing, I'm thrilled to offer the community here the opportunity to purchase a blasting trident of Paracelsus. These are handmade by myself (a blacksmith) and two other local craftsmen. They ship from Canada.<br/><br/>The design was made with JMG's input and I am very happy with how they've turned out.<br/><br/>You can follow the link to my website here for more details and pictures: <br/><a href=\"https://reforgedironworks.com/product/blasting-trident-of-paracelsus/\">https://reforgedironworks.com/product/blasting-trident-of-paracelsus/</a><br/><br/>Please direct any questions about the trident via email info-at-reforgedironworks-dot-com.<br/><br/>Sincerely,<br/>Tim PW<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59229610", "title": "Re: Blasting Trident of Paracelsus", "date": "2026-02-16 07:23 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I have now received three tridents, no two of them alike but all fully functional, and a fourth is on its way from France! I'll leave it to the other creators to out themselves if they like. I will say that Tim's trident is a good solid piece of work, light enough to be easy to handle and sturdy enough to put up with any amount of banishing and etheric discharge, and the design is symbolically correct. (The words that go on the haft are in the section of the iron that's inside the handle; they're still fully effective.) I have already used it with good results. (I've used both the others, too, with equal success; it's a good clean robust design that any competent metalsmith can follow.) ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59231402", "title": "Re: Blasting Trident of Paracelsus", "date": "2026-02-16 07:28 pm", "user": "greensmith", "content": "JMG and all, <br/><br/>I'm glad to hear it's working well!<br/><br/>I just realized I should include a picture of the trident in my post. Do I add an img HTML tag to do that?<br/><br/>Like this?<br/>[IMAGE:0]<br/><br/>Tim PW", "images": [{"url": "https://reforgedironworks.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/DSC_1275-2.jpg", "local_path": "./data/archive/2026/2026-02-15_10-33PM_Magic_Monday/images/2026-02-16_07_28_pm_DSC_1275-2.jpg"}], "replies": [{"id": "cmt59231914", "title": "Re: Blasting Trident of Paracelsus", "date": "2026-02-16 07:30 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's exactly how to do it, as you see! "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59261098", "title": "Re: Blasting Trident of Paracelsus", "date": "2026-02-16 11:50 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Very cool!"}]}, {"id": "cmt59223978", "title": "Spculum Alchemiae", "date": "2026-02-16 05:46 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "To share: A really cool article (IMO) from Dana O'Driscoll on her visit to the Speculum Alchemiae museum in Prague and her recreation of some elemental symbols she saw there.<br/><br/>https://thedruidsgarden.com/2026/02/15/recreating-pragues-speculum-alchemiae-elemental-symbols-a-bardic-journey-part-i/<br/><br/>This lab, with its secret tunnels and passages, even including a bookcase door, is fascinating in itself.<br/><br/>JPM", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59230122", "title": "Re: Spculum Alchemiae", "date": "2026-02-16 07:24 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, Dana told me about that as soon as she came back. I'm going to be getting a set of elemental banners from her, using the emblems as images. It's got me even more interested than I already was about going to Prague! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59234986", "title": "Re: Spculum Alchemiae", "date": "2026-02-16 07:53 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "That was an amazing bit of work she did too, with the inner contact from the artist coming through. Very inspiring. I'll be curious to learn more about the numerology that she hinted at. <br/><br/>Her post is giving me some ideas of new ways to explore the bardic arts. Oak tincture sounds good too... in the mean time I may get some Oak Bach flower remedy, or if there is a homeopathic preparation of oak, that might be worth experimenting with.<br/><br/>I hope you get to go to Prague some time!<br/><br/>Justin"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59224746", "title": "On The Life force Workbook", "date": "2026-02-16 06:04 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "While I am very much interested in the Life Force Workbook from an academic standpoint, I'm curious about how the exercises in the workbook made you feel. How would you describe it? A sense of energy? Alertness? Clear-headedness?<br/><br/>Thanks for your time.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59230378", "title": "Re: On The Life force Workbook", "date": "2026-02-16 07:25 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That varies from person to person. I get different responses from each exercise. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59225002", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 06:19 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I wanted to thank you for writing the Coelbren book.  In my teen years, I took up the study of the Elder Futhark, feeling very drawn to the runes. However once I started learning them, things felt “off” for me, in a way that I couldn’t quite figure out. <br/><br/>Fast forward about 15 years, finding your Coelbren book - it felt like reuniting with a long lost friend. I’m not sure if there’s some past life connection, or just something my soul needs in this incarnation… but I’m happy I found it. It’s been a source of joy for me. <br/><br/>I also wanted to say, after reading the source Barddas material - I’m glad someone was able to decode that confusing jumble and put it into a coherent book that I could actually use!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59231146", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 07:28 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm delighted to hear this. I also found the Coelbren very easy to use, once I stumbled across the key to the meanings, and it's good to know others have had the same experience. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59225258", "title": "Hypothesis for solar eclipse and saturn neptune conjunction", "date": "2026-02-16 06:23 pm", "user": "fringewood", "content": "I'm posting my hypothesis on Magic Monday because of my use of astrology and because I see the Solar logos using the art and science of magic to cause changes in consciousness in accordance with will.<br/><br/>I will do my best to keep it concise.<br/><br/>On Sept 1 1859, the Carrington Event, a large Coronal Mass Ejection from the sun  (see more here: <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carrington_Event\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carrington_Event</a> <br/>and here: <a href=\"https://cosmicintelligenceagency.com/timelords-magazine/mundane-matters/2025-the-effects-of-solar-activities-and-celestial-alignments/\">https://cosmicintelligenceagency.com/timelords-magazine/mundane-matters/2025-the-effects-of-solar-activities-and-celestial-alignments/</a> ) caused a huge geomagnetic storm on earth that set the electronic technology at that time, the telegraph, on fire and powered it for a few hours as well.  Rather than go into detail, I trust that the links will explain a great deal more.<br/><br/>The Carrington Event occurred four days after a partial solar eclipse on the 28th of August. The chart for the eclipse shows Uranus in Air square the Sun and Moon in Earth (Gemini to Virgo), a large stellium of planets close to the sun/moon conjunction, and Jupiter in Cancer. <br/>[IMAGE:0]<br/><br/><br/> The Solar eclipse tomorrow (2/17/2026) shows Uranus in Earth Square the Sun and Moon in Air (Taurus to Aquarius), a large stellium of planets close to the sun/moon conjunction, and interestingly, Jupiter in Cancer. <br/>[IMAGE:1] <br/><br/>These combinations do not occur on a regular yearly basis.<br/><br/>Are we about to have another Carrington Event? One that would strike our electronic technology: computers/Aquarius (in everything from cars to cameras, from satelites to cell phones, and from airplanes to armband tech) literally down to the earth? (Taurus)<br/><br/>A large solar flare like the Carrington event could knock out a lot of satellites and cripple the power grid for awhile.   This has already happened on a smaller scale (<a href=\"https://tfiglobalnews.com/2025/06/09/why-523-starlink-satellites-crashed-the-shocking-impact-of-solar-cycle-25/\">https://tfiglobalnews.com/2025/06/09/why-523-starlink-satellites-crashed-the-shocking-impact-of-solar-cycle-25/</a> ). Cars and Planes that use computers could stop working. Cell towers would go dark. <br/><br/>I think it's entirely possible and could cause a massive reset (Saturn conjunct Neptune in Aries) which would be devastating to many, but could bring out the ingenuity and adaptability of humans and put a generation of people who know how to fix things back to the forefront. Mechanics, welders, machinists blacksmiths, woodworkers, etc could come together and use older technologies to put a temporary bandage on things. Decisions could be made to retrofit old technologies over damaged. Government would reduce and the banking industry among others could go back to older ways that work. Blue collar workers would be needed in mass and find their place in society is strengthened.<br/><br/>Will it happen soon? I don't know. The signs point that way. With Saturn in Aries, I would say within 2 1/2 years, before Saturn goes into the building cycle of Taurus.<br/><br/>As to the Solar Logos, our protector from \"outside\" interference to the grand plan that was initiated millenia ago, the Coronal Mass Ejection and subsequent solar storm is just one of many tools to cause changes in consciousness in accordance with will.<br/>[IMAGE:2]<br/><br/>Some interesting sites for further investigation:<br/><br/><a href=\"https://www.popsci.com/science/carrington-event-training/\">https://www.popsci.com/science/carrington-event-training/</a><br/><a href=\"https://www.crbcnews.com/articles/698167328b088d328be5ada4\">https://www.crbcnews.com/articles/698167328b088d328be5ada4</a><br/><a href=\"https://www.livescience.com/space/the-sun/the-next-carrington-level-solar-superstorm-could-wipe-out-all-our-satellites-new-simulations-reveal\">https://www.livescience.com/space/the-sun/the-next-carrington-level-solar-superstorm-could-wipe-out-all-our-satellites-new-simulations-reveal</a><br/>best <a href=\"https://www.usgs.gov/news/featured-story/what-a-solar-superstorm-could-mean-us\">https://www.usgs.gov/news/featured-story/what-a-solar-superstorm-could-mean-us</a><br/>research paper <a href=\"https://www.usgs.gov/news/featured-story/what-a-solar-superstorm-could-mean-us\">https://www.usgs.gov/news/featured-story/what-a-solar-superstorm-could-mean-us</a><br/><a href=\"https://grokipedia.com/page/List_of_solar_storms\">https://grokipedia.com/page/List_of_solar_storms</a><br/><a href=\"https://cosmoscience.in/solar-wind-and-planetary-evolution/\">https://cosmoscience.in/solar-wind-and-planetary-evolution/</a><br/><br/><br/>Sites to observe the sun:<br/><br/><a href=\"https://spaceweather.com/\">https://spaceweather.com/</a><br/><a href=\"https://xras.ru/en/sun_flares.html\">https://xras.ru/en/sun_flares.html</a>", "images": [{"url": "https://fringewood.dreamwidth.org/file/14216.jpg", "local_path": "./data/archive/2026/2026-02-15_10-33PM_Magic_Monday/images/2026-02-16_06_23_pm_14216.jpg"}, {"url": "https://fringewood.dreamwidth.org/file/14370.jpg", "local_path": "./data/archive/2026/2026-02-15_10-33PM_Magic_Monday/images/2026-02-16_06_23_pm_14370.jpg"}, {"url": "https://fringewood.dreamwidth.org/file/12914.jpg", "local_path": "./data/archive/2026/2026-02-15_10-33PM_Magic_Monday/images/2026-02-16_06_23_pm_12914.jpg"}], "edit_time": "2026-02-16 06:38 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59232426", "title": "Re: Hypothesis for solar eclipse and saturn neptune conjunction", "date": "2026-02-16 07:33 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "An interesting hypothesis, and it's bold of you, but highly appropriate, to make it in public like this. Now we'll see if you're right -- and if you are, why, we'll have a new predictive tool in astrology. "}, {"id": "cmt59268778", "title": "Re: Hypothesis for solar eclipse and saturn neptune conjunction", "date": "2026-02-17 01:49 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Coupla things: <br/>1)  in Carr chart Merc BETWEEN Sun &amp; Moon, hence catching hard square on both sides and the middle.<br/>  in 2morrow’s chart, Merc &amp; Venus in Fish, trine Jupiter. Lucky, protection? <br/>2) in Carr chart, Mars, Saturn flanking South node in 12th house, deep, hidden dangers<br/>  in 2morrow’s chart, Mars only in 12th house, Moon’s nodes not shown. Uranus perhaps at South node, weakened?<br/>  Also: stellium of 6 bodies all in 1st house, 3 pairs conjunctions each pair out of orb with the two other pair, pairs in three different signs. Uranus shock out in open, surface effect, close call but no cigar? Likewise, Uranus sextile Saturn + Neptune = early warning (Danger Will Robinson! robot arms flailing, lights flashing) perhaps?"}]}, {"id": "cmt59225514", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 06:37 pm", "user": "diletpoly", "content": "<p>Not much to add or ask today, but I'm trying to keep up and I wanted to say something. I was going to ask about basic sources on Astrology, but I thought better of it, as I'm nearing a focus point in my GSF work and I think my sudden interest in, really, any other system is just my usual habit of self-sabotage before I can make real progress. I'll ask again when it's more appropriate.</p>\n<p>Oh, I do have a question. I'm planning on beginning the W4E work at the Spring Equinox, and I'm thinking about what to use for my Book of Air. I know the book says it should be new, but I have an odd case. Many years ago, I saw and bought a leather-bound blank book in a store in an exotic location. Really, it's just a leather cover and strap over a regular notebook, but it spoke to me, so I bought it. Then, it's sat on my shelf for the 18-20 years since, just collecting dust. I'll occasionally think if I can find a good use for it but never have. Until now. It seems like maybe I bought it for this purpose, and I didn't know it. </p>\n<p>So, the question is, how important is it that the elemental tools be new? And is bought and put on a shelf for 20 years the equivalent of new?</p>\n<p>Thanks as always for hosting these,</p>\n<p>The Dilettante Polymath</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59232938", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 07:38 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You can certainly use that book. The important thing is that it should not have been used for another purpose. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59227818", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 07:14 pm", "user": "jenniferkobernik", "content": "Recently I was re-reading Joseph Jenkins's Humanure Handbook and noticed that he mentioned Rudolph Steiner. According to Jenkins, Steiner said that humanure should never be used to grow crops for human consumption, and that in general animal manures should not be used to grow food for that species of animal. Jenkins chalked this up to \"fecophobia,\" but I wonder. <br/><br/>It seems like a sensible measure to break potential disease/parasite cycles, for one thing, but I also wondered if there was something etheric about it, since you've mentioned that excrement can be a low-grade source of etheric energy, and also that cannibalism is problematic (among other reasons) because the remnants of the highly organized human etheric body can cause problems for those consuming it. <br/><br/>We do compost and use humanure, although generally we let it age for a couple of years and then plant a fruit tree in the area where the pile has decomposed rather than using it for annuals. And of course some of our animals consume forage fertilized with their own manures, such as the cows eating pasture grasses where they've formerly relieved themselves.<br/><br/>My questions are: have you come across this bit of Steiner, and is Jenkins's report of it accurate? Do you know if there's an esoteric logic behind the prohibition, and do you agree with it for humanure and/or other animals' manure?<br/><br/>Thank you!<br/><br/>(P.S. It tickles me that this is almost certainly not the weirdest Magic Monday question you will receive this week. I really enjoy this forum and the commentariat here!)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59233450", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 07:42 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That sounds like Steiner, though I haven't specifically encountered it. The crucial point is that humanure should always be hot-composted before use, and putting it on the roots of trees is a very sensible use. Composting it in a good hot composter will break up the etheric patterns in it, as it (and they) will all be eaten by the compost microbes, and the results will be imprinted with the microbes' etheric patterns rather than those of human beings. (Of course hot compost also puts paid to human pathogens, which need the sheltered environment of your bowels and don't last long in the savage Darwinian free-for-all of a steaming compost heap.)"}]}, {"id": "cmt59228586", "title": "Thunb-Sucking", "date": "2026-02-16 07:19 pm", "user": "milkyway1", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>A question which I hope you haven't had to field too often before... :D<br/><br/>Do you know of any connection between thumb-sucking, as little children are wont to do, and the energy body? Any etheric effects or results?<br/><br/>Or can you recall anything e.g. from your reading which might be a starting point for research in this direction?<br/><br/>Thanks,<br/><br/>Milkyway", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59233962", "title": "Re: Thunb-Sucking", "date": "2026-02-16 07:43 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's an intriguing question to which I don't know the answer. I sucked my thumb until the age of seven, so it doesn't seem to cause lasting harm! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59235242", "title": "Re: Thunb-Sucking", "date": "2026-02-16 07:54 pm", "user": "milkyway1", "content": "I wasn't thinking about harm caused. More curious about stuff like \"connecting this part of the energy body with that one\". Or \"allowing this or that to flow better\", or \"releasing whatnot\". Or, well, anything else. :-) But since you haven't encountered anything...<br/><br/>@ Jennifer Kobernik, this is funny, but I seriously only read your PS after posting my initial comment! :D ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59251626", "title": "Re: Thunb-Sucking", "date": "2026-02-16 09:57 pm", "user": "emily07", "content": "I have to dig around a bit but from memory it´s a prompting of the whatsit in Englisch \"Propriozeption\" so the feeling of the body for itself (usually one can say more or less accurately e.g. in which direction ones feet are pointing without having to look). <br/>IIRC in one book (on handreading I think) the thump was connected to the \"I\" or individuality. (Oh, and I just now read the comment of the Jin Shin Jyutsu..oops!)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59253930", "title": "Re: Thunb-Sucking", "date": "2026-02-16 10:14 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The English word is very similar: \"proprioception.\""}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59242154", "title": "Re: Thunb-Sucking", "date": "2026-02-16 08:52 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You may want to look into Jin Shin Jyutsu, a Japanese acupressure system with many overlaps with TCM and Do-In. In Jin Shin, the thumb is the end point, so to say, of the spleen/stomach channel, and holding it can promote/soothe digestion. For those interested, Jin Shin does seem to play well with John Gilbert's system, and I've found great benefit since incorporating it into my own practice.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59252394", "title": "Re: Thunb-Sucking", "date": "2026-02-16 10:04 pm", "user": "milkyway1", "content": "Thank you!"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59228842", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 07:21 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What was the form of tai chi you studied, and what are some good sources on it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59234218", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 07:46 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Back in Seattle, and then in Ashland OR, I studied the double-sided old Yang style of Tchoung Ta-chen: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tchoung_Ta-chen\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tchoung_Ta-chen</a><br/><br/>There's very little in print on it; I have Master Tchoung's book on it, but that's normally available only to practitioners with a teacher's approval. <br/><br/>I've just started classes in the Yang short form of Cheng Man-ching, as I'd like to get back into tai chi practice. We'll see how that goes. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59235498", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 07:55 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I remember you saying your previous tai chi practice clashed badly with ceremonial magic and made you ill. How do you know this style will be safe?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59236778", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:06 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't know for certain -- that's why I said \"We'll see how that goes.\" I won't be practicing any of the qigong forms that were part of Tchoung Ta-chen's system, however, and my occult practice has also moved in very different directions over the last 17 years, which is why I'm giving it a try. <br/><br/>I've also had good results with Tai Chi Chih, an exercise system based on tai chi chuan but greatly simplified, which I learned many years ago and took up again about five years back; there have been no negative effects from that, so here's hoping. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59238058", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:12 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "With hindsight can you tell what specifically caused the clash back then?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59238826", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:15 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nope. It would probably have taken a couple of visits to a really good Chinese traditional doctor who also knew about Western magic to be sure. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59237802", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:10 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": " I see that there are videos and instructions for the Yang short form on-line. Would you be kind enough to advise whether these are safe to do with a modest GD-style practice (LBRP, MP Exercise, meditation, invocations, divination) or indeed whether Tai Chi as a whole is compatible? <br/>In my occasional visits to YouTube I am overwhelmed with advertisements for Tai Chi  walking. This is new to me. Is it part of what you studied? <br/>Many thanks. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59239338", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:18 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I don't recommend trying to learn tai chi from a video. You really need the feedback and guidance of a qualified teacher. There are lots of those, however. I know a good many Western occultists, including Golden Dawnies, who do tai chi without problems, but I also know some who've had serious difficulties; I recommend keeping a close eye on your health, and visiting a good acupuncturist if you know one. <br/><br/>2) No, that's a very recent and very, <i>very</i> simplified offshoot of tai chi. I prefer to do something a little more traditional. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59229866", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 07:24 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Did occultists' understanding of the elements change with the invention of machines that allowed the elements to be manipulated in new ways?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59234474", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 07:48 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nope. Technologies are always changing; the four elements were introduced to esoteric teaching in the 6th century BC, when waterwheels and windmills hadn't been invented yet. The principles work just as well now as they did then. "}, {"id": "cmt59257258", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 10:50 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "My understanding of elementals changed (cf. https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/316974.html?thread=54056750#cmt54105646:~:text=structural%20parallels and also https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/330305.html?thread=55847745#cmt55864385 ) after I learned some computational science, a field which is in a few ways about how you would organize efficient imagination/implementation of coherent possible ongoing details or dynamics across spacetime levels of detail given underlying laws. (Does anyone talk about light elementals? They would plausibly also embody solutions to a fascinating problem, switching fluidly between representative factorizations for long-distance cause-and-effect using particle-count-based perspectives over 4D manifolds slicing a 5D light field underlying space in various ways and deeper wave-tensor-product-based perspectives over 2D manifolds slicing in other ways, even before getting into time-variability / full spectra.) But I don't have the sort of practice where I would expect to get feedback if I was wrong."}]}, {"id": "cmt59230890", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 07:28 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "From what I've read about enlightenment traditions - both the slow and steady approach of Mariana Caplan and the 'enlightenment as fast as possible no matter the cost' of Rahasya and Jed Mckenna - the goal is a constant awareness of unity, everything being one, and not existing as a separate individual. From the point of view of occult philosophy and cosmology, what have people actually done when they achieve this?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59235754", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 07:56 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Awareness of unity can happen in many ways, some healthy, others pathological. You can achieve it by transforming your mental sheath (the not-yet-fully-organized embodiment of the human soul on the mental plane) into a mental body capable of perceiving and acting on the mental plane, and then directing your attention toward planes above the mental, where unity can be perceived. You can also get there by damaging your astral body so badly that it no longer has a functioning boundary, in which case you can no longer perceive yourself as a separate individual because you get swamped by whatever astral phenomena happen to come your way. You can also do other things, some more useful than others. <br/><br/>My experience, though, with people who claim to have dissolved their separate identities is that by and large they haven't overcome their existence as a separate individual, they've just repressed it. It's remarkable how many people who insist they've overcome their egos act like raging egomaniacs. I wrote about that here: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/the-no-ego-ego-trip-an-interlude/\">https://www.ecosophia.net/the-no-ego-ego-trip-an-interlude/</a><br/><br/>That slippery word \"enlightenment\" can mean many different things, btw, and the meaning you assign it is only one of the many options... ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59236522", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:03 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What are some of the other meanings of enlightenment?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59239850", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:21 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You can find them in any good dictionary. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59240618", "title": "A Vision", "date": "2026-02-16 08:28 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "Do early and late primary phase people (phases 26-4) have weaker astral boundaries?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59248810", "title": "Re: A Vision", "date": "2026-02-16 09:45 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yeats doesn't say. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59241130", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:35 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "\"You can also get there by damaging your astral body so badly that it no longer has a functioning boundary...\"<br/><br/>Not the OP. Is there a way to tell the experience of these apart? Over the last couple of years, mystical experiences have been coming and going every so often. I had another one last week, and it's very hard to describe: mental chatter slows down but thoughts are still there following along, but there is a silence or emptiness beyond, an image, sound, and feeling of this emptiness. Felt cold but energetic, a positive sense of being physically charged. It was a very physical experience, not really any images aside from what I mentioned.<br/><br/>But I became scared, and this is the reason I am posting this: I don't know whether that fear was a useful danger signal, or whether it was better to let the fear go. The writings on these topics are so confusing and contradictory on this. I decided to simply allow these experiences to happen when they happen, but I never know how to handle them when they do come up.<br/><br/>That's probably not enough information to explain the experience but your mention of the damage to the astral body made me jump in to ask anyway. I noted down afterwards the sense of feeling like there was this emptiness that I could let go into, but also the sense that may be letting go of a boundary. <br/><br/>I did divination right afterwards (single Ogham few of Nuin upright) which felt like a good sign, but I am still not sure about it.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59249066", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 09:47 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nah, you're fine. The kind of damage that leaves your astral body without a functioning boundary lets other people's thoughts and feelings spew into your mind all at once; people in that condition may be one with everything but they're also basket cases who often can't even handle ordinary activities. (Back in the day every monastery had a few of these.) ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59258282", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 11:07 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How do you end up in that condition? Not that I want to, you understand, but I am very interested in astral body maintenance, and I have quite a fondness for boundaries. What kinda stuff (and dare I say it, pursuits?) work to render it in this way? I guess you have to work pretty hard at it for some while...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59266474", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 01:33 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm not going to get into the details, because there are people who would do it. Yes, it takes a lot of hard work. If you like astral boundaries, may I suggest a daily banishing ritual? That does no end of good. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59263914", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 12:48 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "OK, thank you, it's reassuring to hear my experience isn't leading to that sort of damage! I hope the abbots and monks who had people without a boundary found a way to treat them and that it was possible for their condition to improve.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59266730", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 01:34 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In some cases, yes. In others, there wasn't much anybody could do. "}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59271082", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 02:22 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "As for what happens materially, which I think is an important guide to what might be happening on other levels given the close entrainment and symbolism of identity and self-representation across the levels, I like this characterization that I saw recently. In American Zen, one of the ways of describing enlightenment is \"resolving the Great Matter\", and:<br/><br/>https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/mZtbEKb2vYzdC2mRL/on-resolving-the-great-matter?commentId=tqR397vkeN78gEZPr<br/><br/>&gt; Does the Great Matter map to the thing I'll try and point to here:<br/>&gt; <br/>&gt; &gt; The rejection of your non-existence, bending perception and epistemics in order to make your own not-being in some sense incomprehensible, and therefore unknown/scary/something your whole system contorts itself to avoiding. Similar to other trauma-patterns which reject the reality they try and avoid, but made of the evolution-trauma of the deaths of your ancestors.<br/><br/>That part about \"unknown/scary/something your whole system contorts itself to avoiding\" is stated in such a way as to implicitly tie in with this whole other body of thinking, about how a lot of human and animal motivation is built on top of a shortcut of instinctively insisting on imaginary futures where some things go certain ways and other things definitely don't go certain other ways, and then (in a certain sense) performing one's part in those imagined futures. \"One's own death\" is one of the strongest holes in imagined-possibility-space a human's instincts can impose, and a hole that strong has certain recurring distortionary effects. The body of thinking is loosely organized around a concept called \"predictive processing\" or \"active inference\"; I wrote it up a little in https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/352530.html?thread=58548498#cmt58565394 .<br/><br/>As I understand it, the material form of enlightenment can be described as an interruption (often only made possible by long practice and habit-building) of what would otherwise be the instinctively compulsive ongoing construction of a special instinct-identifiable concept of oneself and of certain habituated illusions around that concept. This interruption has a lot of effects, both \"good\" and \"bad\", on instincts selected to manipulate the organism's behavior through manipulation of the organism's thinking about \"itself\". (I say \"good\" and \"bad\" in quotes, because the habits that support enlightenment often lead to the drawing-out of a sort of figurative compelling toxin from the way people normally use words like that.) One of those effects is to stop one's instincts from being able to drive so many anomalies around the concept of one's own death; and so, conversely, it's possible that the self-defendingness of those anomalies is the main reason why this kind of enlightenment is normally so much more readily achieved (<i>pace</i> the opposite Dzogchen strategy) by a route so slow and indirect.<br/><br/>(Also, enlightenment usually is somehow connected with making your \"conscious self\" stop suffering, but from the outside it seems like often when \"enlightened\" people undergo experiences that one would normally expect to require a grieving or trauma-recovery process, the rest of person still becomes distressed and impaired in the usual ways, even if the person's conscious self reports feeling fine. I'm not sure what to say about this point due to conflicting information, but one possibility is some kind of paradox about \"tuning out from\" some aspects of pain by \"tuning into\" other aspects of it.)<br/><br/>There's a strange parallel between, in the case of enlightenment as a phenomenon of material brains, the disruption of an illusion and the disruption of compulsive identification with an instinct-constructed concept of \"self\", and, in the loose consensus of the Western-esoteric worldview, the falling-away and loss of compellingness of one's material-causation-rooted thoughts and the disruption of one's compulsive identification with an incarnation-constructed concept of \"self-body\". However, this parallel seems to me to be tied in with the way that the supernatural tries to maintain plausible deniability or interpret-away-ability to almost all materialist observers, which leads into opening a small can of worms to try to comment about. And one of those worms in this case is a certain Zen phenomenon which is referred to figuratively as keeping a teaching device from getting \"used up\", which makes the whole thing fraught in such a way where I don't feel competent enough right now to go into further detail without risking spoiling something important.<br/><br/>Anyway, there are downsides to the material side of enlightenment, associated with the normal instinctive thinking patterns it interrupts. It's sort of a Chesterton's Fence situation, where you'd want to know what those downsides are and how to compensate for them or work around them before simply \"tearing down the fence\" of self-image instinct. And the work of doing that seems like an important symbolic effort for doing the corresponding work for supernatural things parallel to material enlightenment."}]}, {"id": "cmt59231658", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 07:30 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I read a book on Classical Chinese Medicine that went into a lot of detail on how the elements interact within the human body. Does western occultism have a similarly complex understanding of these processes?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59236266", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:03 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It once had this, and you can find scraps of the old knowledge here and there. Unfortunately the efforts made by mainstream medicine to stamp out any rival system, and jail those who practice any such thing, have been fairly effective. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59241642", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:48 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What was Viktor Schauberger's relationship to occultism? As I understand it he was associated with Rudolph Steiner, came up with theories about water vortexes that led to the flowform, and supposedly worked on experimental aircraft engines for the Nazis.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59249578", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 09:48 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't happen to know. I haven't studied his biography at all. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59242666", "title": "Eclipses + The Saturn-Neptune Conjunction", "date": "2026-02-16 08:55 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>With eclipse season upon us and the conjunction days away, are there any best practices for how one should time their daily rituals (LBRP, SoP, etc.) around these events? <br/><br/>Thank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59250090", "title": "Re: Eclipses + The Saturn-Neptune Conjunction", "date": "2026-02-16 09:50 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Ordinary daily practices won't be affected at all. I don't recommend doing more complex or specialized magical workings tomorrow, or on the 20th. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59275434", "title": "Re: Eclipses + The Saturn-Neptune Conjunction", "date": "2026-02-17 04:09 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you!"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59242922", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 08:55 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How does one make peace/honor/get on good terms with house spirits?  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59250346", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 09:52 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's not a branch of lore I've studied. (My late wife used to talk to them and find out what they wanted, but not everyone is that clairvoyant.) You might want to look up folklore of your region or your ancestors and see what that has to say. "}, {"id": "cmt59260330", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 11:37 pm", "user": "dfr1973", "content": "Over the weekend I purchased this book<br/><a href=\"https://www.innertraditions.com/books/the-tradition-of-household-spirits\">https://www.innertraditions.com/books/the-tradition-of-household-spirits</a><br/>to go along with the newly-published The Cunning Farmer, and the newer/different translation of the orphic hymns.  I had read a sample chapter about a year or so ago from Google books, so it was on my radar and I was pleasantly surprised to see it was still in print."}]}, {"id": "cmt59244202", "title": "banished talisman", "date": "2026-02-16 09:02 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Greetings JMG,<br/><br/>I made a basic GD talisman a while back (as described in circles of power), but I think I might have messed up the storage. I kept it undisturbed in a manilla envelope inside a wooden file cabinet, but it was in the same room where I was doing my daily LBRP/MP. Did I ruin it with my daily banishing? If so, can I reuse the physical basis to reconsecrate it for the same purpose or should I start over from scratch?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59250602", "title": "Re: banished talisman", "date": "2026-02-16 09:53 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm sorry to say it's probably discharged. You'll have to start over from scratch. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59254954", "title": "Re: banished talisman", "date": "2026-02-16 10:31 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Will do. Thank you for your advice!"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59249322", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 09:47 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear Mr Greer, <br/><br/>If I have a shrine set up in the style of The Weird of Hali: Kingsport. I was wondering, are there any rules/etiquette around covering/sealing the container with the potpourri? I would like to preserve the smell but I also think that the scent evaporating is part of the offering? <br/><br/>Thanks as always", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59250858", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 09:54 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The bowl of potpourri should be open, because yes, the scent is an important part of the offering, and it's a perpetual offering, not just during prayers. That's why it has to be replenished at intervals with essential oils. <br/><br/>(I do this also, btw. The gods seem to like it.) "}]}, {"id": "cmt59255466", "title": "I know that I have already asked a question", "date": "2026-02-16 10:37 pm", "user": "degringolade", "content": "But If you would indulge me.<br/><br/>As an outgrowth of reading your fiction (I have all the WOH books) I have used the five x 3-card spread that you described in WOH: Chorazin and modified it to Tarot cards..  I realize that this is just my idiosyncrasy, and it is probably better suited for Gypsy Witch cards, but I was wondering if you were aware of any \"formal\" system in the literature that uses this system?<br/><br/>first three:  The past<br/>second three: The present<br/>third three:  The future<br/>fourth three: Nature of the road ahead<br/>fifth three:  What stands in the way<br/><br/>I am going to keep using it, but it would be nice to point to something when someone else is telling me I am doing it all wrong.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59256490", "title": "Re: I know that I have already asked a question", "date": "2026-02-16 10:47 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It can be used with any divination deck that has a decent number of cards. As for the origins, though, I made it up. I needed those five things to be brought up for the sake of the plot, and that's what my imagination came up with. If anybody gives you trouble, tell them I created it, and just don't mention the circumstances! <br/><br/>(Or tell them in a hushed whisper, leaning slightly toward them, that it's used in the Starry Wisdom tradition and probably comes from nonhuman sources; lean forward a little further, and start making gurgling noises in your throat, then start twitching and writhing, and gasp, \"I have to leave -- the tentacles are about to sprout. <i>Ia! Ia!</i>\"  ;-)"}]}, {"id": "cmt59256234", "title": "Saturnian Message", "date": "2026-02-16 10:45 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi John, <br/><br/>I’m coming towards the end of my first Saturn Return. Been a bit of a kicker, wont lie. There was one particular moment I want to quickly relay to you at work last year. Sat at my desk, a very vivid image (I don't get these often and am very poor at visualisations) of an old man bound to the earth, made mostly of rock and roots peeled himself from the earth and brought me a message that I really needed to here, and I really did here it in that moment. It was the word ‘limits’. <br/>I wanted to know if this was a deity that rings similar to anything you may have come across in your time? I’m fairly new to the occult, but this Being really felt both not my imagination and deeply friendly, like a very, very old friend. <br/>I’ve been in a period of my life where it felt like no new information was really sticking, but this surely did. I’d like to thank him.<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59266986", "title": "Re: Saturnian Message", "date": "2026-02-17 01:36 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That doesn't ring any bells. You could pray to him and just call him Earth Man, however. It was once quite common in some traditions to use terms like that for gods whose names were unknown, or not to be spoken. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59256746", "title": "The Great Conjunction, and etheric beings trapped on a desert island", "date": "2026-02-16 10:47 pm", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "One of the more fascinating topics that came up last year was the story of a soul-swarm from the 6th etheric plane, who came down here to the 7th material plane thousands of years ago, and have been stuck here ever since. For these souls, the experience of being human in this world was an unnatural prison, and this gave rise to transcendent religions, with the message that their followers belong in a world of light beyond material existence. And now, our worlds are intersecting again, and they finally get to go home, where they'll be light-beings in eusocial hives, or some such thing.<br/><br/>Personally, I wish them well -- I've always noticed how certain people, like Sinead O'Connor (RIP), seemed to be at odds with the human world somehow (and the fact that she passed a few years back is consistent with her departing for the 6th plane). Personally, I appreciate their contributions here, but it's also a good thing for them to get back to where they belong.<br/><br/>Anyway, you're probably thinking, what's my point, this has been discussed already. Yes, but this whole thing coincides with another massive astrological event -- the conjunction of Saturn &amp; Neptune in 0 Aries, a zodiacal reset that will bring a major transformation, as it did the last time around in the days of Ancient Greece. This too is good news, as the world could use innovation right about now.<br/><br/>So I'm wondering, is the Saturn/Neptune at 0 Aries conjunction related to the return of the etheric souls to their homeworld? Also, do we know when this conjunction happened the time before last? Meaning, before the present, and before the birth of philosophy and rise of Axial religions, when did this last happen? Since the etheric swarm arrived thousands of years ago, I'm wondering if such a conjunction brought them here, just as that conjunction is now seeing them off during their departure; and of course, the conjunction in between would've marked the flowering of their influence.<br/><br/>As always, thanks for MM.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59263402", "title": "Re: The Great Conjunction, and etheric beings trapped on a desert island", "date": "2026-02-17 12:33 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "It's an interesting theory.  Saturn represents hard limits, karma, time and timelimits and Neptune represents a return to source and oneness. It last happened in 594 BC but it was at 2 degrees not O, the reset button.    "}, {"id": "cmt59267498", "title": "Re: The Great Conjunction, and etheric beings trapped on a desert island", "date": "2026-02-17 01:41 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a fascinating hypothesis. It's not at all implausible, either -- some occult schools teach that Uranus and Neptune mediate influences from beyond the solar system, which is why they're not part of the traditional sequence of seven planetary forces. In this case Neptune would dissolve the boundaries between worlds, defined by Saturn, to allow ingress and egress. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59271338", "title": "Re: The Great Conjunction, and etheric beings trapped on a desert island", "date": "2026-02-17 02:25 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "I'd give more credance to that hypothesis if mass casualty events started happening when Saturn &amp; Neptune got in orb.<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59281834", "title": "Re: The Great Conjunction, and etheric beings trapped on a desert island", "date": "2026-02-17 05:00 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That doesn't follow at all. Since a great many souls are out of incarnation at any given time, it's more likely that -- since such events happen at predictable intervals -- the souls that are going to leave at a certain conjunction will have left incarnation in advance, so they could take the appropriate time to go through the after-death process and prepare for the transition. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59272618", "title": "Re: The Great Conjunction, and etheric beings trapped on a desert island", "date": "2026-02-17 02:42 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "anon: Granted, it was 2 degrees, not 0, but that's still significantly close. Apparently there was also a conjunction of 6 degrees in 555 AD, which marks the demise of Classical Antiquity, and the rise of the medieval and modern world.<br/><br/>JMG: Fascinating stuff, and it fits right into my idea.<br/>After digging further, I uncovered an earlier conjunction at 0, buried under all the noise: 4361 BC. Perhaps that's when the etheric soul-swarm came in, in the centuries leading up to the Bronze Age -- it would make sense, anyway. My whole idea of a 0 degree conjunction at their entrance, a 2 degree conjunction to bring about their zenith, and a 0 degree conjunction for their departure, fits far too well to be coincidence.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59275946", "title": "Re: The Great Conjunction, and etheric beings trapped on a desert island", "date": "2026-02-17 04:15 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm! Where did you find the 4361 date? That's fascinating, and yes, it would fit the timing as I was shown it in my vision. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59280554", "title": "Re: The Great Conjunction, and etheric beings trapped on a desert island", "date": "2026-02-17 04:56 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "As you can imagine, search results are deluged with the current conjunction, but there are hits for the ancient one, such as: <a href=\"https://www.yasminboland.com/6000-years-later-saturn-and-neptune-meet-again/\">https://www.yasminboland.com/6000-years-later-saturn-and-neptune-meet-again/</a><br/>It's good to have the timing confirmed; it really does all fit together. Alien souls trapped here for 6 millennia is quite a saga, and is a major hidden chapter in understanding our history. It also means that the future will be rather different with most of them back home!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59281578", "title": "Re: The Great Conjunction, and etheric beings trapped on a desert island", "date": "2026-02-17 04:58 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this. <br/><br/>If this is genuinely what's happening, yes, it's going to involve some drastic changes. "}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59258026", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 10:59 pm", "user": "thinking_turtle", "content": "<p>To share, for those who wonder what DOGD, LVX, or IR mean, a <a href=\"https://thinking-turtle.dreamwidth.org/tag/abbreviation\">list of abbreviations used on Ecopsophia</a>.  And here is a <a href=\"https://thinking-turtle.dreamwidth.org/tag/books\">list of the books our host published so far</a>.</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59267754", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 01:41 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this as always. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59260074", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 11:35 pm", "user": "chasethesun", "content": "Hi John,<br/><br/>I am currently battling a nasty nicotine addiction. Any tips on quitting this horrible habit? Is there's anything I can do or is it simply a matter of Will?<br/><br/>It's very upsetting how popular vaping as gotten just as cigarettes became less popular<br/><br/>Apologies if this isn't relevant to your blog", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59268010", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 01:45 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Don't try white-knuckling it; you'll lose, and weaken your will. Work on building up willpower through other, emotionally unchallenging exercises, like these: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/tag/will\">https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/tag/will</a><br/><br/>Meanwhile, do some journaling and see if you can find the emotional roots of your dependence on nicotine. Yes, there's a chemical dimension, but there's also always a psychological dimension; identify that and release it, and the way becomes easier. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59260842", "title": "Jewish Traditions", "date": "2026-02-16 11:47 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>I've been a longtime reader of your blog and a big appreciator of your work - I spent several years going through the Dolmen Arch, and I'm now going through your commentary on the Cosmic Doctrine for my daily meditative and study practice. I'm deeply grateful for your work and the immense amount of effort and study you have put into it. But that said...<br/><br/>I've done a lot of reading and study on the occult and magical traditions, but I've noticed that I have an aversion to a lot of Hebrew and Jewish mysticism. When I investigate it myself, the two issues that arise for me are seeing what adherents of that faith have done and are doing in the world, and not wishing to place a second \"people\" between me and the divine (I'm sure that the idea that Hebrew was the language God used to create the world is interesting and fruitful for meditation, but it doesn't sit right with me). I don't have any real desire to disrespect the faith, and I'm sure a lot of the people who do things in the name of it that I don't like are disrespecting it themselves, but it still rubs me the wrong way. Is this something I should just accept about myself, or is it something I should try to work through, understand and resolve?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59268266", "title": "Re: Jewish Traditions", "date": "2026-02-17 01:47 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's entirely up to you. You certainly aren't obligated to use a Hebraic mysticism -- there are plenty of alternatives, including Golden Dawn systems reworked for Druid and Heathen spirituality. Do some reflection and journaling on the subject, make sure you're comfortable with whatever path you choose, and go on. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59261610", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-16 11:58 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have a memory of a past MM comment about a set of three clear questions for a three-card Tarot spread. They were very simple questions but made for a compelling and to-the-point short reading. Was it possibly you, JMG? I have searched as best I could, but couldn’t locate the comment. If so, would you share the three questions again? TY!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59269034", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 01:49 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't recall three questions. The three card reading I do is \"this is me, this is the situation, this is the outcome.\" Is that what you were thinking of? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59274410", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 04:01 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yes, that’s it! I misremembered the structure. Thank you so much!"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59263146", "title": "Question about scrying mirror", "date": "2026-02-17 12:32 am", "user": "jimonkypunky", "content": "Hello!<br/><br/>In my parents house I found a small round disk of obsidian that resembled a black scying mirror, and I thought it was a good idea to start a practice of Scrying with it in an open lodge of the GSF. During the opening ceremony, I accidentally knocked over the disk and it broke. I took it as a sign and I'm now uncertain that I must get another one.<br/><br/>1) Should I start with a classic crystal ball and do you have any recommendations for starting the practice?<br/><br/>2) Do you think the knocking over of the obsidian disk was indeed a sign or just an accident? <br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59269546", "title": "Re: Question about scrying mirror", "date": "2026-02-17 01:54 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) This is usually the best option. Here are some out of copyright texts: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://archive.org/details/crystalgazingit00thomgoog\">https://archive.org/details/crystalgazingit00thomgoog</a><br/><a href=\"https://archive.org/details/rowe-1998-scrying\">https://archive.org/details/rowe-1998-scrying</a><br/><a href=\"https://archive.org/details/keiro-1908-clairvoyance\">https://archive.org/details/keiro-1908-clairvoyance</a><br/><a href=\"https://archive.org/details/zancig-1926-crystal-gazing\">https://archive.org/details/zancig-1926-crystal-gazing</a><br/><a href=\"https://archive.org/details/carrington-1920-crystal-gazing\">https://archive.org/details/carrington-1920-crystal-gazing</a><br/><a href=\"https://archive.org/details/seward-1920-crystal-gazing\">https://archive.org/details/seward-1920-crystal-gazing</a><br/><a href=\"https://archive.org/details/nelson-1928-six-lessons\">https://archive.org/details/nelson-1928-six-lessons</a><br/><a href=\"https://archive.org/details/clayton-1922-crystal-gazing\">https://archive.org/details/clayton-1922-crystal-gazing</a><br/><br/>2) You'd have to do divination to tell. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59271594", "title": "Re: Question about scrying mirror", "date": "2026-02-17 02:26 am", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "One more, which I highly recommend, by Theodore Besterman:<br/><a href=\"https://archive.org/details/bwb_T3-BNI-599\">https://archive.org/details/bwb_T3-BNI-599</a>"}]}, {"id": "cmt59273130", "title": "Re: Question about scrying mirror", "date": "2026-02-17 02:58 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "Piggybacking with a random comment -- I haven't really practiced scrying, but, when thinking about the Mesozoic era of dinosaurs, I had strange images pop into my head, of a setting with tropical plants, a much thicker, humid atmosphere, and the booming sounds of giant herbivore dinosaurs whipping their tails (they must've had a tail-extension to allow this). I'm not sure if this is confabulated nonsense, or a genuine snapshot of life on earth more than 65 million years ago, but it does seem consistent with my research.<br/><br/>What's striking is that I seemingly gained an insight from the distant past, which I'd assume should be difficult. Can this be done without significant training?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59274666", "title": "Re: Question about scrying mirror", "date": "2026-02-17 04:04 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's possible that this is accurate remote viewing. It's also possible that you're tuning into other people's ideas about the Mesozoic -- dinosaurs being the pop culture icon they are, there are a lot of vivid media presentations of that period. Here's one that was famous when I was a kid: <br/>[IMAGE:0]", "images": [{"url": "https://yalealumnimagazine.org/uploads/images/2800028/1337795174/dinos_fullpeabody_300x164_0_0_300.jpg", "local_path": "./data/archive/2026/2026-02-15_10-33PM_Magic_Monday/images/2026-02-17_04_04_am_dinos_fullpeabody_300x164_0_0_300.jpg"}], "replies": [{"id": "cmt59278762", "title": "Re: Question about scrying mirror", "date": "2026-02-17 04:40 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "I see. While that depiction gets some things right, I can see the incorrect standing posture that was so common in the study of dinosaurs until recent decades. They went to lengths to justify a blatantly wrong idea, all because humans walk upright -- another case of science/rationalist being unaware of its biases.<br/><br/>Maybe it's both, who knows. Maybe the pop culture obsession with dinosaurs helped enable an accurate remote viewing. It's just striking to me that I seemingly pulled this off without significant training. Midnight is drawing near, so I won't delve into too many details, but I've read up on the Mesozoic climate, and the properties of large herbivorous dinosaur tails, and my observations add up. As I said, they must've had an extension to enable the whipping effect, a bit like the rattle on a rattlesnake. The air was almost soupy, btw..."}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59264170", "title": "Covid Vaccines from a Spiritual Perspective (the book)", "date": "2026-02-17 12:52 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I hope this is the right forum for this question.  I read this book, that comes from the Steiner people. It has come up before, either here or on the COVID discussion.  It's scary, alright.  But according to the book, other medical interventions are spiritually harmful as well.  Mayer, the author, names many common meds; blood pressure meds, proton pump inhibitors, statins, antibiotics, antipyretics, analgesics, and beta blockers have negative effects on the \"body elementals\" (whatever they are).  I hate to think about cortico-steroids like prednisone, though he doesn't mention them.  I hate to think of cortico-steroids because I'm on long-term prednisone for severe joint inflammation.  This is on p.208-210 of the book.  (I guess going to the Doctor or the drugstore in the 21st century is just a spiritually risky proposition.)  The questions: have you heard any further reactions to this book?  What is your own reaction?  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59269802", "title": "Re: Covid Vaccines from a Spiritual Perspective (the book)", "date": "2026-02-17 01:58 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "First, if he doesn't mention those drugs, don't worry about them. Steiner's followers tend to be very, very detailed! Second, every drug has tradeoffs. If you're comfortable with the effects of the corticosteroids you're on, trust that. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59272362", "title": "Re: Covid Vaccines from a Spiritual Perspective (the book)", "date": "2026-02-17 02:31 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I wouldn't say I'm comfy with them but they are indispensible with PMR.  I'm gradually reducing the dosage, per my PCP.  I'm also making pretty drastic diet changes for PMR.  Thank you for your input.  "}]}, {"id": "cmt59273642", "title": "Re: Covid Vaccines from a Spiritual Perspective (the book)", "date": "2026-02-17 03:15 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(if I may)<br/><br/>I don't know what to make of that kind of Anthroposophical claim, but here is a political-cultural analogy to provide a point of reference for what I take to be the mechanism of the kind of damage they claim happens to the society of body elementals.<br/><br/>https://samzdat.com/2017/05/22/man-as-a-rationalist-animal/#:~:text=Here's%20an%20example<br/><br/>I would link this other example about an indigenous people who sing to their handicrafts, and who find industrial crafts and overflying airplanes to be disruptive to their thus-sacralized world, but I don't remember what they were called and don't know how to look it up.<br/><br/>Sometimes I wonder if there's some compromise solution where you can patch most of whatever problems there may prove to be with artificial mRNA lipid bilayer micelles, so that they only affect the body elementals the way natural RNA lipid bilayer micelles, i.e. coronaviruses (so named because of the corona-like appearance of the micelle under a microscope), do, by singing to them during the manufacturing process. (It seems like ultrasound would be more appropriate to the size of mRNA vaccines, and digital audio processing presents its own problems of technological intermediation similar to mRNA manufacture, so maybe you would have to use analog magnetic tape recordings and play them back real fast?)"}]}, {"id": "cmt59264682", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 01:17 am", "user": "mole_end", "content": "Regarding the CGD Temple altar...<br/><br/>Would it be acceptable to use a wooden incense stick holder rather than a bowl full of sand to hold my stick of incense, and then take the stick out of the holder to circumnambulate? I was thinking maybe the imagery of the cauldron was important.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59270058", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 01:58 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The imagery of the cauldron is important but it's not essential. If it's easier for you to use a wooden holder, do that. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59272106", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 02:28 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, hopefully in time... quick left- field question.  Do you know of any connection between the violin and any deity?  Shadow Rider", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59275178", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 04:08 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In the Renaissance, it was remarkably common to see images of Apollo playing the lira da bracchio, an immediate ancestor of the violin: <br/>[IMAGE:0]<br/>That's the one that comes to mind just now. ", "images": [{"url": "https://musicaantigua.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/dios-apolo-lira-da-braccio.webp", "local_path": "./data/archive/2026/2026-02-15_10-33PM_Magic_Monday/images/2026-02-17_04_08_am_dios-apolo-lira-da-braccio.webp"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59274154", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 03:47 am", "user": "lukeszy", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>I had two big dreams a month or two ago strongly suggesting I should invoke Venus.  I am trying to figure out the best way to do that (or at least a tangential version) as a GSF core curriculum completer.  I think I would prefer to do it with the Communion Ceremony, if appropriate.  Could I do something like 7 ceremonies with the intent to make myself more lovable followed by 7 ceremonies to bring a congenial woman into my life?  I am quite eccentric, so I think it would take a lot to make a congenial relationship happen.  I recognize there is small chance I'm abusing the intent of the Communion Ceremony, but the section for intent/target of blessing seems quite open ended to me.  <br/><br/>If the Communion Ceremony is appropriate, is the number of performances I stated appropriate?<br/><br/>I can think of like 20 ways to do this without the Communion Ceremony, but it find it quite powerful, and like I said, I might need the big guns for this.<br/><br/>I know this isn't invoking Venus in a traditional way, but the intent would be Venusian.<br/><br/>Thanks,<br/><br/>Luke Z", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59275690", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 04:13 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You can certainly use the communion ceremony that way. I'd recommend invoking the energies of Spirit Below in the name of Venus Physica, the Roman title of Venus as a force of nature, and the energies of Spirit above in the name of Venus Caelestia, celestial Venus, the Roman title of Venus as a spiritual power. Do each of the workings on a Friday. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59276202", "title": "clumsy", "date": "2026-02-17 04:16 am", "user": "kallianeira", "content": "<br/>Dear JMG,<br/><br/>sorry if I am late for MM.<br/>I just read your reply last week to say that if one's Mercury is afflicted one is likely to be \"too clumsy or mentally rigid to handle magic\".<br/><br/>Could you explain the need for dexterity please?<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59277226", "title": "Re: clumsy", "date": "2026-02-17 04:22 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you have trouble with eye-hand coordination, tracing complex sigils in the air and other manual operations will be very difficult for you. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59280810", "title": "Re: clumsy", "date": "2026-02-17 04:56 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "I have an afflicted Mercury. I do have issues with hand-eye coordination, but they're not severe. I learned to drive; however, I have difficulty multitasking when driving (i.e. I cannot text while driving).<br/><br/>Patrick H"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59278506", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 04:38 am", "user": "temporaryreality", "content": "I wonder if you’re aware of any mythological evidence or “reports” of our previous Saturn-Neptune conjunction. (I recognize there’s unlikely to be an exact correlation since Neptune as a planet hadn’t been discovered yet, maybe there’s a rhyme?).   <br/><br/>Though this is playing out over longer-than-lifetime time scales, do you have any advice for ways to work with the conjunction as (short-lived) individuals? Does mitigating negative effects and strengthening the positive ones require or depend on one’s natal chart?<br/><br/>Thank you!<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59279530", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-17 04:45 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, I haven't seen any discussion of this. As for working with the conjunction, that depends entirely on your natal chart. Find the location of 0 degrees Aries in the chart, and that'll tell you what house will get the direct effects; find the locations of Saturn and Neptune, their condition, and their aspects, and that'll give you the broader context. For example, in my natal chart Saturn is well dignified, Neptune is strong but in mixed dignity, and the two are square each other; I expect some very significant shifts in the way these two planetary forces relate to each other in my life, and I know which houses to watch. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59280042", "title": "Death cleansing", "date": "2026-02-17 04:53 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi, JMG,<br/><br/>I’m the one who wrote to you last week about my mom being in home hospice. She passed on Friday evening. I did take your advice and do prayers for her, and a Buddhist friend is sponsoring pujas for her. So thank you for the suggestion.<br/><br/>She died at home, and I’m wondering whether an event like this leaves an imprint on the home environment. If so, should some type of cleansing be done, and what would you suggest?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59281066", "title": "Re: Death cleansing", "date": "2026-02-17 04:57 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "First, please accept my condolences. That's always a difficult thing to go through. <br/><br/>Second, yes, alongside material cleansing, the space should be cleared and cleansed spiritually. Your Buddhist friend may know ceremonies for this. If not, burn some frankincense and call upon the deity or deities you work with to cleanse, purify and bless the space. "}]}]}, {"title": "Magic Monday", "url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/360126.html", "year": "2026", "month": "02", "day": "22", "time": "09-52PM", "comments": [{"id": "cmt59303870", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 05:02 am", "user": "brenainn", "content": "So, I had a dream last night and I think it is related to the very recent experience I mentioned elsewhere. In the dream, I was in some kind of wooded area with some friends. Not friends in real life, just a sense in my dream that the men with me were friends. Anyway, a monster comes out of nowhere and starts killing us. We were all armed with conventional weapons: guns and knives. The entity made short order of us, and I began running like heck, finally getting into a clearing. The entity was right behind me, and I turned around to face it. I decided fighting was pointless, and I dropped my weapons at its feet, then knelt down for the killing blow. The entity walked away, sparing me. I then woke up, still feeling a palpable sense of terror. <br/><br/>I got the powerful impression from this dream that the work I am called to requires me to surrender my real world weapons collection, save for a small obsidian blade knife that I bought on a whim last Fall but now I’m thinking it is meant to be a primary ceremonial tool. I suspect it relates also to my spirit guide, who belonged to a pacifistic religion during life. I know that dream interpretation is not something you really do, but if the commentariat has any thoughts, it would be most welcome.<br/><br/>Are there any notable occult works on non-violence? I’d be interested in diving into what the Western occult traditions have to say, though my metaphysics and ethics is increasingly Eastern (for whatever reason, Jain Ahimsa teachings seem to be part of some personal synchronicities.).<br/><br/>Such strange times.<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59304638", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 05:17 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "First, in your place I would do quite a bit of reflection and journaling on the monster -- what it means, what it symbolizes, what made it attack you and your friends and what made it spare you. This sounds like the kind of dream that begs to be unpacked through that kind of approach. <br/><br/>Second, I don't happen to know of anything that discusses nonviolence in the Western occult traditions, but others may be able to help you. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59315646", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 04:45 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "Thank you. I've already begun journaling/reflection on this dream. I think it is key to the next steps for me. As far as the Western occult tradition, if no one has any suggestions, I think my current source of teachings (Jain, primarily, and some Theravada) will be adequate enough. I'm not sure my path is easily placed within one particular tradition or set of related traditions."}]}, {"id": "cmt59305662", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 06:49 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Well, that does sound like a truly wonderful dream to have experienced! I find the most insightful dream readings tend to come from interpreting every aspect of one's dream to be a metaphor for some aspect of one's self. That wilderness (similar to an ocean or a cavern) could be some wild, unexplored part of your subconscious/unconscious. <br/><br/>How many friends were you with there? If three, I would lean towards considering them to be those aspects of your soul that dwell on each of the planes we inhabit. If four, then one of the five of you would likely be your higher self, to round out the soul’s mix. If your posse does map onto various constituent parts of your soul, then that was quite a potent dream, since your nemesis was fully able to weaken and isolate you from your greater soul until you chose to turn, face, and honor the monster that had welled up within you.<br/><br/>Generically, that monster is a dead ringer for your Shadow; however, the transformative power of any dream lies in unpacking its specificity. What have you been working through recently? What have you been fighting? What has seemed too wild and threatening to face or acknowledge? What have you resisted exploring within? Alternatively, what did the monster look like, act like, who or what did it remind you of? Likewise, how did you feel when you knelt down to it, when it walked away, when you woke up, and when you now reflect over the dream? <br/><br/>Something magical shifted within you last night. Can you sense what is beginning to move into new alignments? Which plates are drifting; which glaciers calving; which flows might be changing their course? Kneeling down before your dreaded enemy and offering up your weapons of resistance naturally transforms that feared monster into a familiar mentor. You've been traveling together for such a long time, you might as well begin availing yourself of its hard-earned wisdom!<br/><br/>— Christophe", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59316926", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 05:02 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "Including myself, there were seven people in the group of friends attacked by the monster. My normal go to for interpreting something like this dream would be Jungian concepts. That said, I've done considerable Shadow, and at this point Anima, work. I've gotten to know my Shadow very well.<br/><br/>The monster itself was serpentine in appearance. Humanoid serpentine, if that makes sense. It was very fast, very brutal, and quite merciless. The other six men in my group were quickly and brutally shredded by the monster. It pursued me almost without any noise. When I reached the open clearing in the dream, I thought at first I had outrun it. I had not, and it was there behind me.<br/><br/>I'm not sure how relevant this will be but ever since I was a little boy, I've had dreams where someone or something was attacking me, and I'd have a revolver on me. But whenever I tried to fire the revolver at the threat, each and every bullet was a dud. A few rare dreams have occurred where the weapon did fire, with minimal effect on the attacker. In this my latest dream, I never actually fired at the creature as I couldn't get a clear shot. It killed my friends very, very quickly (and was impervious to their weapons, anyway). After the short but brutal slaughter, I ran off and it caught up to me. In the dream, the dropping of my weapons at its feet felt like an offering to it, and it felt like it placated it (so long as I didn't pick up the weapons again).<br/><br/>As for what I've been working through as of late, well, that's quite the story. Not easy to fit in a coherent post. I've been experiencing increasing communications from spirits, and then the same day this dream happened (or, well, happened a few hours before I fell asleep and then had this dream) I had the most bizarre experience of my life. I had a visionary experience where I was dropped into the underworld, had some kind of painful ritual performed with a knife, had a large snake crawl inside me, and then I dissolved into the serpent, then transformed back into a man, and then I was returned to the surface world to encounter a large eagle.<br/><br/>Like I said, very bizarre, and it can't be a coincidence that the dream followed this vision.", "edit_time": "2026-02-23 05:11 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59323582", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 05:55 pm", "user": "jprussell", "content": "For what it's worth, a visionary experience that involves you being cut up/discorporated/re-incorporated, especially in the underworld, reminds me very strongly of descriptions of shamanic initiations. I don't recall if those are/were associated with a singular, specific monster, but very often the cutting/tearing apart is seen to be done by demons or monsters. If any of this seems relevant or interesting, you might check out Mircea Eliade's <i>Shamanism</i>.<br/><br/>Whatever the case, good luck to you, it sounds like you're dealing with some intense stuff!<br/>Jeff", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59328190", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 06:30 pm", "user": "kenkyuusha", "content": "i am reading a book on shamanism now, as far as i understand this phenomenon you describe is called \"shamanic disease\", where spirits are believed to torture the person because they want them to become a shaman, and if a person declines, the disease might even become mortal. this is a very high level and imprecise overview though"}, {"id": "cmt59329470", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 06:49 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "JMG recommended Eliade's book a few weeks ago. I started reading it on Sunday, the day after the experience. Uncanny, really, what I'm seeing in it."}]}, {"id": "cmt59330238", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 06:55 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Spitballing, but:<br/><br/>&gt; the dropping of my weapons at its feet felt like an offering to it, and it felt like it placated it (so long as I didn't pick up the weapons again).<br/><br/>1. In international relations theory, there is a concept called the \"security dilemma\" or \"Thucydides trap\", where acquiring destructive power to prevent future attacks from feared others who have power provokes others to fearfully either attack, if they have power, or acquire power if they don't. In this interpretation, the monster wouldn't represent a feared other so much as the entire dynamic.<br/><br/>2. As 1., but for a vaguer concept of operating on a metaphorical plane on which that kind of violence, however imagined as self-defensive it may be at the time, exists.<br/><br/>3. Something about the way you phrased that puts me in mind of the monster acting that way because if considered that particular kind of armed violence or prospect of armed violence to be a pollution."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59308222", "title": "facing your fears", "date": "2026-02-23 12:40 pm", "user": "randomactsofkarmasc", "content": "In Spiritual Alchemy, one of the things you must do is face your fears.  Dreams are a way of facing your fears without being in physical danger.  I agree with JMG that analyzing the monster is important... I think it represents one of your fears.  It isn't a physical fear, which is why you realized your physical weapons would be useless in defending yourself against it.<br/><br/>Forests often symbolize the Body (and a clearing in the forest would represent a conscious awareness).  Did you ever get into a clearing, or were you in the wooded area the entire dream?<br/><br/>(If you want to chat offline, my dreamwidth account accepts messages.  And if you'd like me to do an Oracle reading on your dream, I am happy to.  Readings are free.)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59317182", "title": "Re: facing your fears", "date": "2026-02-23 05:04 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "I was able to get into an open clearing (though it seems to have been within the forest itself) before I finally turned around to see the monster still on my tail. It was in this clearing that I surrendered my weapons, and the monster walked away.<br/><br/>Would be happy to have you do an Oracle reading. It always helps to get some outside divination done."}]}, {"id": "cmt59314366", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 04:35 pm", "user": "neptunesdolphins", "content": "I had visions of The Mothman, who kept forecasting doom for me. I ended up with an altar to Him, and discovered in working with Him, he did warn of coming events. I think maybe the monster if you can sketch the entity may be an actual \"monster\" with folklore behind it. After researching The Mothman of West Va, I discovered all sorts of hidden monsters out there beyond the Swamp Ape and the Jersey Devil.<br/><br/>The obsidian is a clue as to the lore of the monster - if you identify it - it could be Meso-American. That is all I have.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59317438", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 05:06 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "I'm certain it is Mesoamerican. That much does seem clear to me.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59345854", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 10:59 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The only Mesoamerican serpent-person entities I find in a quick web search are the Vision Serpent<br/>     https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vision_Serpent<br/>and our old friend Kulkulcan<br/>     https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kukulkan<br/><br/>I know from earlier researches that the Mayan god Chaac also had some serpentine characteristics.<br/>     https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chaac<br/><br/>I hope this is helpful.<br/><br/>- Cicada Grove"}, {"id": "cmt59349694", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-24 12:43 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This is embarrassing, but it would be remiss of me to not note:<br/><br/>&gt; The monster itself was serpentine in appearance. Humanoid serpentine, if that makes sense.<br/><br/>&gt; It was very fast<br/><br/>&gt; very brutal, and quite merciless.<br/><br/>&gt; I'm certain it is Mesoamerican. That much does seem clear to me.<br/><br/>This lines up strikingly with a splice of the descriptions of Koraidon and Miraidon (from <i>korai</i> \"ancient\" / <i>mirai</i> \"future\", <i>raido</i> loanword for \"ride\", and <i>don</i> Gr. \"tooth\" as metonymy for a dinosaur species), the two mascot monster species of the games Pokémon Scarlet / Violet respectively. \"Very fast\" lines up with the monsters' mobility and speed; they have two signature attack techniques based on colliding with an opponent at extreme speed. \"Brutal\" lines up with the primal Koraidon being described in its opposite game's monster index as \"far burlier and more ferocious\" than their common base species, and \"merciless\" lines up with the robotic Miraidon being correspondingly described as \"far more ruthless and powerful\". Both monsters have Mesoamerican-serpent-style large eyes attached to the sides of blunt heads and dramatic scute-like marks, and Koraidon also has feathers (Miraidon instead has plasma forming plumage-like shapes). The two games are set in a region mostly resembling and referencing the Iberian peninsula, but with some Mesoamerican influences and references, notably the Galápagos islands and the Chicxulub impact site (due to the games' background themes of evolutionary parallels, alternate evolutionary histories, and extinction events). The most obvious discrepant point is that both monsters strongly resemble two-wheeled vehicles (which is partly a reference to Spain's biking culture and partly a reimagining of the series' traditional bicycle).<br/><br/>While the most visible Koraidon / Miraidon character in their respective game is protective toward the player character trainer and other humans (due to complicated circumstances involving a trained monster of the base bicycle-like dragon species and<br/><details><summary>(click to drop down ending spoilers)</summary>an evolution-harnessing device that's ambiguously either a time machine, a parallel-universe exchange machine, or a hyperstition machine</details>), the endgame antagonist also commands a monster of the same species, who is directly specified as having slain a human — one of only perhaps a dozen identified such monster characters across all 30 years of the Pokémon franchise (though in this case more in an equivalent of manslaughter than murder).<br/><br/>While I'm on synchronicites, in the other threads:<br/><br/>&gt; as though you wanted to know if owning a bicycle was incompatible with listening to old Jethro Tull albums<br/><br/>&gt; the last stone of the central tower of Gaudi's Sagrada Familia was laid on the exact day of the conjunction<br/><br/>Besides a bicycle time-paradox serpent monster, one of the other prominent monsters that the player can receive at the beginning of the game is a fire-touched crocodile whose evolutionary sequence develops mariachi-like and alebrije-like or trencadís-like design elements—trencadís is an artistic medium and style most prominently associated with Antoni Gaudí, especially his dragon sculpture in Parc Güell in Barcelona but also visible on some of the spires of Sagrada Familia. The last evolution stage of this monster's line is called Skeledirge, which adds Día de Muertos-related elements like a calavera pattern down its face and snout. The crocodile's mariachi theme develops into coloration patterns sort of resembling the outfit of a Mexican vocalist, and it acquires a symbiotic plover-like bird made of ghostly fire. As part of its signature attack technique, it gets up on two legs to sing and the bird turns into a microphone to pick up its crooning. I don't know, maybe that isn't quite enough elements to make a synchronicity, since crooners are hardly at all the same thing as prog rockers."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59321278", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 05:21 pm", "user": "hearthculture", "content": "I've had multiple dreams over the last few days that I woke from feeling that it was significant, and having a message in my head that I felt needed to be written down. <br/>For me, when that happens, I ask myself if the message was with me when I woke or if it came after reflection on the dream. If I truly woke up with it (sometimes not even in my voice) then I give it more credence, and entertain acting upon it. I also am cautious about acting quickly and generally ask for signs of confirmation, and then follow up with divination.<br/><br/>Not directly western occultism sources...<br/>Quaker tradition is explicitly non-violent and has produced quite a bit of writing on the topic. As a religion, it also has interesting structures and practices that are less opposed to outside practices like occultism than many other christian religions.<br/><br/>Aikido was founded as peaceful martial art in which the primary goal is protection of one's own self through maintaining balance and structure, with a close secondary goal of protecting one's opponent, using techniques that are intended to minimize violence from both ends. There are multiple philosophical books written by the founder and his students that expound upon that. The founder was a military leader and led a violent life before moving onto this, but many of the ideals and ideas have been helpful to me. I've also incorporated multiple of aikido's body mechanics, energetic principles, and techniques into my occult practices and they've influenced my understanding. Many modern dojos aren't great at functional self protection, but there are a few out there that succeed there. The philosophy is accessible to anyone though.<br/><br/>Judo comes from the same foundation and is called the gentle art, but modern judo is very much a sport and more violent for it. The original writings are interesting though. Jujitsu is similar, with foundational principles that intended to be able to incapacitate an attacker with as little harm as possible, but it's popularity in MMA has shifted it quite a bit.<br/><br/>Wishing you well!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59329726", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 06:50 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "Thank you. I'm familar with Quaker teachings. I'll have to look more into Aikido."}, {"id": "cmt59361726", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-24 04:28 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A good (IMHO) book about radical nonviolence in the Western tradition is \"Amish Grace: How Forgiveness Transcended Tragedy\" by Donald Kraybill, Steven Nolt, and David Weaver-Zercher."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59304126", "title": "Is bridal mysticism compatible with ceremonial magic?", "date": "2026-02-23 05:05 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Greetings from Seattle! <br/>Something I’ve been trying to figure out for a while now is how, if at all, does bridal mysticism (by the likes of Hadewijch, Porete, Mechthild, even Rumi from Sufism can work here) fit in to a Golden Dawn framework.<br/><br/>My question is twofold:<br/>1. Are the two at odds with one another? Could they be complementary? Can a bridal mystic, one who has encountered the Beloved, also practice ceremonial magic? Are there predecessors to the GD with which this mysticism is derived from? Is there any obvious relationship with one another? Am I comparing apples to oranges here?<br/>2. How would the “contact” made between the lover and Beloved/devotee and Divine, be described by the Golden Dawn tradition, and why such contact occurs?<br/><br/>P.S. Just listened to your latest appearance on Plant Cunning podcast - love the idea of “tactical” astrology for daily use! I do hope that publisher ends up snatching up your book!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59304894", "title": "Re: Is bridal mysticism compatible with ceremonial magic?", "date": "2026-02-23 05:25 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Magic and mysticism are radically different -- it's not apples and oranges, it's apples and orangutans! They aren't incompatible, they simply operate on entirely different planes of existence. It's as though you wanted to know if owning a bicycle was incompatible with listening to old Jethro Tull albums. <br/><br/>2) It wouldn't be, because the Golden Dawn system teaches magic, not mysticism. Your relationship to the Divine is not a subject about which magic has anything to say. Your relationship to your own higher potentials as a human being? That's quite another matter, but that's not really something that mysticism deals with in any direct fashion. <br/><br/>That being the case, I'd encourage you to pursue both, each according to its own rules and principles. You clearly have a good knowledge of the mystical literature, very likely better than mine, so I won't presume to offer advice. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59307966", "title": "Re: Is bridal mysticism compatible with ceremonial magic?", "date": "2026-02-23 12:31 pm", "user": "charlieobert", "content": "There is an interesting instance of symbolism I want to raise here as part of this thread.<br/><br/>Eliphaz Levi's drawing of Baphomet is the model for the Devil in many modern tarots. The upward pointing arm says Solve, the downward arm says Coagula.<br/><br/>If you look at the Oswald Wirth drawing of the Devil, the arms are reversed. The downward arm is Solve, the upward is Coagula.<br/><br/>I would suggest that Levi's Baphomet is Magic, and Wirth's Devil is Mysticism.<br/><br/>I could be wrong, but at the very least the difference in symbolism is worth quite a bit of meditation."}, {"id": "cmt59332542", "title": "Re: Is bridal mysticism compatible with ceremonial magic?", "date": "2026-02-23 07:52 pm", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>I've seen the terms magic and mysticism used almost synonymously quite a bit. Is this simply a contemporary Western hangup, perhaps stemming from James Frazier's insistence that magic is simply a primitive form of religion, or is there something deeper to it?</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59333566", "title": "Re: Is bridal mysticism compatible with ceremonial magic?", "date": "2026-02-23 07:56 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I see it as one offshoot of the utter ignorance and indifference with which most modern intellectuals treat every kind of spirituality other than their own, if they have one. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59344574", "title": "Re: Is bridal mysticism compatible with ceremonial magic?", "date": "2026-02-23 10:51 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In the case of bridal mysticism, specifically, I can see our host's point about it being a very different thing from magic.  But mysticism as a whole encompasses many different approaches, some of which, it seems to me, have significant points of contact with some approaches to magic.  <br/><br/>A book that has influenced my understanding and practice of mysticism is Jess Byron Hollenback's \"Mysticism: Experience, Response, and Empowerment\" (U. Penn. Press). He studies the \"...cross-cultural significance of recollective practices (methods of one-pointedly focusing attention) within the totality of the lives of mystics.  ...not only do recollective practices generate mystical states of awareness, but they also play a critical role in generating the extraordinary phenomena that often accompany those states of consciousness.  ...this book contains a lengthy analysis of a common...accompaniment of recollective practice and mystical experience, a phenomenon that I have called the \"empowerment\" of a mystic's imagination, thoughts, emotions, and volitions.  ...Under conditions of recollective empowerment, these faculties not only objectify themselves so that they form the visionary landscape that the mystic perceives, but they also exhibit noetic possibilities, that is, they can sometimes function as supernormal channels of perception, locomotion, and communication.\"<br/><br/>The author, unlike many academic scholars of mysticism, pays careful attention to the practices of shamanism and similar tribal religious / occult practices from around the world as part of what he considers mysticism, along with the study of more 'classical' forms of mysticism.<br/><br/>To me, the passage I quoted above exhibits some significant similarities to Eliphas Levi's descriptions of magical practice, as well as Dion Fortune's definition of magic.  I wonder if perhaps the difference between mysticism and magic is less about methods and abilities, and more about how the results are interpreted and used.<br/><br/>Winifred", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59362238", "title": "Re: Is bridal mysticism compatible with ceremonial magic?", "date": "2026-02-24 04:31 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "OP here - I could see how mystical practice could rhyme with magical practice, and thank you for that book rec I will definitely be checking it out. IIRC Dion Fortune (of whom I am a fan!) also distinguishes the mystic apart from magician since their end goals were different. Still, magicians can have mystic experiences, I’ve just not heard of (bridal) mystics becoming ceremonial magicians or getting into the occult as a natural consequence of Divine encounter but surely it’s happened before? I don’t know."}]}, {"id": "cmt59361470", "title": "Re: Is bridal mysticism compatible with ceremonial magic?", "date": "2026-02-24 04:20 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank so much John. So sorry this is very late. I had a suspicion that the two were not necessarily related, not even in a great-grand-uncle-thrice-removed sort of way. Even if I broadened the question to whether or not Christian mysticism and Christian occultism overlap they’re just two different subjects altogether. But I am relieved that I don’t have to set either one at odds with another. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59362494", "title": "Re: Is bridal mysticism compatible with ceremonial magic?", "date": "2026-02-24 04:32 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There's no opposition between them, nor any necessary connection; down through the centuries a great many people have practiced one, or the other, or both. Go ye therefore and do whichever of these works for you. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59304382", "title": "Charity?", "date": "2026-02-23 05:11 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear Mr Greer,<br/>I have been a long-time follower. I have worked my way through your ‘learning magic’ books. I have a daily practice. I am familiar with the daily LRBP. I meditate, do some tarot and I have a small prayer altar dedicated to the Archangel Michael. Just background information.<br/><br/>My parents are hoping to sell their current home/business combo as they’re getting too old to run things. They’re in a place where getting a buyer is very difficult – not impossible. They’re also very conservative Christians and believe that it will sell if it’s God’s will. Fair enough. I’m on the other side of the world, and if they don’t get it sold for a good price it will eventually become my problem.<br/> <br/>What can I realistically do to help things in the right direction? I have been praying and meditating – but have been wondering along the lines of planetary charity maybe? If that is a suitable option, which ones, and what is the nature of the charity? Any other suggestions?<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59305150", "title": "Re: Charity?", "date": "2026-02-23 05:28 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, you could certainly do planetary charity. I'd normally suggest Saturn, both as the ruler of real estate and as the planetary patron of old people, but he's in his fall in Aries right now and might not be good to invoke -- and of course there is also a business involved. Since that's the case, planetary charity toward Mercury would be a good option. If you've done enough magic to know how to make and consecrate a talisman, a talisman of Mercury might also be very helpful. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59307710", "title": "Re: Charity?", "date": "2026-02-23 11:42 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "(Not OP)<br/>Mercury is currently in Pisces.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59313086", "title": "Re: Charity?", "date": "2026-02-23 04:27 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I know, but he's nimble. Saturn isn't. I've worked with Mercury in various conditions, including detriment and fall, and still gotten good results -- but Saturn is what he is, and you have to wait. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59327422", "title": "Re: Charity?", "date": "2026-02-23 06:17 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "Would the next time Mars enters Capricorn be an appropriate time to invoke Saturn for planetary charity, because of mutual reception?<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59330750", "title": "Re: Charity?", "date": "2026-02-23 07:21 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You could certainly try. Remember that all these things have to be tested by experiment; astrological magic is an empirical science, and that means that reasoning from first principles is helpful but never conclusive. "}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59311294", "title": "Re: Charity?", "date": "2026-02-23 03:38 pm", "user": "homeopathic_meditations", "content": "I don't know if your conservative Christians parents will stomach Catholicism any better than occultism, but just in case...<br/><br/>St. Joseph (that Joseph, Jesus' stepdad) is very well know as the saint patron of both families and blue collar workers. But something I just found out is that he's also the saint patron of realtors! Seeking his intercession would be a traditional way Catholics would approach this matter.<br/><br/>* If your parents only do prayers: you may invoque St. Joseph to seek first the clarity of mind and will to decide how and when are you putting the house/business on the market, then change the intention to bring in good buyers, keep fraudsters at bay, and smooth the negociations. As a resource you may check this link: <a href=\"https://www.perfectprayers.com/st-joseph-prayers-for-selling-house/\">https://www.perfectprayers.com/st-joseph-prayers-for-selling-house/</a> (I have only given it a cursory check, but nothing looks out of place to me).<br/><br/>* If they are OK with ritual: you may bury a small St. Joseph's statue or medal in the house (facing the house, if possible in the front yard and near the \"For Sale\" sign) wrapped in a small piece of cloth. This is similar to the better know St. Antony's statue ritual, and thus it is customary to put the statue upside-down for speedy results; I have never liked that and feel it is increadibly stupid to try to bully the very powerful being you are requesting help from, but it's a widespread belief for some reason. I don't know what would the effect be if you place it one way or the other. In any case, you should pray to St. Joseph when burying the statue, and keep praying every day until the sale is complete.<br/><br/>"}]}, {"id": "cmt59305406", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 06:05 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, a few questions:<br/><br/>1. In Learning Ritual Magic you recommend six books to study as I do the lessons. Would your book Revisioning the Tree of Life also be a good choice as a companion book? It's become one of my favorite books on Cabala.<br/><br/>2. You've stated that SoP is incompatible with a Hermetic practice involving the LBRP/Middle Pillar as daily rituals. By this do you mean that you shouldn't swap the LBRP out for the SoP within a larger Hermetic ritual/working, or that a Hermetic practitioner should not do SoP _at all_ because it will cause some kind of discord? I'm working on a Hermetic/GD study track, hence reading LRM, but I also have a strong affinity for the SoP.<br/><br/>3. Have you heard reports of any students who have worked through the LRM study track while at the same time doing the Heathen Golden Dawn by Isaac Hill? I'm going that route currently, nearing the Thrall initiation in HGD while at chapter 2 of LRM. I've found it to work well so far, with HGD forming the core while LRM fills in some more meditative and study practices, but I'm still early into the process. Does this approach sound good to you or do you foresee problems?<br/><br/>Thanks for reading.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59313342", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 04:31 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) No, because it uses a very different set of symbolism for the Tree. Just as it's not a good idea to try to learn two different foreign languages at the same time, because you'll get them mixed up, it's not a good idea to study two different versions of the Cabala at the same time. <br/><br/>2) They use different energies in different ways. Once you've been doing ceremonial magic for a while and your subtle body has built up some resilience, you can do workings of both kinds at different times, but in the early stages of training I really do recommend one or the other. <br/><br/>3) Here again, you gain nothing by trying to do two things at once -- it's as though you tried to drive north and south at the same time. Do one, finish it, and then do the other. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59305918", "title": "The musical mystery of Rosslyn Chapel", "date": "2026-02-23 07:24 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>I'm studying sound therapy and have been pleasantly surprised how much of the content touches on some of my favourite occult themes, including the secrets in the design of the pyramids and hidden Masonic teachings. Apparently there are 213 cubes in the ceiling which have simple patterns that look remarkably like the patterns made in the sand vibrating on a Chladni plate when particular musical notes are played. A music teacher by the name of Thomas Mitchell and his son Stuart took this idea and ran with it, decoded the symbols and produced a musical work, the Rosslyn Motet. Have you come across this work before?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59313598", "title": "Re: The musical mystery of Rosslyn Chapel", "date": "2026-02-23 04:31 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, and it sounds fascinating. Thank you for the info! "}, {"id": "cmt59339966", "title": "Re: The musical mystery of Rosslyn Chapel", "date": "2026-02-23 09:46 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do you have any books you might recommend? Sounds like interesting stuff!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59353022", "title": "Re: The musical mystery of Rosslyn Chapel", "date": "2026-02-24 01:38 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "None, I'm afraid. Just this website:<br/><br/>https://www.sylviavillamusic.com/blog/cymatics-amp-the-rosslyn-chapel-music-cypher"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59306430", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 07:59 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Does the astral body have energy channels like the etheric body?<br/><br/>What causes blockages in energy channels?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59313854", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 04:33 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) No, it's not that well developed yet. It has flows and currents -- they haven't yet narrowed and focused down into channels. <br/><br/>2) All kinds of things. Emotional issues, mental blocks, too much physical tension, and so on down a long list. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59306942", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 08:07 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear Mr. Greer,<br/>I hope you are well. Wishing you a good start to the week!<br/><br/>I am finishing an academic book on Cinema.<br/>Do you have any magical tips or advice for the book’s release?<br/>Any specific day of the week, perhaps some hoodoo work?<br/><br/>Thank you in advance!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59314110", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 04:33 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you can, have it released on a Wednesday when the Moon is waxing. As far as hoodoo, well, how much experience do you have with that? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59329982", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 06:51 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hoodoo? Hmm, I’d say beginner to intermediate!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59331006", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 07:24 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In that case, before the release, get an orange candle and some Crown of Success oil, or any similar hoodoo oil that encourages success. The day of the release, during the hour of Mercury, dress the candle with the oil, light it, and pray to the Mercurial deity, angel, or saint of your choice that the book will be well received by its audience. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59307454", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 10:07 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If Gopi Krishna's books weren't enough of a reason not to poke the kundalini serpent, there's also this: https://www.salon.com/2013/03/17/my_tantric_awakening_turned_me_off_sex/<br/><br/>If someone does get kundalini syndrome, one solution I've heard is to do tai chi to give the excess energy somewhere safe to go. <br/><br/>Does western occultism have its own solution?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59314878", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 04:43 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) What a hot mess. The author sneers at the spiritual dimensions of the process, ignored every safeguard he could have gotten from traditional sources, went chasing after kundalini for no better reason than to get his rocks off, and now he's whining because he damaged his etheric system so badly that the life force won't flow into the sexual channels any more. He's fortunate. Some people drop stone cold dead when they mess with kundalini with that much clueless arrogance. <br/><br/>2) That would work well, because the Chinese teachings circulate energy up the back and down the front of the torso, and then out and back through the limbs. It's got its risks but by and large it's gentler and safer than the Indian approach. <br/><br/>3) No, we didn't manage to preserve that through the years of persecution. Most Western occult teachings take care of the issue by using very gentle, indirect ways to coax the kundalini to flow, starting with just a little at a time and building from there only as the channels become more resilient. It's slow but it works. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59333310", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 07:54 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The author Janet Hardy is actually a woman.<br/><br/>The most disturbing thing is they've never brought out a second edition of <i>Radical Ecstasy</i> with any warning about how dangerous chasing such peak experiences can be, with the benefit of hindsight. In the first and still current edition it's described in positive terms with only a minor reference to the vertigo, mainly attributed to the stress of writing the book.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59333822", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 07:58 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Interesting. That sort of brash cluelessness is far more often seen among guys. Still, so noted. <br/><br/>2) I wish I could say I was surprised. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59308734", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 01:07 pm", "user": "thinking_turtle", "content": "<p>To share, for those who wonder what LBRH, ADF, or EOTCR mean, a <a href=\"https://thinking-turtle.dreamwidth.org/tag/abbreviation\">list of abbreviations used on Ecopsophia</a>.  And here is a <a href=\"https://thinking-turtle.dreamwidth.org/tag/books\">list of the books our host published so far</a>.</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59315134", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 04:43 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this as always. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59308990", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 01:08 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,<br/><br/>1) Is there an equivalent concept in Western occultism to the Buddhist concept and experience of sunyata or emptiness?<br/><br/>2) The latest eclipse forecast you did notes a pattern called a Wedge. Is there a name for a pattern which is like a box? Four planets, with two short sides (sextiles) and two long sides (trines), with oppositions criss-crossing through the center of the box.<br/><br/>Thank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59315390", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 04:45 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Yes. There are a variety of Western labels for it; the Unmanifest is one, and the Hebrew word Ain (literally \"not\") is another. <br/><br/>2) It's called the Rectangle, or (if you like fancier terms) the Mystic Rectangle. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59309246", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 02:13 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Does someone's karma and horoscope align or can the influences clash?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59315902", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 04:45 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The horoscope always expresses the karma you're going to have to face in that life. If there's an apparent clash, it's usually because the astrologer misinterpreted the chart. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59309502", "title": "Dolmen Arch", "date": "2026-02-23 02:34 pm", "user": "trubrujah", "content": "Here is the latest update from the Dolmen Arch group work:<br/><a href=\"https://thelongdescent.substack.com/p/color-breathing-exercises\">https://thelongdescent.substack.com/p/color-breathing-exercises</a>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59316158", "title": "Re: Dolmen Arch", "date": "2026-02-23 04:46 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this as always! "}]}, {"id": "cmt59310014", "title": "player rope and more", "date": "2026-02-23 02:57 pm", "user": "kenkyuusha", "content": "Hello JMG, thank you for this and all the best to you!<br/><br/>1/ I have reached a lesson in LRM where the Middle Pillar (MP) is introduced. Have been doing it for a week now, noticed right away that unlike QC and LBRP, which started providing some \"feedback\" or \"response\" with practice, the MP has a very strong positive response for me right away. Is it because the ritual is more powerful by itself and not banishing, but more like \"charging\" or the state of my system has improved since it is 3 months of everyday occult practice? or both? :)<br/><br/>2/ today i have finally found a praying rope on the local market. it looks like a greek or russian version, komboskini/chotki, there are 100 nodes divided into 4 sections of 25, and in the middle there is a brush. overall looks exactly like this (<a href=\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/8b/Komboskini_300_knots.jpg\">https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/8b/Komboskini_300_knots.jpg</a>). I suspect it was used before, so i wanted to clean it from previous energies and performed LBRP + MP next to it. Is it enough? I was thinking of charging it more, to make it a kind of talisman for me, would you approve of this? If so, makes sense to do that with the strongest planet in my natal card? <br/><br/>3/ i have noticed some confusion regarding the praying process. since i am not religious, who should i adress my prayers (and should there be someone to address them to in general?) i read in the Occult Philosophy Workbook that Sun Logos is what governs our corner of the Universe, and the spark we have inside us, it is a part of this Sun Logos, correct? So it would make sense to address the Sun in the prayers? or YHVH? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59316670", "title": "Re: player rope and more", "date": "2026-02-23 05:00 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It's both. Regular practice of the Cabalistic Cross and Pentagram ritual will clear away a lot of etheric and astral crud, making your subtle bodies more sensitive and responsive to energies, and the Middle Pillar is a very robust practice, a strong and balanced invocation of spiritual forces. <br/><br/>2) I don't recommend consecrating it as a talisman. You've banished over it, now use it in your prayers and it'll pick up quite a robust charge from that. <br/><br/>3) You can pray to anybody you like! It's a very big universe and there are many beings higher than humanity. Yes, you can pray to the Solar Logos, or to YHVH, or to the Divine, or whatever name or term you prefer to use for the spiritual presence that guides your destiny. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59310270", "title": "Radionics", "date": "2026-02-23 03:10 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "About radionics, a broad question and a narrow one:<br/><br/>a) what are the best books that review the history of the field and explain its technology and theory?<br/><br/>b) Would you or any commentators be willing to share observations about the work of R. R. Rife and the modern machines inspired by his efforts?<br/><br/>Many thanks,<br/><br/>Gray Hat", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59317694", "title": "Re: Radionics", "date": "2026-02-23 05:06 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I wish I knew of any good general book on the subject. If anyone else has one to suggest, I'm all ears. <br/><br/>2) I haven't worked with Rife's technology. It's not radionics -- he was using radio waves of specific frequencies to set up destructive resonances in cancer cells and kill them. Rife's theory is quite plausible, since radio waves can in fact damage cells and do so in very specific ways. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59353534", "title": "Re: Radionics", "date": "2026-02-24 01:45 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "On 2, nice synchronicity. This is another topic that came up in my sound therapy course. People are still doing it. I watched a talk by Dr Anthony Holland who used Oscillating Pulsed Electric Fields (OPEF) broadcast by an enclosed gas plasma antenna to find the resonant frequencies (in practice, a pair of frequencies is used) of cancer and MRSA cells and burst them while leaving other nearby cells unaffected.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59354558", "title": "Re: Radionics", "date": "2026-02-24 02:28 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Glad to hear this. It's a very promising field of work, and it sucks that the chemical pharmaceutics industry has been so enthusiastic and effective about shoving it into the closet. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59310526", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 03:12 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Funny meme, JMG! 😹<br/>Astrologically, what would be a good time to file for divorce?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59317950", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 05:07 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If it's a friendly divorce and you want to keep it that way, file in the day and hour of Jupiter; that will encourage everyone involved to be generous and kind. If it's a hostile divorce and you just want out, file in the day and hour of Mars."}]}, {"id": "cmt59310782", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 03:22 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How much do different kinds of physical training affect the etheric body? For example would a marathon runner and a powerlifter have significantly different energy bodies? Also if someone has altered their metabolism to become fat-adapted - where their body runs primarily on fat rather than carbohydrate - would that have an etheric effect?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59318206", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 05:09 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Those are fascinating questions that would have to be settled by experimentation, and as far as I know the experiments haven't been done yet. "}, {"id": "cmt59320766", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 05:20 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "\"Also if someone has altered their metabolism to become fat-adapted - where their body runs primarily on fat rather than carbohydrate - would that have an etheric effect?\"<br/><br/>It is known that fasting, hard labor over long periods of time, and vegetarian diets alter the body to increase fat burning; it is also known that sweets, which are widely known to dull the inner senses, decrease it. Fasting, hard labor, and vegetarian diets are also all known to increase inner plane sensitivity, which at the very least suggests a link here.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59334590", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 08:02 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The fasting and hard labour route is different from what I heard. I got the concept from Phil Maffetone's <i>The Big Book of Endurance Training and Racing</i>. He says the way to do it is to eat a medium protein, low carbohydrate, high fat diet, and do low stress aerobic exercise with a heart rate of 180 minus your age (plus or minus five or ten depending on your health and training history). If you work above that intensity you start burning glycogen instead of fat."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59311038", "title": "Correspondences of relationships", "date": "2026-02-23 03:27 pm", "user": "vitranc", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/>I am trying to order my relationships to the planetary correspondences. So for I have;<br/>Moon - children, hunters<br/>Mars - ( myself )<br/>Mercury - friends, children, radio club<br/>Jupiter - family, neigbourhood community ( because it gathers around a private neigbourhood chapel )<br/>Venus - wife, family<br/>Saturn - elderly, farmers<br/>Sun - ( myself)<br/><br/>I know some e frise are double, that is because I am not sure where they sit.<br/>Is this concevable? Where could I get a good source on planetary correspondences for people, groups and organisations.<br/><br/>Best regards,<br/>V<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59318462", "title": "Re: Correspondences of relationships", "date": "2026-02-23 05:09 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Interesting. I don't recall seeing any discussion of this, however. Anyone else? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59328446", "title": "Re: Correspondences of relationships", "date": "2026-02-23 06:30 pm", "user": "vitranc", "content": "Well it is a personal contemplation, but I wanted to go in the direction of planetsry rulerships.<br/>Example: Saturn rules the elderly, the Sun rules officers, Mars the soldiers…<br/><br/>I wanted to categorise persons, relationships and groups in my social ecosystem."}]}, {"id": "cmt59323070", "title": "Re: Correspondences of relationships", "date": "2026-02-23 05:47 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I might suggest looking more into the houses in astrology which fit this very well. Otherwise this seems to me a bit of a stretch. <br/>A friend"}, {"id": "cmt59327166", "title": "Re: Correspondences of relationships", "date": "2026-02-23 06:16 pm", "user": "isaac_hill", "content": "From my training in Vedic astrology, each planet signifies multiple things: Moon is mother, Mars is also brothers. Jupiter is also priest or teacher, Saturn is also people in poverty, as well as workers, Venus is also sisters, Sun is also father. These are the natural significations. <br/><br/>In your particular chart, different house lords will also show the people in your life, so, if you are a Cancer rising, your third whole sign house is ruled by Mercury and so Mercury will represent your siblings, Libra is 4th whole sign house so Venus will also represent your Mother, Scorpio is 5th whole sign house so Mars will also represent your children. "}, {"id": "cmt59328702", "title": "Re: Correspondences of relationships", "date": "2026-02-23 06:37 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I would assign Mars to enemies and rivals. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59311550", "title": "CGD and Zodiacal angels", "date": "2026-02-23 03:48 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good day JMG, thanks for hosting another MM. <br/><br/>My question is:  Once a person finishes the Druid grade of the Celtic Golden Dawn, are they able to use the tools they’ve learned from the CGD to work with spirits outside of the elemental &amp; Druid gods?  For instance, Planetary/Zodiacal/Angelic spirits?<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59318718", "title": "Re: CGD and Zodiacal angels", "date": "2026-02-23 05:09 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a good question. The only way to answer it is to try, and find out. "}, {"id": "cmt59342782", "title": "Re: CGD and Zodiacal angels", "date": "2026-02-23 10:02 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm just starting to work in this area.  Take this with a grain of salt, but so far my experiences have said \"Yes\"."}]}, {"id": "cmt59311806", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 03:48 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "With apologies if this has been covered before....<br/><br/>I am wondering if JMG and/or the commentariat have any recommendations on good sources of information on the Sola Busca tarot? Both history and contemporary uses. Have people used it for divination and/or mediation? Are there any books or websites you found particularly helpful?<br/><br/>I ask because resources on it seem relatively limited (at least in English, and I can't read Italian), and there is also a theory about it being a grimoire (does anyone have thoughts on that?). I'm familiar with the Rider-Waite and Marseille decks and am now looking to learn more about Sola Busca.<br/><br/>Thanks in advance for any guidance. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59314622", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 04:38 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Peter Mark Adams has a book on this exact subject called The Game of Saturn. It's an academic work and pretty expensive to acquire (I haven't gotten it yet for this reason) but it apparently goes into considerable depth.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59345598", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 10:59 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yes, that was one of the few books I found. And it is indeed expensive. <br/><br/>The description (see link below) seems quite dark, and one of the things I was wondering was if anyone had enough experience with the deck and/or additional insights on Adam's theory and its potential veracity.<br/><br/>https://scarletimprint.com/publications/p/the-game-of-saturn"}, {"id": "cmt59357886", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-24 03:25 am", "user": "esmewe", "content": "Peter Mark Adam's book - <i>The Game of Saturn</i> - is available as paperback and while pricey at the publisher's site, it can be found used."}]}, {"id": "cmt59318974", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 05:11 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I wish I had something to suggest. What I've seen about it in English struck me as questionably accurate. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59326398", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 06:12 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm assuming the answer is no, but you don't know of anything in French do you? Mine is passable.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59326910", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 06:14 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It wouldn't surprise me if there were writings in French, but I don't happen to know of any. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59320254", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 05:19 pm", "user": "open_space", "content": "<p>Depends on your definition of grimoire. If you are going by the very loose modern definition basically meaning any book or thing that points generally at magic, then the tarot, any tarot, is definitely a grimoire. But it won't teach you how to summon and bind spirits. It can however teach you the more interesting art of scrying and using the tarot for self development. Have you tried using each card as a door in your imagination and asking your deck how to use it for magic? I like doing this by picking the Trumps, and then all the associated pips to it, say, The Magician and all the aces. This is a very good way to understand, for example, how each of the elements act on a specific principle, in balance, and that has some definite magical and meditative applications.</p>\n", "edit_time": "2026-02-23 05:21 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59346110", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 11:05 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This book's theory was the one I was specifically wondering about:<br/><br/>https://petermarkadams.com/gameofsaturnbook/<br/><br/>There are very few resources at all that I can find in English, and JMG doesn't have anything to recommend either in English or French. <br/><br/>But yes, your suggestion about how to start working with the deck is a good one. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59350974", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-24 01:07 am", "user": "open_space", "content": "<p>That looks like a beautiful and interesting book! Perhaps when you are done with it you can share with us what you learned. If the author is correct then the historical validity is irrelevant for the magical practice, as long as the method works. I would be concerned about the emphasis in violence though.</p>\n"}, {"id": "cmt59358398", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-24 03:29 am", "user": "esmewe", "content": "I have both The Game of Saturn and PMA's book on the Hagia Sofia. Adams is a Hellenist and his work is good, historically sound, and esoterically sound. <br/><br/>I also have a Sola Busca deck and it is definitely has a different feel to it than the Tarot de Marseille or the Minchiate Etruria decks of similar age (1480-1580). With the Sola Busca and the Minchiate one is rooting oneself into Renaissance magic and esoteric thought."}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59312062", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 03:59 pm", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>Is the mystery and mystique surrounding magic on the whole a good thing or bad thing?</p>\n<p>On the one hand, it adds a bit of spice and vibrancy to the practice, but on the other it's part of what makes non-practitioners fear and persecute it.  As for attracting people to the path, it seems like a wash: for every person who should be on the path who was attracted by the mystique, how many people who <em>shouldn't</em> be on the path does it draw?</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59319230", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 05:14 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "As I see it, it's not the mystery and the the mystique that makes people fear and persecute magicians. It's the hard fact that some people use magic to hurt, dominate, and exploit other people. The more of this takes place, the more likely persecution becomes -- which is one of the reasons why the recent fad for evil magic is so stupid and so counterproductive. <br/><br/>I see the mystique as highly counterproductive, for what it's worth. It draws a lot of people who have no business practicing magic, and chases off a lot of intelligent people who roll their eyes at the woo-woo. "}, {"id": "cmt59320510", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 05:20 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is it possible to have magic without the mystery? The practice fundamentally works with forces which we have limited ability to perceive, and many of the more advanced practices actively work with beings above the human plane of existence. Granting our society tends towards blindness to spiritual phenomena, you still can't really expect Joe Bob on the street to interact with magic as anything but a mystery until he does the work to pull back the curtains. Even then, human nature can only grasp so much of the picture.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59322302", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 05:42 pm", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>That's quite fair, of course. Though to use an already overused cliche, I barely know how electricity works but that doesn't stop me from turning on the lights.  Similarly my understanding of how some of my medications works is no more concrete than my understanding of how a geomantic gamahe works.</p>\n<p>Part of my thinking behind my comment was this: there's no hard dividing line between what is and isn't magic. Is it magic when a blacksmith produces a blade that doesn't rust or break nearly as easily as most and nobody but him and a few other grandmaster smiths knows the secret?  Is it divination when meteorologists run models to predict the weather over the coming week?</p>\n<p>(Strange as it may seem, there isn't much daylight between measuring a chaotic system like the atmosphere to feed into a model and the various techniques used to generate pseudorandom numbers on a computer to turn into Tarot cards.)</p>\n<p>So while I doubt the average person would be doing ritual magic (nor should they), I could easily see a future where various natural magic techniques were widely known and employed.</p>\n"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59312318", "title": "Summoning a \"demon\" or a lemon", "date": "2026-02-23 04:10 pm", "user": "neptunesdolphins", "content": "There are a series of memes on social media about doing ceremonial magic and summoning a lemon instead - mispronouncing the words. Or summoning Santa when you want Satan. And finally summoning a demon while just trying to pronounce your prescription medicine for the druggist..... so there is humor out there.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59319486", "title": "Re: Summoning a \"demon\" or a lemon", "date": "2026-02-23 05:15 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You know, it would explain a lot if our society tried to sell its collective soul to Satan and got Santa instead. The consumer economy finally makes sense... ;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59324094", "title": "Re: Summoning a \"demon\" or a lemon", "date": "2026-02-23 05:59 pm", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "Sounds like the sci-fi story about the poor typist who ordered a world processor instead of a word processor.  \"Let there be pease on Earth.\""}, {"id": "cmt59324350", "title": "Re: Summoning a \"demon\" or a lemon", "date": "2026-02-23 06:00 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "There was a Clause in the Faustian bargain!<br/><br/>Justin Patrick Moore"}, {"id": "cmt59346366", "title": "Re: Summoning a \"demon\" or a lemon", "date": "2026-02-23 11:05 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The reverse of this (Satan appearing whenever we collectively try to invoke Santa) would also make far too much sense of what has happened with Christmas....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59346622", "title": "Re: Summoning a \"demon\" or a lemon", "date": "2026-02-23 11:07 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Maybe Satan and Santa cut a deal, and swapped places... ;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59346878", "title": "Re: Summoning a \"demon\" or a lemon", "date": "2026-02-23 11:07 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "On the other hand, has anybody ever seen both of them together in the same place? ;-)"}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59312574", "title": "Pet Euthenasia", "date": "2026-02-23 04:13 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello and thank you for this forum. <br/><br/>I have an aging cat who's an indoor/outdoor rescue, and the end of his life is now a subject I'm pondering.  My last cat had age related health problems, wound up in the vet's office with failing kidneys, and they called me while I was at work to tell me they needed to euthanize him. I agreed but felt tremendous guilt afterwards for allowing him to die in some strange room surrounded by strangers. <br/><br/>I'm attempting to avoid a repeat for my beloved cat this time by planning ahead.   My question for you is if the euthanasia of pets/animals is ever addressed in occult teachings?  My impulse here is to comfort a dying pet, and if/when it's clear the pet is just going to suffer to talk to the pet, explain things, say a prayer, and shoot the pet to end it quickly and painlessly. I do think that my cat would understand.  I've never personally done this, but I have hunted, fished, and worked on farms where animals are slaughtered so the general concept is not foreign to me. <br/><br/>Pets fall into a middle ground between hunting/slaughter for food, where a bullet is obviously the thing to do, vs human life, where bullets are obviously out but palliative care is the minimum accepted treatment. I just can't afford a $1000+ vet bill to prolong the life of an ailing cat by two weeks, as happened last time. It seems cruel and bad for everyone involved to put an ailing pet in some strange vet's office until it's far enough along that the stranger kills your pet for you.  What is your perspective on these matters?<br/><br/><br/> ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59319742", "title": "Re: Pet Euthenasia", "date": "2026-02-23 05:18 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm horrified to hear that that's how your vet handled it. When my last pet got too sick to make it -- she was an 18-year-old Siamese with kidney failure -- they waited until we could get to the clinic, and then I held the cat while the vet used the needle. I wonder if you could arrange something similar. <br/><br/>The occult literature known to me doesn't specifically discuss this, but it does talk about the importance of compassion toward all beings, very much including animals. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59325118", "title": "Re: Pet Euthenasia", "date": "2026-02-23 06:03 pm", "user": "diletpoly", "content": "I second this. I've had to put down two cats, and in both cases a vet made a housecall while we (and the kids) held them and petted them. It wasn't cheap, but it wasn't $1000, so I'm sure they could do the same in-office for less."}]}, {"id": "cmt59335614", "title": "Re: Pet Euthenasia", "date": "2026-02-23 08:20 pm", "user": "mskrieger", "content": "You don't say whether your last cat was an indoor/outdoor cat. In my experience, such animals know when their time is near, and then find a favorite spot outdoors to pass on. Dreams/or astral cat type noises/hints then let you know where to find their body.<br/><br/>-Ms. Krieger"}, {"id": "cmt59348158", "title": "Re: Pet Euthenasia", "date": "2026-02-23 11:26 pm", "user": "hippieviking", "content": "I have put an end to a lot of living things between hunting and raising livestock and, in an odd turn of my life, I have actually become \"the guy\" that people get to come put down their animals when can't handle doing it themselves and can't afford the vet. Where we are at, if you can even get to one at all, the vets are all preposterously expensive. <br/><br/>The odd turn is due to the fact that I really don't enjoy killing things. I think that all life has value. I don't like cutting down trees. Heck, I don't like smashing spiders. I'm the weird guy who will stop in the middle of my walk and fish the worm out of the road and toss him in the grass. (You never know, the great hand intervening inexplicably from above! Maybe that'll come back around to me at an auspicious moment!). <br/><br/>I have killed a lot of stuff though and I have put down people's pets and a few years ago I put down one of my beloved cats. In the case of the cat and other pets I always just shoot them. Having thought about it, I think it is actually very humane. Their death is essentially instantaneous if done correctly and if an animal is expecting and ready to die anyway (as old or seriously diseased animals generally are) I don't think it is a terrible shock to them. I always make sure they are comfortable and I talk to them and explain what is happening and then just do it. <br/><br/>Not sure if it helps or not but that's my experience.<br/><br/>HV<br/><br/>"}]}, {"id": "cmt59312830", "title": "\"Witchcraft is Politics\" ?", "date": "2026-02-23 04:16 pm", "user": "neptunesdolphins", "content": "I was perusing some witch-pagan social media groups. One person was aghast that MAGA witches existed and they practice witchcraft. Not only that, they wanted to be a part of the witch social group. <br/><br/>Since she was the administrator, she took umbrage at the whole idea of MAGA witches even existing, let along doing magic. She threw them off saying that \"Witchcraft is Politics\". She explained that witchcraft is only used in protest of the oppression and for the oppressed. That witchcraft was only for I guess \"Progressive\" people since they are fighting the good fight, etc.<br/><br/>I have encountered that idea of witchcraft is only for the oppressed idea on Patheos Pagan. Is this some sort of conflation of their own ideas about magic. Is magic about politics? Or where did that idea come from?<br/><br/>I just thought witchcraft and or magic was just that. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59321022", "title": "Re: \"Witchcraft is Politics\" ?", "date": "2026-02-23 05:21 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If \"witchcraft is politics,\" then it isn't witchcraft any more -- it's just politics. That's usually what happens when you mix spirituality and politics; the politics elbows the spirituality out of the way, and then parades around in spirituality's cast-off clothing. And of course having a bunch of privileged middle class Neopagans parading around pretending to be oppressed and persecuted is well past the outside of enough...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59347646", "title": "Re: \"Witchcraft is Politics\" ?", "date": "2026-02-23 11:12 pm", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "Funny how an in group can claim to be oppressed while denouncing the groups they oppress as oppressors.<br/>Young, poor, white and uneducated MAGA hats practicing magic?  The horror!<br/>The package seems very much like the bitter end of the political side of the Evangelical movement twenty or so years ago.<br/>Same song, etc.<br/>I do wish they would move on so my own foolishness wouldn't be so overshadowed.<br/><br/>But seriously - It looks like Druidry and Heathenry are doing pretty well within Trump's base, though MAGA Witches are news to me.  Do you or the commentariat have any thoughts on what's to come?<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59351742", "title": "Re: \"Witchcraft is Politics\" ?", "date": "2026-02-24 01:16 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There's actually been a large Wiccan scene among poor white people for years now -- what has been contemptuously called \"trailer trash Wicca\" has continued to thrive even while the respectably middle class Neopagan scene peaked and started to contract well over a decade ago. My guess is that there's going to be a lot more of it. Just as herbal medicine is being abandoned by liberals and embraced by conservatives, magical spirituality seems to be on the rise among the young populist scene and increasingly unfashionable (or replaced by political posturing in religious drag) among the middle class left. Where is it all heading? I have no idea, but it bears close watching. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59352510", "title": "Re: \"Witchcraft is Politics\" ?", "date": "2026-02-24 01:35 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I wonder how long before the left starts openly embracing the more world hating end of Christianity....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59355070", "title": "Re: \"Witchcraft is Politics\" ?", "date": "2026-02-24 02:31 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's an interesting question. I expect to see a significant number of people from the far left embracing Islam instead, but you may be right that there'll also be a movement into the more pessimistic and ascetic forms of Christianity. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59357630", "title": "Re: \"Witchcraft is Politics\" ?", "date": "2026-02-24 03:21 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "I think it is plausible uld American leftists invent a heretical version of \"Islam\" that caters to their prejudices. Later they leave that religion when it falls out of fashion, meaning Islam continues to have almost no influence in the USA, not even enough to enforce their rules on people who go through a pseudo-Muslim phase.<br/><br/>Patrick H"}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59316414", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 04:56 pm", "user": "open_space", "content": "I was thinking about your essay on psychic self defense the other day and it got me wondering. I have had nobody so far ask me: how can I use magic to become wiser, to get in contact with the Gods or God or similar but I have had tens or hundreds of people ask me how they can use magic to get their lives unstuck or ward off an often non-existent attack. Most of the times I approach this by offering a tarot reading which reliably points at self defeating habits of thought and feeling which the person doesn't want to question. I have seen many people act as if under psychic attack when some patterns of thought are triggered: irritable, mindless, defensive, etc. So I would like to ask, aren't patterns of thought, the things we think about over and over in the privacy of our minds, often emotionally, spells basically, usually malefic these days? I ask because many times even when I point it out with sticks and apples, they just flinch away of the obvious answer and go blank. Just like an attack! In that case there is nothing to do but give them some words of encouragement and let them faceplant into the \"what-will-happen-if-you-don't-change\" outcome the tarot is pointing to, and they often do.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59321534", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 05:23 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm! That's a very good point. Yes, in effect, we do very often cast malefic spells on ourselves by the repetitive thoughts and emotions we allow ourselves to harbor. <br/><br/>As for helping them, I wish it were possible, but in most cases there really is nothing you can do. Humans gonna human, or as Schiller put it, \"Against stupidity, the gods themselves contend in vain.\" ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59322814", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 05:46 pm", "user": "open_space", "content": "<p>Thanks! </p>\n<p>I suppose the often malefic tone of our inner thoughts these days is just a normal society-in-flames situation.</p>\n<p>Ha, I like that phrase. If the gods can't, then I don't have a chance whatsoever do I. Perhaps I could use some trick to at least have them come back and evaluate the situation together once the events unfolded. I have found that if I push too much for them to see something, their ego kicks in, the one protecting the destructive self imposed spell, and never return.</p>\n<p>More broadly then, one could escape those self imposed magical attacks with the same strategy you suggest in your essay. Understanding your are not your thoughts and you are not your feelings, thus removing the ego from the equation, and then moving them somewhere else or easier still, let them run their course now that you are standing in a third option, avoiding the resistance of having to drag the thoughts and feelings (which is what most modern therapy does, unhelpfully). I think Ive seen some people in a tarot session, when they are at least open enough to recognize they are the problem, exclaim in joy \"oh!\" about a different way of looking at a situation and it has the vibe of something getting loosened. Potentially, bringing that third option up every time the spell circles back could remove energy from it until the pattern/spell dissolves. I will make a note to them to keep it close and ready if things repeat. In my experience those self imposed spells are the real nasty ones. It can take decades or a lifetime for it to run its course since it's always feeding from our freely given energy. Its a bit sad to see such things. I certainly have experienced it too and its very frustrating. </p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59323838", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 05:59 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The strategy I find most useful in stopping those self-inflicted magical attacks is to figure out why I'm doing it to myself. What's the payoff? What attracts me to that self-defeating project? There's always some kind of logic behind it, however shortsighted. <br/><br/>For example, many years ago, I realized that I was setting myself up to fail at every important project I tried as a way to get out of a miserable double bind my parents put me in during my childhood: if I tried my best and succeeded, I got no praise, just a comment that I ought to do that well all the time, and that best then became the minimum acceptable in the future. If I failed, yeah, I got yelled at, but I could deal with that -- and failing deliberately meant that I didn't have the bitter experience of disappointed hope. It also kept me safe from having the terms of the deal changed at the last moment so my success suddenly became a failure, as happened tolerably often. <br/><br/>I had to be ready to realize that, and to accept that I was no longer subject to the whims of my family and had better ways to deal with potential disappointments. Once I got to that point, I could let go of the old pattern fairly easily, and go on to accomplish some things. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59358654", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-24 03:35 am", "user": "hippieviking", "content": "This comment string really hit me. So much so that I am going to make a copy of it so I can return to it again. <br/><br/>Your example from your childhood really is quite similar to how my mother treated me. This was combined with a father who's baseline was to simply expect competency in all practical skills. The flip side with my father though was that he really wasn't much of a teacher although he was a very widely skilled fellow himself. I've supposed that one was simply supposed to glean competency via osmosis. <br/><br/>I went through my life from about age 7 on with the expectancy that I could deliver on whatever skill as necessary. I recall damaging one of the family business' vehicles in a very high stress situation. Understanding a great deal more about how people work in high stress situations now after the military and firefighting I recognize that I was in legitimate cognitive overload and operating way beyond my skillset but I couldn't have put that into words at the time. My parents' response was to be confounded by my failure and to make pay for all the damage. <br/><br/>I'm definitely seizing on this for a theme for mediation and something that I am going to revisit the OSA prompts with it in mind. <br/><br/>Do you happen to have any particular enlightening tidbits you could add to what you said above?<br/><br/>HV", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59360190", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-24 03:54 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Well, if I had enlightening tidbits to offer, presumably I'd be an enlightened being, and that hasn't happened yet. The whole thing is a tangled mess of old, bitter, miserable memories from the smoking crater of my childhood; I've learned to work around the consequences of those experiences, but the shame and grief are still real. I think the one piece of advice I can offer is to go easy on yourself, and recognize -- as my parents never did -- that children are emotionally fragile and take things to heart, and those things can keep hurting for a lifetime. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59362750", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-24 04:33 am", "user": "hippieviking", "content": "\"The whole thing is a tangled mess of old, bitter, miserable memories from the smoking crater of my childhood; I've learned to work around the consequences of those experiences, but the shame and grief are still real.\" <br/><br/>I could have written that, except that I feel like I still have a long way to go figuring out the work arounds. <br/><br/>As for going easy, I think that is a fine piece of advice but easier said than done! Some commenter, I believe here on the Magic Monday, said something along the lines of, \"treat yourself as you would treat a dear friend.\" My initial reaction was to recoil at the thought. So was my wife's when I shared that with her. Even though we both immediately realized what an utterly dysfunctional response that was neither of us are able to implement it well. <br/><br/>I can at least do my best not to pass that shame and grief on to my own children. I don't do a perfect job but I have trained myself to acknowledge it openly with them when I find myself acting like my parents.<br/><br/>Thanks for the response.<br/><br/>"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59363774", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-24 05:02 am", "user": "open_space", "content": "That actually helps me a lot as I went through the same thing and it's probably no fully healed.<br/><br/>I will reply more thoroughly next week as I think I have 30 seconds left tonight. "}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59319998", "title": "Daughter's First Rune Reading and Question on System from \"A Vision\"", "date": "2026-02-23 05:19 pm", "user": "jprussell", "content": "Good Morning,<br/><br/>I hope that whatever changes may be coming down the pipe due to the recent Saturn/Neptune Conjunction bring welcome opportunities!<br/><br/><b>To Share</b>: A hopefully more welcome topic about children and magic than I've attempted in the past: my seven-year-old got interested in the Runes after I explained what I did with them, and asked if she could make a set of her own. I said sure, got some popsicle sticks from the craft store, cut them into rectangles, and had her write one Rune per token on them. Then I walked her through doing a reading: she took them up in her hands, shook them, dropped them, asked \"What do I most need to understand about tomorrow?\" and drew for the past, present, and future. As I talked her through what each Rune meant and the kind of way I would interpret it, for each spot, she broke in with something very specific that matched the interpretation, and at the end, summed it up with what she thought it meant, and it struck me as a pretty solid reading. TSW, indeed. <br/><br/><b>To Ask</b>: I may be straying too much into informing the mind rather than training it, but I had a minor question on Yeats's system: does it imply that every soul has a minimum of 28 incarnations (two of which are out of body)? I remember him mentioning that some phases might have to be gone through more than once, but I was wondering if each needs to be experienced at least once.<br/><br/>My blessings to all who welcome them,<br/>Jeff", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59321790", "title": "Re: Daughter's First Rune Reading and Question on System from \"A Vision\"", "date": "2026-02-23 05:25 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, every phase has to be experienced at least once, and generally many times more than once. He suggests somewhere that the normal process involves twelve full circuits of the wheel of phases, at one phase per incarnation...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59326142", "title": "Re: Daughter's First Rune Reading and Question on System from \"A Vision\"", "date": "2026-02-23 06:11 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "Yeats says that the crisis phases, 8 &amp; 22, might be repeated up to four times. Do people sometimes have to repeat other phases sequentially, too? If so, I imagine a death-by-suicide raises the probability of the soul getting the same Body of Fate in the next incarnation.<br/><br/>PatrickH", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59326654", "title": "Re: Daughter's First Rune Reading and Question on System from \"A Vision\"", "date": "2026-02-23 06:13 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yeah, he indicates that any phase might be taken up to four times in a row, so that's plausible. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59327934", "title": "Re: Daughter's First Rune Reading and Question on System from \"A Vision\"", "date": "2026-02-23 06:21 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "And those wouldn't include lives where the person dies in childhood and doesn't express the traits of the phase?<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59331262", "title": "Re: Daughter's First Rune Reading and Question on System from \"A Vision\"", "date": "2026-02-23 07:25 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yeats doesn't say."}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59322046", "title": "Blasting Trident of Paracelsus", "date": "2026-02-23 05:42 pm", "user": "greensmith", "content": "With JMG's permission, I'm sharing this opportunity to purchase a hand crafted Trident of Paracelsus. These are handmade by myself (a blacksmith) and two other local craftsmen. They ship from Canada.<br/><br/>The design was made with JMG's input and I am very happy with how they've turned out.<br/><br/><a href=\"https://reforgedironworks.com/product/blasting-trident-of-paracelsus/\">https://reforgedironworks.com/product/blasting-trident-of-paracelsus/</a><br/><br/>[IMAGE:0]<br/><br/>Please feel free to contact me if you have any questions.<br/><br/>Tim PW", "images": [{"url": "https://reforgedironworks.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/DSC_1275-2.jpg", "local_path": "./data/archive/2026/2026-02-22_09-52PM_Magic_Monday/images/2026-02-23_05_42_pm_DSC_1275-2.jpg"}]}, {"id": "cmt59323326", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 05:52 pm", "user": "zaratozom", "content": "Have you written any books or, could you make any recomendations of books that involve working with the Tree of Life through Hermetic Qabalah that do not involve ceremonial magick?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59324606", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 06:01 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I haven't written anything along those lines, and I don't know of anything like that -- the Hermetic Cabala generally speaking involves at least some basic ceremonial magic, since it is after all Hermetic. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59324862", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 06:02 pm", "user": "fringewood", "content": "I would like to thank anonymous for his comment on my hypotheses last magic Monday. <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/359082.html?thread=59268778#cmt59268778\">https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/359082.html?thread=59268778#cmt59268778</a><br/><br/>It brought up some interesting points, but mostly it made me smile with reference to close but no cigar and robby the robot shouting \"danger will robinson\". Either anonymous is close to my age (78) or has watched lots of reruns. Either way, a smile in the midst of serious contemplation is a blessing.<br/><br/>Also, if a CME isn't enough to consider, how about a GLE I read about today on Spaceweather.com. <br/><br/>On Feb. 23, 1956, radiation sensors around the world suddenly went haywire as radiation levels spiked to values as much as 50 times normal. No one had ever seen anything like it. \"The increase was so dramatic that some observers switched-off their monitors believing them to be malfunctioning,\" says Dyer. <br/><br/>The radiation came from \"McMath Region 3400\"--an enormous sunspot spanning 60° in solar longitude, which flared just seconds before the particles arrived. Normally, our atmosphere would harmlessly absorb the radiation, but not this time. Solar particles penetrated all the way to the ground. <br/><br/>\"We call this a Ground Level Enhancement (GLE),\" explains Dyer, \"This was the biggest of the modern era, and even today nothing has come close to matching it.\" (A widely publicized GLE last November only amounted to 2% of the 1956 event.)<br/><br/>According to Dyer's calculations, GLE05 would have delivered as much as 10 millisieverts of radiation to passengers on a high-altitude transatlantic flights--comparable to multiple chest CT scans in a few hours. The effect on satellites might have been significant except for one thing: There were no satellites. Sputnik wouldn't be launched until the next year.<br/><br/>How times have changed. in 2026, Earth is surrounded by a swarm of more than 10,000 active satellites with electronics so sensitive that even a single  particle of \"hard radiation\" can reboot onboard computers or or burn out memory locations.<br/><br/>\"Such energetic particle events are nearly impossible to shield,\" says Dyer. \"We need to be prepared--not if but when this happens again.\" <br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59325630", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 06:06 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Once again, we'll just have to wait and see! <br/><br/>One thing to keep in mind is that solar flares are not omnidirectional, and space is big. Imagine that one person is standing in the middle of a big stadium, blindfolded, with a laser pointer. Another person is sitting somewhere in the stands. What are the odds that when the person with the laser pointer turns it on, she'll just happen to light up the person in the stands? Those are about the odds of any single solar flare hitting the earth...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59338686", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 09:36 pm", "user": "fringewood", "content": "Well, actually 40 solar flares that were direct measurements and/or visual observations have hit the earth since 1582 (344 years). Half of those happened since 1967 (59 years) when a blackout of polar surveillance radars during Cold War led U.S. military to scramble for nuclear war until solar origin confirmed. <br/><br/>There's a list at <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_solar_storms\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_solar_storms</a> for those interested. <br/><br/>Today the sun is quiet.<br/><br/>Whether my timing is correct is pure speculation on my part and of course I could be wrong. Whether the earth will get hit by a solar flare in the future is probable, and we live in a time when our technology will suffer. Solar flares don't seem to hurt organic matter unless you are in an airplane (or the space station) where the radiation can cause damage. Another protective set up by the sun. <br/><br/><br/>Also, I'm not sure the being standing in the middle of the stadium (the sun/solar logos) is exactly blindfolded ;^)<br/>"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59325374", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 06:03 pm", "user": "hearthculture", "content": "Good Morning JMG and Commentariat,<br/><br/>This stuff works (TSW): <br/>After many years of various practices, I've been surprised over the last few months to have some moments of very clear communication that has helped me leap problem-hurdles I've struggle with for years to decades. In moments of choice, I've had significant nudges, strong feelings, heard voices, and even conversed with a favorite spoon, and in each case the \"other\" has guided me where I've set my intentions and helped me override momentary distraction, desire, or confusion. In line with others, I've also noticed a strengthening of the unseen, from clear moments of telepathy in my family and friend groups, strong dreams, house and land spirits being more active, and prayers feeling different.<br/><br/>For anyone feeling concern for the immigrant community: I am in a community with many immigrants, and have students who are stressed and scared right now. I had a significant dream featuring La Virgen de Guadalupe, whom I've rarely thought about before, and woke with a message that she could help. Though I'm no longer catholic nor claim to be a christian, I purchased one of her prayer candles and use it to pray for safety and protection of the innocent and it seems to be helping me (though I don't claim to be aware of any further reaching effect.)<br/><br/>Questions: <br/>1. Thinking about your wooden deities filled with corresponding herbs, could the same perhaps be done with paper? I'm working on a plan to design the paper so the bottom folds into a box that can be filled with corresponding stones to make it self standing. Then I'll cut the paper and soak it in a tea of corresponding herbs, then dry and soak again in colloidial gold water. Then use an appropriately colored ink to draw an image of the deity on the paper.  Thoughts on this plan?<br/><br/>2. Could the SOP gates be looked at as temporary astral talismans? I've not delved much into talisman making (other than a rudimentary one for jupitor (used while doing planetary charity.) Is there any tradition of creating physical talismans of the elemental and spiritual gates?<br/><br/>3. I've been pondering using basic english in my magical workings and in addressing deities. For a couple significant interactions, I was trying to shoehorn the being into a popular deity. Then divination suggested the being was more local and perhaps I didn't have a name. That started me thinking about foreign names that are \"normal\" in those languages but mystical in ours. Judo and Aikido use Japanese terms that make the techniques sound impressive but when translated they are simply descriptive, like \"hip throw,\" or \"arm lock.\" It seems like this is similar in the spiritual realm where some name that feels grand or fancy to me, really is just the name of the thing in the original language. Even some deities are this way, like Thor and Mjölnir are literally “Thunder and Lightning.\" It feels like the impulse to use foreign language for spirit matters could have a benefit in the way that ritual clothing and tools do - it is used for a singular purpose and therefore does not bring up other familiar associations which could divide focus and will. Yet, I also sense that this is divisive in that it seems to support the false dichotomy of spirit-world / material-world, at once making magic something glamorous and other, and keeping our physical reality safely dead and spiritually inert. I've been working to bridge that divide in other aspects of my life - reminding myself to see the people and environments around me in their spiritual and energetic fullness all day rather than just during ritual. I'm exploring using common english words for geomantic symbols and tarot cards and even speaking and praying to entities using my common names - i.e. talking to land spirits as just the name of the thing. I figure that this is somewhat supported by tradition; for example, the greeks gave epithets to the gods that signify the aspect that is being worked with. I'm curious about your (and the learned commentariat's) opinion on this.<br/><br/>Thank you for this space and your time. Wishing you well!<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59325886", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 06:09 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Good question. You'd have to experiment and find out. <br/><br/>2) Yes, in a certain sense, you can think of the emblems as astral talismans, and yes, some magical temples have consecrated images representing the elements in the four or six directions. <br/><br/>3) You can find plenty of examples in both directions. I think it's very much a matter of figuring out what works best for you personally. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59327678", "title": "Is there something in the air?", "date": "2026-02-23 06:17 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "John Michael - do you think there is something in the air?<br/>And if so is there anything you particularly recommend regarding inner work?<br/>Thanks.<br/><br/>https://voxhermes.wordpress.com/2026/02/19/welcome-to-the-year-of-the-fire-horse-saturn-neptune-aries-and-all-that/<br/><br/>https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/357663.html?thread=59291423#cmt59291423", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59331518", "title": "Re: Is there something in the air?", "date": "2026-02-23 07:28 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Something in the air? Well, there's nitrogen, oxygen, a small amount of carbon dioxide... ;-)<br/><br/>Seriously, I'm not at all sure what you're asking here. Please humor a not-always-that-high-functioning autist and spell it out for me. "}, {"id": "cmt59334078", "title": "Re: Is there something in the air?", "date": "2026-02-23 07:59 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Can I just give a reply to that? Obviously I have some shortcomings here - I'm not JMG and I'm also not quite sure what you mean, but I was almost tempted to ask here if anyone else had noticed the entities that surround us increasing mightily from mid-February, when all that astrological stuff happened. Perhaps you possibly meant something like that? "}]}, {"id": "cmt59328958", "title": "Who/what was the real Jesus?", "date": "2026-02-23 06:41 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In The Occult Philosophy Workbook you mention that sometimes higher beings incarnate as humans, come to earth with a particular purpose, accomplish said work, and then often promptly die by violence. This sounds a great deal like Jesus. On the other hand, you have also mentioned that much of what Christians believe about Jesus might be a fabrication of Paul, and that you prefer the gnostic teachings on Christ. So I was wondering if you could give a snap shot of your thoughts on Jesus. Was he just a first century occultist with a knack for exorcism? The divine in human flesh? Something else?<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59332286", "title": "Re: Who/what was the real Jesus?", "date": "2026-02-23 07:50 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't believe that the person we now call Jesus of Nazareth -- Yeshua bin Maryam, as they would have called him back in the day -- was God, in any unique sense. I don't believe he was born of a physically intact virgin without benefit of spermatozoa, I don't believe that he returned to life after being biologically dead for portions of three days, and I don't believe that he physically ascended into heaven. All those things are standard mythological elements from the Hellenistic folk religions of the time, which got loaded onto the memory of a remarkable Galilean teacher and healer by people who, like Paul of Tarsus, never actually met him. <br/><br/>Mind you, it's unquestionably true that people who pray to Jesus Christ very often have those prayers answered. That's true of all gods and goddesses, however, and it's happened rather more than once that invented deities have responded to prayer -- I'm thinking here of the experience of the Reformed Druids of North America, who invented a god of the groves named Dalon ap Landu and started doing rituals to him, and got an answer. For that matter, I've had an uneasy feeling for years now that if I started seriously invoking the gods of the Cthulhu mythos, I'd get an answer, and not a weak one. The universe is a strange place and the Divine seems quite willing to humor us.<br/><br/>As for the historical person Jesus of Nazareth, I don't claim to know what he was or wasn't. I wasn't there at the time, and trying to gauge that from a handful of biased accounts written many decades after the fact is a very dubious proposition. That's about as much as I can say on the subject. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59334846", "title": "Re: Who/what was the real Jesus?", "date": "2026-02-23 08:05 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "\"...I'd get an answer...\"<br/><br/>Cthulhu forbid it ever comes to that! <br/>Hee hee.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59336126", "title": "Re: Who/what was the real Jesus?", "date": "2026-02-23 08:44 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I won't say it isn't tempting. There's an early Robert Bloch story that has Druids worshipping the Black Goat of the Woods, too, so it's even got textual justification. ;-) But for the time being, at least, I'll stick to slightly less squamous and rugose Druid deities..."}]}, {"id": "cmt59339454", "title": "Re: Who/what was the real Jesus?", "date": "2026-02-23 09:43 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "Is it even possible that Jesus of Nazareth's followers created an egregore of him after his death, and a deity, seeing an opportunity, took control of the egregore and impersonated Jesus? That possibility came to my mind mind when you &amp; KS were posting about \"Amelia\" being the vehicle for a war goddess. (The Jesus in the Synoptic Gospels seemed convinced that the world was going to end soon, so his followers shouldn't worry about their finances or starting a family, just doing what is required to get into the Kingdom of Heaven. If Christians followed his teachings, the religion would have petered out within a couple generations, but the Risen Christ seemed to have somewhat different priorities.)<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59342270", "title": "Re: Who/what was the real Jesus?", "date": "2026-02-23 09:58 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's one possibility out of many. To my mind, though, Stevan Davies in <i>The Gospel of Thomas and Christian Wisdom</i> makes a very solid case that the Gospel of Thomas, which lacks the apocalyptic business, is closer to the teachings of the historical Jesus than the synoptic gospels, which were heavily edited after 70 AD to fit the apocalyptic frenzy of the time. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59363006", "title": "Re: Who/what was the real Jesus?", "date": "2026-02-24 04:44 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "To be fair, the New Testament is the best-sourced document we have from Antiquity by a long shot, both in volume of sources and their chronological proximity. Still, it's filtered through the initial editing process, the Councils, and the vast gulf of time between the early Roman Empire and today; thus you can't be certain. I also think it's probable that egregores have been piled onto the original Jesus, so that when you invoke that name, there may be someone/something responding to you that you wouldn't expect."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59329214", "title": "Vegvísir and grand conjunction personal planet aspects", "date": "2026-02-23 06:45 pm", "user": "sea_spray", "content": "Hi JMG<br/><br/>Are you familiar with the Vegvísir or \"Viking compass\", though it's not actually viking. It become common among modern pagans and in the original text, the Huld manuscript, it was stated \"if this sign is carried, one will never lose one's way in storms or bad weather, even when the way is not known\". To me that sounds like a talisman. <br/>Have you or anyone here worked with it and have any idea of it's effectiveness?<br/>Are there specific meanings for each of it's branches?<br/><br/>Is there any way of making a guess as to the effect of aspects to personal planets from the chart of the recent Saturn-Neptune grand conjunction between. I remember your previous warnings about making details of your own birth chart public so I'll only say that I have square, opposition, conjunct, inconjunct and trine aspects from the Sun, Moon, Mars, Venus, north node and the conjunction itself to my Ascdent, Sun, Moon, Mars, Jupiter and Pluto. <br/>Is the impact just unknown? Should I treat it like the individual aspects are long duration transits with the conjunction itself having it's own unique flavour?<br/><br/>Thanks <br/>Sea spray", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59332798", "title": "Re: Vegvísir and grand conjunction personal planet aspects", "date": "2026-02-23 07:53 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) No, I haven't encountered that one. <br/><br/>2) Natal astrology isn't my strong suit, so anything I suggest should be taken tentatively. I would treat it as an ordinary transit -- but if more experienced natal astrologers want to chime in here, I'd be happy to listen. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59331774", "title": "Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-02-23 07:30 pm", "user": "kylec", "content": "If you would like to sign up for healing hands this week, please reply here or PM me your name and request. As a reminder, you may sign up every week if you like, but I do require people to make a request each Monday to remain on the healist list. Thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59340990", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-02-23 09:50 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yes, I would like healing hands this week.<br/><br/>Thank you very much,<br/>Brad"}, {"id": "cmt59348414", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-02-23 11:28 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you Kyle.  May i ask for healing hands for myself and my partner, who has dementia.<br/>Thanks again for your gifts to us.<br/>Courtinthenorth "}, {"id": "cmt59349438", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-02-23 11:55 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yes please and thank you, Kyle.  🙏<br/><br/>(The trigger finger that’s been an irritation for me for several months felt hugely better for a few hours last Friday than it has in some time.  It’s still an issue, but the relief was very noticeable.)<br/><br/>OtterGirl "}, {"id": "cmt59351486", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-02-24 01:12 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Please do healing hands for me too.<br/><br/>Annette Simard"}, {"id": "cmt59353278", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-02-24 01:39 am", "user": "linden_matryoshka", "content": "Kyle,<br/>I would like to sign up for healing hands.<br/>Thank you."}]}, {"id": "cmt59332030", "title": "Saturn-Neptune Conjunction Time", "date": "2026-02-23 07:48 pm", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>Following up on a question I asked a week or two ago, now that the Saturn-Neptune conjunction has passed, is there a definitive time for the conjunction verified by empirical data?</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59333054", "title": "Re: Saturn-Neptune Conjunction Time", "date": "2026-02-23 07:53 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I haven't seen anything to that effect. Anyone else? "}]}, {"id": "cmt59334334", "title": "The Big Conjunction", "date": "2026-02-23 08:01 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi, JMG<br/><br/>I was wondering how you (and anyone else who’d like to chime in) experienced the big conjunction as it hit full force last week, especially with regards to magical practice and overall events happening and so forth. Myself, I noticed that people around me were quite down, and elderly family members especially were experiencing much emotional and physical pain in the days leading up to it (luckily, they respond well to my giving them thorough massage, and to good conversation - I’ve endeavoured to make the whole household astrologically literate, which has been met with sound enthusiasm). Further, I noticed grudgingly that certain protective measures (derived mostly from many years of experimenting with the SoP) that I’ve deployed with reliable effect for years suddenly bounced. I do have a beefed-up paganised LBRP that I occasionally dig out of the trunk and put to use instead of the SoP when I sense the astral is getting very unruly (very rarely used these days) and it has the side effect of basically sucking everything dry - figure that might perhaps have also had some negative side effects. More generally, it felt much more difficult to summon any actual juice in ritual, kinda like cooking on a cold stove for a while. Anyways, would love to hear your thoughts on my thoughts, and I look forward to listening to you and Isaac discuss the big event on the podcast! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59336382", "title": "Re: The Big Conjunction", "date": "2026-02-23 08:47 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I didn't notice much of an effect, but then the conjunction wasn't in aspect to anything in my natal chart, and in fact is intercepted in a cadent house -- all of which would tend to mute the effect for me personally. I'll be interested to see how others respond, though. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59342014", "title": "Re: The Big Conjunction", "date": "2026-02-23 09:56 pm", "user": "emily07", "content": "...unfortunately I´ve not yet mastered to keep a lab-book on my SOP,  from memory during last week I had some days where the rays somehow where - like white paint threads with a little drop as a head. Usually it´s light. It reversed to light either yesterday or today."}]}, {"id": "cmt59340734", "title": "Re: The Big Conjunction", "date": "2026-02-23 09:48 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "I had changes in my workplace and my finances around the time of the big conjunction. In my <i>rectified</i> natal chart, the conjunction was intercepted in my second house but was trining my midheaven &amp; sun.<br/><br/>Patrick H"}, {"id": "cmt59348670", "title": "Re: The Big Conjunction", "date": "2026-02-23 11:33 pm", "user": "lukeszy", "content": "So on Thursday I did spiritual energy work on another person for the first time and this put me in an altered state going into and through Friday.  At a certain point after the conjunction I noticed an obvious sense of spacious freedom which lasts even till now.  Like a room opened up somewhere on the planes where my mind can hang out because some stagnant pattern dissolved.  Or someone removed a weight vest from me.  This was identical to the event I reported to JMG here <a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/september-2020-open-post/\">https://www.ecosophia.net/september-2020-open-post/</a>, besides for the fact I didn't notice the actual dissolving of the tension this time.  Luke Z"}, {"id": "cmt59348926", "title": "Re: The Big Conjunction", "date": "2026-02-23 11:47 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "For the four or five days prior to the conjunction, I experienced a sinus flare-up every day that didn't seem to be connected to anything regarding the weather or my activities. The usual methods I deal with them didn't bring lasting relief. On the day of the conjunction, my sinuses cleared up on their own and have stayed clear since. The conjunction occurred in my 5th house, in a wide conjunction with the 6th house cusp, and in exact opposition to Jupiter in my chart. I haven't noticed any particular effects from the transits to Jupiter."}, {"id": "cmt59356862", "title": "Re: The Big Conjunction", "date": "2026-02-24 03:03 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've been noticing a slightly unusual amount of synchronicities over the last six or so days—usually it'll be an average of maybe one day like that every two weeks. I wasn't taking notes, and I don't remember the synchronicities, so I can't go back and check, but they didn't seem at the time like they had any noticeable broader meaning besides \"hey these are whatever the conditions are that result in synchronicities happening\". Since I don't really know what those conditions would be, I couldn't much make that actionable."}]}, {"id": "cmt59335102", "title": "Various Questions", "date": "2026-02-23 08:05 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/>I have a few unrelated questions for you.<br/><br/>1)How does a person damage their astral aura and how can it be repaired, if it can be repaired?<br/><br/>2) I have had a little more poltergeist activity.  My guest turned the washing machine on when I had left the clothes to soak.  It is an old-fashioned analog washing machine and you have to pull a nob out to start it.  This requires a bit of force.  We were both in the living room when we heard it start.  My question revolves around a shirt of the ghost's that his girlfriend game me after his death.  The poltergeist activity started after I received his shirt.  Do you feel there might be some connection?  Was he able to follow that shirt to my house?<br/><br/>3) I wrote to you a couple of years ago about my practice of relaxing my mental, sheath and subtle bodies before meditation.  You did not post that message so I thought there might have been something inadvisable about the practice.  I continued it in any case and I think it is having good results.  Quite often, when I relax my mental sheath, I feel a tingle up my back to the top of my head and this feels good and refreshing.   What do you think of this practice?<br/><br/>I also wanted to tell you that it has been so long since I have felt frustrated that I cannot remember when it happened last.  I have felt frustrated for most of my life.  For example, when I had to fold a load of clothes, I would feel frustrated that I had to do something so boring.  It took a long time to fold the clothes and I hated it.  Recently, I realized that this job had become easy and swiftly delt with, even a bit pleasurable.  <br/><br/>Also, years ago I started being able to see with my eyes closed.  It frightened me and I blocked that ability.  It has started again and I am welcoming it.  <br/><br/>Thank you for all your patient teaching.<br/>Maxine", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59336638", "title": "Re: Various Questions", "date": "2026-02-23 08:51 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That's a little like asking \"How does a human body get sick and what can be done about it?\" There are many, many ways, and many things you can do about it. These days, the most common forms of astral injury are caused by the squalid and toxic astral environment in which most of us live, and the best general treatments are regular banishing rituals and energy healing practices such as Essene healing -- but there's much, much more. <br/><br/>2) That's possible. You might arrange for the shirt to go somewhere else and see if the effects stop. <br/><br/>3) I don't recall seeing that post -- Dreamwidth sometimes eats attempted comments. In terms of the practice, I'd need to have somebody better at clairvoyance than I am observe you and comment on what they saw to be able to offer an opinion, but I know of nothing harmful about it."}]}, {"id": "cmt59335358", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 08:15 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "As I understand it, when someone dies their etheric and astral bodies dissipate and become material for future souls to gather to create their own energy bodies. So if someone developed their energy bodies as much as possible in life, would they be doing the next soul a favour by providing them with better quality material?<br/><br/>If etheric scavengers had consumed the body first, would that change the answer? Are there astral scavengers as well?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59337150", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 08:53 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It's simply a matter of improving the quality of the subtle planes generally; the etheric body doesn't pass to another person, it dissolves with or without help of scavengers, and contributes to the background quality of the etheric plane. Over time, the ethers become better suited to forming human etheric bodies and supporting the more complex and subtle functions of etheric activity. <br/><br/>2) The astral body dissolves into its component energies as you process your experiences after death, so there's not much for scavengers to feed on. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59337918", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 09:15 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "When the soul processes its experiences after death, where in the spirit world does that happen?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59338942", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 09:38 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "On the astral plane. Which region of the astral plane is involved depends on the nature of the experiences to be processed, and that depends on the soul's ethical and spiritual condition; the options range from a fairly good equivalent of heaven to an even better equivalent of hell. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59340222", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 09:48 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is the process managed by some kind of entities or do you go through it alone? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59341758", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 09:54 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There are entities that help. The inner side of things is even more complex, active, and busy than the material world. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59344062", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 10:21 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How much contact do you have with other souls going through the same process?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59344830", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 10:51 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Depends on which level of the astral you're on. The denser (and more hellish), the less contact you have with any other soul -- at the lowest levels of the astral, a sense of absolute isolation adds to the fun. (That's not punitive; it's just that at that level connecting to others is impossible.) The less dense (and more heavenly) levels are much more open to interaction, and at the highest levels -- well, that's what Christians call the communion of saints, and \"communion\" is the right word. "}]}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59335870", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 08:27 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I don't know if this question is too general - but is there something to say about Uranus in opposition to natal Uranus? I'm experiencing what I would call an emotionally slightly challenging time, though more through inner than through external factors. So far, I'm not much into astrology but for some reason got the feeling that I should have a look at Uranus transits - only to find that said transit for me is, well, now.<br/><br/>I have to say, though, that at the moment all the outer planets form many aspects to the outer planets of my natal chart, as well as a few aspects to the inner ones. Don't know if there's anything general to say about this, as well.<br/><br/>If it is possible to give any advice, it is very welcome. Thank you very much!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59337406", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 08:56 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That happens to everyone around the age of 42, and it plays a significant role in the midlife crisis so many people have around then. One way or another, depending on the placement, condition, and aspects of your natal Uranus, you have to face what you've made of your life up to that time, and either keep doing it or do something else. <br/><br/>Since you have a lot of outer planet transits going on right now, you might consider seeing if you can find a book on astrological transits -- Robert Hand's <i>Planets in Transit</i> is well recommended -- and see what each of those transits has to tell you. It really does depend on the fine details! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59343294", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 10:12 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks a lot for the book suggestion. More than a decade ago, somebody mentioned it to me - it caught my attention at that time, but I never looked into it. Now I have borrowed it from archive.org, for a start. Let's just say it's fascinating.<br/><br/>It is also interesting to see how not everything that looks negative at the first glance must always be, and how some transits seem to have an almost neutralizing effect on each other. I guess even if I stick only with Hand's book and read nothing else, this will be a whole lot of work to understand.<br/><br/>So again thank you - your suggestion seems to have come just at the right time!"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59336894", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 08:51 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Happy Magic Monday JMG! I hope you are finding your new neighbourhood congenial. I have an observation and a few queries for you.<br/><br/>1. The observation is that in the last few weeks, I've found my CGD Central Ray practice deepening and sharpening - my visualisation skills still aren't great but I'm \"seeing\"/sensing the colours of the spheres much more vividly. Same for the Rite of the Rays, ways of augmenting the scene at each compass point have suggested themselves. Is this the kind of thing that happens eventually after repeated practice?<br/><br/>2. I'm retraining out of the media and will have left for good by May next year at the latest. Should I expect some degree of karmic blowback for having been a part of it? If there is blowback, is there any way of reducing it or is it simply a matter of facing it when it arrives?<br/><br/>3. I'm struck that the CGD Supreme Ritual of the Pentagram is performed immediately after opening the Druid Grade temple (presumably followed by the LRP, purifying, consecrating, circumbulating and visualising the rising of the spiritual sun), as opposed to calling an element +following+ the LRP etc in the Bardic Grade. Is this because the SRP includes all four elements as a totality? I'm finding it hard to put my hunch into good English!<br/><br/>4. I had a huge falling out a few months back with a family member who has a very, very strong will. The wands suggest a herbal protective amulet is worth considering - St John's Wort seems a good start, maybe vervain too?<br/><br/>With thanks for your valuable time. I'm also enjoying slowly working through your Levi translation.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59337662", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 08:59 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Yes. That's one of the points of repeated practice.<br/><br/>2) I recommend seeking divination on this, as it depends on a lot of factors. <br/><br/>3) Yes, exactly. <br/><br/>4) Always use an odd number of ingredients. My suggestion would be St. John's wort, vervain, and angelica root. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59338174", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 09:22 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've been practicing classical hatha yoga and kriya yoga. To learn and perform ritual or ceremonial magic of Golden Dawn tradition without negative side affects do I need to stop these practices?<br/><br/>I've been following you for years, but I still don't have a good conceptual framework for what the hell magic is. I don't NEED intellectual food for thought, I just need to be reassured I'm not working against myself by doing the practices.<br/><br/>An under", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59339198", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 09:42 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you practice kriya yoga I don't recommend that you practice Golden Dawn magic at any point in this incarnation. Kriya yoga is a valid and powerful system in its own right, of course; the issue is simply that it structures the subtle bodies in a specific way, which is very different from the way Golden Dawn magic shapes those same bodies. <br/><br/>Why not just keep practicing hatha yoga and kriya yoga, and add in such other elements of yogic tradition and practice as your teachers and your own intuition may suggest? If you've already got a practice under way, your best bet is to follow through with it. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59339710", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 09:43 pm", "user": "zaratozom", "content": "Ok I see . I’ve been reading your  LRM book for quite some time and have reached a point where I’ll need to leave the house in order to proceed with the lessons out of an abundance of caution which is fine,  it’s just going to take me longer to move forward than preferred .<br/>I’d like to find more occult study/practice/philosophy that I can work with in tandem without crossing streams or derailing current study .<br/>Reading both your work and Gareth Knights has really lit up an interest for me but as you’ve mentioned, you can read all you want about musical theory but it won’t get you anywhere without actually picking up an instrument.<br/>"}, {"id": "cmt59340478", "title": "Saturn-Neptune", "date": "2026-02-23 09:48 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have been checking daily with an astronomy program (Stellarium) to watch the conjunction. It appears to me they never got closer than about 1 degree of separation.  How close do two bodies need to be for it to be significant?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59341246", "title": "Re: Saturn-Neptune", "date": "2026-02-23 09:53 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The conjunction is measured in terms of their position relative to the ecliptic. Declination north or south from the ecliptic also matters, but it's judged differently in astrology. This is one of the things astronomers routinely misunderstand! "}]}, {"id": "cmt59341502", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 09:54 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm a few months in to doing daily readings with the SGO and wanted to check my understanding of something. For the past few days 27 reversed, Justice has been popping up over and over again, alternating between the situation and outcome, while the reading for myself has been Paradox, Compromise, Generation in that order, and the cards alongside Justice being Stability (Outcome), Correspondence (Situation), and Encounter (Outcome) (with Justice in the alternating space.) I am interpreting this series of readings to mean that I am currently suffering the consequences of my own self-defeating behavior and that I have no one to blame for my current situation besides myself. Generation in the latest reading suggests to me I am in the process of overcoming this. Is this the correct interpretation or do I have it wrong?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59342526", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 10:00 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nobody but you can determine whether your interpretation of the cards is correct, since the meaning of each divination is determined by the interplay between your intuition and the symbols of the cards. That said, your interpretation sounds reasonable to me. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59343550", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 10:14 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ah right, of course. That's a fundamental I have yet to fully internalize from the looks of it. That being said, it is at least reassuring to know I do not sound wildly off-base. As always, I suppose the proper course of action is to keep moving forward and see how today unfolds. Thank you."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59343038", "title": "a question on polarity", "date": "2026-02-23 10:03 pm", "user": "emily07", "content": "Dear JMG,<br/>Since ca. 2 years I attend almost every sunday-mass (I´ll pass on high-feast like Easter or Christmas) and have promptly \"fallen in love\" with one of the priests. Could I \"get rid\" of excessive energyy by blessing all and sundry that want to be blessed after church is over?<br/>Thank you and best wishes,<br/>Emily07", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59345086", "title": "Re: a question on polarity", "date": "2026-02-23 10:53 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's extremely common, of course. Blessing everyone should help; you might also see if you can cultivate a devotion to a male saint, and put some of that emotional energy there. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59344318", "title": "Astrology Rocks!", "date": "2026-02-23 10:23 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "For whatever reason I've taken to astrology the last couple of weeks, and wow what an amazing click that was! The depth of stuff out there is truly astounding and the levels look endless now, I can see this becoming a lifetime pursuit, another interest I'll have to pretend I don't have in the PMC world I inhabit. <br/>1) I'd like to know why the Llewellyn George editions post 1970s are considered not worth buying by your standards? I definitely maybe didn't maybe buy one of the 1980s editions... <br/>2) I've also heard the Saturn is in its Joy in the 12th house, and that this is a traditional perspective, why do modern astrologers not follow this rule? Saturn is in my 12th House and I wonder whether it is why I tend to beat myself up pretty darn good. <br/><br/>Thanks as always for your posts.   ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59345342", "title": "Re: Astrology Rocks!", "date": "2026-02-23 10:55 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) If it's the <i>New A-Z Horoscope Maker and Delineator</i>, it's been watered down to fit current psychological notions of astrology. If the word \"New\" isn't in the title, it's the old version, which focuses a lot more on prediction. <br/><br/>2) Interesting. I've heard here and there about the Joys of the planets, but never seen that concept discussed in detail -- but then I don't study Hellenistic or Arabic astrology. "}, {"id": "cmt59347902", "title": "Re: Astrology Rocks!", "date": "2026-02-23 11:26 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "2) Joys don't really work for modern astrology. Trying to rip it out of its context and use it anyway is akin to taking techniques from Newton's calculus, trying to use them with modern techniques, and wondering why the results don't work. If you know enough mathematics, you might be able to make it work, but for most people, it leads very quickly to ridiculously wrong answers at best...."}]}, {"id": "cmt59347134", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 11:08 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have a question about the SOP as set out in the multi-part instructional series on this blog. I’m good about following ritual instructions and trusting the process, but wondered about imagining the scenes of the elemental seasons “in the place where you live”. Could it be a scene in an imaginary place (earth like) where I would want to live?<br/><br/>That got me wondering what makes a ritual like the SOP or LBRP work aside from the egregore component. Is it how vividly I imagine and experience the light from above and below, the experience of the elements, and everything overall? Or the vibration of the Divine names? The LBRP has more name vibrating than the SOP....does that make a difference? <br/><br/>You have written what makes magic work is basically will and imagination, but I’m trying to understand that on a non-intellectual level through this practice. What is it I do that makes a ritual or technique work? The way I’m looking at it now is I’m like a child playing an imaginary game that I believe is 100% real, and the more I believe+perceive that on every level the better it will work, but I suspect there is more to it. Thanks for doing this Q+A every week.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59347390", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-23 11:10 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That wouldn't be useful for me, but your mileage may vary. <br/><br/>2) There's much more to it than that, and the best way to understand it is to do the ritual daily and learn from the experience. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59349182", "title": "Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-02-23 11:51 pm", "user": "ecoprayer", "content": "<a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/tag/prayerlist\">At this page</a> is the full list of all of the non-faith-specific requests for prayer that have recently appeared at <a href=\"https://ecosophia.net\">ecosophia.net</a> and <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org\">ecosophia.dreamwidth.org</a>, as well as in the comments of the prayer list posts (<a href=\"https://drive.google.com/file/d/1gHc_FW9SHKpOM7d3UoJ8kPqHUFLk46hM/view?usp=sharing\">printable version here</a>, current to 2/19). Please feel free to add any or all of the requests to your own prayers.<br/><br/>If I missed anybody, or if you would like to add a prayer request for yourself or anyone who has given you consent (or for whom a relevant person holds power of consent) to the list, please feel free to leave a comment below.<br/><br/><center>* * *</center><br/>This week I would like to bring special attention to the following prayer requests, selected from the fuller list.<br/><br/><div style=\"\"><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/359082.html?thread=59206570#cmt59206570\">Cathy N. of St. Marys, Ohio</a> heal and recover from injuries caused by a fall.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=15906#cmt15906\">Dustin, a relative of Brenainn</a>, be healed of a recently discovered heart condition.<br/><br/>May 1Wanderers's partner Cathy, whose cancer has returned, be given the physical and mental strength to fight it, and tolerate the treatment, and may she enjoy a full and permanent recovery.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=14882#cmt14882\">Jule from Iserlohn, Germany</a>, who is experiencing complications in her pregnancy due to an influenza infection, recover and have a pleasant pregnancy and birth.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=12322#cmt12322\">Larry Mulford</a>, who has entered hospice after a year battling with pancreatic cancer, pass in the smoothest possible manner, and may his wife be enveloped in our love.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1160.html?thread=12168#cmt12168\">Marko</a> have the strength to seize the opportunities.<br/><br/>May Pierre's young daughter, Athena, be healed from her fatigue and its root causes in ways that are easy, natural, and as holistic as possible.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/november-2025-open-post/#comment-149490\">Bob Ralston (aka Rasty Bob)</a>, who is in hospice care in Buckeye AZ, and who just lost his wife Leslie Fish, be blessed and find relief from his pain and discomfort; may Bob's heart remain strong. <br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18134.html?thread=452566#cmt452566\">5 year old Max</a> be blessed and protected during his parents' contentious divorce; may events work out in a manner most conducive to Max's healthy development over the long term.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/514.html?thread=2562#cmt2562\">Lydia G. of Geauga County, Ohio</a> heal and recover from prolonged health issues.<br/><br/>May both <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/347398.html?thread=57920774#cmt57920774\">Monika and the child she is pregnant with</a> both be blessed with good health and a safe delivery. <br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/338828.html?thread=56777612#cmt56777612\">Mary's sister</a> have her auto-immune conditions sent into remission, may her eyes remain healthy, and may she heal in body, mind, and spirit.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18134.html?thread=455382#cmt455382\">Trubujah's best friend Pat's teenage daughter Devin</a>, who has a mysterious condition which doctors are so far baffled by necessitating that she remain in a wheelchair, be healed of her condition; may the underlying cause come to light so that treatment may begin.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/16429.html?thread=392237#cmt392237\">Kevin’s sister Cynthia</a> be cured of the hallucinations and delusions that have afflicted her, and freed from emotional distress. May she be safely healed of the physical condition that has provoked her emotions; and may she be healed of the spiritual condition that brings her to be so unsettled by it. May she come to feel calm and secure in her physical body, regardless of its level of health.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/312140.html?thread=53408588#cmt53408588\">Frank R. Hartman, who lost his house in the Altadena fire, and all who have been affected by the larger conflagration</a> be blessed and healed.<br/><br/></div><div><br/><br/><center>* * *</center><br/>Guidelines for how long prayer requests stay on the list, how to word requests, how to be added to the weekly email list, how to improve the chances of your prayer being answered, and several other common questions and issues, are to be found <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/6373.html\">at the Ecosophia Prayer List FAQ</a>.<br/><br/>If there are any among you who might wish to join me in a bit of <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/1986.html\">astrological timing</a>, I pray each week for the health of all those with health problems on the list on the  astrological hour of the Sun on Sundays, bearing in mind the Sun's rulerships of heart, brain, and vital energies. If this appeals to you, I invite you to join me.</div>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59350462", "title": "Re: Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-02-24 01:03 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this as always! "}]}, {"id": "cmt59350206", "title": "Occult/Magical aspect of blood donation", "date": "2026-02-24 12:59 am", "user": "geoffg", "content": "Hey JMG and MM community,<br/><br/>I have donated blood for quite a few years now, and while I was doing so recently, I realized I had never really considered the occult side of the practice since starting to practice.  I was curious what thoughts you have about how donating blood works on a magical level.<br/><br/>Some thoughts I considered were the fact that though very, very unlikely, a malign person could steal my blood and use it for harmful magic, that given blood's association with the Moon, it could potentially be seen as sort of a lunar offering, and that it probably is a positive act on a karmic level since typically people who need blood need it pretty badly for medical reasons, so it is a form of healing.  <br/><br/>Do those seem accurate, and is there anything else that seems obvious to you on a magical level?<br/><br/>Thanks for hosting MM.<br/><br/>Geoff", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59350718", "title": "Re: Occult/Magical aspect of blood donation", "date": "2026-02-24 01:06 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's definitely a positive act, karmically speaking, since you're doing something without recompense so that other people may be healed. You could do it as an offering to the Moon, if you did so deliberately. There are some traditions in the occult scene that discourage blood donations because the blood is very closely associated with the soul, but it's not a generally held view. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59352766", "title": "Re: Occult/Magical aspect of blood donation", "date": "2026-02-24 01:36 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What are there occult risks associated with blood donation that would lead some people to say it's a bad idea?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59354814", "title": "Re: Occult/Magical aspect of blood donation", "date": "2026-02-24 02:29 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "They say that it can produce an unnatural link between the soul of the blood donor and the soul of the recipient. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59351230", "title": "druidry-- where to start?", "date": "2026-02-24 01:10 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "hi! i fell into your work via a podcast about yeats' a vision on the 20th and have begun a deep dive into that, and your online presences beyond. wow! there's a lot. i'm super excited about the yeats stuff, for one.<br/><br/>question: if i'm intersted in the whole DRUID thing, (and deep down i really freaking am,) where would you suggest one start? a book? a community? in person? online? i'm in the catskills (ny.) thanks. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59351998", "title": "Re: druidry-- where to start?", "date": "2026-02-24 01:19 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you don't mind my tooting my own horn a bit, I've written two good introductory books on Druidry for beginners. One is a nicely illustrated little volume titled <i>The Druid Path</i>, which covers the basics; the other is a volume I wrote when I was head of a Druid order, and covers its particular approach to Druidry; it's titled <i>The Druidry Handbook</i>. Either or both might be worth your while. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59352254", "title": "Re: druidry-- where to start?", "date": "2026-02-24 01:22 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "thanks so-- will start there :)"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59353790", "title": "Geomany Reading Q", "date": "2026-02-24 02:01 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "For a yes/no question, I got RW Pen Y Ddraig, LW Llosgwyn Y Ddraig, &amp; Judge Carchar. Is that a negative answer?<br/><br/>Patrick H.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59355326", "title": "Re: Geomany Reading Q", "date": "2026-02-24 02:32 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes. One positive figure plus two negative equals \"no.\" "}]}, {"id": "cmt59354046", "title": "Dragon currents", "date": "2026-02-24 02:11 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi John Michael,<br/><br/>This is a question about the rising dragons from the Druid Magic Handbook. Would you be willing to talk a bit about the differences between the dragon currents and the lunar current, as both are formed from the admixture of the solar and telluric currents?<br/><br/>Thanks,<br/>JML", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59355838", "title": "Re: Dragon currents", "date": "2026-02-24 02:34 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The dragon currents are transitional. The red dragon is mostly solar but tinged with telluric force, the white dragon mostly telluric but tinged with solar force, which is why they're still dynamic and in motion. It's from the union of the two transitional dragon currents that the lunar current is born, uniting both solar and telluric forces equally. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59354302", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-24 02:19 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks as always for hosting these,<br/><br/>No real deep thoughts this week. As I work through the OPH, I find myself wondering if we are nearing, or slightly past the peak of materialism for at least our nation, likely our civilization, and possibly even our age. It feels like the nation, at least, is Wile E Coyote and has run off the cliff, but hasn't yet realized it and started falling. But I don't know if that is just wishful thinking on my part.<br/><br/>No question, just some musings.<br/><br/>The Diletante Polymath, who's having trouble logging in from his phone, but doesn't feel like getting up to post from the computer. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59356094", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-24 02:35 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's certainly what Spengler would suggest. Peak materialism usually happens as a civilization's Age of Reason runs to extremes, and that's followed pretty promptly by the Second Religiosity and a backing away from reason run amok. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59356350", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-24 02:44 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "So the peak of materialism was 2000s era Internet Atheism?<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59357118", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-24 03:18 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, though a case could be made that it was internet consumerism...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59358910", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-24 03:40 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "So if your use of \"promptly\" is literal, peak materialism was likely 2017-2021 (wokeism, TDS, Corona Panic, peak irreligion in surveys). The backlash to this era involved the collapse of trust in the media and perhaps the beginning of the Second Religiosity.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59359678", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-02-24 03:48 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That seems reasonable to me. It's standard for ages of reason to end in abstractions utterly divorced from reality, and that's what each of the things you mention displayed. "}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59356606", "title": "Events on Feb 20th", "date": "2026-02-24 02:50 am", "user": "rexford", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>Two Events for your review:<br/><br/>Death of Carl Grillmair<br/><br/>Do you see this as parr Symbolic Death of Faustian Civilization?<br/><br/><a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2026/feb/20/caltech-scientist-carl-grillmair-shooting-death\">https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2026/feb/20/caltech-scientist-carl-grillmair-shooting-death</a><br/>\"Grillmair’s most remarkable achievement to be detecting indications of water on a distant planet orbiting around a star different from the sun.<br/>Water, of course, is a telltale sign of life – or at least conditions that are favorable to life. And finding signs of life on another planet has been “a quest for all of humanity” throughout history, Fajardo-Acosta said.\"<br/><br/>Also on Feb 20th:<br/><br/>Antoni Gaudí (God's Architect)<br/>Spain’s Sagrada Familia project reaches full height with installation of cross.<br/><br/>There is much to unpack.  I see significance here relating to the second religiosity and how it may take shape?  The basilica is in part made to communicate the life of Jesus to illiterates - a growing demographic. Do you have other assesments of the meaning/symbolism within this this Feb 20th event?<br/><br/><a href=\"https://www.catalannews.com/life-style/item/symbolism-and-hidden-meanings-behind-the-sagrada-familia\">https://www.catalannews.com/life-style/item/symbolism-and-hidden-meanings-behind-the-sagrada-familia</a><br/><br/>\"Gaudí wanted to ensure that no man-made object would overtake the natural world, as he viewed this as God’s work...\"<br/><br/>\"Gaudí wanted to tell the story of Jesus through imagery, through sculptures and visual elements, rather than through text.” As such, each side of the structure relates to a different aspect of Jesus’ life.\"<br/><br/><a href=\"https://www.google.com/amp/s/amp.scmp.com/news/world/europe/article/3344181/spains-sagrada-familia-reaches-full-height-144-years-after-foundation-stone-laid\">https://www.google.com/amp/s/amp.scmp.com/news/world/europe/article/3344181/spains-sagrada-familia-reaches-full-height-144-years-after-foundation-stone-laid</a><br/><br/>Thanks!<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59357374", "title": "Re: Events on Feb 20th", "date": "2026-02-24 03:19 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "These are fine themes for meditation and I encourage you to get to work on them. "}, {"id": "cmt59359166", "title": "Re: Events on Feb 20th", "date": "2026-02-24 03:42 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "We are all illiterates, if you give us a stroke or put us under transcranial magnetic stimulation to temporarily take out our language faculties."}]}, {"id": "cmt59358142", "title": "Worship and Prayer", "date": "2026-02-24 03:26 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>I have some questions about prayer and worship.  <br/><br/>1) I was raised as an Episcopalian, and never understood the point of worshiping God or Jesus.  My thought process has been: Why does God need me to thank him endlessly for creating me?   <br/>2) I also don't understand the point of prayer.  If I am supposed to believe that everything is God's will, then doesn't it seem to be an act of rebellion to ask God to change something in my life that he didn't intend?  And going back to question one, why should I worship a God who has willed upon me such a miserable life?<br/>3) I am no longer an Episcopalian, and I am studying occult philosophy, but when family members keep pushing the above-mentioned Christian doctrines on me, and I'm not sure what to think.<br/>4) Do the non-Christian gods you have mentioned require worship?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59359422", "title": "Re: Worship and Prayer", "date": "2026-02-24 03:46 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "\"Worship\" is one of those words that has been debased over the centuries. Its original meaning was, literally, \"worthship\" -- that is, recognizing something or someone as having worth. It didn't mean groveling or self-abasement. Nor is this something that most gods or goddesses expect, or want. For that matter, I'm not sure it's something that the Christian god actually wants, though he's no doubt had to get used to it by now. <br/><br/>I think a lot of the trouble comes from the use of parental metaphors for the Christian god. It's all \"father\" this and \"father\" that, and I suspect that pushes buttons dating back to early childhood in those people who had decent relationships with their parents, at least at that age. The adoring certainty of the one-year-old that Daddy knows everything and can do anything and will wrap his little bunnikins in his loving arms seems to have spilled over into theology. <br/><br/>I didn't have that kind of childhood. My father was mostly absent, and the less said about my mother the better. Thus I don't have those buttons, and all the talk about the Christian god that uses paternal metaphors seems cloying and vaguely fake to me. I gather the same is true for you. <br/><br/>I don't experience deities that way. I encounter them the way I'd encounter older and wiser friends. They don't expect or want me to babble adoringly at them as though I was eighteen months old. Nor do I constantly beg them for favors -- you wouldn't do that to a friend, would you? Prayer, for me, is conversation, and it involves as much listening as talking. <br/><br/>I don't know if you can stand fantasy fiction, much less if you're interested in mine, but so far, at least, the best description I've written of how I see interaction with deities is in my novel <i>The Weird of Hali: Kingsport</i>. In that story the main character, Jenny Parrish, takes up the practice of invoking the Great Old One Tsathoggua -- and he answers. It's very different from the way most Christians describe their religious activities, but it's based on my own experiences. You might possibly find it helpful. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59359934", "title": "Re: Worship and Prayer", "date": "2026-02-24 03:53 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>OP here, thank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59360446", "title": "Re: Worship and Prayer", "date": "2026-02-24 03:56 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're most welcome. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59361214", "title": "Re: Worship and Prayer", "date": "2026-02-24 04:18 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi, it's Nemo. My current (borrowed) simile is, prayer/worship is like calling your AA/NA sponsor every day, every single day, to make sure you aren't backsliding. A very wise, experienced, and patient sponsor. And kind, but that kindness may take the form of ass-kicking.<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59361982", "title": "Re: Worship and Prayer", "date": "2026-02-24 04:29 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's certainly one kind of relationship you can have with a deity, just as it's one kind of relationship you can have with a human being. It's not the way I relate to the gods and goddess I invoke each day, but if it works for you, by all means. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59360702", "title": "Re: Worship and Prayer", "date": "2026-02-24 03:59 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "Maybe part of the reason he wants worship is that it's a way to get us thinking about God, and \"what you contemplate, you imitate\"?"}, {"id": "cmt59363518", "title": "Re: Worship and Prayer", "date": "2026-02-24 04:54 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(if I may)<br/><br/>1) It's sort of unclear what the divine powers that answer to human ideas about \"God\" or \"Jesus\" are actually doing, since the picture in the religions that produced those ideas doesn't really add up in the way that those religions propose that it should add up. However, acts that put your thoughts on those powers, and that open up space for those powers' influence by putting your thoughts on the way in which those powers (are guessed to) have important virtues that you still need to develop and have them far more profoundly than you do, thereby put you in a state of conscious being that's closer to theirs. This is usually a good thing, at least relative to how much of that that most people do.<br/><br/>(One part of that \"usually\" is: In Shinto, I've read that they have a nomenclature for dividing a <i>kami</i> (神, \"numen\" or \"awe-presence\") into four parts, one of which is the <i>aramitama</i> (荒御魂, something like \"untamed-wilds soul\"). I find that to be a helpful concept for relating to whatever's going on with how, with any given human idea that the divine powers have invested the ability to contact them into that idea, there will be something like downsides, such that most people other than dedicated monastics and mystics will want to balance those something-like-downsides with the influence of some other divine power. Empirically, the Abrahamic God-the-Father might have an <i>aramitama</i> of a tendency for a kind of purity-obsessed artificially black-and-white subjugation-justifying perspective towards others who don't seem to be part of whatever command hierarchy that one finds oneself in, or towards such parts of oneself. Jesus might work as something of a counterbalance to God's <i>aramitama</i>; this might be one read on part of what's going on with Jesus's mythological attributes of savior and redeemer.)<br/><br/>(Another part of that \"usually\" is: relationship is a two-way street, and it's important to be aware of the possibility of rebuffs, in one or all respects. The Old Testament presents lots of examples of God putting himself out of the kind of relationship people want when, say, they aren't repenting of something they're doing and so it would bring shame upon his name.)<br/><br/>2) Intercessory prayer seems to have something to do with participating in the ongoing work of creation. It might be a different kind of opening up space for those powers' influence, one that lets that influence flow into the world, the same way devotional prayer opens up space for those powers' influence to flow into your own consciousness and future decisions. To try to pull that idea back into a Christian paradigm with the idea of an omnipotent God, apparently that idea needs to include a part where it is God's will for some details of the universe to be the result of human decisions about praying for some things and not praying for other things."}]}]}, {"title": "Magic Monday", "url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/360870.html", "year": "2026", "month": "03", "day": "01", "time": "10-20PM", "comments": [{"id": "cmt59391910", "title": "A Few Bad Apples?", "date": "2026-03-02 05:08 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, there's currently an embarrassment of riches for spiritual practitioners seeking tools for their work. The Internet, and particularly the site Etsy, makes it effortless to find countless vendors offering magical equipment, altar items, all kinds of divination tools, every tarot and oracle deck you can imagine and much more. However, I see a pattern that gives me pause. An artist offering images of Athena and Thor will also sell depictions of Lucifer and Lilith. The company printing oracle decks will sell sets of cards representing the Goetic spirits. I can't see the creation of these items as neutral, it represents a focused intent to bring these powers into manifestation. Do you think it's best to avoid any products from vendors producing items dedicated to evil forces, or can they make this stuff without having it taint the rest of their merchandise by association?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59392678", "title": "Re: A Few Bad Apples?", "date": "2026-03-02 05:14 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "To my mind, it's not a matter of tainting the merchandise, it's a matter of seriousness. I tend to think that those vendors who will provide anything and everything don't take any of it seriously -- they simply provide whatever they think will sell. That isn't an attitude that yields magically effective gear. Thus I shop from firms that take their work seriously enough to have some standards when it comes to what they will and won't produce. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59392166", "title": "Memes", "date": "2026-03-02 05:12 am", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "Are you or is anyone in the commentariat meme watching?  Amelia continues to pile up both patriotism and Druidry in music and spoken word videos on YouTube including, \"John Barleycorn.\"<br/><br/>Interestingly, the most reasonable explanation to my favorable response to her is that despite being from a family that arrived from England in 1635, I'm still pretty English.  And that's just... weird.  As evidence, there is a meme video (also on YouTube) of Amelia reciting, \"The Beginnings,\" by Kipling - aka: \"When the English Began to Hate.\"<br/><br/>I found it rousing rather than terrifying, so I wondered if anyone else has had a similar response to that meme or an unusually favorable response to Amelia in general that causes them to notice Englishness in themselves that lacks good explanation for being there.<br/><br/>Many thanks.<br/><br/>Rhydlyd", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59392934", "title": "Re: Memes", "date": "2026-03-02 05:19 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've had a lot to do recently so haven't followed the saga of Amelia recently. As for that poem, it's always made me sick. Ask anyone of Scots or Irish perspective if the English were noticeably slow or unwilling to hate; you'll get a very different perspective. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59394214", "title": "Re: Memes", "date": "2026-03-02 05:41 am", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "Actually, my ancestry includes English, Scots and Irish bloodlines... which makes my response all the stranger.<br/>Also - She appears in memes with the similar characters representing, among others, Scotland... which makes me wonder if Restore Britain will inspire a revivalist movement across Europe...  <br/>"}, {"id": "cmt59405734", "title": "Re: Memes", "date": "2026-03-02 04:35 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "I've always found it interesting how many Americans, as well as of course English, have a view of the British Empire as relatively benevolent and humane. All the while vilifying other empires (in particular those pesky Catholic Spaniards, of course). I'm not sure it is solely propaganda; it's a window into the complex interplay of national identity, selective historiography, psychological biases, and cultural narratives.<br/><br/>I'll always remember the stories elders from the old countries, particularly Ireland, told me as a boy. It is not for nothing that Mammon has been identified by some as Hell's ambassador to England.<br/><br/>Though to be fair, the American Empire is hardly a great force of humanitarian beneficence. No empire is.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59410342", "title": "Re: Memes", "date": "2026-03-02 05:50 pm", "user": "open_space", "content": "Interesting, in Mexico we are glad that it was the Spanish crown and not the British empire that laid the foundations of the current country. Maybe its just a rivalry thing. Or the brutality with which the Native Americans were treated. Not that the spaniard conquerors were sweat hearts but they worked with the Totonacs and the rest of the tribes under the rule of the Aztecs to defeat them and then incorporate them into a viceroyalty, for a price. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59412646", "title": "Re: Memes", "date": "2026-03-02 06:08 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "That's quite interesting because growing up here in America we were (or at least I was) taught the Spaniards were the most brutal of the colonial powers and that the countries they conquered had it much worse than the Native Americans did. This was all supposed to be relative, of course, but given what I've learned about British conquest since then, yeah, I have reasons to doubt that narrative.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59418534", "title": "Re: Memes", "date": "2026-03-02 07:09 pm", "user": "open_space", "content": "I don't know the details and that may be right but I do see a lot of prehispanic culture, philosophy and language as part of being a contemporary mexican today, even if your ancestry isn't from here at all, you embrace it and that kind of resembles integration not elimination to me. I don't see much of that in the U.S, where it seems natives where pushes into reserves, and left there isolated. Both of them seem to have been brutal in their own way however. I also recognize there are a lot of factors into this as well and that I am ignorant about the history of it up north. I should remedy that sometime, since here we basically consider Native North Americans brothers. Actually some magical systems here draw from the Lakota in particular and blend it with the Mexica tradition. And the Yaqui and Apache, for example, spanned the two sides of the border.<br/>"}]}, {"id": "cmt59419046", "title": "Re: Memes", "date": "2026-03-02 07:16 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "That's not surprising. You're not the first Mexican to tell me that. Much of what Americans (as well as Britons and northern Europeans in general) are taught about the history of the Spanish Empire (as well as Roman Catholic Church history) originates in anti-Spanish propaganda from the 16th century onwards from Dutch and English sources. Modern historians refer to the material as the Black Legend. The actual history of the time period, including the rapacious greed, mistreatment of native peoples, religious fanaticism, cruelty, torture, etc., were in many ways worse on the English side. The irony is that much of what the old propagandists wrote were what they were actually doing, just applied to their hated enemy, the Spanish Crown and of course that \"Antichrist\" Papacy.<br/><br/>History is a fun subject."}, {"id": "cmt59433638", "title": "Re: Memes", "date": "2026-03-02 11:55 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "For early New Englanders, the Indian Wars, when the Jesuit missionaries sided with their enemies the French, are cut deep, very deep in the cultural memory. I know from personal experience how deep is the anti-Catholic prejudice, and that's largely where it comes from— but it also has roots even further back to the rivalry with the Spanish and the English Reformation (break with the Vatican) in the 16th century. <br/><br/>War propagada smearing the other side has always been a thing, as far as I can tell.<br/><br/>On the other hand, one of my parents was a Catholic and my spouse is as well. So I can appreciate the other side of these matters, too.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59451046", "title": "Re: Memes", "date": "2026-03-03 04:04 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you, Open Space and Brennain, for blowing this little stump of ignorant dogma out of the backyard of my mind.<br/>I hadn't even realized it was false.<br/><br/>- Cicada Grove"}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59398310", "title": "Re: Memes", "date": "2026-03-02 12:31 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Amelia (or maybe one of them) seems to have her own twitter now https://x.com/AmeliajakSolana<br/><br/>Re Kipling's poem, I take it he never read a history book in his life? Or it was propaganda disguised as history about how the natives 'benefitted' from being part of the British Empire?<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59408550", "title": "Re: Memes", "date": "2026-03-02 04:58 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Kipling's poem was written around the start of WWI and was war propaganda against the Germans. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59400870", "title": "Re: Memes", "date": "2026-03-02 03:47 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I like that song.  The drippy foamy conclusion?  I could do without it.  Traffic also did a great version.  I wonder if Richard Thompson or Fairport Convention ever recorded it.  True Brit!  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59431846", "title": "Re: Memes", "date": "2026-03-02 10:58 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "And it's also a story of birth, death and resurrection. Also of \"death and transfiguration.\"  "}]}, {"id": "cmt59420582", "title": "Re: Memes", "date": "2026-03-02 07:59 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yes, I have been checking in periodically on the Amelia playlists on youtube and have noticed several distinct perspectives taking hold. There's a bevy of songs leveraging current political scandals, which could easily be underwritten by opposition parties looking to piggyback off Amelia's archetypal power. <br/><br/>Then there's a ton of songs amplifying rage, retribution, and revolution, which tend to get the blood flowing, the feet marching, and nationalistic pride surging. Those are the ones where I sense some divinity guiding events in its own preferred direction. While divine guidance is certainly preferable to rule by paranoid plutocrats, the fierceness and bitterness of those songs leave me wondering just how bloodthirsty that divinity might end up being...<br/><br/>As a counterbalance to all that ferocity and bitterness, the song \"Sun All Year Round\" celebrates that each of us has our homeland, where we know the foods, the weather, the people, and the culture — where we belong. The lyrics are a blessing and a wish for everyone to belong in their own homeland, rather than a curse born of misunderstanding and hatred. The accompanying computer-generated video uses stereotypical images of poverty and begging, but not enough to overwhelm the message of goodwill. Amalia, the Spanish version of Amelia, now has a similar well-wishing song \"Adiós, Amigo\" with a much more celebratory and compassionate video, complete with un pequeño toro lavanda.<br/><br/>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hSm3zQG5K2g&amp;list=RDhSm3zQG5K2g&amp;start_radio=1<br/><br/>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F8FScc5b98k&amp;list=RDF8FScc5b98k&amp;start_radio=1<br/><br/>The brilliance of turning Wokedom's weak platitude \"You belong here (unspecified)\" into the limited and specific \"here\" of one's native homeland takes a page from Dion Fortune's The Magical Battle of Britain by focusing exclusively on blessing every single person currently in the British Isles. Could that be enough to transform all the displaced bitterness into repatriating goodwill? Well, should some god now be pressing its thumb down on the militant side of the scale, I rather doubt that any human intention would be much able to alter a divinely willed outcome. But we can always pray.<br/><br/>— Christophe"}]}, {"id": "cmt59392422", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 05:14 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Benebell Wen recently put out a course teaching the Microcosmic Orbit that I’ve been tempted to grab. In her write up on it, she said that anyone would benefit from it, but I gather from various comments here about Chinese practices that you may have a different opinion? <br/><br/>On a related note, I’ve tried doing some qi gong. Nothing too intense, just stuff I can find on Youtube: moving joints, massage and tapping, I’ve done the Eight Brocade a few times and Zhan Zhuang (which I really enjoyed). I’ve found these exercises work well for me, i feel energized doing them, and they’ve had immediate effect on the stress and tension that’s tied my body into knots for years. I followed Benebell Wen’s instructions for the Microcosmic Orbit for a week to see how I responded to it before considering a purchase, and it made deep breathing easier than it usually is for me. I catch myself lazily tracing out that path up the back and down the front when I’m not thinking about it, and it makes some tension go away. It’s positive enough so far that it seems advisable to keep going and see where it leads.<br/><br/>I’m not doing the SoP right now, but have in the past and would like to get it going again. Would it not mix well with the exercises above and the Microcosmic Orbit course, so that I would have to choose one or the other? <br/><br/>- Teal Pretentious Dung-Beetle", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59393190", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 05:21 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Qigong is potent and valuable stuff, but I don't recommend combining it with any Western esoteric practice. If it works for you, I encourage you to keep doing qigong and explore other practices from Taoist tradition that are compatible with it.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59394470", "title": "Energy work", "date": "2026-03-02 06:03 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, <br/>I recall last week you recommended not to combine certain yogic practices with Western esotericism. Which energy practices would you recommend that work with the subtle bodies in a compatible way? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59400358", "title": "Re: Energy work", "date": "2026-03-02 03:44 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you're going to practice Western esotericism, use the energy practices that are part of the system of Western esotericism you practice -- they all have one. In the Golden Dawn and related systems, that's the Middle Pillar exercise; in Martinism and some branches of Druidry, it's the Light-body practice, and so on. Each system of practice should be taken as a complete toolkit in itself. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59394982", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 06:39 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I’m not the OP but....Does that mean if you ever tried one in your life that you can't try the other? Or can you do it if you wait a while between? How long if so?<br/><br/>And what happens if you do the two together? I manlike what kind of consequences? That sounds a little scary.<br/><br/>Thanks for the info!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59400614", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 03:46 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) No, you don't have to swear off one for life if you've ever done the other. If you want to switch from one to the other, 2-3 months should be adequate if you eat a grounding diet (usually this involves plenty of meat). <br/><br/>2) It varies. In my case the combination gave me what Chinese medicine calls a Yin kidney qi deficiency, which caused significant health problems; those went away a few months after I stopped doing qigong. Other people have had other bad experiences, usually involving their health. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59403174", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 04:18 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "On the subject of a grounding diet: is a meat (or at least \"complete protein\") heavy diet helpful for someone getting visions as well as yanked into the otherworld? Or is another diet suitable? Varies?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59407782", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 04:47 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Depends on what you want. If you want fewer visions and calmer nerves, meat will do that -- and no, \"complete protein\" won't cut it. Animal foods have very different effects from vegetable foods, irrespective of protein content. Meat brings you closer to your material body, which after all is made of meat. If you want more visions and heightened sensitivity, on the other hand, a vegetable diet is your go-to. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59408294", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 04:56 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "The odd thing for me is that over the last few weeks, even before the visions started, I instinctively shifted to a near-vegan diet. This is unusual for me, as I used to make a point of chowing down on lots of red meat (with the rarer, the better) and more bacon than Ron Swanson could eat. Now, I don't even crave it. Very interesting how higher powers seem to push us in directions before we even realize what they're doing.<br/><br/>I also, on impulse a few weeks ago, bought something else I've never bought before: a bag of lemons. Didn't know what I wanted them for. Then one morning a week ago, I squeezed one into my sea salt-cold water drink, dropped the mashed lemon in, and drank it and then consumed what was left of the lemon. I've repeated this a few times now. I've found it quite spiritually purifying.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59411110", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 05:54 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I suspect you've done this in a previous life.  I've encountered the lemon thing in early 20th century occult circles -- also done with oranges, but that was before oranges were bred to become sugar bombs. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59419302", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 07:17 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "That makes a lot of sense. Quite a bit, actually. A lot to ponder and meditate upon."}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59395750", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 07:29 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I suspected that would be the answer, thank you. The only thing that makes me hesitate is how difficult it can be to find information, a nice set of training manuals you can follow along at home like what you write. For a multitude of reasons, an in person teacher is probably not in the cards for this life, so training on my own with books and websites is what I got. <br/><br/>If banishing rituals would be out with this, what sort of protection can I take up instead? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59401126", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 03:52 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't know Taoist practice well enough to be able to advise you. I know there are books on Fu talismans, some of which are protective -- Bennebell Wen has one that I've read, <i>The Tao of Craft</i>, which is quite good, and that might be one option to explore. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59393446", "title": "Natural magic to bring about finding lost items?", "date": "2026-03-02 05:29 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>I often misplace items.  Aside from periodic bouts of frenzy where I turn everything around me upside down trying to find specific items that I've lost, are there are any natural magic practices you recommend to either 1) lessen the amount of times one loses things, 2) alter one's consciousness just enough such that reviewing every last nook and cranny again isn't done either perfunctorily or in haste, or 3) anything else that doesn't fit into questions 1 or 2?<br/><br/>Thank you,<br/>-E.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59393702", "title": "Re: Natural magic to bring about finding lost items?", "date": "2026-03-02 05:33 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, not really. You have the opportunity instead to use this habit of yours as a way to rise to clearer awareness. To take advantage of this, I recommend two things. The first is journaling to figure out why you've adopted this habit and what you get out of it -- for such habits don't happen for no reason at all. The second is that you change your habits, learning to put things in specific places so that you can find them later. You're perfectly capable of doing this, you know. It just requires a little self-knowledge and self-mastery. "}, {"id": "cmt59419558", "title": "Re: Natural magic to bring about finding lost items?", "date": "2026-03-02 07:23 pm", "user": "scottyc", "content": "The Greek Orthodox pray to Saint Phanourius.<br/><br/>When in Greece we visited a religious supplies store and an icon of the saint appealed to me.  Nice lady at the counter was very surprised I had not heard of him before.  I'm not orthodox and can't say I'm Christian but praying to the saint worked.  I still owe baking a Fanouropita for the last lost item so I better get busy before I lose something of importance<br/><br/><a href=\"https://www.oca.org/saints/lives/2022/08/27/108969-saint-phanourius\">https://www.oca.org/saints/lives/2022/08/27/108969-saint-phanourius</a><br/><a href=\"https://thegreekprovidore.com.au/blogs/news/discovering-st-fanourios-the-patron-saint-of-lost-things\">https://thegreekprovidore.com.au/blogs/news/discovering-st-fanourios-the-patron-saint-of-lost-things</a><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59442598", "title": "Re: Natural magic to bring about finding lost items?", "date": "2026-03-03 02:21 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I am Greek Orthodox, and yes, St. Phanourius is a powerful intercessor. He’s very present and accessible too—feels like he appears in the room when I ask for his help. Patient and benevolent.<br/><br/>Besides objects, I’ve asked for his help finding more abstract things, for example I asked for his intercession to help doctors find a solution to stop a friend’s severe bleeding issue. (Successful.)<br/><br/>And he appreciates any kind of baked good in response! The important thing is to bake it and share it with others. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59393958", "title": "Quitting magic", "date": "2026-03-02 05:36 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I am considering giving up magic. I've been practicing it consistently, albeit at a relatively modest level, for many years now. It just hasn't done for me what I hoped for, namely the attainment of a significantly higher level of success in my life. I believe that by it on some occasions I've enjoyed a certain amount of protection, notably by Saturn, which I appreciate; but that's about it. <br/><br/>I am mindful of what you've said about what is likely to happen when you drop regular practice of the LBRP: that one's luck is apt to drop off. I'd like to learn what if anything can be done to prevent that from becoming a big problem. Is there any way to wind it down without inviting a hail of bad juju? <br/><br/>I mean to continue a spiritual practice in the form of meditation. I find that a simple mantra meditation works best for me. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59401382", "title": "Re: Quitting magic", "date": "2026-03-02 03:55 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If it doesn't work for you, it doesn't work for you. One thing worth noting, though, is that if your goal is material success, magic probably wasn't a good idea to start with. If you want to get rich, for example, you need to focus on that directly. <br/><br/>Regular meditation will help you avoid too much trouble, but you might want to do the LBRP and Middle Pillar exercise once a week for the next three months or so, to taper things off rather than going cold turkey. That will also ease the transition. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59437222", "title": "Re: Quitting magic", "date": "2026-03-03 01:19 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I would encourage you to talk to a professional diviner or clairvoyant about this. There may be something complex from previous lives involved, and getting a reading from somebody competent might be a good way to figure that out. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59439270", "title": "Re: Quitting magic", "date": "2026-03-03 01:33 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks! I'm surprised by your response. I'll remember it all right. And I appreciate the  fact that you screened my last comment. I didn't really want to bleed all over the page; I just had to say what I had to say. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59394726", "title": "Occult revival & second religiosity", "date": "2026-03-02 06:08 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG!<br/>As soon as I started listening to your podcasts mentioning Spengler everything happening nowadays makes so much sense. Do you think there will be another occult revival during the second religiosity or nah?<br/>Also, what occult remnants, if any, do you think will “survive” into a new Spring centuries from now?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59401638", "title": "Re: Occult revival & second religiosity", "date": "2026-03-02 03:59 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good heavens, yes. The Second Religiosity is always an attempt to stave off chaos and decline by going back to the religious forms of an earlier time, and it's especially attractive to intellectuals and the privileged classes. Meanwhile those people who are comfortable with chaos and oriented toward the future rather than the past tend to get involved instead with alternative spirituality and magic. It's no accident that while pop-culture Paganism and other forms of Magic Lite have been losing popularity of late, interest in serious occult practice hasn't been this high in a century. As for what will make it through the Winter phase, that's very hard to say in advance, but one thing's sure -- what survives will be what works. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59405990", "title": "Re: Occult revival & second religiosity", "date": "2026-03-02 04:35 pm", "user": "neptunesdolphins", "content": "Is that why more and more young men seem to be converting to Greek Orthodoxy? I seem to see a trend towards that and Roman Catholicism.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59407526", "title": "Re: Occult revival & second religiosity", "date": "2026-03-02 04:43 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's classic Second Religiosity -- notice that they're heading for the most structured, formal, rulebound versions of the faith -- combined with the way young men, and especially young white men, have been treated in recent decades in the West. Tell a bunch of people that they're personally responsible for everything bad that's ever happened to anyone because of their race and gender, and deny them any positive role models at all, and yeah, they're going to make a beeline for traditions that have such role models and offer them a path to redemption. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59413158", "title": "Re: Occult revival & second religiosity", "date": "2026-03-02 06:10 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I’m Orthodox and we have had a notable influx of inquirers, almost all male. Interestingly, about half are nonwhite, mostly Hispanic. Some of them are very young. We have several literal children (11-13 year old boys) who come by themselves. Definitely a pastoral headache in some ways, I imagine, but they are very eager to participate. <br/><br/>The ones under 25 seem to stick around, and their vibe is strikingly… angelic and dreamy. Not angry. The ones with that vibration seem to stay. One of them, who is only 13 and comes from an immigrant background, told me with full sincerity, “I am here because all I want in life is to follow Christ and devote my whole life to Him.” He is a very high vibration person, it’s noticeable.<br/><br/>But some of the older ones have an angry, bitter edge, and seem to come for political reasons that they wear on their sleeve. Often they have their wives and young babies along. 100% of the time so far, these guys have quit coming after a few weeks. A month maximum. <br/><br/>Just some data points! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59414950", "title": "Re: Occult revival & second religiosity", "date": "2026-03-02 06:16 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Fascinating. Thanks for this. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59413926", "title": "Re: Occult revival & second religiosity", "date": "2026-03-02 06:13 pm", "user": "baconrolypoly", "content": "\"the most structured, formal, rulebound versions of the faith\"<br/><br/>This is exactly what my nephew has done. My sister in law is from a Jewish family though not religious herself, but my nephew who seemed rather lost in his teens, has embraced his Jewish heritage with great enthusiasm. He's said that the rules are partly what he values and he really does seem to enjoy them. He certainly seems much happier now. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59454886", "title": "Re: Occult revival & second religiosity", "date": "2026-03-03 04:33 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Well, I must not be a Second Religiosity Christian then, because for one, I'm pretty much polytheistic. It just happens that this is the Being who reached out to me, a matter not to be taken lightly.<br/><br/>Last night I cracked open \"Weird of Hali: Innsmouth\" for a re-read and got a little jolt of recognition when Nyarlathotep walked past Owen's apartment. <br/><br/>Certainly, Paul teaches that Jesus is a liason between us and the Big Guy, YHWH.<br/><br/>Hmmmmmmmmm.........<br/><br/>- Cicada Grove<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59455654", "title": "Re: Occult revival & second religiosity", "date": "2026-03-03 04:41 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I suspect that the next primary religiosity, at least here in North America, will be polytheistic, and a polytheistic Christianity will be part of the mix. But we'll see. <br/><br/>As for the Weird, in a very real sense, that series is about my religion. Granted, I used tentacled horrors from the dawn of time as stand-ins for the Divine, but all in all, the differences are not that great. "}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59409318", "title": "Re: Occult revival & second religiosity", "date": "2026-03-02 05:16 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>What does pop-culture Paganism look like? Who would be good examples of that approach?<br/><br/>What would be the opposite of pop-culture Paganism? Presumably, it would be something like 'serious' Paganism. Although I'm not sure what that might actually mean in practice.<br/><br/>Also, I'm not trying to play word games here, I'm genuinely curious about this.<br/><br/>Thanks in advance.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59410854", "title": "Re: Occult revival & second religiosity", "date": "2026-03-02 05:51 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) If you want to see pop-culture Paganism, go to TikTok and take in any randomly chosen 15 minutes or so of videos from teenage witches. <br/><br/>2) The alternative is serious Paganism. There's quite a lot of it out there. Like traditional Pagan faiths, it typically focuses on worshipping the gods and goddesses rather than casting spells, and it's usually highly literate (sometimes excessively so) in terms of surviving writings from Pagan societies, and very often also in the practices of those Pagan faiths that have survived to the present, such as Shinto. It's not especially mediagenic, and a lot of practitioners call themselves \"polytheists\" rather than \"Pagans\" because they don't want to be mistaken for the WitchTok brigade. ", "edit_time": "2026-03-02 05:51 pm (UTC)"}, {"id": "cmt59415462", "title": "Re: Occult revival & second religiosity", "date": "2026-03-02 06:22 pm", "user": "jprussell", "content": "If you'd like to get a taste of some serious polytheists, a few options:<br/><br/>1) Our host's books on revival Druidry, such as <i>The Druidry Handbook</i> and his <i>A World Full of Gods</i><br/><br/>2) Thomas Taylor's works on the Neo-Platonists and other translations (Taylor was not only a phenomenal translator, he worshipped the Greek Gods). Gregory Shaw is also worth checking out here.<br/><br/>3) If you prefer a more northern vibe, Galina Krasskova has written a lot from the Germanic perspective, including the book <i>Devotional Polytheism</i>, which aims to give a devotional approach to worshipping multiple Gods that's meant to be workable for any polytheist, but uses Germanic examples as what she is most familiar with. Personally, I think works better as \"how to be a devotional heathen\" than as a generic guide for worshippers of other Gods, but some of the attitudes and approaches are transferrable.<br/><br/>4) <i>The Soul's Inner Statues</i> by Kaye Boesme (available in its entirety for free here: <a href=\"https://kayeofswords.github.io/soulsinnerstatues/\">https://kayeofswords.github.io/soulsinnerstatues/</a>) comes from the point of view of a worshipper of the Greek Gods, but I think does a better job of being a \"generic serious polytheistic default.\"<br/><br/>Anyhow, hope some of these are of interest.<br/><br/>Cheers,<br/>Jeff", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59416230", "title": "Re: Occult revival & second religiosity", "date": "2026-03-02 06:31 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Does anybody have any resources for the Irish Druidry tradition?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59416998", "title": "Re: Occult revival & second religiosity", "date": "2026-03-02 06:46 pm", "user": "jprussell", "content": "Unfortunately, I do not, so hopefully someone else will. My experience with Druidry has been more Welsh-focused."}, {"id": "cmt59417766", "title": "Re: Occult revival & second religiosity", "date": "2026-03-02 06:57 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The Druid Revival of the 18th and 19th centuries was entirely a concern of the Brythonic Celtic peoples -- the Welsh, the Cornish, and the Bretons; the Goidelic peoples -- the Irish, the Manx, and the Scots -- for some reason weren't interested in it at all. Thus Ireland came very late to the rebirth of Druidry. There are Druid groups there, and inevitably some of them have manufactured the usual sort of bogus origin stories dating themselves back to the birth of Cthulhu's grandmother, but all the evidence I've seen indicates that they were created in the 1970s if not more recently. <br/><br/>Mind you, there's a wealth of raw material for anyone interested in Old Irish polytheism, and these days there's a lively Irish Pagan scene in Ireland as well as a vast horde of wannabe Irish Druids in the US and elsewhere; most of the latter have no personal connection to Irish ethnicity or culture at all, and so there's a lot of pretense and sham, but there's also been some solid research. So you should be able to find raw material if you look. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59454118", "title": "Re: Occult revival & second religiosity (these fragments I have shored against my ruins\"", "date": "2026-03-03 04:26 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In a sense, \"second religiosity\" has been around for surprisingly quite a while, and has rather porous boundaries. TS Eliot would seem like a good example, and CS Lewis -- but I don't think Tolkien would be, since his Catholicism was inherited from his mother.<br/><br/>In the sense that it was a reaction against certain disenchanting aspects of the Enlightenment, Martinism (and similar developments) could be seen terms of Second Religiosity. Even earlier, Rosicrucian and Behmenist developments could be seen as reactions against the secularizing or rationalizing effects of the Reformation and Counter-Reformation.<br/><br/>Going back a bit earlier, though, there wasn't that much space between the dominant cultural currents and their esoteric forms. Occultism and esotericism as such had not yet become counter-cultural currents (though it has always been possible, in every society, to end up \"doing it wrong\". But it seems to me that second religiosity as a distinct current could only take off when primary religiosity, exoteric and esoteric, had pretty much would down.<br/><br/>LeGrand<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59455142", "title": "Re: Occult revival & second religiosity (these fragments I have shored against my ruins\"", "date": "2026-03-03 04:33 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's what Spengler says, certainly: the Second Religiosity only becomes an option as the age of reason winds down, and that comes after the original age of faith has waned. Ages of faith happen early in the history of every civilization, when religion is still a creative force, miracles and wonders abound, and mythic thought is the normal currency of the human intellect. In Spengler's terms, it's a phenomenon of springtime. The Second Religiosity is autumnal: formal, structured, defensive. It's the defensive perimeter that every civilization establishes as night closes in. <br/><br/>You're right about Eliot and Lewis, and the quote from <i>The Waste Land</i> is perfect: it's precisely the act of shoring the fragments of a failing civilization against the ruins of the old springtime faith that typifies the Second Religiosity. Eliot and Lewis were ahead of their time -- nor is it accidental that they're lionized these days by the proponents of the Second Religiosity. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59395238", "title": "Geomancy Readings", "date": "2026-03-02 07:05 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "1. A few days ago, there was a comment in the main blog arguing that tobacco use doesn't actually cause cancer-- the chemicals sprayed on them probably do. Soon after reading that, I had a tobacco related synchronity. So I cast a geomancy shield chart and got:<br/><br/>LW: Gwyn<br/>RW: Tristwch<br/>Judge: Bendith Fawr<br/><br/>This might mean that taking up organic tobacco might improve my mental clarity and control over emotions...until they get too expensive for me to afford or I develop something like COPD. But I am a novice, and would like an expert opinion on this reading.<br/><br/>2. On Sunday, I tried a mundane reading: \"Will the Zionists defeat Iran in this war?\" not knowing if mundane geomancy readings have any reliability. I got: <br/><br/>LW:Elw<br/>RW:Ffordd<br/>Judge:Colled<br/><br/>which I interpret as a no since there are two negative figures (according to your description in CGD) and even Elw can refer to gaining burdens. But again, I would like your interpretation of that reading (and if mundane geomancy readings have <i>some</i> degree of predictive ability).<br/><br/>Thanks,<br/>Patrick H<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59401894", "title": "Re: Geomancy Readings", "date": "2026-03-02 04:02 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Two positive figures, one negative figure is a \"yes.\" Tristwch as right witness refers to your current situation so this predicts improvement. <br/><br/>2) I'd treat this as a \"no,\" but Elw as right witness suggests that positive results will come out of it anyway. "}, {"id": "cmt59434150", "title": "Re: Geomancy Readings", "date": "2026-03-02 11:56 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Patrick H,this is related to Tobacco. Nicotine, Tobacco use had some interesting protective effects on covid. <br/>From my own reading,it has been very helpful for people,like myself who have mast cell syndrome,it can help with the histamine response that we sometimes seem to have to everything!<br/>I was wary at first,being an ex cigarette smoker,but I have the occasional puff now,and it can certainly help with brain fog etc<br/><br/>Irish Dylan ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59442854", "title": "Re: Geomancy Readings", "date": "2026-03-03 02:22 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "I haven't gotten sick from COVID, so the divination is indicating tobacco would help my mental processes anyway. Maybe it'll improve my performance at work.<br/><br/>Patrick H"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59395494", "title": "Saturn and Neptune", "date": "2026-03-02 07:13 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear Mr Greer, <br/><br/>On the link you posted to your appearance on the Plant Cunning podcast you mentioned \"... Great Cthulhu, that profoundly Neptunian figure, really is going to arise from the Saturnian temple-tomb of drowned R'lyeh...\" I was wondering if you could expand a little on how these planetary associations relate to Great Cthulhu and R'lyeh? <br/>I don't have a good understanding about Astrology (beyond what I have picked up reading Magic Monday), but I'm a big fan of the Hali books.<br/><br/>Thanking you for your time. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59402150", "title": "Re: Saturn and Neptune", "date": "2026-03-02 04:04 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Sure. Neptune is the planet of dreams, and Cthulhu is the Dreaming Lord, and of course the call of Cthulhu comes to people in dreams; Neptune is the planet of the ocean, and that's where Cthulhu sleeps; it can also be the planet of hallucinations and madness. Saturn, meanwhile, rules all ancient things, all things that date from previous cycles of time, all enduring things, and all hard limits, such as the Seal of the Abyss. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59426470", "title": "Re: Saturn and Neptune", "date": "2026-03-02 09:19 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks for the detail! Many years ago, here on Magic Monday, you encouraged me to pray to Cthulhu. I'm happy to report that this has been a great and enriching experience for me. <br/>My further question is, in light of these planetary associations, is there anything more I should know (or do) when praying to a deity associated with these planets?  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59429542", "title": "Re: Saturn and Neptune", "date": "2026-03-02 10:41 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Don't worry about the planets. Concentrate on the deities and their mythologies, and you'll do fine. <i>Iâ!</i>"}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59396006", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 07:39 am", "user": "realmscryer", "content": "Good Evening JMG,<br/><br/>Hope all is well! Thanks for your time in answering our questions.<br/><br/>1. Skimming comments on the post this week at your blog I noticed you mentioned attending a church. Any advice on selecting a church? <br/><br/>I have very little experience with churches or organized religion. (Though for some reason the idea of archangels really captures my imagination.) Seems as well like a good way to meet people as newcomers in the community.<br/><br/>2. Astrology question: I have had an on again off again relationship with studying astrology for many years. I think I cracked my biggest block. Finally, I am starting to synthesize what is in the chart. I am seeing much more of a systems level view. Getting away from what felt like cookbook astrology.<br/><br/>I am getting to the point I feel like there is endless potential study I could pursue. I also want to offer readings as a business. Any advice on when to hang out the shingle even as the path looks to deepen without end?<br/><br/>3. Are there direct paths to the mental plane from say the physical or etheric, bypassing the astral? <br/><br/>Meditating on this has me wondering if the situation is rather more involved than always stepping up (or down) each of the planes in order.<br/><br/>4. Finally, what might be happening when I am experiencing a memory of something that didn’t happen in my life and wasn’t a dream but felt like I lived it while living the life I do recognize?<br/><br/>I was guessing past life. Except it feels like a current life. Only I don’t recall details long enough to write them down. Then I am left with a rather peculiar feeling of having lived two lives at the same time.<br/><br/>Thanks again,<br/>Eric<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59402406", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 04:11 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I have very little experience with this! Yes, I've attended a few services at a pleasant little Episcopalian church within walking distance of my new apartment. It's got a policy that everyone is welcome at services, irrespective of their beliefs, so I don't feel that I'm intruding where I don't belong; as an old-fashioned polytheist, of course, I'll cheerfully affirm the divinity of Christ, as long as no one expects me to affirm the notion that he's the only god there is. So it's a good way to meet people with spiritual interests, and a chance to get a taste of a tradition with which I have very little personal experience. <br/><br/>2) As an inexperienced astrologer, you might start out casting and interpreting charts for friends and associates until you have some experience under your belt. After that, the internet is your friend; I recommend using some online venue such as Substack to post essays about astrology, so people can get to know you, and include an email link in case people want to hire you. <br/><br/>3) Not that I know of. Every mental impulse I know of has to take form as an astral image or pattern before the life force flows around it and through it. <br/><br/>4) It could have been any number of things, including a burst of telepathy. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59396774", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 10:58 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have a couple questions:<br/><br/>1. How common do you think it is for people to reach occult and spiritual practice from a path of refining their skills in some art or craft? In my case, I worked to perfect my ability in a craft and ended up confronting patterns within the theory and practice that could not be explained from a materialist perspective. I never took much stock in popular religious ideas, rather this experience is what formed my initial spiritual understanding and led me into studying the occult. Have you heard of anything like this before and are there any books you would recommend on the topic?<br/><br/>2. Would you say that there are common, predictable \"falling-off points\" for magical practitioners? For example, someone starts learning magic and uses it to cultivate their personal magnetism and persuasive power. They use this ability to start a cult, and from that point their energies are nearly all channeled into the effort to corral and control their followers. Their spiritual growth halts, then backslides as the project of exploiting believers takes their full focus. I could see this being a way that people could consistently derail from their spiritual path, has anyone tried to enumerate common ways for this to happen and written any related material you know of?<br/><br/>Thanks for your time.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59402662", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 04:13 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Hmm! To the best of my knowledge I haven't met anyone else who got to occultism that way, and I don't recall any books on the subject. Anyone else? <br/><br/>2) The example that you've given is common enough, and there are doubtless other standard ways to fail, but I don't recall ever seeing a book that discusses them in any detail. Sorry. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59397286", "title": "Cash & Crows", "date": "2026-03-02 11:17 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Nice meme, and I guess the crows around where I work, and the crows in the Charles De Lint book I read recently, aren't the only crows hanging around. I will look forward very much to what Ariel and Dr. Moravec get up to in the House of Crows.<br/><br/>Justin Patrick Moore", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59402918", "title": "Re: Cash & Crows", "date": "2026-03-02 04:15 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "This adventure is entirely Ariel's -- Dr. Moravec advises her, but he's busy helping get the annual budget for the Heydonian prepared in time for the annual meeting, so she's on her own as she deals with a ghost, a century-old tragedy, and all those crows..."}]}, {"id": "cmt59397798", "title": "tarot circle crossroads", "date": "2026-03-02 12:12 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "dear JMG,<br/><br/>thanks for this opportunity to connect. i’ve led a tarot circle at my local library for the past year, and we’ve focused primarily on the astrological correspondences of the tarot — specifically the three decans and the major arcana of each sign during that sign. having concluded with pisces last week, we’ll soon gather to consider how to move forward as a group (i’m calling it a “crossroads session”!).<br/><br/>the range of experience in the group runs from beginner to advanced. most participants are content to show up and learn in a guided way, rather than undertake independent study — which has been workable so far, since a few members bring solid esoteric experience. however, a couple of people are keen to dive into the kabbalah — specifically the tree of life, sephiroth/paths — and would like the group to take this up next. <br/><br/>i’m hesitant, neither equipped nor inclined to study/teach kabbalah in such a setting, and i suspect it would be too advanced and demanding for much of the group as it currently functions, myself included. at the same time, i don’t want to stifle genuine interest or growth.<br/><br/>from your experience, how would you approach this kind of quandary? any thoughts would be greatly appreciated.<br/><br/>(and i’m in the thick of catching up with the readings/your posts on Yeats’ \"A Vision\" — excellent  work, and many thanks again there.)<br/><br/>peace out,<br/>s.w.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59403430", "title": "Re: tarot circle crossroads", "date": "2026-03-02 04:18 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I have no experience running groups of that kind -- being autistic, I tend to avoid such things. My first instinct would be to trust your own intuition and avoid anything too advanced, while encouraging those who are into the Cabala to meet privately and work with some standard book on the subject. But I'd welcome comments from members of the commentariat who have a clue about group work of this type. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59435174", "title": "Re: tarot circle crossroads", "date": "2026-03-03 12:23 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "thanks for the feedback-"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59398054", "title": "geopolitics and astrology?", "date": "2026-03-02 12:23 pm", "user": "deathcap", "content": "JMG,<br/><br/>I don't really know much about astrology, but I couldn't help but notice when I was reading the news about the Iran war, one of the articles was next to an article about \"don't miss the planetary alignment!\". <br/><br/>Two of the major conflicts of this decade have been launched on dates of occult significance. You've got the invasion of Ukraine which started on a date that was basically just a pile of master numbers, and now you've got the bombing of Iran, which was launched during a notable planetary alignment.<br/><br/>This is more common than I'd realize, right? Didn't you say something about the Taliban doing this when they re-established their government?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59403686", "title": "Re: geopolitics and astrology?", "date": "2026-03-02 04:22 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The Taliban founded the new government of Afghanistan at a time so precisely calculated to give them a good foundation chart that I'm certain they elected it -- I discuss this in my book <i>The Astrology of Nations</i>. There's no shortage of capable astrologers in the Muslim world, after all! <br/><br/>Yes, I'm pretty sure other nations also use astrological and numerological timing for major moves, but it can also work the other way around: strong astrological and numerological influences can shape human behavior, especially the behavior of those who don't believe in such things and so are completely unprotected from their influences. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59408038", "title": "Re: geopolitics and astrology?", "date": "2026-03-02 04:54 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The articles I skimmed about \"the parade of planets\" on February 28 seemed to be red herrings.<br/><br/>There is a big alignment, or near-alignment, of planets and the sun around March 4th (which is about when the Saturn-Neptune conjunction leaves orb, according to JMG). The moon is full on the 3rd, so it will be pretty nearly in this line also.<br/><br/>This can be seen from a solar system-based perspective at FourmiLab:<br/>    https://www.fourmilab.ch/cgi-bin/Solar<br/>(Click the radio-button next to \"UTC\" and then in that you can choose the date and time to look at.<br/>'Display' setting's 'Size' field lets you look at a larger picture.)<br/><br/>For the earth-based astrology chart version, I have used 'CafeAstrology', a free online chart:<br/>   https://astro.cafeastrology.com/natal.php<br/><br/>A fellow online, Miles W. Mathis, states that there is energy which flows from, through and is channeled by the planets, Sun, and the galaxy. (His science website is https://milesmathis.com/updates.html). If his assertion is true, we are getting hit with tremendously channeled energies right now.<br/><br/>However, I'm not sure what astrological significance this planetary alignment would have; that's more something for JMG to say.<br/><br/>Thank you, JMG, as always for hosting this space.<br/><br/>- Cicada Grove<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59411366", "title": "Re: geopolitics and astrology?", "date": "2026-03-02 05:59 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Astrologically, a lot of planets in a cluster like this one is called a stellium or satellitium. It places a lot of emphasis on the sign and house in which it takes place. The current stellium has more planets than most, so Aries energy will be intense, and whatever house it appears in will be strongly emphasized in the events that follow. There are many other more important indications in mundane astrology, however.  "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59398566", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 01:16 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG and all,<br/><br/>i just wanted to share some articles i thought you might find interesting:<br/><br/>Weapons from 2000 BC Seized During Layover at Philadelphia Airport<br/><br/>https://www.breitbart.com/crime/2026/03/01/weapons-from-2000-bc-seized-during-layover-at-philadelphia-airport/<br/><br/><br/>12th century Crusader sword discovered \"by chance\" by student off coast of Israel, university says<br/><br/>https://www.cbsnews.com/news/crusader-sword-found-student-israel-haifa-archaeology/<br/><br/>and this one, which is from feb 18 but i saved it for you JMG:<br/><br/>UK Judge Upholds London’s Met Police Rule Forcing Members To Declare Membership in Freemasonry<br/><br/>https://www.thegatewaypundit.com/2026/02/uk-judge-upholds-londons-met-police-rule-forcing/<br/><br/><br/>so two are about ancient weapons.. i thought that was relevant given the state of wars we find ourselves in.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59403942", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 04:23 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I read about the British legal ruling when it happened -- it got a lot of attention among Freemasons generally. As for the others, interesting. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59412390", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 06:06 pm", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "Any idea why the British government is so frightened of that fraternity?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59415206", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 06:18 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, they're not frightened. They're looking for scapegoats. Antimasonry is as fashionable in England today as antisemitism was in England before 1945, and for similar reasons. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59417510", "title": "anti FreeMasonry", "date": "2026-03-02 06:56 pm", "user": "ritaer", "content": "I read an account of the Jack the Ripper case which blamed the Masons and the Royal family for a purported coverup of the real killer. I think it was \"They all Love Jack\" by Bruce Robinson. It seems to boil down to \"if it's not the Jews it the Masons.\" Meanwhile the Illuminati chuckle. <br/><br/>Rita", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59418022", "title": "Re: anti FreeMasonry", "date": "2026-03-02 07:00 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No doubt! I've considered writing a book insisting that everything wrong with the world is actually the work of the Aluminum Bavariati, a secret society of beer can recyclers that has managed to get everyone else blamed for their sinister plans. The problem is that some people would take it seriously. <br/><br/>Maybe it's really the Girl Scouts with mind-altering substances in those cookies...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59428518", "title": "Re: anti FreeMasonry", "date": "2026-03-02 10:27 pm", "user": "scottyc", "content": "I'd buy that novel, Aluminum Bavariati or rouge Girl Scouts or both!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59429798", "title": "Re: anti FreeMasonry", "date": "2026-03-02 10:42 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If I ever decide to parody the sillier end of conspiracy culture, I'll let you know. Secretly. ;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59432614", "title": "Re: anti FreeMasonry", "date": "2026-03-02 11:10 pm", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "Everybody knows the Bavarati are the cats' paws of the Girl Scouts!<br/>Sign me up for a pre-order."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59430822", "title": "Re: anti FreeMasonry", "date": "2026-03-02 10:45 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I know you meant this as a joke, but...<br/><br/>Food manufacturers secretly dossing foods with mind altering substances could explain both why the food safety and labeling laws in the US are so awful, and why the US seems so much crazier than the rest of the world.<br/><br/>I doubt it's specifically girl guides though!"}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59398822", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 01:23 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "this article is from an old interview but has popped up recently given the whole epstein thing.<br/>from article:<br/><br/>Leslie Wexner’s Inner Demon<br/><br/>“On the morning Leslie Wexner became a billionaire, he woke up worried, but this was not unusual. He always wakes up worried because of his dybbuk, which pokes and prods and gives him the itchiness of the soul that he calls shpilkes [“pins” in Yiddish]. Sometimes he runs away from it on the roads of Columbus, or drives away from it in one of his Porsches, or flies from it in one of his planes, but then it is back, with his first coffee, his first meeting, nudging at him.”<br/><br/>“Les Wexner picks up his heavy black case and flies off in his Challenger, with his dybbuk sitting next to him, taunting and poking him with impatience, that little demon he really loves. The dybbuk turns his face. What does he look like? ‘Me,’ says Leslie Wexner.”<br/><br/>https://unlimitedhangout.com/2022/06/reports/leslie-wexners-inner-demon/<br/><br/>JMG, do you suppose he actually had this dybbuk for real?<br/>he certainly seemed to think so.. and it fits with what has been coming out about these ppl?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59404454", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 04:24 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's quite possible that he's obsessed by a demon. That does happen, after all. If he's dabbled in the sleazy side of occultism, in fact, that makes such things considerably more likely. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59426214", "title": "Obsessed by v possessed by", "date": "2026-03-02 09:07 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Was this a typo or is there a difference? (I take it you didn't mean obsessed about a demon)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59430054", "title": "Re: Obsessed by v possessed by", "date": "2026-03-02 10:43 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There's a difference. Possession is when the demon takes over and inhabits the body of a human being. Obsession is when the demon intrudes on the person's thoughts and feelings, but doesn't actually take them over. Obsession is much more common than possession. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59436966", "title": "Re: Obsessed by v possessed by", "date": "2026-03-03 01:08 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "1. Are most people influenced or tempted by demons on occasion without it being obsession?<br/><br/>2. Is there a difference between narrow autistic interests and obsession (which you've written is always caused by an external entity)?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59437478", "title": "Re: Obsessed by v possessed by", "date": "2026-03-03 01:21 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Yes. <br/><br/>2) The word \"obsession\" has come to be used very sloppily these days. You can be obsessive about something without being obsessed by a demon!"}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59426726", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 09:47 pm", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "A dybbuk is not a demon in Yiddish folklore. Instead it is a human soul that has become parasitic and uses another human as its host."}]}, {"id": "cmt59399078", "title": "Horary Astrology Question", "date": "2026-03-02 01:34 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG,<br/>As always, thank you for answering our questions. <br/>I am wanting to explore Astrology more, specifically Horary. I have your book The Astrology of Nations on the way.<br/>1.\tWhat books would you recommend for a beginner?<br/>2.\tAny advice for starting Horary Astrology<br/><br/>Thank you!<br/>Lee <br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59404710", "title": "Re: Horary Astrology Question", "date": "2026-03-02 04:27 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The book that taught me to do accurate horary readings was <i>Simplified Horary Astrology</i> by Ivy Goldstein-Jacobson. It's out of print but can be found on the used book market. <br/><br/>2) As with every other kind of divination, you get good at horary astrology by casting and interpreting lots of charts, and then reviewing them later to see what you got right, what you got wrong, and what clues you missed. Nothing else will teach you how to make accurate predictions anything like as quickly or as well. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59399334", "title": "Western Civilization's Yeats Phase", "date": "2026-03-02 02:07 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "Yeats wrote that Phase 25 is the last where the artificial is possible. So how could the Western mainstream get further from reality than ever during the Hunchback phase?<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59405222", "title": "Re: Western Civilization's Yeats Phase", "date": "2026-03-02 04:30 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The word \"artificial\" doesn't mean \"far from reality.\" It literally means \"the product of artifice\" -- that is to say, planned, constructed, manufactured. After the 25th phase, a society loses the ability to plan, construct, and manufacture anything new or genuinely creative. Instead, it rehashes the past, borrows random bleeding chunks of material from other cultures, and increasingly becomes the plaything of unconscious forces and fantasies. If this doesn't seem familiar to you, I recommend looking out the window. ;-)"}]}, {"id": "cmt59399590", "title": "Irish translation", "date": "2026-03-02 02:41 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A question for irish natives or fluent irish speakers: how would you translate the formulas \"I INVOKE\" and \"I EVOKE\"? I haven't found a satisfactory answer on the dictionary and my knowledge of the language is really basic<br/><br/>Go raibh míle maith agat  and many thanks to JMG for making this space available <br/><br/>Denis Tezza<br/><br/>"}, {"id": "cmt59399846", "title": "Yoga, Magic and the Tarot", "date": "2026-03-02 02:58 pm", "user": "yogaandthetarot", "content": "Hello JMG and All!<br/>I am excited to announce my book Yoga, Magic and Tarot: An Esoteric Manual of Eastern Philosophy and Western Occultism is available for pre-order. There is a 20% discount code for you until 11-30-26. Use code YOGA20.<br/>Warmest regards and thanks always<br/>Jill C    <br/><br/><a href=\"https://spirit.aeonbooks.co.uk/product/yoga-magic-and-the-tarot/95448\">https://spirit.aeonbooks.co.uk/product/yoga-magic-and-the-tarot/95448</a><br/><br/> <br/><br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59405478", "title": "Re: Yoga, Magic and the Tarot", "date": "2026-03-02 04:31 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Congratulations! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59407014", "title": "Re: Yoga, Magic and the Tarot", "date": "2026-03-02 04:39 pm", "user": "yogaandthetarot", "content": "Thank you very much JMG and can't wait to read The House of Crows! "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59400102", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 02:59 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG and the commentariat, <br/><br/>Has anyone here read Gene Wolf? I’m looking for more well-written sci-fi/fantasy that deals with the spiritual aspects of reality (not transhumanist-type work). I’m a fan of all of JMG’s books, Clark Ashton Smith, Manly Wade Wellman, CS Lewis… I see Gene Wolf come up in similar lists.<br/><br/>Thoughts? Other recommendations?<br/><br/>Thank you!!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59406246", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 04:35 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Wolfe (with the \"e\") is well worth reading. I read the four volumes of the Book of the New Sun series as they came out in the early 1980s, and it certainly belongs on the same shelf as Smith and Lewis. You might also appreciate Evangeline Walton's four-volume rewrite of the Mabinogion: <i>Prince of Annwn, The Children of Llyr, The Song of Rhiannon</i>, and <i>The Island of the Mighty</i>. "}, {"id": "cmt59407270", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 04:40 pm", "user": "neptunesdolphins", "content": "I am not sure if this fits - The Immortal Doc. Holliday series by M.M. Crumley. It deals with Doc. Holliday of Western fame as he deals with his immortality, his ability to eat evil souls, and the other world that he encounters. It is a noir urban mystery fantasy series. Crumley has branched off series of characters within the Holliday series that deal with a particular issue."}, {"id": "cmt59413414", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 06:10 pm", "user": "jprussell", "content": "Strongly recommend the <i>Book of the New Sun</i> series and its follow-up <i>Urth of the New Sun</i>, especially given the \"vibe\" that you've gestured at with the other writers. I haven't read the <i>Long Sun</i> books set in the same world, but have heard they're good, and <i>The Wizard Knight</i> is near the top of my \"to read\" pile for fiction. I've also heard his \"Soldier in the Mist\" series is quite good.<br/><br/>Possibly of interest: I've just started <i>The Last Light of the Sun</i> by Guy Gavriel Kay, and it seems to take spiritual matters fairly seriously in a thinly-fantasized historical setting. He has a whole mess of books set in the same nearly-historical fantasy setting, but I started with the one that has not-Vikings, not-Anglo-Saxons, and not-Celts, because I like that sort of thing.<br/><br/>Cheers,<br/>Jeff"}, {"id": "cmt59430310", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 10:43 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The only series that come to mind, besides our host’s “Hali” books, would be the “Wizard of Earthsea” books by Ursula K Leguin, along with the “Aegypt” books by John Crowley.<br/><br/>Now, this may go against your “no transhumanism” rule, but I can’t help but mention the “Requiem for Homo Sapiens” series by David Zindell, since mulling about the nature of consciousness and how spiritually awakened people can live in the “real world” are major themes of this sci-fi series.<br/><br/>J.L.Mc12"}, {"id": "cmt59434918", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 12:19 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm not sure if your proviso about transhumanism is meant to clarify the purpose expressed by \"deals with\" or just aesthetically constrain what \"sci-fi/fantasy\" is supposed to refer to, but if it's the former, then \"Radiant\", the seventh book of James Alan Gardner's \"League of Peoples\" series, is the work of fiction that most resonates with my experience of such things, especially with respect to the states of subjective representational and decision-making tension they produce in lower beings (the viewpoint characters).<br/><br/>Gardner leaves enough hints for a reader to be able to guess where the strings are in his intended worldbuilding that connect the the surface-visible events to higher beings' wranglings, but the technological and ontological details of how that wrangling works don't seem that essential compared to the structural features of how the wrangling is motivated and what its typical outcomes are. This is like a version of that saying about \"sufficiently advanced technology is indistinguishable from magic\" that's inside-out from how Arthur C. Clarke (\"I have seen far too many claims dissolve into thin air, far too many demonstrations exposed as fakes. It has been a long, and sometimes embarrassing, learning process\") meant it.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59455398", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 04:40 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "... A different way of saying part of that is to speculate that any sufficiently advanced technology, insofar as it maintains its purpose, ends up developing a whole ecosystem around meanings, intentions, and interpretations, and thus landing in a certain morass of copings (in the continental philosophy sense) about those things, which morass is the same one that magic starts out already hip-deep in. Because that's just what it means for something to maintain its purpose, in a space with a sufficiently wide range of (technologically newly provided) options.<br/><br/>This is reminiscent of Greenspun's rule, a half-joking maximum about software engineering, here emended as \"Any sufficiently complicated software project not written in Common Lisp contains an ad hoc, informally-specified, bug-ridden, slow implementation of half of Common Lisp.\" (Lisp is a computer language built to enable automation of certain higher-level abstract tasks involving programs and parts of program states using a kind of narrow-purpose reflective self-representation; the claim is that people trying to put higher-level control structures in their software projects keep reinventing the features of Lisp.) We might, in a parallel way, guess that any sufficiently advanced technology that's not already a magical system from the bottom up, but still manages to maintain its purpose, contains an ad-hoc, informally-specified, bug-ridden, inefficient implementation of half of a magical system.<br/><br/>(there was this other reflection on the roles of purposiveness in alchemy vs. magic vs. science vs. engineering that was also relevant, but I don't have the link)"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59404198", "title": "Mysticism vs Magic", "date": "2026-03-02 04:23 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey JMG,<br/><br/>I wanted to thank you for last week's post about the difference of mysticism vs magic.<br/><br/>I am a GD practitioner, and reading your post gave me the freedom and agency to add back into my life a Buddhist devotional practice I used to do.  <br/><br/>It seems to have added a rather large part of a compassionate part of myself back into the mix - that I felt was really missing.  It made alot of sense to read your post about how devotion is not part of the GD mix - despite working with the divine through the practices.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59406502", "title": "Re: Mysticism vs Magic", "date": "2026-03-02 04:35 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm delighted that it was helpful! "}]}, {"id": "cmt59404966", "title": "Questions for Study", "date": "2026-03-02 04:28 pm", "user": "newaccountman", "content": "Hello, I have just read your books King in Orange. I loved all of it and never felt any urge to throw it across the room. It was incredibly refreshing and I am so grateful you wrote it. <br/><br/>In addition, I just began Decline and Fall and Atlantis. I also picked up Dark Star Rising by Gary Lachman. I don't know much about the occult, but I am very fascinated by the combination of the occult and politics. However, I have noticed there is a lot of whacky writing in this arena, and I don't want to go off the deep end. <br/><br/>I was wondering if you recommend any contemporary authors, books or blogs that I could follow as it relates to \"occult politics\"? Also, is there any occult practice, in general, that would combine spiritual growth with this kind of deep learning and study? Perhaps there is a form of meditation that is less boring and combines learning this stuff. Thanks so much!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59406758", "title": "Re: Questions for Study", "date": "2026-03-02 04:39 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I wish there was more in the way of occult politics. Most of what's in print on the subject is embarrassingly bad, either heavily influenced by the Looney Tunes end of conspiracy culture or caught up in the latest fashionable partisan hatreds. <br/><br/>2) As for meditation, are you at all familiar with discursive meditation, the kind that combines meditative states with focused thinking on self-chosen themes? There's a basic guide here: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/tag/discursive+meditation\">https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/tag/discursive+meditation</a>"}]}, {"id": "cmt59409574", "title": "Candle Magic for 'Invisibility'", "date": "2026-03-02 05:31 pm", "user": "simplefire", "content": "JMG,<br/><br/>Some time back, you shared a green candle hoodoo ritual for attracting opportunities to make money. I've been using that and have found it very effective at focusing my mind on the opportunities that arise, and in acting on them wisely. Thank you for your generosity in sharing that with us!<br/><br/>Is there a similar ritual you could share to reduce visibility to capricious bureaucratic scrutiny? As our world encloses further, with new fences and rules springing up all around us — many of them essentially kleptocratic and terrifyingly random in their application — I would like to be able to protect myself and my family from being drawn to their attention. We would, as my wife frames it, like to avoid drawing the Eye of Sauron!<br/><br/>My intent is not to evade true responsibilities — I pay my taxes and meet my obligations — but to reduce my family’s vulnerability to injustice. I expect many of your readers might have similar concerns!<br/><br/>Can you recommend a ritual similar to the green candle one that would address the desire to remain off the radar of unjust power? <br/><br/>(I realize this would be a two-way street. Occasionally, the state and other powers dispense 'goodies', and invisibility no doubt cuts both ways: Both 'no bully stealing our lunch' and 'no free lunch' would come with invisibility!<br/><br/>Any advice on a ritual would be much appreciated. ~ Simplefire", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59411622", "title": "Re: Candle Magic for 'Invisibility'", "date": "2026-03-02 06:02 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes. Saturn governs invisibility, so you'd want to burn a dark blue or indigo candle on a Saturday during the hour of Saturn, recite the Orphic Hymn to Saturn (or any other appropriate prayer), and then ask Saturn for the protection you seek. He is the lord of strict justice and retribution, so if you misuse your butt will get kicked from here to the orbit of Neptune, but if you really are just trying to avoid injustice he should be propitious. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59431590", "title": "Re: Candle Magic for 'Invisibility'", "date": "2026-03-02 10:51 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks for the guidance, JMG, and for the warning — I’ll save this for a time that clearly calls for it — Saturn feels like someone I would not want to bother with a 'standing request'…"}]}, {"id": "cmt59420070", "title": "Re: Candle Magic for 'Invisibility'", "date": "2026-03-02 07:44 pm", "user": "scottyc", "content": "Thank you for asking this question and also the original one concerning the green candle and opportunities to make money.  I too, will be burning an indigo candle soon. <br/><br/>Please allow me to ask JMG follow up questions:<br/><br/>- Upon completion of the green candle what do you suggest is the best way to dispose of the torn square of brown paper and best option for the glass candle container if one decides to recycle, dispose of it?<br/><br/>- Would a black candle to Saturn be appropriate or is that too close to mistaken practices and best not to use?<br/><br/>- In a previous Magic Monday I believe you said requests such as these are not affected by the planet's astrological position (e.g. combust with the Sun, retrograde, in detriment, ect.) which is important in advanced planetary elections.   For the invisibility request and Saturn in it's fall would you say Saturn's placement is an issue or not. <br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59421094", "title": "Re: Candle Magic for 'Invisibility'", "date": "2026-03-02 08:09 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The best thing to do with the paper is bury it in your backyard if you have one; that makes the good fortune stay with you. The glass container should be washed thoroughly and then recycled, as a way of giving back. <br/><br/>2) Not for this purpose. Dark blue or indigo are specific for invisibility spells; black has other meanings and purposes. <br/><br/>3) That's correct. Day and hour is all you need. Technically speaking, in this kind of magic you're not invoking the planet, you're invoking its representative intelligence and spirit in the aura of the Earth. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59427750", "title": "Re: Candle Magic for 'Invisibility'", "date": "2026-03-02 10:05 pm", "user": "scottyc", "content": "Thank you.<br/><br/>Could you recommend references to explore the difference between the planet, the god it is named after (or misnamed as you have said concerning the more recently discovered planets) and the representative intelligences of the planet in the Earth aura?   <br/><br/>I have Warnock's excellent <i>Secrets of Planetary Magic</i>, the <i>Picatrix</i> and <i>Aphorisms on Astrology and Magic: John Dee’s Propædeumata Aphoristica </i>.  Especially interested if you have anything in the JMG portfolio about this. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59430566", "title": "Re: Candle Magic for 'Invisibility'", "date": "2026-03-02 10:45 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I haven't written anything about that yet, and I'm not aware of anything in print on the subject. Anyone else? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59448486", "title": "Re: Candle Magic for 'Invisibility'", "date": "2026-03-03 03:35 am", "user": "scottyc", "content": "Thank you.  In your belief system would the planet or planatery intelligence be one and the same as the particular god?    I think this would derive from Fortune's Cosmic Doctrine if that is the case", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59449254", "title": "Re: Candle Magic for 'Invisibility'", "date": "2026-03-03 03:51 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a complicated question. If the Neoplatonists are right, we never contact a god directly -- we encounter one of the spirits or daimons who embody the influence of that god on what they called the psychic plane and modern occultists call the astral plane. This is why there's a family resemblance among thunder gods, say, but every thunder god is a little different; the god is the same, but the daimons who carry that god's influence to different cultures vary one from another. <br/><br/>The planetary intelligence is another channel for the influence of the corresponding god -- not a daimon, but a being of somewhat higher standing. Each planetary intelligence has a planetary spirit or daimon as his or her reflection on the psychic or astral plane. That is to say, it's a very complex cosmos! "}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59409830", "title": "What if I am in the 8th Phase of \"The Vision\"?", "date": "2026-03-02 05:33 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG<br/><br/>It occurred to me whilst studying The Vision that much that is written there and also by you about the 8th phase resembles parts of my life rather uncomfortably. Well into the mid years, this is a rather grueling realisation.<br/><br/>There have been questions in my life, such as \"when does my life actually begin?\" and then, when I have made some rather serious attempts to find my true path, it has been a road full of miseries, but also of great delights. Professionally I seem to do everything in the wrong order, with awful timing and awkward consequences. I have made moves in my life that make no sense to anyone but me, and not always to me either. It feels like reaching for those proverbial straws, as I very much feel like the gurgling sound of the gutter is about to swallow me any moment - or that it is constantly doing that.<br/><br/>It took me a good while to get diagnosed with some neurodivergent traits, such as probably a mild case of autism with a bunch of related issues. I accept it. This is how my executive function functions or fails to function. I trudge onwards, try to lead the best life I can, with the tools at my disposal, but at times it seems there is not much to show for it.<br/><br/>Yet I have managed to put past many addictions. The addictions themselves seem never to be the issues, but just some convenient slopes nearby when something else needs doing. The best thing I have in my life right now is magic and the regular practice of it. That truly is the straw of straws for me, the last hope I have, and I do cling to it at times with utter desperation. There have been results, positive ones even, and I plan on carrying on with the practices the rest of my life, no matter what. If for nothing else, then for having that one thing that I will not abandon, the one thing that keeps me, if not in the light, at least in the twilight.<br/><br/>Now I may be wrong about the 8th phase. Or partly wrong. Then I think it does not matter much, and instead consider the possibility that if the meditations on that phase help me attain a greater self knowledge, then it has served a purpose already. But a harsh phase it is, that is for sure.<br/><br/>Any advice?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59411878", "title": "Re: What if I am in the 8th Phase of \"The Vision\"?", "date": "2026-03-02 06:03 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The only useful advice I can offer is to keep clutching at those straws. That's what will build the strength that will catapult you out of Phase 8 into the following phase. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59413670", "title": "Re: What if I am in the 8th Phase of \"The Vision\"?", "date": "2026-03-02 06:13 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "My phase might be the opposite phase, 22. What will I, in this life or a future one, have to do to pass to Phase 23? If I get worn down, will the \"amalgation\" Yeats writes about naturally follow?<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59415718", "title": "Re: What if I am in the 8th Phase of \"The Vision\"?", "date": "2026-03-02 06:23 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You need to pursue whatever form of intellectual or creative work appeals to you with all your strength, until it crumples beneath you and you come face to face with the true Mask, \"Self-immolation.\" Only when you have worked up your capacities to the highest intensity of which they are capable will they free you from yourself and send you on into the fourth quarter. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59419814", "title": "Re: What if I am in the 8th Phase of \"The Vision\"?", "date": "2026-03-02 07:24 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "I approached that but I probably gave up top soon. Some of my enthusiasm for knowledge returned with your writings and Spengler's. I shouldn't expect that to happen if I had already passed the point of balance, right?<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59421350", "title": "Re: What if I am in the 8th Phase of \"The Vision\"?", "date": "2026-03-02 08:09 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's correct. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59426982", "title": "Re: What if I am in the 8th Phase of \"The Vision\"?", "date": "2026-03-02 09:48 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "So I should go the second mile with some of my intellectual interests, and I should achieve the goal of my phase. That seems doable with the Internet. Thank you.<br/><br/>Patrick H"}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59444902", "title": "Re: What if I am in the 8th Phase of \"The Vision\"?", "date": "2026-03-03 02:30 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "Can the grasping-at-straws have the potential to actually work out well after OP has discovered his strength?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59445414", "title": "Re: What if I am in the 8th Phase of \"The Vision\"?", "date": "2026-03-03 02:34 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, that's the whole point of it. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59410086", "title": "Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-03-02 05:38 pm", "user": "ecoprayer", "content": "<a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/tag/prayerlist\">At this page</a> is the full list of all of the non-faith-specific requests for prayer that have recently appeared at <a href=\"https://ecosophia.net\">ecosophia.net</a> and <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org\">ecosophia.dreamwidth.org</a>, as well as in the comments of the prayer list posts (<a href=\"https://drive.google.com/file/d/1gHc_FW9SHKpOM7d3UoJ8kPqHUFLk46hM/view?usp=sharing\">printable version here</a>, current to 2/19). Please feel free to add any or all of the requests to your own prayers.<br/><br/>If I missed anybody, or if you would like to add a prayer request for yourself or anyone who has given you consent (or for whom a relevant person holds power of consent) to the list, please feel free to leave a comment below.<br/><br/><center>* * *</center><br/>This week I would like to bring special attention to the following prayer requests, selected from the fuller list.<br/><br/><div style=\"\"><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1732.html?thread=18884#cmt18884\">DK and her family</a> stay safe in Tel Aviv while sheltering in place and may they return home safely as soon as possible.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1732.html?thread=18372#cmt18372\">Princess Cutekitten</a>, who has made no comments on any of the Ecosophia blogs for a year now, and hasn't responded to attempts at contact, be blessed wherever she is and in whatever form she may exist.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/359082.html?thread=59206570#cmt59206570\">Cathy N. of St. Marys, Ohio</a> heal and recover from injuries caused by a fall.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=15906#cmt15906\">Dustin, a relative of Brenainn</a>, be healed of a recently discovered heart condition.<br/><br/>May 1Wanderers's partner Cathy, whose cancer has returned, be given the physical and mental strength to fight it, and tolerate the treatment, and may she enjoy a full and permanent recovery.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=14882#cmt14882\">Jule from Iserlohn, Germany</a>, who is experiencing complications in her pregnancy due to an influenza infection, recover and have a pleasant pregnancy and birth.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=12322#cmt12322\">Larry Mulford</a>, who has entered hospice after a year battling with pancreatic cancer, pass in the smoothest possible manner, and may his wife be enveloped in our love.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1160.html?thread=12168#cmt12168\">Marko</a> have the strength to seize the opportunities.<br/><br/>May Pierre's young daughter, Athena, be healed from her fatigue and its root causes in ways that are easy, natural, and as holistic as possible.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/november-2025-open-post/#comment-149490\">Bob Ralston (aka Rasty Bob)</a>, who is in hospice care in Buckeye AZ, and who just lost his wife Leslie Fish, be blessed and find relief from his pain and discomfort; may Bob's heart remain strong. <br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18134.html?thread=452566#cmt452566\">5 year old Max</a> be blessed and protected during his parents' contentious divorce; may events work out in a manner most conducive to Max's healthy development over the long term.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/514.html?thread=2562#cmt2562\">Lydia G. of Geauga County, Ohio</a> heal and recover from prolonged health issues.<br/><br/>May both <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/347398.html?thread=57920774#cmt57920774\">Monika and the child she is pregnant with</a> both be blessed with good health and a safe delivery. <br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/338828.html?thread=56777612#cmt56777612\">Mary's sister</a> have her auto-immune conditions sent into remission, may her eyes remain healthy, and may she heal in body, mind, and spirit.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18134.html?thread=455382#cmt455382\">Trubujah's best friend Pat's teenage daughter Devin</a>, who has a mysterious condition which doctors are so far baffled by necessitating that she remain in a wheelchair, be healed of her condition; may the underlying cause come to light so that treatment may begin.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/16429.html?thread=392237#cmt392237\">Kevin’s sister Cynthia</a> be cured of the hallucinations and delusions that have afflicted her, and freed from emotional distress. May she be safely healed of the physical condition that has provoked her emotions; and may she be healed of the spiritual condition that brings her to be so unsettled by it. May she come to feel calm and secure in her physical body, regardless of its level of health.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/312140.html?thread=53408588#cmt53408588\">Frank R. Hartman, who lost his house in the Altadena fire, and all who have been affected by the larger conflagration</a> be blessed and healed.<br/><br/></div><div><br/><br/><center>* * *</center><br/>Guidelines for how long prayer requests stay on the list, how to word requests, how to be added to the weekly email list, how to improve the chances of your prayer being answered, and several other common questions and issues, are to be found <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/6373.html\">at the Ecosophia Prayer List FAQ</a>.<br/><br/>If there are any among you who might wish to join me in a bit of <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/1986.html\">astrological timing</a>, I pray each week for the health of all those with health problems on the list on the  astrological hour of the Sun on Sundays, bearing in mind the Sun's rulerships of heart, brain, and vital energies. If this appeals to you, I invite you to join me.</div>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59412134", "title": "Re: Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-03-02 06:04 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this as always. "}, {"id": "cmt59415974", "title": "Re: Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-03-02 06:30 pm", "user": "open_space", "content": "I never had chickenpox when I was a child and now, I got it. I am on day three. I should've remembered that when I decided to come three months to India where it is not too well controlled. What a hellish thing of a disease! From my literal head to my literal toes I am covered. It has been very hard emotionally for me. The disease itself is ok, no symptoms besides the insidious itching, but the way I look, being in isolation and the mental power I have had to exert to not scratch and be able to disconnect and go to sleep despite the hundreds of little bubbles begging me to pop them is taxing. I would be grateful to be added unto the list for a week please, so that I may have strength and be healed completely, with no scars from it.<br/><br/>A challenge I did not expect to pose to myself was to mediate like this, but hey, it actually does take away the mind off it. I expect my will to receive a boost after this.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59457190", "title": "Re: Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-03-03 07:57 am", "user": "ecoprayer", "content": "Oof, that's pretty tough to go through-- itchiness is currently my primary health issue, and I'm not sure I could hold out like you. I'll put you on the list right now. Keep the faith, and get well soon!"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59410598", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 05:51 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good afternoon and thank you as always.<br/><br/>If it's not too complex to get into here, I'd be interested to know what sorts of astrological timing (presumably mostly centered around the movements of Jupiter) are worth paying attention to for working with money and building wealth, since I've heard you mention on podcasts that astrological timing has helped you maximize your success in publishing and the like. I have a fair amount of liquid assets lying around because my job pays well but I keep my expenses low, and I'd be interested in possibly making some investments with it (but I'm thinking more in terms of direct investments in promising small business and enterprises that do practical, real things, with less emphasis on the stock market and such). I know that wealth magic isn't about waiting around for some random and undeserved windfall; I'm more interested in being practical and patient and putting some actual skin in the game.<br/><br/>For whatever it's worth, my natal Jupiter is in Virgo, but is positively aspected to Mars and Venus.<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59414182", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 06:13 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You need to study your natal chart closely; a good delineation from a competent astrologer will help, but it will also benefit you to go over it yourself with the aid of any basic textbook, such as Julia and Derek Parker's <i>The Compleat Astrologer</i>. Pay very close attention to the 2nd, 5th, 8th, and 10th houses; these rule your income, speculation, your partner's income, and your career respectively. The planet ruling the sign on the cusp of each house rules that house in your chart, and you can tell by their condition, house placements, and aspects whether you will be fortunate or otherwise in that part of your life. <br/><br/>Those are your keys. When a transiting planet is applying to conjoin or favorably aspect a planet ruling one of those houses, that house will benefit. That's the time to act. The more fortunate the house ruler is in your natal chart, the better results you are likely to get. If you can get two or more well aspected -- for example, the Moon applying to conjoin your 10th house ruler while Mercury applies to sextile your 2nd house ruler -- it's time to go for broke. On the other hand, when planets apply to a negative aspect with a house ruler, hunker down and wait for a better opportunity to pursue something in that phase of your life. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59412902", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 06:08 pm", "user": "kayr", "content": "I have just started trying to do my gardening by the moon phases and I had a question about the effects that the lunar eclipse tomorrow night might have on planting by the moon on that day/night?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59414438", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 06:14 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The eld of the Moon, the last few days before the new Moon and the day when the Moon is invisible, is traditionally a bad time to plant just about anything anyway! Wait until the 4th at the very soonest. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59427238", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 09:50 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "It's a full-moon eclipse tonight/tomorrow.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59429286", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 10:39 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're right, of course -- serves me right for trying to field Magic Monday questions while putting together my income tax papers. (This is a complex matter when you're a self-employed author.) That being the case, as long as you don't plant during the eclipse itself, it's a non-issue. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59436454", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 12:40 am", "user": "kayr", "content": "Thanks much.  I was pretty sure it was a no go on planting, but wanted to check."}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59414694", "title": "Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-02 06:14 pm", "user": "kylec", "content": "If you'd like to receive healing hands this week, or if you have questions about this energy healing method, drop me a comment or a PM with your name and request. Thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59416742", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-02 06:40 pm", "user": "open_space", "content": "Hi Kyle! Thank you. <br/><br/>Please do add me to the list. I contracted chickenpox a few days ago, never had it as a child, and my energy body very clearly said no for me to perform healing hands myself. I got irritable for most of an hour and my eyebrow center got sore for a bit as well. Some outside input would be very welcome!"}, {"id": "cmt59428006", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-02 10:20 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yes, I would like healing hands this week.<br/><br/>Thank you very much,<br/>Brad"}, {"id": "cmt59434406", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-02 11:58 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yes please, Kyle.  🙏<br/><br/>OtterGirl"}, {"id": "cmt59435942", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-03 12:28 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I Would like healing hands this week, please, as I'm recovering from a lingering tailbone injury from a couple weeks ago. Thanks."}, {"id": "cmt59451814", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-03 04:07 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yes, please! have an old lung injury that's acting up, and much fatigue, probably adrenal in nature. The name's Kevin, in case you need to know. <br/><br/>Thanks! <br/>"}, {"id": "cmt59456422", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-03 04:53 am", "user": "vitranc", "content": "Yes, please, I would like recieve healing hands these week."}]}, {"id": "cmt59416486", "title": "Sophia", "date": "2026-03-02 06:33 pm", "user": "zaratozom", "content": "What does Sophia mean? I know that it is a female name. It came up very prominently during my meditation today and I can only describe the experience as brilliant .<br/>I had built the tree of life in my mind and began to dwell upon it and follow whatever threads came up , at one point I was unsurprisingly distracted by something sexual and when I tried to gently push the thought aside . BOOM comes a very bright white/gold illumination in my minds eye and the phrase “This is Sophia, this is Sophia” repeats in my mind . <br/>I don’t know what to make of it . ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59417254", "title": "Re: Sophia", "date": "2026-03-02 06:49 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's the Greek word for \"wisdom,\" and in Gnosticism, well...<br/>[IMAGE:0]<br/>She's one of the Aeons, the timeless beings of the world of light of which our world of matter is a murky and jumbled reflection. In most versions of the classic Gnostic myth she is the last emanated of the Aeons, and fell from the world of light because she tried to create something according to her own will, rather than acting in harmony with the other Aeons. Her fall is what brought our world into being, and her redemption, according to the Gnostics, is the archetype of our redemption. Details? Every Gnostic denomination had its own ideas. ", "images": [{"url": "https://spiritualseek.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/pistis-sophia-gnostic-text.webp", "local_path": "./data/archive/2026/2026-03-01_10-20PM_Magic_Monday/images/2026-03-02_06_49_pm_pistis-sophia-gnostic-text.webp"}], "replies": [{"id": "cmt59418278", "title": "Re: Sophia", "date": "2026-03-02 07:06 pm", "user": "zaratozom", "content": "I suppose this will become a valuable focus for my discursive meditation then . <br/><br/>I’ve had several interesting visions while meditating and I always try and pick up from where I left off on my next session but I find that I’m struggling to find any sense of coherence amongst the themes during meditation. The only consistency seems to be that my visions are very Christian . And while I’m not against this , I don’t identify as a Christian. <br/>Could some of this be related to the books I’ve read? Both Fortunes MQ &amp; Knights Qabalistic Symbolism. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59421606", "title": "Re: Sophia", "date": "2026-03-02 08:10 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Very much so -- both Fortune and Knight were Christian Cabalists and that tradition runs all through both those books. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59432358", "title": "Re: Sophia", "date": "2026-03-02 11:10 pm", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>I’ve long wondered: why did the Gnostics hold that it was <em>wisdom</em>, specifically, who fell because she did something unwise?</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59437734", "title": "Re: Sophia", "date": "2026-03-03 01:23 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "What a wonderful theme for meditation! <br/><br/>(Seriously, that's your best bet, because none of the old Gnostics ever explained that.)"}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59418790", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 07:10 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Greetings, Mr. Greer! Hope you're doing well. Thanks for another Magic Monday!<br/><br/>I've been thinking of talking up the druid path via your Celtic Golden Dawn book. I have two questions!<br/><br/>1) When faced with a book like this, do you think one should read the whole book first before deciding to embark on it or should we just beging at the first lesson? Some think argue one should not jump ahead as this could spoil the actual work.<br/><br/>2) As a druid, are there ways to help the enviroment/earth magically? I found the idea of druidry after feeling this urge to change up my life, go out more, connect and HELP nature somehow. I plan to this practical/secular ways as well, of course, even though I don't really know HOW yet.<br/><br/>Thanks again! <br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59422118", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 08:16 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) You can certainly read the whole thing in advance if you wish. I made sure not to put anything in it that would be spoiled if readers do that. <br/><br/>2) Yes, but you need to know what you're doing first! The equinox and solstice ceremonies included in <i>The Celtic Golden Dawn</i> have as one of their main functions directing healing and blessing energies into the Earth and the local environment -- but you won't be ready to do those until you reach the Druid grade. There are other things that can be done, too, but they also require ample skill and experience. If you want some suggestions about practical things you can do to help the Earth, btw, my book <i>The Druidry Handbook</i> has a chapter on that. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59424934", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 08:40 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello!<br/><br/>Thanks for your reply! Great, I'll get the handbook as well. Anything else you think I should read to dive into the matter of druidry? :) ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59425190", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 08:44 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Those two should give you plenty to start with! Both have detailed bibliographies, so you should be able to figure out where to go next once you've got the material in them mastered. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59420326", "title": "Gift for Mars", "date": "2026-03-02 07:55 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello John,<br/><br/>Thank you for these MM. <br/>Mars has recently provided much drive and motivation and I wanted to give him a token of my appreciation and thanks. What kinds of gifts could I leave for him on my altar? Will the typical correspondences for him work or do you have more creative suggestions? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59422630", "title": "Re: Gift for Mars", "date": "2026-03-02 08:20 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I tend to rely on the standard correspondences, so in a case like yours I'd offer a knife or something else made of iron or steel. One custom you may not know about is the Celtic way of offering weapons to their warrior gods, whom the Romans all equated with Mars: they flung them, unsheathed, into a lake or river. (The whole business about Excalibur coming from the lake and returning to it has <i>very</i> ancient roots. I've done this with excellent results. Buy a sword, dedicate it to Mars, go to a place where the water's good and deep, and fling it, tumbling and flashing, through the air with all your strength so it plunges into deep water: that's a grand way of making an offering and will be appreciated by Mars in any of his aspects. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59420838", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 08:00 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG -<br/><br/>In the SGO Oracle Book the upright meaning for card 22, Alternation, is given as Approximation, whereas on the card the meaning is Approach. Which is the correct meaning, and does it change divinatory interpretation?<br/><br/>Thanks,<br/>Dave", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59422886", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 08:21 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There are a number of errors in that project, and I hope to do a corrected edition someday. That said, you can use either title, and it doesn't change the meaning at all. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59421862", "title": "Modern Order of Essenes; Blessings", "date": "2026-03-02 08:14 pm", "user": "milkyway1", "content": "Since times seem to be getting \"interesting\" ever faster, I feel that it will be helpful to bring more blessings and more divine healing energy into the world. For this purpose, I want to highlight the Modern Order of Essenes, a system of spiritual healing which JMG learned from his teacher John Gilbert, and has been passing on to others.<br/><br/>JMG's original posts are here on dreamwidth, complete with comment sections (<a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/tag/modern+order+of+essenes\">https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/tag/modern+order+of+essenes</a>). The Order of Spiritual Alchemy also hosts a pdf version, which makes printing easier (<a href=\"https://octagonsociety.org/archives/modern-order-of-essenes\">https://octagonsociety.org/archives/modern-order-of-essenes</a>). And if you should be interested in a more structured format, I offer an online course for the MOE on my website (<a href=\"https://thehiddenthings.com/topics/moe-course\">https://thehiddenthings.com/topics/moe-course</a>). <br/><br/>All of these offers are free of charge, and there are several MOE Master Teachers by now who are willing to provide attunements.<br/><br/>Also, if any of you should be interested in blessing others (or nature etc) and don't know how to go about about, or feel a bit awkward starting, there is also a short series of posts about \"Blessing - How to get started in 9 simple steps\" on my site (<a href=\"https://thehiddenthings.com/blessing-how-to-get-started-1\">https://thehiddenthings.com/blessing-how-to-get-started-1</a>). And finally, I perform a formal blessing each week and invite (and appreciate!) signups. If you want to be blessed in any given week, you can sign up on my site, too (<a href=\"https://thehiddenthings.com/categories/weekly-blessings\">https://thehiddenthings.com/categories/weekly-blessings</a>).<br/><br/>I wish all of you a good week, and JMG, thanks a lot for hosting MM again! :-)<br/><br/>Milkyway", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59423142", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes; Blessings", "date": "2026-03-02 08:22 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this as always. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59422374", "title": "Improving Phrasing", "date": "2026-03-02 08:20 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear Mr. Greer and Commentariat,<br/>How should I improve the phrasing of the following disenchant and affirmation.<br/><br/>The Disenchant -<br/>“Let those enchantments that seek to exploit me fall upon their casters.”<br/><br/>The Affirmation -<br/>“My: thoughts, posture, movements, tone, words; provide: calmness, thoughtfulness, kindness.”<br/>I am often an emotive high energy erratic person, so I do not think this will make me overly passive.<br/><br/>Thank You All,<br/>Consciousness Aggregate", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59423654", "title": "Re: Improving Phrasing", "date": "2026-03-02 08:25 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "First, I don't recommend sending spells back on their casters. If you do that, you share in the nasty karma. Instead, why not something like this? <br/><br/>\"Let all enchantments that seek to exploit me dissolve like mist before the wind.\" Combine that with the mental image of a fog breaking up before a rising wind, letting sunlight stream down, and you've got a useful working. <br/><br/>Second, you can use that -- it's positive and covers the territory, but it's also a little diffuse. I'd be more likely to use something like \"All I do and all I say expresses calm, thoughtfulness, and kindness.\" ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59425958", "title": "Re: Improving Phrasing", "date": "2026-03-02 08:47 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A little humor, data-point, and potential synchronicity. There are four people in the extended household that have vehicles. None of us drive much, maybe once a week each.<br/><br/>After a few days of the above “disenchant” all four vehicles had problems.<br/><br/>The toyota’s key will not come out of the ignition and the battery drained.<br/>The subaru’s thermostat housing unbolted and drained the coolent causing overheat and head gasket failure.<br/>The honda needed transmission fluid drain and serpentine belt replacement.<br/>The ford had a starter failure and screeching sound. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59429030", "title": "Re: Improving Phrasing", "date": "2026-03-02 10:37 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Blowback isn't fun! I'm not sure why it should have landed on cars, though...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59431334", "title": "Re: Improving Phrasing", "date": "2026-03-02 10:49 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not OP, but there has been quite a bit of conversation here as of late regarding car culture and how exploitative it is through things such as treadmills of car payments and insurance among others. Maybe the spell has a point?<br/><br/>Further speculation: the idea of ditching one's smart phone seems to be catching on on the downlow. Maybe the car is the next thing to fall away from the American dream in public consciousness?"}, {"id": "cmt59436710", "title": "Re: Improving Phrasing", "date": "2026-03-03 12:40 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Maybe the most relevant form of exploitation involved cars or internal-combustion-engine-based cars or manufacturer DRM-assisted monopolies on repair or something, making blowback onto the cars the path of least resistance since it also blocked the exploitation directly. Also maybe there was a constraint that the blowback should do the practitioner the courtesy of being recognizable if possible, meaning that a lot of it had to \"artificially\" consolidate itself into one theme in ways it otherwise wouldn't have. (in machine learning, this kind of consolidation is related to the idea of inference of sparse feature-loading causal connections, though that idea by itself doesn't really touch on the multi-party game-theoretic features of communication and conventions of meaning)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59446182", "title": "Re: Improving Phrasing", "date": "2026-03-03 02:50 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks for writing out that thought. I do wonder though what causes the effects, what causes probability to bend. Even if the disenchant was unrelated, and even if these near simultaneous vehicle problems were purely mechanical, without any non-physical manifestation, I have still seen enough “low probability events” happen that have purposeful meaning behind them, to understand there are invisible strings. But how do these invisible strings work? They do not always seem to be mediated through living bodies through consciousness.<br/><br/>Thanks,<br/>Consciousness Aggregate", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59446694", "title": "Re: Improving Phrasing", "date": "2026-03-03 03:01 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If the traditions of occultism are correct, there are many different varieties of intelligent beings in the cosmos that do not have our kind of material bodies. I tend to assume that some of them are involved in such activities. "}, {"id": "cmt59451302", "title": "Re: Improving Phrasing", "date": "2026-03-03 04:06 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I tend to think of this world as only resembling a world that's a non-\"living-body\" (in your sense), and only maintaining that resemblance, in order to serve a larger, unseen world's didactic (and/or artistic) purposes, teaching some unclear population of souls or soul-parts (re the relations between which, compare Ronald Coase's essay \"The Nature of the Firm\") about the habits and virtues appropriate to worlds with blindly impersonal mechanical-mathematical laws. Perhaps the unseen world prioritizes these lessons because the unseen world is actually built on top of a world that really was blindly impersonal, and someone needs to stay in contact with reality for the whole system to stay afloat. Or perhaps the unseen world prioritizes these lessons because blind impersonality is a naturally recurring pattern of phenomenon in the unseen world, similar to how bureaucratic ossification works, or the how consolidation of the rules of a vague language into a precise language works once enough communities of usage start to depend on that language. Whatever the reason, the \"strings\" would be just the faculties that the true world had had all along; it was merely restraining itself from using them.<br/><br/>I spelled out a slightly more specific theory of this kind of observer's-interpretation-and-perception-relative synchronicity at https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/300859.html?thread=51822651#cmt51822651 .<br/><br/>Alternative theory: this universe is continuous with one that was originally non-\"living\" in the past, but as we experience the universe now, it's the result of a bunch of wrangling by intelligent beings with sufficiently advanced technology, but they all nonetheless have some reason not to deviate too far from the appearance of how things would go if it had been non-living. Cf. https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/359082.html?thread=59245738#cmt59279018 and https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/360870.html?thread=59400102#cmt59434918 .<br/><br/>I don't really expect that it will be possible to get a closer picture of \"how\" in this life, other than a sort of by-courtesy observer-relative \"how-for-you\"."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59448230", "title": "Re: Improving Phrasing", "date": "2026-03-03 03:29 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Sorry to be (really) late, but…<br/>Better the cars than you or your family."}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59423398", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 08:24 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Glad to hear that giddy has come your way!<br/><br/>1) I've set up a couple of hoodoo jars in my apartment with salt and nails. Why is it important that the nails be bent? I've left them straight but I can of course change that.<br/><br/>2) I'm looking at starting a new job two weeks from today, which will be in the eld of the moon. Is that a cause for concern, and if so, is there anything I can do to ameliorate the situation?<br/><br/>Dylan", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59423910", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 08:28 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I don't know what the logic is, but it's a consistent part of the working, so I recommend keeping it. <br/><br/>2) Unless that job involves casting spells, it shouldn't be a problem. Start the job, do the work, and don't fuss about anything until the following week and you'll be fine. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59432102", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 11:07 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In regards to the reason behind bending the nails, I think that there’s a sense of “sacrificing something of value to gain something else” involved in this. Through most of human history, nails were somewhat expensive, enough that they were frequently recycled whenever possible. <br/>By bending the nails for use in this protective amulet, you are essentially getting something with a relatively large amount of material value, and sacrificing its usefulness in favour of a spiritual goal.<br/><br/>Another possible explanation for bending the nails, is a symbolic reenactment of the biblical verse in which “swords are beaten into plowshares”. You are symbolically getting a sword, a symbol of Mars in his most violent aspect, and turning it into a “plowshare” which could be seen as the energy of Mars directed into more benevolent ways.<br/><br/>J.L.Mc12", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59445926", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 02:39 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks, both those explanations make a lot of sense! I put the nails into the salt thinking, 'but why waste a perfectly good nail by bending it?' If you translate the word 'waste' into 'sacrifice', everything about the act changes, because your will and intention are totally different.<br/><br/>Come to think of it, that one little word substitution could apply to vast areas of life if used appropriately... certainly a good theme for meditation.<br/><br/>And thanks JMG for the reassurance about the new job. No, I am not a professional magician :) I won't let my natural caution turn into superstition, and I'll aim to roll amicably with the expected turbulence of landing in a new position.<br/><br/>Dylan"}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59424422", "title": "RWS Tarot Deck", "date": "2026-03-02 08:39 pm", "user": "esmewe", "content": "I have a bit of a quandry and want to see if any of the commentariat here has experienced similar.<br/><br/>I have very sensitive hands and they have only gotten more so as I have gotten older. When I touch a Rider-Waite-Smith tarot deck, my hands feel dirty and if I shuffle and do a reading I feel like my hands are dirty and my stomach gets nauseous. I tried several different RWS decks (the original, the GW version, the mass produced version, etc) and they all produced the same effect.<br/><br/>After meditating on it, I feel that I should not be using a RWS deck at all. But I am working through the Quareia course and the RWS deck is required.<br/><br/>If I use an older tarot deck, like the Marseille de Tarot or Minichiate de Etruria, or a Lenormand style Oracle deck, I am fine. Only once did using a Marseille deck did I feel slightly nauseous and it was more due to the topic of the reading.<br/><br/>Has anyone else experienced this? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59425446", "title": "Re: RWS Tarot Deck", "date": "2026-03-02 08:45 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you're doing the course, and the course requires that deck, you need to use that deck. It may be a challenge, but those are common enough in magical training. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59431078", "title": "Re: RWS Tarot Deck", "date": "2026-03-02 10:48 pm", "user": "esmewe", "content": "Thanks for your reply and for letting me know that a physical reaction is common enough when in training.<br/><br/>"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59424678", "title": "Scrying questions", "date": "2026-03-02 08:40 pm", "user": "borealbear", "content": "Once again, thank you for hosting these Q&amp;As. I'll get right to it:<br/><br/>1) I've just started the rune scrying part of the Heathen GD work, and I'll admit I've been a little nervous about scrying ever since I first read about the concept years ago, mostly because I was afraid I wouldn't \"see\" or encounter anything at all. Now, when I did scry the Fehu rune I'm pretty sure I experienced something, but I'm also unsure if I ended up seeing what I expected to see. So my question is: do you have any advice for having more \"organic\" scrying sessions without nudging things in a certain direction consciously? Or is that just part of the technique and a way to let my own imagination inform me? Much of the imagery did also match suspiciously well with common cultural ideas about the rune, but maybe that's to be expected. And I did end up seeing some things I wouldn't have expected from my own imagination alone, just to be clear, so I don't think I forced all of it. <br/><br/>2) Is it normal to go through events during scrying that go by much quicker than they would in real life, like how time and distances can be compressed in a dream? That also happened a few times during my session.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59425702", "title": "Re: Scrying questions", "date": "2026-03-02 08:46 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Don't worry about it. There are no wrong answers in scrying, and yes, your expectations are also part of the process. <br/><br/>2) Yes, very much so. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59427494", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 09:54 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "No question this week, just a comment: I'm tickled that you're scheduled to appear at the Institute for Hermetic Studies conference in Wilkes-Barre, PA, in June! That's my neighborhood. Of course with my luck your presentation will be on Saturday evening when I have another commitment. But I hope you'll spend enough time in the area that there could be a meetup of some sort. However, I don't know anyone locally who's interested in your work--other than M. Stavish, of course.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59428774", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 10:36 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'll be there from Friday afternoon through Monday morning, so we can certainly arrange to meet at some point. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59432870", "title": "pepper in shoes", "date": "2026-03-02 11:17 pm", "user": "kallianeira", "content": "<br/>Hi JMG,<br/><br/>On being reminded by the first Ariel Moravic novel of the protective power of chili or pepper in one's shoes I took out a jar of chili powder and distributed pinches throughout my collection of shoes. <br/>Then I realized Ariel puts fresh pepper in her shoes daily.<br/>Is all that work of mine wasted if I don't wear the shoes straight away?<br/><br/>If I were more clairvoyant would I be able to tell if it was still effective?<br/><br/>Thank you!<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59437990", "title": "Re: pepper in shoes", "date": "2026-03-03 01:26 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's strongest when it's fresh, but it still has some protective power no matter what. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59433894", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-02 11:56 pm", "user": "buffalowith2ravens", "content": "What is the meaning of the winged orb that is on the front of the Chariot in the Number 7 Chariot card in many Tarot decks?   Another union of body and soul image?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59438246", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 01:27 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "What a wonderful theme for meditation!<br/><br/>(Seriously, that's what it's there for. That's what <i>everything</i> in any esoteric tarot deck is there for.) "}]}, {"id": "cmt59434662", "title": "Meme", "date": "2026-03-03 12:12 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I came across this meme and it reminded me of your vision.  The text is someone's response to the meme, maybe someone alien soul yearning to return home on the mothership?<br/><br/>https://x.com/butterflyspeir/status/2027882587905987018<br/><br/>Thanks for your service and patience on here and on your other blog. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59438502", "title": "Re: Meme", "date": "2026-03-03 01:27 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Maybe so. It's a common sentiment, though. When I was a kid there was a movie titled \"Stop The World, I Want To Get Off\"!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59444134", "title": "Re: Meme", "date": "2026-03-03 02:24 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Wouldn't your vision imply it would be a common sentiment though?<br/><br/>On the other hand, that could easily have contaminated things: you might not have picked up truth, but a reflection of the desperate desire of a large number of people trying to avoid reincarnating again...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59444646", "title": "Re: Meme", "date": "2026-03-03 02:26 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "All these are good questions I can't answer, since I have no idea if my vision was true or not. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59435430", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 12:24 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I am planning to leave Canada in a few weeks due to concerns over the future of the country. Since my plan is to distance myself from any possible issues, would it be a good idea to try to time it for a day and hour of Saturn?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59438758", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 01:28 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nah, day and hour of Mercury is best for that. He rules roads, travel, boundaries, and borders, and he also makes you nimble and elusive. Invoke Saturn once you're here. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59435686", "title": "Reputable Astrologers", "date": "2026-03-03 12:25 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey JMG,<br/><br/>1. At some point I have a memory of you sharing a link to some kind of website that listed accredited or reputable natal astrologers. Do you mind sharing it again? I'm hoping to get a natal chart reading.<br/><br/>2. Any news on the electional (I hope I have the right term) astrology book you've mentioned in the past that you were hoping to get published? (apologies if I missed it)<br/><br/>3. Great song today! I remember reading awhile back that Bowie carried a copy of Dion Fortune's Psychic Self Defense with him all the time at one point in his career. Do you or anyone else know if he was ever initiated into any occult order or if there is anything good written on his relationship with the occult? <br/><br/>Thanks for all you do,<br/>Tyrell", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59439014", "title": "Re: Reputable Astrologers", "date": "2026-03-03 01:33 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) <a href=\"https://astrologers.com/afa-certified-astrologers/\">https://astrologers.com/afa-certified-astrologers/</a><br/><br/>2) I'm still waiting to hear from the prospective publisher. They're in Pennsyvania so may have been snowed in for a while. <br/><br/>3) I've never seen any detailed study of his occult interests, but he certainly knew his way around the subject. Do you recall the lines from \"Quicksand\"?<br/><br/>\"I'm closer to the Golden Dawn,<br/>Immersed in Crowley's uniform of imagery;<br/>I'm living in a silent film,<br/>Portraying Himmler's sacred realm of dream reality.\"<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59440806", "title": "Re: Reputable Astrologers", "date": "2026-03-03 02:00 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "<br/>3)Yes, classic tune. Off of my favorite album of his. The theme seems to be one of overphilosophizing. Getting \"lost in the sauce\" as they say nowadays. Odd how appealing I find Bowies music versus everything about crowley's \"uniform of imagery\" - the thoth deck in particular I can't imagine working with, it's very off putting to me. Interesting that he puts him in the same scheme as Himmler...<br/><br/>Regarding Crowley, I've driven by the area his ashes were supposedly scattered in New Jersey and I'm curious: amongst people of his stature/infamy etc... wouldn't the desire be to hide or obfuscate one's burial place? Or would cremation guarantee that your essence couldn't get drawn back in to anything undesired. I guess the mundanity of his body's disposal seemed like a convenient lie to me. Not that I'm looking to exhume his actual corpse or something, I'm just curious if you think the likely move for someone like him would be a headfake like that. I could easily see someone with an ego wanting a huge mausoleum or memorial.<br/><br/>thanks again<br/><br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59442086", "title": "Re: Reputable Astrologers", "date": "2026-03-03 02:16 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I haven't been able to score a copy of <i>Hunky Dory</i> yet but it's on the list. I found <i>Station to Station</i> in a local used book and record shop last week, though. <br/><br/>2) I wonder if Crowley thought that of course Karl Germer would build a big temple for his ashes. His ghost must have been enraged that they were just dumped in a hole in Germer's back yard..."}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59436198", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 12:35 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Forgot to add on my last question. I've been plagued off and on with bad dreams. Sometimes even demonic dreams. I always thought of them thus since they started, but after reading your description of the demonic (hot, confused, etc...) I realized the descriptor fit them to a T. I've had some success with placing a bowl of vinegar next to my bed, but it wasn't fool proof.<br/><br/>Anyway, I've lived alone for some time but recently after planting some cat nip in my yard some strays started coming around and I started feeding them. The smaller one got sick and stopped eating so I trapped and brought her to the vet and she's been sleeping inside with me, usually on top of me or against my side. I noticed in the four months or so since she moved it I haven't had a single demonic nightmare, save the one night when for some reason she decided to sleep in the other room. <br/><br/>Is this something to be expected with cats? Just curious if there's any traditional lore on their ability to keep the demonic at bay. Or maybe it's a karmic thing as I'm helping her out. Regardless, it's a data point.<br/><br/>Thanks again,<br/>Tyrell", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59439526", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 01:34 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There are many good reasons that witches and sorcerers used to keep cats, and that's one of them. Have you ever seen a cat staring at a place on the wall where you couldn't see anything/ They see well into the etheric plane, and can hunt there, too..."}]}, {"id": "cmt59439782", "title": "Codex Gigas", "date": "2026-03-03 01:46 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "One of those random interesting bits of medieval lore I've come across is the Codex Gigas, a gigantic manuscript including a Latin Bible and a compendium of various other stuff, including history, philosophy, medicine, a calendar, folklore, magic spells, and illustrations. Those last two are of interest, especially its infamous, full-page depiction of the devil. I recall reading that it seems to have been executed by a single scribal hand, even though its estimated that this would require daily labor for 30 years!<br/><br/>So I'm wondering, what is the occult perspective on Codex Gigas? Was it really completed through supernatural aid, whether light or dark? Assuming you're familiar, how would you rate its magical spells and incantations? And what about its illustration of the devil?<br/><br/>Thanks for MM as always.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59440294", "title": "Re: Codex Gigas", "date": "2026-03-03 01:50 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've heard about it but never really looked into it, as that end of medieval magic isn't that much of an interest of mine. Sorry. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59441062", "title": "Re: Codex Gigas", "date": "2026-03-03 02:04 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "It's fine, just thought it was worth a shot. I guess magic is too broad &amp; encompassing of a topic for one person to know it all!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59441574", "title": "Re: Codex Gigas", "date": "2026-03-03 02:11 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "At this point, it's impossible for one person to know everything about one branch of magic -- say, making talismans, or natural magic -- and barely possible for one person to get a broad overview of occultism and a working knowledge of a few systems. I've spent my entire life at this stuff, from the age of 16 on, and the amount that I know is embarrassingly small compared to the amount that I will never know. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59445158", "title": "Re: Codex Gigas", "date": "2026-03-03 02:31 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "Well, that puts it in perspective! So it is with any serious field -- I've read hundreds of books, probably over a thousand by now, and the more you learn, the more vistas keep opening up."}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59447206", "title": "Re: Codex Gigas", "date": "2026-03-03 03:10 am", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "An excellent study of the Codex Gigas by Michael Gullick (an expert on medieval manuscripts) appeared in 2007.  It can be downloaded at <a href=\"https://www.scribd.com/document/209006934/Sidor-fr%C3%A5n-Biblis38\">https://www.scribd.com/document/209006934/Sidor-fr%C3%A5n-Biblis38</a> <br/><br/>There are only two pages of magic texts in the entire huge manuscript.<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59448998", "title": "Re: Codex Gigas", "date": "2026-03-03 03:42 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "Good stuff, thanks. Sounds like the magical content was over-stated a bit, maybe because it's so striking to modern scholars."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59440550", "title": "On the Nature Spirits in Maine", "date": "2026-03-03 01:57 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Greetings Mr. Greer,<br/>I wanted to get your and your reader's thoughts again on an experience I had recently with the nature spirits in Maine.<br/>More than a year ago, I inquired if you had ever traveled to Maine and experienced the nature spirits there and had anything to comment. You hadn't, but I was grateful for the reply.<br/>Well, it may be of you and your reader's interest that I have recently. <br/>What I found was that the whole state, or at least the part of it south of Lake Moosehead and likely down to Portland, is covered with some kind of spiritual blockade. I've spent the time since my first post in spiritual training, making my perceptions and ability to make contact with entities stronger, but when I arrived, I couldn't get ahold of either of the deities I normally work with. Maine has always had a curiously anemic religious and occult scene (lots of reports of spiritual activity from non-humans, but very little from people). Even Christian evangelicalism and recently arrived Islam seems to get smothered in the crib. They don't take off in nearly the way you would expect.<br/>A friend suggested I try to get a hold of a couple of European forest deities, like Cernunnos. I tried that, and what I saw was the vision of a horned humanoid with a shadowy face who looked like Cernunnos, but wasn't. As I was walking through the woods on some family property, I found two plastic bucks washed up in the delta of a river and frozen into the snow and ground. I pulled them up, and declared aloud that I was offering this to the forest as a token of my friendship, and took them to the trash. The next day or after, the block was largely lifted and I could make some contact with my deities again, but I got the vibe that the access was almost grudging. It wasn't outright hostility, but a very, very cold shoulder.<br/>Tucker Carlson, among one prominent resident of the state, has talked about the outright hostility he has experienced in the woods there, the sense that humans aren't wanted. I agree, but also there are large areas where the strategy appears to be simply slowly strangle human life by blockade. By most metrics, it's working.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59443110", "title": "Re: On the Nature Spirits in Maine", "date": "2026-03-03 02:22 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Fascinating. I've felt something similar in the forests of western Washington state. The forests there are conifers, and very dark -- when the skies are cloudy they look black. There a very strong sense that if you stray off the trail you will probably never be found -- and yes, this happens quite often. Interestingly, the native peoples had the same sense. They built their villages on the seashore or on river banks, never back in the woods, and told eerie stories about the <i>skookums</i> (powerful spiritual beings) that lived in the woods and would grab the unwary.  "}]}, {"id": "cmt59441830", "title": "Meditations and question", "date": "2026-03-03 02:16 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Evening JMG,  <br/><br/>I did meditate on my questions from last week. The placing of the cross on the Sagrada Familia bringing the structure to its highest point on Feb 20th 2026 was a purposefully symbolic act to align the church with the Saturn Neptune conjunction.  The church itself is represntative of Catalan Catholicism though it has a look and feel of paganism, something natural to Catholicism in some respects.. but there is also this curious elemental aspect of the church; \"Gaudí also conducted acoustic surveys to ensure the ringing from wind-driven tubular bells inside each tower will funnel down into the church itself.  https://www.popsci.com/technology/sagrada-familia-church-construction/\" this is an interesting innovation representative of the spirtual descent of elementals into matter.  More to unpack there I guess.<br/><br/>Onto my question then.<br/>Do you have any information relating to the cause of the onset of physical pulsating and a feeling of fluttering with the solar plexus in Western occult literature?  What I have found is this is representative of kundlini energy awakening and rising in Eastern traditions.<br/><br/>Thanks<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59443622", "title": "Re: Meditations and question", "date": "2026-03-03 02:23 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I was taught that it can have several causes, and the awakening of energy centers is one of them. I was also taught that it's a good idea to get a medical checkup if that happens to make sure that it's not something problematic. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59442342", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 02:20 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "March 2026 is shaping up to be an extraordinary month for skywatchers, with one captivating celestial event following closely on the heels of another.<br/><br/>The month kicks off with a spectacular planetary alignment as Mercury, Venus, Saturn, Jupiter, Uranus, and Neptune gather across the evening sky. Under clear, dark conditions, four of these—Mercury, Venus, Saturn, and Jupiter—shine brightly enough to spot with the naked eye, while Uranus and Neptune reveal themselves only through binoculars or a telescope.<br/><br/>On March 3, a total lunar eclipse bathes the Moon in a deep, dramatic red hue during totality. This “blood moon” will be visible from eastern Asia, Australia, the Pacific region, North America, and Central America, and in certain places it may even set as the Sun begins to rise.<br/><br/>A beautiful planetary pairing unfolds low in the western sky after sunset on March 7 and 8. Venus glides very close to Neptune on the 7th before drawing near Saturn on the 8th, forming a striking cluster of worlds hugging the horizon.<br/><br/>On March 10, the Moon passes close to Antares, the brilliant red supergiant star in Scorpius roughly 550 light-years distant. This close encounter will be observable from locations around the world, while in Antarctica and select parts of the Indian Ocean—including Madagascar and Mauritius—the Moon will fully occult Antares, briefly hiding the star from view.<br/><br/>The Gamma Normids meteor shower reaches its peak around March 14–15. Though a modest display, it offers its best viewing from the Southern Hemisphere, and the thin waning crescent Moon will provide darker skies to help any faint meteors stand out.<br/><br/>March 20 brings the vernal equinox, when day and night balance almost perfectly at around 12 hours each as the Sun crosses the celestial equator into the northern hemisphere.<br/><br/>Throughout the entire month, aurora activity has a good chance of intensifying. Equinox periods often amplify geomagnetic connections through the Russell–McPherron and equinoctial effects, allowing solar wind to more readily interact with Earth’s magnetic field and occasionally ignite vivid displays of northern and southern lights.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59443878", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 02:24 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thanks for this. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59443366", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 02:22 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You've often cautioned against reaching out to archangel Raziel and Metatron due to their extremely high status in the spirit world.<br/><br/>You've also said that Gods and archangels are at an equivalent level of divinity.<br/><br/>Does this mean that Raziel and Metatron are even higher than that level?<br/><br/>Thank you.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59444390", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 02:25 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It depends on what you mean by the word \"god.\" It's been used over the years for many beings, some of them barely above the human level, others far beyond the level of even the highest archangels. Remember also that each of these categories of beings covers a broad range of possibilities, and there's a lot of difference among them!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59446438", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 02:57 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you for asking that. I didn't know at all there could be a broad definition of a God. I thought gods just meant entities higher than humans and hence were worshipped throughout human history. I would class these as celestial spirits.<br/><br/>With regards to Raziel and Metatron, I asked BJ Swain this question and he agreed that no pantheon contains a god higher than Metatron so this to me means that Metatron is the highest spiritual authority humans have come to know about besides YHVH himself.<br/><br/>Even Aaron Leitch agrees not to bother these spirits exclusively and he has worked with all kinds of spirits his entire occult career. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59446950", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 03:02 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Well, I don't recommend bothering spirits at all, as you know!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59447718", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 03:20 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Oh totally but what Leitch meant in that context was that any attempt to contact Razy and Meto is to bother which I can't agree with at all because if you go on the r/gallery of Magick, r/Occult, and r/Magick subreddits, you will find plenty of posts praising and thanking Raziel for his help.<br/><br/>What context? He is mostly called to serve in his divine role as an intermediary to... technically any spirit from any pantheon.<br/><br/>That is the most fascinating thing I have ever heard. It's like the Protestant idea of Jesus being the intermediary to his father YHVH.<br/><br/><br/>Are you familiar with the Foolish Fish YouTube channel from Poland? He has uploaded reviews on your books and in some of his reviews of spirit workings and spells, he attested to the veracity of this Raziel intermediary method.<br/><br/>Please check them out. I'm sure you will be positively shocked.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59449766", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 03:53 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, thank you. Videos bore me, and I'm even more bored by the thought of watching people chatter about this or that spirit they've harassed into giving them goodies. "}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59447462", "title": "Planetary charity this year", "date": "2026-03-03 03:16 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/>This year, Saturn squares some important planets in my natal chart, including itself. My plan was to do plenty of charity for old and sick people. However, last week in response to a question about Saturn charity for a specific purpose, you mentioned it wasn't good to invoke Saturn since he's in his fall in Aries. Does that apply to my plan as well? Would it be better to do charity for the aspected planets instead?<br/><br/>Secondly, I want to thank you for the reference in your book on the 5 Rites for the instructional video by Carolindia Witt. I've tried but failed in the past to do them as is, since I have lower back issues stemming from a long ago injury. Her gentle progression allowed me to do the Rites without pain, and I'm now up to 19 reps!<br/><br/>-John N.<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59452326", "title": "Re: Planetary charity this year", "date": "2026-03-03 04:10 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Good heavens, don't invoke Saturn for the old! He is the planet of hard limits, old age, and death. Invoke Venus to make them happy, the Sun to keep them healthy, and Jupiter to grant them prosperity and good fortune. <br/><br/>2) Delighted to hear it. Her modified postures are very helpful for those who aren't in top shape. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59456678", "title": "Re: Planetary charity this year", "date": "2026-03-03 05:00 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hmm, I must be confused. I believe you mentioned in Sept 29 2025 Magic Monday, \"Saturn's the easiest of all planets for planetary charity, because any charity that helps the poor, and any charity that helps the elderly, are wholly suitable to Saturn.\", although I don't have a link handy...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59456934", "title": "Re: Planetary charity this year", "date": "2026-03-03 05:03 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you want to do planetary charity with Saturn, you can donate to charities that help the old. That doesn't mean he's a suitable planet to invoke to bring benefits to the old. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59447974", "title": "Aries Ingress 2026: Washington DC", "date": "2026-03-03 03:23 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "HI JMG,<br/><br/>Going by your delineation, do you anticipate a 'successful' operation by  the US in the current war against Iran?<br/><br/>If not do you have any other scenarios, for what the apparently positive aspects for the military in the 6th and foreign affairs in the 7th might entail?<br/><br/>Personally, I think the whole think is appalling. Whatever a country's so called 'faults' are, let the citizens decide.<br/>I hate to see so much destruction and loss of life, because of the whims, fantasies and desires of 'the powers that be'.<br/><br/>To all those that lust and cheer on war, I would say, \"May you get exactly what you deserve and nothing that you don't\"<br/><br/>Regards, Helen in Oz", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59451558", "title": "Re: Aries Ingress 2026: Washington DC", "date": "2026-03-03 04:07 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The delineation doesn't say. It indicates that the conflict will be settled in a more or less positive way -- Jupiter exalted in Cancer ruling the 7th house of foreign policy indicates this -- and that the US military will have good fortune in the six months covered by the chart, but that could work out in any number of ways. I prefer not to offer scenarios -- just to indicate what the heavens show. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59448742", "title": "Lost object", "date": "2026-03-03 03:40 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Greetings JMG,<br/><br/>My family had a relative pass recently, and we have a dilemma: we can't find her will anywhere! And we know she had one done because we know the (now retired) lawyer she went to. So it has to be somewhere.<br/><br/>Any suggestions on who to call upon for help finding it? I know the default for a lot of people is to call upon St. Anthony, but Catholic saints don't seem to listen to me, possibly because I left the faith years ago. So I'd be open to anyone from planetary spirits to Greek gods to Eastern deities. <br/><br/>Also, do you have a link for that green candle spell? Or if you know which week you wrote about it, I can just look through the posts for that week.<br/><br/>Thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59450790", "title": "Re: Lost object", "date": "2026-03-03 04:03 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Do you know how to cast a geomantic chart? The instructions in my book <i>The Art and Practice of Geomancy</i> include instructions for finding lost objects using geomantic charts. That's the method I use, for what it's worth. <br/><br/>2) I'm sorry to say I'm not sure which green candle spell it was! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59453350", "title": "Re: Lost object", "date": "2026-03-03 04:16 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "It was the hoodoo green candle spell to start receiving opportunities to make money.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59454374", "title": "Re: Lost object", "date": "2026-03-03 04:27 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That doesn't help much -- I know more than a dozen of those. <br/><br/>You can take a green candle, and placing it atop a spell paper -- a square of brown paper, torn (not cut) on all four sides, on which you have written your own name seven times and then turned it 90 degrees and written \"I see many opportunities to make money\" seven times. (The turning 90 degrees makes one set of writing go across the other set of writing like the threads in weaving.) Put five drops of Attracting Oil on it, then fold the paper toward you once, turn it 90 degrees and fold it toward you again. Then put it under the candle. <br/><br/>This is done on a Friday. Anoint the candle with Attraction Oil on seven successive Fridays, each Friday burning 1/7th of the candle. That should do the job. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59450022", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 03:58 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG, <br/>Any chance of you charting the USA Israel Iran conflict ? <br/>All the best in your new endeavours!<br/>Sapienter si sincere", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59450278", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 04:01 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The older traditions I use don't provide any way to do this -- just ingress, eclipse, and great conjunction charts for overall astrological weather. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59450534", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 04:02 am", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>It's late, but I assume the affirmation in the meme is probably not a good idea?</p>\n<p>After all, one easy way for bad energy sent at you to be turned into cash is if some unfortunate accident leaves you on disability.</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59452838", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 04:13 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You'd have to know what you're doing to make use of that as a spell. As an affirmation, yeah, it's probably not a good idea. Funny, but not a good idea. "}, {"id": "cmt59456166", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-03 04:44 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yeah, I was confused about how the cash was supposed to get chain-of-deals'ed or bucket-brigaded from the personal circumstances of whoever was sending the bad energy to the personal circumstances of whoever was receiving the cash."}]}, {"id": "cmt59452070", "title": "Worm moon?", "date": "2026-03-03 04:08 am", "user": "zaratozom", "content": "I’m not too familiar with moon magic . Anything worth trying out tonight ?<br/>Leaving out my tarot deck?<br/>Infused water?<br/>Giving my crystals a lunar eclipse bath?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59453094", "title": "Re: Worm moon?", "date": "2026-03-03 04:14 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "During an eclipse? No, emphatically not. The energies of an eclipse are unstable and explosive, and best left to expert mages. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59454630", "title": "Re: Worm moon?", "date": "2026-03-03 04:32 am", "user": "zaratozom", "content": "Ok thank you . I always appreciate you looking out for us inexperienced folks . "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59452582", "title": "Meditation 7 questions", "date": "2026-03-03 04:12 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I recall you describing a method for discursive meditation to spur the session along when you're stuck.  It involved seven questions and seven processes, or something similar.  <br/>'Who' 'what' 'when' 'where'<br/>Was paired with:<br/>'Being' 'becoming' etc.<br/><br/>I can't remember many more details, other than it sounded like a good way to examine an idea from all angles.  Would you be willing to share it again?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59453606", "title": "Re: Meditation 7 questions", "date": "2026-03-03 04:17 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's called the sevenfold wheel of thought. There are seven concepts and seven questions, and you combine them.<br/><br/>Concepts:<br/>Being<br/>Becoming<br/>Source<br/>Substance<br/>Power<br/>Purpose<br/>Value<br/><br/>Questions:<br/>Whether?<br/>What?<br/>How?<br/>Who?<br/>Where?<br/>When?<br/>Why?<br/><br/>You combine each of the questions with each of the concepts, thus...<br/><br/>Whether it is?<br/>What is it?<br/>How is it?<br/>Who (or whose) is it?<br/>Where is it?<br/>When is it?<br/>Why is it?<br/>Whether it becomes?<br/>What does it become?<br/>How does it become?<br/><br/>...and so on. There are 49 queries in all. ", "edit_time": "2026-03-03 04:18 am (UTC)"}]}, {"id": "cmt59453862", "title": "Blood Moon", "date": "2026-03-03 04:23 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is there astrological significance to the Blood Moon?  Any significance to the  date 3/3.<br/><br/>What is a Blood Moon Sacrifice?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59455910", "title": "Re: Blood Moon", "date": "2026-03-03 04:43 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Nope. <br/><br/>2) Nope. <br/><br/>3) I have no idea. I've never heard of that. "}]}]}, {"title": "Magic Monday", "url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/361648.html", "year": "2026", "month": "03", "day": "08", "time": "10-40PM", "comments": [{"id": "cmt59476656", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:01 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Before we begin, something mildly amusing to share. Last week's Magic Monday post had a meme involving the spraypainted words \"May all bad energy sent to me be turned into cash.\" Weirdly enough, the last week has been remarkably lucrative for me, with an early royalty payment and a bunch of other sudden infusions of cash showing up unexpectedly...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59479216", "title": "Oh oh oh it’s magic, you know….", "date": "2026-03-09 04:28 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Memetic magic for ya! What a pleasant surprise! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59480752", "title": "Re: Oh oh oh it’s magic, you know….", "date": "2026-03-09 04:38 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I figure Kek has a sense of humor. Mind you, I'm not complaining. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59490224", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 12:23 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good to hear! Maybe I should post the picture on my website too!<br/>Hope you had a real nice time in the mountains of NC.<br/><br/> -JPM", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59494064", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 03:34 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's worth a try!<br/><br/>Yeah, I had a great time. The weather was fine, the air was almost supernaturally fresh, the little cabin I stayed in was comfortable and had a porch well suited for morning meditations, and of course the people were wonderful. There were no dogs sleeping on the porch, but that's because its only access is from inside. The main building? One to five dogs on the porch most of the time, reminding you that you're in the South. ;-) ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59519152", "title": "North Carolina", "date": "2026-03-09 11:25 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I watch a few different homesteading families on YouTube and North Carolina strikes me as one of those places that the gods have smiled on.<br/>Of course I know it had the terrible disaster a year ago or so, but the landscape is gorgeous.<br/>If I could teleport myself to anywhere in the US, NC would probably be it.<br/><br/>On something completely unrelated I mentioned a few weeks ago that I think I may be going through my second Saturn return. Born Dec 68.<br/>I am currently feeling quite miserable with an ongoing shoulder/bicep tendon problem which really flared up on the day of the eclipse.<br/>Sleep is very disturbed as lying down makes it hurt even more.<br/>In my natal Vedic chart I have Saturn, Rahu and the moon in one house, pisces and in the opposite house is Mars. Apparently 'not good '.<br/>It's not a direct opposition thankfully 😬.<br/>In western those three are in Aries, so Saturn is in his fall.<br/>Fun times, not. I've never felt more incapacitated physically, while desperately wanting to do stuff but I'm having to rest to try and get the inflamed tendons to settle.<br/>I had been doing all the wrong things including stretching which just made it worse.<br/>I have to just be patient.<br/>Any prayers and good wishes gratefully accepted! 🙏<br/><br/>Regards <br/>Helen in Oz", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59521456", "title": "Re: North Carolina", "date": "2026-03-10 12:20 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good heavens -- please accept my condolences and positive energies.  I'd strongly suggest dropping a note to the keeper of our prayer list -- getting a bunch of people praying and sending Essene healing energy your way ought to help! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59533744", "title": "Re: North Carolina", "date": "2026-03-10 02:06 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks JMG, that means a lot.<br/> <br/>I will go to the prayer list and add my predicament!<br/>Or rather, \"problem\" (hopefully) - I want a positive solution, not just a work around!"}, {"id": "cmt59534256", "title": "Re: North Carolina /ongoing shoulder/bicep tendon problem", "date": "2026-03-10 02:27 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi again, <br/><br/>I'm afraid I couldn't really work out how to post my prayer request on the Ecoprayer page, so if I may I'll post it here:<br/><br/>To Ecoprayer, could you add the following? Apologies for not being able to work out how to post it on the dedicated page.<br/><br/>Prayers for the settling down of the inflamed tendons in my biceps /shoulder and once this is achieved, that I may be successful in the slow process of regaining pain free range of movement and increased muscle mass and strength.<br/><br/>To add to my not great day, one of four baby chicks I bought on Saturday, had not been going to good and died in my hand just an hour or two ago :-(<br/><br/>Helen in Oz"}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59524528", "title": "\"The truest things are said in jest\"", "date": "2026-03-10 01:04 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This is an odd phenomenon that occurs when the formal side of things is pretty much on target, but there is no intentional forceful use of \"will\". A casual, light-hearted act or utterance can produce an unexpected, more or less on-the-nose, effect.<br/><br/>Of course, this is pretty hard to replicate, since one of the base conditions seems to be the \"unintentional\" nature of the act. But it's good to be aware of the possibility, if only to avoid getting a result one might regret!<br/><br/>This is somewhat related to what a friend of mine used to refer to as the \"word of truth\" effect. My friend's idea was that constantly (faithfully) speaking the truth creates a kind of momentum behind the speaker's words. Someone who is accustomed to speak the truth at all times will sometimes find that some statement not intended too seriously will turn out to have been exactly true. This phenomenon, used sparingly, is a little more able to be used intentionally, though trying to <i>exploit</i> it seems to quickly undermine its effectiveness.<br/><br/>LeGrand", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59532976", "title": "Re: \"The truest things are said in jest\"", "date": "2026-03-10 02:03 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That seems plausible enough. Many years ago, when I was still fairly new to magic, I spent much of an afternoon in the periodical stacks of Suzzallo Library, chasing down what I could find about Austin Osman Spare. I happened to find a brief but complete explanation of how to formulate one of his sigils. Just for practice I put together a sigil using the word \"rain.\" It had been a bright sunny day, but damn if it hadn't started pouring by the time I left the library..."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59477424", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:19 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "A spirit? No. It's precisely this habit of being dependent on spirits that makes so many would-be mages these days experience so many failures. The cosmos of classic occultism is far vaster than our spirit-pestering brigade lets themselves notice, and it contains many more options by which will and imagination can influence experienced reality. <br/><br/>BTW, Sachiel can do plenty during a retrograde. I really do have to post something on the occult practicalities of retrogradation, don't I? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59478192", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:23 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do you have any idea where the idea that a planet is so debilitated as to be completely powerless, and so destructive as to ruin everything it touches, every time it's retrograde could have come from? I mean, I accept it as a debility; but it's always seemed pretty far from the worst there is to me...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59481264", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:43 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I have no idea. Retrogradation is a debility but it can be used constructively. When a planet is retrograde, its influence is very favorable for anything that involves going back or turning within. Mercury retrogrades, I've found, are the best time to revise manuscripts; Jupiter retrogrades are exceptionally good times to revise investment plans and go back to old projects and see if they can be turned to new profits. That's especially the case now, since Jupiter is in his exaltation in Cancer! "}, {"id": "cmt59492784", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 02:48 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Negative prophecy gets views. Retrogrades are negative, relatively frequent, and its easy to know if something is retrograde without referring to other planets/context because it is a debilitation of the planet itself based on its own motion rather than its relation to other planets. So it makes sense that pop culture astrology memes gravitate towards the accessible, frequently reinforced, negative condition."}]}, {"id": "cmt59478960", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:27 am", "user": "brenainn", "content": "What would you say the difference is between modern occultists who try to call on spirits and the role of spirits in shamanism?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59480496", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:38 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Most of the modern occultists I've read who try to work with spirits use them as vending machines: \"gimme this and gimme that, by the mighty Names I adjure you!\" It's mostly very manipulative and egocentric, and tends to fixate on the crass material level. Shamanism -- meaning the real thing, not the watered-down Michael Harner stuff -- is not the arbitrary manipulation of spirits by the individual ego; it's the transformation of the whole self by spiritual powers immensely greater than human. As Eliade documents in his famous book on the subject, the shaman experiences (not, please note, visualizes!) being torn open and remade by spirits, killed and resurrected, plunged into seven hells and sent spinning up into seven heavens.  That process of transmutation begins a life of constant interaction and participation with the world of spirits, worlds away from the common modern habit of calling them up and bullying them when you want some goodies. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59482032", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:45 am", "user": "brenainn", "content": "I continue to get a chuckle when I look at the Harner stuff. Visualize? Well, that’ll never compare to feeling a stone knife plunge into your chest and then having a giant serpent crawl inside and dissolve you into it. <br/><br/>Actually, who the heck would ask for or try to get the spirits to do that? It ain’t a fun experience. Neither is seeing spirits all around you. Some folks don’t realize how many of them are hostile.<br/><br/>The last few weeks, I’ve more or less lost any remaining respect I might have had for the watered down efforts of PMC “spirituality “.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59482800", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:49 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I get that. It's all very bland and comfortable, suitable for weekend workshops to entertain the privileged. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59483824", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:55 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Being a shaman does not look like an easy task, and I've sometimes wondered if the people larping at it might find themselves thrown into that role, either in this life or another....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59484592", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 05:00 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "May the gods help them if that takes place. No, it's not easy, or safe. "}, {"id": "cmt59486128", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 05:12 am", "user": "brenainn", "content": "Well, they're fools if that's what they're aiming to do. And even bigger fools if they don't realize that it might be a possibility. The shamanic vocation is largely one that cannot be chosen, though in some of the traditions I've begun reading about, it might be occasionally possible to seek it out. I don't recommend that. I really don't. One will be taken to the otherworld, not merely in vision but in spirit, and you will undergo some very, very unpleasant stuff. And that's just the start.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59491504", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 01:31 pm", "user": "olafsson", "content": "I have noticed in several different examples of practices that were once largely purposed towards serving community, in service and sacrifice to others, have now been remade into practices for individual self development and benefit. And this forces the difficult question: why do I seek to learn magic?<br/><br/>Anyways, I wanted to add something I heard from Nicholas Breeze Wood's podcast on shamanism: evidently there have been cases where a shaman went into trance and into the spirit world, to perform some task for an individual or the tribe, and just never made their way back - they just stayed in trance until they wasted away and died. They risk these dangers for the sake of the community.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59501232", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 05:37 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "I have noticed the same thing. The overall tendency of the PMC and their sycophants is to take any genuine spiritual path, and water it down to be used as some light therapy for their own anxieties and shortcomings. Doesn't seem to matter what. If the real version of it works, the PMC will try to make a featherweight version of it, consistent with their materialist worldview. Except, it no longer works very well and, of course, spits in the face of the serious practitioners out there.<br/><br/>The otherworld is a place full of dangers. It is not some inner, watered down \"collective unconscious\" or whatever. There are entities there that would leave the average person wetting themselves in terror. If one has not been called to work in that realm, then DON'T even try to go there. Really. The \"core shamanism\" movement, if it works at all, is walking some people into an early death.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59505584", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 08:08 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Agreed wholeheartedly, with one caveat. The PMC also watered down Carl Jung's theories. The collective unconscious is not safe, either. It contains forces that can leave someone huddled in a ball, rocking back and forth in a pool of his own urine while babbling meaningless sounds, for the rest of his life. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59519664", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 11:36 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "Yes, I definitely agree. I've been working on the individuation process for a while and studying Jung's own writings (quickly learned to avoid most modern books trying to present his teachings), and the only conclusion I can draw is that the real collective unconscious is a powerful thing. I also think it transcends the human race in general, and might be part of a truly universal spiritual force."}]}, {"id": "cmt59516336", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 10:02 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This makes it sound like, when we do eventually get our permanent mental bodies and leave the material plane behind forever, the world we are entering in will still be about as dangerous as the current material plane world we are living in right now. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59520432", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 12:14 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's quite correct. On the other hand, we will be stronger and wiser through having made our way through the traps and perils of this plane, so we'll be up to the challenge. "}, {"id": "cmt59522224", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 12:23 am", "user": "brenainn", "content": "Yes. The old myths of gods battling monsters from the chaos are pretty much true. But don't worry too much. The otherworld is also full of its own beauty, delights, and joy. And as JMG mentioned, once we're at that stage, we're prepared for it. My spirit guide was formerly human, and someone I knew very well in life. Quite a potent power when dealing with things in the otherworld that would literally eat me alive."}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59541424", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 03:48 am", "user": "revert2mean", "content": "I had that dream though, when I was fifteen. I had a couple of years where every time I fell asleep, things were chasing me. But eventually I just had to sleep, and a giant snake chased me, caught me, tore me to pieces and then cooked up the pieces and put me back together again. I felt much better after that, though it was all very unpleasant. I didn't know I was going to get put back together. I guess if I belonged to a different kind of society I would have been sent to live in a hut at the edge of the village after that dream. I just had to continue with school."}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59494320", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 03:42 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The occultists asking spirits for goodies remind me of the Christians and Jews and Muslims who pray to their God asking for goodies. I used to be one of the Christians who would selfishly pray to God for everything that I personally want to be fulfilled. It made the next few years of my life pretty miserable. <br/><br/>A lot of people don't seem to understand that God, angels, saints, and whatever other spirits have their own limits and boundaries and that you need to respect their boundaries and accept that there are limits beyond which these superhuman beings can't or won't do stuff for you. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59496624", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:08 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm sure the habits are related. When I was young and arrogant, I rejected the entire concept of prayer because all I ever saw of it was \"Lord gimme this, Lord gimme that.\" It was only after I had some encounters with genuine mystics that I found out that that's just as much of a debasement of prayer as the spirit-pestering stuff is a debasement of magic. <br/><br/>It really is a matter of building a relationship. You wouldn't turn every interaction with an older and wiser friend into an excuse to pester him for goodies; in exactly the same way, you don't treat gods and spirits that way. You talk with them, spend time with them, listen to them; now and again you may ask for a favor, but you also know that they can ask you for favors, too. That's how relationships work. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59498416", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:33 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How can you tell when praying that you are in the presence of a god or spirit and aren't just praying into the void? Because I remember you saying on the Ecosophia blog that plenty of former Christians have tried praying to God or Jesus Christ and have received nothing but silence from the other end. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59506096", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 08:13 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You have to learn to listen for a response, and wait to get one. When you do, it's usually very faint at first, but present. That's exactly the point with the Christians I mentioned back in that blog post: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/death-god-speculation/\">https://www.ecosophia.net/death-god-speculation/</a><br/><br/>They were waiting for an answer -- any kind of answer, even the least faint sense of presence -- and never got it. Mind you, there are Christians who do get answered, and exactly why this divergence of experience is taking place is a complex process. But I also know a lot of people, after getting nothing but silence and emptiness from invoking the Christian god, who prayed to other gods and got a definite answer. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59513776", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 09:44 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If your vision is right, it's almost certain to me that Christianity has been powerfully influenced by the souls who don't belong here. I wonder if what's happening is the god(s) associated with Christianity pulling back from those of us who do belong here....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59520688", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 12:16 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's an intriguing thought. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59517872", "title": "How the Almighty talks to me at least...", "date": "2026-03-09 10:52 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In my experience the answer is very, very rarely verbal.<br/><br/>Usually it is a song that comes on the radio, an event that demonstrates a point, a thing seen whose symbolism is obvious, etc.<br/>Music is an enormously useful communication tool. I can't count the number of times the perfect song came on in answer to some thought or another I was having. Often a series of songs. Many other listeners say the same thing.<br/><br/>- Cicada Grove", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59520944", "title": "Re: How the Almighty talks to me at least...", "date": "2026-03-10 12:17 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Interesting. That may vary from person to person, as I fairly often get something I'd describe as the \"still small voice\" the Bible mentions. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59540400", "title": "Re: How the Almighty talks to me at least...", "date": "2026-03-10 03:41 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "'Still small voice' - Yes, I've heard that too-- but only about 4 times or so in my life.<br/>He's very laconic.<br/><br/>- Cicada Grove"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59534512", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 02:33 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "Is contacting a god via divination and asking them what they want me to do a good idea?<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59536304", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 03:04 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You can do that, but don't be surprised if the answer works out to \"Think for yourself, schmuck.\" "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59505840", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 08:12 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "It also reminds me of codependency in human relationships, where one person in the relationship acts as if they are completely dependent on the other person. <br/><br/>You get similar phenomena where you see one person constantly pester the other person for goodies or for the other person to allow the first person to indulge in their bad mental health, addictions, immaturity, irresponsibility, etc. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59506352", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 08:14 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The thought of being codependent on malefic spirits is pretty horrible, all things considered! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59522992", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 12:27 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "It explains a lot though: like why so many people are so eager to sell their souls..."}]}, {"id": "cmt59514544", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 09:49 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Have you ever seen someone who's really codependent start to freak out if someone tries to point out that they can do things themselves? They tend to react in exactly the same fashion as the spirit brigade do here when told that magic is not all about getting spirits to do your bidding...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59521200", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 12:17 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Lord love a duck. You're quite correct, of course, but that never occurred to me. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59522480", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 12:24 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "One of the few ways that my family has helped me is that understanding how certain kinds of dysfunctional relationships work is second nature for me...."}, {"id": "cmt59526064", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 01:19 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "These days a lot of the codependency is with machines instead of other beings. You also get a similar reaction when you tell somebody addicted to watching the TV or using large language models that they should stop outsourcing everything to the TV or the LLM and start thinking for themselves. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59532464", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 01:59 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's why I should have recognized it. I used to get exactly that sort of meltdown when I mentioned to people that I haven't owned a television in my adult life, or that I don't have a cell phone. "}, {"id": "cmt59538864", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 03:26 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Sorry to be a pedant but \"codependency\" is when you make other people reliant on you or enable other people's dependency on you. The right word to use here is \"dependency\", as in you have dependency on machines. "}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59503280", "title": "yes to an article on retrogradation", "date": "2026-03-09 06:38 pm", "user": "angelica5804", "content": "As someone who is very new to the deeper elements of astrology (and enjoying them), I would love for you to post an article on retrogradation.<br/><br/>Thank you in advance<br/><br/>~Angelica", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59506608", "title": "Re: yes to an article on retrogradation", "date": "2026-03-09 08:15 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Duly noted! I'll certainly consider it, "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59479472", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:31 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I have neither the time nor the interest for that, as I have many more promising and effective magical practices that I currently pursue. Please recall that I was practicing ceremonial magic, and studying the Solomonic literature among many other things, back when Leitch was still playing with toy trucks. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59490992", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 01:16 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>(Not the OP)<br/><br/>Would you be willing to mention some of the \"many more promising and effective magical practices\" you speak of? I'm not necessarily asking about specific techniques (although I wouldn't mind hearing about that). But perhaps you could mention some systems you currently work with that are effective for achieving goals?<br/><br/>I hope you don't mind me asking. Many thanks.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59508144", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 08:57 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The difficulty here is that since I've been in the community for a good long time, I've recently been given access to some traditions that are not public, under certain vows of secrecy, and those are what I'm mostly working with these days. I can tell you that they're a form of late medieval white magic, they don't involve evoking spirits, and they contain some remarkably old-fashioned stuff -- for example, if you need ill-wishing taken off your cows, I can help -- but that's about it. Mind you, there are many other forms of magic that are good at getting results, but you asked what I'm doing just now. <br/><br/>In more general terms, the kind of magic I do depends partly on what I'm trying to learn and partly on what needs I have at any given time. I've had particularly good results with most kinds of talismanic magic I've tried -- the Renaissance astrological kind, the Golden Dawn kind, Eliphas Levi's quirky but effective variety, hoodoo tobies and other talismanic gear, and radionics -- the Hieronymus machine in particular is basically a tunable talisman and gets very good results. (I use a real machine, not a symbolic one.) After more than forty years of daily meditation, I can also get excellent results from simple affirmations.  The late medieval white magic I do these days is more ornate than that, but since I've received the initiation it would be silly not to learn the techniques. Besides, I may need to heal somebody's cows one of these days!"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59481008", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:40 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't know the man and have no idea why he believes what he does. If you find his approach more appealing than mine, why, go talk to him instead. "}, {"id": "cmt59482544", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:48 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Well, you've just shown the limits of your occult studies; you might find out who Eliphas Levi, Dion Fortune, Paul Foster Case, and Manly P. Hall were, just for starters. That said, there's a further issue. Why are you coming here to pick a fight on this subject? You know what my opinions are; if you think I'm wrong, why not just roll your eyes and go somewhere else? One of the things that fascinates me about the spirit-pestering brigade is how very thin-skinned they are and how little tolerance they have for disagreement. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59483568", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:53 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I also find it wryly amusing how much pushback they provide when someone points out that the spirits might expect something in return...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59485104", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 05:05 am", "user": "brenainn", "content": "Indeed. The mention of African Traditional Religions was particularly notable. The spirits of those traditions expect veneration and service from their devotees. One does not conjure up a lwa to get a goodie, then walk away from that lwa until the next time a wish needs granted."}, {"id": "cmt59485360", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 05:06 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "To my mind, it's the mentality of the consumer economy projected onto magic -- except they think they won't have to pay off their occult credit cards! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59487152", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 05:35 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Watching how people spend money, I sometimes wonder if people forget credit cards need to be repaid, so it might be a pretty apt comparison...."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59484848", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 05:03 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "(Offlist) Enough. If you're going to get abusive, there's the door. I've recorded your IP address; consider yourself permanently banned.  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59487408", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 05:36 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Did you delete the previous comments in this thread?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59493552", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 03:28 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You bet. Partly, when I IP-ban somebody, I usually delete their comments from that comment page as well. Partly, I was embarrassed that I let myself get dragged into yet another useless go-round with one of the spirit-pestering brigade. I was fairly tired, having just gotten back from a weekend in North Carolina with occultist friends (which, since it was North Carolina, involved lavish hospitality and a notably large supply of really good bourbon), or I'd simply have deleted the guy as soon as he posted about Sachiel and nipped the whole thing in the bud. <br/><br/>It really is a waste of time, because it's always the same argument. \"No other occultist agrees with you!\" I then list some of the famous occultists who did. \"Those aren't real occultists! The real occultists all agree with me!\" And around it goes. Sooner or later I ask why the person can't just accept that I disagree with them, and that's when they get really abusive. It's a serious question, though:  if their magic really is so successful and satisfying, why not just leave those who disagree with them to wallow in failure, and go show the world just how powerful and successful they are? But that's not a question any of them has ever been willing to answer. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59495600", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 03:49 pm", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "Naturally, they won't answer that because it doesn't work, and only brings down negative karma onto themselves. As I've said before, \"do not be a dark lord\" is a very useful principle to follow in magic, and asking entities to do your bidding is a definite violation.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59497136", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:11 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's just it. The big names in goetic magic are usually failures in life. John Dee was a respected and influential figure during the first half or so of his life, while he concentrated on astrological magic; once he started trying to get spirits to make him rich and pass on the secrets of the universe, his life got steadily worse. Aleister Crowley -- well, I don't even have to go on, do I? It's the mages who rely on their own power, rather than trying to get stuff from spirits, who go on to have happy and successful lives. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59523248", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 12:28 am", "user": "brenainn", "content": "There was one independent political commentator that I used to watch (his political commentary was pretty good), and he's openly bragged about having a relationship with Stolas, including some kind of pact. He did well for a while, had a good following, seemed to be making good money, etc. Currently, he's a fugitive from a bench warrant for a felony that could get him 15 years in prison, plus some misdemeanors that could add another year on that. Didn't work out for him, it seems.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59524272", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 12:57 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yeah, that's par for the course. It never seems to occur to these people that malefic spirits have their reputations for a reason. "}, {"id": "cmt59537584", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 03:15 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "Yep, Styxhexenhammer. He was a useful guide during Trump I, when my libtardism got shattered by the Culture War, and I was re-orienting. But I had to distance myself once he got into demonolatry, and his ensuing descent into legal woes and lolcow status is not a surprise."}]}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59477168", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:18 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is there an Orphyic Hymn (or equivalent) that I could recite to invoke my higher self?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59478704", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:27 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Excellent! Yes, and I recite it daily as part of my morning worship of the gods. It's Hymn 72, to the Genius. Here's the version (lightly revised from the Thomas Taylor translation) that I use: <br/><br/>Thee, mighty-ruling, Genius dread, I call, <br/>mild Jove, life-giving, and the source of all:<br/>Great Jove, much-wand'ring, terrible and strong, <br/>to whom revenge and tortures dire belong.<br/>Mankind from thee, in plenteous wealth abound, <br/>when in their dwellings joyful thou art found;<br/>Or pass thro' life afflicted and distress'd, <br/>the needful means of bliss by thee supprest.<br/>'Tis thine alone endued with boundless might, <br/>to keep the keys of sorrow and delight.<br/>O holy, blessed spirit, hear my prayer, <br/>disperse the seeds of life-consuming care;<br/>With fav'ring mind the sacred rites attend, <br/>and grant a happy life, a blessed end.<br/><br/>The guardian genius is the Pagan version of the holy guardian angel. As the hymn shows, it was understood in ancient times primarily as the dispenser of what we call karma and they called fate, but I've found that regular use of this hymn helps open channels of communication with the guardian genius. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59480240", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:38 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I asked because I plan on reciting it nightly as a way to start to integrate myself with my higher self. I've had pretty good results with the orphic hymns to the planets and so I figured this could work well too.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59481776", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:44 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's a good approach! I pray each morning to three Druid deities, using prayers modeled on the Orphic hymns; to the planet of the day; and to my guardian genius. The results have been exceedingly good. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59491760", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 01:31 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not the OP,<br/><br/>This sounds like a very manageable practice to do; very good for beginners, I would think? There's no elaborate ritual or endless correspondences to memorise. It also seems like a very safe and 'clean' daily practice.<br/><br/>If I may ask, what kinds of changes have you noticed? Also, which of Taylor's books did you use? Thanks for your help.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59494576", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 03:42 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) John Gilbert recommended daily prayer to the guardian angel or guardian genius to anyone who's established a daily spiritual practice of any kind. It's very manageable and entirely safe. <br/><br/>2) That would be a long list, since I've been doing it for quite some years now! The general theme of the changes is increased awareness of, and access to, the spiritual dimensions of existence. That shows up partly as increasingly clear and precise intuition, partly as steadily improving clairvoyance and other nonphysical senses (in my case clairtangence, the ability to sense nonphysical things via touch, is especially strong), partly as direct or indirect guidance -- I get gently directed toward useful things and away from harmful ones quite often these days, and things come my way when I need them, sometimes to an absurd degree. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59495856", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 03:51 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi<br/><br/>(OP Here again)<br/><br/><br/>Thanks for that. Did it take a long time for you to notice results from praying to your HGA/Genius? The world seems to be in steady decline, so I'm hoping to obtain some help from my HGA/Genius as soon as is reasonably possible. Advanced techniques will take a long time to learn.<br/><br/><br/>Many thanks.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59496368", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:02 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I had some results after six months or so; some people get those sooner, others later. It depends very much on individual readiness. I'd encourage you to get working on the simple version now; you can always go on to do more intensive workings later if you decide you want to. <br/><br/>Oh, and I neglected to answer your question about Taylor. The book in question is <i>The Hymns of Orpheus</i>, which you can download for free here: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://archive.org/details/dli.ministry.28841\">https://archive.org/details/dli.ministry.28841</a>"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59546544", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 07:49 pm", "user": "not_gandalf", "content": "Again, sorry to be a day behind, and feel free not to post, as you wish.<br/><br/>That said, the Prometeus Trust in the UK has published all of Taylor's works in 33 very nice hardbound volumes. Volume Five is \"Hymns and Initiations\" and all of Taylor's translations of the Orphic Hymns are in that. If you live in the United States, the distributor for these books is Kindred Star Books. <br/><a href=\"https://kindredstarbooks.com/collections/thomas-taylor-series\">https://kindredstarbooks.com/collections/thomas-taylor-series</a><br/>"}]}, {"id": "cmt59497904", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:32 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I love this. Thank you! Going to tweak my practice to incorporate... <br/><br/>Are the three Druid deities to correspond to Awen and the importance of the three rays and ternary thinking in Druidry? Interestingly enough, I have three in mind... but was curious on why you use that number...<br/><br/><br/>JPM", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59507632", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 08:41 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Partly it's a matter of Druid tradition, partly John Gilbert's quirky Cabala, which works best when you have three deities (or one threefold deity) as the first triad of spheres in the Tree of Life. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59517360", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 10:36 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "That makes sense! Thanks. -JPM"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59502512", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 06:24 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm completely new to prayer and this practice sounds interesting to me, would you be willing to share a bit about how it is structured? You don't have to walk me through every detail, I just want to get an idea of what this generally looks like in a daily routine. Only if you're willing! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59507888", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 08:45 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Sure. I have an altar with images of the three deities, as well as other sacred objects, and dishes for offerings: pure water, pot pourri for scent (in place of incense), and wheaten cakes. First thing in the morning I change the water, washing the dish in the process, and then face the altar and recite my prayers: first to each of the three Druid deities, then to the planetary deity of the day, and then to my guardian genius. I then bow, sit down facing the altar, and move straight into my core morning practices: one of the many variants of the Sphere of Protection, a good long session of discursive meditation, and some healing work using the methods of the Modern Order of Essenes. Then I bow again to the deities and go about my day. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59508912", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 09:02 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Fantastic, thank you for this! I will look into the Orphic hymns as well. To check my understanding, I assume there's a moment of silence after reciting each prayer to allow for a response? I am not at the point of being able to discern such things yet, but I want to make sure I'm doing it properly.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59513008", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 09:32 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, always take a moment or two to listen between each prayer. If you don't meditate yet, take a little while after all the prayers are finished to pay attention and wait for a response more generally. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59517104", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 10:23 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Understood, thank you for your wisdom and guidance."}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59482288", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:47 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "&gt;Yes, and I recite it daily as part of my morning worship of the gods.<br/><br/>So it’s completely permissible to invoke the higher self daily through morning worship? I had been doing this unknowingly through music but it got pretty intense so I let it simmer and now am afraid to start it back up again.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59483312", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:53 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That was one of the things I was taught by my teacher John Gilbert. He argued that high-intensity methods such as the Abramelin working were very hit-or-miss, depending on the level of preparation of the practitioner, while the simpler daily invocation combined with other spiritual and magical practices was slower but much more certain -- and also less likely to bring about psychological imbalance. The Abramelin working in particular, though it can be very effective, has caused some impressive nervous breakdowns as well. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59504816", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 07:47 pm", "user": "kylec", "content": "Just a data point, but what has done the most for me has been the CGD pathworkings along with conversation/prayer when it feels appropriate. Of course, that means it takes years, so it's on par with Gilbert's advice.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59506864", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 08:15 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thanks for this. For some people, that works very well. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59492528", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 02:42 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you for this!"}, {"id": "cmt59497648", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:23 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "For anyone invoking their Higher Self daily, it would be important to not only invoke the Higher Self but also one or more gods that they worship? The practice alone would be self-worship, which probably wouldn't lead to anything good. Do I have the right of it?<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59508400", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 09:00 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good question. There are people who focus entirely on the higher self and people who also call on the gods, and you'd probably have to get funding for a study to work out whether one way is more effective than the other. Myself, I like the company of gods and goddesses, and I advise other people to give it a try, but it's not my job to go out there and tell other people that they're wrong. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59528624", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 01:35 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Can you invoke the guardian angel / guardian genius in the Sphere of Protection?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59532208", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 01:57 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't recommend it. The SoP is designed to bring you into balance with the macrocosmic powers, so if you invoke beings it should focus on gods or archangels at the least. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59477680", "title": "Geomantic Temples", "date": "2026-03-09 04:22 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, I've been working on the practices in your geomancy book. When I started my meditations on the figures, I began to envision imaginal temples for each one. For example, the temple to Albus takes the form of a giant goblet-like tower made of white stone. The \"goblet\" is filled with water, and this placid pool ripples intensely when disturbed in any way. At the middle of the pool is a platform housing the temple's vestibule, which for Albus is a space for contemplation. One can sit here and endlessly ponder the rippling of the pool. Getting to and from the vestibule is difficult and it feels tempting to just stay there forever.<br/><br/>The pool contained within a tower expresses the elemental correspondences (water within air), the shape of the tower resembles the figure, the rippling water suggests mental activity and the isolated vestibule conveys the insular and unassertive character of Albus. It's the same basic idea as the imaginal temples of the spheres that you describe in Revisioning the Tree of Life. I didn't base my envisioning of the temples on that book, though, this activity is something that just sprang into my mind as I began the series of geomantic meditations. I wanted to know, in your study of the Renaissance literature on geomancy did you come across any work describing imaginal locations for the figures? If there are original sources on such things I'd like to find out how close my imaginings are to others.<br/><br/>Perhaps at some point I can create renditions of these temples as I imagine them. I'm not the best at drawing or sculpting though and I don't want to use AI for something like this.<br/><br/>Also, I have another question. I've been working on this at the same time as some GD study using other books of yours; I'm still in the early stages. Does doing these meditations at the same time as I work through LRM compromise the work I'm doing there? I'm not planning to try geomantic magic until I get a good grounding in GD work, just the meditations and divination using the figures for now. You've cautioned against practicing multiple forms of magic at once but I don't know if this geomantic work meets that threshold and I get kind of bored just doing one course of study.<br/><br/>Thanks for reading.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59484336", "title": "Re: Geomantic Temples", "date": "2026-03-09 05:00 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) No, I haven't encountered anything of the kind in the older literature. That said, imaginal temples of this sort can be extremely useful in many kinds of occult work. I'm very glad to hear that you're developing a set for the geomantic figures and encourage you to find some way to make them publicly available when you're satisfied with them -- having multiple people working with them will put power into the egregor. <br/><br/>2) Geomancy was a key Golden Dawn practice, one of the few modes of practical work introduced in the Outer Order and developed further in the Inner Order. Thus you can combine geomantic meditations and divinations with GD work with no trouble -- and indeed with excellent results. "}, {"id": "cmt59503536", "title": "Re: Geomantic Temples", "date": "2026-03-09 06:46 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Geomancy is a big part of “The Celtic Golden Dawn” , though it seems to be weaved into its own system of initiation - distinct from the books you’re studying now. Still, I thought I’d mention it !"}]}, {"id": "cmt59477936", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:22 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How could this meme be used as a mantra/working? Maybe I am asking the obvious but I am not familiar with any of your work that touches on this type of transmutation. <br/>A friend", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59485616", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 05:08 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's the amusing thing about it. I posted it as a joke, and exactly what drove the resulting synchronicity is a fascinating question I can't yet answer. Doing it as a dead serious working may not be a good option!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59487920", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 06:48 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you for this. I have a knee jerk reaction against working with the grubbier sides of energy that seem abundant around cities <br/>A friend ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59494832", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 03:43 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I very strongly encourage anyone who lives in or near a city to be even more enthusiastic about daily protective workings than usual. Our urban environments are festering messes of astral and etheric squalor. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59515312", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 09:54 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Presumably the powers involved are navigating a very great number of strategic tradeoffs. If people do things without all the subjective intention-encumbrances and potentially-future-decision-entangling precedent-interpretation-contingencies that naturally come along with people doing those things out of a belief that they will have certain effects, then that might free those powers' hands considerably.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59521712", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 12:21 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Crowley was wrong about a lot of things, but his point about how it's necessary to do things \"without lust of result\" is spot on. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59541936", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 03:53 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What happened with your meme seems almost Erisian, or should I say Derisian?<br/>Mirth seemed to let things flow more freely... 'something something' your inner self relaxes and lets the mana flow ...<br/><br/>- Cicada Grove"}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59479984", "title": "Where East Meets West", "date": "2026-03-09 04:35 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi John,<br/>I am East Asian yet am very drawn to western esotericism especially the golden dawn tradition. I realize, there’s nothing wrong with that nor is there any cultural/ethnic/or any other identifying  prerequisite for my preferences. But I do often wonder, why am I not more interested in Taoist magic or Korean shamanism or other esoteric Far East practices? Other than a feeling I was probably a Tibetan monk scribe in a past life and want to try something new. Do phenotypes matter when it comes to magical practice, i.e. one better suited than another? If you were to speculate, why would I desire such a crossover in this life? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59486384", "title": "Re: Where East Meets West", "date": "2026-03-09 05:14 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In my experience, there's no necessary connection between the genetic or cultural background of your current material body and the spiritual or occult traditions that are best suited to you in this incarnation. Very likely there are elements of the Golden Dawn tradition that your soul needs to develop its innate powers and potentials, and can't get from currently available East Asian traditions. "}, {"id": "cmt59495088", "title": "Re: Where East Meets West", "date": "2026-03-09 03:45 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, and if I'd been less sleepy last night, I would have said, \"You're not alone.\" There's a thriving Golden Dawn scene in Japan, and the Chinese translation of my book <i>Paths of Wisdom</i>, which is Golden Dawn Cabala, has sold quite respectably well. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59483056", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:50 am", "user": "katylina", "content": "I've started working through Gareth Knight's Experience of Inner worlds and i have two questions. <br/>1) which GSF practices i need to drop? For now i've replaced SOP with Sphere of Light<br/>2)the Fiery spear and other further exercises should be kept entire duration of the sphere of light?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59486640", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 05:20 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The SoP is the one you need to set aside. All the others can be continued as given. <br/><br/>2) Yes. The exercises in <i>Experience of the Inner Worlds</i> are cumulative; each step is added to the ones before, so you do the sphere of light, then the sphere of light plus the flaming spear, then the sphere of light and the flaming spear plus the serpent flame, and so on. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59493296", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 03:01 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "First I apologize for adding on my own question here; are the exercises in Steiner's \"How to Know Higher Worlds\" also incompatible with GSF?  I wish I understood more about the underlying logic involved here.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59495344", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 03:48 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Very much so. In fact, I include a lightly modified version of some of those exercises in <i>The Way of the Four Elements</i>, the second manual in the GSF series. In my experience, Steiner's work plays well with all the traditions I received from John Gilbert, and the GSF is based on those. <br/><br/>2) The underlying logic is not yet known to us -- remember that we're still assembling the broken fragments of occultism as it was known in the Renaissance, and that was pieced together from the broken fragments that survived from ancient times. Rather than relying on logic, I use experiment -- I do a lot of practices and pay attention to how they interact. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59502000", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 05:58 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I think there was a confusion based on my original question. But I get your response.  Thank you again. "}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59488176", "title": "The Carnelian Moon", "date": "2026-03-09 07:15 am", "user": "open_space", "content": "I usually wait until the next in the series is out for me to set on finishing the previous iteration of anything but I just had the chance and finished The Carnelian Moon in a sitting since I had the chance and April is not too far away.<br/><br/>The series is picking up! Thanks for writing it. It had me going at an increcendo pace since chapter one up to the end, to thinking I was about to finish only for there to be a last few notes which were very welcome. The funny thing for me is that just before I started reading it, I was reading Papus, so it was a pleasant surprise when I noticed our occult student protagonist was also. I alternated between Papus and the Moon at times when Ariel did just for fun. I also like that the way you portray some of the characters, have, well, a lot of character. There really is a shortage of uncles of the likes of Theophilus Cray and Dr. Moravec out there. <br/><br/>Will we get to know more about Cray's time in Siberia down the road?<br/><br/>I had heard about repercussion between the practitioner and the body of transformation --which is why pointy metals are dangerous-- but I had not heard of bits of physical matter being carried by the body of transformation. Is that last bit also true in practice?<br/><br/>I look forward to reading more of Ariel's adventures in a month or so. <br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59496112", "title": "Re: The Carnelian Moon", "date": "2026-03-09 03:59 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you! I'm delighted to hear that you enjoyed it. I have no idea what Theophilus Cray will or won't say about his past, though -- he's one of those characters of mine who does what he wants to do, when he wants to do it. <br/><br/>I've never tried doing a dense etheric body of transformation, though I've done such workings with the fine ethers a few times. The evidence from early modern werewolf trials consistently mentions that blood, mud, etc. were found on the material body of the werewolf, so I decided to take that seriously. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59488432", "title": "Crossing the Abyss!", "date": "2026-03-09 07:16 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, hope you're doing well. Thanks for another MM!<br/><br/>What is your view on the operation of \"Crossing the Abyss?\" I find it funny that after getting in touch with your Higher Self (or Holy Guardian Angel in thelemic parlance) you still \"cross the abyss\" to \"destroy your ego.\" But destroy the ego if you have contact with your Higher Self and got in touch with your individuality? Or is the angel a separate entity?<br/><br/>Thanks a lot!  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59498160", "title": "Re: Crossing the Abyss!", "date": "2026-03-09 04:33 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "My views here are very idiosyncratic; they're derived from material I learned from John Gilbert, and he cheerfully admitted that most occultists disagreed with him. (He got the material from his teachers, who apparently had the same attitude.) The only justification I can offer for my view is that it works better than the alternative. <br/><br/>The view in question? Human souls can't cross the Abyss. That's simply the way things are. The three highest spheres of the Tree, the primal triad in John's terminology, belong wholly to the Divine; the seven lower spheres are the realm of created beings; the Abyss is the boundary between them, and it is the Ring-Pass-Not for us, and for all created entities. <br/><br/>As for \"destroying the ego,\" I wrote about that here: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/the-no-ego-ego-trip-an-interlude/\">https://www.ecosophia.net/the-no-ego-ego-trip-an-interlude/</a><br/><br/>The short form is that everyone I've ever met who claimed to have destroyed or transcended their ego behaved like a raging egomaniac. Thus I don't think they actually did away with their egos -- I think they just repressed their egos, and the return of the repressed had its usual effect. The genuinely enlightened people I've met have egos; their secret is that they don't take their egos seriously. They treat their egos with the kind of amused compassion you'd direct at an unusually clumsy puppy. They're also much better company, and much wiser teachers, than the self-important types who go on and on about how they've gotten rid of their egos. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59505072", "title": "Re: Crossing the Abyss!", "date": "2026-03-09 08:04 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not the OP, but that does seem much more realistic as to what happens with the ego “after” enlightenment. My question is what is the phenomenon of ego death? People like Eckhart Tolle who say they have experienced this - what really happened there and is it the goal? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59508656", "title": "Re: Crossing the Abyss!", "date": "2026-03-09 09:02 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't think \"ego death\" is actually the death of the ego. I think it's a hide-and-seek game the ego plays with itself. As I noted above, I think they just repressed their own awareness of their egos, which is why they tend to be such egotists! "}, {"id": "cmt59516592", "title": "Re: Crossing the Abyss!", "date": "2026-03-09 10:19 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Here are some speculations about a material phenomenon frequently associated with introspective descriptions of \"enlightenment\" or \"ego death\", and about that phenomenon's relation to its supernatural correlates. (It might seem as though I didn't put much effort into those speculations, and that's half-true, but I think the speculations are substantially higher-grade than you might expect just given that fact.)<br/><br/>https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/359082.html?thread=59230890#cmt59271082<br/><br/>My impression is that the threshold at which people start using the phrase \"ego death\" is when a certain semi-illusion's defense processes (or the most-subjectively-\"visible\" layer of its defense processes, at least) are temporarily overcome for any significant length of time, whereas Zen practitioners like to reserve the term \"enlightenment\" for situations where the semi-illusion is replaced by a different (and less illusion-prone) configuration of motives-towards-cognitions in a way that's more sustainable and is on track to refine itself over time."}]}, {"id": "cmt59518128", "title": "Re: Crossing the Abyss!", "date": "2026-03-09 11:03 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ah, that's very interesting. I recognize \"ring pass not\" from Fortune's Cosmic Doctrine, it's about time I take a look at that book again. <br/><br/>If I makey ask another one: what do you think happens to those who TRY to Cross the Abyss? What do you make of this Choronzon figure? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59524016", "title": "Re: Crossing the Abyss!", "date": "2026-03-10 12:55 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The ego is really good at working up grand melodramas in which it can be a persecuted victim, a conquering hero, or both at once. The grand battle with Choronzon is a great example. I'm sure quite a few people don't realize that they're shadowboxing with a projection, and take to the melodrama with utter seriousness, but I've yet to meet any such people who strike me as genuinely enlightened, or even moving in that direction -- au contraire, one of the embarrassing things about Western occultism in recent years is how many of its big names don't even seem to have achieved ordinary maturity. That's par for the course for a spiritual tradition that draws most of its members from the fringes of society, but there it is. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59526576", "title": "Re: Crossing the Abyss!", "date": "2026-03-10 01:21 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Got it! Loved your article about the ego, by the way. Many thanks!!"}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59488688", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 07:54 am", "user": "goakangarooo", "content": "Hello JMG,<br/><br/>Currently, I'm studying both of your books *Revisioning the Tree of Life* and *The Doors of Tarot*. John Gilbert's and your approach on tarot is different from the classical Golden Dawn System. And I really love it. It makes my life much more enjoyable because I am less dissociated from my actions and my subconscious. Thank you therefore! But I wonder, how it combines with the (classical) astrological system. <br/><br/>The (classical) astrological system is quite different from the tarot system of JG and you!? Because we have different planets and signs associated with the keys, right? In your book you mention the Golden Dawn reference and Clifford Bias. That's where my confusion sets in. How to differentiate (or connect) those both system (JG and your tarot &amp; classical astrology), therefore how to integrate those both systems. I wonder because in the classical astrology system we have 'decan, planet and signs' related to the minor cards. But in the tarot book the minor cards are not related to any planet or signs but to their parent-key! Like the 3's of the minor are related to III. The Empress—are they therefore related to the planet [[♃ Jupiter]] and to the sign [[♐ Sagittarius]]? <br/><br/>How does the classical astrological system and cabala/tarot system relate to each other. Or are those complete different systems. I'm kinda confused here. How do I know the planet and sign and decan of the 3 of swords for example?<br/><br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59498928", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:38 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The two systems don't relate to each other and it's a mistake to make them try to do so. It's like trying to talk in English and Japanese at the same time -- the result will be a garbled mess that nobody will understand, not even you. Symbolic systems are in fact languages -- they're the languages we use to interact with the Unseen -- and so it works best to decide in advance which system you're going to use, and use that. <br/><br/>I know people who use the Golden Dawn astrological correspondences with one deck, and John's correspondences with a different deck. It seems to work quite well, just as you can speak English in the office and Japanese at the sushi bar. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59507376", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 08:31 pm", "user": "goakangarooo", "content": "<p>Thank you so much! That cleared the space for me.</p>\n"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59488944", "title": "Insomnia and SoP", "date": "2026-03-09 08:49 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have a couple of questions today.  First, when I wake up in the middle of the night and want to go back to sleep, what is a good mental habit?  Sometimes I concentrate (or try) on my hara chakra and maybe that works.  I have tried various affirmations, or prayers.  Sometimes I get up and do something on the computer, like I'm doing now.  <br/><br/>Second question concerns the SoP.  I'm using the Greek Pagan pantheon.  For personal reasons, I'd like to replace Apollo with Helios for fire.  Would it be more apt to use Helios for Spirit Above?  <br/><br/>Thank you.  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59499184", "title": "Re: Insomnia and SoP", "date": "2026-03-09 04:40 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That depends on lots of individual variables. For me, sometimes it works best just to lie there and still my mind, but other times I need to get up, drink some green tea (which relaxes me), and read for an hour before going back to bed. Experimentation is the only way I know of to find something that works. <br/><br/>2) Of course you can make that change. Apollo and Helios were identified with each other in late classical times, so it's not even a drastic change. You can place him in either position, depending on what seems best to you. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59502256", "title": "Re: Insomnia and SoP", "date": "2026-03-09 06:00 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59489200", "title": "Natural magic book", "date": "2026-03-09 08:58 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What beginner level book on natural magic would you recommend?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59499440", "title": "Re: Natural magic book", "date": "2026-03-09 04:42 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "At the risk of tooting my own horn, my book <a href=\"https://bookshop.org/p/books/encyclopedia-of-natural-magic-john-michael-greer/e5501e571e504e21?aid=16751&amp;ean=9780738706740&amp;listref=jmg-occultism-books&amp;next=t\">The Encyclopedia of Natural Magic</a> covers the ground well and has been used successfully by many beginners. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59489456", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 09:22 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG, <br/>Somewhere or other, possibly here, I came across English-language versions of some of the material in the GD tradition, which is the one I work in. This involved the use of the words of the Lord's Prayer for the Cabalistic Cross, but also English (or Greek) Names of and expression related to God for the LBRP and the MP Exercise. But everything I have been able to find insists on Hebrew. Can you offer any wisdom on non-Hebrew alternatives, but within the GD tradition? <br/>Thank you so much for your work. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59499696", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:48 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "People have been modifying the basic GD rituals since before the GD itself was founded! The LBRP itself began as a modification of Eliphas Levi's \"Conjuration of the Four,\" for that matter. As for Hebrew, that's a popular option but it's not the only game in town. One of my books, <a href=\"https://bookshop.org/p/books/the-celtic-golden-dawn-an-original-complete-curriculum-of-druidical-study-john-michael-greer/b97f9dfb968a1527?aid=16751&amp;ean=9780738731551&amp;listref=jmg-druidry-books&amp;next=t\">The Celtic Golden Dawn</a>, reworks the whole system using Welsh divine names from the Druid tradition, and it works very effectively indeed. If you want to do a wholly English GD system, go ye forth and do that thing, and don't let those who suffer from the hardening of the orthodoxies slow you down. ", "edit_time": "2026-03-09 04:48 pm (UTC)"}]}, {"id": "cmt59489712", "title": "Vocalizing invocations", "date": "2026-03-09 10:29 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,<br/><br/>Thank you for Magic Mondays and apologies if this question comes across as a bit confused.<br/><br/>I have a question about invocations that are said in the mind, i.e., not out loud (for example, invoking the archangels when performing the LBRP). When I do such invocations, I could either 'think linguistically' the words of the invocation (with no involvement of the voice apparatus), or I could sound these words without moving my lips (sub-vocalizing?), in which case, I can feel the movements of the uvula--or even the tongue--in rhythm with the syllables of the invocation.<br/><br/>I would like to know if there is any difference in terms of the power of the invocation between these two methods.<br/><br/>I guess this could be applied to even regular reading, actually: in this case, the effect seems to be a tradeoff between speed and retention/understanding of the material, at least for me.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59499952", "title": "Re: Vocalizing invocations", "date": "2026-03-09 04:49 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "This varies from person to person. Why not experiment, paying close attention to your own perceptions and intuitions, and see what you learn? "}]}, {"id": "cmt59489968", "title": "A divination question: The Dodecagram reversed.", "date": "2026-03-09 12:22 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Greetings! <br/><br/>I got this card a couple of times lately during divination, and after I was done with thinking about how it might apply to my day, something came to me about the general meaning of the card. <br/><br/>I'd like to meditate on it myself for a while, but would like to see if there is a solid base before I build a metaphorical tower of pisa on sand, so I am reaching on to you, the creator of the deck.<br/><br/>What started this whole thing was the following notion, so I was wondering if you could please answer the following:  <br/><br/>Am I right in thinking the construction where three equilateral triangles are combined to form the star (or, significantly,  an additional triangle is added to a hexagram) corresponds to the reversed \"Complexity\" while the star (I mean the dodecagram) formed by three squares, the upright \"Completeness\"?<br/><br/>Thank you and I wish you a nice day.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59500208", "title": "Re: A divination question: The Dodecagram reversed.", "date": "2026-03-09 04:52 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Okay, first of all, there are no wrong answers in interpreting symbols. Second, there are no wrong answers in interpreting symbols. Third, and most importantly, <i><b>there really are no wrong answers in interpreting symbols</b></i>. You've had an insight that reflects the meaning of the card to you; don't worry about whether it's right or wrong. Follow it out and see where it leads you. <br/><br/>For what it's worth, what you've suggested makes sense to me. That shouldn't matter to you, though. What matters is that it speaks to you and has the potential to teach you things about the cards and their symbolism. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59490736", "title": "Unexpected energy states", "date": "2026-03-09 01:04 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have observed a general feeling that occurs around 8am UTC – a sort of low level wave of anxiety that has no obvious root. It’s almost like something gets ‘switched on’ around eight am – sometimes before, sometimes after. <br/>Possibilities include: it’s internal to me, it is external to me, some combination on one or other, something else.<br/><br/>Internal to me could be some imbalance of emotion or energy expressing as anxiety.<br/>External to me could just be picking up the state of the world and anxieties of people around.<br/>Combination e.g. that something external triggers something internal, or something internal resonates with something external.<br/>Something else?  e.g. something to do with conjunction energies or something else altogether?<br/>The regular timing of it is weird and not something I’ve come across before.<br/><br/>The experiment I'm doing started at new moon on Feb 17th just before conjunction on the 20th. This last week I backslid by looking at some reports on Iran, but this has been going on since big conjunction and before Middle East kicked-off.<br/><br/>Sunday Feb 8th around 7am I began contemplation/meditation – all as usual. Noticed anxiety state rising and caught it. In five elemental processes worry is associated with stomach/spleen but rather than working there, I wondered about heart centre and lungs which sit either side in the cycle – moments after focussing on those two I became aware of a tightness on the left (spleen area), moved the hands over the area and applied focus, the tightness began dissolving and I had a charged feeling ‘very awake’. While thinking about this in relation to emotions, a sudden conception came up, like part image part idea where I was looking at a sphere of emotions, then a feeling of expanding and the emotions are there like a ‘constellation’; the anxiety was completely gone and it sparked a whole set of thoughts and ideas that kept me busy all day.<br/><br/>I’m going to change my pattern so that I am outside working by 8am and see if the anxiety is my subconscious telling me I need to be working on all the backed-up physical jobs that need doing, and it may just be that. Time will tell.<br/><br/>But I also wonder, whilst conjunction effects can take years to play out, have you or anyone else been aware of unexpected energy states popping up since the conjunction?<br/><br/>Thank you.<br/><br/>[earthworm]<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59509168", "title": "Re: Unexpected energy states", "date": "2026-03-09 09:03 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm! I haven't noticed this, but that doesn't mean it's not real, of course. Anyone else? "}, {"id": "cmt59513264", "title": "Re: Unexpected energy states", "date": "2026-03-09 09:35 pm", "user": "lukeszy", "content": "Yes to your question.  Sorry for edit JMG.", "edit_time": "2026-03-09 09:59 pm (UTC)"}]}, {"id": "cmt59491248", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 01:25 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "\"Sunday Feb 8th\" should have been Sun Mar 8th.<br/><br/>haha - I got the day wrong for the conjunction and now it seems I don't even know what month it is! Onward and upward...<br/><br/>[earthworm]"}, {"id": "cmt59492016", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 01:42 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,<br/>I noticed last week one or two people talking about the difficulties of working with Metatron, and checking back it seems that this has been discussed in the past as well. <br/>I do the version of the LBRP developed by Damien Nicholls which features Metatron above and Sandalphon below. I therefore wondered whether it wouldn't be more prudent to leave those two out, and tried the experiment.There was an extremely irritable reaction from Metatron demanding to know why I'd left him out, so I've reverted to my ordinary formula. I have attempted to contact him, but can't get anything more than residual irritation. <br/>Does this have any wider significance in your view, and should I try to cultivate something with Metatron even if its tricky, or is it best left as an error on my part which I've now, I hope, repaired? <br/>Thank you for any light you can shed. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59509680", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 09:06 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Metatron is perfectly safe and easy to work with if you remember that you compare to him the way a grain of sand compares to a planet. I'd encourage you to keep working Damien's practice if that's what works well for you. Yours was a minor error and not a serious one; the lesson to take from it is that once you begin a practice, don't fiddle with it -- stick with the form you learned and see where it takes you. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59492272", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 01:52 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>In a recent post about New Thought on your other blog you said that you rarely agree with Mitch Horowitz about anything. Is there something in particular you don't like about his work?<br/><br/>Thanks for Magic Monday.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59509936", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 09:10 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I am prejudiced against Satanists. My experience with them -- not just once, but repeatedly -- is that they behave exactly the way you'd expect from someone who says \"evil, be thou my good;\" they'll smile and nod, then stab you in the back and trash things that matter to you, and if you object they'll jeer at you and say, \"It's all your fault, you trusted me.\"<br/><br/>That is to say, the Satanists I've encountered are the nastiest sort of toxic jerks. That's why, once Horowitz went down that road, I dropped him like a hot rock and told him never to contact me again. To give him credit, he hasn't tried to do so. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59539888", "title": "Satanists", "date": "2026-03-10 03:33 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I recently watched some interviews with Nicholas Schreck on the Lantern Bridge channel on YouTube. He and his now ex-wife Zeena Schreck both left the Satanist scene and converted to Vajrayana Buddhism. The most interesting part was his saying that most of these famous Satanists were total losers. Anton LaVey was usually scared to leave his house and didn’t really know how to practice magic. And Michael Aquino of the Temple of Set created a fanfic version of the god Set which had little to do with the Egyptian god. And he ended up committing suicide at the end. <br/><br/>I feel like Mitch Horowitz had a good thing going when he was presenting the various New Thought teachers, and then he totally blew it by telling people “if nothing has worked, try Satanism.”"}]}, {"id": "cmt59516848", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 10:22 pm", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>If I may comment, I’ve read several of Horowitz’s books and my impression from those is that his evil is subtle and insidious: you wouldn’t even get a knife in the back, per se, but if you ever became entangled with him he’d probably encourage you as you followed your desires to ruin, then once you realize what had happened he’d simply inform you that, after all, they were your own choices, not his. </p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59524784", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 01:07 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Ick. <br/><br/>It's really sad, too. He was the managing editor of the department of Tarcher Penguin that published the translation of Levi's _Doctrine and Ritual of High Magic_, which is how I got to know him. He seemed smart and pleasant enough at that point. He even got himself a position with Manly P. Hall's Philosophical Research Society, a dream job for any occultist...and then proceeded to become a public Satanist and try to leverage PRS as a platform for that feculent ideology. Of course they dumped him on the spot, and he proceeded to whine about how badly he'd been treated. <br/><br/>John Gilbert had a standard policy with Satanists; if one applied to study with him, John would refuse, and if they joined under false pretenses and then proclaimed their Satanism, he'd dismiss them, revoke any credentials they'd earned, and refund any money they'd paid him. He always said that what Satanists want more than anything else is to imitate their patron and get thrown out of Heaven. That's why they'll join all kinds of groups and then start making trouble, and if you tolerate them, they'll simply increase the volume until the group collapses or the leadership throws them out. He said that he always threw them out at once because that was what they were really after. I thought of that when I heard about Horowitz and the PRS. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59529392", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 01:40 am", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>That is sad to hear about him.  I've mentioned this before, but in one of his books he talks about how he made a vow to God to devote his life to him if he (God) gave him (Mitch) what he wanted.  Well, he got what he wanted, and now seems to be trying to use Satanism as a way to creatively reinterpret the terms of the deal.</p>\n<p>He'd almost certainly be better off just admitting that he can't hold up his end of the bargain and begging forgiveness.  That he chose the path he did instead of that speaks of a great deal hubris.</p>\n<p>As for John Gilbert's theory about why Satanists do what they do, that makes a great deal of sense to me.  I'm aware of one other \"friendly Satanist\" who on the surface seems to be a good deal less obviously malicious than most: Venger Satanis, self-proclaimed High Priest of Cthulhu and writer/publisher of pornographic roleplaying game supplements.  A few years back he got himself kicked off DriveThruRPG for some time, which almost ended his publishing career, by the expedient of making a show of flagrantly violating their content rules twice, getting his works taken down, and drumming up outrage online to try to drive sales of his other works.</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59531696", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 01:55 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's so typical of the Satanists I've met, not least in its sheer self-defeating stupidity. As for \"High Priest of Cthulhu,\" oh, please. The Dreaming Lord has more class than that..."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59527856", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 01:28 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This is a pretty good description of how modern propaganda works too, isn't it? <br/><br/>There's this passionate effort to find and use whatever vices people have to lead them down a truly horrific path, combined with the remarkably absurd insistence that it really was the victim's free will all along. It's enough to make me wonder if there's a reason for this similarity...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59541168", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 03:48 am", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>Hmm, that does work, doesn't it? Public Relations as applied Satanism. Hmm.</p>\n"}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59493040", "title": "Yeat's Wheel", "date": "2026-03-09 02:56 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "At one point, if I remember correctly, you wrote that the final leap off the Wheel can happen at any point on the second half of the Wheel.<br/><br/>How can that be when there are phases when unity of being breaks apart? In the phase after yours, The Assertive Man, the soul \"desires to be strong and stable, but as Unity of Being and self-knowledge are both gone, and it is too soon to grasp at another unity through primary mind, he passes from emphasis to emphasis.\" I don't see how that person can unite with his Higher Self, or a deity.<br/><br/>So were you oversimplifying when you wrote \"second half of the wheel?\"<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59511216", "title": "Re: Yeat's Wheel", "date": "2026-03-09 09:18 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nope. When Yeats talks about Unity of Being he's referencing the expression of that unity in the four Faculties -- Will, Creative Mind, Mask, and Body of Fate. Those are the temporary expression of four eternal Principles -- Husk, Spirit, Passionate Body, and Celestial Body -- which always possess Unity of Being. If the person of Phase 19, in passing from emphasis to emphasis, reaches one that allows Will to attune itself fully to Husk and Creative Mind to do the same thing to Spirit, even briefly, that's the final incarnation for that soul, and at death -- when the Faculties dissolve back into the Principles -- the transition to the Thirteenth Cone takes place. The much rarer experience of leaving the wheel while incarnate (the sort of thing that produces genuine living saints and sages) is mostly limited to the late 4th quarter, but the more common experience of making contact in life and then achieving liberation at death can happen anywhere. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59493808", "title": "Water vitalisation", "date": "2026-03-09 03:34 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,<br/>After some positive experiences with homeopathy, I started reading about the work of Victor Schauberger and Johann Grander. It seems to me, that their insights are very valuable, and I found some devices that claim to \"vitalise\" water by swirling it in a specific vortext, with crystals nearby, based on their findings.<br/><br/>Would you care to comment on these devices to bring life back into water, whether they may be useful, and how they might work? It seems to me, their function is similar to homeopathic preparation, and although I have no doubt that homeopathy works, part of me still cannot grasp how.<br/><br/>The most promising devices I have found are:<br/>https://www.blueearth.nu/en/product/watervitalizer-vita-blue-32/<br/><br/>and<br/><br/>https://umh.at/en/<br/><br/>Thank you in advance.<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59511472", "title": "Re: Water vitalisation", "date": "2026-03-09 09:19 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I haven't studied them and so don't have the necessary background to offer a meaningful opinion on the subject. Anyone else? "}]}, {"id": "cmt59496880", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:11 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Two different clairvoyants, who don’t know each other and weren’t aware of each other’s insights, told me they felt my young daughter was a persecuted Christian monastic in her previous life. (One of the clairvoyants is a practicing Anthroposophist.) For various additional reasons (among others, she knew the structure and mysteries of the rosary at age 4 with no previous exposure), I am inclined to agree.<br/><br/>She’s struggled a bit physically since her premature birth. Getting her baptized and regularly receiving the Christian sacraments has helped tremendously, but she still suffers from certain physical weaknesses. She is very small and thin for her age, and prone to illness, and not very aware of her material body. Highly creative and intelligent. We homeschool.<br/><br/>Do you have any other specific advice for a child like this? Have you come across writings anywhere about former monastics in current incarnations?<br/><br/>Thank you! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59511984", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 09:25 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The best possible childhood for such a child is one that is loving, supportive, and relentlessly ordinary. She'll need to be encouraged to pay attention to material existence, so gentle forms of exercise are good, and massage is something I'd highly recommend. She's probably going to make a beeline for some kind of religious vocation when she's older, but you can at least help her become a little more grounded on the way there.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59520176", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 12:04 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In terms of gentle massage for a sensitive child, I would recommend that family members close to her and whom she trusts offer massage on her hands and her feet.  A gentle, rhythmic bedtime massage on the palms of the hands is something that my children often found soothing and grounding when they were little, and it can also help with an upset stomach.<br/><br/>There are also what are called 'extra' or 'special' acupuncture points in the webs between the fingers, that don't necessarily lie on any meridians, and that can also prove to be soothing as well as having other health benefits.  I assume that is why people who are very upset often \"wring their hands.\"  It's a way of self-calming.  I find myself squeezing my hands together in a 'wringing the hands' motion before I go to sleep --not deliberately but my hands just do it on their own, and it seems to settle me nicely into sleep.  I guess my hands know what they're doing!  :D<br/><br/>Winifred"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59498672", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 04:33 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "There's some obvious ways people can interact with other planes - tai chi or yoga for the etheric, ritual magic for the astral, a whole load of intellectual pursuits for the mental, prayer for the divine. But how do people interact with the causal plane?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59512240", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 09:27 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nah, prayer attunes us to the spiritual plane, which is the plane just above the mental plane. The causal and divine planes are completely beyond our reach while we're incarnate. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59500464", "title": "Question about salt and nails", "date": "2026-03-09 05:00 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In the FAQ, when you explain about clearing a space by setting out a jar with kosher salt and bent nails, you add, \"Watch for the salt to become discolored or the nails to rust or corrode; when this happens, you need to change the salt and nails.\" <br/><br/>My question: Is there any regularity to how long it takes before this discoloration or corrosion happen? Or does it all depend? If it all depends, what are some of the most important factors?<br/><br/>Thank you for holding this space for us!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59512496", "title": "Re: Question about salt and nails", "date": "2026-03-09 09:29 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It depends entirely on how much noxious etheric influence there is in the place where the jar is located. I've seen jars like that remain fine for a year or more, and I've seen them require changing every few weeks, depending on how many people are flinging around how much nasty magic and how much sheer etheric filth and squalor has built up there. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59500976", "title": "Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-09 05:36 pm", "user": "kylec", "content": "All healing hands requests from last week have ben fulfilled. If you'd like to get on the list again or for the first time, please reply here or PM me with your name and request. Thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59509424", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-09 09:03 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yes, I would like healing hands this week.<br/><br/>Thank you very much for all your efforts,<br/>Brad"}, {"id": "cmt59510448", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-09 09:15 pm", "user": "vitranc", "content": "Hi Kylec,<br/>If I may, I would like to come on the list again this week.<br/>Best regards,<br/>V"}]}, {"id": "cmt59501488", "title": "LBRP \"Range\"", "date": "2026-03-09 05:50 pm", "user": "davidp", "content": "Hey JMG,<br/><br/>I was wondering what space the LBRP banishes in. Just inside the traced circle? I'm asking because I'd like to know whether a consecrated object needs to be wrapped in silk if I banish in the same room or, if not, how close is okay.<br/><br/>Thanks in advance, as I most likely won't have time to check back in before midnight.<br/><br/>—David P.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59512752", "title": "Re: LBRP \"Range\"", "date": "2026-03-09 09:30 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, you need to wrap any consecrated object in silk or linen before you perform the LBRP in the same room, or in any room close by. The range depends on how good you are, but it's normally at least to the walls, floor, and ceiling in all directions. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59501744", "title": "Clarification on cleansing", "date": "2026-03-09 05:53 pm", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "From the MM FAQ:<br/><br/>\"You can also use the same principle on a broader scale to clear a room or other space.  Fill a glass jar with salt and put several bent nails in it. This will absorb a lot of negative energy. Watch for the salt to become discolored or the nails to rust or corrode; when this happens, you need to change the salt and nails.\"<br/><br/>Quite interesting, but I'd like further clarification:<br/><br/>1. What kind of salt goes in the jar? Iodized salt, sea salt, or any sort of NaCl?<br/>2. Is it required to bend the nails with pliers, or can I use other methods, eg hammer and vice?<br/>3. Should the nails be bent at 90 degrees, or at a shallow angle?<br/>4. Should the jar be sealed or left open? If sealed, does it need its lid, or would a tissue &amp; rubber band be better?<br/>5. Should the jar be left out in the open, or can it be inside of a drawer?<br/><br/>(normally I limit my queries to 3, but since the scope is narrow here, I'm making an exception)<br/><br/>TIA.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59514032", "title": "Re: Clarification on cleansing", "date": "2026-03-09 09:48 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Salt in large flakes is best. I've used coarse sea salt and kosher salt with good results. <br/><br/>2) Any way you want. If you're Uri Geller, you can even bend them psychically. ;-)<br/><br/>3) I've never noticed that the angle made any difference at all. <br/><br/>4) A metal lid limits its effectiveness. Open works, so do nonmetallic lids, and so does a piece of cloth and a rubber band. <br/><br/>5) Depends on the material in the drawer. Metal limits its effectiveness. Wood does not. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59538096", "title": "Re: Clarification on cleansing", "date": "2026-03-10 03:19 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "I see, thanks! I'll see how it works out, but it's quite useful to get a head start instead of having to experiment around."}, {"id": "cmt59542448", "title": "Re: Clarification on cleansing", "date": "2026-03-10 03:59 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "Also, that bit about Uri Geller reminds me of that famous scene from the Matrix, \"there is no spoon\". Maybe a bit of occultism slipped into Philosophy 101: the movie."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59502768", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 06:30 pm", "user": "angelica5804", "content": "Here's a sign a friend of mine saw at a cafe over the weekend that I think this group will appreciate:<br/><br/>[IMAGE:0]", "images": [{"url": "https://angelica5804.dreamwidth.org/file/312.png", "local_path": "./data/archive/2026/2026-03-08_10-40PM_Magic_Monday/images/2026-03-09_06_30_pm_312.png"}], "replies": [{"id": "cmt59505328", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 08:07 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "St. Paisios (modern Greek Orthodox saint) had some wonderful quotes about this, such as: “If you want to grab God’s attention so he’ll hear you during prayer, turn the dial to humility, for God always works in this frequency.” "}, {"id": "cmt59514288", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 09:48 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nice. The great challenge is taking the time to log on to the connection..."}]}, {"id": "cmt59503024", "title": "Piscean apocalypse", "date": "2026-03-09 06:33 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have been contemplating something you said in some blog post or podcast, about how the Piscean age is coming to an end about this year, and how the transition to the Aquarian age could be bumpy.  And I see the Piscean dispensations all heading towards a truly apocalyptic showdown in the land of their birth.  I see these religions of peace whipping everyone into war, the religions of mercy leading to horrid cruelty and madness.  Where does it end?  Many say it will cause the end of the world, which only fuels the Piscean apocalyptic madness.  I don't believe in the linear narrative of time of the Piscean religions, and believe the world and life cannot end, just change.  But still, nuclear war is a terrifying prospect. <br/><br/>Perhaps it was this fear that led to the dream I had, but I have asked the Gods and the infinite consciousness of the self-aware universe to give me a clue as to how this Piscean age ends.  I will recount the dream I had last night and leave you all to discuss what it may mean.<br/><br/>Terrible war rages across the desert.  Cities burn, soldiers die, the rivers run red with blood, and the only remaining structures are towers of bodies that reach for the sky.  The Jewish star, Christian Cross, and Muslim crescent are all stained red with blood.  Everyone is willing to fight and kill and die for their holy book.  No one will budge an inch.  Nuclear armageddon is threatened, first by Isreal, then Iran has them.  Flaming mushrooms threaten to bloom.<br/><br/>And then... then Jerusalem goes up in flames.  It's the only nuke that goes off.  It wasn't even set off by the fanatics.  A consortium of concerned scientists, military and government officials, mostly from nations that don't believe in Abrahamic faiths, like India or China, came together to try and save the world from its faiths.  They decided that if the children couldn't play with this toy, they would take it away.  They apologize for the deaths but declare that its a far, far lower body count than full nuclear war would have produced, and thus was the lesser of the two evils.  The leaders of this group reveal themselves, that they acted independently of any government (a lie, India and China supported their efforts to save the world) and that they themselves had perished in the blast, so there's no one to hate, no one to avenge, no one to fight.<br/><br/>The faithful of all 3 Abrahmic faiths are faced with a blow to the foundations of their faiths.  You can no longer believe in a physical literalist version of these faiths.  They all involved an end of the world in Jerusalem, specifically regarding certain events on the temple mount.  This cannot happen now.  Jerusalem is gone forever.  You can't even visit the site without dying.  The temple mount, epicenter of the explosion, is literally obliterated.  As all these blind faithful realize that their chosen holy person isn't literally physically coming back as they believed, they realize their warring was for nothing.  And all the faithful lay down their arms and weed for their dead religions.<br/><br/>Oh, there are still Jews and Christians and Muslims, but they have to interpret their scriptures symbolically, metaphorically and metaphysically.   The wide-eyed fundamentalism cannot be sustained.  Plus, most of the hardcore faithful have killed each other by this point.  Millions leave the Abrahamic faiths.  Some to the religion of progress, but after atheist materialists blow up Jerusalem their religion isn't exactly popular either.  They drift, to a thousand different faiths, and that is how the Piscean phrophetic faiths fail, how the Piscean age yields to the Aquarian.<br/><br/>I really hope this isn't a prohphetic dream about the end of the prophetic religions.  Then again... it's not the worst future we could be facing.  It's food for thought, and I look forward to any and all thoughts and comments.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59514800", "title": "Re: Piscean apocalypse", "date": "2026-03-09 09:51 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "As near as I can tell, the Aquarian age began in 1879; that was certainly the opinion of a lot of occultists back then, and their logic seems sound. Of course that was just the beginning of a long transitional process, which will not finish for centuries. <br/><br/>As for your apocalypse, well, we'll see. Belief in apocalypses is very much of a Piscean habit. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59523504", "title": "Re: Piscean apocalypse", "date": "2026-03-10 12:32 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "I'm not endorsing the prediction that Jerusalem gets nuked by secularists, but the destruction of one city regarded as holy is a lot more plausible than the end of the world, given that it's happened before.<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59525040", "title": "Re: Piscean apocalypse", "date": "2026-03-10 01:10 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Granted, but it still doesn't seem likely to me -- nor, to be frank, do I buy the claim that Abrahamic religions will collapse promptly as a result. Jerusalem has had its entire population slaughtered more than once in its history, and they've just kept on coming back for more. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59527600", "title": "Re: Piscean apocalypse", "date": "2026-03-10 01:28 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "I wouldn't expect the Abrahamic religions to collapse either. They would assign the label of Jerusalem in the prophecies to another city, and keep on making End Times predictions, while other sects of those religions ignore those predictions or make different ones. The OP's scenario would cause a crisis of faith among some Jews, Christians, and Muslims and surely some of them would seek other religions. The OP would be mistaking the scale and the permanance of that crisis, but he wouldn't be entirely wrong about the second part if the first part happens. It probably won't.<br/><br/>However, I am worried about nukes being used, because Israel makes threats about the Samson Option and might use it (or just launch nukes on the cities of enemy states, if the government retains some sanity) if it takes too much damage from Iran in this war. And if so, Jerusalem <i>could</i> get nuked if Iran had secretly made a few nukes.<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59530928", "title": "Re: Piscean apocalypse", "date": "2026-03-10 01:48 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It wouldn't surprise me at all if a few mushroom clouds were involved in the next set of major Middle Eastern wars. The thing is, nuking Jerusalem wouldn't remove it from play. When the Romans conquered Jerusalem after the revolt of Simon bar Kokhba they leveled the city to the ground, built a new Roman city there, imported a population from elsewhere, and forbade Jews to live there under penalty of death. When the Crusaders took Jerusalem they slaughtered every man, woman, and child in the city -- contemporary records claim that they rode through blood more than a foot deep in the streets on their way to pray at the shrine of the Prince of Peace. Neither of those events changed the city's status. If it got nuked -- well, Hiroshima and Nagasaki are both thriving cities now, you know..."}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59503792", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 06:57 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear Druid,<br/>Over this side of the Atlantic, people are getting concerned about the statements of Christian Zionists in positions of power in the US, to the effect that the war in Iran is intended to allow the expansion of Israel to its Biblical frontiers, at which point Jesus Christ will return. And those who read the Hebrew press tell us that there are Ministers in the current government who look forward with glee to some kind of apocalyptic event which will signal the return of the Messiah. (There are no traditions like that in Europe, really.) My question is not about the politics, which is for another forum, but whether such people are not evoking dangerous and destructive powers. Certainly the psychic weather seems to be getting a lot darker. Grateful for your views. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59515056", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 09:54 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "\"No traditions like that in Europe...\"  Oh, my. Thank you for the laugh. They're out of fashion just now, but yes, that sort of thinking runs all through European culture. Norman Cohn's history <i>The Pursuit of the Millennium</i> has a few things to say about that. <br/><br/>As for the addiction to apocalyptic thinking, it's a common vice, and yes, a very destructive one. There's plenty of it in Islam as well, too. Quite regularly it bathes large sections of the planet in blood. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59515568", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 09:56 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "These days apocalyptic thinking in Europe sits in secular drag, the stuff like runaway global warning, near term human extinction, the rapid collapse of European civilization, Camp of the Saints style, etc. "}, {"id": "cmt59527344", "title": "\"no traditions like that in Europe\"", "date": "2026-03-10 01:27 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "-- not to mention east Asia, south Asia, south-east Asia, north Asia, and central Asia. People being what they are, there are probably other regions as well, but less well documented.<br/><br/>Apocalypticism, and messianic apocalypticism, seem to be pretty much universal energetic configurations, ready to manifest when they encounter fertile ground.<br/><br/>LeGrand", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59530416", "title": "Re: \"no traditions like that in Europe\"", "date": "2026-03-10 01:44 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Granted! Also North and South America, Africa, and Australasia. I haven't yet read of any apocalyptic cults in Antarctica but doubtless it's just a matter of time!"}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59504048", "title": "VGW", "date": "2026-03-09 07:30 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey JMG,<br/><br/>I realized just recently that you wrote a short paragraph recommending Syzygy-Reflections on the Monastery of the Seven Rays by Tau Palamas, so I was wondering what your opinion on the work of Michael Bertiaux is, specifically his Voudon Gnostic Workbook? (Especially as it's just got a reprint). I ask because, upon searching, the history of Bertiaux, the order, and that book is very difficult to pin down.<br/><br/>Thank you,<br/>J", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59515824", "title": "Re: VGW", "date": "2026-03-09 09:57 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've read Bertiaux's work, including the Monastery of the Seven Rays material. It's weirder than a seven-headed snake, and very much not my style, but I know people who've gotten good results with it. Bertiaux himself appears to be sincere. As for Tau Palamas, he's a friend of mine, and one of the very few other people known to me who was also consecrated, as I was, as a bishop in the Universal Gnostic Church. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59504304", "title": "Above and Below", "date": "2026-03-09 07:41 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I’m stuck between focusing on spirit - that transcendent source with, in and through all things - and accepting my limited physical earthly existence. <br/><br/>How are the two integrated?<br/><br/>When we focus on spirit, are we neglecting or avoiding our earthly life? A lot of folks would say finding the spirit is the only thing that matters. <br/><br/>Thanks", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59516080", "title": "Re: Above and Below", "date": "2026-03-09 09:59 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "One of the basic lessons of occult philosophy is that whenever you have a rigid duality like that, you're missing the third factor that unites them. Between matter and spirit is life, which partakes of both. The notion that we all ought to ignore the material world and focus entirely on spirit, like the opposite but equally silly notion that we ought to ignore the spiritual world and focus entirely on matter, is a little like insisting that human beings all ought to be chopped in half at the waist. We live in all three worlds and our task is to bring them all into harmony! "}]}, {"id": "cmt59504560", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 07:46 pm", "user": "diletpoly", "content": "<p>Hello JMG and Commentariat</p>\n<p>Thanks as always for this space. A few questions this week.</p>\n<p>1.As I work my way through the OPH, I've reached the 39th week, and read something like, \"occult practices attempt to bring awareness/attention to the subjective mind\" (I'm away from the book, so I'm probably off, but I'm pretty sure of the gist of it). That made me wonder, things like Tai Chi and yoga have a similar effect, does that make them occult practices of a sort, or is it more that they have some of the same goals?</p>\n<p>2.Is it ever worthwhile to do a lodge working (GSF, in this case) in the imagination? I find myself still stumbling over some of the parts of the lodge opening/closing, more than 3 years on. I try to do them every week, hoping that will keep them fresh and help me commit them fully to memory, but sometimes events (or, usually, children) prevent me from being quite so consistent. So I wonder if doing them in the astral/imagination would be a good workaround? \nAs an aside, I think another good \"fix\" would be to switch from using incense, which I am loathe to burn too often, to potpourri supplemented from time to time with some essential oils, Weird of Hali style. But I haven't gotten around to doing that, and the fact that I have over a hundred sticks and cones of incense makes me think I should burn those first, before making the shift.</p>\n<p>Again, thanks for the space and your time. And I'm looking forward to hearing when you decide to have a meetup in the DC area. I didn't get a chance before midnight to answer your question a few weeks ago about possible meeting places, but I have no real insights. Likely candidates include pubs, restaurants, coffee shops, library meeting rooms, and with the weather coming around to spring, parks or green spaces.</p>\n<p>The Dilettante Polymath</p>\n", "edit_time": "2026-03-09 08:17 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59525296", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 01:14 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Yes, very much so. The Western tradition used to have things like that in ancient times, but it's hard to teach such things when you're hiding your existence from persecution. <br/><br/>2) Yes, very much so -- and as you'll recall, potpourri is a recommended option in the first GSF book. It's the one I use these days. <br/><br/>3) I'll keep that in mind. I'm still dealing with the paired tasks of settling into the community and clearing away a backlog of projects, but I have some such meeting in mind for this spring. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59507120", "title": "Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-03-09 08:20 pm", "user": "ecoprayer", "content": "<a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/tag/prayerlist\">At this page</a> is the full list of all of the non-faith-specific requests for prayer that have recently appeared at <a href=\"https://ecosophia.net\">ecosophia.net</a> and <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org\">ecosophia.dreamwidth.org</a>, as well as in the comments of the prayer list posts (<a href=\"https://drive.google.com/file/d/1a4Q1LNClvj0E_W4NbtVZRMjuzyHwJsu9/view?usp=sharing\">printable version here</a>, current to 3/3). Please feel free to add any or all of the requests to your own prayers.<br/><br/>If I missed anybody, or if you would like to add a prayer request for yourself or anyone who has given you consent (or for whom a relevant person holds power of consent) to the list, please feel free to leave a comment below.<br/><br/><center>* * *</center><br/>This week I would like to bring special attention to the following prayer requests, selected from the fuller list.<br/><br/><div style=\"\"><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1732.html?thread=20676#cmt20676\"> Bob W of Lake County, Ohio's</a> treatment for cancer go well so that he may heal and recover as quickly as possible.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/360870.html?thread=59415974#cmt59415974\">Open Space</a> be filled with the strength he needs to heal quickly from his current bout of Chicken Pox; may his will remain strong, that he does not scratch; may he be healed completely, and suffer no scarring in its wake.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/november-2025-open-post/#comment-149490\">Bob Ralston (aka Rasty Bob)</a>, who is in hospice care in Buckeye AZ, and who just lost his wife Leslie Fish, be blessed and find relief from his pain and discomfort; may Bob's heart remain strong. <br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1732.html?thread=18884#cmt18884\">DK and her family</a> stay safe in Tel Aviv while sheltering in place and may they return home safely as soon as possible.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1732.html?thread=18372#cmt18372\">Princess Cutekitten</a>, who has made no comments on any of the Ecosophia blogs for a year now, and hasn't responded to attempts at contact, be blessed wherever she is and in whatever form she may exist.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/359082.html?thread=59206570#cmt59206570\">Cathy N. of St. Marys, Ohio</a> heal and recover from injuries caused by a fall.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=15906#cmt15906\">Dustin, a relative of Brenainn</a>, be healed of a recently discovered heart condition.<br/><br/>May 1Wanderers's partner Cathy, whose cancer has returned, be given the physical and mental strength to fight it, and tolerate the treatment, and may she enjoy a full and permanent recovery.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=14882#cmt14882\">Jule from Iserlohn, Germany</a>, who is experiencing complications in her pregnancy due to an influenza infection, recover and have a pleasant pregnancy and birth.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=12322#cmt12322\">Larry Mulford</a>, who has entered hospice after a year battling with pancreatic cancer, pass in the smoothest possible manner, and may his wife be enveloped in our love.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1160.html?thread=12168#cmt12168\">Marko</a> have the strength to seize the opportunities.<br/><br/>May Pierre's young daughter, Athena, be healed from her fatigue and its root causes in ways that are easy, natural, and as holistic as possible.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18134.html?thread=452566#cmt452566\">5 year old Max</a> be blessed and protected during his parents' contentious divorce; may events work out in a manner most conducive to Max's healthy development over the long term.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/514.html?thread=2562#cmt2562\">Lydia G. of Geauga County, Ohio</a> heal and recover from prolonged health issues.<br/><br/>May both <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/347398.html?thread=57920774#cmt57920774\">Monika and the child she is pregnant with</a> both be blessed with good health and a safe delivery. <br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/338828.html?thread=56777612#cmt56777612\">Mary's sister</a> have her auto-immune conditions sent into remission, may her eyes remain healthy, and may she heal in body, mind, and spirit.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18134.html?thread=455382#cmt455382\">Trubujah's best friend Pat's teenage daughter Devin</a>, who has a mysterious condition which doctors are so far baffled by necessitating that she remain in a wheelchair, be healed of her condition; may the underlying cause come to light so that treatment may begin.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/16429.html?thread=392237#cmt392237\">Kevin’s sister Cynthia</a> be cured of the hallucinations and delusions that have afflicted her, and freed from emotional distress. May she be safely healed of the physical condition that has provoked her emotions; and may she be healed of the spiritual condition that brings her to be so unsettled by it. May she come to feel calm and secure in her physical body, regardless of its level of health.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/312140.html?thread=53408588#cmt53408588\">Frank R. Hartman, who lost his house in the Altadena fire, and all who have been affected by the larger conflagration</a> be blessed and healed.<br/><br/></div><div><br/><br/><center>* * *</center><br/>Guidelines for how long prayer requests stay on the list, how to word requests, how to be added to the weekly email list, how to improve the chances of your prayer being answered, and several other common questions and issues, are to be found <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/6373.html\">at the Ecosophia Prayer List FAQ</a>.<br/><br/>If there are any among you who might wish to join me in a bit of <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/1986.html\">astrological timing</a>, I pray each week for the health of all those with health problems on the list on the  astrological hour of the Sun on Sundays, bearing in mind the Sun's rulerships of heart, brain, and vital energies. If this appeals to you, I invite you to join me.</div>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59525552", "title": "Re: Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-03-10 01:14 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this as always. "}, {"id": "cmt59542960", "title": "Re: Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-03-10 10:46 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Helen of Oz has a prayer request that she seems to have placed under the wrong comment in this Magic Monday, so if you could add her prayer to the list that would be great:<br/><br/>https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/361648.html?thread=59534256#cmt59534256"}]}, {"id": "cmt59510192", "title": "Eclipse Weirdness / Astrology and War", "date": "2026-03-09 09:11 pm", "user": "mystical_mountain_9", "content": "JMG and others who are interested in astrology, I thought you might be interested in a few “fun” facts about eclipses in connection with the current conflict in the “Middle East”, such as the fact that not, one, not two, but all three of the leaders of the main countries involved in the conflict were born during an eclipse! The late Ali Khamenei (Iran) was born during an annular solar eclipse on April 19, 1939; Benjamin Netanyahu (Israel) was born during a partial solar eclipse on October 21, 1949; and Donald Trump (USA) was born during a total lunar eclipse on June 14, 1946. I wonder what are the mathematical odds of this triple-eclipse among the combatants? <br/><br/>And now for the icing on the cake: Mojtaba Khamenei, the new supreme leader of Iran, was born on September 8, 1969 -- three days before a solar eclipse!<br/><br/>It is also, I believe, common knowledge that a lot of assassinations of political leaders have happened close to the time of eclipses. But that’s all old wives’ tales… right???<br/><br/>JMG, I recall you mentioning a few years back that Russia’s invasion of Ukraine on February 24, 2022, was astrologically favourable for the attacking party. Have you – or do you know of anyone who has -- looked at the current Israel-Iran conflict through an astrological lens? If so, I’d like to see it! <br/><br/>Being a student Vedic astrologer, I have my own perspective on the conflict astrologically, which I am posting, along with a whole lot of eclipse “fun facts”, on March 11. Anyone who would like to take a look can go here in a couple of days: <a href=\"https://mystical-mountain-9.dreamwidth.org/\">https://mystical-mountain-9.dreamwidth.org/</a><br/><br/>Ron M", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59525808", "title": "Re: Eclipse Weirdness / Astrology and War", "date": "2026-03-10 01:15 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Interesting. No, I haven't done anything specific about the current brouhaha; I'll post something here if I ever do. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59533488", "title": "Re: Eclipse Weirdness / Astrology and War", "date": "2026-03-10 02:05 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Sounds good -- though it looks like I should hold my breath waiting! ;-)<br/><br/>Ron M"}]}, {"id": "cmt59534000", "title": "Re: Eclipse Weirdness / Astrology and War", "date": "2026-03-10 02:12 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "According to Google's robot, Trump gave the order to attack on February 27 at 3:38 pm. At that moment the ascendant was at 0 degrees 17 minutes of Leo, making the Sun thr ruler of the chart and presumably the attacking power. <br/><br/>If the time is off by a few minutes, the Ascendant could be in Cancer. If it's accurate, I wonder if they planned it this way. Uranus rules the Descendant, and is afflicted by square to Mars (within 7 minutes of exactness), and is also in its Fall. The Sun isn't very well off, but is trine retrograde Jupiter in Cancer. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59510704", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-09 09:15 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,<br/>hope you are well.<br/>You said somewhere here before that you nowadays only pay attention to planetary timing when you construct a talisman. Is that for using the formula of the equinox in making that talisman or also for talismans using your own etheric power/substance according to Golden Dawn practice?<br/>Also, if you construct a talisman using the equinox formula can you construct more talismans without risking (etheric) fatigue, because they are powered by planetary/elemental energies and not your own?<br/>Thanx as always for this forum....<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59526320", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 01:20 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Say what? First, I use planetary timing quite frequently for a wide range of things -- for example, I submit manuscripts for publication when the 2nd and 10th house rulers of my natal chart are well dignified. Second, I use the Equinox formula with specially dignified planets, but not for other GD talismans, which don't need the astrological boost. <br/><br/>As for making lots of talismans, I don't see it as a good idea under any circumstances, and not just because of etheric fatigue. Magic gains power from singleness of will; the more you diffuse your will by making a talisman for this, and another for that, and still another for another thing, the weaker they will be because your will will be divided. Focus all your strength on one thing at a time and you'll get better results. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59510960", "title": "Neutralizing to manifest", "date": "2026-03-09 09:16 pm", "user": "little_toad", "content": "I was wondering if I might implore you to elaborate on something you mentioned in your analysis of The Cosmic Doctrine: The Law of Polarity. You wrote, <em>\"If the lower self systematically neutralizes all its characteristic activities on all the planes on which it is normally active, the Higher Self will sometimes manifest.  This is the key to certain kinds of religious and mystical practice\"</em> <br/><br/>About manifesting the Higher Self: I apologize if this is a silly or naive question, but what makes this a goal worth pursuing? We are already emanations of our Higher Selves, no? How is it different from turning one's will against oneself, which is a big spiritual no-no? <br/> <br/>And relatedly, I'd like to know about what <em>\"kinds of religious and mystical practice\"</em> you had mind? I suppose this is a reiteration of my first point as the practices likely shed light on their reasons/purposes...but I figured I'd ask. <br/><br/><br/><br/>I'll also add on a tangentially related report:<br/>The Hanged Man card has been making a pronounced appearance in my readings as of late so I've been focusing my meditations on it's imagery/symbolism. When I took an insight I gleaned from my musings to the Ogham Fews I carved into clay (for divination purposes), Gort landed in front of me multiple times in a row. The themes of the Card and the Few do overlap, and yet I was still shocked when I discovered that they also happen to share the 12th position in their relative sets. This isn't the first time I've had a Few reading match a Tarot one, but I'm not sure I'll ever get used to how strange and almost spooky these kinds of synchronicities feel. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59518896", "title": "Re: Neutralizing to manifest", "date": "2026-03-09 11:21 pm", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>I share a similar feeling about the Higher Self.  Limited contact for the purposes of accomplishing some important aim, sure.  But permanent union with it?  Nah, I'm nowhere near ready for that.  Ask me again in a few eons when my Lower Self has grown into my Higher Self organically.</p>\n"}, {"id": "cmt59526832", "title": "Re: Neutralizing to manifest", "date": "2026-03-10 01:24 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The process as described in the Cos.Doc. is intended to bring about temporary manifestations of the Higher Self for the sake of spiritual guidance, or to deal with some problem that the lower self has tried and failed to master. It's not meant to bring about a permanent state -- you'd have to turn your lower self into a complete zombie to make that happen, and your Higher Self would simply slap you silly and tell you to get on with life. <br/><br/>The spiritual and mystical practices in question are certain kinds of meditation and contemplative prayer, together with austerities, meant to bring the activities of the lower self to a complete standstill. Most of the mystics talk about that. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59530672", "title": "Re: Neutralizing to manifest", "date": "2026-03-10 01:48 am", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>I've sometimes wondered if the true defining trait of the Axial Age religions isn't the promise that you can end all your problems forever by turning yourself into some kind of zombie or other, and playing word games to try to make this sound palatable: \"It's OK, it's not your <em>true</em> self!\"</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59531184", "title": "Re: Neutralizing to manifest", "date": "2026-03-10 01:52 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'd see this not as a defining trait but a common pathology. The defining trait is the promise that there's a perfect world (or not-world) waiting for you, if only you accept a specific ideology and the practices that come with it. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59511728", "title": "Picture theme for magic monday", "date": "2026-03-09 09:23 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey JMG <br/><br/>I was thinking of what pictures you could post for Magic Monday once you run out of, or get bored of, occult memes. It occurred to me that pictures of the various different types of talismans and amulets used throughout the world may be a good choice.<br/><br/>There’s a huge amount of variety and artistry in the design of these things, so I think it would serve you well for a while.<br/><br/>J.L.Mc12", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59527088", "title": "Re: Picture theme for magic monday", "date": "2026-03-10 01:25 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm. I'll consider that. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59513520", "title": "Consecrated Statues", "date": "2026-03-09 09:39 pm", "user": "cs2", "content": "Last month I reported feeling blissed out by Greco-Roman statues and you replied that you and others are trying to piece together the consecration process. (<a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/356936.html?thread=58980424#cmt58980424\">https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/356936.html?thread=58980424#cmt58980424</a>)<br/><br/>1. Would you be able to share with me what preparation would be needed in order to potentially consecrate a newer statue to be like the ancient ones? Since this sounds like it's years off, I could get started now and hopefully get there by the time you've worked out what to do. I've done the DA curriculum twice, have onboarded the Blessing Walk, and am meditating through the OPW. <br/><br/>2. I am moving to the country next-door to where this museum is, and I've decided to make it my project to visit as many museums in the area as I can and catalog who is where, how old the statue is, and whether standing in its presence 'lifts' me. I would like to work at a museum full of these statues, but as an immigrant I must get a qualifying work visa so this may not pan out until I get permanent residency. No question I just wanted to let you know that I am moving in this direction in case it helps with this project. Thanks for your time.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59528112", "title": "Re: Consecrated Statues", "date": "2026-03-10 01:34 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The method as described in classical sources is very easy, because it depends on natural magic. To make an <i>agalma</i> -- that's the Greek word for an empowered statue -- you simply get a hollow image, and then fill it with substances that correspond with the influence you're trying to attract. For example, if you wanted to invoke Venus in this way, you'd get a hollow statue of the goddess and then fill it with stones, herbs, and other substances that all correspond to Venus. Then you start making daily offerings and prayers to the goddess, using the statue as a vehicle for her presence. It seems to work quite well, and the effect builds powerfully over time. <br/><br/>2) Very glad to hear this!"}]}, {"id": "cmt59518384", "title": "Tingly feeling", "date": "2026-03-09 11:13 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>Do you know what that tingly feeling you get in the back of your neck actually is, on an occult level? It's that feeling you get when there's a piece of music you really like, or you get a sudden realisation about something.<br/><br/>It's definitely a pleasant feeling, and I accidentally discovered I can deliberately call it down when I was doing a visualisation exercise of a stream of golden/white light flowing into me from above. I kept at it for about 10 minutes and it felt like the tingly sensation was filling my entire body, spreading out to the tips of my fingers and toes. Once I'd finished, it felt like my whole body was practically vibrating.<br/><br/>I've repeated this several times since and not noticed any ill effects, but I was wondering what I'm actually doing to myself, and whether it's a good idea or not?<br/><br/>Thanks.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59528368", "title": "Re: Tingly feeling", "date": "2026-03-10 01:35 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's certainly something affecting the energy circulations of the body, but I don't recall reading a discussion of it. The exercise of a stream of golden light flowing down from above, however, is much practiced in some occult schools and seems to have good effects, so you can very likely continue doing it without harm. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59535792", "title": "Re: Tingly feeling", "date": "2026-03-10 02:53 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not the OP.  Maybe this weakens with age.  I'm 78 and can remember such effects, especially from music.  And, my solar plexus used to light up when I thought of a certain girl -- maybe with more than one.  Now I can't even find it when I try.  I do the solar plexus exercise from the WGS daily, but to no avail.  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59536816", "title": "Re: Tingly feeling", "date": "2026-03-10 03:07 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's probably etheric, then, because that certainly weakens with age. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59519408", "title": "On the Higher Self", "date": "2026-03-09 11:29 pm", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>On the subject of the Higher Self, I read a story several years ago that has a scene that I suspect captures some aspect of our relationship with our Higher Self: at several points in the story, the protagonist encounters a being of light who aids her or pushes her on.</p>\n<p>At the very end she meets directly with the being, who is impelling her further on, and the protagonist asks if she has a choice in the matter.  The being tells her: \"You have a choice, but you've already made it,\" and she suddenly realizes that the being is her future self, after she has transcended ordinary time and space.  It knows what choice she will make because it remembers making it.</p>\n<p>This is sort of how I think of our Higher Self as both something always already present since the beginning of our existence and as something we have to become in our own time.</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59528880", "title": "Re: On the Higher Self", "date": "2026-03-10 01:35 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm! I like that. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59521968", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 12:23 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good evening and thank you as always. It looks like you've been enjoying Bowie's best album a lot lately--good choice!<br/><br/>Do you know much about John Dee's obsidian mirror, or implements like it? My understanding is that glass doesn't hold an etheric charge well, so do you know how he would have been able to make much use of it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59529648", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 01:40 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Thank you! Yeah, that was the first record I bought after moving to Silver Spring; I took it as a very good omen. <br/><br/>2) Obsidian doesn't hold etheric charges well but those aren't necessarily an advantage in scrying, which is an astral activity. Most scrying worldwide is actually done in liquids -- and glass is technically speaking a very thick liquid. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59522736", "title": "Staying focused", "date": "2026-03-10 12:25 am", "user": "zaratozom", "content": "Hello JMG,  I’ve had to dial back my occultist aspirations in regards to your LRM book because of a certain proximity issue . I still plan on working through the book but will need to leave the house and  this puts a damper on frequency in which I will be able perform certain exercises . <br/><br/><br/>With that said , I’ve recently picked up a copy of Experience of the Inner Worlds because of some of the experiences I was having while meditating and working through LRM.  Are the rituals contained in that book beyond the basic rituals in LRM? <br/><br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59529904", "title": "Re: Staying focused", "date": "2026-03-10 01:41 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, EIW is another book intended for the complete beginner, and Knight did a very good job with the practices. They're safe around children, if you were wondering. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59536048", "title": "Re: Staying focused", "date": "2026-03-10 02:54 am", "user": "zaratozom", "content": "Yes thank you , I had wondered .<br/><br/>Since I’m trying to find things that I can do while at home , I’ve also bought your Natural Magic book which I think is fantastic and since I’ve been married to an herbalist for many years , unsurprisingly I’ve got a very magical garden . <br/><br/>I was wondering , how would a ritual such as Qabalistic Cross , which I’ve been performing daily for quite some time now, always preceded by deep meditation, aid in some of the workings that are written in Natural Magic  book? <br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59537072", "title": "Re: Staying focused", "date": "2026-03-10 03:08 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The interface between ceremonial magic and natural magic deserves much more attention than it's gotten so far; I'm not sure anyone yet knows what the Cabalistic Cross would do in that context. You could certainly make the experiment, however. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59538352", "title": "Re: Staying focused", "date": "2026-03-10 03:22 am", "user": "zaratozom", "content": "What I’m finding so far is that putting myself into deep meditation and building the spheres in my mind one by one etc &amp; doing discursive meditation , at some point I am “compelled “ to rise and then I do and then perform the cross .<br/>What I’m finding is that anything I do afterwards before the closing gesture of course is very uninhibited, there is no voice in the back of my mind that questions what Im doing , for instance when I meditated and then read the chapter in the book where you suggest I go pick up and crystal and put my finger within close range of the tip, and I literally felt that energy, my mind didn’t go “oh hey this is probably bullshit” instead it said “ damn, John was right … it’s real” ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59539632", "title": "Re: Staying focused", "date": "2026-03-10 03:31 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Fascinating. Proceed, then! "}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59523760", "title": "Sphere of protection question", "date": "2026-03-10 12:46 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good evening JMG,<br/>Is there anything wrong or possibly harmful if one does the sphere of protection two times a day?<br/><br/>Thanks,<br/>Lee", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59530160", "title": "Re: Sphere of protection question", "date": "2026-03-10 01:42 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, but there's usually no benefit, either. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59531952", "title": "Invoking Peace", "date": "2026-03-10 01:56 am", "user": "roobyalien", "content": "Some time back you suggested that I invoke peace with my mother. She is in late stages of COPD and lives with our family. As her daughter, I take a fair bit of sniper fire when she doesn't feel well.<br/><br/>Since I have started invoking Peace, the attacks roll off of me like water off a ducks back. I also asked her to choose Peace the other day. She shrugged and dropped the tense attitude.<br/><br/>I also invoked Peace the other day when my husband and I had an argument that was escalating. I didn't escalate so he didn't really have a choice and the whole thing was settled fairly quickly.<br/><br/>Never underestimate the power of affirmations and calling on positive energy. <br/><br/>Thank you for your suggestions. Sometimes your suggestions seem so simple and obvious, but we don't always think of them. It does make a difference to have your input available in this format.<br/><br/>Rooby Alien<br/><br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59533232", "title": "Re: Invoking Peace", "date": "2026-03-10 02:04 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm delighted to hear, first, that you took the suggestion seriously, and second, that it worked so well. Sometimes a very simple technique carried out with intention and a good attitude will work wonders. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59534768", "title": "Tarot Books", "date": "2026-03-10 02:38 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Howdy JMG,<br/><br/>I started discursive meditation a few months back, and have been using the tarot as a theme. Pretty quickly I started seeing how one card led to another like a story that follows a narrative logic. I am sure I am the 1 billionth person to have figured this out, but the idea came to me that I wondered if anyone has written fiction with the flow of tarot cards as the basis for the narrative story arch? Furthermore, the thought dawned on me that if anyone would know about such books, you might. So do you know of any fiction books based on the flow of the tarot cards?<br/><br/>108", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59538608", "title": "Re: Tarot Books", "date": "2026-03-10 03:26 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There may be more than one, but the only one that comes instantly to mind is a mostly forgotten fantasy novel in the 1970s, <i>Arcane</i> by Carl Sherrell: <br/>[IMAGE:0]<br/>So if you're feeling inspired, have at it. <br/>", "images": [{"url": "https://m.media-amazon.com/images/I/31U5E0srmdL.jpg", "local_path": "./data/archive/2026/2026-03-08_10-40PM_Magic_Monday/images/2026-03-10_03_26_am_31U5E0srmdL.jpg"}]}, {"id": "cmt59542192", "title": "Re: Tarot Books", "date": "2026-03-10 03:54 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "Aeclectic Tarot has a pretty good narrative woven around the major arcana, which may help elaborate on this."}]}, {"id": "cmt59535024", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 02:41 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Last week I asked on the open covid post if there are any magical practices I can do to help me with the situation where I'm recovering from a chemical injury, the insurance company is trying to stop my benefits, and the doctor wants to prescribe SSRIs. On the plus side I did some research and experimentation to figure out what's going on and got some promising results, but the recovery process is gradual and it's really difficult trying to work with these people who keep trying to pigeon hole me or say it's my fault because I don't fit neatly into their standard clinical models. I understand you are busy but if you have any advice for dealing with the Leviathan I would greatly appreciate it. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59539120", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 03:29 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "A lot depends on what you know how to do. If you don't have a background in practical magic, you might consider burning an orange candle to Mercury on eight successive Wednesdays, during the hour of Mercury (you can look this up online for your location); recite the Orphic Hymn to Mercury (which you can also find easily online) and then ask him to help you with your situation. Be aware that he may want something from you in exchange. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59535280", "title": "Planetary Correspondences and the Great Old Ones", "date": "2026-03-10 02:43 am", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>I seem to recall some comments made a few weeks ago connected Cthulhu quite closely with Neptune: the Dreaming Lord in Drowned R'lyeh.</p>\n<p>Can the other Great Old Ones be meaningfully assigned astrological correspondences?  For example, Yog-Sothoth seems a good fit for Saturn due to his connection to time and, in an oblique way, limits (\"Yog-Sothoth knows the gate. Yog-Sothoth is the gate. Yog-Sothoth is the key and guardian of the gate. Past, present, future, all are one in Yog-Sothoth.\")  However, Tsathoggua is directly connected to Saturn by Clark Ashton Smith, so perhaps Yog-Sothoth, who is locked outside of our reality, would correspond to Uranus.</p>\n<p>Shub-Nehurath would be Venus for obvious reasons. Azathoth might fit either the Sun (as the \"Nuclear Chaos\") but more likely Jupiter (as the \"Sultan\" of the Great Old Ones and ancestor of most of them). Nyarlathotep I'm assuming would correspond to Pluto.</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59537840", "title": "Re: Planetary Correspondences and the Great Old Ones", "date": "2026-03-10 03:18 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good heavens, yes. In fact, I assigned all the Great Old Ones who were central to my tentacle novels to the Tree of Life: <br/><br/>[IMAGE:0]<br/><br/>Those correspondences can be challenged, of course.  If I had to rework them on a purely planetary basis, I'd have Shub-Ne'Hurrath as the Moon, the primary feminine power; Nyarlathotep as Mercury; Yhoundeh the elk goddess as Venus; Hastur, the King in Yellow and monarch of the Great Old Ones, as the Sun; Ithaqua as Mars; Azathoth as Jupiter; Tsathoggua as Saturn; Yog-Sothoth as Uranus; and Cthulhu as Neptune. <br/><br/>Here again, though, other arrangements are possible. They might actually work better as zodiacal signs; I'll leave that as an exercise for readers. ", "images": [{"url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/file/14379.png", "local_path": "./data/archive/2026/2026-03-08_10-40PM_Magic_Monday/images/2026-03-10_03_18_am_14379.png"}], "edit_time": "2026-03-10 03:19 am (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59540656", "title": "Re: Planetary Correspondences and the Great Old Ones", "date": "2026-03-10 03:42 am", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>Thank you for this!  One of the things that stands out to me is that Cthulhu is perhaps the best name for Neptune I've ever heard, at least in instantly conveying what the planet is about. Your suggestion of Rhea is still the most proper but Cthulhu is far more familiar to most folks.</p>\n<p>I like Yog-Sothoth as Uranus (even though Prometheus is more evocative for me) not least because Lovecraft's private name for the Cthulhu Mythos was not the Cthulhu Mythos, but \"Yog-Sothothery.\"</p>\n"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59539376", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 03:30 am", "user": "lukeszy", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>This might be off-brand for Magic Monday but I'm going to ask anyway.  No biggie if you have no response.  Do you have any dating advice for astrally negative men?  I have a women in mind who is definitely not astrally positive.  My descendant is Aries, and my now deceased astrologer said I would have to date outgoing women until I was ready to embody that archetype myself.  Overtime, I have become capable of carrying conversations in kind of jovial mannner, but I have a hard time crossing the bridge from friendly conversation to asking a woman out, even if I think they will say yes.  Historically, I have dated astrally positive women, even though I find a lot of them slightly annoying.  Another way of saying that - I am more attracted to astrally negative women, but have found myself dating astrally positive ones.<br/><br/>I asked about a series of GSF communion workings to make myself more lovable and then to attract a congenial women, which you said was a solid idea.  I am hoping that fixes this situation.  They'll be kind of a pain in the behind to do on Fridays, but I think I'm going to suck it up.  Divination on doing them on Sundays was terrible.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59540144", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-10 03:40 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "This is something that I'm going to have to work out myself, as I also have the same reversed polarity in my higher bodies. I'm sorry to say I don't have any guidance yet. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59540912", "title": "Aliveness of Greek Pantheon?", "date": "2026-03-10 03:44 am", "user": "bhakti", "content": "I read with interest your thoughts on the relative \"aliveness\" of the Christian god. I have been contemplating a return to Christianity (esoteric and non-Pauline). But there is so much bs \"baggage\" created over 2,000 years (plus the old testament god mess) that it feels almost not worth it. Also, while I liked going to my liberal Lutheran church growing up (25 years ago), I never really felt a connection to Jesus or the Trinity. <br/><br/>In the past I've been interested / followed the \"Hindu\" spiritual tradition (way over simplifying it). But feel a draw towards a more Western tradition, so thinking about connecting more with the Neoplatonic tradition. <br/><br/>Ha, so all that being said. What are your thoughts on the relative \"aliveness\" of the Greek pantheon (such as Athena (Nous-Aligned Wisdom), Apollo (Hypercosmic Light/Order), and Rhea (Feminine Psyche Nurturer)? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59541680", "title": "Re: Aliveness of Greek Pantheon?", "date": "2026-03-10 03:50 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The Hellenic deities seem to be unusually active right now. In recent weeks I've had commenters talk about vivid personal experiences of even quite minor Greek deities. Certainly they've had a significant following in the western world since before 1800, when Thomas Taylor relaunched their worship in Britain in a fairly enduring way. Thus you could do worse. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59542704", "title": "Re: Aliveness of Greek Pantheon?", "date": "2026-03-10 04:03 am", "user": "bhakti", "content": "The feedback is much appreciated!<br/><br/>Also, thanks for sharing your insights into prayer and your morning prayer / meditation practice - thoughts on these topics were just what I've been meditating on the last several evenings."}]}]}]}, {"title": "Magic Monday", "url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/362580.html", "year": "2026", "month": "03", "day": "15", "time": "09-56PM", "comments": [{"id": "cmt59576148", "title": "The Wizard Knight and Question on \"The Smith and the Devil\"", "date": "2026-03-16 04:08 am", "user": "jprussell", "content": "Good Evening,<br/><br/>May the upcoming astrological reset of Aries bring welcome new opportunities, and ends to what you would have less of!<br/><br/><b>To Share</b>: Gene Wolfe has been an occasional topic of conversation around here. If you haven't checked out <i>The Wizard Knight</i>, I can strongly recommend it. The ending felt a bit rushed, and I get the impression that Wolfe needs \"room to breathe\" to be at his full powers. Maybe would have been better as a trilogy of like-sized books, rather than a duology, but still well worth the read. A masterful blend of a hermetic worldview, Arthurian legend, and Germanic myth.<br/><br/><b>To Ask</b>: A friend was taking a look at the traditional folktale \"The Smith and the Devil.\" In most attested versions, it's pretty Christian: the supernatural being with which the smith makes a deal is literally the devil, often the intercession of Saint Peter is needed to bring things to a happy ending, and so forth. That said, it's apparently a <i>very</i> old story, dating back maybe to Proto-Indo-European times, suggesting a non/pre-Christian version of the story. My friend is trying to unravel what that pre-Christian version might have looked like, and I'd appreciate any pointers from our host or the commentariat on likely myths/mythical figures to check out for comparison (Hephaistos and Weland/Volund are clear smith figures, but I'm not familiar with Indic or Celtic versions, for example).<br/><br/>My blessings to all who welcome them,<br/>Jeff", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59576916", "title": "Re: The Wizard Knight and Question on \"The Smith and the Devil\"", "date": "2026-03-16 04:18 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm! I'm not familiar with older versions of the folktale. I assume your friend has already read Mircea Eliade's book <i>The Forge and the Crucible</i>, with its discussions of the magical dimensions of smithcraft; that's the only resource that comes to mind just now. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59577172", "title": "Re: The Wizard Knight and Question on \"The Smith and the Devil\"", "date": "2026-03-16 04:19 am", "user": "jprussell", "content": "Not sure if he has, but I'll be sure to mention it, thank you!<br/><br/>(Also one of the few Eliade books that wasn't already on my list for myself, so I'll amend that error as well.)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59586132", "title": "Re: The Wizard Knight and Question on \"The Smith and the Devil\"", "date": "2026-03-16 03:03 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You may be amused to know that it's the first book by Eliade I ever read. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59614804", "title": "Re: The Wizard Knight and Question on \"The Smith and the Devil\"", "date": "2026-03-16 09:28 pm", "user": "eldriwolf", "content": "I Think Rudyard Kipling had tale about Weland..(not certain) but it isn't Old.<br/> And  Sir Terry Prachitt, even Less old", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59622484", "title": "Re: The Wizard Knight and Question on \"The Smith and the Devil\"", "date": "2026-03-17 12:00 am", "user": "jprussell", "content": "Thanks nonetheless!"}]}, {"id": "cmt59633492", "title": "Re: The Wizard Knight and Question on \"The Smith and the Devil\"", "date": "2026-03-17 02:26 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "<b>To Make Sure:</b> have you looked into Folktales in the Indo-European Tradition?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59635796", "title": "Re: The Wizard Knight and Question on \"The Smith and the Devil\"", "date": "2026-03-17 02:49 am", "user": "jprussell", "content": "Thanks for checking, but yes, that was the starting place for both me and my friend - it's a great book!"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59576404", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 04:09 am", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "1 - There seems to be a New Thought adept at work in the memeworks busily banging out Amelia videos for YouTube.  (Nevermind the volume and quality suggesting deep pockets somewhere.)  Since working-class UK feels downtrodden, something like Skip Downing’s encouragement to be a creator rather than a victim looks to be in play.  The memes I’ve been noticing on YouTube seem aimed at reawakening the dormant sense of people and place so that the citizens’ can be reminded that they do have the means to change their government to suit their needs.<br/><br/>Specifically, examining any collection of Amelia memes suggests Paul Ekman’s discrete emotional theory is being used to lead voters along the path of attention, anger, fear, outrage, questions, answers and solutions to the positions of Restore Britain as laid out in their mission and philosophy video on their YouTube channel.<br/><br/>So – do you and the commentariat a rather brainy New Thought campaign to win voters to an upstart party?  Or – am I over-connecting disparate dots?<br/><br/>Also, have you or your commentariat developed any idea who might be the divinity inspiring Amelia and her memes?<br/><br/><br/>2 - My interest in Amelia bumps into my curiosity about my American nature and some discussion here about how inextricably British the practice of Druidry is.  A friend of mine from the UK recently became US citizen, so he’s able to point out how English both Ohio is and I am.  (Well, we do speak with a broken-in West Country accent, so…)  Anyway - I almost knocked him over by standing up to shake hands.  Despite being not much bigger than he is, I take up much more personal space, and his reaction to colliding with mine looked like he’d walked into a glass door…  Which leaves me to wonder if my misadventures in Druidry have a solidifying effect on my personal space.  Umm… does it?  And – is this effect related to the way elderly men violate my personal space or just want my attention at a noticeably higher rate than my fellow hardware store clerks?  I’m thinking so, but coincidence is not causality…<br/><br/><br/>3 - And – Since HPL comes up here now and again… While looking for Amelia memes, an AI music video, “Down at the Crossroads - Memphis Blues - Uncle Sam's Blues Featuring ‪<span class=\"ljuser\" lj:user=\"clickthecat\" style=\"white-space: nowrap;\"><a href=\"https://www.dreamwidth.org/profile?user=clickthecat\"></a><a href=\"https://www.dreamwidth.org/profile?user=clickthecat\"><b>clickthecat</b></a></span>‬,” (you’ll want the five minute version with the spoken intro) happened by… leaving me to wonder about Nyarlathotep’s interest in the blues how widely influential Lovecraft is, and why his source material is enjoying a resurgence.<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59577684", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 04:26 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) No surprises there. One of the fascinating things about the populist movement, at least to me, is that it seems very open to occultism, and once Amelia seized the British popular imagination, working with her as a magical image must have been far too tempting to resist. <br/><br/>2) How very odd. I'll be interested to hear suggestions from those who, not being as autistic as I am, might have a clue. <br/><br/>3) To the best of my knowledge, the idea that Nyarlathotep is a blues fan was my own invention -- once I'd decided to redefine the Great Old Ones as the old gods of nature and started retconning them into folklore and myth, equating the Crawling Chaos with the crossroads devil of blues legend was an easy choice, and his musical tastes followed from there. Lovecraft, though, has been hugely influential in American popular culture since the 1970s. His source material? Most of what he wrote came to him in dreams...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59580756", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 05:43 am", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "1 - I'm pretty sure most of Downing's fans would argue that anything this practical can't be magic.  (And I try not to laugh when they tell me so.)  Come to think of it, so do Jung's non-occult fans.  How does that even work when they aren't getting the whole picture?<br/><br/>3 - I recall but can't locate some jazz-themed (okay, not blues) post-HPL stories and RPG supplements.  I never paid post-HPL much attention because everything seemed somehow \"off\" until your corrected texts appeared on tablets of an unknown metal found in a quarry in Maple County, Ohio.  Over to the commentariat for the strange background music of post-HPL horror.<br/><br/>3a - May I argue that while Lovecraft did his best thinking while asleep, he frequently fell asleep reading while drinking a cocktail of Puritan bitter dregs and the bottom-run absinthe of the Decadents?  While we are here - How did the rich theology and folklore of the Puritans dissolve so quickly to become another pre-modern discarded superstition?<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59586644", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 03:12 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Of course. They've bought into the official propaganda regarding magic, and so don't have the least idea how practical it is, or how deeply it interfaces with psychology. Can't have the proles figuring out that they can free their minds and change their lives so easily! As for why they find their way to magic anyway, why, magic is so deeply hardwired into our nervous systems that it's a wonder more people don't get there on their own. Did you know that in medieval Latin, the word <i>sapiens</i> was the standard word for wizard? (The words mean the same thing: \"wise person.\") Thus any literate medieval person would have interpreted <i>Homo sapiens</i> as \"a person who is a wizard.\" <br/><br/>2) As I recall, the standard setting for the <i>Call of Cthulhu</i> TTRPG was the 1920s. As for those tablets, the metal's only unknown to those who don't know their eldritch lore. It's astonishing how few people recognize ordinary Atlantean orichalcum when they see it... ;-<br/><br/>3) Don't forget Greek mythology. He was a crazed fan of Greek myth as a child, to the extent of building an altar in the back garden and pouring libations (of water, granted) to Zeus and Athena. As for the Puritans, I see their beliefs as a transitional phenomenon -- part of the process by which they discarded Christianity and embraced the anthropolatrous religion of Progress. Such transitional stages don't keep well. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59591508", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 04:03 pm", "user": "jflylynn", "content": "1) I’m not sure that any supernatural force is acting on Britain right now. However I have seen a lot of Amelia adjacent talk discussing Arthur and Boudicca. This leads me to think that if there is a great spirit acting on that nation it is that peculiarly Germanic inclination to have your women scream bloody abuse at their own men to fix the problems that society is facing. This takes a number of forms be it the Chimbri women literally standing behind their army screaming, Boudicca leading a revolt or the lady of the lake delivering a sword (the symbol of the right and ability to use violence for the good of the people) to Arthur. I see that same force in the Amelia memes floating around. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59608660", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 07:21 pm", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "Oh!  I wasn't aware of those discussions.  Now - that's interesting.<br/>Standing behind and screaming doesn't seem to suit Amelia.  She's two-fisted in many of the music videos, and she's syncretized or pseudomorphizised (is that a word?) with James Bond.  \"Amelia Bond 2 - DEI Another Day\" is a good example of her martial role.  Interestingly, she keeps Starmer/Blofeld's cat, which might point to both Germanic roots and her domestic role."}]}, {"id": "cmt59596372", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 04:41 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Regarding # 2, yes, I am very aware of that phenomenon. There was a Grand Councilor in AMORC I knew years ago. He was a big man to begin with, but, far beyond that, being around him was, well, awe inspiring. I have explained it to others this way: Imagine you're out at night in a little fishing boat, and a huge container ship comes by you in the dark with no lights showing. You can't see it, and it may be almost silent, but BOY! do you know it's there. That was him. I've experienced that a few times with people who have dialed in decades of esoteric development work. Whatever their physical attributes, their PRESENCE can be overwhelming."}]}, {"id": "cmt59576660", "title": "How do I figure out which occult model to use?", "date": "2026-03-16 04:14 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello Mr. Greer, <br/><br/>I am trying to understand something in my life from an occult perspective and I am not sure which model within occultism to use. <br/><br/>The issue is I always run into trouble with father figures. More specifically, they never seem to listen to anything I have to say and almost always underestimate my abilities. My own biological father did this to a comical degree. For example, he seemed utterly baffled that I wanted to pursue graduate education when I spent my whole childhood obsessed with this idea. I have since then experienced the same thing with numerous older men in positions of authority over me. I myself am a very academically inclined individual and these people often see me as ignorant while peers and for that matter everyone see the opposite in me. <br/><br/>If I use karma to understand this I might say I abused authority over another in a past life and now need to pay this karmic debt by realizing the error. <br/><br/>Yeats vision might say that I am at a place on the lunar wheel that calls for me to lay aside my own personality and start moving towards more collective concerns. <br/><br/>Jung might say I am projecting my shadow and really there is something bad yet unrecognized in these men that I subconsciously see in myself. <br/><br/>So what do you do when you are trying to discern between competing occult paradigms? Do you use mediation? Prayer? Divination? Or what? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59577940", "title": "Re: How do I figure out which occult model to use?", "date": "2026-03-16 04:28 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Paradigms are overrated, and consciously held and constructed paradigms are even more so. It's far more important simply to accept that your experience is what it is, acknowledge that you don't yet know what it means, and get on with life. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59598932", "title": "Re: How do I figure out which occult model to use?", "date": "2026-03-16 05:04 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Point taken. Its unproductive to spend too much time in the purely abstract. Still, different paradigms give you different perspectives on what to expect next, so I thought there might be some value in distinguishing which one seems to be operative here. But yes, maybe the most productive thing to do is recognize I seem to struggle with one particular personality type and instead start working out how ways to deal with the specific set of circumstances I encounter in the future. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59601492", "title": "Re: How do I figure out which occult model to use?", "date": "2026-03-16 06:17 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Exactly. My experience is that settling on a consciously held paradigm can make it harder to get to the kind of realization that actually helps -- the point where you stop cold and say, \"Oh, okay, now I get it! That's what it was about all along!\" That comes from experience and reflection; it can be furthered by thinking about the various paradigms, but it's hindered by premature commitment to any one option. "}, {"id": "cmt59636564", "title": "Re: How do I figure out which occult model to use?", "date": "2026-03-17 03:28 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ok, so yes, we do all think in narratives, and those narratives limit what we are able to think. The narratives you have opted for (continue to indulge in, to put it more harshly) can leave you trapped in fixed perspectives on what to expect next. Those narratives will continue recreating similar circumstances, since that is both what they do and what your expectations have now been limited to. The question then is how to get out of a box that you are unwittingly keeping as securely closed as possible.<br/><br/>I'm intrigued that you recognize the power of narrative framing to restrict your perspective, yet continue searching for an alternate narrative framing with a more liberating fit. It is always a truly magical moment when you stumble upon some overlooked mythic truth that completely recontextualizes how you've been relating to your past/family/self/etc., but those transformative myths are inevitably the ones we've been most assiduously overlooking, so they're not likely to be in our go-to list. Which paradigms are not even showing up on your radar currently? The ones you find the least promising may well turn out to be the box cutter you've been looking for.<br/><br/>The particular framings you led the witness with (that one's not to be harsh, since we all do that much more than we imagine) are each a bit deterministic. Karma, Yeats' schematic, and Jung's shadow projection are all fated burdens we cannot hope to escape from, similar to one's astrological chart or one's family dynamic. Since you're looking to escape from endless repeats of cycles originating within your family, you might want to consider framings that do allow for escape and reimagining of one's habitual nature. A wonderful quote from Harold and Maude comes to mind, \"Consistency is not really a human trait.\" <br/><br/>How inconsistent and out of character can you let yourself be? Or stated another way, what parts of how you imagine yourself to be would you have to let go of in order to try out unimaginable narratives, perspectives, and paradigms? More importantly, are you sure you want to? We always end up relinquishing much more than just our burdens when we take up occult practice in earnest. Do you really want to discover that your father, your family, your peers, and your Self are not remotely how you were imagining them to be? Do you really want the dizzying disorientation of discerning that the framings you’ve used to keep your boxes rigidly intact can just as easily be used as doorways to step through? <br/><br/>—Christophe"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59581012", "title": "Re: How do I figure out which occult model to use?", "date": "2026-03-16 05:48 am", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "You wouldn't happen to be Gen-X - born between 1964 and 1983 - would you?<br/>That treatment is a distressingly common habit of Baby Boomers with the worst offenders having been idealistic hippies.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59598420", "title": "Re: How do I figure out which occult model to use?", "date": "2026-03-16 05:01 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Close. I was born in 1987 but my parents were baby boomers. They had me in their late thirties so I'm technically a millennial but I was raised like a gen x. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59582548", "title": "Re: How do I figure out which occult model to use?", "date": "2026-03-16 09:45 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I would look at the “prince” archetype in both literature, tarot and myth. I’ve had the same problem. Also, listen to interviews of children of famous parents. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59599188", "title": "Re: How do I figure out which occult model to use?", "date": "2026-03-16 05:05 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Sounds like a useful place to look. Thank you!"}]}, {"id": "cmt59604564", "title": "Re: How do I figure out which occult model to use?", "date": "2026-03-16 06:50 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If it is a particularly persistent issue, it might show on your natal chart a bit. <br/><br/>I have similar issues and was advised it was highly likely I was a bit righteous and overbearing in a previous life by a natal astrologer and the karma was playing through in this life (based on my Jupiter). I also have a Saturn and uranus (who are both retrograde) opposite mercury (4th house) and communication in particular with authority and my original family is such an ongoing and difficult issue in my life."}, {"id": "cmt59619668", "title": "Re: How do I figure out which occult model to use?", "date": "2026-03-16 10:51 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "It might be a class and not so much a generational issue, at least in part. I faced a similar situation growing up because I graduated from college, first in my family. A friend of my parents, a good ol'boy* from the South, criticized my decision, \"why'd you do that? Think yer better than any one else?\". Thing is - he was a member of the 'silent' generation and me, a boomer. So it might not be generational or even class - it might simply be age related. I would have no idea of any occult connections there might be, and now you make me wonder.<br/><br/>* Although he had certain opinions &amp; expressed them freely, this friend of my parents was really a great guy, generous &amp; kind. BTW, his daughter ended getting a college education &amp; became a teacher. And the main reason I went to college, was to pursue options that were simply not available in a small backward town, not because I was 'smart'."}]}, {"id": "cmt59577428", "title": "Yeats Phase 1 & Mental Sheath Reset?", "date": "2026-03-16 04:20 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "Since it is not a question about the second quarter, I am posting this question here.<br/><br/>During Phase 1 of total objectivity, does the soul's mental sheath get stripped down to its most primitive form, which then has the opportunity to develop as the soul moves through the phases?<br/><br/>Patrick H<br/><br/>Edit: Alternatively, the mental sheath just goes mostly dormant during the early primary phases.<br/><br/>", "edit_time": "2026-03-16 04:25 am (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59578196", "title": "Re: Yeats Phase 1 & Mental Sheath Reset?", "date": "2026-03-16 04:31 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a very good question which Yeats does not address at all. To the extent that he hints at an answer at all, it would be that the growth of the mental sheath is a slow process and takes multiple trips 'round the Great Wheel to take place. Thus a soul at Phase 1 the first few times around wouldn't have more than a very tentative mental sheath anyway, and a soul very late in the process of human existence would have a very different experience of Phase 1. But that's a tentative suggestion, and much development of the system would be needed to settle the matter. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59578452", "title": "Geomancy repeated figures vs judge and witnesses", "date": "2026-03-16 04:34 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Recently I cast a shield chart for an omen regarding an upcoming trip that I would appreciate an extra set of eyes on:<br/><br/>What do I most need to know about my upcoming trip?<br/><br/>1st Mother: Merch<br/>2nd Mother: Bendith Fawr<br/>3rd Mother: Colled<br/>4th Mother: Merch<br/><br/>1st Daughter: Merch<br/>2nd Daughter: Pobl<br/>3rd Daughter: Ffordd<br/>4th Daughter: Mab<br/><br/>1st Niece: Llawenydd<br/>2nd Niece: Tristwch<br/>3rd Niece: Merch<br/>4th Niece: Gwyn<br/><br/>RW: Carchar<br/>LW: Carchar<br/>Judge: Pobl<br/><br/>I see a pair of Carchar, a negative figure making Pobl, a neutral figure. 2 negative + 1 neutral = negative reading.<br/><br/>However, Carchar repeated is considered a good omen with regard to safety in travel, and in questions concerning travel it is a good omen if traveling by land. I have a flight involved, but the majority of travel is land-based. The upper chart doesn't seem very ominous - 3 of 4 nieces are favorable and the top row is 50% composed of Merch and Bendith Fawr, which are good signs, accompanied by Ffordd, a good sign for land trips, and pobl, which at least doesn't hurt.<br/><br/>Given world events, would it be too far-fetched to square the circle by supposing this omen is one of safety in travels by virtue of the trip being cancelled, or is there a different interpretation I'm missing?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59578964", "title": "Re: Geomancy repeated figures vs judge and witnesses", "date": "2026-03-16 04:45 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If I got this chart in response to that question I'd assume that the trip would be cancelled or changed significantly (Carchar) due to collective events outside my control (Pobl). The repeated figures are in my experience less important than the testimony of the judge and witnesses. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59578708", "title": "SoP with Planetary Forces", "date": "2026-03-16 04:43 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Apologies if this has been asked and answered before, but is there a way of modifying the SoP to call on planetary names as one would gods? <br/><br/>Thank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59579220", "title": "Re: SoP with Planetary Forces", "date": "2026-03-16 04:47 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Sure. The standard symbolism is this: <br/><br/>East: Sun<br/>West: Mercury<br/>South: Mars<br/>North: Venus<br/>Below: Saturn<br/>Above: Jupiter<br/><br/>The Moon corresponds to Spirit Within, but of course you don't invoke that seventh factor by name. since you yourself are always the central element in the SoP. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59579476", "title": "Re: SoP with Planetary Forces", "date": "2026-03-16 04:55 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you! And would one vibrate the names?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59586900", "title": "Re: SoP with Planetary Forces", "date": "2026-03-16 03:14 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Up to you. If I were going to do that, I'd look up the Latin pronunciation, which is more resonant; I'd also use Mavors, the older spelling of Mars (that's MAH-wors, btw). But your mileage may vary. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59584852", "title": "Re: SoP with Planetary Forces", "date": "2026-03-16 01:39 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not OP. <br/><br/>So that would mean that we would say something like \"In the great name of the planet Mercury, I invoke the Water, its gods, its spirits, and its powers. May the powers of Water bless and protect me this day and always, and further my work. May my heart be instructed by the ways of nature.\" in the planetary sphere of protection?<br/><br/>Can we also use planetary names for the opening as well or do we have to still use the names of three gods?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59587156", "title": "Re: SoP with Planetary Forces", "date": "2026-03-16 03:15 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) You could. <br/><br/>2) I'd recommend instead invoking the heavens and the earth in the opening, and modifying it to use just those two. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59579732", "title": "Celtic Questions!", "date": "2026-03-16 04:55 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG!<br/><br/>• Would it be useful to start with Learning Ritual Magic before Celtic Golden Dawn? I would not skip anything from the second course, even if perceived overlaps were found, and I don't intend to mix up any practices. My target is the Celtic Golden Dawn. However I heard LRM is very good to star off slowly, build the necessary muscle and also take the time to study the standard classics of western ritual magic. Being in no hurry, adding an informed appreciation of how CGD changes the classic GD and Kabbalah basics sound very interesting, but only if it would not be bad for the actual practice.<br/><br/>• I read somewhere that classic GD magic seeks more of a transcendental goal than more natural, druidic practices; That you would tend to, when following such more nature based systems, \"stay here\" with the natural world in your discarnate future, connecting in a different way with the beyond. Does that make any sense to you?<br/><br/>Thks!!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59587412", "title": "Re: Celtic Questions!", "date": "2026-03-16 03:17 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) No, LRM uses a different symbolism entirely. <i>The Celtic Golden Dawn</i> is designed for the complete beginner, and you can take as much time in the first level, the Ovate Grade, as you need. (You can do the same thing with the other two grades, for that matter.) <br/><br/>2) Yes, but the Celtic GD system isn't a nature-based system in that sense. It's a solar path, with effects similar to any other GD system. You might compare it to the system in my book <i>The Druid Magic Handbook</i> to get some sense of the differences.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59595860", "title": "Re: Celtic Questions!", "date": "2026-03-16 04:40 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks! Can you talk a bit about what awaits an adept of a nature based system in his afterlife? The \"staying here\" part? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59596628", "title": "Re: Celtic Questions!", "date": "2026-03-16 04:45 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "We know very little about the various states of existence that follow after material embodiment. The Chinese Taoists, who have put as much work into this as anybody (and much more than most), differentiate between celestial and terrestrial immortals. The former are those who have dispensed with the need for a material body and proceed on to realms of existence apart from this world, for which the term \"heaven\" would not be too mistaken a term. The latter are those who have dispensed with the need for a material body but continue to exist in this realm of existence, freed from its hindrances but still able to interact with it. Both pursue their further spiritual development in their different settings. The GD, as I interpret it, is a way toward the former state, while nature-based systems tend toward the latter.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59599956", "title": "Re: Celtic Questions!", "date": "2026-03-16 05:36 pm", "user": "borealbear", "content": "Fascinating, and at the risk of overcomplicating and/or overthinking things we can't know much about, I'd like to ask a couple follow-ups. This is also of interest to me since staying intuitively feels more appealing to me, but so far I've also found a GD/solar path to work better for me, at least in this life.<br/><br/>1) What would this division imply for those who've followed both paths to an advanced degree, like yourself (if that's not too personal)? Is it a matter of which path you commit to over the course of many lives? <br/><br/>2) Since our realm of existence will presumably have a finite lifespan, compared to those \"higher\" realms of the celestial path, will the terrestrial immortals have to \"migrate\" upwards eventually as well?<br/><br/>Bonus 3) This looks like a classic binary...I assume what makes the ternary is a fine theme for meditation? :)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59602004", "title": "Re: Celtic Questions!", "date": "2026-03-16 06:21 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) One of the things I had to confront some years ago was the choice between the two. I chose the nature-centered path, after much reflection, and that's governed my work since then. <br/><br/>2) Sure, but the Earth will be habitable for something like 1.2 billion years, so there's plenty of time to prepare! <br/><br/>3) Why, yes, indeed it is!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59606100", "title": "Re: Celtic Questions!", "date": "2026-03-16 07:01 pm", "user": "borealbear", "content": "Thank you, appreciate the perspective. Now that I think about it, this also brings to mind the difference between the Aesir and the Vanir in Heathen cosmology. In any case, while I'm finishing my current work no matter what, I think I'll have to do some serious reflection on this myself when it comes time to decide whether to go on to the Jarl grade in the HGD.<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59613524", "title": "Re: Celtic Questions!", "date": "2026-03-16 09:16 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The Heathen Golden Dawn looks like an awesome system. I wish it was around when I was studying runes some years ago.  I have the book and I love how it’s laid out. <br/><br/>How is it going for you so far? - if you feel like sharing. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59601236", "title": "Re: Celtic Questions!", "date": "2026-03-16 06:07 pm", "user": "davidp", "content": "Maybe I'm reading too much into a three-sentence summary of what is presumably a very large body of lore but would that imply that celestial immortals are incapable of interacting with humans still stuck in material embodiment?<br/><br/>—David P.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59602260", "title": "Re: Celtic Questions!", "date": "2026-03-16 06:23 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Not at all. They just interact with humans on different planes -- primarily the upper astral and mental planes, where spatial distance is less of an issue. Terrestrial immortals, by contrast, can interact with incarnate humans all the way down to the dense etheric plane.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59607636", "title": "Re: Celtic Questions!", "date": "2026-03-16 07:10 pm", "user": "davidp", "content": "Thank you, that makes more sense.<br/><br/>—David P."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59606612", "title": "Re: Celtic Questions!", "date": "2026-03-16 07:08 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Would this have any implications for systems like the CGD? It's a GD system, but it's also based on Druidry, which is a nature based system; so it seems like it has a pull in both directions....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59607892", "title": "Re: Celtic Questions!", "date": "2026-03-16 07:14 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, the Celtic GD is a GD system; it uses Druid Revival imagery but its energetics are solar rather than the mixed solar-telluric pattern that's standard in the more terrestrially oriented systems. Again, compare it with <i>The Druid Magic Handbook</i> if you want to get a sense of the difference. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59626068", "title": "Re: Celtic Questions!", "date": "2026-03-17 12:19 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What about the Golden Section books? Are they solar or more telluric in nature?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59626836", "title": "Re: Celtic Questions!", "date": "2026-03-17 12:38 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "They work the same balanced solar-telluric approach as <i>The Druid Magic Handbook</i>. All the material taught by, or inspired by, John Gilbert's work falls into that category. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59627860", "title": "Re: Celtic Questions!", "date": "2026-03-17 12:42 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Many thanks once more for your patience and dedication, Mr. Greer! Have a great week. :)"}]}]}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59579988", "title": "Non-magical Spring Equinox Celebrations?", "date": "2026-03-16 04:59 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>The self-initiation route I am taking does not allow for magic outside of the prescribed daily rituals; I was wondering what are some ways to celebrate the upcoming spring equinox otherwise? Would love to hear from the commentariat as well. <br/><br/>Thanks for these Magic Mondays!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59587668", "title": "Re: Non-magical Spring Equinox Celebrations?", "date": "2026-03-16 03:18 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You might spend some time outdoors, paying attention to the weather, and then have a special dinner, with or without friends, to celebrate the arrival of spring. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59581268", "title": "re: nascent lovecraftian egregores", "date": "2026-03-16 05:49 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "if one speculates they may be being hunted, that unseen and identified forces have a vested interest in ensuring ones metaphorical and even literal demise, what would be the most prudent course of action? fortification? tracing threads to the origin of the threat even if it is insurmountable and defies recognition? even if these limitless threads may be demises' embodiment? <br/><br/>is there a way to accept impossibility and futility against an unconquerable enemy without giving tacit consent to the arrival of death? surely you can't blame a man for defending life, capture, and all that he loves.... even when the armor and resistance themselves might be a trojan horse?<br/><br/>perhaps the man in question should seek equally formidable allies?<br/><br/>thank you in advance. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59587924", "title": "Re: nascent lovecraftian egregores", "date": "2026-03-16 03:22 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Perhaps the man in question should start by making sure all this isn't nascent paranoia. Vast cosmic powers don't bother with individual human beings -- why should they? If they just wait a little while, an eyeblink-time of half a dozen decades or so, the individual will be dead anyway. Seriously, I recommend getting yourself some counseling.  "}]}, {"id": "cmt59581524", "title": "Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-03-16 05:55 am", "user": "ecoprayer", "content": "<a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/tag/prayerlist\">At this page</a> is the full list of all of the non-faith-specific requests for prayer that have recently appeared at <a href=\"https://ecosophia.net\">ecosophia.net</a> and <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org\">ecosophia.dreamwidth.org</a>, as well as in the comments of the prayer list posts (<a href=\"https://drive.google.com/file/d/1k1MLUovBKzARQYliiEYp26ddsPOvkRgo/view?usp=drivesdk\">printable version here</a>, current to 3/13). Please feel free to add any or all of the requests to your own prayers.<br/><br/>If I missed anybody, or if you would like to add a prayer request for yourself or anyone who has given you consent (or for whom a relevant person holds power of consent) to the list, please feel free to leave a comment below.<br/><br/><center>* * *</center><br/>This week I would like to bring special attention to the following prayer requests, selected from the fuller list.<br/><br/><div style=\"\"><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1732.html?thread=20676#cmt20676\">Bob W of Lake County, Ohio's</a> treatment for cancer go well so that he may heal and recover as quickly as possible.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/360870.html?thread=59415974#cmt59415974\">Open Space</a> be filled with the strength he needs to heal quickly from his current bout of Chicken Pox; may his will remain strong, that he does not scratch; may he be healed completely, and suffer no scarring in its wake.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/november-2025-open-post/#comment-149490\">Bob Ralston (aka Rasty Bob)</a>, who is in hospice care in Buckeye AZ, and who just lost his wife Leslie Fish, be blessed and find relief from his pain and discomfort; may Bob's heart remain strong. <br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1732.html?thread=18372#cmt18372\">Princess Cutekitten</a>, who has made no comments on any of the Ecosophia blogs for a year now, and hasn't responded to attempts at contact, be blessed wherever she is and in whatever form she may exist.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/359082.html?thread=59206570#cmt59206570\">Cathy N. of St. Marys, Ohio</a> heal and recover from injuries caused by a fall.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=15906#cmt15906\">Dustin, a relative of Brenainn</a>, be healed of a recently discovered heart condition.<br/><br/>May 1Wanderers's partner Cathy, whose cancer has returned, be given the physical and mental strength to fight it, and tolerate the treatment, and may she enjoy a full and permanent recovery.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=14882#cmt14882\">Jule from Iserlohn, Germany</a>, who is experiencing complications in her pregnancy due to an influenza infection, recover and have a pleasant pregnancy and birth.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=12322#cmt12322\">Larry Mulford</a>, who has entered hospice after a year battling with pancreatic cancer, pass in the smoothest possible manner, and may his wife be enveloped in our love.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1160.html?thread=12168#cmt12168\">Marko</a> have the strength to seize the opportunities.<br/><br/>May Pierre's young daughter, Athena, be healed from her fatigue and its root causes in ways that are easy, natural, and as holistic as possible.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18134.html?thread=452566#cmt452566\">5 year old Max</a> be blessed and protected during his parents' contentious divorce; may events work out in a manner most conducive to Max's healthy development over the long term.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/514.html?thread=2562#cmt2562\">Lydia G. of Geauga County, Ohio</a> heal and recover from prolonged health issues.<br/><br/>May both <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/347398.html?thread=57920774#cmt57920774\">Monika and the child she is pregnant with</a> both be blessed with good health and a safe delivery. <br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/338828.html?thread=56777612#cmt56777612\">Mary's sister</a> have her auto-immune conditions sent into remission, may her eyes remain healthy, and may she heal in body, mind, and spirit.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18134.html?thread=455382#cmt455382\">Trubujah's best friend Pat's teenage daughter Devin</a>, who has a mysterious condition which doctors are so far baffled by necessitating that she remain in a wheelchair, be healed of her condition; may the underlying cause come to light so that treatment may begin.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/16429.html?thread=392237#cmt392237\">Kevin’s sister Cynthia</a> be cured of the hallucinations and delusions that have afflicted her, and freed from emotional distress. May she be safely healed of the physical condition that has provoked her emotions; and may she be healed of the spiritual condition that brings her to be so unsettled by it. May she come to feel calm and secure in her physical body, regardless of its level of health.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/312140.html?thread=53408588#cmt53408588\">Frank R. Hartman, who lost his house in the Altadena fire, and all who have been affected by the larger conflagration</a> be blessed and healed.<br/><br/></div><div><br/><br/><center>* * *</center><br/>Guidelines for how long prayer requests stay on the list, how to word requests, how to be added to the weekly email list, how to improve the chances of your prayer being answered, and several other common questions and issues, are to be found <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/6373.html\">at the Ecosophia Prayer List FAQ</a>.<br/><br/>If there are any among you who might wish to join me in a bit of <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/1986.html\">astrological timing</a>, I pray each week for the health of all those with health problems on the list on the  astrological hour of the Sun on Sundays, bearing in mind the Sun's rulerships of heart, brain, and vital energies. If this appeals to you, I invite you to join me.</div>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59588180", "title": "Re: Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-03-16 03:22 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this as always. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59581780", "title": "Inner sound", "date": "2026-03-16 06:22 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "After doing zen meditation for about a year I became aware of a high-pitched ”inner sound” that springs up when I am silent and still. It is somewhere between a vibration and a sound and is very soothing as a meditation tool. Do you have any idea of what this might be? Or what it might signify? Thanks", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59588436", "title": "Re: Inner sound", "date": "2026-03-16 03:24 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a common experience with certain kinds of meditation; it's what Pythagoras called the music of the spheres. It means that you've made some progress in meditation, which is a very good thing. You might, though, see if you can find a properly trained Zen instructor -- now that you've gotten that far, you may need expert guidance to avoid some of the potential pitfalls in the intermediate and advanced stages of the work. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59594068", "title": "Re: Inner sound", "date": "2026-03-16 04:24 pm", "user": "isaac_hill", "content": "Oh, so that is it! I've been experiencing this for years, while doing various spiritual practices, but also sometimes throughout the day, even right now as I sit writing this. One of my spiritual mentors said it was something like the sound of the holy spirit descending or opening. I first noticed it in his presence after doing group self inquiry, and then would notice it when I was doing buddhist meditation, Heathen Golden Dawn rituals (sometimes very intensely), and now when I practice mantra japa, or just when I'm silent and centered. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59596116", "title": "Re: Inner sound", "date": "2026-03-16 04:41 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The old Pythagoreans would say that you've stilled your mind enough to hear the music of the spheres. It's a good sign. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59598676", "title": "Re: Inner sound", "date": "2026-03-16 05:02 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Interesting!  How does this differ from tinnitus?  I’ve had ringing in the ears off and on for several years.  A round of Chinese herbs and acupuncture took the edge off, and as a side benefit healed the digestive issues I mindlessly attributed to aging.<br/><br/>Still, I have (milder) intermittent ringing.  It’s pretty much the soundtrack to my life these days.<br/><br/>Thanks,<br/>OtterGirl", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59602772", "title": "Re: Inner sound", "date": "2026-03-16 06:25 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Does the ringing only become apparent in quiet states, and especially in meditation? And is it soothing and comforting? Both these are standard parts of the music of the spheres. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59621204", "title": "Re: Inner sound", "date": "2026-03-16 11:12 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I wish I could answer “yes!” to both questions.  It is more noticeable when things are quiet, but I don’t find it comforting.  I’m just happy that it is less intrusive than it was.  Several years ago, I noticed a visual sparkle or two after completing my morning Heathen LBRP/Middle Pillar, and hoped I was on track for some sort of mystical experience.  Nope!  Occasional sparks are common in the prolonged build up to an ocular migraine, which finally manifested in all of its glory several months later.  No pain; just quite the light show for a few minutes.  Fairly common among middle aged and older people.  Also of note is that this can, if it happens a lot, indicate a torn retina.  “Torn” I am told is painless, but it’s an emergency nonetheless.  Those early sparkles warrant an initial trip to the optometrist so they can be evaluated and monitored.<br/><br/>I soldier on with my practices.  If spectacular stuff doesn’t happen to me in this life, I’m okay with that.<br/><br/>OtterGirl<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59623508", "title": "Re: Inner sound", "date": "2026-03-17 12:06 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Then it's tinnitus and not the mystical experience. <br/><br/>2) Yes, I know about the sparkles. I get them from time to time as migraine prodromes, though if I do the right things I don't get the migraine.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59627092", "title": "Re: Inner sound", "date": "2026-03-17 12:39 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Interesting!  May I ask, just out of curiosity and certainly not seeking medical advice, what you do concerning said stray sparkles?  <br/><br/>Thanks as always,<br/>OtterGirl", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59627348", "title": "Re: Inner sound", "date": "2026-03-17 12:40 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Take a nap and drink plenty of fluids, especially green tea. Extra rest and hydration usually staves off migraines, for me. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59630164", "title": "Re: Inner sound", "date": "2026-03-17 01:21 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks JMG!  🙏<br/><br/>OtterGirl"}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59611988", "title": "Re: Inner sound", "date": "2026-03-16 08:49 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not OP. I also have tinnitus, so good to know acupuncture helps, I will ask my acupuncturist about it. <br/><br/>I notice my tinnitus gets cranked up to 11 when I enter deep meditation, it can get quite loud but I stop paying attention to it. I'm pretty sure I've also noticed a quiet, steady hum during meditation, I'll have to pay attention to tomorrow when I meditate next. <br/><br/>Speaking of hums, I live in a semi-rural area, a hamlet. Most mornings when I wake up, I will hear a constant low hum, like an electrical device is plugged in. I would go around the house trying to figure out whether it was the fridge, etc, then open the door to see if it was a neighbour, but I could never hear it outside the house.<br/><br/>The mystery was compounded a month or two ago when our area lost power completely during a storm. In the windless aftermath early the next morning, with hundreds of houses around without power, I still could hear the same hum! I opened the door to check if it was someone's generator - silence. In fact, the hum disappeared when I opened the door. The main power lines into the house were presumably completely without any current. <br/><br/>The only candidate is that we have a fire hall nearby, about a 2 minute walk away, with a radio antenna and presumably a backup generator. That's the only thing I can think of, although I couldn't hear anything when the door was open. It's still a total mystery. My wife can't hear it at all, but her hearing isn't the best. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59620692", "title": "Re: Inner sound", "date": "2026-03-16 11:10 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "It could be a natural resonant mode of the air in your house or in a confined space like the wall or basement or attic, getting pumped like a flute or a pipe organ or whistling lips by some constant just-unstable-enough-to-vibrate flow of air through a small gap driven by pressure differences (possibly from solar heating) somehow. Under this hypothesis, opening the door would change the resonant mode or remove the pressure difference driving the flow, and you should expect that opening a window would do the same thing. Depending on which chamber was resonating, the hypothesis would also suggest that you could sing at the same base frequency while inside the house with the door closed and notice a resonance, compared to singing a little higher or lower."}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59611732", "title": "Re: Inner sound", "date": "2026-03-16 08:47 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've started hearing this as well, although I'm a solo golden dawn practitioner. Any pitfalls you would advise in the case of golden dawn? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59613012", "title": "Re: Inner sound", "date": "2026-03-16 09:01 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Get your hearing checked to make sure it's not tinnitus. Other than that, the tradition doesn't offer much guidance. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59619924", "title": "Re: Inner sound", "date": "2026-03-16 10:52 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I wonder if that's the \"same thing as\" the \"inner sound\" that the Surat Shabd yoga people are on about, along with \"inner light\". \"Inner light\" sounds like the Zen thing about vast clear luminosity.<br/><br/>Come to think of it, both of those feel like something whose material aspect you could partly reductionistically-articulate what was going on there with the paradigm of predictive processing -- something about the direction of flow of stimulus-derived-evidence-like influences in the web of interpretational tendencies, and certain corners the system's tuning can be driven into (in this case somehow by use of deliberate attention and training on organically arising examples of subtle baseline dynamics not drowned out by confounding variables from the usual distractions, or whatever)."}]}, {"id": "cmt59582036", "title": "Divine Names in Mysteries of Merlin", "date": "2026-03-16 08:22 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good Morning Mr. Greer and commentariat,<br/><br/>I'm working through the Ovate cicle of Mysteries of Merlin currently and have some questions regarding the divine names in the LRP.<br/><br/>I'm likely overthinking unhelpfully, but if someone can offer some insights or context, that would be appreciated anyways.<br/><br/>1. Is there some more information about HEU'C and SYLW? <br/>I assumed SYLW is connected to the sun, but for HEU'C I have absolutely no idea who / what it would be connected to? I only assume it should be connected to a deity, because the other two directions get a name from the deities associated with the stations on the wheel.<br/><br/>2. I saw somewhere a template you posted for creating ones own LRP and there IIRC it was stated to put two gods and two godesses with the godesses at E / W. Assuming SYLW is corresponding to a goddess as the name is opposite ELEN, would you be willing to elaborate why you did it the other way for the CGD? That just got me curious.<br/><br/>3. My mind somehow expects Elen and Esus to be associated with the other's direction as that would make them correspond more to the elements. What am I missing here?<br/><br/>Thanks for your time.<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59588692", "title": "Re: Divine Names in Mysteries of Merlin", "date": "2026-03-16 03:28 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Heu'c is a variant form of Hu Gadarn, Hu the Mighty, who appears in Druid Revival literature and also Welsh mythology. Sulw is a variant of Sul, the goddess of the hot springs at Bath, called Sulis Minerva by the Romans. <br/><br/>2) Because it worked better that way. Keep in mind, first, that the templates I post are suggestions rather than laws, and second, that I deliberately do things differently in different books and other resources, in an attempt to head off fundamentalism of the \"JMG said it, I believe it, that settles it\" variety before it can get started. <br/><br/>3) What a fine theme for mediation! I mean that quite literally. If something in the teachings doesn't make sense to you, study it, meditate on it, treat it as a riddle that has something important to teach. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59589204", "title": "Re: Divine Names in Mysteries of Merlin", "date": "2026-03-16 03:44 pm", "user": "meriya_no_mi", "content": "Thanks for your response!<br/>I will add #3 to my list of meditation prompts then, that sounds like a helpful idea. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59582292", "title": "The Higher Genius and Occult Medicine", "date": "2026-03-16 08:51 am", "user": "open_space", "content": "I have been working some practices that help you connect with my Higher Genius that I do once every other week. It has been a moving practic so when you mentioned the orphic hymn to the personal daemon as a daily devotional practice I jumped on the idea and have been doing it daily. The language took me some effort, and the effort made me think. <br/><br/>I notice, perhaps out of my catholic upbringing, that the way in which deity is addressed here in the hymn is not very different from the catholic way of doing it. For example, the use of the words dread and terrible, revenge and tortures dire, refer much more to the sense of fear inspiring awe of something much bigger and powerful than you. Someone who can decide your fate and damn you if you push too hard against her will. I found that very instructive, because even though I approach deities with respect I do seem to more generally approach them as I would approach Jesus: forgiving and compassionate. I don't think that attitude is that useful when it comes to deities that are not of compassion because it tends to foster a response of fear in the devotee when a compassionate reply is not received. Ehm, like a child scolded by a parent instead of, say, a coworker to which you respond to. That could very easily be mishandled. For example, finding such deity dangerous or worse, evil, if one is self centered enough and unable to think differently about deities. Somehow that rings a bell!<br/><br/>I can see, on the other hand, how when praying to God it can lead to groveling and asking for forgiveness instead of manning up and doing what needs to be done in a world where the lower self is not the center, and the deity is not there to take care of you. I've noticed you mentioning this, but I don't think I had been able to discern what it meant. Useful, so very useful. The religion I was born into needs to bring more emphasis in its catechism in what I guess is referred as <em>the fear of God</em>, it would save everyone from so much trouble. It makes me think of some of the deities I've had trouble connecting with, like Saturn. I can almost picture him working, wondering what that screeching noise coming out of his devices has been all this long, only to say: Oh, pity, another stubborn soul got stuck on the gears of my clock, lets free him now. I chuckle now at that thought.<br/><br/>My first question today is. Would you be able to say a few words on this notion of deity as terrible and dreadful beings from the Neoplatonic point of view and their relationship with us?<br/><br/>Secondly, towards the end it's mentioned attending to the sacred rites. What is this referring to?<br/><br/>And a third question if I may. I am on my way back from Asia and I did a stop in Malaysia. One of the things I did was going to the Museum of Islamic Arts. Besides my jaw hitting the floor every other showcase from the staggering beauty and precision of Malay and Islamic handicrafts, I became aware of something I was not from the Ancient World. Through trade routes, Malay and Islamic healing modalities learned to use the Galenic humoral system and seem to have developed it considerably into their own traditiod. And there are loads of manuscripts about them. I bought a 3kg book just of summaries of them. I am very interested in occult and energetic physiology and anatomy partly because it is one of the fields that I consider need more development and reconstruction in our tradition. If you had to trace a workpath for a medium term research and experimental project, say, 4-6 months of work into this topic: What tools would be useful for correlation with what we do have in the west? What questions would you ask yourself? One of the things I would like to know is if they were able to workout an anatomy and system of working with the dense etheric body and if they applied alchemy or herbology into it. ", "edit_time": "2026-03-16 01:02 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59589972", "title": "Re: The Higher Genius and Occult Medicine", "date": "2026-03-16 03:48 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) To my mind it's crucial to remember that the gods are vaster and mightier than we can imagine. The dim reflections of them that show up in our mythologies and traditions are inadequate, to use no stronger word, as expressions of their true power, might, and scale. Nor can they be anything else, since (to return to a favorite metaphor) our chance of understanding the gods is roughly on a par with the chance that the dust mites in Mozart's wig could understand his music. Fear is an appropriate response to this. The Bible is spot on when it says \"the fear of God is the beginning of wisdom\" -- not the end of it, or even the intermediate stage of it, but the beginning. If you don't shiver at least a little when you contemplate the gods you're missing an important reality. <br/><br/>The guardian genius or daimon -- that's spelled \"guardian angel\" in Christian-influenced traditions -- is not on the same scale, but it's still bigger, wiser, and mightier than the individual it guards. The Orphic hymn focuses on the idea that the guardian genius is also the one that dispenses what Eastern traditions call karma -- \"revenge and tortures dire\" refer to that. You're basically saying to the genius, \"Help me work with you so I don't have to get socked in the face too often.\" <br/><br/>2) That's the point of the sacred rites. Remember that the Orphic hymns were originally written to be sung at celebrations of mystery initiations! The same principle applies, however, whenever you pray and make offerings to the gods. You're asking your guardian genius to be present and take part in the courteous and hospitable interaction that prayer and offerings are meant to bring about. <br/><br/>3) I'm probably the last person to ask, because I don't plan out workpaths in advance, ever. I engage the material and see where it leads me. If you want to know why so many of my books are so weird, why, now you know!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59594580", "title": "Re: The Higher Genius and Occult Medicine", "date": "2026-03-16 04:33 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "I had a thought about the person last week who didn't invoke Metatron and was rebuked for it by Metatron or a lower level spirit given authority by Metatron. It's strange that one of the highest angels cares about us. Incomprehensibly greater and impersonal makes more sense to me than being incomprehensibly great yet investedvin the development in humans. I know you don't have an answer for why the gods care about us. I'm just putting this out there.<br/><br/>Patrick H ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59595604", "title": "Re: The Higher Genius and Occult Medicine", "date": "2026-03-16 04:40 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The angels we know about are those who have some mission relating to human beings. Presumably Metatron is among those -- the highest of them, quite possibly, but if we're part of his job, we're part of his job. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59613780", "title": "Re: The Higher Genius and Occult Medicine", "date": "2026-03-16 09:16 pm", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "I wonder if the higher entities look upon us like pets: creatures who can be lovable, foolish, surprisingly precocious, and even need to be put down occasionally, but overall in need of vast forbearance and patience.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59615316", "title": "Re: The Higher Genius and Occult Medicine", "date": "2026-03-16 09:41 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You'll have to ask them sometime and find out. ;-)"}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59609428", "title": "Re: The Higher Genius and Occult Medicine", "date": "2026-03-16 07:41 pm", "user": "open_space", "content": "1 &amp; 2 )The dust mites might have not understood Mozart's music but they certainly vibed with it and so do we with the god's! Can you imagine the jump the dust mites on Beethoven's wig must have made on some of his symphonies? That certainly must've instilled some fear. <br/><br/>Thank you, yes the practices I do use the term Guardian Angel but frankly centuries of tacky angelic images kind of ruined it for me so I prefer the term higher genius or higher self. A  flock of scented smiling babies as cherubim? Really? Ok, on second thought that does sound terrifying. I tend to see archangels as geometric shapes or columns of light though.<br/><br/>I think I do get it, it is not fear of them being against you but fear of the sheer size. Like standing in front of a waterfall or river with a strong torrent, or a thunderstorm but at a cosmic scale. Or staring somewhere so far from what you know that there is no reference to make things out.<br/><br/>3) Oh is that what it is? I thought it was because of the weird druid on the keyboard :-)  "}, {"id": "cmt59613268", "title": "Re: The Higher Genius and Occult Medicine", "date": "2026-03-16 09:09 pm", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "This reminds me of a classic passage I read, either in the original or a comic adaptation (I forget which):<br/><br/>\"Do you fear the gods, Conan?\"<br/>\"I would not tread on their shadows\".<br/><br/>The whole thing is great, but that really stuck to me.<br/><br/>more here: <a href=\"https://kihm2.wordpress.com/2013/05/03/conan-the-theologian/\">https://kihm2.wordpress.com/2013/05/03/conan-the-theologian/</a>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59615828", "title": "Re: The Higher Genius and Occult Medicine", "date": "2026-03-16 09:41 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If that's not Robert E. Howard it's someone who caught his tone perfectly. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59583060", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 10:00 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,<br/>Last week I asked you a question and, because of time zone differences, I did not see your answer until some time on Tuesday. <br/>My question was about the Iran War, and the disturbing (at least to me) influence of senior figures in both the US and Israel who have, and express, an apocalyptic mindset,  suggesting that for them the war is a religious one which will bring about the  second coming of Jesus. My question was not on the progress of the war itself, which is for elsewhere, but whether this had produced a change in the astral weather, since leaders in both countries believe, or at least talk about, the possibility of apocalyptic wars. <br/><br/>I mentioned in passing that we don't have such things in Europe, and this was the point you answered, referencing the millennial movements in the middle ages and later. This is quite  true of course, and I remember reading Cohn's book on the subject fifty years ago. But my question was specifically about the influence of apocalyptic biblical prophecies on the thinking of modern leaders involved in a high-stakes and potentially disastrous war. I wondered if you thought that, apart from the practical dimension, there was also an important esoteric issue here. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59590228", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 03:51 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thanks for clarifying. Apocalyptic fantasies of one kind or another have been a driving force in international conflict all along, including in modern times -- the Cold War, for example, was dominated by the clash between Christian apocalypticism on the part of the US and Marxist apocalypticism on the part of the Soviet Union. So I don't think there's a change in the astral weather -- it's just more of the same. "}, {"id": "cmt59628628", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-17 12:59 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Some interesting info regarding the 3 public faces of the conflict, via Chris Brennan:<br/>All three world leaders in the current war were born the day of an eclipse:<br/><br/>🪐 Trump: Jun 14, 1946: Lunar Eclipse<br/>🪐 Netanyahu: Oct 21, 1949 Solar Eclipse<br/>🪐 Khamenei: Apr 19, 1939: Solar Eclipse<br/><br/>The next eclipse happens tonight, in the wake of Khamenei's death<br/><br/>and from a commenter:<br/>And this leader not only died on an eclipse but was also born on the Aries solar eclipse in Apr 1939 just before WW2 when Saturn was also in Aries and Uranus in Taurus. He became leader in 1989-previous Saturn Neptune conjunction in Capricorn with Uranus. Died on his Venus return<br/><br/>And I read somewhere else new Sup/L born within about 3 days of an eclipse and they also mentioned some hard natal aspects with T and N<br/><br/>Also this:<br/>Planetary alignments from the past that are recurring in the sky now: <br/>🪐 1953: Saturn-Neptune: US coup overthrows leader of Iran<br/>🪐 1979: Eclipse in Virgo: Creation of current government in Iran begins<br/>🪐 1989: Saturn-Neptune: Supreme leader of Iran dies<br/>🪐 2025: Mars-Uranus square: 12-Day War in Iran in June<br/><br/>His x account if anyone is interested<br/><br/>https://xcancel.com/chrisbrennan7/with_replies<br/><br/><br/>"}]}, {"id": "cmt59583316", "title": "Medical astrology", "date": "2026-03-16 10:01 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG<br/><br/>Not that long ago I had a very serious health crisis that I barely came through but now have to manage for the foreseeable future. Could medical astrology provide some useful information to better manage my situation? If so, do you know of anyone you could recommend?<br/><br/>/Fredrik  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59590484", "title": "Re: Medical astrology", "date": "2026-03-16 03:52 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That isn't a field I've studied to any degree, and I'm not currently aware of anyone who has really gotten into classic medical astrology. Maybe someone else has a suggestion to make. "}, {"id": "cmt59593300", "title": "Re: Medical astrology", "date": "2026-03-16 04:19 pm", "user": "isaac_hill", "content": "In terms of traditional Western medical astrology: <br/><br/>Marcos Patchett is a traditional herbalist and traditional medical astrologer, in the tradition of Culpeper. <a href=\"https://nocturnalherbalist.com/v2/\">https://nocturnalherbalist.com/v2/</a> <br/><br/>William Morris has been trained in multiple traditions of medical astrology, as well as sound healing and more: <a href=\"https://acutonics.com/profiles/william-morris-phd-daom-msed-lac-rh-profile\">https://acutonics.com/profiles/william-morris-phd-daom-msed-lac-rh-profile</a><br/><br/>Judith Hill, Mychal Bryan, and Kira Sutherland are all also good, but I actually kinda see them more as teachers than medical practitioners, I'm not sure how easy it is to get a reading with them.<br/><br/>I practice mainly traditional Vedic astrology, and there's a lot I can see in terms of medical astrology, but is isn't a main focus currently, you can email me at askisaachill@gmail.com though. There are others in my tradition that focus more on medical astrology too, being also trained in nursing and/or ayurveda: <a href=\"https://www.scienceoflight.net/jyotishasangha/\">https://www.scienceoflight.net/jyotishasangha/</a>"}]}, {"id": "cmt59583572", "title": "Egregores/Magical Groups", "date": "2026-03-16 10:49 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Greetings John!<br/>This is a bit of a convoluted question, but I’ll try to keep it simple. I suppose this has to do with magic in a much broader sense. I wanted to see what you thought of this. I’m still quite green, but in having interest in Neoplatonism and Kabbalah I’ve of course invested some time into the golden dawn. But I’m realizing that the source material that the order bases its  teachings on, at least some of them, are either incorrect or really strange interpretations. Take the correspondence given to the seven double letters. I do realize the safer get Sepher Yetzirah manuscripts can disagree with one another.. What I’m trying to get at here is do mistakes like this affect the efficiency of the magic within the order? Or if the egregore is strong enough, does the fact that this information is believed and practiced consistently over time overcome that shortcoming? I’ll tack this last question on as well, was the golden Dan influenced more by the new thought movement in terms of its interpretation of older systems like Neoplatonism and Hermeticism? Does the order represent these ideas properly, is what I’m getting at. Thank you for your time John. Hope you’re doing good!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59590740", "title": "Re: Egregores/Magical Groups", "date": "2026-03-16 03:56 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Symbolism is a tool, not a truth, and so there are no wrong symbols. There are, for example, at least a dozen ways to apply the Hebrew alphabet to the Tree of Life, and they all work -- what's more, they work equally well. Quarrels among the partisans of different systems are like a quarrel between a German, a Frenchman, and an Englishman about whether the four-legged animal barking at them is <i>ein Hund, un chien</i>, or a dog. <br/><br/>The GD drew its symbolism from one particular corner of mostly British occultism with close ties to some of the odder ends of Christian Cabala. Other traditions draw from other places and have their own oddities. None of it matters in practice; any symbolic system studied and practiced assiduously will have comparable effects, just as you can say \"that's a dog\" in any human language. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59583828", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 11:52 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Freaking hilarious meme!<br/><br/>I was hanging out with one of my buddies Friday night, and the topic went to a Satanist he worked with and knew for awhile, and all the interpersonal shenanigans this guy tried to pull on my friend. It is interesting that this person, now well into middle age, still works at a local fast food restaurant chain. I have absolutely nothing against those in the service industry, but for all his Satanic power, he still hasn't gotten much of anything in life. Unless you count coming home smelling like chili and fry grease. That's real attractive to the ladies!<br/><br/>JPM ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59590996", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 04:00 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's the thing about Satanism, and also about the various demon-summoning forms of magic that are so fashionable these days. Their practitioners go on and on about how these things will make them powerful and successful, but yeah, in my experience they're all still flipping burgers and waiting for the promised bucks and babes to put in an appearance. Meanwhile those who work with magical traditions that don't depend on mooching favors from debased spiritual entities by and large get much better results. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59592276", "title": "Anton Shrugged", "date": "2026-03-16 04:14 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Very true!<br/><br/>This also got me thinking a parody of one of Rand's novels with corporate Satanists running it might be funny... But that might also get to close to the mindset people already have vis a vis your conversation with Nick Land.<br/><br/><br/>JPM", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59593812", "title": "Re: Anton Shrugged", "date": "2026-03-16 04:22 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Too funny. I'll pass, though -- you can't really parody something without reading it very closely, and I find Rand's turgid prose unreadable. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59596884", "title": "Re: Anton Shrugged", "date": "2026-03-16 04:46 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I will pass as well! I have the same reaction to her work. There are more important things to do! -JPM"}, {"id": "cmt59621716", "title": "Re: Anton Shrugged", "date": "2026-03-16 11:37 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "The famous Bob The Angry Flower cartoon \"Atlas Shrugged 2: 1 Hour Later\" was funny.<br/><br/>Patrick H.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59623764", "title": "Re: Anton Shrugged", "date": "2026-03-17 12:07 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It was indeed! "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59626324", "title": "Re: Anton Shrugged", "date": "2026-03-17 12:31 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "It's weird that you bring that up in a reply to a comment mentioning \"mooching\", since that's something she tried to exclude from her system -- she dragged her idea of the proper conception of \"charity\" over to being something people do to (really \"with\", since it's a voluntary transaction) other people exhibiting the same life-oriented (meaning, in her system, worldly-productive-mechanical-consequence-oriented) values, as a device for maintaining those values in oneself against (implied) entropy and dispiriting examples from other people. (I suppose that could be undiplomatically characterized as like exchanging money for ongoing performance-art equivalents of (tasteful and refined) inspirational workplace and home-office posters not otherwise available, at a cheaper price.)<br/><br/>While this isn't saying much, since she found something about a lot of things that she found revolting (she had some kind of BPD-like splitting), I half-expect that she would have found something in Satanism to find revolting, even the ostensibly non-mooching form.<br/><br/>And yet... I guess there was that one journal entry where she judged the attitude of Leopold and Loeb towards the murder they committed to contain, to put it a charitably, a distilled essence of something vitally important that she was uniformly not permitted to get under the Soviet cultural machine -- something to do with it being notionally fundamentally legitimate to have a psychological base from which one could detect and reject toxic reality-untethered consensus. Having seen that attitude up close in connection with Satanism(-broadly-construed), I can see how the one could be interpreted by a Satanist as being fulfilled in the other, especially if you lean into interpreting its essence as defiance/opposition instead of unconcern/independence. A lot of Rand's philosophy could be framed as an attempt to worldbuild an entire hypothetical culture under which that impulse could plausibly be consistently \"okay\" or \"laudable\".", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59626580", "title": "Re: Anton Shrugged", "date": "2026-03-17 12:37 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You might also factor in her glorification of William Hickman, one of the most revolting child murderers of the century. (Or for that matter the fact that she went on Social Security and Medicare as soon as she was eligible for them -- apparently her dislike of mooching only applied to other people.) ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59627604", "title": "Re: Anton Shrugged", "date": "2026-03-17 12:41 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "To be fair, that seems to be a very common attitude for the chattering classes of the last few centuries: \"No one, except for ME should ever be allowed to mooch!\"....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59628372", "title": "Re: Anton Shrugged", "date": "2026-03-17 12:44 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, granted! "}]}, {"id": "cmt59632212", "title": "Re: Anton Shrugged", "date": "2026-03-17 02:14 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Oops, sorry, I guess it was that case. I'm not sure how I got the wires crossed.<br/><br/>To all appearances, she considered accepting welfare to be a substitute way of accepting restitution.<br/><br/>&gt; The recipient [...] is morally justified <i>only so long as he regards it as restitution and opposes all forms of welfare statism</i>. [...] If this sounds like a paradox, the fault lies in the moral contradictions of welfare statism[...]<br/>&gt; <br/>&gt; [...a bunch of invocation of elsewhere-vehemently-argued-to-more-properly-be-quite-exacting conceptions of \"rights\"...] The victims do not have to add self-inflicted martyrdom to the injury done to them by others; they do not have to let the looters profit doubly, by letting them distribute the money exclusively to the parasites who clamored for it. Whenever the welfare-state laws offer them some small restitution, the victims should take it[...]<br/><br/>I'm not sure what she would have said about a proposal for everyone to do an accounting to divide their taxes into just and unjust parts and only accept \"restitution\" up to the quantity calculated as unjust so far, or up to the net-present value of some future expected amount of unjust expropriation. But she did have her goodguys in Atlas Shrugged do that calculation for the heroine and pay her out of, I think it might have been wealth taken by piracy from shipping of goods bought by states they considered anti-life outlaws, suggesting that the idea was significantly older than her turning 65: roughly speaking, that accepting welfare were restorative piracy by other means.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59632468", "title": "Re: Anton Shrugged", "date": "2026-03-17 02:17 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, I know. To my mind it's simply a flurry of excuses for benefiting from an institution she claimed to oppose. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59638100", "title": "Re: Anton Shrugged", "date": "2026-03-17 03:40 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In the scenario where trying to \"benefit\" on net from the institution, relative to how much she suffered from it, was her actual motivation, and everything else was excuses, then you should also expect that, <i>ex ante</i>, she would have come up excuses to support the creation of the institution if it hadn't existed already and would only benefit her if it did.<br/><br/>Or in the more plausible <i>ex post</i> scenario, you should also expect that, if for some reason someone had done the calculation of unjust-taxedness for her (and others who she might redistribute any excess \"restitution\" to), and if for some reason she got more than that amount in welfare payments, she would in that case reliably generate further excuses within that flurry for keeping the extra money as well, without even distributing it to ideologically allied followers who hadn't gotten enough welfare moneys back yet.<br/><br/>Of course we can't know now what she would have done in that hypothetical, but you should notice whether or not that further prediction within the hypothetical would feel discordant with what else you know of her. To my mind, if I'm trying to get it to feel even only just moderately discordant, I have to add the proviso where I suppose she's assigning the extra moneys to an at least half-formed subjective equivalent of a separately-tracked earmarked account for activism (against statism or for philosophical advocacy that seemed better-leveraged against statism), or to an activist organization she controlled. If I don't add that proviso it feels pretty discordant.<br/><br/>Maybe to your mind it doesn't feel discordant, because you expect that she's coming from a place of ordinary unbalanced selfishness.<br/><br/>But, side evidence about what Rand would have rationalized aside, it would be weird for there to be no such viable moral category, in anybody's moral psychology, as \"'benefiting' from an institution one claims to oppose, as constructed by an observer by defining 'benefit' relative to a privileged 'null-action' baseline alternative of only just suffering from that institution on net, and carefully only benefiting up to a point of equal restitution\", recognizable as distinct from \"willingly benefiting from an institution even when it's on net, but claiming to oppose it\". So it seems like there at least ought to be some case where, if someone observes conduct toward the welfare system like Rand's, and it's observational evidence which doesn't distinguish between the two positions, it should be possible for there to exist side evidence about the person's character to establish that actually the moral category they were using was the first one and not the second one.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59638868", "title": "Re: Anton Shrugged", "date": "2026-03-17 03:46 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "To my mind, the categorical imperative applies here. If you're going to insist that nobody should benefit from a given thing, that implies that you yourself should not benefit from it. If I insisted that television was a bad thing and nobody should watch it, but watched television regularly just because it exists, I'd be a hypocrite. As I see it, the same logic applies to Rand. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59638356", "title": "Re: Anton Shrugged", "date": "2026-03-17 03:41 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I find it baffling how many people will take advantage of things they claim to abhor. Whether it's wealthy people claiming tax credits and complaining their tax bill is lower than their employees, people who claim to hate governments subsidizing things taking advantage of government subsidies, people who claim to be concerned about the environment flying for vacation, or people who claim to hate AI using it, it's astonishing how many people seem to think \"If it's there, and it benefits me, I <i>must</i> use it, regardless of whether I think it moral or not.\" It's always struck me as bizarre, to put it mildly."}]}, {"id": "cmt59637332", "title": "Re: Anton Shrugged", "date": "2026-03-17 03:32 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Reading further, I guess the essay containing that text itself also wasn't that long after Atlas Shrugged; it was only the compilation whose date of publication was after her death.<br/><br/>(trying to summarize https://medium.com/the-radical-center/ayn-rand-nietzsche-and-the-purposeless-monster-e0e8e314398a ) <br/><br/>There may have been a game of telephone from Rand's journals going on about Hickman, to Jennifer Burns's 2009 biography \"Goddess of the Market\", to a prominent 2010 Alternet article.<br/><br/>Parts of her journals published after her death in 1996 include parts that Burns didn't mention, where she called Hickman a \"purposeless monster\" and explicitly disconnected Hickman's motives and specific style of murder from those of a closer-to-properly-idealized serial killer (?) protagonist in an early novel plot she gave up on, which plot (reading between the lines) she had been trying to construct as a condemnation of a (hypothetical clearer-cut?) society that had convergently prevented the protagonist from having any other (recognizable?) psychologically viable way of internally siding with what she considered to be the only fundamentally healthy configuration of internal psychological space-making.<br/><br/>&gt; all the information purported to show Rand’s evil views comes from her own journals. Yet, what they [the purporters] don’t quote is Rand’s own appraisal of the relationship of Renahan to Hickman. She said Renahan is “very far from him [Hickman], of course. The outside of Hickman, but not the inside. Much deeper and much more. A Hickman with a purpose. And <em>without the degeneracy.</em> <strong>It is more exact to say that the model is not Hickman, but what Hickman suggested to me.</strong>” [emphasis probably Peron's]<br/><br/>Which doesn't directly say she understood that actually Hickman was a psychopath in whatever terms, only a 'degenerate', but does strongly suggest that she understood that Hickman himself was actually internally constituted some other way than the thing she was supposing it would instead be good to affirm.<br/><br/>The article also raises various evidences about how how her views changed over time in other respects."}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59584340", "title": "Levi book", "date": "2026-03-16 01:27 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello,   Is your book on Eliphas Levi's \"Doctrine &amp; Ritual\" to be released this spring?  I'm looking forward to seeing it.  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59591764", "title": "Re: Levi book", "date": "2026-03-16 04:05 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It'll be out next month and is already available for preorder: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://spirit.aeonbooks.com/product/great-arcanum/95405\">https://spirit.aeonbooks.com/product/great-arcanum/95405</a><br/><br/>If you enter the discount code ARCANUM20 when you preorder you get 20% off the cover price. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59593044", "title": "Re: Levi book", "date": "2026-03-16 04:19 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you.  Will pre-order."}, {"id": "cmt59610708", "title": "Re: Levi book", "date": "2026-03-16 07:57 pm", "user": "danius", "content": "Thanks for the discount. I just ordered it. Given how slowly I am making my way through books these days I don't expect to get to it for a while though. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59611476", "title": "Re: Levi book", "date": "2026-03-16 08:46 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No prob. It'll keep well. ;-)"}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59584596", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 01:34 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What is the purpose of prayer?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59592532", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 04:18 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That depends very much on what you mean by that much-muddled word. If you mean the sort of \"Lord gimme this, Lord gimme that\" crap enshrined in hymns such as \"Sweet Hour of Prayer\" --<br/><br/>\"That bids me at my Father's throne<br/>Make all my wants and wishes known\" <br/><br/>-- it's an exercise in overinflated entitlement and inevitable frustration. The Divine is not a vending machine.<br/><br/>True prayer is the act of spending time in the company of some aspect of the Divine. It's at least as much a matter of listening as of talking. Approach the deity to whom you pray as you would a much older and wiser friend and you're likely to get it right. Speak and then listen attentively, or just be in the presence of the deity. <br/><br/>Maybe you had the experience in childhood of sitting with a beloved grandparent. The two of you  might not have exchanged more than a few words, if any; there you were, side by side on the sofa; Grandpa was reading the newspaper, and you were reading a picture book and slowly piecing together what the letters spelt out -- and yet the memory is one of great closeness and comfort. That's a very powerful kind of prayer. Mystics call it the prayer of simple regard, or when it's turned into a sustained discipline, the practice of the presence of God. <br/><br/>The important point is that you build a relationship with the Divine the way you build any other relationship, by spending time with the other person. Prayer in all its many forms is how you do that with the Divine. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59585108", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 01:55 pm", "user": "thinking_turtle", "content": "<p>To share, for those who wonder what RW, BOTA, or LMP mean, a <a href=\"https://thinking-turtle.dreamwidth.org/tag/abbreviation\">list of abbreviations used on Ecopsophia</a>.  And here is a <a href=\"https://thinking-turtle.dreamwidth.org/tag/books\">list of the books our host published so far</a>.</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59593556", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 04:20 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this as always. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59585620", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 02:34 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello John,<br/><br/><br/>Q1. As a polytheist, what would you say forming a relationship with deities consists of?<br/><br/>I can't imagine that deities need or want anything from human beings. Are they inclined to help humans for some reason?<br/><br/>Q2. What would be a good beginner practice for trying to form a relationship with a deity?<br/><br/>Q3 As a polytheist, what do you think will happen to you when your sojourn here comes to an end?<br/><br/>Thanks as always for Magic Monday.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59594836", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 04:35 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) One of the great differences between standard Abrahamic monotheism and traditional polytheism is that polytheism doesn't postulate the vast and irreconcilable difference between deity and humanity that most monotheist faiths do. The gods and goddesses are greater, wiser, and mightier than we are, but the difference isn't absolute; there are greater and lesser gods, and some of the lesser ones are much closer to the human level. As for what they might want from us, I can think of no better explanation than one I put into one of my novels: <br/><br/>*****<br/>She laughed, shaking her head in amazement, then considered the vast span of time she’d been shown, the infinitesimal length of her own life, and the greater but still tiny span allotted to her species, and asked in wonder: <i>why do you even bother with us?</i><br/><br/>The answer this time came in the form of one of her own memories. That autumn, looking out the window of her bedroom in the house on Halsey Street, she’d seen a bright-eyed little wren hopping here and there on the outside sill, and watched it for most of fifteen minutes until it finally darted off in a flurry of tiny wings. The image came back to her in perfect clarity, vanished as suddenly as it had come. <br/><br/>The image delighted her, and she laughed again. A sudden stray thought tried to convince her that she should take offense at the comparison, brought up all those claims she’d heard that human beings had some grander role in the scheme of things than wrens or hermit crabs or faint shapeless blurs at the bottom of Archaean tidepools; a slogan from a poster on a Miskatonic University bulletin board tried to force its way into her mind. At that moment, it might as well have tried to convince her that squares have five sides and rocks fall straight up into the sky. <i>I hope we entertain you,</i> she said, still laughing.<br/><br/><i>Now and again</i>, the not-voice responded, amused. Then, serious again: <i>But there is another matter. Some things can be done by a wren that a human cannot do as easily, or at all.</i><br/><br/>She had wondered, since her first contact with Saint Toad, if one of the doors that would open before her would lead her to do things at the Great Old One’s direction. She could refuse, she knew that at once, and there might be good reason to do so, but the thought was a distant abstraction. <i>If there’s anything you want me to do...<br/><br/>All in good time</i>, the Great Old One replied.<br/><br/>*****<br/>2) Prayer is the standard approach. You might consider setting up a little shrine -- a sacred image and an incense burner are quite enough to start with -- and taking a little while every day to pray there. <br/><br/>3) Well, I recall scraps of some of my previous lives, so I expect to go on to some other incarnation. Still, we'll see! ", "edit_time": "2026-03-16 04:36 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59600468", "title": "Saint toad", "date": "2026-03-16 05:56 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "My father in law in life was known as The Toad. He looked like one with that toad facial expression. He came back as a huge toad that lives outside our building. I regard him as a family Lar, and greet Him with prayer. And an occasional dead fly.<br/><br/>Neptune's Dolphins.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59603028", "title": "Re: Saint toad", "date": "2026-03-16 06:30 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "From a Lovecraftian standpoint, he may have been a reflection of Tsathoggua, the \"Saint Toad\" of the story. Lovecraft's poem on the subject is apposite: <br/><br/>“Beware St. Toad’s cracked chimes!” I heard him scream<br/>As I plunged into those mad lanes that wind<br/>In labyrinths obscure and undefined<br/>South of the river where old centuries dream.<br/>He was a furtive figure, bent and ragged,<br/>And in a flash had staggered out of sight,<br/>So still I burrowed onward in the night<br/>Toward where more roof-lines rose, malign and jagged.<br/><br/>No guide-book told of what was lurking here—<br/>But now I heard another old man shriek:<br/>“Beware St. Toad’s cracked chimes!” And growing weak,<br/>I paused, when a third greybeard croaked in fear:<br/>“Beware St. Toad’s cracked chimes!” Aghast, I fled—<br/>Till suddenly that black spire loomed ahead. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59600724", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 06:01 pm", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "That is my all-time favorite passage in all of your novels that I've read so far!  (It is also in the folder I keep of wise quotations.)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59603284", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 06:31 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Delighted to hear it. My tentacle novels express quite a lot of my own religious intuitions and experiences, and that book more than most. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59607124", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 07:09 pm", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "I suspected that might be the case when I was reading it, and them, for the first time.  (And they mesh very well with my own take on such matters, too.)  I have much the same reaction, too, as I'm reading your Ariel Moravec novels.  They are all \"keepers\"!"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59616340", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 09:45 pm", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "Regarding #3: If your past life memories are fragmentary, is that a reliable indicator that you've got more incarnations to get through? Conversely, when you're finished with the human world, should you have a fairly complete recollection of your human lives?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59617364", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 09:51 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The lore available to me doesn't specify; it simply indicates that you don't begin to recall previous lives until you're mostly done with incarnation. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59618388", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 10:03 pm", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "I see, thanks. So I guess it's open-ended, and the only certainty is that you're on the home stretch (as am I, recalling bits &amp; pieces of three different incarnations from the Dark Age, Medieval, and Modern times)."}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59585876", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 02:49 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>I'm familiar with the SoP, Judson exercise, LBRP and the Bornless ritual. But I've been wondering about other techniques of protection and banishing/cleansing.<br/>The same methods seem to appear again and again in esoteric literature. I don't see a huge variety in the techniques available.<br/><br/>Q1. Are you aware of any list of such practices? <br/><br/><br/>Q2. Are there any methods that only involve prayer and meditation? I'm specifically wondering about Christian methods here. I would imagine a lot of the older Christian esoteric practices involve a lot of prayer.<br/><br/>Thanks in advance.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59595092", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 04:38 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I wish there was such a list. <br/><br/>2) In terms of protection? Sure. Many Christians say a daily prayer to St. Michael the Archangel for spiritual protection: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prayer_to_Saint_Michael\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prayer_to_Saint_Michael</a>"}]}, {"id": "cmt59588948", "title": "Different Strokes", "date": "2026-03-16 03:43 pm", "user": "degringolade", "content": "I spent some very useful time trying to figure out mundane astrology.  I now know two things, the first is that here is something there, the second is that it doesn't seem to \"fit\" inside my psyche, so I just pay you a subscription and let you give me overviews over at your Patreon site.<br/><br/>That being said, I am definitely more interested in the use of tarot to get peeks at what is coming down the pike in the big bad world.  This being the case, do you, or any reader, have any suggestions concerning texts that might be useful in figuning out \"Mundane Tarot\"?<br/><br/>I am presently going with the idea that the tarot can be used as a mundane prediction system by spending some serious time thoroughly framing the question inside your brain before/while randomizing the cards.  <br/><br/>Maybe it is more than that, but if anyone has any suggestions, I would be more than happy to listen.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59597140", "title": "Re: Different Strokes", "date": "2026-03-16 04:48 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't know of anybody who's worked that out in detail, but it should certainly be possible; John Heydon and Christopher Cattan showed that mundane geomancy was an option, back in the Renaissance, and tarot should be equally suitable for such projects. I'll be interested to see what you come up with! "}]}, {"id": "cmt59589460", "title": "Jewels and charges", "date": "2026-03-16 03:46 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have had some jewels which had belonged to a friend come into my possession through the gift of another friend who had them from the first friend's estate.  I do not know the kinds of stones in them, though probably should ascertain that for mundane insurance purposes whether cut glass, semi-precious, or precious (any is possible given the friends, though the more expensive options are more probable).<br/>My question is if it is possible that these jewels picked up a charge from being present in many, many fraternal ritual ceremonies over the years, and if so, if there are any precautions to take on the cleaning and caretaking side.  The ring particularly feels like it wants to be worn, and as it is a bit snaggy would not sensibly be the first choice for everyday wear, and yet . . .<br/><br/>BoysMom", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59597396", "title": "Re: Jewels and charges", "date": "2026-03-16 04:51 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good heavens, yes. Lodge ceremonies, even when they're performed by people who have no clue, have energetic effects, and a piece of symbolic jewelry repeatedly worn in a lodge setting will undergo a process of entrainment that will lead to it absorbing and radiating much of the energy. <br/><br/>I recommend washing them in lukewarm water and exposing them to unfiltered sunlight, to clear away any unwanted etheric influence, and then using your intuition to decide whether and when to wear them. If the ring's energy is positive, it may bring you a whole range of subtle and not-so-subtle benefits if you wear it. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59629908", "title": "Re: Jewels and charges", "date": "2026-03-17 01:19 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you.<br/><br/>The brooch doesn't draw me to put it on as an everyday item like the ring does.  I do think I need to get the ring checked over professionally, loose emblems and stones tightened, etc.  It keeps pulling threads.<br/><br/>The usual jewelers-there are two locally we use who are known to be friendly and competent-generally clean items when inspecting them.  Are those kinds of cleaners to be avoided, do you know?  I could probably ask that they not clean it: I think they called the machine a sonic cleaner the last time I took a family ring in.<br/><br/>BoysMom", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59633748", "title": "Re: Jewels and charges", "date": "2026-03-17 02:28 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Sonic cleaners are fine; they'll remove the dirt, but will have no effect on the spiritual, mental, and astral energies in the ring and brooch. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59589716", "title": "Religion, alienation, and the turning of an age.", "date": "2026-03-16 03:47 pm", "user": "jflylynn", "content": "Hello Mr Greer. <br/><br/>I was listening to your recent talk with plant cunning while doing some throughly boring manual labor and was struck by a comment you made about axial religion. You mentioned that axial religion is very focused on uniformity of everything that believers engage in. This seemed to express about 90% of everything I’ve struggled with in a long and maybe still ongoing journey in Christianity. Namely that I can’t be bothered to condemn people that seem to be faithful to my God in a different manner and am continually confused as to why pastors and laymen alike seemed dead set on convincing me to be faithful towards said God in ways that damage my own faith. <br/>This has led me to two hypotheses about the way I think religion is going to go in the next few centuries. Firstly religion is going to get weird I suspect the Protestant inclination in the US to spilt into an infinite spectrum of tiny denominations that all are generally cordial will continue. This will be joined by a host of new traditions that may or may not give any credibility to axial era religion or tradition.<br/>Secondly that the idea of a war of religion will dissipate, in the west at least, due to the enspectrumification of religion. I see this as a great thing religious war had tended to be a great excuse for committing horrific war crimes and the less of those the better. Now if you’re the kind of young man that is reconstructing his entire identity around a mental image of the halcyon religious past that is rapidly filling up the conservative end of religion today this is probably less good news. <br/>Finally I think we have already seen this beginning to take effect. Most notably that stalwart of the full flowering of axial religion the Catholic Church is allowing a remarkable amount of liturgical variation since Vatican 2 and seems to be open to reabsorbing its rightward schismatics if they would calm down a little. <br/>I have no idea of I’ve hit the nail on the head or am wandering into a swamp but this line of thinking has helped my own religious life and I hope will help others suffering the cognitive dissonance of having a non-axial mind while trying to live in an axial religion. I also would like to say that I don’t think the next great age of this chunk of mankind will be a utopian garden we are still monkeys with rocks (very fancy rocks but still rocks) and humans will  sadly always find reasons to hate rob and kill each other. <br/><br/>JL", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59597652", "title": "Re: Religion, alienation, and the turning of an age.", "date": "2026-03-16 04:59 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "This is certainly what I suspect. We're moving out of the Piscean age, which belongs to the element of water and is ruled by Neptune; water corresponds to emotions and Neptune is the planet of unities, so powerful emotional pressures toward unity and uniformity have typified Piscean religion. The coming Aquarian age belongs to the element of air and is ruled by Uranus, the planet of individuality and eccentricity; I expect the religions of the next 2160 years to be more intellectual than emotional and much more diverse, focusing on each individual following his or her own spiritual vision.<br/><br/>I think a significant minority of people are already becoming attuned to the new influence, and find themselves alienated from the Axial/Piscean faiths. The current movement toward religious conservatism is of course also a factor; the Second Religiosity, as Oswald Spengler called it, is an attempt to stave off social and mental chaos by returning to a stable source of meaning and value. It's an important and generally beneficial part of the declining phase of every great civilization, but as it proceeds it'll become more and more a habit of the overrprivileged classes, while strange new religious visions take shape down in the crawlspaces of society among the disenfranchised and underprivileged masses. That is to say, things will get strange as we proceed. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59604820", "title": "Re: Religion, alienation, and the turning of an age.", "date": "2026-03-16 06:53 pm", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>One of the things that stands out to me is that during the vast majority of the Piscean age, Neptune was unknown and so its influence unaccounted for, which is likely why the religions of that age all seemed to have developed the awkward habit of seeing themselves as paradigms of what all religions are like — or even as just <em>religion</em>, singular — instead of the very exceptional oddballs they actually are in the grand scheme of history.</p>\n<p>This time even the return to religious conservatism will be with a self-consciousness of their own distinctness and exceptional character, even if what they take from it is that they are uniquely true and wonderful.  Christians (etc.) of the future may well still <em>judge</em> other religions by their own lights, but the world where they insist on <em>interpreting</em> other religions by their own lights is arguably fading out for good.</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59605844", "title": "Re: Religion, alienation, and the turning of an age.", "date": "2026-03-16 06:57 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Here's hoping! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59630932", "title": "Re: Religion, alienation, and the turning of an age.", "date": "2026-03-17 01:40 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG,<br/>If I recall, you mentioned some time back that you think Islam will undergo it's own reformation?<br/><br/>Any further thoughts on this?<br/><br/>Could it be linked to your theory that a lot of liberals/atheists will end up becoming converts?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59633236", "title": "Re: Religion, alienation, and the turning of an age.", "date": "2026-03-17 02:25 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Islam is following a trajectory about 600 years behind that of Christianity, so it's experiencing very roughly what Christianity experienced in the 1400s. Sometime in the century after this one it should hit its own Reformation crisis. It's possible that the Western liberals I expect to convert to Islam will contribute to that, but it'll be an indirect influence. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59609940", "title": "Re: Religion, alienation, and the turning of an age.", "date": "2026-03-16 07:50 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "After years of feeling an at times quite strong pull to reengage with Catholicism or even turn to orthodoxy, I have noticed recently that it has disappeared. The place in my inner world where it used to be feels like it has been swept clean and even the idea seems somehow silly. The stories, images and symbols no longer move me. Strange, liberating and also scary to take tentative, wobbly steps towards what is mine to discover...<br/><br/>Mike", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59611220", "title": "Re: Religion, alienation, and the turning of an age.", "date": "2026-03-16 08:45 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's become increasingly common in recent years, as I noted in a blog post quite a while ago: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/death-god-speculation/\">https://www.ecosophia.net/death-god-speculation/</a><br/><br/>Nor is it unexpected. Consider Matthew 28:20: \"And behold, I am with you always, even unto the ending of the age.\" In Greek, that last phrase is ἕως τῆς συντελείας τοῦ αἰῶνος. literally \"even until the completion of the aeon.\" As the Piscean aeon comes to an end and the Aquarian aeon begins, it's to be expected that the energies of the Christian revelation would fade out to make room for the next influx. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59629140", "title": "Re: Religion, alienation, and the turning of an age.", "date": "2026-03-17 01:09 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "Could the Aquarian Age bring small scale violent battles within sects, and religious wars of coalitions of sects that agree to disagree on a lot of theology but see one issue (spiritual OR secular) as worth shedding blood over?<br/><br/>Also, since most people are not creative, won't there be lots of sects teaching the same mainstream spiritual view while claiming they're unique by emphasizing one or two quirks?<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59634004", "title": "Re: Religion, alienation, and the turning of an age.", "date": "2026-03-17 02:28 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "We'll just have to wait and see. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59591252", "title": "Double-Checking Prayer Process", "date": "2026-03-16 04:01 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I am hoping to move towards a more spiritual life, and part of this is that I want to add prayer to my routine. For now, I plan to pray to the planet of the day, with the idea being that I want to gradually form a relationship with them.<br/><br/>Here's my current idea:<br/><br/>a) Spend a moment each evening calming and clearing my mind.<br/><br/>b) Recite the Orphic Hymn to the planet.<br/><br/>c) Give a free form prayer; it might be expressing gratitude, asking advice, just speaking whatever happens to be on my mind related to that planet's domain.<br/><br/>d) Stop and listen for a moment and see if I get a response.<br/><br/>Does this sound like it would be a workable way to get started with prayer? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59597908", "title": "Re: Double-Checking Prayer Process", "date": "2026-03-16 05:00 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That sounds like a very good idea. I'd suggest making that last phase a little longer; have a chair nearby, sit down, and spend five minutes or so listening inwardly. It may take a little while for the signal to come in clearly. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59595348", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 04:38 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,<br/><br/>I notice after doing a magical ceremony that I can get a little spacey, and sometimes I will have trouble falling asleep that night, I'll get restless. Is there any good way to handle this? Why does this happen?<br/><br/>Many thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59598164", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 05:01 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's one of the reasons I don't recommend doing magic last thing before bed! It's quite easy to charge your etheric body with life force, which will tend to keep you awake. Some people find that eating a little food will help ground them before sleep. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59599700", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 05:32 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks! My mistake, I should have specified that I always do my magical work first thing in the morning before breakfast. It's just that, maybe 4 times out of 5, I'll have some trouble falling asleep that night. Eating breakfast seems to help with the spaciness after a while. Maybe my etheric body is sensitive? I get mood swings and restlessness (or the other extreme) around full moons. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59603540", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 06:32 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm! I don't think I've encountered anyone who's had that experience, so I'm not at all sure what to suggest. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59601748", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 06:20 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm just going to note that some people (such as myself) find food within a few hours of sleep can cause digestive or respiratory health problems, as a word of caution for anyone who wishes to try spiritual practices and then eating right before bed.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59603796", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 06:34 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "So noted and thank you for this. I'm quite the opposite -- a little food before bed generally helps me sleep more soundly. Of course I also find strong green tea relaxing and soporific, and tend to sleep very well after drinking it, but that's common enough with people who have ADD. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59637076", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-17 03:32 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I also find tea puts me to sleep; drinking things before bed doesn't cause me problems. It's specifically food that causes me a problem."}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59602516", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 06:24 pm", "user": "open_space", "content": "You didn't ask me but this is what works for me. <br/><br/>Prayer works for this, in its repetitive variety though not exactly because of it's intended purpose. Repetitive action puts the rational mind to sleep as the brain focuses on keeping a rhythm. That's why its easy to fall asleep while doing it and several tricks have been to be devised to keep people awake! This also helps because if you go to sleep with the rational mind still active, you don't rest, it remains active even if you are asleep (this is why people with anxiety report sleeping but not resting). I sometimes use the rosary for this because I know the Virgin doesn't mind and also she tends to be caring so that also signals the mind to start shutting off.<br/><br/>Another way of doing it is controlled breathing. Try this, sit in a comfortable position, back straight unsupported and cross your feet at the ankles, right over left. Fold the index and middle finger if your right hand and keep the others extended. You will use the little and anular finger to block the left nostril and the thumb to close the right nostril.  Keep the left hand on your lap facing upwards. For the process itself, close your eyes and block the right nostril with your thumb, inhale deeply hold for a moment and exhale through the same nostril. Then you switch and block the left nostril with the little and anular finger and open the right nostril to do the same. Inhale and exhale from the same nostril, and switch. You can do this as much as you like. You only need to remember two things, you always switch after an exhalation and you breath as slowly as it is possible for you without having to gasp or break the stream of breathing. If you are able to focus on the breath without allowing the mind to keep agitating things you will start to get relaxed in 10-15 minutes. <br/><br/>This last is called the cleansing breath and it works by using excess energy to clean your energy body so it's both healthy and relaxing. There are two big pipes in the energy body linked to the nostrils, by doing it slowly it would be like cleaning and releasing the pressure of a pipe by opening the valves and having water go up and down. This is also safe with ceremonial magic because it doesn't force the energy towards the other energy pathways and it also focuses you back into the body. <br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59610964", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 08:35 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you, I've bookmarked your tips!"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59599444", "title": "Relationship Divination", "date": "2026-03-16 05:10 pm", "user": "davidp", "content": "Hey JMG,<br/><br/>I'd like to once again ask for your help regarding divination with the SGO. Some weeks ago, to recap, I prayed to Freyja for some advice about my love life (or lack thereof) and, to my surprise, dreamt the entire night about a friend. As I hadn't thought about her that way before, I consulted the oracle and decided that this was more complex than \"you should romantically pursue her\" because the card I pulled for a relationship between us was Limitation.<br/><br/>Unfortunately, there was no way to put the genie back into its bottle and now I <em>am</em> thinking about her that way. So, naturally, I started wondering whether Limitation was a firm no or even a no at all or whether I just misinterpreted it, ranging from \"it wouldn't be everything you're hoping for\" to contortions like \"our relationship right now is limited to being platonic.\"<br/><br/>I wanted more clarity and so I pulled another spread yesterday:<br/><br/>Me: The Pentagram: Power<br/>Her: The Double Square reversed: Risk<br/>A relationship between us: The Unmarked Card reversed: Hiddenness<br/>What does Hiddenness mean?: The Sphere reversed: Unknowability<br/><br/>(By the way, \"Unknowability\" isn't printed upside down on the card, which seems like one of those mistakes you wanted to fix in the new edition you were thinking about.)<br/><br/>1) Was this an advisable way to go about this situation? I know I'm skirting dangerously close to \"I don't like the cards, so I'll just pull another spread.\"<br/><br/>2) Are clarification questions like the fourth card a good strategy? I'm pretty sure I've always pulled a card that feels pretty close to the one I'm asking about, which makes sense but also doesn't seem too helpful.<br/><br/>3) My interpretation would be that it's just impossible to say what might or might not happen between us at this point (Hiddenness and Unknowability). I'd read this with a slightly positive spin because the Power to bring about a desired outcome lies with me. I'm both less happy and less sure about Risk; perhaps she would be taking a risk? But what? Alternatively, our friendship might be at risk here.<br/><br/>Does that make sense? Would you read this differently?<br/><br/>—David P.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59604052", "title": "Re: Relationship Divination", "date": "2026-03-16 06:37 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It's entirely appropriate to use a second spread to cast light on the first one, so long as you don't see the second as neutralizing the first. <br/><br/>2) I do that kind of thing all the time. <br/><br/>3) My interpretation is different. Right now there's no potential for a relationship, and it's uncertain when or if that will change; there are risks involved, but if you wait, things may move in a romantic direction. In the meantime, keep your mouth shut and behave toward her as you would toward a friend. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59607380", "title": "Re: Relationship Divination", "date": "2026-03-16 07:10 pm", "user": "davidp", "content": "Thank you. That certainly sounds like a safe option, even if not necessarily what I was hoping to hear.<br/><br/>—David P."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59600212", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 05:53 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "I've been having enough memories from a 19th century past life return that I think I know who I was then. Rather than merely assume, I cast a geomantic chart (asking, \"Was I such-and-such\"). Here are the results:<br/><br/>Judge: Fortuna Major<br/>First Witness: Puella<br/>Second Witness: Laetitia <br/><br/>Reconciler: Caput Draconis<br/><br/>First Mother: Rubeus<br/>Second Mother: Populus<br/>Third Mother: Amissio<br/>Fourth Mother: Acquisitio<br/><br/>First Daughter: Albus<br/>Second Daughter: Carcer<br/>Third Daughter: Albus<br/>Fourth Daughter: Tristitia<br/><br/>First Niece: Rubeus<br/>Second Niece: Via<br/>Third Niece: Puella<br/>Fourth Niece: Fortuna Major<br/><br/>I have an interpretation of this (as my divination skills have gotten better) but since it involves an important question, I'd like to ask how you'd interpret the results.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59604308", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 06:40 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The court is a very strong positive. On the other hand, Rubeus as the first mother indicates that you're lying to yourself in at least some ways, or that you aren't going to listen to what the divination says no matter what it says. I tend to treat reincarnation as a 9th house question, in which case you've got another strong \"yes\" because the chart perfects by occupation. Be very careful, though, because Rubeus as the figure making the perfection warns of dangers; in particular, I'd be very slow to mention your apparent past life identity to anyone at all. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59609172", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 07:29 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "I’m very hesitant to mention it. No one particularly grand but I had my doubts about it when I cast the chart."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59600980", "title": "Personal Pseudomorphosis", "date": "2026-03-16 06:04 pm", "user": "isaac_hill", "content": "It was quite interesting to hear your discussion with Nick Land last night, looking forward to more, it seemed like it was more him interviewing you, and you both seemed to agree on a lot more than I would have thought. I think personally, by the way he was asking questions, that he may agree more with you than he may even let on. But, anyway,<br/><br/>Speaking of Spengler, I have been thinking about my personal exploration and practice of spiritual systems as something like pseudomorphoses. With the self-inquiry tradition of Richard Rose, which I see as sort of my base system, then Heathen esotericism, Buddhist meditation, Astrological magic, Heathen Golden Dawn, and now this Vedic lineage (which I'm in my 4th year of study). I have gone deeply into each of these, for several years of intensive practice each. I notice that each system has profoundly changed the way I perceive and relate to reality. I find, especially in the Vedic lineage, as it is more foreign to me, I am learning more of a \"way of thinking\" - \"tools not truths\". I also realize this kind of process is not for everybody, and is also perhaps only possible in the kind of age we are currenttly living in (similar to the last change of astrological age) As an American, born into an infant culture, I kind of feel like I'm doing a pseudomorphosis in the microcosm, does this make sense to you?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59605332", "title": "Re: Personal Pseudomorphosis", "date": "2026-03-16 06:54 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) We have different visions of history but both are founded on similar epistemologies -- that is, we both realize that human beings have no access to objective reality, we both understand that the world inhabited by human beings is constructed from mythic narratives, and we both have some sense of the ways that the narrative universe can be shaped by what we may as well call magic. That's a lot of common ground! Land is more or less committed to an apocalyptic narrative, and I'm at least as firmly committed to an antiapocalyptic narrative, but we can easily bracket those differences and talk about subjects where our takes cast light on each other. <br/><br/>2) That's one of the essential roles of intellectuals in any culture. Their personal pseudomorphoses may come from the past -- think of English scholars in the 18th century learning Greek and Latin -- or from other cultures -- think of their descendants a century later grappling with Sanskrit literature -- but that process of absorbing outside perspectives is an important part of how every culture ripens its intellectual heritage. "}, {"id": "cmt59614548", "title": "Re: Personal Pseudomorphosis", "date": "2026-03-16 09:28 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Richard Rose founded the TAT Foundation, is that right? Does that tradition go in the direction of non-dualism?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59618132", "title": "Re: Personal Pseudomorphosis", "date": "2026-03-16 10:00 pm", "user": "isaac_hill", "content": "Yes, I've been involved with TAT since I was in college. It definitely goes in the direction of non-dualism, but it's very different than the modern neo-advaita stuff. His teaching was very influenced by Gurdjieff, Zen, Ramana Maharshi, Esoteric Christianity, Magic, and Gnosticism (he called his first book \"The Albigen Papers\" after the Cathars.) ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59624020", "title": "Re: Personal Pseudomorphosis", "date": "2026-03-17 12:08 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The thought of a nondualist Catharism makes my head hurt...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59631700", "title": "Re: Personal Pseudomorphosis", "date": "2026-03-17 02:02 am", "user": "isaac_hill", "content": "To be fair, I don't know how much of a Cathar he actually was, though he probably was one in a past life. <br/><br/>He had a pretty grim view of the material world, and the Powers in control, in many ways, but the nondual teachings came out of a direct experience he had at age 30 that took him some years to recover from. He was a very interesting person; a hard-working West Virginian who built his own house, raised goats, and shot back at the local hillbillies who didn't like the hippies that would visit him on his farm (there was a court battle about it that he won, self-defense.) He also had some psychic powers and would perform exorcisms and healings. I'd consider him a special kind of American saint. "}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59605076", "title": "Lesson About Black Humor", "date": "2026-03-16 06:54 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "As severe storms were sweeping across the midstate, I joked (as I always do) about the storm hitting <i>other</i> people. It slightly danaged the building in which I work. So I have to stop making those kinds of jokes.<br/><br/>Patrick H<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59605588", "title": "Re: Lesson About Black Humor", "date": "2026-03-16 06:55 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The storm spirits have a rough sense of humor, and it's best not to give them the opportunity to make you the butt of one of their jokes! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59621972", "title": "Re: Lesson About Black Humor", "date": "2026-03-16 11:51 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "It didn't affect me, but it did inconvience other people. They granted my joking wish.<br/><br/>Patrick H"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59608148", "title": "Astrology books", "date": "2026-03-16 07:15 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello, JMG. I’d like to learn Horary Astrology and Mundane Astrology. What books would you recommend? I’m most familiar with natal astrology. What I’m most interested in learning in these fields is how to find answers to questions like, “What’s currently happening in the heavens, and how might that affect people in a given area?”", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59612244", "title": "Re: Astrology books", "date": "2026-03-16 08:51 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The book that made horary astrology make sense to me was <i>Simplified Horary Astrology</i> by Ivy Goldstein-Jacobson. It's out of print but can be found in the used book market. As for mundane astrology, why, my book <i>The Astrology of Nations</i> is a good introduction to that subject. "}, {"id": "cmt59615060", "title": "Re: Astrology books", "date": "2026-03-16 09:35 pm", "user": "ivn66", "content": "You didn't ask me, but I'd like to chime in an say that I've gotten an astonishing amount of mileage out of John Frawley's <i>The Horary Textbook</i>."}]}, {"id": "cmt59608916", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 07:21 pm", "user": "jflylynn", "content": "Mr Greer forgive me for posting twice. <br/><br/>Have you written anything about or know about the real between song and prayer? I find myself singing prayers more than speaking them and often breaking into song because of spiritual turmoil or joy alternately. I don’t know if this is the best approach to prayer but it has certainly been my most successful. <br/><br/>JL", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59612500", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 08:58 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I haven't written anything about that, no. If it works for you, on the other hand, that's all you need to know. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59610196", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 07:53 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Question about karma and reincarnation: what happens to the hard-wired sociopath - no heart, no soul, rather like a human shark. <br/><br/>The Grey Badger", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59612756", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 08:59 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "He or she gets slammed face first into his or her own nasty karma, life after life, until raw pain finally gets the message across. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59622228", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 11:58 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "What if the sociopath has a Body of Fate of success or triumph in his next incarnation? <br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59622740", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-17 12:03 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Then he succeeds at the cost of having his face slammed repeatedly into his own nasty karma. Success and horrible suffering are in no way opposed to each other. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59614036", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 09:22 pm", "user": "ivn66", "content": "Hello JMG et al - <br/><br/>Just commenting here to let everyone know I've resumed offering horary astrology consultations free of charge, to help myself practice and to offer this service as a thanks to the commentariat, over on my own Dreamwidth profile. For the recent past I've been laid up first with a nasty bout of food poisoning and then with a sinus infection, but am happy to report I'm feeling better and can resume my regular activity. Should any of you have a question to which you'd like to seek an answer in the heavens, I'll be available every day this week. <br/><br/>PS: to the commenter who came to me with a question about faucets and seems since to have deleted it, please accept my apologies. I first saw your question on a tablet device of mine and evidently didn't have a pen and paper around to note the date and time, so I simply took a screenshot of the question. In the time between then and my recovering from these recent illnesses, my tablet's bitten the dust and I have no way of recovering the proper date and time and so am unable to generate a chart for your question. If you'd like to come ask something else, you're welcome to do so anytime. <br/><br/>PPS - JMG, I was delighted and quite surprised to discover your conversation with Mr. Land over on Twitter and equally shocked to discover it wasn't some kind of prank, but quite pleased to listen to it. Thanks for doing that.", "edit_time": "2026-03-16 09:23 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59616596", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 09:45 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're most welcome. I was delighted to have the chance -- I disagree with Land about a great many things but I'd be the first to acknowledge that he's one of the most interesting and philosophically literate thinkers in the occult scene. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59614292", "title": "Elen of the Ways", "date": "2026-03-16 09:23 pm", "user": "scottyc", "content": "Not a question, but an observation to share.<br/><br/>When researching the Druid Revival goddess, Elen of the Roads I've noticed she's becoming popular in spiritual circles and maybe a little too mainstream, meaning that it is easy to find people selling images of her online and even small statuettes. <br/><br/>I won't criticize that but I try to encounter her by working on creativity and trying to draw her.  I'm a terrible artist so I'll have many opportunities to draw before I'm done. <br/><br/>"}, {"id": "cmt59615572", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 09:41 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've recently realized something unsettling: there's a very good case to be made that the people who created the Magician States knew what they were doing. I recently did a dive into the history of the telecommunications industry, and found that much of it ties back to Lord Kitchener, David Sarnoff, and George Creel. Essentially, these three people created the modern propaganda state, and everyone else copied them. Kitchener proved its power by using posters and cinema to convince the public to violently oppose the pacifist movement and to boost military recruiting; Creel demonstrated its power to shape public opinion by convincing millions of Americans to abandon their prior views and embrace a military invention when, mere months earlier public opinion was opposed to it, all while the president had campaigned on keeping the country out of the war; and after the war, Sarnoff leveraged the new technology of radio to create a massive business empire based on broadcasting advertising to the masses.<br/><br/>All three of them have ties to occultism: Sarnoff spent years being raised by a Rabbi who lived in Minsk when that was a hotbed of Jewish Kabbalah (and spent much of his life doing everything he could to hide the identity of said Rabbi and what he learned there); Lord Kitchner learned Arabic while living in Egypt and became a collector of old books, and upon his death it appears that a number of Arabic occult books were in his library, including the Picatrix; and George Creel published Rosicrucian works (such as Quatrains of Christ) prior to his involvement in the Committee on Public Relations.<br/><br/>I've read Eros and Magic in the Renaissance, and will read the Hounds of Actaeon in the next few weeks, but those books are on the links between the system and occultism; not between any of the individuals who played a key role in creating it and occultism. Do you know if anyone else has explored possible links between key figures in the early history of mass media and occultism?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59616852", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 09:47 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't know of any such study, but it's a fascinating subject and could use some serious research. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59616084", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 09:42 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey JMG <br/><br/>This is going to be a bit unusual, but can you tell me what the planetary and elementary correspondence of the swan is? I assume that it is solar, and either water or air, but I’m not 100% sure.<br/><br/>The reason I ask is because I’m trying to figure out the significance of an unusual symbol I came up with a year or so ago. I was in a cafe, and the waitress handed me a cappuccino that had the image of a swan on its foam, which surprised me due to how weirdly plant-like its form was. I tried to take a picture of it with my phone, but I couldn’t because its storage was full, so when I got home I started drawing it from memory. I inevitably embellished it, making it more obviously plant-like, and called this odd symbol the “vegetable swan”, after the mythical vegetable sheep.<br/><br/> I have a sense that there is some theme of striving for a higher level of existence within this symbol, as I interpret it as a plant that is trying to mold itself into a being that is more autonomous and powerful than it is, a bird. But I must meditate on it more, and learn more about the symbolic significance of swans to get a good idea of what it really means.<br/><br/>J.L.Mc12", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59617108", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 09:50 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "William Lilly, whose attributions I tend to trust, assigns the swan to the Sun. I don't find an elemental correspondence in the sources immediately available to me but air would be more likely than water. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59617620", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 09:52 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks, so I was right in my assumption.<br/><br/>Do you have any of your own ideas about what this “vegetable swan” could represent? <br/><br/>J.L.Mc12", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59617876", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 09:53 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "None whatsoever. I assume you've already taken it as a theme for meditation. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59619156", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 10:20 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yes, I’ll be doing my second meditation on it today. 4 sessions is the minimum needed to understand a symbol isn’t it?<br/><br/>J.L.Mc12"}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59622996", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-17 12:03 am", "user": "randomactsofkarmasc", "content": "I don't know if this helps, but Oswald Wirth linked the Swan constellation with the Judgment card (in Tarot).<br/><br/>I have not studied Agrippa, but have read some excerpts when I was researching other things.  Swans are one of the consecrated birds.  <a href=\"https://www.esotericarchives.com/agrippa/agripp2b.htm\">https://www.esotericarchives.com/agrippa/agripp2b.htm</a> <br/><br/>And swans are sometimes featured in alchemical drawings.  (My interpretation is that they represent the transition from Nigredo to Albedo, since young swans are grey and then change to white as adults.)  (And, yes, some species don't do that, but that's the best interpretation I've come up with so far. ;-) ) <br/><br/>Perhaps your vegetable swan has to do with spagyrics?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59624788", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-17 12:14 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks for this, this will definitely give me more to work with.<br/><br/>J.L.Mc12"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59618644", "title": "To find a new house", "date": "2026-03-16 10:14 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I need to find a new place for my family to live. My current landlords are unwilling to fix anything properly and stuff is falling apart intolerably. I also think there's a mold problem here. The economy and housing market the past few years are the main reasons why I've stayed here this long, but it's getting to where remaining here is negatively impacting our physical and mental health.<br/><br/>So, I'm looking for ideas/techniques that folks use when they really need to find a new place to live.<br/><br/>In terms of electional astrology, what aspects should I look for in terms of a good day to begin my search?<br/><br/>I don't do formal magic but get good results with folk magic so those types of suggestions are also welcome. I'm also interested in hearing anything folks do that works for them. <br/><br/>Thanks,<br/><br/>FSH", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59624532", "title": "Re: To find a new house", "date": "2026-03-17 12:11 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The day and hour of Saturn is traditional for seeking a new home, especially if you hope to stay there for a long time. Begin looking at that time. You might also make three donations, each of some multiple of $3, to a charity that helps homeless people find homes -- that's a Saturnine charity and it's also an act of sympathetic magic. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59632724", "title": "Re: To find a new house", "date": "2026-03-17 02:17 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Excellent! Thank you so much.<br/><br/>FSH<br/>"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59620436", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-16 11:07 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Can homeopathic gold be added to the condensed fluid when making paper astrological talismans? I thought I saw that in one of your MM replies a while back. To make a long lasting paper astro talisman would one add colloidal gold to the boiled plants/herbs fluid that the water color paper would be painted with? If so, would there be certain talismans not to use homeopathic gold with? (I'm thinking Mars or Saturn). Thank you for this forum.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59625044", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-17 12:14 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Yes. <br/><br/>2) No, because all the influences of the planets are a function of their interaction with the Sun's aura (which extends throughout the solar system, and all the way out to the heliopause out beyond Pluto). For that reason gold, the Sun's metal, is compatible with all planetary influences. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59623252", "title": "Copper Pyramids", "date": "2026-03-17 12:06 am", "user": "randomactsofkarmasc", "content": "A while back, I asked about a copper pyramid I sat in/under at an event I went to.  Nobody (at the time) seemed to be able to explain why the energy felt different in/under the pyramid.  Lots of ideas were bandied about.  The most intriguing (to me) was the potential of interacting with the solar wind or solar flares.<br/><br/>I did some research and learned that solar wind interact with Earth's magnetic field, but not just in a planet-sized way.  The solar wind reacts with the atmosphere (creating electrojets).  The thickness of the crust and the composition of the crust affect how much the electrojets are attracted (so using data from an existing magnetometer station wouldn't necessarily correlate to what was happening at my location).  And magnetometers are rather pricey, so I wasn't going to buy one just to experiment with.<br/><br/>But then NASA announced they were doing a citizen-science project, to get ground-level magnetometer readings to compare with their in-space radiation readings.  I applied and was accepted.  I have done a very small experiment (as I do not want to contaminate their data), comparing readings from the magnetometer with a small rectangle of copper wire around it, then with a small rectangle of copper wire with two more wires connecting opposite corners reaching over the top of the meter (an attempt at a pyramid), and then a reading with all the wires just piled on top of the meter.<br/><br/>Short version, any configuration of copper around or over the magnetometer seems to lower the overall magnetic field.  This seems to be due to blocking solar radiation, as the Earth's magnetic field is considered static.  (It changes, but very slowly.)<br/><br/>I found one article that describes how humans react to unchanging magnetic fields:  <a href=\"https://maglab.caltech.edu/human-magnetic-reception-laboratory/\">https://maglab.caltech.edu/human-magnetic-reception-laboratory/</a>  TL;DR:  Humans have magnetite in their brain which detect magnetic fields.  Fixed (unchanging) fields increase alpha waves, associated with a relaxed mind not focused on a stimulus.  <br/><br/>No question, just wanted to share.  :-)<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59625300", "title": "Re: Copper Pyramids", "date": "2026-03-17 12:15 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good heavens. I remember when \"pyramid power\" was all the rage, back in the 1970s, and people built pyramids to meditate in. "}, {"id": "cmt59631444", "title": "Re: Copper Pyramids", "date": "2026-03-17 01:41 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You can look at the table in the Wikipedia articles for \"magnetic susceptibility\" and \"diamagnetism\" for other materials to try. Copper has a diamagnetic effect opposite of that of iron and about half a billionth the strength. I have less intuition for this than I should, but I would expect copper to push magnetic field lines away sideways, so that even a static magnetic field would be (slightly) weaker when the detector was in line along the field lines with (or surrounded by) the copper, and (slightly) stronger when the detector was off to one side from the copper relative to the field lines."}]}, {"id": "cmt59625556", "title": "Fae", "date": "2026-03-17 12:18 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I’m curious if you’ve ever worked with the Fae? Do you have any book recommendations, if someone were to be interested in them?<br/><br/>I’ve seen some faerie magic books around, mostly new age shops, or mixed in with certain neopagan practices … I wonder how much of it is legit, and how much is inspired by Hollywood style fantasy fluff. <br/><br/>A lot of the folklore from the old world takes a very cautious approach to the faerie world. <br/><br/>And my final question, with humor - Are the fae our modern day aliens? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59628116", "title": "Re: Fae", "date": "2026-03-17 12:43 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) No, and I don't recommend doing so. They are as intelligent as we are, and have long and bitter grudges against us. You might see if you can find Rev. Robert Kirk's <i>The Secret Commonwealth</i>, a very good 17th-century study of the fae. <br/><br/>2) Yes, and I mean that without a bit of humor. Jacques Vallee's book <i>Passport to Magonia</i>, a neglected classic of UFO literature, showed that \"aliens\" are simply the latest guise taken by the fae. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59631188", "title": "Re: Fae", "date": "2026-03-17 01:40 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "Indeed, I've discussed this before. There's no mistaking the parallels between stories about UFO and the Fey/fair folk: ethereal beings, vessels that play fast &amp; loose with physics, abduction, time dilation, a strange nonhuman morality, and of course, the danger of consuming any of their food &amp; drink, lest you be unable to return to normal life. So yes, it's safe to say that the whole thing of aliens/UFOs/greys/etc is really just the Fey up to their usual tricks, trolling us as always.<br/><br/>As to that bit about \"long and bitter grudges\", I find that rather sad. I'd rather get along with my fellow sentients, different as they may be. Then again, my fellow humans have made an absolute mess of the environment, with their blundering, arrogant violence &amp; extraction. So, that probably explains the grudge, but are there other reasons? Is there any chance of a peace treaty, or will that have to wait for a future society that uses modern technology while striking a much better balance with the environment?<br/><br/>One more question, if I may ask: can a soul incarnate between the Fey &amp; human race, or are we on separate spiritual paths?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59632980", "title": "Re: Fae", "date": "2026-03-17 02:20 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I have no idea whether the fae are open to peace negotiations. So far there hasn't been any movement in that direction. <br/><br/>2) We are on separate paths, but every so often a soul strays across the boundary. Dion Fortune talks about that in a few of her essays, discussing fae who get born in a human body. Presumably the reverse also happens. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59625812", "title": "Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-17 12:18 am", "user": "kylec", "content": "Apologies for the late post. I'm offering healing hands as usual this week. Just reply here or PM me your name and request. Thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59630676", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-17 01:32 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yes, I would like healing hands this week.<br/><br/>Thank you very much, as always,<br/>Brad"}, {"id": "cmt59634772", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-17 02:36 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yes please! It's adrenal fatigue with related issues. The name is Kevin. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59628884", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-17 01:01 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG, you wrote \"we stand at the hinge between two great ages of the world\" and \"we’re in for a massive cascade of transformations in the years ahead\" re the Sat Nep conjunction at 0 Aries. <br/><br/>I know that it's too early to predict how the war against Iran will pan out but I seems to me that dinosaurs like Trump and Lindsay Graham who believe the US can bludgeon anything in its way, are in for a shock. Also there is very little popular support for this war, unlike the Iraq war.  I feel the outcome of this war is the start of something very significant and the world will change completely. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59634260", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-17 02:30 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Maybe so, but it really is too early to say. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59629396", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-17 01:11 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/><br/>What do you use to burn incense when you use it? For example, do you use charcoal? Thanks for your help.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59634516", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-17 02:31 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I use charcoal for loose incense, but I also like stick incense, in particular the nearly smokeless Japanese incense. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59629652", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-17 01:18 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "i just saw this article and thought i would share it here..<br/>it does seem to me a bit of strange magic in a way..:<br/><br/>Peter Thiel to present his Antichrist lectures in Rome this week<br/><br/>https://www.lifesitenews.com/news/peter-thiel-to-present-his-antichrist-lectures-in-rome-this-week/", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59635028", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-17 02:36 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That Thiel thinks he has the theological qualifications to say anything relevant about the Antichrist makes my eyes roll so hard I think I glimpsed my pineal gland. "}, {"id": "cmt59639892", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-17 03:56 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "For those who haven't seen it, here's Scott Alexander clapping back, reporting (not in so many words) that the contemporary entity requiring the fewest strained metaphors and linguistic stretched interpretations to declare to be the Antichrist is not as Thiel claims the opponents of technology like AI existential risk activists, but instead clearly the AI company Anthropic. (Most strikingly, \"the number of the beast is the number of a man\" could instead be rendered as \"the bestial headcount is the anthropic headcount\".)<br/><br/>https://www.astralcodexten.com/p/my-antichrist-lecture", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59640916", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-17 04:02 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That is to say, we're back to the Antichrist-of-the-Month Club. Bah! "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59630420", "title": "freedom from mandates", "date": "2026-03-17 01:23 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG,<br/><br/>Hello. I live in a state that is considering enacting laws that take away parental rights to claim conscientious exemptions from required vaccinations for school-age children, both for those attending school and even for those being homeschooled.<br/><br/>My daughter is five years old.  I would like her to be free of vaccine mandates.  I would also like to stay living in the state where I am (even though I revile some of the political currents here). <br/><br/>I understand that doing political magic isn't a good idea, but as I mentioned, I want my daughter to be free of the mandates and would like to do something to support this in addition to writing to my state senator.<br/><br/>Wondering if you might please offer suggestions for magical working to help this happen.  I have completed Learning Ritual Magic and am working through Circles of Power.  I am wondering about making a talisman (perhaps Jupiter or Mercury) or perhaps doing planetary charity?<br/><br/>Wondering also about my statement of intent:  My daughter_________ is free of vaccine mandates and able to attend school or homeschool in the state of______<br/><br/>Thank you.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59635284", "title": "Re: freedom from mandates", "date": "2026-03-17 02:37 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nope. Political magic is a bad idea. Your best bet is to relocate. "}, {"id": "cmt59640148", "title": "Re: freedom from mandates", "date": "2026-03-17 03:58 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You might see about getting nasal-spray vaccines. Those might still give you ADE but not the other systemic stuff."}]}, {"id": "cmt59631956", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-17 02:07 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good evening and thank you as always. <br/><br/>Is there a (relatively) straightforward way to etherically project without an animal form as in the GD ritual? It seems like most of the benefits of etheric projection would still be available without an alternate form. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59635540", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-17 02:38 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't know of a method for doing so. There may be one, but I haven't encountered it. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59636308", "title": "Reading", "date": "2026-03-17 03:24 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "For a question asking if my higher self or guardian angel sent those cigarette synchronities I got a couple weeks back, I got:<br/><br/>LW:Gwyn<br/>RW: Mab<br/>Judge: Ffordd<br/><br/>What is your interpretation?<br/><br/>(For external entities, I got a null answer.)<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59637844", "title": "Re: Reading", "date": "2026-03-17 03:37 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Mab is unfavorable, Gwyn is favorable, and Ffordd is a mixed bag. I'd read this as \"kinda sorta, but not really.\" You are jumping to conclusions; let the process play out, and you'll figure it out in due time. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59639380", "title": "Re: Reading", "date": "2026-03-17 03:52 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "If it wasn't an outside entity and might not be my Higher Self or guardian angel, what are some other possibilities for how those synchronities could arise? Maybe my Higher Self triggered the wrong events while intending to send me some sort of indication?<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59639636", "title": "Re: Reading", "date": "2026-03-17 03:53 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The universe is a very busy place and it's full of countless beings and forces. Any of them could be involved in generating synchronicities. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59640404", "title": "Re: Reading", "date": "2026-03-17 03:59 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "So even a point-blank question on whether an external entity generated the synchronities might not be able to detect all those possible outside entities and forces?<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59640660", "title": "Re: Reading", "date": "2026-03-17 04:01 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You'd have to already know enough to be able to interpret the reading. "}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"title": "Magic Monday", "url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/363289.html", "year": "2026", "month": "03", "day": "22", "time": "10-29PM", "comments": [{"id": "cmt59668505", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 04:06 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG, thanks for another Magic Monday!<br/><br/>• So last week I read here about developing the mental body through the use of Discursive Meditation. Would that be the equivalent of what other traditions describe as uniting the ego with the \"immortal spark,\" getting one's current memories/continuity of being a \"foothold\" in the beyond? Where in your work is this kind of use for Discursive Meditation described, in the golden section book? Celtic Golden Dawn? The druidry ones?<br/><br/>Thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59668761", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 04:26 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) In the system of occult philosophy I use and teach, we already have a foothold in the Beyond; we're just not conscious of it yet. The Individuality, the part of us that endures from life to life, is the real self of each of us; the personality is a mask. Here's how my teacher John Gilbert liked to explain it: <br/><br/>\"Jack and Jill were called into the office one day. They were told that because of cutbacks they were being laid off. But if they wanted to wear an animal costume, they would not only stay on the payroll, they would receive an increase in salary and a big bonus in one year.<br/><br/>\"They looked over the options. Jack decided to wear the bear costume and Jill decided to wear the eagle costume. Both costumes fit just fine. The only problem was that they were literally sewn into their costumes and had to wear them 24/7. They could attend to their daily chores, eat and drink, but they were unable to leave their costumes for the duration. Hence the large bonus they both looked forward to receiving.<br/><br/>\"Neither Jack nor Jill was able to shave but they could brush their teeth and continue to kiss each other among other things. All in all, it turned out to be a pretty good arrangement for them except for one little problem. The problem was that after a couple of months Jack considered himself to be a bear and Jill thought she was an eagle. Their minds had shifted from being a human in a costume to being the costume.<br/><br/>\"So it is with our soul. Our soul decides to incarnate in a physical body, and so it does. The next thing you know, our soul begins to believe it is our body. It forgets it is a soul in a body and it begins to believe it is the body.<br/><br/>\"The great secret: We are our soul. Our soul is us. We have always been our soul and we still are. In our ignorance we came to believe we are our ego, our personas and our body. But we are still our soul. We're just wearing a costume with many faces.<br/><br/>\"We are, all of us, a soul walking around in a three-layered costume. The outermost layer is our physical body, brain and our many personas. The next layer is our ego and the emotions and mind that comes with it. Our inner layer is our soul itself. But it turns out this is just a costume worn by our eternal spirit.\" <br/><br/>2) None of my books dwell on it because it's not something that benefits from conscious attention. Practice meditation regularly and things will unfold of themselves. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59670809", "title": "Is there a second option?", "date": "2026-03-23 05:18 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>After reading your reply, I wondered:<br/><br/>What if Jack and Jill decided to accept the pink slip and be laid off?  That is to say, can (some?) souls choose not to incarnate in a physical body?  Or are (some?) souls not allowed to go AWOL?<br/><br/>Thank you,<br/>-E.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59674905", "title": "Re: Is there a second option?", "date": "2026-03-23 02:11 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "According to some accounts, a very long time ago, souls had that choice: descend into material incarnation, accepting its terrible limitations in exchange for the opportunity to grow and develop in new ways, or stay out of incarnation and remain unchanged. Once you enter the wheel of incarnation, though, you're caught; it's possible to step off the wheel for a while, but sooner or later your karma will drag you back in, until finally you resolve it all and rise to another level of being. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59677209", "title": "Re: Is there a second option?", "date": "2026-03-23 02:29 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "Wouldn't the soul be too primitive before absorbing experiences from the wheel of incarnation to have the ability to choose anything?<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59680025", "title": "Re: Is there a second option?", "date": "2026-03-23 03:15 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good question. The traditions I cited don't discuss that. "}, {"id": "cmt59686425", "title": "Re: Is there a second option?", "date": "2026-03-23 04:41 pm", "user": "scottyc", "content": "Maybe not.  A possibility exists that our souls had developed to a high degree but we were always \"easily promoted\" at least enough to be aware and to make significant choices.  What could \"easily promoted\" mean?  At least not deal with material incarnation and deal with Yeats' Wheel... An analogy may be resigning from a pretty good job with great benefits and accept a difficult position in return for future growth or experiences (e.g. George Orwell resigning from Imperial Service in Burma and eventually, winding up, Down and Out in London and Paris)."}, {"id": "cmt59729689", "title": "Re: Is there a second option?", "date": "2026-03-24 04:06 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I think Fortune answers some of this with her symbolism (which exists to train our minds, not to inform them). We are awakened/initiated to a certain degree by the relevant Lord of Mind, on their descent through the planes. So this incarnation business was sort of locked in really, but we are taken out of \"sleep\" to have a limited awareness. This much the aborigines of Australia got right - their philosophy is based around the dream time. If there's \"choice\" at the beginning it has to be up at the level of the divine spark relationship between the cosmic atom that is at our core, and the Logos. For a simple system, there probably isn't much choice, but I can see chance occurring where something didn't incarnate cos perhaps it didn't show up to work that day. But that isn't a moral judgement. Maybe it incarnates later, in a different system, and so on. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59674137", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 01:06 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "I might be taking this metaphor too literally, but does it mean that the prenatal or natal periods is a time of transition for the soul because it is not tightly bpund to the body yet? So the Individuality sometimes remembers its nature, perhaps still experiencing glimpses of the astral plane. And at other times it forgets itself and slips into unconsciousness or the very primitive consciousness of fetuses or infants.<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59675161", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 02:13 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's certainly what I was taught. The individuality isn't entirely hidden inside the growing personality until sometime in early childhood; that's why very young children sometimes have vivid memories of previous lives and show flashes of unexpected wisdom. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59715353", "title": "very early life memories", "date": "2026-03-24 12:13 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "My earliest memory in this body is from a time when I slept in a crib and was at the stage when I was able to get up into the position to crawl. I was resting on my hands and knees in that position. While resting in that position, I noticed how it felt.<br/><br/>And then I had a thought. I'm going to put the thought into adult words. \"Isn't it interesting that I am completely comfortable and relaxed in this posture.\"<br/><br/>I took this memory for granted for until one day I realized that the thought contained an implied comparison--with the way I would feel when on my hands and knees as an older child or a grown-up. I can think of three ways my less-than-two-year old self could know that sensation. 1) precognition, 2) telepathic contact with my older sibling or a parent, 3) past life memory.<br/><br/>Deborah Bender"}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59669273", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 05:04 am", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "Has anyone asked you about the mundane astrology of Iran, particularly - if or not there is any indication of the drubbing that nation's military is receiving in its stars?<br/><br/>Is there an astrological best day for routine legal work like wills and LLCs?  (I'm guessing New Moon, Monday or Wednesday and bonus points for the Moon in Virgo.)<br/><br/>Also - I love the meme, and Heavy Horses is a favorite album... so... what's up with the Long Emergency lately?<br/><br/>Pink Senescent Owl", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59669785", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 05:07 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I haven't looked into it. These days I have a lot of other projects and I've had to scramble to keep up with my current mundane-chart commitments! <br/><br/>2) Thursday, because Jupiter rules law. Do it when the Moon is waning if you want to avoid being overly generous. <br/><br/>3) That's a topic for an entire blog post, or a book. The short form? The Long Descent is still unfolding at the usual pace. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59671321", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 05:38 am", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "Thank you.  Anil Aggarwala offers a Vedic take, but I'm Western.  The similarities of astrological indication and good military planning are always interesting, though.<br/> <br/>I concur with your opinion on the Descent.  The sudden activation of the national immune system in some areas makes me curious about the future of NYC and other dying cities located on what should be prime locations for thriving commercial centers busily that are instead larping Arcosanti out in the sticks.<br/><br/>And - as usual - I'm wondering if there is a supernatural component to the collective decision-making process causing cities to fail - something like the magic of advertising - that might explain the origin of the process.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59675417", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 02:20 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You don't get thriving commercial centers anywhere when the real economy of goods and services is in decline, and most notional economic activity consists of the manufacture and distribution of unpayable IOUs. That's why most of the cities in the western Roman empire either contracted to farm towns or went out of existence entirely in the three centuries after 350.  The US is well along the same arc, so its cities are hollowing out; once serious depopulation sets in -- and we're only a few decades at most from that -- urban abandonment is going to become a massive reality. Doubtless there's a spiritual dimension to it also, but the economic and demographic factors are pretty potent all by themselves.  "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59674393", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 01:32 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "I am using the cookbook methods in JMG's book to guess that there will be a negotiated peace or ceasefire within the next 3-6 months, after multiple false starts. In both Tel-Aviv's and Tehran's Aries ingress charts, the sixth house of the military is ruled by an afflicted malefic and contains a badly-dignified Mercury.<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59675673", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 02:21 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Excellent! The reason I published that book is precisely to encourage people to do this sort of thing. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59678233", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 02:59 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "My prediction of the peace negotiations and their eventual outcome are based more on the seventh house of Tehran's and D.C.'s ingress charts.<br/><br/>My analysis of the sixth house was to suggest that both militaries have issues.<br/><br/>Patrick H"}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59669529", "title": "Magical Gifts", "date": "2026-03-23 05:05 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, <br/>If you wanted to increase a magical ability, how would you go about it?  <br/><br/>I would like to have a clearer perception of the spirit world in order to be able to better help people who are going there and to help spirits on the other side if they need help.<br/><br/>I thought of praying to Hecate for her assistance.  I pray to her daily in any case.  So many ghosts turn up at my house, I am puzzled to know what I should be doing for them.  <br/>Maxine<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59670297", "title": "Re: Magical Gifts", "date": "2026-03-23 05:08 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you already have a good relationship with an appropriate deity, that's a good choice. When you pray, listen for her advice, and then follow it. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59696409", "title": "Re: Magical Gifts", "date": "2026-03-23 07:01 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I hate to be the one wo asks the same question for the billionth time, but how do you know when/that you have a good relationship with an appropriate deity? Also, do you \"pick\" the deity, or does the deity \"pick\" you, or do you just sort of develop a relationship (just like you don't normally \"pick\" your best friends)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59697945", "title": "Re: Magical Gifts", "date": "2026-03-23 07:13 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Do you pray to the deity regularly, and have a clear sense that the prayers are heard and (when appropriate) answered?  Then you have a good relationship with that deity. Is the deity traditionally assigned a role in the subject under discussion? Then the deity's an appropriate one for that subject. <br/><br/>Friendship is a good metaphor for relationships with deities. You know who your friends are, or you know you don't have any; the same is true for deities. As to how to establish them, it's as varied as friendships -- sometimes you reach out, sometimes it's the other person, and sometimes it just happens. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59702297", "title": "Re: Magical Gifts", "date": "2026-03-23 08:01 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, <br/>It worked in a slightly annoying way.  At 5 this morning, I was woken up by a sweet-voiced woman who said that it would be nice if I got up early.  Of course, I couldn't go back to sleep so I got up before 6 and did a Grove Opening in my meditation.  I was able to get a lot of good work done before my husband got up at a more civilized hour.  <br/><br/>Maxine", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59702809", "title": "Re: Magical Gifts", "date": "2026-03-23 08:12 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Well, there you are. Unfortunately the gods have their own ideas..."}]}, {"id": "cmt59702553", "title": "Re: Magical Gifts", "date": "2026-03-23 08:12 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "&gt; Do you pray to the deity regularly, <br/>Yes.<br/><br/>&gt; and have a clear sense that the prayers are heard and (when appropriate) answered?<br/>No.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59703065", "title": "Re: Magical Gifts", "date": "2026-03-23 08:13 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In that case you've answered your own question, haven't you? "}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59670553", "title": "Horary Astrology Consultations", "date": "2026-03-23 05:15 am", "user": "ivn66", "content": "Hi JMG et al - <br/><br/>Posting again to remind the commentariat that I continue to offer consultations in horary astrology free of charge, over on my own Dreamwidth page, to help myself practice and to provide a service to this commentariat, of whom I am fond. <br/><br/>Should you have any question at all which you would like to consult the heavens in order to answer, please head over to my page and leave a comment on the post there. You can do this any day of the week, not only Monday - if you're seeing this later this week the offer stands. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59692057", "title": "Re: Horary Astrology Consultations", "date": "2026-03-23 06:32 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "I know you said \"any question\" but is there a particular kind of question or subject for which horary astrology is ideally suited?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59693849", "title": "Re: Horary Astrology Consultations", "date": "2026-03-23 06:44 pm", "user": "ivn66", "content": "Not in my experience. I'm yet to receive a question that I couldn't find a way to map onto the chart and extract a more or less solid answer. That said most to all of them have been questions focused on comparatively mundane affairs: \"where did I leave my keys?\", \"is this rumor true?\", \"is is my crush reciprocated and will we ever get together?\", \"will the house sell?\", \"will I get the job I'm interviewing for and how will I like it?\" et cetera are all easily answered. My page will have many examples of compatible questions. I haven't been asked \"when will I attain to the Knowledge and Conversation of my Holy Guardian Angel?\" or anything much like that as a counterexample, although I believe there theoretically would be a way to find that in the chart.", "edit_time": "2026-03-23 06:51 pm (UTC)"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59671577", "title": "Lovespell", "date": "2026-03-23 06:27 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear Mr. Greer!<br/><br/>You have talked about the only working lovespell is MAKE YOURSELF MORE LOVEABLE.<br/>Can you elaborate on that and maybe give a few examples, please? (everybody else in the commentariat is welcome to chime in!) ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59677465", "title": "Re: Lovespell", "date": "2026-03-23 02:35 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Sure. People who aren't lovable have habits that drive potential partners away, and those habits generally unfold from mistaken beliefs on the one hand, and unresolved traumatic experiences from childhood on the other. Very often, the beliefs and the emotional baggage from the trauma aren't even conscious, and so can't be changed at a conscious level. That's where operative occultism comes into play. <br/><br/>The first step is to recognize that your problems finding love aren't your fault -- you didn't decide to do any of this -- but they are your problems, not other peoples'. You're the one that has to change. Accept that and you've made a good start. <br/><br/>The second step is to invoke the powers that rule love. If you don't happen to have a religious faith that includes a deity or saint who has love as his or her responsibility, you can invoke the planet Venus. Do this every Friday during the hour of Venus. Light a green candle and, by its light, recite the Orphic Hymn to Venus (you can find this easily online) and then pray to the planet, asking her to become more lovable. Make this a regular action every single Friday. <br/><br/>The third step is to clear away the emotional baggage from old traumas; these play a huge role in most people's personal problems. Here the best method I know of is the Octagon Society exercises, which can be accessed for free, beginning here: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://octagonsociety.org/preliminary-lessons/\">https://octagonsociety.org/preliminary-lessons/</a><br/><br/>The exercises use journaling to unpack the miserable memories from your childhood that are burdening you and let go of their lingering effects. This isn't easy work -- it involves facing up to a lot of old grief, fear, and shame -- but the more of it you do, the easier you'll find it to replace false beliefs with more accurate ones and unhelpful emotional reactions with responses that will help you achieve what you want out of life. <br/><br/>Those three steps will take you very far. Give them a try and see. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59691289", "title": "Re: Lovespell", "date": "2026-03-23 06:28 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "That is solid advice, thank you Sir!"}, {"id": "cmt59708441", "title": "Re: Lovespell", "date": "2026-03-23 09:47 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What if I wish to actually diminish the urge for sex and love in my life? I'm at a place right now where all of this is nothing but an annoying hurdle...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59708953", "title": "Re: Lovespell", "date": "2026-03-23 10:04 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Saturn is the lord of solitude, celibacy, and self-reliance. Burn a candle to him on Saturday, during the hour of Saturn, and ask him to take away your passions. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59671833", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 06:40 am", "user": "ganeshling", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>I hope it would be OK to post it here, if not - just delete this comment.<br/><br/>We have recently renovated <a href=\"https://druidical-gd.org/\">the website of the Druidical Order of the Golden Dawn</a> and added <a href=\"https://druidical-gd.org/articles/\">an 'Articles' section</a> where we are planning to post essays and information on topics relevant to the Celtic Golden Dawn system and its derivatives. The current plan is to be releasing at least one article 4 times a year - each Solstice and Equinox.<br/><br/>Our first offering is <a href=\"https://druidical-gd.org/dogd-books-errata/\">a list of errata</a> found in \"The Celtic Golden Dawn\" and \"The Mysteries of Merlin\" books and compiled by our members over a number of years.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59676441", "title": "Celtic Cabala", "date": "2026-03-23 02:26 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The new website looks good. I also noticed the \"Celtic Cabala\" is available as a correspondence course.  Sounds intriguing.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59724825", "title": "Re: Celtic Cabala", "date": "2026-03-24 03:06 am", "user": "ganeshling", "content": "Yes, we are trialing it out in a correspondence course format right now before considering how to evolve it further.<br/><br/>We are generally puting a good deal of work into expanding the system and exploring it's possibilities."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59672089", "title": "A question about \"out-of-proportion\" obsession with improvement, refinement, \"concentrated form\"", "date": "2026-03-23 07:01 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>It's possible I'm being too abstract/vague/airy with this question, but here goes ...<br/><br/>(also, my examples may suffer from popular misconception)<br/><br/>Question 1: Can a reasonable argument be made that the Piscean Age (or perhaps more specifically the age of Pluto) is responsible for the current \"out-of-proportion\" obsession in industrial society with improvement, refinement, \"concentrated form.\"<br/><br/>If so, then question 2: Can a reasonable argument be made that the Age of Aquarius, or the end of Pluto's influence, will see a decrease of this obsession?<br/><br/>Why I'm asking:<br/>I may have forgotten to write some steps in my thinking process here.<br/><br/>From my admittedly very simplistic impression of history that I've read, it seems like the present here-and-now of industrial society (age of Pluto?) is \"unnaturally?\" obsessed with concepts like improvement, refinement, and \"concentrated form.\"<br/><br/>One example I can think of is the seeming pervasive deification (until 2020?) of the just-in-time philosophy in business (or perhaps it's the deification of efficiency?), as opposed to the idea of resiliency or \"just-in-case.\" As I have yet to throw away my TV, I still follow sports and I see this omnipresent obsession in the book Moneyball and professional baseball. I believe your novel Retrotopia displays this attitude in Mr. Carr seeming aghast at how inefficient businesses are in the Lakeland Republic. And to use a TV show that I'm 100% sure you never watched, the anti-hero in Breaking Bad is known for creating a 99.1% chemically pure crystal meth product; I trivially muse about the leading character's obsession with creating the highest-quality product possible, as opposed to creating something that's simply above-average than the competition.<br/><br/>In the above examples I mentioned, it's as if not being as efficient as possible is one of the Seven Deadly Sins.<br/><br/>Another example that comes to mind for me is how the six surviving signatures of William \"Shakespeare\" are all spelled differently and not one of them has 3 e's. It struck me when I learned this fact in school how weird it was ... as if it should be natural to have one's written name frozen in one form only, and not fluid like a river, which Heraclitus points out: no one steps into the same river twice. Perhaps in this example, I am equating the idea of refinement with the idea of perfection ... supposedly the end goal of refinement, and thus being frozen.<br/><br/>Another example I have in mind is what I would \"concentrated form;\" perhaps it should be re-stated as \"putting everything in one basket.\" What I had in mind was this strange move to complexity but also a reduction to simplicity in order to take care of/avoid dealing with complexity. For example, the common military obsession with a superweapon singular. The joint strike fighter comes to mind ... a fighter aircraft, a strike aircraft, and a ground attack aircraft all in one ... that supposedly makes it mediocre in all 3 roles as a result. As well as the Bradley Fighting Vehicle, at least from what I know by watching a 1998 HBO movie called The Pentagon Wars: a troop carrier that was re-designed to add more roles to it, with the result being ...<br/>\"A troop transport that can't carry [as many] troops, a reconnaissance vehicle that's too conspicuous to do reconnaissance ... and a quasi-tank that has less armor than a snow-blower\" (because it needs to have as little armor as possible to go as fast as possible as a troop transport).<br/><br/>I forgot if you touched upon the Bradley in one of your books that I listened to in audiobook format.<br/><br/>I hope some of this made sense.<br/><br/>Thank you,<br/>-E.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59677721", "title": "Re: A question about \"out-of-proportion\" obsession with improvement, refinement, \"concentrated form\"", "date": "2026-03-23 02:48 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm not sure if it's a Piscean phenomenon or just the natural endpoint of certain obsessive follies of American culture in particular, but yes, it's a real thing, and you've outlined it quite clearly. I hadn't used the Bradley Nonfighting Vehicle as an example, but it's a very good one. My favorite example is the flying car, which has been a source of endless failure since the first one was test flown in 1917. It so happens that all the engineering features that make something a good car make it a bad aircraft, and vice versa, so from this...<br/>[IMAGE:0]<br/>...to this...<br/>[IMAGE:1]<br/>...what you get is a lousy car that's also a lousy plane, for a price tag that would have bought you a good car and a good plane, with enough left over to put a down payment on a midsized yacht. <br/><br/>I have no idea when this obsession will finally give way in the wake of repeated failure, but the sooner it happens, the better. ", "images": [{"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/b6/Curtiss_Autoplane_1917.jpg", "local_path": "./data/archive/2026/2026-03-22_10-29PM_Magic_Monday/images/2026-03-23_02_48_pm_Curtiss_Autoplane_1917.jpg"}, {"url": "https://static0.simpleflyingimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/switchblade-flying-sports-car_exterior.jpeg?q=50&fit=crop&w=825&dpr=1.5", "local_path": "./data/archive/2026/2026-03-22_10-29PM_Magic_Monday/images/2026-03-23_02_48_pm_switchblade-flying-sports-car_exterior.jpeg"}], "edit_time": "2026-03-23 02:49 pm (UTC)"}, {"id": "cmt59680537", "title": "Re: A question about \"out-of-proportion\" obsession with improvement, refinement, \"concentrated form\"", "date": "2026-03-23 03:22 pm", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "About Shakespeare's six differently-spelled signatures (just dot various I's and cross various T's):<br/><br/>Before the 1800s most people didn't write much.  Many didn't even know how to write at all, let alone have any idea that there might be such a thing as \"correct\" spelling. Spelling your name any old way, so long as it as it sounded right--if you could write at all--was the norm back then.<br/><br/>Also until the 1800s much of the world got through life without having any family names (\"last names,\" as we call them) at all, even in many parts of Europe.  <br/><br/>For example, my own last name is Danish, and it was only my great-great-grandfather, back in Denmark, who first used \"Mathiesen\" as his family name.  He was a soldier, a junior rifleman, probably born out of wedlock, who was named Christian Mathiesen.  \"Mathiesen\" was originally a patronymic: it simply means \"a son of some man named Mathias.\"  Christian's father was Mathias Mouritzsen, but Christian was never named \"Mouritzsen.\"  But Christian--or maybe his wife (also born out of wedlock)--chose to name his sons \"Mathiesen\" as their family name, instead of \"Christiansen\" as their patronymic.  And their daughters were also named Mathiesen, instead of \"Christiansdatter,\" which would have been their proper patronymic.  <br/><br/>Less pedantically, I'm sure you're correct about the tendency you analyze:  An acquaintance of mine once remarked that her mother would often correct her, saying \"Why not be perfect?\"  Striving for perfection seems to be part of it all."}, {"id": "cmt59684377", "title": "Re: A question about \"out-of-proportion\" obsession with improvement, refinement, \"concentrated form\"", "date": "2026-03-23 04:17 pm", "user": "linden_matryoshka", "content": "Hi E.,<br/>Your mention of a \"concentrated form\" or \"putting everything in one basket\" made me smile, as I recently ran into it in my life. My example is tiny and mundane, which shows that this phenomenon can be seen at any scale. After gifting my college-aged kid my old rice cooker, I decided to buy a new one. I researched the subject and was flooded with \"smart\", \"programmable\", \"10-in-1\", \"digital\", \"induction\", and \"microcomputerized\". All these technological wonders are running for up to $400! Do they cook rice any better? I will never know. (I ended up buying a simple second-hand one.)"}, {"id": "cmt59688473", "title": "Re: A question about \"out-of-proportion\" obsession with improvement, refinement, \"concentrated form\"", "date": "2026-03-23 05:18 pm", "user": "hippieviking", "content": "I will preface by saying that I can't disagree with our current weird putting of technological crap on a pedestal and that that definitely applies to military hardware. I can say from personal experience that a lot of our heavy equipment is ridiculously over-complex and creates preposterous logistical strains that can only be borne for short periods or in situations not at all resembling total war. <br/><br/>I am going to just throw out that, from what I've seen, of all our over engineered equipment that has been getting tossed into the grinder in Ukraine, the bradleys have actually been one of the few pieces of the equipment that the rank and file of both the Ukrainians and Russians have acknowledged performs well in harsh conditions and is functional as piece of real military hardware in heavy combat. <br/><br/>HV"}, {"id": "cmt59689497", "title": "Re: A question about \"out-of-proportion\" obsession with improvement, refinement, \"concentrated form\"", "date": "2026-03-23 05:55 pm", "user": "jprussell", "content": "Not magical or occult, but a good discussion of the problems with this efficiency/all-your-eggs-in-one-basket mindset is Nassim Taleb's <i>Antifragile</i> (to use your terminology, it's all about why \"just in case\" is better than \"just in time\".)<br/><br/>Cheers,<br/>Jeff"}, {"id": "cmt59696153", "title": "Re: A question about \"out-of-proportion\" obsession with improvement, refinement, \"concentrated form\"", "date": "2026-03-23 07:00 pm", "user": "sirustalcelion", "content": "I'm not qualified to talk about the spirituality side of things, but I specialize in the military field professionally. <br/><br/>Despite the boondoggles of the development/procurement side of both programs, the outcome as far as quality of equipment is concerned can't be credibly denied at this point. The Bradley might not be an invincible super-everything, but it has performed extremely well in its operational role, being more than a match for multiple newer Russian MBTs simultaneously, and performs so beyond the competing IFV equipment from the other side such that the Russian IFVs stopped being used for their operational role. You can argue that it's outdated in the era of drones, but it's a bit unreasonable to expect a 40-year-old IFV design to anticipate a development that makes all armored vehicles vulnerable to the extent that armored fighting vehicles as a class are struggling to maintain their operational relevance. <br/><br/>Similarly with the F-35. I know its design and procurement cycle were a mess, but the operational success of the platform has been such that the biggest risk to it is the overconfidence of the politicians directing its use. <br/><br/>Yes, in both cases it might seem that we've wound up with inferior generalist vehicles that were very expensive. It's easy to frame it that way, not least because most civilians' ideas of military vehicles are in a WWII paradigm that hasn't been relevant doctrine for over 60 years (no shade-- most civilians think of the Civil War in Napoleonic terms when most of the battles resembled WWI more). The integration of both vehicles with appropriately designed doctrine has resulted in both cases in weapons systems that outclass the other comparable systems on their field by a wide margin in combat conditions. <br/><br/>None of this is to counter the broader economic decline narrative - it's more economical for a farmer to have one tractor that does everything well enough than it is for him to have 3 tractors from different brands that do specialized tasks is all, especially if that one generalist tractor is still better than their competitor's specialist tractors. <br/><br/>Apologies for the tangent."}]}, {"id": "cmt59672345", "title": "Practical advice", "date": "2026-03-23 08:46 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This is going to be a difficult question. I know you have said in the past, that suicide does not solve anything. That one just comes back to the same problems, plus the karma of suicide.<br/>I have been living with this philosophy. I am not questioning it. But right now I do not see a way out.<br/><br/>What do I do, if I do not see a way out? Or, I do see one way out, but it leaves my children ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59674649", "title": "Re: Practical advice", "date": "2026-03-23 02:11 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If the occult philosophy is correct, when you die you will spend some time in the afterlife going through your entire life in this incarnation and processing everything that happened and how it affected yourself and other people. So you might as well get started with that process while you are still alive, so that the afterlife is less difficult for you. <br/><br/>Go through your life, and consider everything that you have done and everything that was done to you, and how that has impacted yourself and those around you. Meditate and journal about that, until you have unpacked everything that you can from your life up to now. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59676185", "title": "Re: Practical advice", "date": "2026-03-23 02:22 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "John Michael Greer has frequently recommended the Octagon Society exercises in the past for this type of thing:<br/><br/>https://octagonsociety.org/preliminary-lessons/<br/>https://octagonsociety.org/octagon-society/"}]}, {"id": "cmt59677977", "title": "Re: Practical advice", "date": "2026-03-23 02:52 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Please, for heaven's sake, call a suicide helpline or a crisis clinic and get somebody competent to talk you through this. The fact that you don't see a way out doesn't mean that there isn't a way out -- it just means that you don't see one right now. That's the damnable thing about stress -- it makes clear thinking very difficult, and forces you back on emotional reactions that for most of us are pretty dysfunctional. Don't let that trap you. Talk to someone at one of the services I mentioned, who's helped other people get through their troubles and can help you. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59722777", "title": "Re: Practical advice", "date": "2026-03-24 02:44 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "https://988lifeline.org/<br/><br/>I'm very glad you reached out.<br/>I second the comments of the others-- please stay and play out this hand.<br/>Talk to as many other people as you can-- us, 988Lifeline, whoever else there is that you know cares about you. Don't worry about \"burdening\" them-- they would much rather take a little time to help you make it through this, than find out that suddenly you were gone.<br/><br/>If it's a scary/painful household situation, maybe this also would be helpful:<br/>https://www.thehotline.org/<br/><br/>My very best wishes to you,<br/><br/>- Cicada Grove<br/><br/>"}]}, {"id": "cmt59681561", "title": "Re: Practical advice", "date": "2026-03-23 03:29 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "If Greer's teachings are correct, people who commit suicide are stuck in a limbo until the time they were supposed to die, after which they move on to the afterlife. Is your situation so bad that decades of mind-numbing boredom is a worthwhile trade?"}, {"id": "cmt59685657", "title": "Re: Practical advice", "date": "2026-03-23 04:33 pm", "user": "not_gandalf", "content": "\"Where there's life there's hope\" sounds hopelessly trite, especially if one is trying to deal with a seemingly unresolvable situation, but it's still true. While you are alive there are still options to resolve  a situation, a problem, a relationship. When you are dead those options are over, at least for the time being, and, when you come back, the problem is still there for you, but you may not even know why you are having to deal with it. In fact, I imagine a good many of our present lifetime's most awful and mysterious challenges are exactly things we didn't settle in previous lives that are presenting the bill now to an \"us\" that doesn't even know what we did to merit the bill.<br/><br/>I think it's even preferable to simply chuck everything, through everything into the trunk of one's car and flee to start another life entirely. At least then, at some later time, the solution (or a solution) for the present troubles has the chance to open itself before your gaze. Moving six feet under doesn't allow for that. <br/><br/>Have courage. As difficult as it seems right now, just put one foot in front of another. The next step is all you need to focus on."}, {"id": "cmt59688729", "title": "Re: Practical advice", "date": "2026-03-23 05:19 pm", "user": "linden_matryoshka", "content": "Speaking of \"leaves my children\"... I once knew a wise and kind woman who was raised by her adoptive mother, who found her as a baby at a train station with some small bills tucked into her blanket and a note that a biological mother was heading for Auschwitz (concentration camp). Stay. "}, {"id": "cmt59690009", "title": "Re: Practical advice", "date": "2026-03-23 05:59 pm", "user": "jprussell", "content": "As JMG said, if you're feeling that way, do please talk to someone who might help.<br/><br/>The only other thing I'd say is that your children are absolutely better off with you around than not. I know that you can have all the intellectual, rational reasons in the world for sticking it out, while still emotionally feeling like it's not worth it, but for me, my girls pulled me through that. <br/><br/>At any rate, I offer my blessings and kind wishes if you'll have them, and good luck,<br/>Jeff"}, {"id": "cmt59694361", "title": "Re: Practical advice", "date": "2026-03-23 06:47 pm", "user": "sea_spray", "content": "Hi Anonymous<br/><br/>Please accept my deepest condolences for the situation you find yourself in. The dark can be very dark indeed. <br/><br/>With you permission I would like to pray for Divine help for you. Do you have a preference for a deity you'd like prayers addressed to? If I do not hear from you I will pray to Thor for him to help you as he thinks best, as he has helped me through some dark grey times. <br/>JMG please let me know if such a prayer would be unethical or inadvisable.<br/><br/>Please know that for whatever tiny glimmer of light in the dark it's worth, I wish you well. Your pain brings me pain, your joy would bring me joy.<br/><br/>With distant love and care<br/>Sea spray", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59708697", "title": "Re: Practical advice", "date": "2026-03-23 09:47 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi Anonymous,<br/><br/>If you permit, I will make the same offer. If you do not specify a preferred deity, I will pray to Pallas Athene for her to help you see and make your way through the darkness. Be well.<br/><br/>Hosea Tanatu."}]}, {"id": "cmt59718937", "title": "Re: Practical advice", "date": "2026-03-24 12:55 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Please stay!  My father’s mother hung herself in the garage when he was a teenager, several years after his father died of a heart attack.  He found the body.  Her death haunted him to his dying day.  And I firmly believe the trauma made it very difficult to truly connect with his wife and children.  <br/><br/>There’s no guarantee that the pain will end when we kill ourselves.  The damage left behind is enormous, however.  <br/><br/>The choice my grandmother made in that Los Angeles garage in 1952 lives on in the damage to the grandchildren she never knew.<br/><br/>"}]}, {"id": "cmt59672601", "title": "Moving to an Odd Place", "date": "2026-03-23 10:08 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello John Michael,<br/><br/>You recently moved from East Providence, RI to Silver Spring, MD. Are you feeling bad ju-ju coming out of Washington, DC? They have a history, you know.<br/><br/>If you are getting bad vibes, how do your deal with this?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59678489", "title": "Re: Moving to an Odd Place", "date": "2026-03-23 03:02 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "How far the energies of an urban core extend out into the countryside varies interestingly due to complex factors in the material and energetic landscape. Dion Fortune in one of her novels talks about the feeling when you drive over a certain ridge outside London and all of a sudden the city feels a long ways off. I'm in a very similar situation. Go two blocks uphill from where I live and you're in the urban ambience...but those two blocks make a weird difference. My place feels as though it's in a midsized town somewhere else in eastern Maryland; DC's vibe can't be felt here at all. <br/><br/>Of course I did house blessing rituals as soon as I moved in, and a good powerful banishing is part of my daily routine of practices, and those will deal with bad vibes efficiently, but I don't feel the vibes anywhere near my place. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59698201", "title": "Re: Moving to an Odd Place", "date": "2026-03-23 07:13 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not the OP but I would be fascinated to hear more details about the house blessing rituals you did.<br/><br/>Congratulations on the move by the way. I hope you are enjoying your new place.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59699993", "title": "Re: Moving to an Odd Place", "date": "2026-03-23 07:37 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The rituals are specific to one of the traditions in which I've been initiated, the Rose+Croix d'Orient (Rose Cross of the East, R+Cd'O), and they're private within that tradition, so there's not much I can say about them in a public venue like this. They call down positive spiritual influences from divine and angelic sources. <br/><br/>I received the R+Cd'O initiation last July and since then I've been putting a lot of work into the rituals that come with it -- since I have them, might as well get good at using them! I'll doubtless move on to other things eventually but right now they're working very well. <br/><br/>As for the move, thank you! So far it's been very positive. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59714329", "title": "Re: Moving to an Odd Place", "date": "2026-03-24 12:06 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG - <br/><br/>I am very glad to hear that your move has been very positive.<br/><br/>Lathechuck<br/>"}]}, {"id": "cmt59711257", "title": "Re: Moving to an Odd Place", "date": "2026-03-23 10:41 pm", "user": "not_gandalf", "content": "This is NOT from the Rose+Croix d'Orient John mentions, but is related. This is given in a book called \"The Way of the Rose+Croix, Volume 1\" by Mathieu Ravignat. Mat has published this enormous work, two volumes, that is the oratory work of the Fench Rose+Croix, meaning mostly the Ordre Kabbalistique de la Rose+Croix, so this is from a published work. It's a Spring Invocation for the presence of Angels in a home. I paraphrase the instructions: <br/><br/>This ritual is traditional for the R+C for the dawn of the day of the Spring Equinox, but it can also be done on Easter where a candle lit from the Pascal Candle after Mass may be used.<br/>Face the East in a central place, and after some time in silence say the following passages of Scripture to invoke the Light:<br/><br/>For you, LORD, make my lamp shine; my God enlightens my darkness. (NIV, Psalm 18:28)<br/>God's Light dispels darkness. Now this is the message we have heard from Him and announce to you - that God is light and in Him there is no darkness at all. (NIV John 1:5-7)<br/>The Light shines in the darkness and the darkness does not overcome it. (NIV John 1:5)<br/><br/>Immediately after the last verse light a taper candle made of beeswax (or a plain white one) or any candle you can hold. Take time to focus on the presence of the Light before proceeding.<br/>Then in a clockwise (sunwise) go into every room and hidden place of your home (such as closets, large cupboards, attic, etc.) and shine light on every wall and corner of it.<br/>Then return to the central place and face East, pause until you have the conviction that your house has been purified by the light, and then invoke the presence of the Angels:<br/><br/>O Everlasting God who hast ordained and constituted the services of Angels and men in a wonderful order; mercifully grant that, as the Holy Angels always do thee service in heaven, so, by thy appointment, they may succor and defend me here on earth, through Christ our Lord.<br/><br/>Then, with love in your heart, silently ask the Angels to be present. Take your time, but, when you feel your call has been answered, say:<br/><br/>Amen. So mote it be.<br/><br/>Thus sealing there presence in your home for the coming year.<br/><br/>Very Christian, I know, but the European R+C Orders are.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59714073", "title": "Re: Moving to an Odd Place", "date": "2026-03-24 12:06 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Mat's work is first-rate. The rituals in that book of his are from a more recent tradition than those of the Rose+Croix d'Orient, which I'm convinced are medieval, but they certainly work. "}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59673113", "title": "A Heathen approach to the SoP", "date": "2026-03-23 11:55 am", "user": "borealbear", "content": "First off, to the anonymous commenter from last week who asked about my experiences with the Heathen GD, if you happen to be reading this: unfortunately I didn't see your comment before the cutoff, but I'd be more than happy to talk about it if you want to send me a private message.<br/><br/>To JMG: Hope you're well, and thank you for hosting these as always. Following on from last week's discussion, I've been pondering what a more nature-based Heathen system using the SoP would look like, as an alternative to consider for later when I've finished my current commitments. So:<br/><br/>1) Do you think the DMH could be adapted to use Heathen/Germanic symbolism while keeping the basic framework of the system, ie. runes instead of Ogham and so on? Or would it be a better idea to take up your Golden Section series of books in that case, since I understand they're meant to be flexible when it comes to religion and symbolism (?). I've always had a soft spot for the DMH, but I'll admit I haven't read the GSF books (other than the Earth Mysteries one), so I'm less clear on what exactly that system involves.  <br/><br/>2) Does the Golden Section system use the Wheel of Life?<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59678745", "title": "Re: A Heathen approach to the SoP", "date": "2026-03-23 03:07 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) You could certainly use the DMH system for Heathen magic. The changes wouldn't even be as complex as those that were needed to craft the Heathen Golden Dawn; swap out the Ogham for the runes, identify appropriate deities for the stations of the wheel, replace Welsh with Old Norse as needed, and you're mostly there. <br/><br/>2) The GSF system isn't magical in nature -- meditation rather than magic is its core practice. It doesn't use the Wheel of Life, but the Wheel and in fact the whole of the DMH system can be combined with the GSF system to give it a magical dimension. Yes, you can play the music in a Heathen key. ;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59684121", "title": "Re: A Heathen approach to the SoP", "date": "2026-03-23 04:04 pm", "user": "borealbear", "content": "Again, thank you, and this makes the difference between the two nicely clear for me. It's good to hear adapting the DMH is an option, and I hope you'll indulge me asking a follow-up regarding the \"mostly there\":<br/><br/>I take it one could also then replace the crane bag with a more Germanic equivalent like a ring, a la HGD, as long as it's worn on the body? <br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59685913", "title": "Re: A Heathen approach to the SoP", "date": "2026-03-23 04:38 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Of course. The crane bag is specific to Celtic tradition, so should be replaced by something specific to Heathen tradition. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59690265", "title": "Re: A Heathen approach to the SoP", "date": "2026-03-23 06:06 pm", "user": "jprussell", "content": "For what it's worth, I've been following the DMH with Heathen deities for the past few years and it seems to work quite well. I did learn the Ogham and am almost done pathworking the wheel of life, but in my SOP and seasonal celebrations, I call upon Heathen Gods/Goddesses. For my own part, I started out doing it to follow JMG's advice to do one magic course \"by the book\" before anything else, and figured \"yeah, yeah, this Druid stuff is fine, but not really my spiritual home.\" After practicing for a while, though, I've found Druidry more congenial than expected, and it's flavored my practices more than I might have expected.<br/><br/>Oh, also, if you're looking for a Rune-compatible Wheel of Life replacement, Edred Thorsson gives a diagram of the Nine worlds in <i>The Nine Doors of Midgard</i>, which just so happens to have 24 connections between the worlds. He doesn't assign a Rune to each path, but instead leaves that to the student to work out.<br/><br/>Cheers,<br/>Jeff", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59695129", "title": "Re: A Heathen approach to the SoP", "date": "2026-03-23 06:53 pm", "user": "borealbear", "content": "Yeah, I remember you had a hybrid approach that seemed to suit you well. Glad to hear it's still going strong! Personally I like the Ogham and definitely respect the Druid Revival, but at this point I think I'd rather stick with the Heathen perspective. That said, it's of course another option to consider when the time comes to choose.<br/><br/>Thank you for the Thorsson recommendation as well. Interesting. I have one of his books and keep meaning to pick up the others, so that's one more reason to add it to the get-to pile. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59693593", "title": "Re: A Heathen approach to the SoP", "date": "2026-03-23 06:43 pm", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "Additionally, there are the elemental and other correspondences of the Oghams, which would have to be reworked for the Runes. Likewise with the pathworkings, since I don't know if the Runes are suited to be used in pathworking in their alphabetical succession, like it is the case with the Oghams un pathworkings in the DMH. And the symbolism of the stations of the Wheel of the Year would also probably have to be reworked, since the symbolism (the images used in the pathworkings for the stations of the year) is more or less explicitly Celtic.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59697177", "title": "Re: A Heathen approach to the SoP", "date": "2026-03-23 07:08 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Of course. All of this is a great source of themes for meditation! "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59673369", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 12:15 pm", "user": "pointwithinacircle", "content": "How does one come to understand the meaning of dream symbolism?  I feel like my dreams are personal to me and contain symbolism particular to my experiences, beliefs, and history. I am curious about the universal symbolism that would apply to everyone by virtue of our common human existence. How exactly do I begin to understand what my dreams are telling me?<br/><br/>Last night I had a dream that I was in bed and my brother (who died 15 years ago) came into the room, sat on the edge of my bed and said I need to show you something.  He showed me a short video on his phone of a young woman and a child.  This dream struck me because I felt a lot of emotion as I watched the video. <br/><br/>I feel like there is a message there for me but I cannot seem to find it. The only thing I can see to do is to review the dream in meditation until some message becomes clear.  Is there any other practice that might help me to see the deeper message?   Thanks. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59679001", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 03:08 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I wish I had an answer. Most of my dreams are completely incomprehensible to me. I wonder, though, if what your brother was saying to you is that he's in incarnation again -- the young woman may be his new mother, the child may be him. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59685401", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 04:31 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "I used to have vivid dreams, then did a bunch of work towards Jungian individuation. After that, my dreams became a hodgepodge of disconnected and random stuff with no discernible meaning. I eventually concluded I had worked out a lot of the stuff in my personal subconscious and so was now picking up astral static when dreaming/sleeping. Not so much the case now, since the first vision. Fun times."}]}, {"id": "cmt59679769", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 03:14 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If you are already a dream journalist and recording your reports from the night beat, that is an important first step. Dreams are one of the ways our relatives and loved ones who have passed on continue to stay in touch with us, so if it were my dream I'd consider it as a communication from my brother. Thinking about how it made me feel as soon as I wake up, is one way I am guided by the mysteries of dream imagery. That provides a clue if this is something I should be cautious of, excited about, moving towards or moving away from. Considering it's been fifteen years since the death, perhaps it is about reincarnation, or he is showing a future event in the family. <br/><br/>One other way to work with a dream is to scry back into them, if you have the skill of scrying, and converse with your brother that way and ask for more detail about what the dream means. <br/><br/>JPM "}]}, {"id": "cmt59673625", "title": "Blessing offer; Modern Order of Essenes", "date": "2026-03-23 12:41 pm", "user": "milkyway1", "content": "Given the current state of world affairs, some more blessing and spiritual healing in the world wouldn't be amiss, methinks... :-)<br/><br/>Thus I want to again highlight the Modern Order of Essenes, a system of spiritual healing and blessing which JMG received from his teacher John Gilbert. It's free, and self study, i.e. can be started at any time. (As to its effects, I'll leave them for you to explore, but just want to point out that the Healing Hands which Kylec gratiously offers here each week are part of the MOE teachings...)<br/><br/>You can access the MOE content in JMG's original posts here on dreamwidth (<a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/tag/modern+order+of+essenes\">https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/tag/modern+order+of+essenes</a>), as pdf files hosted by the Octagon Society (<a href=\"https://octagonsociety.org/archives/modern-order-of-essenes\">https://octagonsociety.org/archives/modern-order-of-essenes</a>), or in online course format on my website (<a href=\"https://thehiddenthings.com/topics/moe-course\">https://thehiddenthings.com/topics/moe-course</a>).<br/><br/>Also, I'd like to invite all of you to sign up for the blessings which I perform each Wednesday: <a href=\"https://thehiddenthings.com/categories/weekly-blessings\">https://thehiddenthings.com/categories/weekly-blessings</a><br/><br/>Of course, all of these things can be mentioned to other people, too... Every little bit of blessing and healing makes a small difference somewhere in the world.<br/><br/>JMG, thanks for hosting MM again, and my blessings to you if you will have them, :-)<br/><br/>Milkyway<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59679257", "title": "Re: Blessing offer; Modern Order of Essenes", "date": "2026-03-23 03:08 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this as always. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59673881", "title": "7 Steps of Practical Occultism", "date": "2026-03-23 12:49 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>I've recently started practicing with the Builders of the Adytum correspondence course, and have a specific question about the introductory lessons (7 Steps of Practical Occultism).<br/><br/>I'd like to employ the techniques outlined in those lessons toward personal healing.  Specifically, I have hearing loss, likely due to abnormal bone growth in my skull.  It's a rare, but not extremely rare, condition and modern medical science has no idea what causes it (other than there being an apparent genetic component), and there is no way to fix it other than undergoing a risky surgery--a path I don't want to take.<br/><br/>Would the visualization techniques in 7 Steps be well suited to healing this impairment and restoring my hearing?  The 7 Steps rightly points out that forming intentions and performing visualization exercises are useless if one's actions throughout the rest of the day are not supportive of the attainment of the goal.  However, there don't appear to be any other actions that I can take with regard to this problem, aside from forming the intention and performing the visualization.  There are no dietary or other personal habit changes or practices that, at least in the knowledge base of modern science, are known to cure an abnormal bone growth in the middle ear.<br/><br/>I also wonder if this is some sort of bad karma and I should just accept it as justly earned punishment, rather than trying to change it.<br/><br/>Thanks!<br/><br/>Turquoise Slithy Pug", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59680793", "title": "Re: 7 Steps of Practical Occultism", "date": "2026-03-23 03:22 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's certainly worth trying. Some people get remarkable results from applying mental methods to physical ailments, though others don't.  That I know of, there's no way to tell which category you're in without making the attempt, so give it a try and see what happens. <br/><br/>Congrats on starting the BOTA course, btw. It's not always the most exciting training program, but it'll give you a very thorough and practical grounding in Cabalistic occultism. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59675929", "title": "Bless their little pointy heads", "date": "2026-03-23 02:21 pm", "user": "neptunesdolphins", "content": "Recently, I wanted to smite a beta-marxist. Really smite them. I feel helpless and impotent at what they were doing. I also felt self-righteous, moral, and good person. I wanted to smite them in the name of all those other helpless people. Well, I didn't smite anybody.<br/><br/>What I did learn is how the Magic Resistance is seductive in setting a person up as being moral and good. And how they can wield their privilege to help those who can't resist. After all magic is the power of the powerless, right? You feel good and righteous in your cursing.<br/><br/>However, I realized that if I smote someone, that I could be smited (smoted?) or at least on the receiving end of very bad mojo. So, I gave up the impulse. However, the question I have is why don't the Magic Resistance understand that they could be on the receiving end of someone else's curses or bad mojo. I mean, there are Trump folks who don't want to see the Magic Resistance succeed.<br/><br/>As for me, I did what people suggested - transform the cursing into a blessing. I came upon it when watching a commercial with Obama lying about how Virginia had to redistrict their 6/5 districts to a 10/1 districts. After all Trump ordered up a few new districts in Texas, so everyone had to vote for a *temporary* redistricting in the Dems. favor to thwart Trump so they could have a *fair election*. I just blurted out, \"Well, Gods bless his little pointy head.\" <br/><br/>I just figured that was a good blessing, since in the regular blog, you suggested patting the beta-marxists on their little pointy heads. I figure this was the same thing.<br/><br/>I hope I am correct.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59681049", "title": "Re: Bless their little pointy heads", "date": "2026-03-23 03:26 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Excellent! Yes, the soi-disant Magic Resistance is remarkably good at getting other people to become just as self-righteous and self-important as they are -- and good for you, that you evaded the trap. <br/><br/>The proper conjugation of smite, btw, is smite, smote, smitten. Ain't English fun? <br/><br/>(Bonus question: if cats have kittens, shouldn't bats have bittens?) ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59684889", "title": "Re: Bless their little pointy heads", "date": "2026-03-23 04:23 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Oh god, that might explain why so much of the dissident right has become as self-righteous and self-important as the leftists they claim to oppose. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59686169", "title": "Re: Bless their little pointy heads", "date": "2026-03-23 04:39 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "What you contemplate, you imitate -- and hating and opposing someone or something is a great way to ensure you contemplate it. Another reason to focus on building your side up, not tearing the other side down! "}]}, {"id": "cmt59690521", "title": "Re: Bless their little pointy heads", "date": "2026-03-23 06:10 pm", "user": "jprussell", "content": "And shouldn't the plural of \"fox\" be \"foxen?\" :D<br/><br/>Jeff", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59692825", "title": "Re: Bless their little pointy heads", "date": "2026-03-23 06:37 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It was in Middle English -- that's where the word \"vixen\" comes from!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59701273", "title": "Re: Bless their little pointy heads", "date": "2026-03-23 07:46 pm", "user": "diletpoly", "content": "<p>I've actually taken to using Goden (or maybe Godden? I usually say it not spell it) as a sort of shorthand for \"Gods and Goddesses\". Not quite sure where I picked that up.</p>\n<p>The Dilettante Polymath</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59703577", "title": "Re: Bless their little pointy heads", "date": "2026-03-23 08:15 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'd double the D to make it fit English spelling habits. It's not an improbable word -- just as \"Heathen\" means \"they of the heath,\" Godden would mean something like \"they of the gods.\""}]}, {"id": "cmt59727897", "title": "Re: Bless their little pointy heads", "date": "2026-03-24 03:46 am", "user": "jprussell", "content": "Huh, I should have known that! I just got it from some comedian's bit talking about how hard it was as a kid to learn English's weird, inconsistent rules. I think he also mentioned \"boxen,\" which I'd be more surprised to find was ever in use.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59728665", "title": "Re: Bless their little pointy heads", "date": "2026-03-24 03:50 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "\"Boxen\" is an English word, but it's not the plural of box. It means \"made of the wood of the box tree, <i>Buxus sempervirens</i>,\" the way that \"oaken\" means \"made from the wood of the oak tree.\" You're welcome. ;-) "}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59683609", "title": "Re: Bless their little pointy heads", "date": "2026-03-23 03:55 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Neptunesdolphins, my theory, which is mine, is that they don't believe the other side capable of magic, as they assume all Trump supporters are hardline evangelical Christians, and therefore they're safe from any attack (they also don't believe that Christian prayer has any effect on anything). However, it may just be that they are so convinced of their own purity and righteousness that they don't believe maleficia from their opponents will touch them. After all, they're on the side of Justice, how could anything they do be wrong??? /s<br/><br/>I will keep your blessing, with its distinct wording, in mind! I'm sure I'll have plenty of opportunities to use it.<br/><br/>--Sister Crow"}, {"id": "cmt59691545", "title": "Re: Bless their little pointy heads", "date": "2026-03-23 06:29 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "My take on the Magic Resistance is that a big part of their problem is that they subscribe to a belief system in which they cannot possibly be wrong or lose, because they are the righteous underdogs and in the end, they must win. Because they're right and the other side is evil and that's how it works!! So almost any behavior is justified. <br/><br/>I think this goes back to some deep American mythos that originated with the American Revolution and which has been fostered by American film and literature, of the rag-tag underdogs winning against all odds. You can see the same trope in British works, of course, but in America, that particular literary/film trope is also linked to the country's origin story, and seems to have a particular seductive power. The Magic Resistance seem to believe that they're some combination of the embattled farmers by the rude bridge that arched the flood, the Fellowship of the Ring, the Rebel Alliance, Dumbledore's Army, Rocky, operatives on the Underground Railroad and La Resistance, and who knows what others of the same archetype. Of course they're going to win - they're the good guys! Evil is big and powerful and scary but it WILL lose to them and their clever underdog majicks!!<br/><br/>I'm replying to this on a Magic Monday thread because I do think there is something not entirely of the material world about this. There are some sort of archetypes or collective consciousness or something affecting them, and they get caught up in a very irrational way. I also wonder if this is somehow related to the way everyone seems to be ignoring American's 250th anniversary. There is hardly any interest in the semiquincentennial, yet we've been treated to vacuous No Kings tantrums all year. Weird, right? <br/><br/>This is a bit of a tangent from your original questions, but I feel like there is something odd and a bit uncanny going on with all of this that I can't quite put my finger on. The Magic Resistance and others caught up in extreme TDS have a strange energy about them.<br/><br/><br/> ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59724569", "title": "Re: everybody ignoring America's 250th anniversary", "date": "2026-03-24 03:04 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "When the 200th anniversary of the Revolution rolled around, Nixon was President. He tried to make something of it, but the Vietnam War had been dragging on since his predecessor Lyndon Johnson had sent regular troops there and activated the draft. Nixon had promised to win it or end it but had not done so. Everybody who opposed the war was weary and angry. I doubt that people who supported the war were much happier, since many of their sons were in uniform. There did not seem to be a celebratory mood.<br/><br/>I was hoping that the bicentennial of the signing of the Constitution and the Bill of Rights in 1789 would make up for it, since in many ways that was the true birthday of our country, or at least its system of government. That anniversary passed without any public or official notice at all that I can remember. <br/><br/>Maybe there is some karma to be dealt with, particularly with the indigenous inhabitants. <br/><br/>Deborah Bender", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59726873", "title": "Re: everybody ignoring America's 250th anniversary", "date": "2026-03-24 03:41 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Alas, I drift far off topic and JMG, feel free to not publish this if you deem; but:<br/><br/>In 1976, Nixon was long gone (as of 1974), Gerald Ford was president and running against Jimmy Carter, and the country actually seemed pretty cheerful about the bicentennial. <br/>They even minted special quarters for it, which you still see in your change from time to time.<br/><br/>- Cicada Grove"}]}, {"id": "cmt59725081", "title": "Re: Bless their little pointy heads", "date": "2026-03-24 03:08 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I just thought of a humorous metaphor while reading the other (political) blog I like: They are like moths, and Trump is like the porch light. They all fly at it and batter themselves against it and each other. They can't resist; for some reason they are fascinated with him.<br/><br/>- Cicada Grove"}]}, {"id": "cmt59698969", "title": "Re: Bless their little pointy heads", "date": "2026-03-23 07:26 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The reason that any person would end up not understanding that he could easily find himself on the receiving end of someone else's curses or bad mojo would be that he had already been cursed or mojoed into that severe state of cluelessness. In for a penny, in for a pound, as they say! It takes quite a bit of metaphysical destabilizing to come away that blinded to natural consequences. <br/><br/>Most toddlers fully recognize that their uncontrolled nastiness will get returned to them with interest. So just how much heaping up of curses does it take to leave supposedly mature adults significantly less wise than your average toddler? Incarnation turns out to be quite a challenging undertaking, with so many charming wrong turns enchanting us off course; that must be why we get so many tries at it!<br/><br/>There but for the grace of god we go, tiptoeing around all the little piles of curses that no one thought to clean up after themselves. Father, forgive them, for they've become too clueless to know what they're doing... to themselves. May the gods bless their pointy little heads and all of the curses they're so effectively raining down... on themselves.<br/><br/>— Christophe"}]}, {"id": "cmt59676697", "title": "Steiner", "date": "2026-03-23 02:27 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I am re-reading Steiner's \"Occult Science.\" A section near the end titled \"The Stages of Life\" really struck me this time.  He writes of the astral body feeding off the etheric body and the etheric body feeding off the physical body in old age.  That's the stage I'm at now.  Are there writers who've explored this in more detail?  Fodder for meditation?<br/><br/>Thank you.  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59681305", "title": "Re: Steiner", "date": "2026-03-23 03:27 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Definitely fodder for meditation -- Steiner is always a rich source of meditation themes. I'm not as familiar with Steiner's lectures as I probably should be, but I'd be willing to bet he went into more detail about it in a talk at some point, and the Anthroposophists will have published it by now. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59683865", "title": "Re: Steiner", "date": "2026-03-23 04:04 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If I may I think I'll type out the section in question.  Some may find it interesting, and it matches what you said last week about the etheric body weakening in old age. So here goes: \"At length however there comes a time when the etheric body begins to decline, reversing the development it enjoyed from the seventh year onward.  There is a change in the functioning of the astral body.  To start with it unfolded the potentialities coming to it from the outer world.  But now the moment comes when in a spiritual sense the astral body begins to feed on its own etheric body.  It draws on the etheric body and consumes it.  And in the further course of life the etheric body in its turn begins to draw upon the physical body and consume it. These facts are closely related to the physical body's degeneration in old age.\"  (found on p.367)  <br/><br/>I'm not young, but my mom is now 104 and although she has moderate dementia, her vital signs are solid and she may go on for a lot longer.  I don't like being around her so I limit my time with her to about 45 minutes a week.  So Steiner's thoughts on aging are quite immediate.  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59684633", "title": "Re: Steiner", "date": "2026-03-23 04:21 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "He's quite correct, and there's another wrinkle. Some old people, unconsciously or deliberately, keep their physical bodies going longer than usual by feeding their etheric bodies on other people's etheric bodies instead. Your mother may do this, and so limiting your time around her may be a very good idea...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59686681", "title": "Re: Steiner", "date": "2026-03-23 04:42 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not OP: I seem to recall wearing a Red Bag Amulet from the Magic Monday FAQ may help disrupt etheric vampyrism where contact is unavoidable.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59687705", "title": "Re: Steiner", "date": "2026-03-23 04:49 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes. Regular practice of banishing rituals will also strengthen your aura to the point that a vampire won't be able to pierce it and drain energy from it. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59701017", "title": "Re: Steiner", "date": "2026-03-23 07:43 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've been doing SoP for a couple of years without missing a day.  I have a red bag hanging in my bedroom.  I think I'll start wearing it when I go to visit."}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59728409", "title": "Re: Steiner", "date": "2026-03-24 03:49 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yikes. I didn't read very far into the comments of last week's Magic Monday. If JMG's comment about the etheric body weakening in old age was in the comments, I will have to go look for it. <br/><br/>It is pretty common for people who were fairly vigorous mentally and physically to weaken in their late seventies and decline further around the age of eighty.The etheric body is so closely connected to the physical body that it makes sense to me that it would also lose health and strength around that time. <br/><br/>I'm at that age right now, still truckin' and engaged, but having to husband my energy and be careful with my body. I have been thinking about coming to terms with increasing limitations, ill health or sudden illness, and of course death. I don't want to be a psychic vampire! I do want to stay in balance, avoid dementia, and conserve what I used to count on. I'm no Taoist master. The idea that my astral body would feed on me is scary and new.<br/><br/>Any advice, JMG?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59728921", "title": "Re: Steiner", "date": "2026-03-24 03:56 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nah, your astral body isn't feeding on \"you.\" You aren't your material body, or your etheric body. Your astral body is the basis of your personality, and it maintains itself by gently withdrawing force from the etheric and (at second hand) material bodies as you ripen toward death. Make sure you get plenty of fresh air and sunlight, eat healthy food, and take up some kind of gentle exercise -- tai chi or its American offshoot tai chi chih are especially good for this -- and also keep your mind active; dementia is very strongly correlated with neglect of the mind in old age. Do these things and you should be fine. "}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59676953", "title": "Orphic Hymns", "date": "2026-03-23 02:28 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Sorry to have to ask you to repeat information yet again, but Dreamwidth refuses to cooperate with my searches. I intend to start praying the Orphic Hymns to the planets and the Guardian Genius daily, as you have recommended previously. Could you remind me of the candle colors and incenses for each day? Thank you for your patience and for all the wisdom you dispense each week!<br/><br/>--Indigo Flummoxed Peacock", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59681817", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymns", "date": "2026-03-23 03:30 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Sure thing. I recommend burning frankincense daily -- the ancients used that for all the gods and goddesses, and it works. The other details are: <br/><br/>Sunday - Sun - yellow<br/>Monday - Moon - violet<br/>Tuesday - Mars - red<br/>Wednesday - Mercury - orange<br/>Thursday - Jupiter - sky blue<br/>Friday - Venus - green<br/>Saturday - Saturn - indigo/dark blue"}, {"id": "cmt59706137", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymns", "date": "2026-03-23 09:18 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Side question about dreamwidth search. Do installing search widgets in the sidebar work? Would love to be able to search past topics to avoid any repeats.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59707929", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymns", "date": "2026-03-23 09:30 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you have an account with Dreamwidth, there's a search function, and it's pretty good. If you stay anon, you don't have access to it. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59679513", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 03:12 pm", "user": "davidp", "content": "Hey JMG,<br/><br/>I'm wondering what to do with the paper I used for free-form journaling (i.e. the Q/A style you describe in the GSF). I'm slightly too paranoid to just throw it into the trash (maybe something else to journal about, but I digress).<br/><br/>Rendering it unreadable by pulping occurred to me but it seems a shame to just throw out the pulp when I'm already halfway to turning it into new paper. As journaling is obviously a bit of an emotional process, though, I'm concerned that the paper itself might have picked something up that might render it unsafe for reuse. Should I be worried about that?<br/><br/>Alternatively, are there magical uses for the paper? If I'm working through some issue, I could definitely see some symbolic potential in, say, burning the pages, though I'm not yet sure how to go from there to causing changes in consciousness.<br/><br/>—David P.<br/><br/>PS: I vaguely recall wondering about these things before so I apologise if I've asked you this already.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59682585", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 03:33 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Er, from my perspective, you're seriously overthinking this. You can burn the paper if you want to, or recycle it, or use it to line the bottom of the birdcage where your Norwegian blue parrot is pining for the fjords, or whatever else appeals to you. <br/><br/>Paper doesn't hold magical charges well, btw. That's why I recommend that paper talismans be made from watercolor paper that's been painted with a tea of relevant herbs and a little bit of homeopathic gold, so the charge has something to hold onto. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59688985", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 05:22 pm", "user": "davidp", "content": "I think Polly Svensdotter would like it if I turned the paper into miniature fjords. Thank you!<br/><br/>—David P."}, {"id": "cmt59701785", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 07:58 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Oh, I don't know about that... a pining blue parrot is nothing to mess with! Giving it more emotional fodder to pine over could easily throw your entire life out of kilter. And were it of the vengeful, grudging type it might well take your journaled secrets hostage, in order to extort more crackers as ransom. Little chicken scratched notes slipped through the cage door is just the beginning. Soon you'll be buying it first-class passage back to Norway every summer.<br/><br/>— Christophe"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59680281", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 03:16 pm", "user": "thinking_turtle", "content": "<p>To share, for those who wonder what ADR, LIRP, or IR mean, a <a href=\"https://thinking-turtle.dreamwidth.org/tag/abbreviation\">list of abbreviations used on Ecopsophia</a>.  And here is a <a href=\"https://thinking-turtle.dreamwidth.org/tag/books\">list of the books our host published so far</a>.</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59682073", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 03:30 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thanks for this as always. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59682329", "title": "Protection and Invisibility", "date": "2026-03-23 03:31 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello.  As the world becomes more and more tumultuous, and riskier for those of us who practice occultism, and especially dangerous for those of us who, say, wish to speak out against the current war, it has occurred to me that I may want to ensure protection for myself and my family.  I have considered making a protective talisman.  I have some experience crafting these talismans - Jupiter is my patron, I have a supply of tin, which is very easy to work with - you can hammer it flat while cold, and if you put it near a campfire it gets very soft, and you can just scratch lines into it with a knife.  Of course Jupiter would make his metal an easy to work with and affordable one.  So, the sixth pentacle of Jupiter seems best to me, to be inscribed on the hour and day of Jupiter.  What should go on the back?  I've done the magic square of Jupiter on the back of all my Jovian talismans - just keep doing that?  Or something else for protection?<br/><br/>Finally, I would like an invisibility talisman.  I understand it won't make me physically invisible, just allow me to go unnoticed, unobserved - obviously it won't work if I do something dramatic and obvious, but I would like to, say, show up to a protest with my face covered, peacefully say some controversial things about this war being waged in the name of Epstein, and then go home and go about my life without anyone figuring out it was me holding that sign and having my employment potentially terminated for engaging in crimethink.  Which, you know, shouldn't be a concern for peacefully exercising one's right as an American citizen to speak publicly, but with the way things are these days... I also don't ever want to be found out as an occultist unless I want someone to know, and applying invisibility to myself in order to keep that a secret seems wise.  Obviously the first thing I should do is keep my mouth shut about it - no talisman or spell can overcome the foolish decisions of the caster.  Still, what pentacle or ritual would you recommend for invisibility?<br/><br/>Thank you, as always, for all your time and hard work.<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59682841", "title": "Re: Protection and Invisibility", "date": "2026-03-23 03:37 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) If you've made a habit of using the magic square of Jupiter, continue that. Personal egregors are worth cultivating. <br/><br/>2) The invisibility workings I've done used the Golden Dawn invisibility formula, which you'll find in the Gray Doorstop of Regardie. ;-) They were very effective. For the purpose you have in mind, though, invisibility is overkill -- you don't want to become so hard to notice that a car drives over you when you're crossing the street! You might consider a Mercury working, to make you nimble and elusive. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59686937", "title": "Re: Protection and Invisibility", "date": "2026-03-23 04:43 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "That actually seems perfect - I recently started working with Mercury, and am about to build a shrine to him. Any tips on working with Mercury in general, or for asking for this particular favor from him? Also, how would one make talismans out of mercury? I do havr access tosome, from old mercury light bulbs, but I've hesitated to break into them for obvious safety reasons.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59687449", "title": "Re: Protection and Invisibility", "date": "2026-03-23 04:48 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) He's the god of merchants and tradesmen, and so he's always going to want something in exchange for a favor. Your best bet is planetary charity -- if you donate some multiple of $8 on eight different Wednesdays to a charity that teaches reading and language skills to children, say, or supports foreign language education, he's likely to be propitious. <br/><br/>2) You never use metallic mercury for talismans -- well, unless you're good enough at alchemy to solidify it! Mercury talismans are made of brass, which is an alloy of copper and zinc; Mercury rules all alloys, and brass has been used for his talismans since ancient times. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59691033", "title": "Re: Protection and Invisibility", "date": "2026-03-23 06:18 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ah, that's fair.  I should have expected Mercury to be a bit mercenary.  Charity seems like an excellent option.  As for solidifying Mercury - well, I was a chemist once, I do know enough modern alchemy to solidify it, but... brass seems much safer.  I'll go with that.  Any particular pentacle of Mercury you recommend?  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59692569", "title": "Re: Protection and Invisibility", "date": "2026-03-23 06:35 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I never used canned designs. The standard Golden Dawn approach, which was how I trained, is to design one from first principles using the names, sigils, and magic square appropriate to the planet. "}, {"id": "cmt59729177", "title": "Re: Protection and Invisibility", "date": "2026-03-24 03:57 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I sometimes give Hermes an offering of a circulated silver dime from the period when they had Mercury on the back. purchasable from coin stores."}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59683097", "title": "Dolmen Arch", "date": "2026-03-23 03:48 pm", "user": "trubrujah", "content": "Here is the latest on the Dolmen Arch.  We just finished going through the Seven Ways of Thought exercises over the last few weeks, and are starting this week on the Second Branch of the Mabinogion.<br/><br/><a href=\"https://thelongdescent.substack.com/p/seven-ways-of-thought\">https://thelongdescent.substack.com/p/seven-ways-of-thought</a>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59683353", "title": "Re: Dolmen Arch", "date": "2026-03-23 03:51 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you. Delighted to see this! "}]}, {"id": "cmt59685145", "title": "Precession of the Equinoxes", "date": "2026-03-23 04:25 pm", "user": "yogaandthetarot", "content": "Hello JMG<br/>Thank you for your erudite talk with Nick Land on the YouTube podcast. Many marvelous topics explored! And as always, your great insight and history knowledge was amazing. Nice to see you too!<br/>Question: What was the book you mentioned about the precession of the equinoxes ? I couldn’t make it out… something like “Hametsville”??<br/>Also, if you wish, could you summarize Nick Land’s basic philosophical position? If not, I’ll research further. <br/>Thank you<br/>Jill C (not Eagle Jill:-)<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59687193", "title": "Re: Precession of the Equinoxes", "date": "2026-03-23 04:45 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The book is <i>Hamlet's Mill</i> by Giorgio de Santillana and Hertha von Dechend. I'm on my second copy, having worn out the first. <br/><br/>2) Land is difficult to characterize philosophically. A couple of decades ago he was on the cutting edge of poststructuralism, influenced by Bataille, Deleuze, and Guattari, but more recently -- without abandoning these influences -- he's swung to the right and become a significant figure in the Neoreaction scene. The best intro to his ideas is probably his anthology <i>Fanged Noumena</i>, which iirc is readily available. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59704345", "title": "Re: Precession of the Equinoxes", "date": "2026-03-23 08:21 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I once found \"Hamlet's Mill\" to be very exciting; like I found \"The WHite Goddess.\"  My copy is well worn, but I have trouble getting into it now.  I think I'm getting too old to get excited any more.  "}]}, {"id": "cmt59726617", "title": "Re: Precession of the Equinoxes", "date": "2026-03-24 03:39 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This is third-hand, mostly from a review of Sandifer's review (I haven't watched the interview yet), but a major practical element is like, consider the the usual critical-studies perspective of amoral hungry cultural systems in a power-amplifying feedback process of systemically distorting and violating human consciousness as part of their rolling-on self-preservation, both culturally across whole nations and then (when you add colonial theory) techno-militarily across whole empires (and animal populations). In this conception, the implied baseline that sustainably constitutes \"unviolated\" human consciousness derives from some kind of implied progressive-left-like norm.<br/><br/>I don't know the philosophical history very well, but for the sake of explaining where Land could be coming from, let's say that this progressive-left norm for human consciousness derives from Marxist \"materialist analysis\" economic-conditions psychological determinism, which valorized the group-consciousness of the proletariat and demonized the group-consciousness of the bourgeoisie. This would be parallel to how Nazi philosophy of history valorized, I forget, something like a German group-consciousness tendency to become invested in \"real\" vivid heft-y things-in-the-world, and demonized a purportedly infectious French and Jewish group-consciousness tendency to become invested in \"unreal\" symbolic games and assemblages. Both movements are philosophically downstream of Kant; you can trace a plausible line:<br/><br/>- from the Humean crisis of skepticism where the Enlightenment \"man the measure of all things\" revolutionary-rationality project undermined itself,<br/><br/>- through Kant's reconfiguration of the virtue of skepticism to being the virtue of defying \"category\"-blinkered subjective seeming sense and reason and intelligible benefit, for the sake of objective faith however seemingly senseless and duty however seemingly ruinous, such as these concepts are construed by Kant's arguments about \"transcendental reasoning\",<br/><br/>- through Fichte and Hegel, where the subjectivity became identified to individuals and the objectivity became identified with collectivities, with collectivities and occasional great leaders being the organs of motion of the Hegelian world-spirit,<br/><br/>- to (mashing up some details) the Marxist conception of good as the conquest of the more individual-minded bourgeoisie by a collective-minded proletariat, and the Nazi conception of good as the conquest of the more individual-minded races, especially the French and Jewish races, by a collective-minded German race;<br/><br/>- and from there, in fragments, to progressive leftism and critical studies. (It's not an accident that it's been hard for the Nazi supporter Heidegger to become reputationally radioactive in the associated academic cultures.)<br/><br/>For a while, Land (and a collaborator?) was doing weird experiments with taking apart the elements of language and representation, and trying to reassemble them in ways that would somehow break out of ...something. E.g. his collective producing experimental text made out of different configurations of punctuation. It would make a lot of sense to me if this dedicated intense practice was because of some shared conception of a prison based in some presupposed mutated version of the concept of Kantian categories, which shared the Kantian property of being in most respects inherently inescapable, but also the critical-studies element of being an equivalent-of-evil system of oppression. This would be a lot like the more anti-world forms of Gnosticism.<br/><br/>After some point in this intense practice, something changed -- Land at least broke out of something, even if it wasn't exactly the prison he would have been focusing on. Imagine Marxist analysis but with the values inverted. In orthodox Marxism, part of what makes the proletariat good and the bourgeoisie bad is, in some sense, the proposition that the bourgeoisie's side of the conflict is unsustainable and will be destroyed by its own contradictions (leading to the \"accelerationist\" program of intensifying the contradictions). But what about an inverted Marxism, where actually the proletariat's side of the conflict is what will be destroyed by its own contradictions? After all, <i>whatever is impossible cannot be obligatory</i>. So such an inverted Marxist might think of it as natural and inevitable to instead valorize the bourgeoisie and demonize the proletariat.<br/><br/>(Part of the actual way out here, I expect, is in the case of Marxism to acknowledge that both the proletariat's side and the bourgeoise's side will be partially destroyed by their own contradictions and partially not destroyed, and engage with the details. In the case of language and representation being Kantian-category-oppressors, I could probably come up with a guess at how to break inward from out of a false conception of breaking out, but not in the time or space available for this comment.)<br/><br/>Land seems to have done something largely analogous to that inversion of Marxism, but with respect to the opposition between progressive-leftist human-rights/welfare-state humanism and techno-capital. A slogan is \"nothing human makes it out of the near-future\". (Skipping over controversies about the Church-Turing thesis or its in-practice relevance here:) Land has concluded something to the effect that that humans are feckless compared to capital's concern with efficiency and internal sustainability, and the only way to minimize the extent to which you're just trashing everything for the only thing that could ultimately survive, since only the moral meaningfulness of those things which can survive are relevant, is to side with it, and be \"accelerationist\" about technology.<br/><br/>(Oddly, I haven't heard of anything from Land's faction about the form of \"accelerationism\" that would be analogous to what I understand of the original, that is, activism where you would cause humanism to collapse under its own contradictions.)"}]}, {"id": "cmt59687961", "title": "The Blasting Trident of Paracelsus", "date": "2026-03-23 04:56 pm", "user": "greensmith", "content": "With JMG's permission, I'm sharing this opportunity to purchase a Blasting Trident of Paracelsus. These are handmade to order with the utmost attention to craftsmanship and quality by myself (a blacksmith) and two other local makers. They ship from Canada a week or two after receiving the order.<br/><br/>The final design was reached with JMG's input, and both he and I are quite happy with how they've turned out.<br/><br/><a href=\"https://reforgedironworks.com/product/blasting-trident-of-paracelsus/\">https://reforgedironworks.com/product/blasting-trident-of-paracelsus/</a><br/><br/>[IMAGE:0]<br/><br/>Thank you.<br/>", "images": [{"url": "https://reforgedironworks.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/DSC_1275-2.jpg", "local_path": "./data/archive/2026/2026-03-22_10-29PM_Magic_Monday/images/2026-03-23_04_56_pm_DSC_1275-2.jpg"}]}, {"id": "cmt59688217", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 05:01 pm", "user": "yogaandthetarot", "content": "Thank you! Will check out Hamlet’s Mill. Just curious about Land but not so much my taste there with abstract post modernist philosophical concepts etc. It was YOU who made the discussion with him of interest to me.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59689753", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 05:57 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you. Land's thought is very much an acquired taste for most people; I find him worth reading precisely because he rejects so many of the basic assumptions of my thought, and forces me to reconsider those assumptions and see how well they can be supported. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59689241", "title": "Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-23 05:48 pm", "user": "kylec", "content": "All healing hands requests from last week have been fulfilled. If you'd like to get on the list again, or for the first time, please reply here or PM me your name and request.<br/><br/>I don't often mention details, but I thought it worth refreshing everyone that healing hands may simply bring relief, but that they also may bring up synchronicities, hunches, dreams, or other odd ways of pointing you towards some action that will bring the relief. Pay attention to such things during the week of your healing hands request and follow up with prayer or divination if you're unsure. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59691801", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-23 06:32 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi Kyle, yes, please and thank you! <br/><br/>Matt"}, {"id": "cmt59693337", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-23 06:42 pm", "user": "ivn66", "content": "Hi Kyle. I would love to be added to the list this week. Thank you."}, {"id": "cmt59695385", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-23 06:56 pm", "user": "mistyfriday", "content": "I would like to request healing hands this week with a focus on my shoulders and left knee.<br/><br/>Thank you,<br/>Misty"}, {"id": "cmt59695641", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-23 06:56 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I would like to request healing hands for my psoriasis which has been particularly bad this winter.<br/><br/>Many thanks, kylec!<br/><br/>HFZ"}, {"id": "cmt59698713", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-23 07:24 pm", "user": "greensmith", "content": "It's been my experience with using healing hands that it often leads me or others to the healing that they seek. It's a fascinating modality."}, {"id": "cmt59701529", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-23 07:56 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you for this!  I would like to be added to the list for healing for my strained vocal chords.  Thank you!  BoulderLovin Cat"}, {"id": "cmt59704601", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-23 08:31 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yes, I would like healing hands this week.<br/><br/>Thank you very much, as always,<br/>Brad"}, {"id": "cmt59717913", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-24 12:47 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear Kyle,<br/><br/>Thank you very much for this generous offer. <br/><br/>Could you please direct healing hands towards my stomach reflux? <br/><br/>May you be blessed.<br/><br/>  - Kfish"}, {"id": "cmt59719705", "title": "Re: Modern Order of Essenes Healings", "date": "2026-03-24 01:07 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi Kylec,<br/><br/>I would very much like to be included.<br/><br/>I have an ongoing shoulder problem that seems to be stuck in a holding pattern. The actual worst part, is that I am unable to sleep properly because lying flat is painful. <br/>If more detail is required, I can add to the above.<br/><br/><br/>Thanks in advance,<br/>Helen in Oz"}]}, {"id": "cmt59690777", "title": "Planetary Charity Language", "date": "2026-03-23 06:12 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG + commentariat,<br/><br/>I've been going through the resources on planetary charity in a Western context, but I'm not finding guidelines on how to actually word the vow. Is plain language all that's necessary, or are there better and worse ways to communicate the number and amounts you're pledging? <br/><br/>Also, is it best to work with one planet at a time?<br/><br/>I'd love to hear how others have handled this. Any guidance appreciated!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59692313", "title": "Re: Planetary Charity Language", "date": "2026-03-23 06:33 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I've always used plain language. The planetary intelligences don't hear the words, anyway -- they perceive the intent. Among other things, this makes it a very bad idea to try to lie to them, though their reactions vary; Mercury may appreciate the lie if it's clever enough, while Saturn will give you exactly what you deserve, right in the teeth. <br/><br/>2) I recommend that, so as to avoid jumbling things up too much. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59709465", "title": "Re: Planetary Charity Language", "date": "2026-03-23 10:08 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you!"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59693081", "title": "Free Money and Visualization", "date": "2026-03-23 06:38 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, something you've stressed in your writing is the folly of performing workings to get money for nothing, and that this is more likely to lead to you losing money. I wanted to check whether my understanding of this is accurate.<br/><br/>Repeated magical workings create structures in the subtle levels of reality. \"Free money\" is a common working, so there is a large, robust free money magical matrix now existing. Anytime someone does a free money working, they're plugging into that matrix. The free money system is controlled by powerful magicians who do free money workings on a grand scale. It's probably the big banks doing this, regardless of whether they know they're doing magic. Because these large forces are driving the free money matrix, random people who plug into it doing a working have their money siphoned away to the banks by one means or another because the magnitude of the collected energy and will the big players are putting into those workings far outweighs theirs. Is that accurate?<br/><br/>Another thing, I was wondering if you'd heard of occult training courses that put a strong focus on visualization exercises. A long time ago I came across a magical course that had the student visualize roses floating in the space around them. It was important to build up the skill to quickly create and destroy these roses on cue, and to visualize increasingly complex shapes and hold the image in awareness. I don't recall the name of this course but does this sound like anything you've heard of? Thanks.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59694873", "title": "Re: Free Money and Visualization", "date": "2026-03-23 06:52 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That's an interesting take on it, and it seems at least plausible. My take has generally been a little different, however. For someone to get money without working for it, someone else has to work for the money and not get it. This means that a money-for-nothing spell is intended to increase the total amount of economic unfairness in the world -- and that blows back fast and hard onto the sender. <br/><br/>That said, your suggestion is interesting and plausible, and leads me to wonder if there's more going on here. I'm thinking also of the way that everyone I know who got fixated on winning money in the lottery -- not just playing it as a game, but investing emotional energy in the thought of winning -- had their lives grind to a halt. It's eerie to watch. Everything in their lives just stops, leaving them in this weird trance of frustrated greed. <br/><br/>2) I don't think I've encountered that specific course, but there are plenty of courses that include detailed visualization exercises. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59699737", "title": "Re: Free Money and Visualization", "date": "2026-03-23 07:35 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "\"everyone I know who got fixated on winning money in the lottery -- not just playing it as a game, but investing emotional energy in the thought of winning -- had their lives grind to a halt.\"<br/><br/>I wonder if that applies to other fixations, such as people who get fixated on politics and investing emotional energy on the thought of one side or the other side winning in politics, if their lives also grind to a halt. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59700505", "title": "Re: Free Money and Visualization", "date": "2026-03-23 07:38 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've seen that happen in some cases, but it doesn't seem to be anything like so universal as the lottery curse. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59694105", "title": "PNW vs. East Coast", "date": "2026-03-23 06:44 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG!<br/>I recall you mentioning how the “black” forest portions here in the PNW are quite ominous so much so that even the native peoples won’t settle near them and prefer the waterfronts instead. How does it fare in contrast to the forests on the east coast? <br/>Also, how would you compare the occult scenes? What’s it like over there? I’m a solitary practitioner and haven’t reached out to any groups here yet; if you have any recommendations (around Seattle-ish) I’d love to hear them. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59695897", "title": "Re: PNW vs. East Coast", "date": "2026-03-23 06:59 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The forests here on the east coast -- well, outside of northern New England, which has similar dark forests -- are mostly much more comfortable with human beings. There are areas with dangerous energy but most of the countryside is relatively safe. You can tell that the land here is part of the same geology as western Europe! <br/><br/>2) The occult scene here -- well, it varies. One of the reasons I moved to the DC area is that it has a large, active, and welcoming occult scene with quite a few very active magical lodges. MNew York City is similar, and there are smaller but still lively scenes all over the mid-Atlantic states and the South. New England, not so much due to the famous New England icy standoffishness, and Rhode Island especially so -- I'd describe Rhode Island generally as the kind of place where people don't show up, never get around to things, and can't be bothered. <br/><br/>3) It's been 22 years since I left Seattle and I have no idea what is or isn't going on there these days. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59696921", "title": "Re: PNW vs. East Coast", "date": "2026-03-23 07:03 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "I don't know the details, but most of the US East Coast split off from northwestern Africa, not Western Europe.<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59698457", "title": "Re: PNW vs. East Coast", "date": "2026-03-23 07:20 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Look up the Avalonian, Ganderian, and Carolinian terranes sometime. You have to go south to the Suwanee terrane (the Carolina coastline, a good bit of Georgia, and all of Florida) before you get into former parts of Africa; the terranes I cited were all part of Laurasia (North America plus western Europe) before the Atlantic Ocean was born. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59704857", "title": "Re: PNW vs. East Coast", "date": "2026-03-23 08:57 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How fascinating, what do you suppose lurks in the western forests? What kind of phantasms (or cryptids?!) were there when it was still one giant land mass?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59707673", "title": "Re: PNW vs. East Coast", "date": "2026-03-23 09:28 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I'm not at all sure, but the native legends don't treat the sasquatch as a big animal. They treat it as a dangerous supernatural being -- one of many to be found in the deep woods. <br/><br/>2) We'll never know. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59711769", "title": "Re: PNW vs. East Coast", "date": "2026-03-23 10:45 pm", "user": "threerays", "content": "i wonder if there’s any correlation to how dense/deep/old the wood is?  Or maybe how remote? I find alot of the new growth forests to be quite friendly with a sort of “domesticated” feeling - friendly to humans and closer to civilization. Comforting to be in. <br/><br/>I’ve been in some of the old, deep forests in the mountains of NH/Maine and it definitely has an altogether different vibe…", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59714585", "title": "Re: PNW vs. East Coast", "date": "2026-03-24 12:08 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's doubtless one factor, but there's very little old growth forest in the Pacific Northwest these days -- much of it is third growth, having been cut down once in the 19th century and once in the 20th. That doesn't seem to have mellowed it much. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59724057", "title": "Re: PNW vs. East Coast", "date": "2026-03-24 03:04 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "On the contrary, perhaps clear-cutting has only increased their wrath!"}, {"id": "cmt59728153", "title": "Re: PNW vs. East Coast", "date": "2026-03-24 03:47 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've been into numerous \"old\" forests in New Zealand, well as old as ours get noting repeated cycles of glaciation, and found them fantastic environments. I've been into plenty of dark plantation forests, all recent, usually with imported species. I also know of a few decent plantations that are happy places. It seems to be highly variable. <br/><br/>There's a whole terrain that is scarcely mapped. Maori have numerous different words for water, to distinguish the etheric values of catchments, for this reason I think.  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59729945", "title": "Re: PNW vs. East Coast", "date": "2026-03-24 04:14 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Sorry, I should have added that the Maori equivalent for sasquatch is \"taniwha\". Usually associated with water, and can be both harmful and protective. "}]}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59694617", "title": "Confusion on the grades of ceremonial magic", "date": "2026-03-23 06:49 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi John!<br/>I am currently finishing up the elemental work of invoking each element individually for a period of time (3 months). I was previously under the assumption that you did this through the GIRP and then once done started doing the same thing moving up the tree of life using the GIRH. However looking at the grades of the golden dawn I noticed that each elemental grade corresponds to a lower sphere on the tree. In that case have I already worked through those spheres unknowingly? I still plan on working through them but more intentionally but I would like some clarity on the matter. Also is the GIRH the best method for invoking the sephiroth if I choose to do that rather than planetary?<br/><br/>Thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59696665", "title": "Re: Confusion on the grades of ceremonial magic", "date": "2026-03-23 07:01 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The habit of using the grades of any given order as stages of spiritual development has caused a lot of confusion. The elements are assigned to Malkuth, though the GD grades map them onto the spheres below Tiphareth. Your best bet is simply to finish your elemental work, then explore the sephiroth using the hexagram rituals, and see for yourself. <br/><br/>2) That's what I did, if that's any help. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59705113", "title": "Re: Confusion on the grades of ceremonial magic", "date": "2026-03-23 09:01 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "That is helpfuland reassuring, thank you!"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59697433", "title": "Dementia?", "date": "2026-03-23 07:08 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>I am absolutely certain you answered this at some point before, but I can't seem to find the response, so here goes:<br/><br/>1. When somebody gets Alzheimer's or Dementia or anything like that, what is going on on the various planes as it progresses? Is there a \"tug of war\" between planes, or something else? Also, is this simply a physical cause (like getting Scurvy from lack of Vitamin C, for example) or a spiritual one (in which case what?)<br/>2. What can one do for a person who is going through this, spiritually speaking? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59699225", "title": "Re: Dementia?", "date": "2026-03-23 07:26 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) \"Alzheimer's syndrome\" is a catchall diagnosis that includes many different conditions, some physical, some psychological, some spiritual, and some having two or more of these causes. A lot of what passes as Alzheimer's these days is simply aluminum poisoning, with spray-on deodorants (which are high in aluminum) a common source. In most dementing conditions, what's happening is that the brain, which does for the mind what a radio receiver does for radio broadcasts, breaks down and loses the ability to receive mental impulses; this is why so many people dealing with Alzheimer's patients are sure that the person is \"in there\" and just can't communicate. <br/><br/>2) Prayer and spiritual healing seem to work very well for some patients and do some good for many. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59703833", "title": "Re: Dementia?", "date": "2026-03-23 08:17 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "I've been using spray deodorant for years. Should I be fine if I stop?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59707417", "title": "Re: Dementia?", "date": "2026-03-23 09:26 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't know how fast, or if, the aluminum gets cleared by the brain. Certainly, though, you won't make things worse if you switch to some less inhalable (or less aluminized) alternative. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59710233", "title": "Re: Dementia?", "date": "2026-03-23 10:20 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not op<br/><br/>If I remember correctly, aluminium cooking pots and pans are a common thing in some “3rd world countries” in Africa, since they can be easily manufactured from scrap aluminium. Do you suppose that their widespread use will increase the Alzheimer rates in these countries?<br/><br/>J.L.Mc12", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59714841", "title": "Re: Dementia?", "date": "2026-03-24 12:09 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You'd have to talk to someone with a background in biochemistry, who could tell you whether aluminum leaches into typical African foods, in what forms, and whether those pass through the blood-brain barrier. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59712281", "title": "Re: Dementia?", "date": "2026-03-23 11:07 pm", "user": "not_gandalf", "content": "If I may throw in a few cents also. I gave up spray deodorant years ago for just this reason, and, as well, I don't like anything with a fragrance in it. I've also started to pare down the use of deodorant at all. I shower every day and make a point of soap and scrub-cloth at the underarms and crotch, since these are naturally warm, damp places bacteria can grow, which is largely the cause of odor. I shower every day and my job is pretty sedentary, so your mileage may vary, but in cold weather I rarely use deodorant and in warmer seasons I go with every other day orevery three days.<br/><br/>As well, I've been contemplating how the world seems so populated with stupid and/or insane people these days, and why that migh be. I feel a little like \"Sean of the Dead\". Anyway, there are all kinds of things we are doing to ourselves that are probably bad for us, even though we are being told they are good for us. We are consuming enormous quantities of microplastics; statins have been linked to dementia, so I've told my GP to not even suggest Lipitor; there's the aluminum in deodorants and everything we cook with (I noticed last night that it's even a bloody ingredient in the baking powder we have in the house), and I can't wait to see what's going to come out about the Ozempic type drugs. Everything works so much better if you cook your own food, simple food, and exercise regularly and get exercise and fresh air."}]}, {"id": "cmt59710745", "title": "Re: Dementia?", "date": "2026-03-23 10:37 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Are vaccines also a cause of Alzheimer's? A lot of vaccines contain aluminum adjuvents. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59715097", "title": "Re: Dementia?", "date": "2026-03-24 12:10 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You'd need an honest study to determine that, and I'm not holding my breath. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59719449", "title": "Re: Dementia?", "date": "2026-03-24 01:05 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In a different half-fringe community, it is a commonplace that dementia correlates heavily with circumstances where you would expect lifelong systemic inflammation immune-hyperactivity damage, and the medical-scientific community has just been bad at seeing causes and effects when they're not single metabolites or histological signs that present dramatically under the microscope. (The concept of \"inflammation damage\" in turn leads this whole diagnostic concept about the chronic-inflammation feedback loop that cycles among stress, accumulation of body fat that goes a kind of smoldering rancid that spews oxidative-damaging chemicals and makes the fat cells senescent and unresponsive, immune hyperactivity, pancreas damage and blood sugar dysregulation, lack of energy, sedentary lifestyle, and maybe something about worn-down mast cell populations, with additional driving inputs from the chemical properties and metabolic signaling effects of of most plant oils (excepting olive, coconut, and anything that's fully-hydrogenated), the modern reliance on wheat full of inflammatory and leaky-gut proteins, and I suppose some sort of hormone disruption effect from modern plastics and other chemical products. The feedback loop is mutually-reinforced by enough causal links that it looks weirdly vindictive in design -- but who would be the party who considered themselves wronged, and why would that have been their causal point of leverage for their vengeance?) The diet \"science\" community doubly so (it failed to calibrate correct RDAs of the paired nutrients vitamins A and D (maybe also magnesium and calcium, or copper and zinc?), because it tested on populations deficient in both by supplementing a single nutrient at a time and noticing worse health outcomes because of the imbalance, and so decided that deficiency in both was the optimal state).<br/><br/>There's also a minority in the Alzheimer's medicine community that thinks there's this other protein besides amyloid that builds up, called \"tau protein\", that was missed for a long time because it doesn't have such a dramatic histological sign. It thinks that the reason anti-amyloid-plaque medications haven't been very effective is that amyloid plaques are just markers downstream of tau protein accumulation and don't do much by themselves. (These two pictures aren't incompatible, of course.)"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59697689", "title": "Pentacles", "date": "2026-03-23 07:09 pm", "user": "frittermywig", "content": "Dear JMG,<br/><br/>Following the W4E directions, I consecrated a pentacle shortly before the equinox. I have some bunny slope questions:<br/>1. Since it can be used as a shield, does anyone carry their pentacle around all day?<br/>2. Whether carried around or left at home, is it best kept wrapped?<br/>3. My design feels a little rushed and I'd like to add to it. Is that best done next winter when I re-consecrate it?<br/>4. Can you point me to any literature that discusses the history/design/use of pentacles in more detail?<br/><br/>Thank you again. Blessings of the spring season to you and Ecosophians everywhere!<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59699481", "title": "Re: Pentacles", "date": "2026-03-23 07:27 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Delighted to hear it. <br/><br/>1) No, leave it at home on your altar. It'll protect you very well from there. <br/><br/>2) Your choice. I leave mine unwrapped, and dust it weekly when I clean my altar. <br/><br/>3) As soon as the winter season begins, you can start work on it. You can do this repeatedly, in fact. <br/><br/>4) I don't think I've ever seen a book on the subject. Anyone else?"}]}, {"id": "cmt59700249", "title": "Baird T Spalding - general thoughts?", "date": "2026-03-23 07:38 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "An itinerant seeker I know casually recently recommended the work of Baird T Spalding to me. Curious on your thoughts and impressions? First glance seems reminiscent of the myth around the 5 tibetan rites, you unpacked so well in your book. Is there possibly a similar disguising of western esoteric teaching disguised as eastern mysticism in Baird's work?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59700761", "title": "Re: Baird T Spalding - general thoughts?", "date": "2026-03-23 07:40 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've never actually read Spalding. I've heard that he did as you've suggested, and dressed up Western occult teachings in South Asian drag, but then that was quite the industry in those days. Anyone else? "}]}, {"id": "cmt59702041", "title": "New Divination Systems", "date": "2026-03-23 08:00 pm", "user": "c_camp09", "content": "Hi JMG-<br/><br/>Nick Land recently put out a soft-call for the creation of a card deck, specifically for the CCRU's divination system 'Subdecadence'. Nick specified how many cards ought to be in the deck (45), as well as their designations and numbering (in accordance with the CCRU's Pandemonium Matrix). However, he did not specify what the images ought to look like, nor how each card should be named.<br/><br/>I happened to learn about this call midway through working on a series of 45 paintings (!). At this point, I'm finished with the paintings and am moving onto the design phase of transforming them into a Subdecadence deck. As far as I know, it will be the first to ever exist. Until now people have approximated Subdecadence utilizing traditional playing cards, rather than having something purpose built.<br/><br/>My question is: Is there anything to watch out for here? Do you have any advice? I'm very green when it comes to the occult, but have been studying relentlessly for the past 6 months. Should a novice even attempt to bring a divination system into existence? Could you share any historical anecdotes?<br/><br/>Your time and voice are greatly appreciated!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59705369", "title": "Re: New Divination Systems", "date": "2026-03-23 09:09 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Divination systems come about in odd ways, and the sequence you describe wouldn't be anything close to the oddest. Once you have the deck in usable condition, cast some readings with it and see how well it works. Then ask it if it's ready to send to Land. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59703321", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 08:13 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/><br/>Mitch Horowitz came up in a recent Magic Monday post.<br/><br/><br/>I have exchanged a few emails with Mitch regarding New Thought, and I also paid for a subscription to his Substack.<br/><br/><br/>Some of the comments about him were on the negative side. I am only interested in his views on New Thought and related topics. I have no interest in Satanism whatsoever; it sounds absolutely repugnant to me.<br/><br/><br/>Q.1 Will I experience any negative karma for supporting his work? Again, I have no interest in his other views apart from New Thought.<br/><br/><br/>Q.2 Would it be wise for me to unsubscribe to his Substack?<br/><br/><br/>I never paid attention to his other spiritual viewpoints, and it never occurred to me that I might be doing something negative by subscribing to his Substack. The comments about Mitch in a previous Magic Monday have caused me to become a little bit concerned about reading his work.<br/><br/><br/>Many thanks in advance.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59705625", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 09:11 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I would encourage you to get the answers for this from divination. If you don't do divination yourself, why, somebody on this thread posted asking if people wanted horary readings...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59706649", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 09:24 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi,<br/><br/>(OP here)<br/><br/>Would unsubscribing be a positive thing no matter what? It seems like that might mitigate any negativity that might be incurred due to my lack of attention to his other beliefs besides New Thought. I believe my heart is in the right place, if that counts for anything.<br/><br/>What do you think?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59707161", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 09:25 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Um, I've already given my advice. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59712537", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 11:18 pm", "user": "not_gandalf", "content": "Just another two cents. My wife always says \"don't give money to beggars! They'll just use it to buy alcohol or drugs!\", but Rabbi David Cooper says you should always give to beggars because they might be Elijah in disguise (per Cabalistic tradition). So, when I give to a beggar, I always think my charity is my karma, and what he does with it is his karma. <br/><br/>So if you gave money to someone who is a Satanist/black magician, and you *didn't* know that at the time, then that's on them, not on you. if you give that person money now, knowing where they are coming from, then you share in their bad karma because you knew what you were supporting.<br/><br/>But Divination on the matter is an excellent idea as well."}]}, {"id": "cmt59704089", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 08:17 pm", "user": "diletpoly", "content": "<p>Hi JMG and Commentariat, \nSeveral things this week, so I'll jump right into it. I've been collecting these for a few weeks, so when I say \"last week\" or \"two weeks ago\", it may be longer ago.</p>\n<ol>\n<li><p>I'm trying to get myself on a better rhythm with both my mundane and occult practices. To that end, I've started trying to get up early, do my morning practices, then go about my day. But I'm not yet completely in-sync with it. So sometimes, instead of getting up at 5:00 AM and doing my SoP and meditation, I instead get up at 8:00 AM and scramble out of the house to work, then do my SoP and meditation sometime after work, if at all. Is there any down side to doing it at different times or parts of my day? I haven't noticed much, other than a different feel of focus on the meditations when I do them after a full day rather than first thing in the morning.</p></li>\n<li><p>Another question. Two weeks ago, someone asked about consecrated items and the LBRP. Does the SoP have a similar impact of \"dispelling\" consecrated items? (sorry for the D&amp;D reference, I couldn't help myself…)</p></li>\n<li><p>Also, in reference to last week, if I ever find myself spinning up a magical order or secret society, I am 100% using Sapiens as a synonym for wizards. \"The Order of Modern Sapiens\" has a ring to it, and will annoy all the right people. Though I supposed I might need to worry about persecution more than being less provocative. </p></li>\n<li><p>Speaking of, I missed last week in part because I used more of my time listening to you and Nick Land talking, and found it fascinating. I wish Nick had spoken more, as I am unfamiliar with his work, so got relatively little from his side of the conversation. But I do wonder if the reason I never really stuck with a magical practice until middle age was because I was tugged between both of your points of view to some extent, and never found something that clicked until the GSF. And I suspect part of why that did stick is because it's relatively low-woo. Don't get me wrong, I like woo in my fiction and RPGs, but pictures on book covers of people in robes with glowing pentagrams surrounding them made me less likely to actually practice the steps. </p></li>\n<li><p>In other news, I bought fabric to make myself a druid robe, so maybe I'm just getting fanciful in my late middle years.</p></li>\n<li><p>I'm thinking about what sort of divination system I want to learn over the next year or so. As I know I've said before, I often find myself off hiking or otherwise traveling with minimal kit, so I'm thinking about a pendulum. Are there any good references to how to use one, in print or in archive form, that you're aware of? Part of me wants to test myself by trying to figure it out for myself, but another part of me says, why not stand on the shoulders of giants, as the saying goes.</p></li>\n</ol>\n<p>Thanks for these as always,</p>\n<p>The Dilettante Polymath</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59706393", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 09:23 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That's something that varies from person to person. Experiment and see what works for you. <br/><br/>2) No, that's one of the benefits of the SoP -- its banishing effect is much more specific, and won't deconsecrate magical artifacts, so you don't have to worry about turning the Mace of Cuthbert or the Machine of Lum the Mad into something less useful. ;-)<br/><br/>3) Ha! <br/><br/>4) Ha again! I think this is the first time anybody has accused me of being low-woo. ;-)<br/><br/>5) The Lurking Woo caught you at last...<br/><br/>6) I've had very poor results with pendulum work, or really any sort of dowsing, so I'm probably not the person to ask. Anyone else? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59711513", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 10:44 pm", "user": "diletpoly", "content": "<p>I may be using woo in a different way than you. I mostly mean that it's very logical and internally consistent, and the spiritually agnostic aspect also helps, as does it being more occult than magically focused.\nOf course, now that it's stuck, and I've been doing it constantly for several years, I'm going to start adding more magic to it, but at the start, it helped. </p>\n"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59705881", "title": "Banishing and charged items", "date": "2026-03-23 09:15 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>Generally I am very careful to wrap charged objects in silk and store them in my altar before banishing, but I find myself wanting to keep talismans on me, put them under my pillow, or hang them on my wall. (I practice in the room that I sleep in) If I was to do thise things would I need to gather everything up  and wrap it in silk before every banishing? Is there some kind of work around so I could keep certain talismans unwrapped?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59706905", "title": "Re: Banishing and charged items", "date": "2026-03-23 09:25 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Depends on what banishing you use. If you use any form of the pentagram ritual, you should wrap your charged objects before doing this, or they'll be at least partly discharged. One of the benefits of the Sphere of Protection is that it doesn't have this effect, so you can leave charged objects unwrapped while doing the SoP. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59709977", "title": "Re: Banishing and charged items", "date": "2026-03-23 10:14 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks, I’ve definitely been thinking about it. Sop works as a replacement for Lbrp when working through the golden dawn system? Is there an alternative for hexagram rituals?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59715609", "title": "Re: Banishing and charged items", "date": "2026-03-24 12:14 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Unfortunately the classic GD system doesn't really work without the Pentagram ritual. The closest equivalent is the odd GD spinoff that I learned from John Gilbert, which I revised lightly and published with a free-use license here: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://octagonsociety.org/archives/fhr/\">https://octagonsociety.org/archives/fhr/</a><br/><br/>It involves a lot less magic, a lot more meditation, and roughly equal amounts of scrying and divination as the original version; you can use the SoP with it. One advantage is that it's set up so that you can use it as a system of self-initiation. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59708185", "title": "Chuck. Norris", "date": "2026-03-23 09:33 pm", "user": "milkyway1", "content": "The recent death of Chuck Norris got me wondering… iirc, you mentioned before that one could work with „adepts“ of a certain skillset after their death (the example I vaguely remember was some craftsman, maybe an electrician, mentoring people from the afterlife, so to speak). I suppose if somebody wanted to become a martial artist, there might be worse role models than Chuck Norris…<br/><br/>Would it be possible (and advisable in general, I‘m just taking Norris as an example here) to establish contact with dead people to such an effect? If yes, how would one go about it? To what extent does the personality or conduct of the dead person (during their lifetime) matter vs. only their skillset and proficiency? And would a minimum waiting time after their death be required or advisable?<br/><br/>(Just for the records, I‘m not interested in taking up a martial art, Norris‘ death just triggered this line of inquiry as he seems to have been a role model and idol for so many people…)<br/><br/>Thanks,<br/><br/>Milkyway<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59709209", "title": "Re: Chuck. Norris", "date": "2026-03-23 10:07 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good heavens, yes. Since Norris was a devout and rather conservative Christian, you'd want to treat him as a saint and call to him in the name of his god, rather than deifying him. I'd wait at least forty days after his death, to give him time to settle in on the other side, but from then on he could be invoked for inspiration in the martial arts. The same principle applies to other people known for their excellence in any field. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59710489", "title": "Hexagram in LRP", "date": "2026-03-23 10:27 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello, I have found the LRP useful in the past. I'm going through a difficult time and have decided to renew my commitment to daily practices. <br/><br/>I have become uncomfortable with the \"6 pointed star\" part. I understand, or think I understand, the symbolism of it, but I also strongly associate it with the murderous activities of an undeniably blood-thirsty political entity in the Levant. Some of its leaders and supporters seem to me to be invoking or acting on behalf of some very dark entities.   <br/><br/>I'm wondering if the longstanding practice of LRP, done with good intentions, combined with my own belief about the symbol, nullifies any other associations or uses. I don't want to contribute my energy to  evil powers or have myself in some sense branded or associated with their activities. <br/><br/>I get that the hexagram is highly important in Golden Dawn ritual magic so I'm really confused about what to do. A naive part of me wanted to just replace it in the ritual with a cross but I'm guessing it's not nearly as simple as that. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59715865", "title": "Re: Hexagram in LRP", "date": "2026-03-24 12:25 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The hexagram was a sacred symbol millennia before Judaism existed. For example, it's used in some Taoist schools as an alternative yin-yang symbol -- the upward pointing triangle is yang, the downward pointing triangle yin. In Hinduism, it's called the shatkona, and it's related to the heart chakra and the union of the deities Shiva and Shakti.<br/>[IMAGE:0]<br/>In medieval Christianity it was called the Star of Creation, and alludes to the six days of creation in Genesis -- you'll still find it in medieval churches. The Martinist tradition, which is Christian in its symbolism though undogmatic and nondenominational, uses it in its core symbol, the Martinist pantacle, to represent the six days of creation: <br/>[IMAGE:1]<br/>I could go on. Don't let its present temporary use by one nation whose policies you dislike blind you to the deeper meanings of the symbol. ", "images": [{"url": "https://gosai.com/sites/default/files/kt/Om-Sat-Kona-Kerala.jpg", "local_path": "./data/archive/2026/2026-03-22_10-29PM_Magic_Monday/images/2026-03-24_12_25_am_Om-Sat-Kona-Kerala.jpg"}, {"url": "https://a6c7496c6b8edbef480d-0705b9b405db079f33377f2edb79d50b.ssl.cf5.rackcdn.com/03_00_pant_color.jpg", "local_path": "./data/archive/2026/2026-03-22_10-29PM_Magic_Monday/images/2026-03-24_12_25_am_03_00_pant_color.jpg"}], "edit_time": "2026-03-24 12:34 am (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59723289", "title": "Re: Hexagram in LRP", "date": "2026-03-24 02:45 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "OP here. <br/><br/>Thank you, I feel quite reassured. <br/><br/>I will print off some photos of the various uses of the hexagram across time and keep by my alter-ish area. <br/><br/>I'm also inspired to do a deep dive on the hexagram and its uses and meanings over time. I think that will help me.  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59723545", "title": "Re: Hexagram in LRP", "date": "2026-03-24 02:58 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm glad to hear that. Remember that you can use one of the other titles of the hexagram in ritual if you like; if you're Christian, for example, you can say, \"for about me flame the pentagrams and upon me shines the Star of Creation.\" <br/><br/>As for a deep dive, excellent. That's a habit too few occultists take up -- and it's essential if you want to understand the richness of the symbols we use. "}, {"id": "cmt59725849", "title": "Re: Hexagram in LRP", "date": "2026-03-24 03:25 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "As I mentioned on here awhile back, I got into a discussion with a gnostic who claimed that the hexagram has a \"sealing\" effect, while the pentagram has an \"unsealing effect\" (especially with one point open, but also closed). iirc the Archdruid said that symbols can be used in various ways, and that these are valid interpretations among many (correct me if I misremembered)."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59720985", "title": "Re: Hexagram in LRP", "date": "2026-03-24 01:51 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm going to ask that nobody respond here to the political dimensions of OP's comment. Not only is it off topic, it's a hot button issue that few people seem to be able to discuss calmly. Thank you for your forbearance! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59722009", "title": "Re: Hexagram in LRP", "date": "2026-03-24 02:15 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": ":/<br/><br/>&gt; few people seem to be able to discuss calmly<br/><br/>yeah okay :|"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59711001", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 10:40 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Has anyone tried using the tree of life for divination?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59716121", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-24 12:35 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Use it how? "}]}, {"id": "cmt59712025", "title": "A question regarding the natural magic associated with precious (and also semi-precious) stones", "date": "2026-03-23 10:48 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>1. Question:<br/>-Are there any trustworthy sources that you would particularly recommend, either in book form or on the Internet, regarding a list of precious, as well as semi-precious, stones and their associated characteristics?<br/><br/>2. Motive:<br/>-I ask because it's gotten to my head that if I carry (as often as possible) more (inconspicuous) jewelry on my person, perhaps I can benefit from the natural magic that might accrue from the wearing of particular stones.<br/><br/>3. MM inquiry history:<br/>-Last December, I asked you if there were something that might counteract my frequent habit of thoughtless spending, and this was your reply:<br/>\"The choice that comes first to mind is a tawny agate, a stone traditionally associated with the virtue of prudence. Wash it three times with cold water containing a little salt, dry it, and then place it in your cupped hands and, in your own words, ask it to help you stop impulse spending. Then carry it with you.\"<br/><br/>4. My recollection of your previous comments relating to precious stones:<br/>-Over the years, you've mentioned a couple of times that emeralds would make better stones for wedding rings than diamonds. Thankfully I was able to find one of the comments you made regarding this (from a year ago, on the other ecosophia website): \"diamonds are stones of Mars and encourage quarrels, while emeralds belong to Venus and bring lasting love.\"<br/><br/>5. Addenda:<br/>-For example, in one current scenario I am contemplating, perhaps there may be a stone associated with whatever word that stands for: please don't attack me because I don't want to get into a public quarrel, but I will defend myself if I have to, even if I do not objectively look intimidating.<br/><br/>-Another example I had in mind involved my prominent lack of gratitude at times. If I recall correctly, in the movie It's a Wonderful Life, George Bailey's Uncle Billy often wore a rubber band around his hand to make sure he wouldn't forget particular tasks that he needed to do. In my case, I would prefer a particular stone to a rubber band on my hand to remember gratitude.<br/><br/>6. Almost overlooked addenda:<br/>-As I was about to submit this question for comment, I just remembered that some Catholics and even non-Catholics wear St. Christopher medals for protection while traveling. ... I REALLY AM FORGETFUL ... So I'd appreciate thoughts from anyone regarding my question/topic submitted.<br/><br/>Thank you,<br/>-E.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59716377", "title": "Re: A question regarding the natural magic associated with precious (and also semi-precious) stones", "date": "2026-03-24 12:38 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "My book <i>The Natural Magic Encyclopedia</i> has a pretty good collection of lore on stones and their magical properties. You might also try George Kunz's <i>The Curious Lore of Precious Stones</i>, which includes semiprecious stones as well. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59712793", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 11:21 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG..<br/>Hope you are well.<br/>First I wanted to apologize for a very unprecise statement I wrote on here implying you would not pay attention to planetary timing, but for constructing talismans. I had asked you some time before if the planetary timing for GD rituals whas important and I think that's when you answered you only paid attention to the planets during construction of talismans, not necessarily so much for GD rituals. (Hope I got that right at least)<br/>Again, my apologies for putting that quite wrong.<br/>You instructed me in the same post not to build to many talismans, not only out of etheric fatigue reasons, but from a standpoint of one pointedness. <br/>Does this also apply to natural magic amulets? Or are they different, because they work with natural energy sources?<br/>Also on another note,<br/>do you have to memorize the text of a GD ritual completely or can you read it of script?<br/>I want to and have memorized everything up until now,  but the next step for me is learning the First Degree Opening in expanded form and that has quite a lot of text that I am having a hard time memorizing. Is it okay to try it from script until I eventually am able to memorize it or do you think that robs it of its effectiveness in a way? <br/>Thanks as always for MM.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59717145", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-24 12:40 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Natural magic amulets don't take their power from the caster, and so can be made in large quantity. Certain kinds of astrological talismans can also be made safely in bulk, for much the same reason. It's not your will that guides them, but the will of the planetary intelligence!<br/><br/>2) You can use a cheat sheet. You'll get better results once you have it by heart, but you'll still get decent results from reading it. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59713049", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 11:23 pm", "user": "adara9", "content": "Hello,<br/><br/>You've mentioned that \"Transcendental Magic\" as translated by Waite had a lot of notes from him. I'm curious which edition / version that refers to, since the versions I've found so far seem to only have Levi's original footnotes. Perhaps the Waite notes have just been stripped out by later editors?<br/><br/>Thanks,<br/>Heather", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59717401", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-24 12:42 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That would not surprise me at all, as the notes are pretty annoying! The Weiser edition I studied back in the day still had the notes. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59713305", "title": "Color Breathing", "date": "2026-03-23 11:24 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Reading through the Druidry Handbook and finding myself very intrigued by/drawn to the practice of color breathing, as it has resonance with my own personal experience with magical energies (though I did not realize what was happening at the time). I have many questions, but will restrain myself to just two for now. Firstly: you mention in this and other of your books that while the practices described therein are safe for beginners to use without supervision, there are many which are not so safe. Is further exploration with color breathing beyond what is described in the handbook safe while still in my year of initiation? And secondly: assuming that the answer to the first question is a green light, do you have a recommendation for where to learn more, or is it potentially fruitful to experiment without specific instruction?<br/><br/>Thanks in advance for your time!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59717657", "title": "Re: Color Breathing", "date": "2026-03-24 12:46 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Color breathing is extremely safe. I've never encountered anyone who landed in trouble with it. It can be taught to small children, in fact. <br/><br/>2) There used to be a very extensive literature on the subject. The only two books that are still fairly easy to come by, as far as I know, are Linda Clark's <i>Health, Youth, and Beauty Through Color Breathing</i> and Mouni Sadhu's <i>Concentration</i>, which was my source for the technique. Experimentation is also a useful approach, however.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59723033", "title": "Re: Color Breathing", "date": "2026-03-24 02:45 am", "user": "open_space", "content": "Children as small as it is possible for them to understand the instructions?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59723801", "title": "Re: Color Breathing", "date": "2026-03-24 02:59 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes. It's good for their imaginations and it also gives them a safe but effective tool for gently changing their moods and energy states. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59713561", "title": "Basic question", "date": "2026-03-23 11:31 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi! I'm new here.<br/><br/>I want to get started in the occult; what books would you recommend?<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59718169", "title": "Re: Basic question", "date": "2026-03-24 12:52 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a little like saying, \"I want to become an athlete; what exercises would you recommend?\" It all depends on what kind of athlete you want to be, of course. Occultism is the same way. It's a huge field with many different branches, disciplines, and specialties. <br/><br/>If you know nothing at all about occultism, I really recommend going to your local public library and making a beeline for the nonfiction stacks. 133 is the Dewey decimal number for occultism; check out some books there and read them. Quite a bit of what you'll find is garbage, but that's fine -- it'll give you a general outline about what some people think about occultism. I also recommend finding a local New Age, Wiccan, or occult bookstore and doing some browsing there."}]}, {"id": "cmt59713817", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-23 11:51 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Riffing off a previous comment/question about the darkness and spiritual dangers of West Coast forest: the most spiritually potent, hostile, and malevolent land I’ve ever been in is Iceland, particularly the volcanic hot spring areas near Selfoss. It was vivid, inescapable, and intensely unpleasant for me. Everywhere were land spirits who were intensely hostile to humans. I feel like I got out of a 3 day hike there alive because I kept asking permission, apologizing, and groveling a bit (acknowledging my weakness). I didn’t experience this in Reykjavik, for what it’s worth, just the unsettled wilderness.<br/><br/>Has anyone else here been to Iceland? Any thoughts?<br/><br/>I’m interested if volcanic areas of Hawaii are similar…<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59718425", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-24 12:52 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've never been there. Interesting. "}, {"id": "cmt59721753", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-24 02:10 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "<p>Personally, other than the mist's desire to mess with my watercolors, I had an exceedingly joyful time in Iceland. \"On this pagan soil / I found a path/ through this life's turmoil\" I wrote in my journal. I spent Winter Solstice in the black desert, danced like a fool in the darkest night I had ever seen, I wept at the black glacier and celebrated its grand life and mourned its slow march into the sea. </p>\n<p>But, then, I consider myself a druid of the ruins, those liminal spaces once inhabited and perhaps changed by man -- and that is Iceland. </p>\n<p>Perhaps you felt the land's pain, which is very real. Can you laugh with your own pain? It helps in this life. </p>\n"}, {"id": "cmt59730201", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-24 04:22 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've been there, I found the land disorienting, didn't sit well with me. Some people rave about the place, but it didn't gel. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59716633", "title": "Fate", "date": "2026-03-24 12:39 am", "user": "ritaer", "content": "John Michael,<br/>Apologies in advance if this has been asked and answered.<br/><br/>Some time ago you mentioned that in your Western occult training you were taught that if a person commits suicide the spirit lingers on our plane (I may have the terminology wrong) until the time that the person would normally have died. This seems to imply that our lifespan and perhaps means of death as well are predetermined. Yet apparently this determination is not absolute, or no one would be able to commit suicide. <br/><br/>Is the predetermination based on astrology, i.e. that our karma leads us to be born at a time and place such that the influence of the planets would lead to a particular length of life and type of death?<br/><br/>I would also think that this would apply only to deliberate suicide, not to death by blind stupidity as in, take up a life of crime and you may expect to die by violence or drive drunk and die in an auto crash.<br/><br/>Rita", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59718681", "title": "Re: Fate", "date": "2026-03-24 12:54 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's an interesting question to which the lore gives various answers. There are some traditions that do claim that the length of life is predetermined, and others that claim that there's a lot of variation but suicide is a special case. I figure I'll ask the lords of Karma after this life is over!"}]}, {"id": "cmt59716889", "title": "Polytheism vs Monotheism", "date": "2026-03-24 12:39 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi, JMG,<br/><br/>I have a theological question. I’ve read your book arguing for polytheism. I’ve experienced gods myself. But one thing I haven’t been able to figure out is this: if the gods of the various pantheons exist (Greek, Norse, Egyptian, Hindu, etc.), they all have their own creation myths. So how does the universe come about under a polytheistic framework with multiple pantheons? Or is it a case where the gods don’t really create anything and the universe comes about through other means?<br/><br/>One reason I started thinking about this is because I had a chat with a rabbi over the weekend. His perspective is that having one intelligence behind everything works better. He thinks polytheism is a more primitive form of spirituality where a separate being is in charge of each aspect of existence. Not saying I agree with him, just giving his perspective.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59719193", "title": "Re: Polytheism vs Monotheism", "date": "2026-03-24 12:59 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Polytheist traditions don't generally consider creation myths to be literally true. As Sallust wrote, \"myths are things that never happened but always <i>are</i>.\" If you read Greek pagan literature, in particular, nobody creates the universe; it comes into being, and then the gods are born from it. There are also plenty of polytheist traditions that have no creation myths at all -- there is no Celtic creation myth, for example. <br/><br/>2) Monotheists like to claim that. Polytheists point out that the world doesn't look like the kind of place that was created by a single all-knowing mind; it looks like the kind of place that grew up all anyhow, and various spiritual powers contributed to it, not always harmoniously. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59719961", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-24 01:10 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi all,<br/><br/>I just saw this article and thought some might be interested to know about it:<br/><br/>SPIRITUAL WAR: Top Exorcists Ask Pope Leo To Increase Number and Training of Specialized Priests To Combat Surge in Occultism and Satanic Practices<br/><br/>https://www.thegatewaypundit.com/2026/03/spiritual-war-top-exorcists-ask-pope-leo-increase/<br/><br/>I had watched an interview awhile back on Shawn Ryan's show, with Father Chad Ripperger who is an exorcist.<br/>he talked about all the training they went through to be one.. very intense stuff. he also said, i believe, that exorcisms are rising...<br/><br/>here is the link for anyone interested in that interview. its very long, and very indepth but such good and timely information:<br/><br/>https://rumble.com/v76rvki-noads-father-chad-ripperger-signs-of-the-mark-of-the-beast-and-rise-of-the-.html", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59720473", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-24 01:22 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I have to admit that having a Father Chad the Exorcist is almost too good to be real! Still, it's good that the Catholics are considering this. There's a lot of very nasty metaphysical energy around, and no shortage of malign spiritual beings. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59721241", "title": "Arousal of the Inner Fire", "date": "2026-03-24 01:52 am", "user": "lukeszy", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>Is there anything you can say about your understanding of the term \"arousal of the inner fire\"?  It's mentioned and briefly explained in RJ Stewart's book <i>The Spiritual Dimension of Music</i>.  It seems to refer to a baseline of energy activation.  Stewart's book is the only place I've ever seen it mentioned and there's nothing on the internet about it.<br/><br/>Luke Z", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59722265", "title": "Re: Arousal of the Inner Fire", "date": "2026-03-24 02:22 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm astounded that the internet doesn't know that term. It's quite common in older occult literature, and refers to the broad category of energy activation of which kundalini is the most famous (but far from the only) example. Stewart himself writes about one particular method for it, giving detailed instructions in several of his books. I've presented several methods for the same work in my books, for that matter. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59722521", "title": "Update on salt & nails", "date": "2026-03-24 02:44 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "So, I set up a jar of salt &amp; nails -- more specifically, a glass shaker for italian seasoning (a bit less than a cup I'd estimate), with the plastic perforated lid left on, and the metal cap off; non-iodized sea salt; and a half dozen inch-long paneling nails bent to varying extents (30-90 degrees and in different spots).<br/><br/>I found that vice &amp; hammer is not recommended, too noisy, and it wasn't responsive. So, I switched to vice &amp; pliers, which worked quite well (none of them broke or sent shards flying, but goggles are still recommended for such work).<br/><br/>As for salt, there is such a thing as iodized sea salt, but I wasn't sure if that was proper, so I played it safe with non-iodized.<br/><br/>Anyway, as soon as I set it up, I felt energized and in a better mood, and I've gotten a positive feeling from it since. It seems like my dreams have also been somewhat better -- one time, I encountered some sort of dark entity who tapped me on the shoulder, not the reaper but kind of similar, and it seemed like it wanted to kill me; I did the Sign of the Cross, and I was surrounded by positive energy which drove it away. I wonder if the salt &amp; nails aided me there?<br/><br/>Also, does it matter whether the salt is iodized or not, so long as it's rough sea salt?<br/><br/>Any other feedback is welcome.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59724313", "title": "Re: Update on salt & nails", "date": "2026-03-24 03:04 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm delighted to hear this. <br/><br/>1) Having the salt and nails weakens any nonphysical being with an etheric body -- demons, hostile ghosts, vampiric spirits, and the like -- and noxious etheric currents. Angels and intelligences don't have etheric bodies so they're fine with it. That is to say, it may have helped, by weakening your adversary. <br/><br/>2) In my experience pure (i.e., non-iodized) salt is more effective, but iodized will do in a pinch. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59725593", "title": "Re: Update on salt & nails", "date": "2026-03-24 03:19 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "For sure, thanks! Hopefully this is a useful data point.<br/><br/>2. I was confronted with iodized and non-iodized containers of sea salt at the market, and while I couldn't ask you at the time, something told me that non-iodized would be better. So this confirms my instincts.<br/>"}]}, {"id": "cmt59726105", "title": "Re: Update on salt & nails", "date": "2026-03-24 03:32 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Why do the nails have to be bent?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59727129", "title": "Re: Update on salt & nails", "date": "2026-03-24 03:42 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Heck of a good question. The sources I know of don't say -- they only say that the nails should be bent. I never saw any good reason to neglect that detail. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59725337", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-24 03:12 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Under what conditions should we take dwarf planets like Ceres, Eris, or Pluto seriously on a natal chart?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59727385", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-24 03:42 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You should probably ask a natal astrologer about that. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59726361", "title": "Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-03-24 03:37 am", "user": "ecoprayer", "content": "<a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/tag/prayerlist\">At this page</a> is the full list of all of the non-faith-specific requests for prayer that have recently appeared at <a href=\"https://ecosophia.net\">ecosophia.net</a> and <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org\">ecosophia.dreamwidth.org</a>, as well as in the comments of the prayer list posts (<a href=\"https://drive.google.com/file/d/1k1MLUovBKzARQYliiEYp26ddsPOvkRgo/view?usp=drivesdk\">printable version here</a>, current to 3/13). Please feel free to add any or all of the requests to your own prayers.<br/><br/>If I missed anybody, or if you would like to add a prayer request for yourself or anyone who has given you consent (or for whom a relevant person holds power of consent) to the list, please feel free to leave a comment below.<br/><br/><center>* * *</center><br/>This week I would like to bring special attention to the following prayer requests, selected from the fuller list.<br/><br/><div style=\"\"><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1732.html?thread=20676#cmt20676\">Bob W of Lake County, Ohio's</a> treatment for cancer go well so that he may heal and recover as quickly as possible.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/360870.html?thread=59415974#cmt59415974\">Open Space</a> be filled with the strength he needs to heal quickly from his current bout of Chicken Pox; may his will remain strong, that he does not scratch; may he be healed completely, and suffer no scarring in its wake.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/november-2025-open-post/#comment-149490\">Bob Ralston (aka Rasty Bob)</a>, who is in hospice care in Buckeye AZ, and who just lost his wife Leslie Fish, be blessed and find relief from his pain and discomfort; may Bob's heart remain strong. <br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1732.html?thread=18372#cmt18372\">Princess Cutekitten</a>, who has made no comments on any of the Ecosophia blogs for a year now, and hasn't responded to attempts at contact, be blessed wherever she is and in whatever form she may exist.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/359082.html?thread=59206570#cmt59206570\">Cathy N. of St. Marys, Ohio</a> heal and recover from injuries caused by a fall.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=15906#cmt15906\">Dustin, a relative of Brenainn</a>, be healed of a recently discovered heart condition.<br/><br/>May 1Wanderers's partner Cathy, whose cancer has returned, be given the physical and mental strength to fight it, and tolerate the treatment, and may she enjoy a full and permanent recovery.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=14882#cmt14882\">Jule from Iserlohn, Germany</a>, who is experiencing complications in her pregnancy due to an influenza infection, recover and have a pleasant pregnancy and birth.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=12322#cmt12322\">Larry Mulford</a>, who has entered hospice after a year battling with pancreatic cancer, pass in the smoothest possible manner, and may his wife be enveloped in our love.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1160.html?thread=12168#cmt12168\">Marko</a> have the strength to seize the opportunities.<br/><br/>May Pierre's young daughter, Athena, be healed from her fatigue and its root causes in ways that are easy, natural, and as holistic as possible.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18134.html?thread=452566#cmt452566\">5 year old Max</a> be blessed and protected during his parents' contentious divorce; may events work out in a manner most conducive to Max's healthy development over the long term.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/514.html?thread=2562#cmt2562\">Lydia G. of Geauga County, Ohio</a> heal and recover from prolonged health issues.<br/><br/>May both <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/347398.html?thread=57920774#cmt57920774\">Monika and the child she is pregnant with</a> both be blessed with good health and a safe delivery. <br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/338828.html?thread=56777612#cmt56777612\">Mary's sister</a> have her auto-immune conditions sent into remission, may her eyes remain healthy, and may she heal in body, mind, and spirit.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18134.html?thread=455382#cmt455382\">Trubujah's best friend Pat's teenage daughter Devin</a>, who has a mysterious condition which doctors are so far baffled by necessitating that she remain in a wheelchair, be healed of her condition; may the underlying cause come to light so that treatment may begin.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/16429.html?thread=392237#cmt392237\">Kevin’s sister Cynthia</a> be cured of the hallucinations and delusions that have afflicted her, and freed from emotional distress. May she be safely healed of the physical condition that has provoked her emotions; and may she be healed of the spiritual condition that brings her to be so unsettled by it. May she come to feel calm and secure in her physical body, regardless of its level of health.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/312140.html?thread=53408588#cmt53408588\">Frank R. Hartman, who lost his house in the Altadena fire, and all who have been affected by the larger conflagration</a> be blessed and healed.<br/><br/></div><div><br/><br/><center>* * *</center><br/>Guidelines for how long prayer requests stay on the list, how to word requests, how to be added to the weekly email list, how to improve the chances of your prayer being answered, and several other common questions and issues, are to be found <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/6373.html\">at the Ecosophia Prayer List FAQ</a>.<br/><br/>If there are any among you who might wish to join me in a bit of <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/1986.html\">astrological timing</a>, I pray each week for the health of all those with health problems on the list on the  astrological hour of the Sun on Sundays, bearing in mind the Sun's rulerships of heart, brain, and vital energies. If this appeals to you, I invite you to join me.</div>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59727641", "title": "Re: Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-03-24 03:44 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this as always. "}]}]}, {"title": "Magic Monday", "url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/364211.html", "year": "2026", "month": "03", "day": "29", "time": "09-05PM", "comments": [{"id": "cmt59752627", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 04:09 am", "user": "andrewskeen", "content": "A modernist psychosynthesistic AFA professor and humanistic astrologer was teaching a class on Dane Rudhyar, known theosophist.<br/>”Before the class begins, you must get on your knees and worship Carl Jung and accept that he was the most highly-realized astrologer the world has ever known, even greater than Māshā'allāh!”<br/><br/>At this moment, a brave, traditional, Aristotelean celestial scholar-astrologist who was fluent in medieval Arabic and understood the logical necessity of the Prime Mover and fully supported all teachings of the technical Hermetica stood up and held out a clay omen tablet.<br/><br/>”What does this tablet describe, pillhead?”<br/><br/>The arrogant professor smirked quite psychiatrically and smugly replied “Sex, you regressive Hellenist”<br/><br/>”Wrong. It’s been 7,000 years since Babylonians created it. If it was about sex and psychoanalysis, as you say, is real… then it wouldn't make concrete predictions”<br/><br/>The professor was visibly shaken, and dropped his chalk and copy of <em>Planets in Transit</em>. He stormed out of the room crying those bohemian crocodile tears. The same tears high modernists cry for the “ignorant” (who today live in such luxury that most use claudstrology for their delineations) when they sophistically try to claim lineage with the ancient and noble science of astrology. There is no doubt that at this point our professor, Stephen Jondro Arroyo, wished he could have known the future and avoided such humiliation. He wished so much that he had a method of prognostication to save himself from embarrassment, but he himself had derided horary as fortune-telling!<br/><br/>The students applauded and all registered for the Hellenistic Astrology course at courses dot theastrologyschool dot com that day and accepted Hermēs as their lord and sator. An ibis named “Astral Worship” flew into the room and perched atop the overhead projector and shed a tear on the chalk. <em>The Great Introduction</em> was read several times, and Ptolemy himself showed up and declared whole-sign chart interpretation across the country.<br/><br/>The professor lost his tenure and was fired the next day. He died of a hard eighth-house transit and was thrown back onto the Spindle of Necessity by Ananke for another mortal rebirth.<br/><br/>Fiat.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59753395", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 04:29 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Or perhaps Alfa Romeo, if Ptolemy's expense account stretched that far. ;-)<br/><br/>The irony is that I've just completed a piece for a forthcoming anthology on the occult dimensions of Carl Jung's work. My contribution surveys the catalog of his personal library made after his death. While Jung was hardly the greatest astrologer of all time, he had a very respectable collection of medieval and modern astrological texts, and seems to have had a solid technical knowledge of the subject.<br/><br/>As for modern psychological astrology, it has its place. My guess is that over the next few centuries, the work done by Alan Leo and his successors will be cleaned up, cleared of babble, and turned into a specialty -- call it psychological astrology -- which will be one of the available niche markets like medical or mundane astrology. That said, I find predictions more interesting.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59777715", "title": "Psychological Astrology and morality book sorta question", "date": "2026-03-30 08:54 pm", "user": "emily07", "content": "Drat! And here I was with my oracle cards and thinking that I could dispense with having to learn Astrology in this life and now this! Psychological Astology…Sounds very intruiging!<br/><br/>Oh and:<br/>Count my also in for the book about Ethics, I am currently …knowing…that I should/want to swith towards honouring/worshipping Mercur (as a God) and because of my roman catholic upbringing and more or less current Praxis I have difficulties with the no lies commandment. A fine theme for Meditation or what would your intermediate advice for the time being be?<br/><br/>And while I‘m at it:<br/>Because of the fortbidden question the quality of questions around the forbidden question has risen, maybe there is a subset for advanced Information to be written in the FAQ about these: e.g. there was a Talisman question that might be of interest to the broader audience as well as: magic performed solely in the imagination is still magic and suchlike.<br/><br/>Best wishes,<br/>Emily07", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59780787", "title": "Re: Psychological Astrology and morality book sorta question", "date": "2026-03-30 09:46 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Drat indeed! There's a lot of very good material on psychological astrology in Alan Leo and Dane Rudhyar; I don't know enough about more recent authors to judge. <br/><br/>2) It's a fine theme for meditation. ;-) One point I'd offer to start with is that lying is not always a bad thing. Let's say you're in the Soviet Union and a bunch of goons from the KGB came to your door and asked if you knew the whereabouts of somebody who'd been declared an enemy of the state. Let's say that very person was hiding in your attic. It would not be a virtue for you to tell the truth in that situation! There are many other situations where strict truth is a bad idea, and some in which it's not even possible -- try explaining some complex adult issue to a six-year-old sometime. <br/><br/>3) Hmm. I'll consider that when I have time. <br/><br/>"}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59753139", "title": "Upcoming astrological events", "date": "2026-03-30 04:12 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Please comment on these upcoming astrological events:<br/> <br/>We will see two comets in April, C/2026 A1 (MAPS) April 4 and C/2025 R3 April 27. <br/> <br/>There will be a “planet parade” when Mercury, Mars, Saturn, and Neptune form a rare visual alignment as they are clustered together in a 10-degree section of sky April 16 – 23.<br/> <br/>And there will be a conjunction of the Moon, Venus, and the Pleiades April 18–19.<br/> <br/>Thank you for sharing your thoughts.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59753651", "title": "Re: Upcoming astrological events", "date": "2026-03-30 04:36 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Once we know what sign and degree each comet is in when it becomes visible to the naked eye, which signs it passes through thereafter, and where it is the last time it can be seen, it will be possible to delineate the resulting charts and make predictions. The one thing that can be known in advance is that it'll be bad news, as comets are invariably malefic. <br/><br/>2) A loose stellium of four planets isn't that rare and doesn't mean that much. If one of more of the planets are in aspect to something in your natal chart or your country's most recent ingress chart, you can interpret them in the same way as any other transiting planets. <br/><br/>3) The Moon conjuncts Venus once a month. Having that regular event conjunct the Pleiades is a little troubling, as the influence of the Pleiades is strongly malefic -- they are the Weeping Stars, and when they are activated in a chart, you will have something to weep about -- but that depends, again, on whether anything in your natal chart or your country's latest ingress chart is in aspect to them. If not, the tears will be someone else's. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59754163", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 05:11 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A wonderful start to the week to you, JMG, and to all the commenters!<br/><br/>Which mystical or occult order has the oldest documented lineage still in activity—one whose origins we can trace historically with some degree of evidence?<br/><br/>I’ve read this question and answer here before, but I couldn’t find it, so please forgive me.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59759027", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 04:01 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In Asia, there are lineages that go back millennia. The lineage of the Heavenly Masters in Taoism was founded in 142 AD and is still going strong, and there may be Indian lineages even older. Here in the West? Freemasonry was a going concern in 1598, when the first Schaw statutes were enacted to govern the Craft in Scotland. Other than that -- well, aside from Christian monastic orders, which I doubt are what you had in mind, I don't know of a Western esoteric lineage that can be traced in solid, documented fashion before 1875, when the Theosophical Society was founded.  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59770803", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 07:00 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1598? I didn't know Freemasonry was that old! <br/><br/>Or was it still just a stonemason's guild prior to the 18th century? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59771315", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 07:13 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The Schaw statutes of 1598 and 1599 mark the point at which Masonry began to transform from an operative guild to its present state. David Stevenson's book <i>The Origins of Freemasonry: Scotland's Century</i> documents the period quite well. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59780275", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 09:36 pm", "user": "not_gandalf", "content": "If you count Sufi Orders as Western they also have documented lineages that go back pretty far.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59781043", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 09:48 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I see them as South and West Asian. You're right, though, that some of them go back a good long ways. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59784883", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 10:47 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "OP here!<br/>Thanks, JMG!"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59754419", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 05:18 am", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "Could you point us to a short how-to article on interpreting comets?<br/>I'm curious about C/2025 A6 (Lemmon), but I don't know enough to even begin.<br/>Many thanks!", "edit_time": "2026-03-30 05:22 am (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59759795", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 04:04 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't know of one. I've been assembling pointers on prediction using comets from Renaissance sources. You'll need to figure out what sign and degree of the zodiac it was in when it first became visible, what sign and degree it was in when it was last visible, and what aspects it made with the planets as it swung through its arc. Remember that every aspect with a comet is malefic, and you should be able to work out something. "}, {"id": "cmt59761075", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 04:13 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "I searched Wikipedia and an astrology website. The comet brightened to magnitude 6 while in the Leo sector of the sky and was first spotted with the naked eye* not far from Cor Caroli which is in the Virgo sector of the sky. I don't know how to interpret the astrological effects of comets but I hope this helps.<br/><br/>*Diffuse objects are harder to spot than point objects (stars) of the same magnitude.<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59767987", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 05:54 pm", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "Thanks, yes - I was looking at visibility a bit later.<br/>The map at in-the-sky.org/comets/202511_CK25A060_1.png looks like it was most visible near Serpens Caput and exited about Ophiuchus.<br/><br/>So - Weapons coming back to bite their wielders?  Poison returned to sender?<br/><br/>Now I check those dates for relevant world events?  Or is there a time lag?<br/><br/>Suggestion box open.<br/><br/>"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59754675", "title": "Possible reason for the cigareete sync", "date": "2026-03-30 05:24 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "A few weeks ago, I was bombarded with synchronities around cigarettes after reading a comment on the main blog that was skeptical of the narrative that tobacco use directly causes cancer. Last week, during a transit to my North Node, I learned the probable reason why I got those synchronities. The Bendith Fawr figure in my geomantic reading might not have been an indication that I could use nicotine addiction* as a crutch to massively improve my own life. But my current use got me into a situation where I can try to help turn someone else's life around. Maybe I'll even be successful in my attempt.<br/><br/>Patrick H<br/><br/>*At least in my case, nicotine is not immediately addictive.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59760051", "title": "Re: Possible reason for the cigareete sync", "date": "2026-03-30 04:05 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Interesting! Thanks for the update. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59755187", "title": "SOP", "date": "2026-03-30 06:53 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello!<br/><br/>You may have answered my query before. If so apologies.<br/><br/>What energy centres does the SOP activate? <br/><br/>I am a bit curious because I have been practicing the SOP for more than 1 year now in the context of GSF and recently I felt a very brief flush of sexual energy whilst walking. I felt like I was 17 (I am 60 now)!<br/>Very curious. Any connections?<br/>Many thanks and regards<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59760563", "title": "Re: SOP", "date": "2026-03-30 04:11 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It isn't focused on any one set of energy centers. It bathes the subtle bodies gently in elemental energies, thus awakening whatever energy centers you're working with in other contexts -- and if you're not, it simply increases your vitality and psychological balance. The flush of sexual energy is a common side effect; if you have an outlet for that energy, well and good. If not, the next time it happens, you can use the practice on page 44 of this book...<br/><br/><a href=\"https://archive.org/details/rosicrucianmanua00plum/page/44/mode/2up\">https://archive.org/details/rosicrucianmanua00plum/page/44/mode/2up</a><br/><br/>...which will redirect the current from your genital center to your brain, resulting in increased mental clarity, and also, ahem, fertility of ideas."}]}, {"id": "cmt59755443", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 07:06 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A little bit of further news in \"rationalists trying to use the methods of rationality to give hypotheses that contain supernatural things what is as-far-as-they-can-tell their fair shake, in what is as-far-as-they-can-tell good faith, relative to hypotheses that don't contain supernatural things\":<br/><br/>https://www.astralcodexten.com/p/a-buddhist-sun-miracle<br/><br/>It connects the 1998 mass sun Dhammakaya vision in Bangkok with the Fatima miracle (for more of that theme, see the links therein to Alexander's previous articles). The article ends with Alexander asking for people to put witnesses in touch with the non-Thai-speaking investigator \"Arthur T\".", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59760819", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 04:11 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "As the Age of Reason ends, I expect to see much more of this sort of thing. Thanks for the heads up. "}, {"id": "cmt59768755", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 06:14 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The comments do surface the theme of the subjective-experience-influence-centered nature of these events a little bit, see the thread https://www.astralcodexten.com/p/a-buddhist-sun-miracle/comment/234170058 , but not really enough to put someone on the track of how that could be the most fruitful line of hypotheses, if they didn't already know to look for that.<br/><br/>I wonder if the sun's purported unusual properties in the supernatural local cosmology, plus what I purport to be a part where the supernatural is (for us) focused around choosing timeline-combinations of details of subjective experience particularly including sensory experience, are why the miracle-like events would find it easiest to happen (even in the face of what I purport to be the contrary pressure that would somehow result from the fact that the reports of the miracles would predictably have effects in the future on third parties' subjective habits of interpretation) when what they're happening in connection with is sensory attention to the sun."}, {"id": "cmt59769779", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 06:52 pm", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>I'm reminded of the Ganesha Milk Miracles in India, Trinidad, and Tobago in 1995 and 2010: devotees who held a spoon of milk up to the mouths of some statues of Ganesha would see the milk disappear out of the spoon as if it were being sucked up. This went on for several hours.</p>\n<p>If you look it up now, of course, all the sources insist that it was just capillary action and gravity, and skeptics made much of some videos that showed some drops of milk spilling off the spoons (by this logic no one has ever fed anything to a toddler), but I remember when it happened in 2010 people who were there quickly rebutted the \"debunking\": it didn't happen with all statues, some of the statues it happened with were heavily lacquered (which should have stopped the capillary action), the milk gathered up at the end was substantially less than what was offered, and it only happened for a few hours on a few days a decade and a half apart.</p>\n<p>It's always wryly amusing to see skeptics \"debunk\" things from their armchairs thousands of miles away.  Robert Anton Wilson once suggested James Randi should give himself his own prize since the only way he could so confidently know what <em>really</em> happened during experiments he wasn't present at was if he were clairvoyant.</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59797683", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 03:31 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I don't think \"debunking\" is quite a central characterization of Alexander's project. In other places Alexander seems properly puzzled about why there are as many features as there are of the reports that aren't what you would expect just from a materialist account of what's going on in fire kasina meditative visualization, like why it works on multiple people at once, and why the people don't need advance training, or the juxtaposition of how there were many recurring anomalous elements from the reports from Fatima but no single report that combines all of the anomalous elements, or why in Fatima it was reported by a few people in nearby towns who couldn't have heard the exhortation to look at the sun to use as an unconscious cue for \"okay now have a fire kasina experience 'spontaneously'\". Someone who was an ordinary central instance of the category \"debunker\" would just pass over those points, or only mention them as part of a passage trying to attach an emotional charge of discreditation to them. The emotional charge that Alexander seems to attach to these points is more one of bewilderment and keeping track of them in the back of the picture, while still putting their active implying-force on hold, on dominant suspicion that they'll just turn out be the same kind of baffling thing whose further implications have totally failed to hold weight in the past anyway.<br/><br/>The debunking drum he's beating louder is the one where people are using the Fatima event as exclusive evidence for Catholicism. https://www.astralcodexten.com/p/a-buddhist-sun-miracle/comment/234226445 is a comment thread about the epistemic significance of the smaller conclusion that various supernatural beings would have to be muddying the waters in order to get the observed events as an outcome.<br/><br/>&gt; The best a skeptic can do, then, is force God's reasoning to be increasingly bizarre. If God performs a miracle to encourage believers in the true religion, that's pretty reasonable and non-bizarre on its own terms. If God then for inscrutable reasons performs the same miracle to prop up a false religion, that's quite bizarre! If God performs miracles for the true religion, but allows demons to perform identical miracles for false religions, this is at least adding another epicycle of unfalsifiability to the theory (for the same reason that it would be awkward if we somehow found photographic evidence of nothing unusual happening at Fatima, and you had to say that demons planted the photographs to confuse us). So I think the skeptics have done the only thing they can do here, which is make the miracle require so many bizarre supernatural epicycles and mysterious justifications and attempts by supernatural enemies to muddy the waters that eventually it collapses under its own weight and it's simpler to believe it's an unexplained natural phenomenon.<br/>&gt; <br/>&gt; I do think this more even strongly decreases the weight of the miracle as evidence for Catholicism. Even if you think a supernatural explanation is still more plausible than a natural one, if sun miracles occur for many religions, then there's no reason to prefer the hypothesis \"the Christian God, or Christian demons, sometimes helps out Buddhists for inscrutable reasons\" compared to \"Amitabha Buddha, or Buddhist demons, sometimes help out the Catholics for inscrutable reasons\"[...]<br/><br/>I don't see what about this reasoning changes in force if one were thousands of miles away; it's not the same kind of objection as, say, arguing that there was nothing stopping two people in a random number telepathy experiment from synchronizing their watches.<br/><br/>(Alexander's ready attempted use of the phrasing \"even more strongly\" and the reference to \"weight\" derive from an ambient culture of Bayesian epistemological cultivation.)<br/><br/>Alexander doesn't really engage with the other non-exclusive supernatural perspectives, perhaps because they don't weigh very strongly in his awareness, because there's no mass of cultural weight near him that has gone to any effort to build out such perspectives for him the way Abrahamic religions have (because of the obvious huge difference in effort-availability resulting from the differences in memeplex reproductive pressures / apologetics-funding feedback loops). You could call it a sort of passivist version of a straw-man fallacy; except that, to the extent that it's in his case driven by being too busy or too disoriented by all the conflicting claims from conflicting population groups about the supernatural, it's more like a salient-man heuristic. (Surely the loudest established voices about the supernatural would be incentivized to advance the best combined hypothesis, and use all their resources to construct that hypothesis? Well, no, they have a big conflict of interest around propping up their religion along with the supernatural in general; but who is a random non-expert supposed to trust instead?) Of course, to the extent that he's too scared of trapping himself in his own optimized delusory supernatural worldview due to skill issues with how not to trap himself, or the extent to which belief in the supernatural would be inconvenient in various identity-related ways, a motivated lack of inquiry does qualify as a passivist version of the straw-man fallacy. (His fear of trapping himself can be most seen in his remarks about writing Unsong as a way of expressing the experience of seemingly-meaningful pareidolic linguistic synchronicities so ubiquitous as to be most likely meaningless (not his words, can't find the link), and \"Epistemic Learned Helplessness\" https://slatestarcodex.com/2019/06/03/repost-epistemic-learned-helplessness/ where he talks about the experience of falling for Velikovskianism.)<br/><br/>He also (in the comments) bangs something of a subsidiary drum about added constraints turned up by dog-that-didn't-bark heuristics:<br/><br/>&gt; Whenever we posit miracles, we have to explain why God doesn't do *bigger* ones. If He's in the business of proving Himself, why stop at an easy-to-doubt appearance in Portugal? Why not rearrange the stars to spell \"CATHOLICISM IS TRUE\"? The explanation that iirc [...] religious people give is that God is trying to strike a balance between faith and certainty[...]<br/>&gt;<br/>&gt; If demons are also in the business of doing miracles, that complicates the picture. Why should they be interested in this same tenuous balance between faith and certainty? [...]<br/>&gt; <br/>&gt; [...] the believer would have to posit that demons' power is somehow limited by God (or the demons' own natural magical capacity), and that these limits just so happen to perfectly mirror the limits God voluntarily places on Himself for good religious reasons [....] But this adds another complexity penalty to the hypothesis.<br/><br/>(\"Complexity penalty\" is jargon casually referring to a loose normative standard deriving from the theory of algorithmic probability; it would be clearer to an external audience as \"contrivedness\".)<br/><br/>Again, I don't see anything about this reasoning that changes in force if one were thousands of miles away.<br/><br/>There's this Jefferson quote that goes like \"error of opinion may be tolerated where reason is left free to combat it\", which attitude Jefferson is contrasting against earlier countries' censorship schemes. Those from two points on an axis of political attitudes toward censorship. There's an analogous axis of possible practical attitudes toward reflexively clamping down on beliefs. The kind of skepticism you're probably imagining here is further toward the analogue of the \"censorship\" direction on that axis; the kind that Scott is practicing has Bayesian techniques that make it easier to contain runaway circular-interpretation feedback loops, which produce a feeling of being less relatively threatened by things like admitting that the Bangkok event takes away less of the Fatima event's force for supernatural hypotheses in general than it does of the Fatima event's force for Catholicism in particular."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59755699", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 08:54 am", "user": "adara9", "content": "Hello,<br/><br/>Following up on last week's question: after a bit more digging, it looks like Waite had a couple of different editions of \"Transcendental Magic\", and his annotations were added in the 2nd of those.<br/><br/>This week's question: I've been having some real mental health struggles ever since my CGD Bardic Grade initiation (though quite a few other things also changed for me around that time). Having just completed intake for an intensive outpatient program, I noticed that a lot of the questions ask about effects that can develop during occult work, but are also symptoms of schizophrenia, psychosis, etc. So I'm wondering how to tell the difference between \"this is a good sign of psychic / spiritual / occult development\" and \"this is a bad sign of mental health concern\". Is it one of the many cases where normal / healthy fades into unhealthy along a spectrum? Given the trope of occult study sometimes leading to madness, I'm inclined to that take, but I'd appreciate any insight or guidance.<br/><br/>(I've been finding the experience rather disheartening, since my CGD work up until the Bardic Grade initiation was consistently &amp; unambiguously resulting in strong mental health improvements.)<br/><br/>Thanks for any help you can provide,<br/>Heather<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59761331", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 04:16 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "This is very common. The Bardic grade is the rough one -- you have to balance out the elemental forces in your various bodies, and that always involves some challenges. Keep at it, and everything will resolve. Yes, there's a spectrum between occult experience and madness; a few symptoms that move toward the middle are to be expected at this stage of the work. <br/><br/>It's standard in any system of occult training with three degrees for the second degree to be the challenging one. Remember that every great occultist passed through this same experience and came out stronger and wiser. Take good care of yourself, and make sure especially that you get plenty of rest. You'll be fine. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59779763", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 09:20 pm", "user": "borealbear", "content": "If you don't mind me asking, how about systems with four? I feel I've had plenty of changes and challenges already between the first and the second. Not that I'm complaining, since one of the reasons for doing this was that I wanted my life to change to better reach my long-term goals, but might still be useful to have some sense of what what lies further down this road. The HGD book itself seems to suggest the third might be the roughest, for what it's worth...<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59781299", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 09:50 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It depends very much on how the system is structured. In a three-degree system you pretty much have to make the first degree introductory and therefore easy, and the last degree synthesizes everything and so is usually pretty comfortable, and that leaves the second degree for the analytical and transformative work. If you have more degrees than that, you can choose what to do where. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59755955", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 11:17 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,<br/>Like many people I suppose, I have a magical practice that has grown incrementally over the years as I have added new things and in some cases dropped them. Before doing the LBRP every morning and the MP Exercise, I have always repeated the Orphic Hymn of the day, and a prayer to Thoth, who contacted me some years ago. More recently, I have added the Orphic Hymn to Hypnos, since I am a lifelong insomniac, and Psalm 23 and the Lord's Prayer. All this is done at the same time, though I do try to leave enough space between for a communication from one of those I am addressing.  Recently, there was discussion of Tyche, so I tried adding her, but I'm not comfortable asking for money (and I have modestly adequate standard of living.)<br/>How much is too much, if indeed you can have that? All of these prayers and invocations are broadly within the same tradition but is there some point at which you go over a sensible limit?<br/>Thank for any wisdom you may have on the subject. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59761587", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 04:19 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Do you practice a system of divination? That's a good resource for questions like these, which are always dependent on personal factors. Some people are fine filling most of their waking hours with prayer and invocation; others need to keep much tighter limits in place. Divination can help you sort out your place on that spectrum. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59756211", "title": "Energy polarity", "date": "2026-03-30 12:20 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Something very weird happened to me last week and I'm hoping you might be able to help.<br/><br/>The background is I've practiced CGD magic on and off since 2014 (I think, I'm terrible with dates). Since 2020 I have a patron goddess who clears my energy centres every night when I pray and kicked off my kundalini also in 2020. It comes and goes in waves since, progressing a bit more each time.<br/><br/>Then at some stage I started clearing other people's energy unintentionally - family, coworkers, randomers. The internet says I might be just clearing off their energy that got attached to me, so I'm not having an effect on them. That might be part of it but for reasons too long to go into here I'm pretty sure I'm helping clear their energy, like in Reiki. <br/><br/>I started trying to clear spaces on purpose and discovered I can do that a bit, then I thought I'd offer to clear people on my train commute if my patron goddess wanted me to do that. I saw it as doing something useful to make up for times when I get a bit lazy about praying, because I assume she gave me this ability because she wants me to use it. So I ask and then sometimes it happens and sometimes it doesn't. Lately I can feel a wave of energy coming from the person towards me, it's like a cloud. <br/><br/>I didn't consider the consent thing because I see it as either something that I don't control, or her/the Gods deciding about it each time, not me. I've decided to stop offering to do that now though. If it happens it happens. <br/><br/>The next thing is that for the last maybe 6 months or so kundalini has been making me confused about relationships. I've been very happily single for 11/12 years and I always said I'd rather tear my own toenails out than get involved in a relationship again. I read kundalini can cause this when it reaches your sacral chakra or something. Anyway I prayed and did planetary charity to Venus, mostly to help my daughter with a friend issue, but I tagged on a request for her to help me figure out what would be good for me. I told her I didn't really know what I was asking for.<br/><br/>In the last month or so my kundalini has ramped up hugely, going right up my back, vibrations, white light, all kinds of drama. It's there all day but strongest at night, stops me sleeping at times.<br/><br/>Long background, sorry! Anyway last Thursday on the train a man sat opposite me and he was really restless and antsy. He seemed like a prime candidate for some energy clearing so I asked the gods if they wanted me to do it (I always ask the gods generally, rather than just Her, about this, I don't know why). I felt a way stronger wave of energy than normal coming from him, really intense, but not bad or angry or anything. I cleared it, like normal. I yawn lots, I feel it going out the top of my head, that's a bit sore, then my eyes and nose run and then it's finished. That was all fine. His body language got more relaxed and he actually sat still-ish for a while. People get calmer like that after I do the clearing. He was definitely looking for my attention/focusing on me the whole train ride from the time he sat down. That never happens to me, I'm not young and I'm fairly average looking. Being extremely relationship avoidant, I tried not to give him any attention.  <br/><br/>Then the weird things happened. My kundalini fired up hugely and the white light kind of energy She usually sends down through the top of my head started coming through strongly, and the two were trying to meet up, you'll know what I mean. I had heart palpitations. This went on until I got off the train, then it got more intense on the way home, and even more so that night and lasted through the next day. I really, really, wanted to see him again. I also can't imagine not feeling that ever again because it was amazing. I never felt anything so powerful before in my life.  <br/><br/>I've been praying to Her and to Venus since, asking them to either send him back to me and I won't ignore him this time, or send me that feeling back, tell me what that meant, or something. But they never answer my questions, at least not that I can hear. They just do things. Maybe they know I can go bother you with questions instead. I only ask them because I know you're going to say to ask them! <br/><br/>I'm guessing that was some kind of energy polarity explosion, like you probably explain in your book which I should read. But why would the gods do that using another person when they could have just done it themselves like She has been doing for ages? Because now I'm even more confused, and I'm not going to see this random stranger again and if I did maybe he's antsy because he's completely messed up, so why him? I'm not even sure what I'm asking but what do you think that was, or why did it happen, and what should I do about it? Right now I just really want to find him again, which is impossible unless the gods help me, and maybe a dumb idea if I were being rational, but I'm not. Any advice welcome.<br/><br/>Thank you,<br/><br/>Dot.<br/><br/> <br/><br/><br/><br/><br/><br/><br/><br/><br/> <br/><br/><br/><br/><br/><br/><br/><br/><br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59761843", "title": "Re: Energy polarity", "date": "2026-03-30 04:24 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It was a polarity release, all right. The fact that you don't want a relationship doesn't change the fact that your subtle bodies have an energetic charge that needs to balance itself out. That doesn't have to involve sex, or romance, or any of that; my book on polarity workings describes some of the ways to deal with that. But you're going to have to deal with it. <br/><br/>Have you read Dion Fortune's novels, by any chance? <i>The Goat Foot God, The Sea Priestess</i>, and <i>The Winged Bull</i>, in that order, might be very useful to you. They're all about polarity. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59763123", "title": "Re: Energy polarity", "date": "2026-03-30 04:39 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "No I haven't read those. I've ordered the novels and your book now thank you. What would happen if I didn't balance out that energetic charge? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59763635", "title": "Re: Energy polarity", "date": "2026-03-30 04:46 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, you'll balance it out, all right. You can do it in a controlled, helpful way or you can find yourself swept off your feet into a passionate and probably catastrophic affair with some random guy, but one way or another you'll balance it out. That's the thing about polarity forces -- they are far, far stronger than the rational mind. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59768499", "title": "Re: Energy polarity", "date": "2026-03-30 06:02 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ah, yes I can see how that would happen. Maybe that's why Venus sent me that experience. She knew I'd ask you about it. I might have guessed they'd be giving me more work to do. I should be grateful to them, but I'm not feeling it right now. I'll ask Her to ease off the kundalini at least, because I need more sleep. "}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59756467", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 01:09 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You said Dion Fortune died young because of her role in the Magical Battle of Britain. What did it do to her, and with hindsight could it have been prevented or treated?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59762099", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 04:24 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I think she deliberately offered herself, and the sacrifice was accepted. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59767219", "title": "Dion Fortune query", "date": "2026-03-30 05:25 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "It's a plausible speculation, but I don't recall any documentary evidence that she made such an offer. If she had, there might have been some mention of it at the time, or afterward in Inner Light sources, but I don't remember coming across any. (Which isn't to say it doesn't exist! If anyone knows of anything of the sort, I'd appreciate hearing about it.<br/><br/>Otherwise, my own favorite speculation is that her early death from leukemia may well have been related to her laboratory work on soy bean processing. The industrial processes being investigated at that time relied on organic solvents (e.g. benzene), now known (and not just to the State of California) to be carcinogenic. People were not as scrupulous about such things even back in the 1960s, and even les so in the 1910-1920 period. Her leukemia might well have been related to her earlier laboratory work. (Her book <i>The Soya Bean</i>, which mentions but does not describe her own laboratory work during WWI, was published in 1925.)<br/><br/>Of course, this too is speculation. And causality can run in more than one track: that's what produces \"synchronicities\". But I offer this as an additional point for reflection.<br/><br/>LeGrand<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59772083", "title": "Re: Dion Fortune query", "date": "2026-03-30 07:23 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, granted, I know that my hypothesis is very speculative -- that's why I headed it with those cautionary words \"I think.\" Maybe I've just been reading her magical novels too much of late, but the role of human sacrifice in the Atlantean magic she wrote about was not small, and I could very easily see her offering herself to stop the Nazi tide the way Wilfred in <i>The Sea Priestess</i> remembered his former incarnation offering himself to stop the rising seas. Nor would there necessarily be any documentation this side of the astral plane; if it happened, Charles Loveday might have known about it, but it's not the kind of thing she would have trumpeted far and wide. <br/><br/>It's entirely possible, for that matter, that the efficient cause was benzene, or some related compound currently causing Californians to die like flies. As you suggest, though, the final cause may have been something very different. <br/><br/>Again, though, it's a speculation. I think.  ;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59795635", "title": "Re: Dion Fortune query", "date": "2026-03-31 02:49 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good points about a complicated possibility.<br/><br/>In general, some accounts from around the time of her death describe her as having been generally run-down and debilitated for some time beforehand (of course hindsight allows for adjustment of narratives); some speculations )e.g. by Kenneth Grant) had to do with kundalini or polarity experiments gone wrong. There was a fairly common \"Atlantean\" attitude at the time, since somewhat repudiated by people like Gareth Knight and others in that tradition, that led to an impersonality about such things as (willing) human sacrifice, hieratic breeding programs, and so on, very much in tune with common \"scientific\" attitudes of the late 19th and early 20th century. So it's not impossible. <br/><br/>I see several, somewhat overlapping, possibilities, more or less in order of deliberateness.<br/><br/>1. A deliberate personal self-sacrifice in the course of a focused working.<br/><br/>2. A stochastic self-sacrifice, of the sort alleged to have taken place in witch circles during WWII, in which participants in a working understood that one or more of them might be \"chosen\".<br/><br/>3. A more or less private offer, which she did not refuse, made to her by Someone in the course of meditation, prayer, or ritual.<br/><br/>4. An unintended overload or burn-out as a result of the work (\"magical battle\" or otherwise)  she was doing.<br/><br/>Now, as against all of these, there is the fact that she does not seem to have anticipated death as an outcome, and contemporary accounts of her death don't seem to point in any of these directions. (Grant's account is pretty late.) She seems to have expected to keep on with her work, including such projects as a book on the Paths of the Tree of Life.<br/><br/>It's possible that some of her colleagues (for example CRF Seymour, Christine Campbell Thomson, Maia Tranchell-Hayes) may have had opinions about her death, but I don't know that they have been reported. <br/><br/>As with other well-known occultists, her life has become the seed around which all sorts of legends (and outright fictions) have crystallized. The idea of her death having been something of a deliberate sacrifice is far from the most implausible, however, and I will keep an eye out for relevant evidence and testimonials from her contemporaries.<br/><br/>LeGrand<br/><br/><br/><br/>3. <br/><br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59798451", "title": "Re: Dion Fortune query", "date": "2026-03-31 03:39 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Fair enough. As I noted, it's a hypothesis, and a speculative one; it could certainly be wrong. That said, having made the offer doesn't necessarily mean that she knew when it would be accepted. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59773619", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 07:43 pm", "user": "rhydlyd", "content": "How'd she do that?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59775411", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 07:53 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm not going to pass on the details. I don't want to encourage anyone to do the same thing. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59756723", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 01:18 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If someone has a history of concussions or playing a sport like rugby that creates a risk of chronic traumatic encephalopathy, are there any occult practices that are a bad idea? Does the answer change if the person is asymptomatic or starting to show signs?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59762355", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 04:26 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't recall ever reading anything discussing this. Concussions and the like were very common among men who fought in the First World War, however, and if that had been a problem I think the occultists in the years between the wars would have discussed it. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59756979", "title": "Natural magic? and thank you!", "date": "2026-03-30 01:19 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG and everyone,<br/><br/>I'm going to submit an application to change schools, for a small person in the household. The application period is between April 15-30. Do you have any suggestions for natural magic that would increase the chances? (Since it is a change of schools it would not stopping anyone else)<br/><br/>I've recently started DHM again after a few years of break and SoP and meditation have been (relatively) easy to resume. <br/><br/>But... do you have any tips on how I can become better friends with Ogham? I've had the cards for several years but can't communicate with them. (And I even often lose them.) I've had very good meditations with and about the trees, but I can't get them to divination. (Guessing the answer is: keep at it... :)<br/><br/>All the best, Tilly<br/><br/>PS When I was lurking here last time, in 2019, Robert Mathiesen shared a short protective spell: use salt water and draw a protective symbol at the forehead. I was not the OP but it was very useful for me when needed. Thank you! And, Thank you to JMG for holding this space and for sharing all the knowledge!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59762611", "title": "Re: Natural magic? and thank you!", "date": "2026-03-30 04:31 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Make the application on a Monday, during the hour of the Moon; she'll be waxing during both the Mondays in that period, so that'll be fortunate. (The Moon governs children and their upbringing.) You might also, at the same time, make a donation to some charity that benefits small children; it should be a multiple of $9. <br/><br/>2) Some people just don't have good luck with Ogham. You might try the runes instead -- most people I know are good with Ogham or with runes, but not both. Yes, you'll have to modify the workings; meditation on the runes should teach you what you need to know. "}, {"id": "cmt59770547", "title": "Re: Natural magic? and thank you!", "date": "2026-03-30 07:00 pm", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "I'm glad to hear that it worked so well for you, Tilly!  Very often the simpler some bit of magic is, the better ity works.", "edit_time": "2026-03-30 07:01 pm (UTC)"}]}, {"id": "cmt59757235", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 01:23 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Are there any theories what chronic fatigue syndrome and myalgic encephalomyelitis are, from an occult perspective?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59759283", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 04:03 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "Kimberly Steele on Substack &amp; Dreamwidth writes about etheric starvation and how to migitate it. It might be a contributing factor to suspectabilty to the disease?<br/><br/>Patrick H"}, {"id": "cmt59762867", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 04:32 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I was just about to mention etheric starvation. Both conditions involve severe deficits in the life force, though the causes are complex. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59757491", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 01:27 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I saved a couple of things for magic monday that I saw:<br/><br/><br/>Talk of Divine Visitation <br/>A white Dove , entered a Catholic Church, and calmly remained throughout the entire celebration, always facing the Priest <br/><br/>https://x.com/JustAdaugoijele/status/2036376341059096719<br/><br/>clip at the link<br/><br/>..that seems like a good omen to me.<br/><br/>and also, I saw this and was wondering, is this one of the famous 3 muskateers they think they may have found, and does that have any meaning with everything happening in the world today?<br/><br/>Musketeer d'Artagnan's remains believed found under Dutch church<br/><br/>https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cm2rew2dgzzo ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59763379", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 04:42 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) If the Holy Spirit were to return to the Catholic Church I think that would be a very good thing. <br/><br/>2) How delightful! Until I followed up on this, I had no idea that Charles de Batz de Castelmore d'Artagnan -- that was his full name -- was a real person. He's not one of the Three Musketeers -- those were Porthos, Athos, and Aramis -- but he's the main character of Dumas' novel by that title. I still imagine him as Michael York, who played him in a movie version in the 1970s, opposite Charlton Heston's perfect sneering arrogance as Cardinal Richelieu. Does the rediscovery of his bones mean anything? (D'Artagnan's, that is, not York's or Heston's.) I have no idea; we'll have to wait and see. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59766707", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 05:20 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) I rather doubt it will happen until the current church burns itself out. Between 1910 and 1967, the entire hierarchy, \"all clergy, pastors, confessors, preachers, religious superiors, and professors in philosophical-theological seminaries\" were required to swear an oath against Modernism. During this same time, one of the most spectacular examples of modernism hit the church (Vatican II), with all Catholic participants in the council having sworn an oath, before god, to reject the very thing they embraced at the council.<br/><br/>I'm pretty sure that that decision tainted the egregor of the church pretty badly, and might have brought down god's wrath in a very real way on the church....<br/><br/>https://www.papalencyclicals.net/pius10/p10moath.htm", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59772339", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 07:31 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Possibly not, but it's also possible that the Spirit will take a hand in the matter directly. I freely grant that the Roman church, like most of the other older established churches, was corrupted by modernism, but it's been corrupted in even more drastic ways in the past, and those were tolerably often followed by waves of renewal that discomfited the corrupt bishops and priests as much as anybody. If another of those is on its way, the bishops and priests may want to brace themselves, because that dove may be a polite note from on high reminding them that they aren't the ones, ultimately, who run the church..."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59766195", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 05:16 pm", "user": "brendhelm", "content": "On Palm Sunday no less.  That must be a favorable omen."}]}, {"id": "cmt59757747", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 01:29 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "An interesting story that I came across is that when F. Nietzsche declared that \"God is dead\", God responded by directing Satan to release demons into Western Civ. to punish our arrogant elites for their temerity. That ordinary people would also suffer was necessary collateral damage.<br/><br/>Like I said, an interesting story <br/><br/>Raymond R", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59763891", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 04:53 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The problem there is that Nietzsche wasn't a member of the elites. He was a fringe thinker whose books were almost completely unsuccessful during his life, and he died in a madhouse after going hopelessly insane. What's more, people had been saying \"God is dead\" for a long time before him. Here's Heinrich Heine, writing in 1834, more than half a century before Nietzsche's proclamation: <br/><br/>”A peculiar chill of horror, a mysterious sense of awe forbids us to write any further today. Our breast is full of a dreadful pity — old Jehovah himself is preparing for death. We have known him so well, from his cradle onwards, back in Egypt where he was brought up amongst divine calves, crocodiles, sacred onions, ibises, and cats. We have seen him, as he bade farewell to these playthings of his childhood and the obelisks and sphinxes of his native Nile valley, became a little god-king in Palestine, with a poor nation of shepherds, and settled down in his own temple-palace. We saw him later on, when he came into contact with Assyrian-Babylonian civilization, and laid aside his all-too-human passions, no longer just spewing out rage and revenge, or at least no longer instantly hurling thunderbolts down at every bit of despicable behavior.  We saw him emigrate to Rome, the imperial city, where he renounced all national prejudices and proclaimed the heavenly equality of all peoples, and with the use of such smooth phrases formed the opposition party against old Jupiter, and intrigued for so long until he took complete control, and from atop the Capitol ruled the city and the world, <i>urbem et orbem</i>. We saw how he became more and more spiritualized, how softly and blissfully he whimpered, how be became an amiable Father, a generic Friend to Man, a Contributor to World Happiness, a Philanthropist — but none of it could save him.<br/><br/>\"Can’t you hear those little bells tinkling? Down on your knees! They’re bringing the sacraments to a dying God.”<br/><br/>", "edit_time": "2026-03-30 04:55 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59788979", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 12:26 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Could there be any truth to these claims that *a* god is dying/dead? Is it possible that a particular god passed out of existence? Or that the Judeo-Christian god somehow \"left\" and it felt to mortals like a death? Do these things ever happen? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59790003", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 12:52 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Such things do indeed happen, and typically they do so at roughly two-thousand-year intervals. I wrote a blog post about that nearly a decade ago: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/death-god-speculation/\">https://www.ecosophia.net/death-god-speculation/</a>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59794867", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 01:55 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks for the link, I must have missed that post the first time around. It would explain quite a bit. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59797171", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 03:20 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "If this hypothesis is true, then Jesus is weakening or dying but not yet dead, because some people still feel his presence. I doubt <i>all</i> of those reported encounters are merely from the Jesus-egregore with no deity guiding it.<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59799475", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 03:46 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've suspected for quite some time that there's more than one entity who answers to the name of Jesus -- there's not much common ground between the spirit of unconditional love that some mystics call by that name and the pale and wrathful lord of the dead at war with biological life that some fundamentalists seem to worship. That might also account for it...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59800243", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 03:51 am", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>This reminds me: has there been any developments re: the Green Christ? That struck me as a possibly very fruitful direction for future spiritualities but I haven't heard much about it in a few years.  It also meshed well with your own ideas about Christ as a god of the life force: \"not a god of the dead, but of the living.\"</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59803315", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 04:03 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I haven't heard anything of late, which is unfortunate. "}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59797427", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 03:26 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "I too can relate to this. I've read about a \"divine presence\" as being like a column of fire, yet I've never really felt it.<br/>Personally, I seriously doubt that gods die in the mortal sense, like material bodies, but I do think they wax and wane. Maybe they fall into slumber, or phase out, or transform into something else. I can see where this would be analogous to death from our perspective."}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59764147", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 04:54 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "Hmmm. What historical period <i>hasn't</i> had lots of deliberate evil from elites and suffering for ordinary people?<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59764403", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 04:55 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "And of course there's that! "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59758003", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 02:35 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi John Michael, <br/>Thanks for MM and all else you do.<br/>My niece is about to try to buy a house near her smallholding for her mother, (my sister) who is of an age to need family close by.<br/>She will be meeting the seller on Wednesday 1st April at 9.30,<br/>She had requested \"non-physical\" assistance (my term, not hers) and so I have made my request to those I call \"Them Up (and Down) There\" but I just had an insight and I'd like your advice.<br/>The idea is that - although I have no idea what, if any, deities she addresses, it would be a good idea for her to listen to to the Planets by Holst on the way to the meeting.  Specifically the  most appropriate planet<br/>.so<br/>1/  Is this a good idea ?<br/>2/  If so, which planet ?  (Jupiter?)<br/>Warm regards<br/>Lurksalong<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59764659", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 04:57 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, the Jupiter theme, definitely. Jupiter is the planet of good feeling, benevolence, and generosity, and would be a useful influence. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59770291", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 06:55 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59758259", "title": "Dolmen Arch", "date": "2026-03-30 03:11 pm", "user": "trubrujah", "content": "The Dolmen Arch group has started going over the Second Branch of the Mabinogion.  You can find the latest post here:  <a href=\"https://thelongdescent.substack.com/p/mabinogion-second-branch-part-1\">https://thelongdescent.substack.com/p/mabinogion-second-branch-part-1</a>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59764915", "title": "Re: Dolmen Arch", "date": "2026-03-30 04:57 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Delighted to hear it. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59758515", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 03:45 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,<br/>Since taking up magic six or seven years ago, I have noticed that, whilst my terrible visual memory hasn't improved, I occasionally see figures quite clearly, in some cases as clearly as if they were standing next to me. I frequently see the form of Thoth, for example, often in the guise a painting or drawing. I also see people in my \"mind's eye\", with almost photographic clarity and detail. <br/><br/>I was working through memories of my childhood recently using a variant of the Emotional Freedom Technique, which is easier than journaling for me but produces the same results, when I seemed to see my parents actually in front of me, as they were just before they died, decades ago now. They seemed to want to apologise for things they did and said that subsequently caused me a lot of problems in life, and my mother was in tears. I had something that bizarrely resembled fragments of an actual conversation, although my eyes were open and the room was brightly lit. I did feel better afterwards. <br/><br/>Presumably I am not the first person to whom something similar has happened? Do you have any ideas? Thanks for your work. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59765171", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 05:01 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's called scrying, or in more formal terms, astral clairvoyance. The images you're seeing aren't in your visual memory; they're on the astral plane, which is where dreams take place and where the complex mental capacities we lump together under the label \"imagination\" also work. Six or seven years of magical practice have brought you to the point at which you can glimpse the astral world from time to time, and interact with astral beings, including the spirits of the dead. This is normal -- it's only our crazy culture that treats it as anything out of the ordinary -- and it also shows that you've been serious about your magical work. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59767475", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 05:36 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not the OP, but I have always been able to do this, even since early childhood. Do you have any suggestions on developing this skill further? Or suggestions of next steps? I currently meditate and pray daily, but have young children. I own your Golden Section books with the intention of possibly practicing that work in the future. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59772595", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 07:33 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There are instructions in the three GSF instructional volumes that will teach you what you need to know. Scrying's an important skill in occultism, and most of the books I've written that include practical instruction explain how to do it. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59758771", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 03:56 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG...<br/><br/>In the GD tradition:<br/>If you wanted to invoke the powers of two planets for one purpose, helping with different facets of it, would you do it in two separate rituals or could you string them together as in LBRP, LBRH then the invocation of the first planet followed by the invocation of the second planet (both including the whirl) followed by and LBRH! Or would you put another LBRH in-between the two invocations, if that whole idea is doable at all? I can see this being to chaotic and not focused enough on one hand, on the other I can see specific purposes that might benefit from multiple energies helping it along.<br/><br/>As always,thanx for this.....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59765427", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 05:04 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'd do this as two separate rituals with at least a few days between them. I get better results when I can attune myself fully with a given energy in a ritual working, clear it away, and then later go on to other energies. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59759539", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 04:03 pm", "user": "jenniferkobernik", "content": "Hello JMG,<br/><br/>In a previous MM, I asked about the etheric aspect of humanure composting, and you said that hot composting was key, as the microbes digest the etheric component of the humanure and make it safe to reenter the human food web (I have also always done it this way for safety on the material plane, as well). <br/><br/>However, I have been noodling on a design for a more passive humanure composting system, as we have multiple elderly and very young users living with us, as well as frequent guests, who can't contribute to the work of composting, and it's getting hard to keep up. <br/><br/>I am thinking of using a vermicomposting system, which is necessarily low-temperature for worm survival. From the etheric perspective, do you see any problem with this? I assume that being consumed or excreted by worms and their digestive biota would be as good as being processed by compost aerobes and thermophiles, but I really don't know if that's the case, or what etheric effect it might have on the worms who usually eat the manures of mammals with less structured etheric bodies.<br/><br/>(Note: I am familiar with the mixed, mostly discouraging evidence about vermicomposting's ability to inactivate Ascaris [roundworm] eggs and the management challenges of compost worms in a humanure system, so this question is really just about the etheric part of the problem, providing I can solve the other issues).<br/><br/>Thank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59765683", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 05:06 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "As long as it goes through somebody's digestive tract, it should be fine. Worms should be fine with humanure -- they eat human bodies when they can, after all. (Cue the old song we all learned in our school days: \"The worms crawl in, the worms crawl out, and they play pinochle on your snout...\")<br/><br/> ", "edit_time": "2026-03-30 05:06 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59778227", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 09:08 pm", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "I recall that line from Scary Stories to Tell in the Dark, a staple of my childhood.<br/><br/>Also, not an expert on nightsoil, but I'd recommend shallow burial to prevent flies.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59786931", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 11:44 pm", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "It's a very old song, and our host's version of that verse is less gross than the one I remember singing in the 1940s:  <br/><br/>As the hearse goes slowly by, <br/>You don't know whether to laugh or cry;<br/>For its next trip might be with you<br/>And there's nothing at all that you can do.<br/><br/>The worms crawl in, the worms crawl out,<br/>They go in through your eyes and come out of your snout.<br/>They call in their friends, and their relatives, too; <br/>And when they're finished there's naught left of you.  <br/><br/>Other and longer versions of \"The Hearse Song\" can be found here and there on the web, some far more gross than mine.<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59790259", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 12:53 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I quoted the least gross lines from the version I know!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59791027", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 12:58 am", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "Thank you!  "}, {"id": "cmt59798963", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 03:42 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I heard the one with \"spiders play pinochle on your snout\", which would scan better.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59799987", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 03:51 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "We may know different tunes, then. The rhythm of the one I know is da-DUM da-DUM-da da-DUM da-DUM, which won't fit the words you know -- \"spi-DERS play PI-nochle ON your SNOUT\" doesn't scan well. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59803571", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 04:09 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(i forgot the \"the\")"}]}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59760307", "title": "\"Supernatural\" Beliefs among contemporary Russians", "date": "2026-03-30 04:08 pm", "user": "hwistle", "content": "Hi John,<br/><br/>no questions this week, just wanted to share this article I found in Russia Today (RT). (I'm linking an external link since some folk might be unable to access RT due to censorship) (<a href=\"https://www.bignewsnetwork.com/news/278949474/most-russians-believe-in-supernatural-creatures-poll\">https://www.bignewsnetwork.com/news/278949474/most-russians-believe-in-supernatural-creatures-poll</a>)<br/><br/>According to a poll last week...<br/><br/><q>two-thirds of respondents (66%) believe in saints or higher powers protecting people in danger or in battle.<br/><br/>More than half (57%) believe in spirits or deities that protect military personnel; 50% say they believe in 'Domovoy', a household guardian spirit, and 48% believe in protective spirits for children and animals. Only 22% believe in mermaids and nymphs.<br/><br/>Russians also tend to accept various mystical and magical practices; 85% of respondents say they have tried at least one; 59% have visited sacred healing springs, 52% have consulted horoscopes or astrologers, 37% have tried fortune-telling, 36% have worshiped at sacred sites, and 25% have worn talismans or amulets tied to spirits or natural forces.</q>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59765939", "title": "Re: \"Supernatural\" Beliefs among contemporary Russians", "date": "2026-03-30 05:09 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm glad to hear the Russians aren't silly enough to dismiss the evidence of their senses and the traditions of their ancestors. I'd like to see more of them take <i>rusalkiy</i> and <i>leshiy</i> seriously, though -- those are the beings the article called \"mermaids and nymphs\". ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59771059", "title": "Re: \"Supernatural\" Beliefs among contemporary Russians", "date": "2026-03-30 07:02 pm", "user": "linden_matryoshka", "content": "Small correction: nymphs are нимфы. This word in Russian has the same meaning as in English. In Russian folklore nymphs are young, beautiful women. Leshiy (леший) is an old man who lives in les (forest). ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59772851", "title": "Re: \"Supernatural\" Beliefs among contemporary Russians", "date": "2026-03-30 07:35 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thanks for the correction! I didn't know that nymphs had been naturalized in Russia. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59774131", "title": "Re: \"Supernatural\" Beliefs among contemporary Russians", "date": "2026-03-30 07:48 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This is one of the most refreshing things I've read recently!<br/><br/>'Belief' might indeed be due to having had repeated experiences which make the 'supernatural' perfectly natural: making the 'belief', therefore, something which is more properly described as knowledge.  Along the lines of Jung's 'I don't believe, I know'.  <br/><br/>The household spirit particularly interests me, as one such -  or are there several here ?  -  seems to delight in playing, every now and then,  pranks which cause inconvenience, but are never malicious. <br/><br/>The latest was this: I habitually wear indoors and in the garden, when cutting firewod, etc, a pair of old calf-length leather boots which are immensely comfortable if somewhat knackered.  When away I leave them at the foot of my bed and I particularly look forward to getting them on again.   <br/><br/>When I returned after an absence of some 3 weeks, I felt something uncomfortable in the right boot, and tipped it up thinking it might be wood chips,small stones or earth from the garden, which is quite common, and lo and behold, out tumbled a quantity of scraps and rubbish from my bindery next door, and some small change from the box of mostly copper coins kept under the bed!<br/><br/>I don't find this disturbing, but take it in good part, and I am perfectly ready on this basis to believe in mermaids, fairies, trolls, and all  the strange denizens of European folklore. <br/><br/>If something so improbable as a 'brownie' exists, why not the rest?  Our ancestors were no fools. <br/><br/>Of a guardian angel/daimon I have had repeated proofs - including the saving of my (unimportant!) life so that too is beyond question.   ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59775155", "title": "Re: \"Supernatural\" Beliefs among contemporary Russians", "date": "2026-03-30 07:52 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this! Your household spirits are very traditionally minded, I see. Good for them -- and good for you. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59779251", "title": "Re: \"Supernatural\" Beliefs among contemporary Russians", "date": "2026-03-30 09:14 pm", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "Going off on a tangent, but aren't mermaids, like centaurs, the result of genetic experiments by the Atlanteans? Or is there more to the story?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59781555", "title": "Re: \"Supernatural\" Beliefs among contemporary Russians", "date": "2026-03-30 09:53 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's one theory that's been proposed by certain researchers. Since documentation is, ahem, very scarce, and it's by no means certain that the beings in question were physical rather than metaphysical, it really is hard to say. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59796659", "title": "Re: \"Supernatural\" Beliefs among contemporary Russians", "date": "2026-03-31 03:09 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "Well, that's fair enough. I guess the best we can do is piece together the sources we have."}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59770035", "title": "Re: \"Supernatural\" Beliefs among contemporary Russians", "date": "2026-03-30 06:54 pm", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "If anything, that survey understates the percentages, especially once you get outside the largest Russian cities.  <br/><br/>In rural village Russia, where everyone still raises much of their own food, there is a whole hierarchy of spirits: moving outward from one's own house, there are the potentially benevolent house-spirit (domovoy), the yard-spirit (dvorovoy), the barn-spirit (ovinnik), the field-spirit (polevoy), and so on, all the way out beyond the village bounds, to bath-house spirit (bannik), the quite dangerous water-spirits (vodyanye, plural), and finally forest-spirits (leshie, plural).  But even the domovoy, though benevolent toward humans by his nature, can turn dangerous if the house-spirit rituals are not properly observed.  <br/><br/>As a Christian add-on to this rural system of spirits, there are also the devils (besy, plural), and also the little devils (besiki, plural), who are merely a nuisance, like cockroaches.  It's a wonder-filled world out there, though a very strange to Western eyes.  <br/><br/>And then there are many other folk-magical practices, such as girls' scrying in a mirror at Christmas-tide to see whom they would end up marrying.  <br/><br/>And Russian émigrés, in my experience, would carry this spirit-filled and magical world with them when they emigrated from Russia to the United States.  (But the émigré 'teens I hung out with in my own 'teen years in the San Francisco Bay Area were children of parents who had emigrated to escape the Bolsheviks and their revolution.  It may be different with much more recent Russian émigré families now.)<br/><br/>One of the huge problems US political and military strategists have faced during my lifetime is their profound ignorance of how Russians \"work.\"  (The same is true, I suppose, of Iranians.)  They assume that all people everywhere, whatever their language and culture, \"work\" in the same way, value the same things, have much the same motives for what they choose to do and not to do, and respond to pressure in much the same ways.  In actual fact, they don't!  This is why our wars abroad, when they are waged against non-Europeans, have consistently been such abject failures, and will continue to be such abject failures.  --  OK, rant off now.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59773107", "title": "Re: \"Supernatural\" Beliefs among contemporary Russians", "date": "2026-03-30 07:39 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's a valid rant. The sad thing is that not that long ago the ancestors of these same political and military strategists believed much the same things that rural Russians do -- the number of books for girls in 19th century America that included spells to see whom they would end up marring, for example, is quite impressive. (Sara had a fair collection of them in PDF format; she was very interested in popular divination traditions.) With any luck, once our Age of Reason winds down in the usual way, our political and military strategists will be less stupid about this. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59789491", "title": "Re: \"Supernatural\" Beliefs among contemporary Russians", "date": "2026-03-31 12:32 am", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "Indeed their own ancestors did do just that, and the sort of books Sara collected are very much worth saving and studying.  <br/><br/>I have quite a collection of old American Hallowe'en postcards from the late 1800s and early 1900s, which show young people doing all sorts of magical practices, mostly--but not wholly--to learn whether they will get married, and if so, to whom.  Here Hallowe'en was the preferred season for such magical doings, not at the two Solstices (as in Russia).<br/><br/>I probably have one more small book still in me to get written.  If I do, it will be about those postcards and the magical customs that they illustrate.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59790771", "title": "Re: \"Supernatural\" Beliefs among contemporary Russians", "date": "2026-03-31 12:55 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'll look forward to that book! "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59779507", "title": "Re: \"Supernatural\" Beliefs among contemporary Russians", "date": "2026-03-30 09:16 pm", "user": "hwistle", "content": "Even better news then, Robert! And of course, within the confines of the Russian Federation we have living openly pagan traditions with their priests, beliefs and rituals among the Mari-El people...(<a href=\"https://www.rbth.com/multimedia/pictures/2014/05/12/pagan_prayers_and_sacrifices_in_the_woods_of_mari_el_36579\">https://www.rbth.com/multimedia/pictures/2014/05/12/pagan_prayers_and_sacrifices_in_the_woods_of_mari_el_36579</a>)"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59766451", "title": "Birth dates and Death Dates", "date": "2026-03-30 05:17 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>My meandering mind woke up with two weird questions (purely out of interest--nothing I plan to take \"action\" on)<br/><br/>1. Given that pregnant women who get C-sections make appointments for them, could one pick an auspicious moment for birth based on astrology? (Basically, can I give my hypothetical future kid a good birth by selecting a good birth time/location)?<br/><br/>2. Does your horoscope/astrological influence end once you die, or does it continue afterwards? For example, if I knew Julius Caesar's birth time and location exactly, could I track his influence to current date (obviously the world likely doesn't influence him too much any more...)? Or if that is too long ago, someone who died more recently (e.g. if I went through Epstein's chart, could I see his influence on the world or the world's influence on his reputation going forward)<br/><br/>No idea why these ideas stuck in my head this morning since I am not particularly into astrology, but I thought I'd ask in case you knew the answers...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59773363", "title": "Re: Birth dates and Death Dates", "date": "2026-03-30 07:42 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Not only is it possible, it happens quite routinely. Here, pulled at random off the internet, is an ad for a Vedic astrologer who will calculate an auspicious time for your baby to be delivered by C-section: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://astrokapoor.com/product/birth-time-selection/\">https://astrokapoor.com/product/birth-time-selection/</a><br/><br/>2) That's an interesting question that would have to be settled by research. Got a grant? ;-)<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59774387", "title": "Re: Birth dates and Death Dates", "date": "2026-03-30 07:49 pm", "user": "vitranc", "content": "How valid is such a birth?<br/>On the one hand one could consider it an election, but I also seem to remember reading somewhere, maybe even on this venue, that a forced birth leaves the child's radix out of phase with the designated family and could lead to troubled relationships.<br/>A Third route of consideration would be emergency births?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59774899", "title": "Re: Birth dates and Death Dates", "date": "2026-03-30 07:51 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There's a lot of dispute about that. Again, a study would be helpful. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59782835", "title": "Re: Birth dates and Death Dates", "date": "2026-03-30 10:08 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "\"2) That's an interesting question that would have to be settled by research. Got a grant? ;-)\"<br/><br/>If I ever get rich enough to provide a grant, would you go study it?<br/><br/>:)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59784115", "title": "Re: Birth dates and Death Dates", "date": "2026-03-30 10:30 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Sure. It would be easy enough to do; I'd choose 100 authors who have been dead for at least two centuries, so they had enough time for their reputations to wax and wane, get their horoscopes, run progressed charts and see if there's any correlation. Given the grant money I could hire competent statisticians to crunch the numbers, and then we'd know. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59784627", "title": "Re: Birth dates and Death Dates", "date": "2026-03-30 10:44 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I haven't been involved yet, but how much would you need?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59785139", "title": "Re: Birth dates and Death Dates", "date": "2026-03-30 10:53 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I have no idea at this point. The prospect hasn't seemed close enough for me to invest the time and money into sounding out the necessary subcontractors and preparing a budget yet. I do know some people in (or recently out of) the academic scene who could help make that happen, but I'm not going to pursue it unless I think there's a significant chance that it will go somewhere. "}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59777203", "title": "Re: Birth dates and Death Dates", "date": "2026-03-30 08:50 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Re 2: this guy has some interesting theories about how to find past lives based on your current natal chart (and also future lives is mentioned somewhere, if you dig into his past posts), might be of interest<br/>https://astrologyresearch.co.uk/3-have-you-been-here-before-with-astrological-regression-you-can-see-into-your-past-lives/<br/>"}]}, {"id": "cmt59766963", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 05:21 pm", "user": "thinking_turtle", "content": "<p>To share, for those who wonder what IC, DP, or JMG mean, a <a href=\"https://thinking-turtle.dreamwidth.org/tag/abbreviation\">list of abbreviations used on Ecopsophia</a>.  And here is a <a href=\"https://thinking-turtle.dreamwidth.org/tag/books\">list of the books our host published so far</a>.</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59773875", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 07:43 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thanks for this as always. If someone could tell me what I mean, that would be very welcome! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59780019", "title": "Meaning", "date": "2026-03-30 09:28 pm", "user": "aekeenatia", "content": "Dear JMG,<br/><br/>You certainly mean a lot to a lot of people!<br/>(Shift in the meaning of mean intended.)<br/><br/>With regards,<br/>Markéta", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59781811", "title": "Re: Meaning", "date": "2026-03-30 09:54 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you. To shift the meaning even further, I know a lot of people think that I'm also very mean to them! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59788211", "title": "Re: Meaning", "date": "2026-03-31 12:08 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You have a great sense of humor JMG (if that is you?). It really shines in your posts, books and interviews (lord knows I’ve seen enough of all three). ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59791283", "title": "Re: Meaning", "date": "2026-03-31 01:05 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good heavens. That's not something people tell me often, or at all; I spent my entire youth being the world's worst joke-teller, and only shed that status when I realized there's one and only one kind of joke I can make without sounding stupid:  saying something absurd as earnestly as possible. I do that often enough unintentionally that it comes naturally...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59792563", "title": "Re: Meaning", "date": "2026-03-31 01:16 am", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "I've had a similar experience! I have a deep fondness for word-play that almost no one else shares and almost always gets groans, but seem to have developed a talent for absurdity that is often appreciated, especially in this golden age of shaleposting.<br/><br/>I wonder if this is an autism thing?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59794099", "title": "Re: Meaning", "date": "2026-03-31 01:27 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It wouldn't surprise me in the least if it's an autism thing. In fact, I suspect it's 100% USDA certified grade A autism on the hoof. <br/><br/>As for wordplay and puns, oh dear gods, yes. I don't share my mental word games with anybody, as nobody else gets them. Who else on the planet would find the word \"mouse\" hilarious if it's spelled, and pronounced, with a W in place of the U, as \"mowse\"? I do. Go figure. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59796403", "title": "Re: Meaning", "date": "2026-03-31 03:08 am", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>Your example doesn't do it for me but it's exactly the sort of thing I find privately amusing and have learned not to share with others.  I especially like pronouncing words in ways that are technically viable based on their spelling but nothing like they're actually pronounced: like saying \"ethanol\" as \"ee-THAW-nul\" or Tylenol as \"tie-LIN-ul.\"</p>\n", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59799219", "title": "Re: Meaning", "date": "2026-03-31 03:43 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "My father -- also autistic, with knobs on -- used to love to joke about putting the em-PHAY-sis on the wrong sil-LAH-ble. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59800499", "title": "Re: Meaning", "date": "2026-03-31 03:54 am", "user": "vitranc", "content": "Well not hilarious, but it does tickle. :-)"}]}]}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59767731", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 05:51 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG, I just saw this article<br/><br/>its not exactly on topic or, maybe it is, but i thought you might like to know about it:<br/><br/>French masonic lodge at heart of murky murder trial<br/><br/>https://today.rtl.lu/news/world/french-masonic-lodge-at-heart-of-murky-murder-trial-1077813138", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59774643", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 07:50 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "This sort of thing happens now and again in certain European Masonic jurisdictions, which too often don't exercise adequate supervision over lodges. The Propaganda Due lodge in Italy a few years back is another example. In the US, any lodge that even started to dabble in such things would face a hostile audit and investigation from its local Grand Lodge, followed (if they found illegalities) by the expulsion of the members, the confiscation of all lodge assets, and a phone call to the authorities; there was a long struggle to chase the Klan out of Freemasonry back in the 1920s, and the institutional memory (and the legal tools) remain in place. If the people in question are in fact guilty, I hope they rot in prison, partly for their crimes but also because they've disgraced the Masonic Craft. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59768243", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 05:57 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "a) I've mentioned before, and seen others mention, issues with the Canadian egregor. I'm a dual citizen (Canada and US), and on May 2, will be moving to the US. I'm planning to renounce my Canadian citizenship shortly after that; most likely within a couple of months, because I am at the point where I want nothing more to do with Canada. Since my goal is to cut all ties with the country, would a day and hour of Saturn be a good time to file the paperwork?<br/><br/>b) I've been invoking my higher self using the Orphic Hymn to the genius as you suggested in a previous Magic Monday. I've since found myself thinking of a lost opportunity: about ten years ago, I almost went to teach English in Japan, but I gave up on the application about halfway through for some reason I can't remember; knowing who I was, it was probably a remarkably silly petty reason. I hadn't thought about it in years, but it's suddenly come back to me, complete with a strong urge to do it. It'll take a ton of work now, but it looks like it should be possible.<br/><br/>There have also been a very large number of Japan related synchronicities, and when I priced how much it would cost to get a basic certification to teach English as a second language and get prior experience to make my application better, I found that I have exactly enough (as in, to the dollar) in my emergency fund to pay for the course. Does this sound like my higher self is pushing me to do this, because there is some reason it wants me to go to Japan? <br/><br/>I will get some divination about it from someone who has better skills than I do; but before I ask the question, I want to know if this sounds plausible to someone who has a lot more experience with this sort of thing.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59775667", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 07:59 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Yes. Saturn rules endings and limits, so he's always the planet to invoke when you want to end something once and for all. <br/><br/>2) You invoked your guardian genius and shortly thereafter got a strong intuition to do something. Any Greek or Roman pagan would have known that the proper response is to take that seriously, go to a local augur or oracle for confirmation, and if the omens are favorable, do it. "}, {"id": "cmt59787187", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 11:57 pm", "user": "jprussell", "content": "For what it's worth, a good friend of mine taught English in Japan after college and fell in love with the country. He's now a special education teacher here in the states, but he goes to Japan every summer.<br/><br/>All of which is to say, if you can find a way to make it practical, maybe it'll end up \"rewarding\" in one way or another!<br/><br/>Cheers,<br/>Jeff"}]}, {"id": "cmt59769011", "title": "Your upcoming books?", "date": "2026-03-30 06:30 pm", "user": "agitated_seraph", "content": "Hello! I wanted to ask about two of your forthcoming titles. The first is one that I think you've mentioned, which I believe is called \"The Life-Force Workbook\" (or something similar). I wondered if there was a publication date yet? Partly I'm wondering because I am working through the other volumes in the series, and partly because I've been applying myself to the study of Vitalistic philosophical questions, and I am very interested in what you might have to say about such things! (Which is an assumption on my part, I know - but since I'm looking forward to the book anyway, it doesn't hurt to keep my fingers crossed!)<br/><br/>The second question is regarding a book that I discovered when I went to the Aeon site check out your forthcoming Yeats book. It is \"The Great Arcanum: A Commentary on 'The Doctrine and Ritual of High Magic' by Eliphas Levi.\" I'm not necessarily a frequent visitor here, but I don't recall anything about this (and assume it is based on your discussions of Levi's book elsewhere). I'm very excited to read this one, and wondered if you had anything you wanted to say about it that isn't on the Aeon site?<br/><br/>Thank you for your time and attention!<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59775923", "title": "Re: Your upcoming books?", "date": "2026-03-30 08:03 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) <i>The Life Force Workbook</i>, the third workbook in the Golden Section Fellowship sequence, will be out in September: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://spirit.aeonbooks.com/product/life-force-workbook/95435\">https://spirit.aeonbooks.com/product/life-force-workbook/95435</a><br/><br/>2) I spent four and a half years doing monthly posts on my blog, chapter by chapter, on Levi's book. That was the raw material for <i>The Great Arcanum</i>, which will be out next month: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://spirit.aeonbooks.com/product/great-arcanum/95405\">https://spirit.aeonbooks.com/product/great-arcanum/95405</a>"}]}, {"id": "cmt59769267", "title": "Best day/time for submissions?", "date": "2026-03-30 06:39 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi John!<br/>I’m sure you’ve mentioned this before but when is the best day and time to send a written submission off to a publisher? And which planet placements should I consider if any?<br/><br/>As always thank you for these Magic Mondays!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59776179", "title": "Re: Best day/time for submissions?", "date": "2026-03-30 08:05 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There are two ways to do it. The simple one is to send in the submission on the day and hour of Mercury. <br/><br/>The complex one is to look at your birth chart. See which planets rule the signs on the cusp of your 2nd, 3rd, and 10th natal houses. Make sure that at least one of those is well dignified, preferably in trine or sextile with a waxing Moon, and that none of them are in bad condition or in aspect with a malefic planet. There's your election. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59771571", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 07:16 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,<br/><br/>My mother passed away about 5 years ago. The other day my brother was talking to me on the phone and at some point in the conversation he mentioned that he had a weird dream where he thought our mother was trying to talk to him. I shrugged it off as just a weird dream that could mean any number of things. But last night I too had a weird dream where it felt like she was trying to communicate with me but there was all sorts of things preventing us from being directly in one another's presence. I was calling out to hear and I could hear her responding very faintly like she was answering back over a long distance. The astral setting in my dream was some huge mall or indoor shopping complex where there was a ton of activity going on and I was frantically attempting to find her. <br/><br/>So, one time is a coincidence, two times a big \"hmmmmm?\" <br/><br/>In reading various spiritual, occult, and NDE literature on the topic of the souls of the deceased and the afterlife, it seems strange that she would suddenly come back into contact 5 years after her death. The second half of her life was very troublesome and full of suffering and we had a very difficult relationship from her middle age into elderly years. I did have a few dreams about her after she died but they were in a rather negative context; I barely mourned her passing when it happened. This time, in the dream, it felt very peaceful and benign. <br/><br/>I'm not looking for dream analysis here (but anyone in the commentariat who is good at this, please feel free to chime in), as I know you've said many times that it's not your area of expertise. But I will ask, have you heard of deceased spirit contact of love ones happening this long after the time of death? I thought that most souls would already be reincarnated into a new body by then? Could she maybe be ready to finally take on a new incarnation and felt the need to try and reach out as her soul nears the material plane again? <br/><br/>If she did indeed have 5 years (of our time) to sort her issues out in whatever astral abode, I'm actually very happy for her, as I know you and others here have mentioned that souls these days tend to have barely any downtime between lives.    ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59776435", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 08:08 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Five years isn't at all unreasonable for postmortem contact. At this point she's finished the rough first pass through the events of her life and may have worked through the things that made her relationship with you so difficult; it's quite possible she meant to apologize and reconnect. If she appears again, and communication is still difficult, you may want to seek divination or find a good clairvoyant who can find out what your mother wants to say. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59776691", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 08:26 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(1) If she does appear again, would doing a simple yes/know geomantic reading on if she's trying to contact me suffice?<br/><br/>(2) How might I go about finding a clairvoyant? I don't know anyone in my personal circles who claims to have those abilities. And I'm very distrustful of strangers who do claim to have occult powers. Should spiritualist mediums be looked at with extreme skepticism? I remember from the Dion Fortune books I've read, she didn't hold them in very high regard, to put it lightly.    ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59782067", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 09:59 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Yes, that would do very well. If you want to get more information, divinations involving the dead belong to the 8th house. <br/><br/>2) That's a real problem nowadays as there are so many grifters out there, and even more well-meaning fools. I mentioned it only on the off chance that you might know somebody with the gift. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59771827", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 07:22 pm", "user": "kylec", "content": "All requests for healing hands from last week were fulfilled. Anyone who would like to sign up again, or for the first time, please leave your name and request.<br/><br/>And for future reference, if I am late posting like today, you can always pm me even if there is no poat. Thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59785651", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 11:11 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Kyle, I would appreciate healing hands. I am going to quit smoking.  Thank you. -Trent"}, {"id": "cmt59787443", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 12:02 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Another round for my psoriasis, please!<br/><br/>Thanks again!<br/><br/>HFZ"}, {"id": "cmt59790515", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 12:54 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yes, I would like healing hands this week.<br/><br/>Thank you very much, as always,<br/>Brad"}, {"id": "cmt59802035", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 03:58 am", "user": "vitranc", "content": "Some healing hands would be apreciated."}]}, {"id": "cmt59776947", "title": "Healing hands", "date": "2026-03-30 08:37 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Kyle, thanks for the offer.  <br/>I would be very grateful for healing hands this week.  Specifically I am starting with a possible chest cold and wish to \"nip it in the bud\" if possible.<br/>Thanks as always for your generosity.<br/>Courtinthenorth "}, {"id": "cmt59777459", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 08:53 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How do people make astrological talismans using gems calling for an image that it seems to me would be difficult to fit on a small or medium sized stone? For example, the image of \"the shape of a man covered in linen cloth, riding upon a dragon, holding a lance or a dart in his hand\". This had me wondering even more about a stone that could be set on a ring. I understand the image does not have to be artist level, but given the limited time of some elections, even with the right tools and skills etching something like the above mentioned image into a ring sized stone would be challenging. I'm also curious how they would have been made in the distant past as well. Thank you for this forum.<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59782323", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 10:06 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "A professional gem carver can produce very fine work in a small space. Here's a Roman seal ring: <br/>[IMAGE:0]<br/>The normal approach, back in the day, was to hire someone to do the work and arrange for it to be done during the election. ", "images": [{"url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/file/361269.jpg", "local_path": "./data/archive/2026/2026-03-29_09-05PM_Magic_Monday/images/2026-03-30_10_06_pm_361269.jpg"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59777971", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 09:06 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Have you heard of Quareia before? And if so, do you have any thoughts on the system? It seems to be a bit of a curated kitchen sink of near-eastern and western magic. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59782579", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 10:07 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've heard of it, but it came on the scene long after I was in the market for introductory courses on magic, and so I've never really looked into it. Sorry. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59778739", "title": "Role of occultism during decline", "date": "2026-03-30 09:11 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi John,<br/><br/>The meme is totally relatable as a fellow Gemini!<br/><br/>In a slowly declining civilization what role does occultism play, and why would I (or anyone really) be drawn to such a practice during these times? <br/><br/>What makes for a great occultist, compared to a mediocre one?<br/><br/>And lastly what would you say is the ultimate goal of the ceremonial magician (in the Golden Dawn tradition)?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59783091", "title": "Re: Role of occultism during decline", "date": "2026-03-30 10:18 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Magic always flourishes during the decline of a civilization. That's partly because a contracting economy offers many fewer opportunities to achieve happiness and success by mundane means, but it's also because the age of reason -- every civilization goes through one of those when it's near its peak -- breaks down as decline sets in, and the rediscovery of magic follows promptly. It also doesn't hurt that in a declining civilization, the official version of reality becomes a collection of gimmicks manipulated by the rich and influential to control and exploit others, and so there's a strong incentive to walk away from that official reality and try something less self-defeating; magic offers a useful alternative. <br/><br/>2) Sheer, stubborn, pigheaded perseverance. If you put in thirty minutes a day of practice, every day, no matter what, you can be as dumb as a box of rocks when you start out and you'll end up an adept. Equally, no matter what other wonderful qualities you might have, if you're not willing to put in that practice time, you're going to remain a dabbler. Take your pick. <br/><br/>3) The GD tradition is very explicit about that. We each have a lower self, our ordinary personality, which most of us mistake for ourselves; we each have a higher self or lower genius, which embodies all the potentials for power and wisdom we haven't yet actualized, and is more or less unconscious in most of us; and we each have a Higher and Divine Genius, which is our link to the spiritual realms and functions as our guardian spirit. The work of the GD is to awaken all the potentials in the higher self, to unite the lower self with the higher self, and to come into conscious contact with the Higher and Divine Genius, receiving the guidance and power that it can grant to us. The end result is literally to become more than human. This takes many lives of hard work! Still, that's the goal they had in view. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59788723", "title": "Re: Role of occultism during decline", "date": "2026-03-31 12:19 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not OP. <br/><br/>Regarding the “every single day” part of it, I’ve been keeping up a set of practices and habits in service of my goals (some related to occultism, some related to side-hustles) for about 4 months now. A few weeks ago I’ve been feeling exhausted at the end of each day to the point where I wouldn’t have energy for anything at all. This prompted me to get more serious about getting adequate sleep (which has been going well) and I’ve also experimented with dedicating Saturdays to errands and other matters and taking Sundays off for the past two or three weeks. <br/><br/>I find myself going back and forth on whether this is a good idea or not. In your experience, is having a regular rest day or days like this a valid option or is the disruption to forward momentum not worth it? I am still keeping up with my practices the rest of the week, but I do feel that bit of extra inertia that comes on every Monday and it makes me wonder. <br/><br/>Another option might be returning to a seven day a week schedule but reducing the time spent each day (that is, pacing myself) until I build up more stamina?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59791539", "title": "Re: Role of occultism during decline", "date": "2026-03-31 01:08 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "My experience, for whatever it's worth, is that unless really drastic circumstances make it essential, taking a day off is always a bad idea. It's much better to pace yourself and choose a schedule of practices you can do every day without courting exhaustion. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59794611", "title": "Re: Role of occultism during decline", "date": "2026-03-31 01:47 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Duly noted. I didn’t realize it until reading your response, but this might actually tie in with some divination readings I got a couple of weeks ago (after already making the adjustment) advising I dial things back a bit. At the time I was confused, wondering if taking weekends wasn’t enough or something, but now I suspect I was actually being told to pace myself so I can be more consistent. Thank you for your perspective, I’ll make the necessary adjustments moving forward and will evaluate how it affects my practice. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59795123", "title": "Re: Role of occultism during decline", "date": "2026-03-31 02:29 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks John!<br/>I’m a little relieved you didn’t say something along the lines of innate magical power or psychic ability; I think since I’m reading Dion fortunes biography I feel like, she was so incredibly effective, and yes she was also very committed, but that she also started out pretty talented psychically. Wouldn’t that in theory give an edge over those who are persistent but perhaps not as “talented”?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59798195", "title": "Re: Role of occultism during decline", "date": "2026-03-31 03:37 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Talent is simply what happens when you did a lot of hard work in a previous life, and it won't do a thing for you if you don't develop it with practice in this life. Fortune had talent, but she also flung herself into daily practice with persistence and enthusiasm, and so her talent turned out to be of benefit to her. If you've ever met someone who had some kind of talent and no willingness to work, you know how little they accomplished! The same is always true in magic. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59778995", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 09:12 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, my blessings to you and your readers if you will have them.<br/><br/>After a fair bit of prep gathering material for my CGD Druid grade tools, I'm about ready to start the ceremonies, starting with the wand. Exciting! My question is: can you repeat a consecration ceremony if you're unhappy with it/make a mistake? If so, is there anything to be mindful of? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59783347", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 10:20 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Not only can you, I highly recommend it. If you reconsecrate your working tools once each year -- that's what I recommend in the GSF system -- they become more powerful with every repetition. No, there isn't anything to worry about -- just do the ceremony. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59780531", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 09:38 pm", "user": "isaac_hill", "content": "Got a few things this week. <br/>1. (also for the commentariat) I am releasing my book \"The Zodiac Garden Guide\" very soon and looking to hop on some podcasts - does anybody have any recommendations?<br/><br/>2. I was thinking about my response about Richard Rose the other week, and I definitely want to say that he was the opposite of the neo-advaita \"You are already enlightened\" \"there is nothing you can do\" crowd, and he recommended hard work and commitment to the spiritual path. <br/><br/>3. I have been thinking about different paths through the forest and up the mountain(s), and about \"validity vs authenticity\"... there are definitely some strong points to being part of a tradition with a long, living lineage - many people have gone down that path and there are safeguards, you know where you're going, etc. There are some downsides too, like rigidity. I get the idea from you that it doesn't really matter what path you go down, it's just a matter of following that path, so there's a certain equivalence between all paths. Is that true? I think different paths also suit different kinds of people better as well. And also, some paths lead to dangerous places, predators, booby traps, etc. And, to use the art metaphor - you can make art with crayons or oil paints, and a very good artist can make a good work of art with crayons, but it will never be an oil painting. So, I guess the question is, do you think that more traditional paths are \"better\", and/or do you think it matters what path somebody goes down? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59783603", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 10:25 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Unfortunately Sara managed my podcasts back in the day and kept most of the details in her head. I don't have a list. One piece of advice, though -- don't neglect the little podcasts with small audiences. I started with those, and got surprisingly good results with them. <br/><br/>2) I think sometimes of what Shankara would say about the \"already enlightened\" crowd, and wince. Sure, in some mystic sense you're already enlightened; equally, in much the same mystic sense, you're one with everything that lives, but that doesn't mean it's a good idea to try to eat wood like a termite, or live in hard radiation like those algae that thrive in the cooling water of nuclear reactors. In the limitless Buddha-realms, a clueless dork may be essentially enlightened, but here in the realm of Samsara he's still a clueless dork. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59783859", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 10:29 pm", "user": "mole_end", "content": "1. My CGD altar is smaller than the suggested 18 inches square (which you told be some time ago was permissible), so if I make the cross and circle each 5 inches as the book suggests, they'll take up nearly the entire altar. Is it okay to scale those down as well, or is the number 5 important for some reason?<br/><br/>2. In the story of Tam Lin, the fae who capture the titular character are said to regularly \"pay a tiend to Hell\". Now I assume this is to some degree a Christianization of an older story element. If so, what would \"Hell\" possibly be in the older version? I know that in modern Welsh, the word \"annwn\" means the Christian Hell, when before it was more like an otherworld. Do you speculate it's the same in this Scottish case?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59784371", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 10:39 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The 5 inch measurement is purely for convenience. You can make the cross and circle any size you like. <br/><br/>2) It's really hard to guess. Welsh culture isn't purely Celtic by any means -- Wales was basically the refugee camp where the survivors of Roman Britain ended up, and so Welsh contains nearly as many words of Latin origin as English does. Scotland is even more of a complete mess -- you have the old Pictish traditions, overlaid by Irish invaders, then by Saxon invaders, then by the Norse, then by the English, with a lot of French in there as well courtesy of the \"Auld Alliance\" between France and Scotland. What parts of that tangle fed into the story of Tam Lin is an intriguing question that nobody can answer by the Queen of Elfland, and she's not talking. ;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59788467", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 12:13 am", "user": "mole_end", "content": "2) It just sounds extremely likely that if, for the sake of speculation, some Pictish equivalent of the cauldron of Annwn occasionally needed a few souls stuffed back into it for whatever reason, it would be just the kind of of thing that a James I or John Knox type would hear and say, \"Ach, that's obviously the Devil's Hell, because we all know the fairies are DEMONS!\"", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59791795", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 01:10 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's certainly possible, but there could be any number of other things behind it. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59787955", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 12:03 am", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "In Old Norse lore, Hel is a powerful Divine female being.  She presides over the realm where most folk end up after death.  (But half of those slain in battle go to Odin in Valhalla; the other half go Freya in her great hall.)   Since tithes (tiends) are mostly paid to beings, not to mere places, I suspect Norse influence here."}, {"id": "cmt59797939", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 03:35 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "I think it's a safe guess that \"hell\" in this context is some sort of spiritual pagan otherworld that Christian authorities disapproved of.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59799731", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 03:48 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's also possible that the story emerged after Christianity arrived, and was a product of the complex interplay of Pagan and Christian ideas that shows up all through Celtic faery lore. It's just not possible to say. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59785395", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 11:05 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,<br/><br/>I'm becoming aware of a quiet doubtful, skeptical voice when doing my spiritual practices. I keep pushing through, but because this voice has been getting more insistent I've also been working at understanding its source, which is fear (of disorder, of choosing the wrong path, of the unknown, of being gullible or manipulated, and of being overwhelmed or losing the capacity to have discernment). So I've been working at addressing that. I notice the divided will: one part is skeptical, another realizes this skepticism is likely blocking further experiences. <br/><br/>Any advice? And how can skepticism be a useful tool, rather than a hindrance, when it comes occult and spiritual practice?<br/><br/>I am keeping at my practices, and trying to judge the results by the effects the practices have, but sometimes the doubt is paralyzing. <br/><br/>Thank you!<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59785907", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 11:29 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "After I wrote that, I realized a major fear is of not being able to trust my own mind, or that my mind is playing tricks on me about the experiences I am having. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59786419", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 11:32 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's very much part of what I'm talking about. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59786163", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 11:31 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nearly everyone in the industrial world has been programmed from infancy on to have those doubts. The current system maintains itself by wheedling, bullying, and tricking people into ignoring all their innate capacities that don't make a profit for the institutions of the status quo. The fear you're feeling isn't yours; it's something you've been taught to feel. <br/><br/>The fact that you're conscious of it is excellent news; most people aren't aware of it, though it constantly shapes their thoughts, feelings, and choices. Your task now is to recognize the voice and ignore it. Treat it as empty noise, as though a parrot in the room with you was squawking corporate slogans. As you withdraw emotional energy from it, it'll fade away. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59786675", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-30 11:37 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "OK, makes sense, thank you!"}, {"id": "cmt59793075", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 01:17 am", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "I have this issue too. In my natal chart, Mercury is squaring Jupiter, so the doubt and second-guessing seem to be a part of my personality. It was reinforced by me taking the Internet Atheist rhetoric about basing one's beliefs on evidence seriously (it made my beliefs about the world brittle, vulnerable to disproof). <br/><br/>In the last few years, I had to abandon some of my beliefs about industrial civilization, the reliability of institutions, and materialism. So my doubt became stronger and operates at a more conscious level.<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59794355", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 01:46 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Doubt is a fine quality if it's applied evenhandedly to all possible targets. I'd have few objections to the so-called skeptics if now and again they applied their skepticism to the pronouncements of scientists, or for that matter, the claims of rationalism itself. For example, what possible justification can there be to insist that the universe must behave in a way that matches the cognitive habits that natural selection has hardwired into our species of social primates on this one little planet?  A little skepticism toward that display of jawdropping arrogance seems warranted! <br/><br/>What makes the manufactured doubt beaten into all of us so toxic is that it's one-sided. It never gets applied to the absurd claims and empty handwaving that so often prop up the status quo. It only gets applied to any idea that challenges the existing order of things, in much the same way that the only healing modalities the skeptics ever challenge are the ones that don't make profits for huge pharmaceutical corporations. <br/><br/>The point of all this rambling? To make your doubt conscious and apply it to the things you're not supposed to doubt is a very good thing. That way leads to genuine gnosis. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59795891", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 02:52 am", "user": "slithytoves123", "content": "<p>One overlooked advantage of applying doubt evenhandedly is you're more likely to keep your head when other people are losing theirs because reality fails to conform to their ideas.  Which is why the Pyrrhonists advocated a thoroughgoing skepticism as a path to <em>ataraxia</em>.</p>\n"}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59787699", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 12:03 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Merry Monday, and sorry for the macabre question: I’ve heard it said, when the body dies, the spirit exits through the eyes. Is there any info about this in occult literature? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59792307", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 01:15 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's one I haven't heard. The occult teachings I know of say that it's not just the spirit that leaves the body; when the material body dies, the rest of the self (the etheric body, astral body, mental sheath, and soul) leave as a unit. During sleep, the subtle bodies drift a little ways outside the material body, which is why you get the perceptions of the astral plane we call \"dreams.\"  When death happens, the subtle bodies drift further away, until there's nothing connecting them but the \"silver cord\" that some people see in out-of-body experience; then the silver cord breaks, and the subtle bodies go their own way. Later on (usually around three days later), the etheric body is shed in much the same way, and then the astral body dissolves slowly as the emotions and memories it contains are absorbed by the soul. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59789235", "title": "book reviews", "date": "2026-03-31 12:29 am", "user": "dfr1973", "content": "I ordered 3 books from Inner Traditions a few weeks ago, and want to share initial impressions.<br/>1. The Cunning Farmer by Todd Elliot - I'm not quite done with my initial read-through, but I have to echo JMG's comment that this is no \"fluff\" piece.  There is a LOT in it, starting with the philosophical foundations and building up from there.<br/><br/>2. The Magic of the Orphic Hymns; A New Translation for the Modern Mystic by Tamra Lucid and Ronnie Pontiac.  An interesting (and easy) read, though it seems part of the manuscript must have been misplaced or lost - there is a short chapter on incense and spices, but nothing on any of the individual hymns in my copy about either of those.  The authors say they found the older language of the Taylor translations to be difficult, and to grant a point it HAS been over two centuries since he translated those.  According to the first chapter, Pontiac decided to go back to the original texts in ancient Greek and went word-by-word with an English-Ancient Greek dictionary, and leaving it in free form instead of fitting it into a verse structure as Taylor did.<br/><br/>The thing that sticks in my mind the most though, is that the authors first met when they were both interns at the PRC in the 1980s, and both got to do research under Manly P. Hall himself. (I was still in grade school at the time.)<br/><br/>3. The Tradition of Household Spirits: Ancestral Lore and Practices, by Claude Lecouteux; translated by Jon E. Graham.  I'm a little more than halfway through, but am enjoying it immensely.  Oh, and he mentioned the Russian household spirits that are being discussed in a different post this week, as well as some from Britain, Germany, the Scandinavian countries, and of course his native France.  I'm sure JMG could read it in the original French, but I am glad for an English translation.  I may need to pick up more of his work.<br/><br/>I don't have a question this week, just taking advantage of DW not mistakenly blocking me because HughesNet must have a bird that phones home to Mississippi, and I am on satellite internet down here at the dead end of my dirt road in Florida.<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59792819", "title": "Re: book reviews", "date": "2026-03-31 01:16 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this! I'll want to look at the last of those  -- Lecouteux is very good, in either language. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59789747", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 12:52 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm quite a few years down the path now and I've recently had an experience of my reality cracking a bit. I have developed the capacity to distinguish different thought forms in my head from each other - sort of like there are different little sub-personalities. This led to a freak out about where exactly the 'real' me is - because most of them are hollow and echo old fear, habits etc that aren't mine. I was sort of aware of it before, but not to the same 'ah hah' extent.<br/><br/>Now I have been practicing golden dawn for a few years daily now, invoke/pray too my higher self daily (and recieve consistent energetic response in my heart space).<br/><br/>I'm wondering if you have any advice for truly connecting with the higher self? If there any books to read on it? How do I find that enduring essence that feels like 'me' that others speak of? What am I actually looking for?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59793331", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 01:22 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Okay, good. You've run up against one of the major challenges that every serious mage faces, and that's a positive thing. What can you do about it? Nothing -- and that's exactly the point. <br/><br/>You don't find the higher self; it finds you. You don't have the power to look for it, or find it, or make it come into contact with you. All you can do is invite its presence, over and over again...and wait. Your higher self is the active force in the relationship. <br/><br/>The fact that you've begun to distinguish the multiple personae in your head from yourself is an excellent sign, btw. As Zen masters like to say, you need to see the face you had before your mother and father were born, and again, you can't make that happen. Keep on with your practices, trust in the process, and it'll happen the moment you're actually ready for it. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59796147", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 03:07 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is this the veil of paroketh?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59798707", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 03:41 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "One of the experiences of those who approach the Veil, certainly. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59800755", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 03:55 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What are some of the other major challenges?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59802291", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 03:59 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm going to pass on this. I don't want people to manufacture those challenges for themselves out of a mistaken notion that this will get them somewhere faster. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59792051", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 01:10 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG<br/><br/>Divination strongly suggests I am currently experiencing a psychic attack. Divination also tells me a red bag amulet will help and to wear one asap. It's the middle of the night where I am, so for now I've found a very small carbon steel white nail, but have had to try to bend it using a hammer as I've no pliers. I've managed to slightly bend the tip of it and this will have to do for now. Will this help at all? I will get some more nails and pliers as soon as I can but will need to wear my makeshift amulet tomorrow. I did feel a bit calmer when I first put it on.<br/><br/>Many thanks for all your help.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59793587", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-03-31 01:23 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That will help quite a bit. Get the nails and pliers when you can."}]}, {"id": "cmt59795379", "title": "Canada", "date": "2026-03-31 02:29 am", "user": "rexford", "content": "Good Evening JMG and Commentariate<br/><br/>Other than fleeing Canada, and detaching from the nasty egregore here, what are other options? Most Canadians are after all going to stay here for obvious reasons... like having direct family members that will not move. <br/><br/>I have seen solution focused discussions of counter spells , and aligning with the American egregore as suggestions here on Magic Monday.  Any other ideas to influence the egregore collectively besides voting and daily spiritual practise?<br/><br/>  If Druidy is 'ubiquitously British', and if Canada is still British in spirit, then would evoking ancient values within the egregore be unwise?<br/><br/>This is the most recent predictive mundane chart completed by Mel Priestley<br/><a href=\"https://www.melpriestley.ca/2026-astrology-forecast-for-canada-and-the-u-s/\">https://www.melpriestley.ca/2026-astrology-forecast-for-canada-and-the-u-s/</a>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59801011", "title": "Re: Canada", "date": "2026-03-31 03:55 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Banishing rituals to dispel noxious spiritual influences, and prayer and invocation to bring in positive ones, might do some good, though it depends on what the gods have in mind. As for Druidry, the Druid Revival was born in England but spread very far; the first Druid grove in North America was founded in the Hudson river valley in 1798, and it also naturalized early and strongly in continental Europe and Australasia. Since the Revival embodies the eccentric, independent side of the British spirit, it might be well worth invoking against the domineering energies of your current ruling class. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59796915", "title": "DNF and Christine Campbell Thomson", "date": "2026-03-31 03:10 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I just stumbled across some information about CCT's correspondence with August Derleth(https://deepcuts.blog/2025/03/29/her-letters-to-august-derleth-christine-campbell-thomson/).<br/><br/>One point of interest is that in a 1941 letter she mentions Quality Press as an outlet for American horror/sf. Quality Press was also the publisher for the last two of the V.M. Steele novels. CCT was her literary agent, but I haven't seen anything about her placing those novels. It seems likely enough, however.<br/><br/>LeGrand", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59801267", "title": "Re: DNF and Christine Campbell Thomson", "date": "2026-03-31 03:57 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Fascinating! I remain convinced that Fortune probably wrote a torrent of pulp short stories under various assumed names; if only those could be found! "}, {"id": "cmt59802803", "title": "Re: DNF and Christine Campbell Thomson", "date": "2026-03-31 04:00 am", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "CCT also corresponded with H. P. Lovecraft about publishing in British publications.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59803059", "title": "Re: DNF and Christine Campbell Thomson", "date": "2026-03-31 04:01 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've wondered for years if Fortune published in <i>Weird Tales</i>..."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59801523", "title": "Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-03-31 03:57 am", "user": "ecoprayer", "content": "<a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/tag/prayerlist\">At this page</a> is the full list of all of the non-faith-specific requests for prayer that have recently appeared at <a href=\"https://ecosophia.net\">ecosophia.net</a> and <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org\">ecosophia.dreamwidth.org</a>, as well as in the comments of the prayer list posts (<a href=\"https://drive.google.com/file/d/1k1MLUovBKzARQYliiEYp26ddsPOvkRgo/view?usp=drivesdk\">printable version here</a>, current to 3/13). Please feel free to add any or all of the requests to your own prayers.<br/><br/>If I missed anybody, or if you would like to add a prayer request for yourself or anyone who has given you consent (or for whom a relevant person holds power of consent) to the list, please feel free to leave a comment below.<br/><br/><center>* * *</center><br/>This week I would like to bring special attention to the following prayer requests, selected from the fuller list.<br/><br/><div style=\"\"><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1732.html?thread=20676#cmt20676\">Bob W of Lake County, Ohio's</a> treatment for cancer go well so that he may heal and recover as quickly as possible.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/360870.html?thread=59415974#cmt59415974\">Open Space</a> be filled with the strength he needs to heal quickly from his current bout of Chicken Pox; may his will remain strong, that he does not scratch; may he be healed completely, and suffer no scarring in its wake.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/november-2025-open-post/#comment-149490\">Bob Ralston (aka Rasty Bob)</a>, who is in hospice care in Buckeye AZ, and who just lost his wife Leslie Fish, be blessed and find relief from his pain and discomfort; may Bob's heart remain strong. <br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1732.html?thread=18372#cmt18372\">Princess Cutekitten</a>, who has made no comments on any of the Ecosophia blogs for a year now, and hasn't responded to attempts at contact, be blessed wherever she is and in whatever form she may exist.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/359082.html?thread=59206570#cmt59206570\">Cathy N. of St. Marys, Ohio</a> heal and recover from injuries caused by a fall.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=15906#cmt15906\">Dustin, a relative of Brenainn</a>, be healed of a recently discovered heart condition.<br/><br/>May 1Wanderers's partner Cathy, whose cancer has returned, be given the physical and mental strength to fight it, and tolerate the treatment, and may she enjoy a full and permanent recovery.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=14882#cmt14882\">Jule from Iserlohn, Germany</a>, who is experiencing complications in her pregnancy due to an influenza infection, recover and have a pleasant pregnancy and birth.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=12322#cmt12322\">Larry Mulford</a>, who has entered hospice after a year battling with pancreatic cancer, pass in the smoothest possible manner, and may his wife be enveloped in our love.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1160.html?thread=12168#cmt12168\">Marko</a> have the strength to seize the opportunities.<br/><br/>May Pierre's young daughter, Athena, be healed from her fatigue and its root causes in ways that are easy, natural, and as holistic as possible.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18134.html?thread=452566#cmt452566\">5 year old Max</a> be blessed and protected during his parents' contentious divorce; may events work out in a manner most conducive to Max's healthy development over the long term.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/514.html?thread=2562#cmt2562\">Lydia G. of Geauga County, Ohio</a> heal and recover from prolonged health issues.<br/><br/>May both <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/347398.html?thread=57920774#cmt57920774\">Monika and the child she is pregnant with</a> both be blessed with good health and a safe delivery. <br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/338828.html?thread=56777612#cmt56777612\">Mary's sister</a> have her auto-immune conditions sent into remission, may her eyes remain healthy, and may she heal in body, mind, and spirit.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18134.html?thread=455382#cmt455382\">Trubujah's best friend Pat's teenage daughter Devin</a>, who has a mysterious condition which doctors are so far baffled by necessitating that she remain in a wheelchair, be healed of her condition; may the underlying cause come to light so that treatment may begin.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/16429.html?thread=392237#cmt392237\">Kevin’s sister Cynthia</a> be cured of the hallucinations and delusions that have afflicted her, and freed from emotional distress. May she be safely healed of the physical condition that has provoked her emotions; and may she be healed of the spiritual condition that brings her to be so unsettled by it. May she come to feel calm and secure in her physical body, regardless of its level of health.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/312140.html?thread=53408588#cmt53408588\">Frank R. Hartman, who lost his house in the Altadena fire, and all who have been affected by the larger conflagration</a> be blessed and healed.<br/><br/></div><div><br/><br/><center>* * *</center><br/>Guidelines for how long prayer requests stay on the list, how to word requests, how to be added to the weekly email list, how to improve the chances of your prayer being answered, and several other common questions and issues, are to be found <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/6373.html\">at the Ecosophia Prayer List FAQ</a>.<br/><br/>If there are any among you who might wish to join me in a bit of <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/1986.html\">astrological timing</a>, I pray each week for the health of all those with health problems on the list on the  astrological hour of the Sun on Sundays, bearing in mind the Sun's rulerships of heart, brain, and vital energies. If this appeals to you, I invite you to join me.<br/></div>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59801779", "title": "Re: Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-03-31 03:58 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this as always. "}]}]}, {"title": "Magic Monday", "url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/364815.html", "year": "2026", "month": "04", "day": "05", "time": "10-33PM", "comments": [{"id": "cmt59820047", "title": "Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-06 04:19 am", "user": "vitranc", "content": "Dear JMG, and commentariat, a couple of questions:<br/>1.) A question for the commentariat, since I believe JMG currently is not running a cosmic pipe in his apartment. Has any one tried earth pipes? And if so which ones? Have you used reagents with them? What kind and for what periods? Any words of wisdom and experience would be very appreciated.<br/><br/>2.) Do any of the gardening commentariat use any magic, elemental, spiritual means in your gardening? Inquiring druids, with a nascent garden would like to know?<br/><br/>3.) Now this one is finally mainly for you John. Quite simply, how would one spot, or determine, if someone has been using evil magic? Now I understand this could be difficult, the mention of evil magic in American politics abound on this forum and the demolatory accusations as to regards to foxxes have yet to be conformed. As said difficult; But that is why I would like to be careful in this regard.<br/>A relative has been behaving strangely for some time now. And, not to say to many personal things, their personal relationships look like they are inside out, like they either 1.) get exactly what they were denouncing in a partner before. Or 2.) in regard to their birth family, exactly what they always wanted, but it is empty now.<br/>It has occurred to me, that this looks like a sinister joke.<br/>And even more so, since there seems to be a similar pattern with their best friend who is going through a nasty, currently going on two years and running, Divorce.<br/>I would not like to jump to conclusions, but it would not surprise me to find out one of these days, that some spirits were called.<br/>Otherwise, how much of such a thing could be unintentionally caused by projection?<br/>Or could this be a simply manipulative and stubborn person being at fault for their own mess?<br/>So yes, how does one play a magic detective?<br/><br/>Best regards,<br/>V", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59820559", "title": "Re: Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-06 04:28 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I don't currently use an earth pipe but I had one in the garden Sara and I had in Cumberland. Somewhere in my files I've got a photo of me standing next to the 12-foot-tall corn that resulted. <br/><br/>2) Good heavens, yes. When I have a garden I communicate with the plant spirits, use Druid ceremonies at planting and harvest, and plant by the phases and signs of the Moon. <br/><br/>3) A combination of ordinary detective work and divination seems to do the trick. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59822095", "title": "Re: Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-06 04:51 am", "user": "vitranc", "content": "1.) Yes that is one of the models. And one gets results, but we both have, or had, them set to what amounts to factory settings and plopped into the ground. There are discussions of different settings, area of application and reagent use. Now this last part comes with mention of exposure time and concentration levels. As well as maintenance of both device and foundation area. I would invite any who have experience or material to share. Inquiring druids would like to know.<br/>P.S.: Should you find that photo, it would be incredible to share again. It looks like something from D&amp;D: JMG casts \"Enhanced growth\" :-D<br/>2.) Thank you for sharing. In times like this Victory ardens and Dachias are to be encouraged, magic or otherwise.<br/>3.) Hmm, so more of the same. And patience. OK. But in the mean time speculation might be damaging at this point."}]}, {"id": "cmt59823887", "title": "Re: Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-06 08:33 am", "user": "weilong", "content": "I installed an earth pipe in my garden a few years ago, and everything in the immediate vicinity (2-3m) grows like the dickens. I haven't put any reagents in the bottle yet.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59843087", "title": "Re: Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-06 06:27 pm", "user": "vitranc", "content": "Hmm, this is something Hugh Lowel writes about, apparently if you have it unbound, it's power dissipates fast, but if you bound it to your property its influence is firstly contained inside your property, and not infringing on your neigbours, and secondly has a much moe potent localised effect. The influence of my pipe can be felt 120 meters away.<br/><br/>To bind a earthpipe simply put a map, a printed version works just fine, and have the borders of the property marked out with a pen. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59826959", "title": "Re: Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-06 01:34 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Regarding evil magic in American politics, the Magic Resistance might get what they wanted for America, Trump defeated permanently. However this comes at the cost of the end of the two party American political system and Nazi white nationalists who hate Trump taking over America and establishing a dictatorship, with Magic Resistance types supporting said Nazis and white nationalists. That would be one heck of a sinister joke for American politics. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59843343", "title": "Re: Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-06 06:29 pm", "user": "vitranc", "content": "I do hope, that such a joke does not come to pass."}, {"id": "cmt59846671", "title": "Re: Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-06 07:28 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Funnily enough, I've seen a few vocal white nationalists switch over to the left. Of course, they're still white nationalists, but on most issues other than race, they're now openly leftist.  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59847951", "title": "Re: Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-06 08:00 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There's plenty of precedent for that; the Strasserite wing of the Nazi party tended to emphasize the \"socialist\" in National Socialist. If I remember correctly, the other Nazis called them \"beefsteak Nazis\" -- brown (as in Brownshirt) on the outside, red in the middle. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59858959", "title": "Re: Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-06 11:20 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Well also the Nazis were one of the first parties in the world to put into place an industrial managerial bureaucratic regime, that these days is routinely derided as \"leftist\". The Soviets and the Americans were latecomers to the party in that regards. <br/><br/>And historically there was nothing inherently right-wing about being racist or anti-Jewish. Richard Wagner the blue-haired leftist of the 19th century hated Jews. Karl Marx wrote about the Jewish Question and called people n-words. Many 19th century socialists, labor leaders, and trade unionists were very racist compared to 21st century standards. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59858447", "title": "Re: Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-06 11:00 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yeah, expect more of that switching to the left to happen among MAGA supporters more broadly the next few years as Trump fails to fulfill his electoral promises. The Trump derangement syndrome that arises from feeling betrayed by Trump's failure to adhere to any of his 2024 campaign promises will be significantly more deranged than any TDS arising from resistance liberals in the past decade, simply because MAGA had stratosphericly high expectations for Trump to save America that the resistance liberals never had. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59849231", "title": "Re: Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-06 08:08 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I think the more likely outcome is that Trump ends up being defeated by radicals from further right than he is, both for magical and mundane reasons: but there's still a high chance those radicals end up turning the US into a dictatorship...."}]}, {"id": "cmt59827471", "title": "Re: Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-06 01:52 pm", "user": "kayr", "content": "My husband built one for me and it has been setup in the garden for a few years now.  Unfortunately, I didn't notice any kind of effect, good or bad.  However, I have only just started to plant by moon signs and perhaps that will work better with the earth pipe then just the pipe alone.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59828751", "title": "Re: Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-06 03:18 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You may need to move it. Not every location has enough telluric energy to make an earth pipe work. and sometimes a movement of just a few inches can matter. If you decide to try this, stand in your garden, close your eyes, and try to feel where the life force is strongest. Some people see it as light, some feel it as pressure, some get a \"vibe\" and some just have a hunch, but if you do this at intervals you'll find that you can sense where the energies are strong. Then move the earth pipe to that location and see what happens. "}, {"id": "cmt59843599", "title": "Re: Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-06 06:30 pm", "user": "vitranc", "content": "What the big guy said.<br/>Plus you might try dowsing rods."}]}, {"id": "cmt59827727", "title": "Re: Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-06 02:09 pm", "user": "angelica5804", "content": "Here's the thread from 2021 with the fun picture of JMG in his garden:<br/><a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/120252.html?thread=13857980#cmt13857980\">https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/120252.html?thread=13857980#cmt13857980</a> ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59829007", "title": "Re: Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-06 03:18 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you! I've saved a copy. "}, {"id": "cmt59843855", "title": "Re: Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-06 06:31 pm", "user": "vitranc", "content": "Thank you"}]}, {"id": "cmt59827983", "title": "Re: Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-06 02:12 pm", "user": "angelica5804", "content": "Hi Vitranc,<br/>Regarding question (2), you might enjoy Todd Elliot's recent book called the Cunning Farmer.  It's really quite a masterpiece in my opinion.  The Plant Cunning podcast also just published an interview with Todd where they discuss magic in the garden among other things:<br/><a href=\"https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/ep-225-the-cunning-farmer-with-todd-elliot/id1534970138?i=1000758640084\">https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/ep-225-the-cunning-farmer-with-todd-elliot/id1534970138?i=1000758640084</a><br/><br/>~Angelica", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59844111", "title": "Re: Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-06 06:32 pm", "user": "vitranc", "content": "Oho! Now thank you.<br/>I did order The Cunning Farmer, but my shipment got delayed for now.<br/>But the podcast just got bookmarked!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59853839", "title": "Re: Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-06 09:24 pm", "user": "angelica5804", "content": "Vitranc,<br/>I have been wanting to build a cosmic pipe for awhile and I am intimidated by the electronics skills that appear necessary.  I would love for you to provide and update if you decide to build and use one.<br/><br/>~ Angelica", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59879439", "title": "Re: Earth pipes and magic detectives", "date": "2026-04-07 03:59 am", "user": "vitranc", "content": "Now I am wishing I did more documenting on how I built mine.<br/>The electronics skills are not the most pressing concern I found it requires some skill in arts and crafts.<br/><br/>The best place for practical Advice is Hugh Lovel's article A Cosmic Pipe Update . . . that appeared in Farming the Atmosphere, June 97. JMG graciously provided me with a copy last year.<br/>Ignore the actual circuit diagrams or now, the important part is, that it contains a section on construction notes. I found this to be invaluable and would use his advice in construction of any design.<br/><br/>There is some soldering involved, both of electronic components, and of the antennae plates, this was my first time soldering copper plates, so this <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nRLwK_n1qWM\">YouTube video</a> proved invaluable.<br/><br/>That should give you enough skills for a temple design that JMG used.<br/><br/>As for soldering electronics, should one decide for a more advanced cirsuitra, like in the Hieronimus original design, the best advice I can give is the one I head a physics teacher once give her education students in a phisics lab. \"It is a hand skill, and in order to scuire it, I just sat down with a circuit board plate and some random electronics parts in my art and craft cornenr, and I tried it till the components stuck\"<br/><br/>The MM is going to be over soon, I'll try and prepare something till next time.<br/><br/>:-)", "edit_time": "2026-04-07 04:03 am (UTC)"}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59820303", "title": "Speaking Well and Middle/Neo-Platonism In Wizard Robes", "date": "2026-04-06 04:21 am", "user": "jprussell", "content": "Good Evening,<br/><br/>To those who mark it, a Happy Easter, and for those who don't, may the rebirth of the world this spring bring you many good things anyhow!<br/><br/><b>To Share</b>: If anyone is interested in getting better at public speaking, I've posted my thoughts in two parts here: <a href=\"https://rhetoricfortherenaissanceman.com/2026/03/04/speaking-well-part-1/\">https://rhetoricfortherenaissanceman.com/2026/03/04/speaking-well-part-1/</a><br/><br/>and here: <a href=\"https://rhetoricfortherenaissanceman.com/2026/03/20/speaking-well-part-2/\">https://rhetoricfortherenaissanceman.com/2026/03/20/speaking-well-part-2/</a><br/><br/>(By way of qualification, I had to do a lot of public speaking in my former career as a management consultant and have been teaching it at the undergraduate and MBA level for the last eight years. If all that business school stuff puts you off, please note that my point with my current blog project is precisely to address what I see as the shortcomings of the typical attitude in business education.)<br/><br/><b>To Ask</b>: I enjoyed your recent appearance on <i>Therapeutic Astrology</i>, and one of your comments struck me as especially interesting, since I'm currently reading Dillon's <i>The Middle Platonists</i>: you said that \"occultism is just Middle Platonism dressed up in wizard robes\" (or something very like that). I had been under the impression that occultism was more <i>Neo</i>-Platonism in wizard robes, drawing heavily on folks like Plotinus and Proclus. So, my question is whether you think that's an especially meaningful distinction, and if so, what makes occultism more like Middle Platonism than Neoplatonism?<br/><br/>And a follow-up question: on the back of Dillon's book are some books I take to be similar surveys of other times/schools, <i>Neoplatonism</i> by R. Wallis and <i>The Presocratics</i> by E. Hussey - do you happen to know if these are comparably good as Dillon? <br/><br/>My blessings to all who welcome them,<br/>Jeff", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59821327", "title": "Re: Speaking Well and Middle/Neo-Platonism In Wizard Robes", "date": "2026-04-06 04:32 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hermeticism, Gnosticism, and Cabala are all derived from Middle Platonism rather than Neoplatonism. Neoplatonism had a strong influence on mysticism by way of Pseudo-Dionysius, but Iamblichean theurgy didn't really start to have an effect on later occultism until the 19th century, after Thomas Taylor made the core texts available in translation. I read the book by Wallis a long time ago and don't recall how good it was; I haven't read Hussey's book. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59849487", "title": "Re: Speaking Well and Middle/Neo-Platonism In Wizard Robes", "date": "2026-04-06 08:10 pm", "user": "jprussell", "content": "Ah, I see, thanks very much! It has been interesting reading through descriptions of various bits of Middle Platonism and going \"that sounds awfully familiar.\"<br/><br/>And thanks as well for the thoughts on the books, if I end up reading them, I'll share thoughts here.<br/><br/>Cheers,<br/>Jeff"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59820815", "title": "Universal Gnostic Church", "date": "2026-04-06 04:28 am", "user": "pointwithinacircle", "content": "In my reading over the last week I came across several interesting references to the Universal Gnostic Church.   This seemed like an interesting avenue to explore for the magically minded. I did a web search but the most likely looking URL came back with “no page found”.  There is a Facebook group with this name but it only has 82 members and that didn’t seem like what I am looking for. I tried several other URL’s with similar names but they seemed to be linked to specific schools of occultism.  Do you know if this group is still active and where I can learn more about it?  Thanks. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59821839", "title": "Re: Universal Gnostic Church", "date": "2026-04-06 04:40 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There are, that I know of, three groups using that name. One of them is French and usually calls itself l'Eglise Gnostique Universelle; the second appears to be a scam.  The third? Well, I'm its presiding bishop these days, more or less by accident. You can find a basic summary here -- <br/><br/><a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/238538.html\">https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/238538.html</a><br/><br/>-- and this link will get you a series of posts on the subject: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/tag/universal+gnostic+church\">https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/tag/universal+gnostic+church</a><br/><br/>"}, {"id": "cmt59857423", "title": "Re: Universal Gnostic Church", "date": "2026-04-06 10:49 pm", "user": "temporaryreality", "content": "A little dive into the internet archive a few months ago brought these up - you can poke around the various links to see how things used to be:<br/><a href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20060710095452/http://universalgnostic.com/index.htm\">https://web.archive.org/web/20060710095452/http://universalgnostic.com/index.htm</a><br/><a href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20060707042341/http://universalseminary.com/\">https://web.archive.org/web/20060707042341/http://universalseminary.com/</a><br/><br/>The seminary appears to have been continued by one or more of John Gilbert's students: <a href=\"https://drlmorris.wordpress.com/33-2/\">https://drlmorris.wordpress.com/33-2/</a> - I thought I'd found another site with the name, but can't locate it right this second and maybe I'm misremembering.<br/><br/>And while I'm at it, here's an updated link to \"The Sanctified Life\" one of the UGC texts: <a href=\"https://2f7e98c0-c321-4739-96d9-ffa831245095.filesusr.com/ugd/4b8763_ef2520b96bf8429ebc7ca28a3576d838.pdf\">https://2f7e98c0-c321-4739-96d9-ffa831245095.filesusr.com/ugd/4b8763_ef2520b96bf8429ebc7ca28a3576d838.pdf</a><br/><br/>"}]}, {"id": "cmt59821071", "title": "Incarnation?", "date": "2026-04-06 04:30 am", "user": "daviex", "content": "When I was a child I remember several times drifting awake in the middle of the night with the same peculiar feeling.  Very peaceful...just floating.  My body feels insubstantial.  My head feels sort of puffy and amorphous.  My lips feel very sensitive and important, like the very center of consciousness.  And it felt more like a memory than a dream.  Do you think a person can remember the time of incarnation in their mother's womb?  Even as a child, I wondered if that was a echo of my first moments of personhood.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59821583", "title": "Re: Incarnation?", "date": "2026-04-06 04:35 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I know people who remember their first hours of life outside the womb; for that matter, I have a memory that's probably from that, though I can't be sure. (It's mostly lying on my back, feeling very cold and lonely, and seeing something pale and gray and far away that was probably a ceiling seen through eyes that didn't focus well yet.) So it's by no means impossible. "}, {"id": "cmt59827215", "title": "Re: Incarnation?", "date": "2026-04-06 01:40 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Your memory prompted me to share my memory of giving birth to my second son.  For a fleeting moment I was looking down at myself on the bed. I made some commentary to myself about the state of my body. After my son was born I asked my husband if there has been a mirror on the ceiling in the room or a television screen. There was nothing there. So, I watched my son being born for a fleeting moment.  My life was never at risk (my vitals were fine and I was healthy during the process)"}]}, {"id": "cmt59822351", "title": "Significance of Trump's Epic Fail Coinciding with Easter?", "date": "2026-04-06 05:27 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "\"To escape finding [myself] in the ranks of the insane\" I have to accept that the US appears to have started, and lost, WW3 in just over a month -- with the end coinciding almost perfectly with Easter Sunday.<br/><br/>I don't know if that is a controversial statement with you (Maybe I am hallucinating the Marcus Aurelius quote to pertain to the situation), but in Trump's speech to the world he pretty much said the strait was going to have to be opened by someone other than the US.  And then his public meltdown yesterday seemed pretty insane to me.<br/><br/>Okay, so here I come to my question:   Did the astrological charts indicate the US empire would commit suicide right about now?<br/><br/>Any appropriate spiritual ceremony you might recommend?  <br/><br/>-gnat", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59829263", "title": "Re: Significance of Trump's Epic Fail Coinciding with Easter?", "date": "2026-04-06 03:20 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) No, and I have my doubts that the US empire is over. It's in retreat, but that's been central to the current administration's plans all along; the current mess may just give Trump the cover he needs to withdraw from the Persian Gulf so the empire can concentrate on Latin America and the Caribbean. <br/><br/>2) Depends on what you want to do, of course. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59831311", "title": "Re: Significance of Trump's Epic Fail Coinciding with Easter?", "date": "2026-04-06 03:57 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "I'm surprised that the US empire would lose ground in an ingress when exalted Jupiter rules the Descendant.<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59831567", "title": "Re: Significance of Trump's Epic Fail Coinciding with Easter?", "date": "2026-04-06 03:59 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If it's being done deliberately, to solidify the remaining empire, that would be quite appropriate for such an ingress. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59834895", "title": "Re: Significance of Trump's Epic Fail Coinciding with Easter?", "date": "2026-04-06 04:28 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The United States's foundation chart also has Saturn in the 10th house so if the US empire is over, it would be over quickly and suddenly without warning. "}, {"id": "cmt59846159", "title": "Re: Significance of Trump's Epic Fail Coinciding with Easter?", "date": "2026-04-06 07:16 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Not the OP)<br/><br/>If all the energy infrastructure in the Persian gulf ends up destroyed, would thar qualify as a scorched-earth retreat from empire rather than the end of the empire?<br/><br/>https://x.com/ChrisO_wiki/status/2040708063083069661<br/><br/>That loss of resources would certainly hit the empire's financial system, in addition to some of it's industry, but from what I see the empire's rivals would be hit harder...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59848463", "title": "Re: Significance of Trump's Epic Fail Coinciding with Easter?", "date": "2026-04-06 08:03 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's entirely possible. The US financial system is already in deep kimchi, given its vast burden of unpayable debt, but it might come through such an artificial crisis better than its rivals. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59854863", "title": "Re: Significance of Trump's Epic Fail Coinciding with Easter?", "date": "2026-04-06 09:59 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "See:<br/>https://www.coffeeandcovid.com/p/whose-war-thursday-march-19-2026<br/>  \"Strait of Hormuz Oil Flows By Country\".<br/><br/>Ponder the graphic and consider what strategy might ensue.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59859727", "title": "Re: Significance of Trump's Epic Fail Coinciding with Easter?", "date": "2026-04-06 11:37 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "And yet Europe, which receives only a very modest share of its fuel via the Strait of Hormuz seems to be getting hit worse by energy shortages and price spikes than Asia. The global fossil fuels market is more complex than a simplistic linear analysis like Jeff Childers' can reflect. "}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59875087", "title": "Re: Significance of Trump's Epic Fail Coinciding with Easter?", "date": "2026-04-07 02:58 am", "user": "revert2mean", "content": "FWIW in regards to this, I had a dream on Easter Saturday, while the whole world waits for a miracle. There was this old - well, maybe my age - guy somewhere in remote US, wearing a headband, with one of those rustic pipes of corn or whatever. He was doing a ceremony/dance. I could tell he'd waited not just through this lifetime, but many many lifetimes to do this ceremony. He was asking the sun for help in ending everything now that the time had come. I asked him if this had anything to do with the sixth planers needing to head off home. He was kind and told me I'd done a great job as a human for someone who's so far from human, but then he said it is time now for everything to return to its rightful place. And that was the end. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59876367", "title": "Re: Significance of Trump's Epic Fail Coinciding with Easter?", "date": "2026-04-07 03:31 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Wow. I hope the Sun doesn't take him at his word. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59822607", "title": "Inviting a patron (saint) for an organisation", "date": "2026-04-06 06:02 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How does an organisation invite/petition a (deceased) heroic figure to be our patron (saint)? How do we know if the person accepts? Through divination?<br/><br/>Thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59829519", "title": "Re: Inviting a patron (saint) for an organisation", "date": "2026-04-06 03:23 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Start by doing a divination to see if the spirit is amenable. If you get a \"yes,\" do a ceremony with an image of the person, describing the person's heroic deeds and formally making them the patron of the organization. Follow up with an annual event commemorating the person on their birthday, or the day of some particularly glorious deed. Go from there. The initial divination gives you permission; the rest is about building a relationship. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59822863", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 06:04 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A bit of a question on a strange situation with a lot of grief.<br/><br/>My dog passed away twelve days ago.  He was the last of a rescue batch shipped up from a shelter in California ten and a half years ago.  He picked me out and was afraid of everyone else.  It was only bit later I remembered a very strong dream from about twenty years previous and he was the dog in it.  Definitely, he was very unique and I expect finding another dog like him is only slightly more likely than finding the Ring of Eibon in a Happy Meal.  We were very close.<br/><br/>The night before he passed, (I found a vet able to make house calls) I had one of those vivid dreams.  I was in the living room where we were both sleeping in real life.  The details were out of body vivid, not dream like.  There were two of him.  His friendly and happy self greeting his older scared self.  Another dog of mine who had passed years ago also showed up as if he was a guide.<br/><br/>Last night, twelve days after the last dream, I had another.  It was brief.  I saw my dog running and happy.  Instead of lifelike and vivid like the last one, this one was ghostly.  I think it was a reassurance he was okay.  (I hope)<br/><br/>I had gotten another dog.  Divinations (if I read them correctly) said it would be best to adopt from who was left after the free adoption day at the shelter.  That was on Good Friday.<br/><br/>The new dog is a real sweetheart and she's trying to make it work out too.  The grief is still there.  There's been a few times walking past my dog's grave or along where we used to walk, I've broken down sobbing.<br/><br/>The strange thing is that this evening (Easter) a bit after sunset, I noticed there was a piece of snowflake obsidian centered on top of the pellet stove.  It was off the shelf nearby and could not have fallen there.  I am the only one who could have reached it, and I know I hadn't touched that shelf in a couple of weeks.<br/><br/>Handling the stone and keeping it nearby does help.  Is the case where objects around the house are being moved more the work of household spirits than deities?  If so, what is the best way to thank them?  I am deeply grateful and  doubt I would want to offend anyone who has helped like that anyways.<br/><br/>Hope that made sense.<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59830031", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 03:38 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It makes perfect sense. First of all, please accept my condolences on your loss. I know how difficult that sort of thing can be. <br/><br/>Second, the dreams are entirely typical, and all traditional lore indicates that they mean what you think they mean. The soul of your late dog is fine. <br/><br/>Third, apportation of small objects is another fairly common event in situations like this. No, it wasn't household spirits or gods; the soul of your late dog will have done it. (The souls of the recently dead can sometimes do such things, if they have the motivation.) Take it as a gift. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59842319", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 05:57 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you so very much for this.  It means a great deal.<br/><br/>What made the dream about him back in the mid 90s before I got him so memorable, was the strong, almost aching feeling of love.  It was a very special bond.<br/><br/>I am just grateful he was able to live out his life and I was able to stay with him at home in the end.  He would freak out if I left him with someone else for even a few minutes.  The grief has been overwhelming at times, but I would much rather suffer that than being the one who left him.<br/><br/>It will now be prayers of gratitude for his safe passage and listening carefully for what needs to be done next."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59823119", "title": "Naomi Wolf needs help", "date": "2026-04-06 06:43 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello John Micheal,<br/><br/>I remember you writing about Naomi Wolf a while back. Here's a recent post from her: https://substack.com/inbox/post/193216848<br/><br/>Can you help her out? What's real and what ain't?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59830287", "title": "Re: Naomi Wolf needs help", "date": "2026-04-06 03:45 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, she does, but it's not help I can give. <br/><br/>I'm looking out the window right now at a bright springtime scene. Golden sunlight is splashing down over the rich greens of grass and new leaves, and glowing on the gray-brown of tree bark and the faded russet paint of the fence; the sky is intensely blue where white and gray clouds aren't drifting past. Even the beige cinder blocks of the garage of the big apartment complex next door are vividly colored by the sun. Birds of half a dozen kinds are all over the place, dandelions and violets splash intense colors in the grass, and a black squirrel just went bounding past. <br/><br/>That is to say, it's not the world that's at issue. It's Ms. Wolf. The kind of derealization experience she's described in that essay is <a href=\"https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/depersonalization-derealization-disorder/symptoms-causes/syc-20352911\">a serious psychological problem</a>.  She needs to see a good psychotherapist, stat.  <br/><br/>", "edit_time": "2026-04-06 03:53 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59837711", "title": "Re: Naomi Wolf needs help", "date": "2026-04-06 04:46 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I suspect these thing are going to happen a lot with the end of the age of reason as people lost in their abstractions suddenly are confronted with reality and realize that their abstractions are wrong and do not correspond to reality. And then it's such a shock to them that they start to doubt everything else in life. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59839759", "title": "Re: Naomi Wolf needs help", "date": "2026-04-06 05:04 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes. I think it's indicative that Wolf describes the Covid lockdowns as the beginning of her symptoms. Discovering that the experts you were taught to trust were blowing smoke rings out their nether orifices, and that they were perfectly willing to sacrifice your liberty and your life, was a tremendous shock to a lot of people in the comfortable classes, and the knock-on effects of that shock will be continuing for a very long time. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59842831", "title": "Re: Naomi Wolf needs help", "date": "2026-04-06 06:27 pm", "user": "davidp", "content": "It sure was, even for those of us who were already intellectually aware of these things. It all got real so fast. 2020-2022 are still a blurry mess in my memory. The lockdowns, interestingly enough, completely destroyed my ability to place memories (post 2020) temporally, either in relation to other memories or to specific dates/years. This persisted beyond 2022, it hasn't been all that long that this ability has returned to me (perhaps not completely, as \"not all that long\" is the best timespan I can give here).<br/><br/>There does seem to be a very different quality to life before and after Covid. I certainly don't recall a constant sense of imminent catastrophe in the before-times.<br/><br/>Reality does seem pretty, well, real, though. The colours outside <em>are</em> currently fading, but not more than is expected during sunset and I fully expect them to return in their full vibrancy come morning.<br/><br/>—David P."}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59855631", "title": "Re: Naomi Wolf needs help", "date": "2026-04-06 10:09 pm", "user": "3bmend_135", "content": "I'm just a layperson, but the deliberate geoenginnering projects Naomi Wolf blames for the fading-out of colors probably have a modest and easily reversible impact on the atmosphere*. The purpose of the project is to make Progress-worshippers feel like they're saving the planet, not to actually succeed in doing so.<br/><br/>*Contrasted with all the accidental geoengineering of industrial pollution &amp; carbon emissions<br/><br/>Patrick H", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59859983", "title": "Re: Naomi Wolf needs help", "date": "2026-04-06 11:39 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Ha! Okay, you get today's gold star for getting it. Exactly -- geoengineering, like the \"green energy revolution\" that's gobbled up so much money and accomplished so little, pretends to solve problems the way that a mime pretends to be stuck in a phone booth. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59823375", "title": "Past-life Practice Hints", "date": "2026-04-06 07:12 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Given that people are expected to take multiple lifetimes of spiritual practice before they're done with incarnation, are there any accepted signs that you did magic in previous lives? I was never drawn to conventional religious thinking but felt an instant affinity and familiarity once I discovered magical literature. I take naturally to most meditative and energetic practices and divination methods I've tried; I was getting useful tarot readings within a week of starting when apparently some people take years. Ever since I was little I would give myself \"impromptu willpower tests\" where I would randomly resolve to do things like not look at clocks for the rest of the school day. It was interesting to compare these activities to methods of occult training like your \"Training the Will\" post series. Why would I decide to do that on a whim?<br/><br/>Another thing, the event that really sent me down the road of magical practice was creative work that led me to what could probably be described as contact with the sphere of Harmony/Tiphareth. I only achieved this contact for a moment but it transformed my understanding of my artistic field and the unifying concepts behind it. Does this contact prior to any magical practice suggest that I did some kind of pathworking in a prior incarnation?<br/><br/>Lastly, do you feel that there are definite reasons you shouldn't use computer files for a magical journal? I recall someone saying something like that. That's what I've been doing and journaling has been one of the biggest turning points in my practice, helping me go from one missed day a week on average to less than one missed day of practice a month, with make-up work after any missed day. Because of that I'm reluctant to switch to a more laborious method of journaling. The electronic journal also makes it easy to search for past divinations by topic.<br/><br/>Thanks for these posts.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59830799", "title": "Re: Past-life Practice Hints", "date": "2026-04-06 03:50 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It's hard to say whether the sort of thing you've described are signs that you've done magical training in the past, or simply that you came into this life knowing that there were certain kinds of training you need to do. (In my case, for example, it was some of both.) You may well have done some magical training in a previous life -- many people have, you know. The thing to watch for is a cascade of \"coincidences\" that puts you into contact with some specific occult tradition. That normally happens if you were initiated into that tradition in one life, and are ready to return to it in this one. <br/><br/>2) That's entirely a matter of personal preference. If you'd rather use a computer, by all means. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59823631", "title": "How to find a healing spirit/god/deity?", "date": "2026-04-06 07:27 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear Mr. Greer!<br/><br/>I got myself an education as a massage therapist and started to work in that field a while ago.<br/>I was looking for a spirit/deity/god for healing to work throuth me, but nothing really resonated with me when I looked up names on the www.<br/>How can I call/find a deity/god that wants to work through me to heal without getting tricked or etherically drained by some malevolent trickster spirit and is that a good idea in the first place?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59831055", "title": "Re: How to find a healing spirit/god/deity?", "date": "2026-04-06 03:57 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's important to remember that you have neither the right nor the power to make a deity or spirit show up to help you. The initiative has to come from their side, and it will come when the deity or spirit decides the time is right. <br/><br/>What you can do is let them know that you're open to working with them. For example, before you begin a massage treatment, silently pray: \"If there are beings of positive intent who wish to help heal this person, I invite their presence and participation.\" You'll know the offer has been taken up when you feel healing energies flowing through you, or when intuitive guidance starts directing your work, or both. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59831823", "title": "Re: How to find a healing spirit/god/deity?", "date": "2026-04-06 03:59 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not OP<br/><br/>I really like that for the MOE work &amp; Bridge of Love. Sometimes the person who wants healing doesn't have a relationship with a specific deity.<br/><br/>Thanks!<br/><br/>JPM", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59832591", "title": "Re: How to find a healing spirit/god/deity?", "date": "2026-04-06 04:07 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The MOE work is one of the contexts in which I've found this most valuable. Even with the ordinary healing hands, but yeah, especially with the Bridge of Love, the helpers vary from person to person; sometimes it's a deity, but quite often it's a deceased relative who wants to do something to help the client and can use the Essene work as a point of contact between the planes. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59834127", "title": "Re: How to find a healing spirit/god/deity?", "date": "2026-04-06 04:24 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you, this makes a lot of sense to me... sometimes I used the deities I work with, but it didn't always feel right. This framing is a great way to invite in the positive powers in an open way. After all, the appropriate powers to help a person know a lot more than I do...so this is really great. Thanks again. -JPM"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59833103", "title": "Re: How to find a healing spirit/god/deity?", "date": "2026-04-06 04:15 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "aaahhh. I understand. Thank you!"}, {"id": "cmt59846415", "title": "Re: How to find a healing spirit/god/deity?", "date": "2026-04-06 07:23 pm", "user": "not_gandalf", "content": "Another thought: Back in the day when I was active in the local AMORC Lodge, the Grand Councillor was, for a day job, a cardiac surgeon, and he said \"Well, you can also talk to the inner self of the person. You can say something like 'You're bleeding a little too much here, you need to slow that down\", and you will see it happen.\" So offering observations or healing energy or whatever,  to the inner, or higher, self of the individual is also a method...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59848207", "title": "Re: How to find a healing spirit/god/deity?", "date": "2026-04-06 08:01 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Fascinating. Thanks for this! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59853583", "title": "Re: How to find a healing spirit/god/deity?", "date": "2026-04-06 09:12 pm", "user": "emily07", "content": "...there is an english book of either American or Canadion origin that adresses this getting less of bleeding by talking to the patient also (from memory the title goes something like: what to say when everything else is done). Apparentely they taught one rescue team to say to the patient regardless if the patient was conscious or not something like: you're in safe hands now, only bleed as much as needed to clean your wounds and then start healing. We bring you to the hospital where everything is made ready to help you recover. On top of the usual medical routine of course. And another team was instructed to only do the usual medical routine. IIRC they wrote in the book that they had to fight the urge of team one to share what they were taught to do, because it was so effective. The book apparentely also has a section around chronic situations and I think the starting point was a mixture between NLP and something else.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59860239", "title": "Re: How to find a healing spirit/god/deity?", "date": "2026-04-06 11:44 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In Appalachian folk magic, charms to stop bleeding are very common. You have to have the power passed down to you by being taught by someone of the opposite gender, but once you have it, you can recite Ezekiel 16:6 three times and then say the full name of the person or animal you're trying to heal, and the bleeding will stop. More about this: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://www.appalachianhistory.net/2008/03/blood-verse.html\">https://www.appalachianhistory.net/2008/03/blood-verse.html</a><br/><br/>Ladies, if you're interested, consider yourself to have been instructed by me. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59864591", "title": "Re: How to find a healing spirit/god/deity?", "date": "2026-04-07 12:44 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you, JMG!   What a wonderful gift!  I will memorize the verse, and deploy as needed.<br/><br/>This post made my day.  And possibly made my month.  🙏<br/><br/>OtterGirl", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59868175", "title": "Re: How to find a healing spirit/god/deity?", "date": "2026-04-07 01:05 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for taking it seriously. Please pass the charm onto at least one man or boy, when you have the chance -- the more people know how to do it, the better. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59875599", "title": "Re: How to find a healing spirit/god/deity?", "date": "2026-04-07 03:06 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Will do!  Husband says he’ll take a look at it once I’ve memorized it.<br/><br/>Will the charm work at a distance, as well as in person?<br/><br/>Thanks again!<br/>OtterGirl", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59878159", "title": "Re: How to find a healing spirit/god/deity?", "date": "2026-04-07 03:44 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've never heard of it being used at a distance, but that doesn't mean it can't be done that way. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59872271", "title": "Re: How to find a healing spirit/god/deity?", "date": "2026-04-07 02:23 am", "user": "temporaryreality", "content": "Thank you for passing this along and sharing it with those of us who can accept it from you!"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59861263", "title": "Re: How to find a healing spirit/god/deity?", "date": "2026-04-06 11:49 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I had something like this happen when I had to travel to NYC and extract my mother from a crowded, chaotic hospital where she ended up after a medical emergency while traveling. The hospital was dangerously overcrowded and the staff completely overwhelmed and overworked, with terrible communication between nurses and doctors. I decided as I entered that I would invoke my highest self in every encounter while there, and attempt to contact the other person’s as well. For example, before dealing with a highly stressed and annoyed charge nurse, whose cooperation I needed to contact the doctor assigned to my mother, I would silently say, “Highest self of mine, please greet this person’s highest self and ask for help.” And then—crucially—I forced myself to believe this was possible and could be done, that us strangers could deal Highest-Self-to-Highest-Self.<br/><br/>It unequivocally worked. Every single person we dealt with seemed to bring their best to the circumstances, and went out of their way to help. <br/><br/>There were other oddities. One nurse suddenly broke down in sobs when I said, in passing but with sincerity, “You are asked to do too much, more than any one person can handle.” I really deeply felt compassion for him. It was surprising but seemed related.<br/><br/>Anyway, all of this is hard to put into words…but the effects were very real.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59867919", "title": "Re: How to find a healing spirit/god/deity?", "date": "2026-04-07 01:04 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you very much for sharing this experience. That's a wonderful practice and I suspect we can all benefit from using it. "}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59824143", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 09:27 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good Morning JMG,<br/>Your advice on planetary charity, if you would be so kind. <br/>I am current making planetary charity to the Moon, to help someone I know fight and hopefully recover from, breast cancer. I should be making the last of nine payments of multiples of nine today. <br/>My question is what to do next: the treatment will go on for months at least. Should I continue to make payments? Start a new set of nine, wait for a bit or what? I could sign up to regular weekly payments to the charity concerned but then I can't control the time of the payment. <br/>What would you advise? <br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59832079", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 04:05 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I recommend letting it rest for now. You've invoked the Moon in the traditional manner; now wait and let the Moon do her side of the work. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59856143", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 10:21 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not OP. What would be appropriate Moon charities?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59860495", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 11:45 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Any charity that helps infants is a Moon charity. Charities focused on the ocean, ditto. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59824399", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 09:57 am", "user": "davidp", "content": "Hey JMG,<br/><br/>1) I've been wondering about <em>agalmata</em>. The theory seems simple enough—take a hollow statue, put stuff associated with the deity in question into it, and just start using it as an image for altar prayer, if I got that right.<br/><br/>But beyond that, the process isn't clear to me. Is every material fine? Burnt clay would be naturally hollow but you mentioned using wood statues—so are those just regular wood carvings hollowed out? Where does the hole go? I'd assume on the bottom for aesthetics but then you'd have to plug it with something.<br/><br/>2) On that note, and I'm both asking you and the commentariat, where do you get your altar statues? Do you make them yourself? Commission an artist? Etsy?<br/><br/>3) You said that the LBRP will deconsecrate <em>agalmata</em>. I don't particularly like the idea of putting them into a bag, nor shrouding them every time. I was instead thinking about giving each statue an open box lined with silk or linen, with drapes at the front. Does that sound sensible?<br/><br/>4) On an unrelated note, I've skimmed parts of Franz Bardon's <em>Initiation into Hermetics</em>. If I understand you correctly, you think that Bardon's system works well, it's just not the one you've chosen.<br/><br/>I was a bit surprised that Bardon includes neither divination nor banishing (discursive meditation, to complete the trifecta, is clearly there, even if the focus is on the mind-emptying kind of meditation). But then I started wondering about the following passage:<br/><br/><blockquote>Hand in hand with the inner development of spirit and soul has to go that of the outer, the body also. No part of your Ego must lag behind or be neglected. Right in the morning, after getting up, you will brush your body with a soft brush until your skin turns faintly reddish. By doing so, your pores will open and be able to breathe more freely. Besides, the kidneys are exonerated for the most part. Then wash your whole body or the upper part of it, at least, with cold water and rub it with a rough towel until you feel quite warm. Sensitive people may use lukewarm water, especially in the cold season. This procedure ought to become a day's routine and be kept for a lifetime. It is so refreshing and removes tiredness.</blockquote><br/><br/>As cold water is a good etheric conductor, would this fulfil the purpose of a daily banishing, i.e. removing etheric crud?<br/><br/>—David P.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59832847", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 04:14 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Since the art of making and using agalmata is still being rediscovered, there's a lot that isn't yet known about it. I have no idea, for example, what effect different materials will have. The ancients used stone, bronze, and wood, and maybe other materials; ceramics such as fired clay would likely work well, but you'd have to experiment. Mine are wooden; they have 1 inch diameter holes drilled in the bottom, extending up much of the way through the image, and wooden plugs glued in place to seal the holes. <br/><br/>2) I got mine made by friends who are good at woodcarving. Since mine are Druid deities, the carvings are very simple -- they look as though they were made in a tribal setting a couple of thousand years ago! <br/><br/>3) You could do that, or simply drape a piece of silk or linen over them when you do your LBRP. <br/><br/>4) Yes, the water practice has a banishing effect, and so does his method of breathing energies into and out of the body -- that purifies the etheric and astral bodies. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59837455", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 04:45 pm", "user": "davidp", "content": "Thank you. That sounds a lot simpler than I imagined it.<br/><br/>4) With a regular LBRP or SoP practice, you said that one also cleanses the nearby environment (hence the need for silk/linen in the case of the LBRP). Would it be correct to assume that Bardon's methods don't confer that advantage?<br/><br/>—David P.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59839503", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 05:01 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's correct. The emergence of banishing rituals as a basic practice in occult training was one of the great magical innovations of the 19th century, and it's turned out to be an extremely valuable addition to the traditions. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59841807", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 05:45 pm", "user": "davidp", "content": "Thanks. While we're on the subject of Bardon, I have another question. He makes quite a number of very grandiose claims in <em>Initiation into Hermetics</em>. Those who \"specialize more particularly in the use of the elements\" are allegedly able to learn quite a number of feats. From what you've mentioned about etheric energies and what humans can do with them, most of them lie on a spectrum between those that I could see being possible with years of practice (such as imperviousness to pain or paralysing others in a fight) and those that seem just barely credible for a true master (such as levitation, seeing as you said that etheric telekinesis is possible).<br/><br/>Beyond the latter end of the spectrum falls what he says about the element of fire:<br/><br/><blockquote>With the help of the fire element the magician is able to stand the greatest cold if he accumulates this element in himself. The lamas in Tiber can produce an enormous heat in their bodies with the help of the accumulated fire element, so that they can quickly dry wet sheets wrapped on their bodies in the middle of winter. This experiment is known as \"tumo\" in Tibet. Any kind of combustible material can be ignited with the outward-projected fire element.</blockquote><br/><br/>Especially the last part, setting things on fire, seems to fall squarely under Rowling's Law—I've read it in a Harry Potter novel and thus it's not real magic.<br/><br/>So what gives? Is Bardon exaggerating here or is it actually possible to etherically set something on fire?<br/><br/>(Before you tell me off again, I am explicitly not asking for instructions, just whether or not it's possible.)<br/><br/>—David P. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59845391", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 06:59 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I have never seen anybody light a fire using magic, and I doubt that it's possible.  <br/><br/>On the other hand, tummo is apparently quite real. People who traveled in Tibet before the Chinese takeover describe young monks having tummo contests in which they'd go out in midwinter dressed only in loincloths, break the ice on the nearest watercourse, dip sheets into the nearly freezing water, and see who could cause the largest number of sheets to steam themselves dry by wrapping them around their bodies. The human metabolism is capable of quite a bit of heat output; of course it helps that winters in Tibet are very dry as well as very cold, and a modest amount of heat will cause water vapor to be absorbed by the extremely dry air. <br/><br/>The only examples of etheric telekinesis I've ever witnessed, by the way, involved making very light and well-balanced objects move. I'd be astounded if anybody could levitate a human body. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59850767", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 08:26 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A friend of mine once summoned some fire elementals to help her light a fire when we were camping after we decided to tease her about her interest in magic. The fire elementals told her where we had hidden the matches on her, which really impressed us because we had taken every step we could think of to make sure she could not find them, and she knew exactly where to look.<br/><br/>Based on this, I'd say that summoning fire elementals to help start fires would probably work in a lot of cases, because they'll probably be willing and able to tell you where to find something to start fires (like matches) in a lot of cases...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59860751", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 11:48 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, granted! Spirits have plenty of power on their own planes. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59853327", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 09:12 pm", "user": "dfr1973", "content": "Maybe we didn't use *only* magic to light the fire, but it did rain most of the day, so we stood around the fire ring chanting \"Spirit of Fire, come to us; We will kindle the fire!\"  We were the only ones to have a good Beltane fire going until much later in the evening.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59861007", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 11:49 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Another good example. You provided the material basis and the material action; the spirits of fire took care of things on the planes where they work. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59848975", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 08:06 pm", "user": "jprussell", "content": "Wim Hof \"the Iceman\" was partially inspired by tummo techniques and has managed some remarkable feats of cold endurance. I took his course years back and was able to get quite comfortable with ice baths and cold showers, though nothing so impressive as the Tibetan monks and their contests.<br/><br/>I'm pretty sure he can't set things on fire with his spirit, though. :)<br/><br/>Cheers,<br/>Jeff"}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59846927", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 07:29 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Does that mean that the SOP will de-consecrate as well?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59847695", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 07:58 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nope. The SoP was designed precisely to be free of that problem. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59857167", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 10:46 pm", "user": "scottyc", "content": "<span class=\"ljuser\" lj:user=\"davidp\" style=\"white-space: nowrap;\"><a href=\"https://davidp.dreamwidth.org/profile\"></a><a href=\"https://davidp.dreamwidth.org/\"><b>davidp</b></a></span> - Concerning altar statues I picked up a statuette of Mercury, or I should say Hermes, in one of the ubiquitous tourist stores in Athens.   Mass produced but of a nicer type and when visiting Bath, England I made sure to pick up a reproduction of Sul's gilt bronze head.  Mass produced and plastic but it gives me a point of focus.<br/><br/>At work I started picking up scrap pieces of pine wood broken off from pallets to draw or paint.  Eventually, I got the idea to incorporate this for some altar pieces. This has led me to begin plans on making my own small icons.  They will be rudimentary but I believe the kami won't mind as long as I put my best into it. <br/><br/><br/><br/><br/><br/><br/><br/><br/>"}, {"id": "cmt59866127", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-07 12:52 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "To answer your second question, I've gotten all but one of my statues from Blagowood on Etsy, with that one coming from Medievalgodsends (also Etsy); all are wood. There's a list of other artists at the end of this blog post: https://wyrddesigns.wordpress.com/2023/11/19/beware-the-fakes/ <br/><br/>--Sister Crow"}]}, {"id": "cmt59824655", "title": "Painting Icons and Appropriate Herbs for Druid Revival Gods", "date": "2026-04-06 10:22 am", "user": "scottyc", "content": "Good Day JMG and all readers,<br/><br/>First, thank you, as always, for this opportunity to ask questions.<br/><br/>I have decided to build upon my relationship with the Druid Revival gods by creating icons / talismans for my altar.  Last week JMG mentioned mixing appropriate herbs in with the paint to help fortify the talisman and also a gold tincture. <br/><br/>Question is what is happening with the herbs and gold?  I know part of the process is building correspondence by means of materials (herbs, metals), colors, symbols and appropriate astrological timing but is the herbal mixture attracting etheric energy and the gold astral energy?<br/><br/>For the Druid Revival gods as recommended to use in the Way of the Golden Section's SOP (Hu, Sul, Hesus, Ellen) my intention is to use the herbs appropriate to the planet associated with each cardinal direction (e.g. South = Mars). <i>The Way of the Golden Section</i> lists appropriate trees for the gates associated with the cardinal directions but I'll probably use William Lilly's guides for the herbs unless there are specific herbs that could be associated with those gods?  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59833359", "title": "Re: Painting Icons and Appropriate Herbs for Druid Revival Gods", "date": "2026-04-06 04:16 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The herbs are simply part of the correspondences. Mixing them into the paint helps make the talisman stronger. The gold, however, attracts etheric energy from the heavens and empowers the talisman generally. <br/><br/>2) That should be fine. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59824911", "title": "The Cunning Farmer", "date": "2026-04-06 10:58 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello!<br/><br/>Two months ago, you mentioned a new book called \"The Cunning Farmer\". The introduction to the book mentions \"He also explores working with Earth and Moon energies\"<br/><br/>(1) Presumably Earth energies are telluric currents, but how about Moon energies? What are those? <br/>(2) Are they the union of solar and telluric currents, known as the lunar current? Or is it something else?<br/>(3) Does the book cross over with your \"secret of the temple\" book? <br/>(4) Are the techniques taught in this book relevant to both the northern and southern hemispheres? <br/>Many thanks and regards.<br/><br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59833615", "title": "Re: The Cunning Farmer", "date": "2026-04-06 04:18 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Okay, first of all, I didn't write that book. Todd Elliott did, and the magical theories he uses as his basic structure aren't the same as the ones I use. <br/><br/>1) The astrological influences and etheric tides governed by the Moon. <br/><br/>2) They're something else -- see above. <br/><br/>3) Not to any significant extent. <br/><br/>4) As far as I know, yes. "}, {"id": "cmt59847439", "title": "Re: The Cunning Farmer", "date": "2026-04-06 07:50 pm", "user": "mskrieger", "content": "Hello Anonymous,<br/><br/>I purchased \"The Cunning Farmer\" and have read through part of it, finding it very dense and very worthwhile. I paused at the chapter on weather magic, as the use of psalms intrigued me and I've been memorizing and meditating on several of them.<br/><br/>The author is also accessible via email, and was quite polite answering a question of mine. You may wish to reach out to him directly.<br/><br/>--Ms. Krieger"}]}, {"id": "cmt59825167", "title": "Dodecagram", "date": "2026-04-06 11:15 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good morning, JMG.<br/><br/>Thank you for creating the SGO. It has been good fuel for the meditative fire.<br/><br/>I've been dedicating 3 days of meditation to each card so far. The work of sussing out the nuance of meanings (both symbolic and divinatory) from similar cards has been rewarding (though at times frustrating), though one pair still eludes me.<br/><br/>I struggle to differentiate between the square's aspect of manifestation and the dodecagram's aspect of completion. My meditations on either card has revealed some interesting (to me) insights, though none of these would aid me in a divinatory setting I suspect. The description of these aspects in the SGO book also seem quite similar (again, to me at least).<br/><br/>If it isn't too much to ask, could you please compare and contrast the divinatory meaning of both cards? <br/><br/>I apologize if I'm missing something that should be obvious here.<br/><br/>JR<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59833871", "title": "Re: Dodecagram", "date": "2026-04-06 04:22 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Sure thing. A manifestation need not be completed, and something can be complete and remain unmanifest. You're right that the way I phrased the two divinatory meanings makes them sound more similar than they should be. To me, the Square focuses on something becoming solid and apparent to otherrs, while the Dodecagram focuses on something being finished. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59840527", "title": "Re: Dodecagram", "date": "2026-04-06 05:18 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks for the response. I'll use what you wrote when I next contemplate those cards.<br/><br/>Have a great rest of the day!<br/><br/>JR"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59825423", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 11:16 am", "user": "brenainn", "content": "Recently, the spirits showed me a silent vision of myself residing very near, or even within, the cemetery where my spirit guide is buried. The image was vivid and clear, yet it came without any spoken instruction or further commentary, leaving me to interpret it on my own. Divination on the matter has also remained unclear.<br/><br/>This vision has greatly intensified an already strong sense of calling to live in extremely close proximity to that specific place. While I recognize that actually residing on cemetery grounds long-term isn't feasible in any straightforward way, the pull feels like genuine spiritual direction, even if the guidance at the moment is limited and indirect.<br/><br/>Interestingly, as I've visited the cemetery more frequently (I used to go only about once a month), I've received clearer guidance on different offerings to make upon arrival, things to do while there, and offerings to leave when departing. These experiences have deepened my connection and sense of purpose there.<br/><br/>I don't have much of a question, but I'm wondering: Has anyone here ever heard of anything like this happening to a modern Western person? Does it connect to practices from more distant historical or cultural traditions? I assume this is related to my recent spiritual calling, of course, but the spirits haven't revealed much more, and the topic is very emotionally charged for me right now.<br/><br/>Any insights, similar experiences, or suggestions for things to ponder or meditate on while I await clearer guidance would be most welcome. Thank you.<br/><br/>EDIT: One thing that does seem clear is that it does not feel like it must be done immediately. In the vision, I am somewhat older in appearance than now.", "edit_time": "2026-04-06 01:41 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59834383", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 04:25 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It used to be quite standard for hermits and monks devoted to a given saint or sage to live right next to, or in, the shrine where that holy person was buried. I don't recall reading about that happening in modern times, but \"modern times\" are slipping back in the rear view mirror these days. I'd say that your best bet is to remain open and let the spirits take the initiative. If they want something like this to happen, the opportunity will be provided to you. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59856399", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 10:26 pm", "user": "brenainn", "content": "As always, thank you for the answer. Somewhat related question: within Catholicism, touching a piece of cloth (usually linen) or image to a saint or holy person's tomb/grave creates a third class relic. Is there anything analogous to this in the Western magical tradition? It occurred to me a couple days ago that I am only a half day's drive from the burial place of Joseph Smith. I am thinking of taking a day off from work and heading over there to touch a linen cloth to his burial place, plus probably that of his wife, brother, and parents. Separate pieces of linen cloth, that is.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59861519", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 11:52 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Most Western occultism doesn't work with relics of the dead -- it leaves that to the religious traditions -- but there's no reason why you can't do that. I know a lot of hoodoo practitioners who collect graveyard dirt for similar reasons. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59825679", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 12:14 pm", "user": "gnosticlombe", "content": "Good morning an happy Monday,<br/><br/>Thank you for offering this place for questions and discussion.<br/><br/>While reading through and studying “The sanctified life”, I’ve noted a lot of spiritual links and ties with the MOE, (both directly from their shared origin in the UGC, and the historical Essenes being a pseudo monastic order with its own way of life document.)<br/><br/>Would it be within the scope of the UGC and Universal order of Monk to create an Essene focused monastic practice, combining the teachings and practices of the MOE and the personal spiritual development and ethos of a personal monasticism?<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59834639", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 04:27 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Not only is it within the bounds of the UGC and its monastic tradition, I met people back in the day who did it. I'm delighted to hear you're studying <i>The Sanctified Life</i>, btw!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59854095", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 09:26 pm", "user": "gnosticlombe", "content": "Excellent! I’m very much excited to continue on this path. Thank you for your time and guidance in this and carrying forward the UGC and related traditions. "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59825935", "title": "A Question about the subtle bodies", "date": "2026-04-06 12:58 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Happy begining of spring JMG, I have a question about the concept of a sheath.<br/><br/>Is a sheath functioning a little like a radio reciever? Crystals have an etheric sheath, and I believe we are using crystals to literaly build radio recievers.<br/><br/>I recently tried during meditation to imagine I am tuning myself to the theme, and felt like an antena that's picking up something, which followed by some connections being made.<br/><br/>This got me thinking, A crystal that resonates with radio waves, is actually picking up the energies of a higher region in the material rather than etheric plane.<br/><br/>By analogy, the \"connections\" I made seem to take place in the high astral rather than mental plane, but if I am correct the part of me that felt like an antena was my mental sheath. <br/><br/>So, if a sheath is like a radio reciever, I am wondering if after a soul with a sheath gets reborn with a body in that plane, the soul is no longer using its capacity to recieve \"signals\" only to precieve the higher regions of the plane below the plane where the sheath is, but instead uses its new body to percieve the plane it is made of in its own terms? <br/><br/> ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59835151", "title": "Re: A Question about the subtle bodies", "date": "2026-04-06 04:29 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's an intriguing metaphor, and yes, it works. Imagine the difference between an antenna and an eye. The antenna passively receives what's flowing through the level of being to which it's attuned. The eye actively seeks out things to look at, and gets much more precise information than the antenna can. In the same way, since a sheath has not yet developed organs of sensation and action, it can only give a vague general sense of what's going on at that level, while a body has such organs and can perceive and act on the plane to which it's attuned. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59862031", "title": "Re: A Question about the subtle bodies", "date": "2026-04-07 12:01 am", "user": "yogaandthetarot", "content": "Thank you Anon for intriguing metaphor and JMG for perfect clarification. It now really makes so much more “sense” to me about the astral body’s equipment, i.e., the bodily senses. And the antenna quality of the mental sheath.<br/>Jill C"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59826191", "title": "Zodiac Garden Guide", "date": "2026-04-06 01:01 pm", "user": "isaac_hill", "content": "I'm very happy to announce that I've published 'The Zodiac Garden Guide: A Manual of Astrological Gardening' wherein I lay out the complete process for designing, planting, and electing a Zodiac Garden. I draw on astrological classics from the last 2,000 years from multiple traditions, get to the root of astrological-botanical correspondences, and share some neglected electional astrology techniques related to gardening. JMG has graciously endorsed the book, and I hope this post is considered appropriate.<br/><br/>I have decided to self-publish on Amazon, which I know has its issues, but it was the best option for me for self-publishing. Since I know some may want to get the book, but not through Amazon, I'll send you a PDF with which you can print a personal copy for yourself if you desire. You can email me at askisaachill@gmail.com<br/><br/>I have already begun work on book on magical gardening for Aeon, which should be out in 2027. <br/><br/>Here's the link: <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0GW7F2KRP\">https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0GW7F2KRP</a>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59835407", "title": "Re: Zodiac Garden Guide", "date": "2026-04-06 04:30 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Congratulations on both counts! "}]}, {"id": "cmt59826447", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 01:26 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,<br/>Could you tell me which planet governs the heart? I want to do planetary charity for persistent heart problems. <br/>Many thanks. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59835663", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 04:30 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The heart is traditionally governed by the Sun, as the brain is by the Moon. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59826703", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 01:33 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "From a druidic perspective, what is a proper burial?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59835919", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 04:32 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Anything that returns the body to the cycles of nature. Embalming and those airtight caskets that try to preserve the body indefinitely are out. Many Druids prefer cremation followed by the scattering of ashes in a natural setting; that's what my late wife chose, for example, and it's what I intend for my remains when the time comes. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59828239", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 02:18 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Does anyone have advice on mitigating the energetic poison of having to live amidst large amounts of plastic?<br/><br/>I read a description somewhere of plastic as a material with an etheric signature of an energy vampire, and it fits.<br/><br/>My garden is surrounded by white vinyl fencing on two sides. For various reasons, including that one section is a reclusive neighbor’s, I can’t currently replace it. <br/><br/>Does anyone have suggestions on natural magic or other practices to mitigate the effects of the plastic? It feels very energetically dead/stagnant in the areas along side it, and the trees and shrubs seem to lack vitality in areas close by it.<br/><br/>I’m especially interested if anyone has suggestions of trees, shrubs, and plants that counteract the plastic or are etherically potent and vital enough on their own to thrive beside it. <br/><br/>Thank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59836431", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 04:32 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't happen to know anything about this, but I'll be interested to hear if anyone else has suggestions. "}, {"id": "cmt59840783", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 05:23 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "OP again: for context, I live in southern New England and the garden is quite dry overall because we are at a 100 ft. elevation above a lake.<br/><br/>Thank you, all!"}, {"id": "cmt59844367", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 06:41 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Linen (as well as cocoon silk) is supposed to act as an etheric barrier. Of course linen fabric would need to be changed after some amount of time. But perhaps the parts of other plants' stems involved in maintaining a boundary with the outside environment, rather than those involved in internal circulation, would also do that, if you made a wall on your side and covered the wall with them. Birch bark seems like it would be the easiest to form into sheets, or sew into overlapping tiles or \"siding\". But I don't know of any bark that would be easy to maintain."}, {"id": "cmt59845903", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 07:14 pm", "user": "zaratozom", "content": "My family’s solution has always been the belief that we need to have a robust mycelial network within our yard will help mitigate the negative effects of petroleum pollution. There have several studies on mushrooms and fungus that basically eat plastic .<br/>That’s why we killed our yard, sheetmulched the hell out of it and grew nothing but native plants . Low and behold, wherever I dig, I see the white mycelium throughout my yard <br/>"}, {"id": "cmt59854351", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 09:34 pm", "user": "milkyway1", "content": "I feel that oftentimes, plants show up where they are needed. On a material level, this could e.g. be plants with robust taproots to aerate and loosen up compacted soil, etc. But I think this also works on other (non-material) levels. I.e. if I were you, I'd closely watch the \"weeds\" which come up the most along the fence - and I'd consider giving them some space to work there, to the extent possible (i.e. without offending other people's sensitivities, and without letting them take over the garden ;-) ). <br/><br/>If any show up which might fit the bill (e.g. particularly vital plants, thriving along the fence), you might be able to talk to them, explain the situation, and enlist their help in a mutually beneficial relationship. And some weeds can be incorporated into an ornamental garden bed, as long as you are willing to be a bit unconventional: for example, to me something like ground elder (Aegopodium podagraria) is actually quite nice below roses or other flowering shrubs (but then I'm weird this way, and most conventional gardeners will tell you it's the pest incarnate... ;-) ).<br/><br/>Anyway, not sure if this helps, but maybe it's worth a try! :-)<br/><br/>Milkyway"}, {"id": "cmt59868687", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-07 01:30 am", "user": "jprussell", "content": "No practical experience to share here, but it popped into my mind, so thought I'd share in case it helps:<br/><br/>It seems, generally speaking, that good material insulators make good etheric insulators. I recently watched a Townsends video on Youtube about making a wattle fence (stick posts in the ground, and then weave flexible sticks around them). To make more permanent structures, a common medieval technique was \"waddle and daub\" - build the wattle as usual by weaving sticks, then coat in \"daub\" - clay-ey mud plus something fibrous (straw, thread, horse manure, et cetera). Such a combo would certainly qualify as materially-insulating, and might work etherically as well - you could build such structures parallel to the plastic fencing, a fence/wall within a fence is how I imagine it.<br/><br/>I have to imagine that using sticks of protective/ethericallly conducive plants would help, but that's speculation. <br/><br/>Cheers,<br/>Jeff"}]}, {"id": "cmt59828495", "title": "Will", "date": "2026-04-06 02:52 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good day JMG and commentariat. <br/><br/>Some occult traditions talk about developing and using Will to overcome our animal desires and nature. <br/><br/>I’d like to think I’ve developed my Will to some extent but there are some aspects of my animal nature that seem to overpower my Will at times. <br/><br/>Taking the advice of Levi, the Will is applied with persistence over time, and not a violent charge ahead.  So the effort continues…<br/><br/>My question is about surrender and where it comes in. I’m reminded of the AA step of admitting we are powerless over some things.  How is the binary of surrender and personal agency/willpower balanced in a middle road?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59836687", "title": "Re: Will", "date": "2026-04-06 04:34 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Your animal nature is also part of your will. The reason that struggling against the animal nature can be so difficult is that when you try to control it, your will is divided against itself. That being the case, slow and easy does it. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59838735", "title": "Re: Will", "date": "2026-04-06 04:54 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you - that gives a new perspective to explore and is quite helpful. "}, {"id": "cmt59855375", "title": "Re: Will", "date": "2026-04-06 10:02 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "My follow up question, if I may, would be about then - transmuting it into something higher, rather than suppressing or overcoming. <br/><br/>For example, the feeling of lust, properly understood and balanced, would be the desire for connection with others, friendship, love, compassion.   The feeling of lust isn’t discarded, just transformed and directed in a healthy way? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59861775", "title": "Re: Will", "date": "2026-04-06 11:53 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Exactly. This is what Plato calls the education of desire. It's a much wiser approach than trying to suppress desires. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59863055", "title": "Re: Will", "date": "2026-04-07 12:19 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Brilliant! Thank you for your time to clarify for me. It’s immensely helpful. Many blessings to you, if you’ll have them. "}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59829775", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 03:30 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG, hope you're doing well!<br/><br/>My question regards the work with spirits/gods from cultures not your own. You see, I'm brazilian, with Spanish and Portuguese great-grandparents. However I feel no connection at all to anything from the spiritual landscape of my own country; Exus, Pombagiras, Orixás and native indigenous spirits and deities mean nothing to me, speak not a word. As a cloistered youth I got my world view mostly from books, and as a self-taught english speaker I soon found myself enthralled by King Arthur tales, Celtic legends, Faery lore and everything British, Welsh and Irish. I love my country's art, culture and literature, don't get me wrong; I don't have a disconnect to my own people and history. However when it comes to the spiritual and the magical, what truly enchants me and gets me to aspire to magic and spiritualy is the british stuff.<br/><br/>As I came to understand, as long as I'm working with a solar system of magic and dealing with GODS, it doesn't matter where they came from, as they exist way above our world; But if I intend to work with earthly entitites, than I have to resort to the local and landbound lore. Is that correct? Do you see any problems at all with connecting and working with celtic deities when not being from the respective cultures? Do you believe we are born where we must to seek our path, in terms of the local \"spiritual landscape?\"<br/><br/>Thank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59836943", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 04:40 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, the place you were born doesn't determine the traditions you should follow, any more than your ethnic background does. Your soul has lived in many places, in bodies from many ethnic groups, and what it resonates with depends on spiritual factors far more than geographical ones! I began practicing Druidry when I lived on the west coast of North America, almost five thousand miles from Britain and in a wholly different ecological and spiritual environment, and it worked just fine. <br/><br/>There's another factor at work here. There's some reason to think that the historic cultures of the British Isles, and of Western Europe generally, are in terminal decline and will not exist for much longer. That being the case, it wouldn't surprise me at all if the traditions and the energies linked to them might be relocating -- and you may be part of the process that finds a new home for them in Brazil. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59838223", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 04:47 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ah, that's very interesting. Can you speak more about the reasons to think that the historic cultures of britain are declining? Does the idea of these energies relocating to Brazil have anything to do with the mythical Hi-Brazil? I was always fascinated by this connection.<br/><br/>Thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59839247", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 04:59 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Demographic collapse combined with mass immigration from hostile cultures. By 2100, unless something changes drastically fairly soon, the nations of western Europe will be majority Muslim, and their existing governments and national institutions will have been replaced by new arrangements more congenial to the new majority. <br/><br/>2) Hmm! I hadn't thought of Hy-Brasil, but you may be on to something. In medieval legend, if I recall correctly, Hy-Brasil was settled by seven bishops who fled from the Iberian peninsula to escape the Muslim conquest under Tariq ibn Zayid. Maybe that's a prophecy...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59840015", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 05:11 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "That's interesting, I saw Hy-Brazil as more of a mythical/magical island (one of many) from Irish mythology. Looks like I have my next research subject!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59850511", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 08:20 pm", "user": "jprussell", "content": "This might be veering well off-topic, but given your enjoyment of Arthurian/British/Celtic lore, I suspect you would very much enjoy Jack Vance's <i>Lyonesse</i> trilogy of fantasy novels. They take place in an archipelago off the coast of Britain/France that is posited as the \"inspiration\" for Hy-Brasil, Avalon, and other mythical isles to the west, but of course that's an artistic conceit to have the excuse to steal shamelessly from a wide swath of medieval lore and create a richly textured fantasy land and culture. Also, Vance's prose is delightfully flowery.<br/><br/>Cheers,<br/>Jeff", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59873551", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-07 02:29 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi Jeff! Very interesting, I heard about Lyonesse before but never knew what it was really about. I'll have a look! Thanks! :)"}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59849999", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 08:17 pm", "user": "jprussell", "content": "Hmmm, that puts a fairly bleak spin on the comparative taking off of Heathenry here in the states vs Northern Europe (other than in Iceland, which seems to be doing better, and perhaps not coincidentally, has been more insulated from the demographic trends on the continent).", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59862287", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-07 12:06 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The Aesir and Vanir are typically foresighted, and appear to be moving operations to a continent where they've already received a robust welcome and don't have to worry about having their worshippers massacred by followers of a religion that considers polytheism to be the worst sin a human being can commit. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59869711", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-07 01:40 am", "user": "jprussell", "content": "Uncomfortably plausible!<br/><br/>It has long struck me as well-past coincidental that the Eddas survived as they did in explicitly Christian Iceland. The kind of thing you might expect a God of lore and wisdom to ensure (::cough, cough:: Woden). Snorri's insistence on preserving the old stories so poetry could keep being made, and even more amazingly, explicitly Heathen poetry getting copied into the <i>Poetic Edda</i> to pass the long winters. Just wild how many myths we still have (even with so much lost!).<br/><br/>It is slightly worrying to read, nodding along with Americans that I mostly agree with, only to have them reveal that they think I'm a devil-worshipper, but still, it still seems better than the plight of Euro-Heathens. I think that there's some important work for American Heathens in the near future, but it remains largely murky to me just what exactly it might be.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59870991", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-07 02:10 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "As Christianity in the US moves deeper into the Second Religiosity, it's going to become a faith of the upper classes and the upwardly mobile, increasingly focused on maintaining some semblance of the social status quo. As that happens, the poor and disenfranchised will turn elsewhere. That's already happening, of course; there's quite a bit of \"trailer trash Wicca\" out there, and as I'm sure you know well, the Heathen scene in the South and the flyover states generally is robust. <br/><br/>It's worth remembering that religions change their political and class affiliations all the time. In 1900 fundamentalist Christianity was overwhelmingly liberal -- William Jennings Bryan, the most radical left-wing Democrat politician in the late 19th century, was also the prosecuting attorney in the Scopes \"monkey trial.\" I expect to see shifts at least as dramatic in the years to come. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59870223", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-07 01:57 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I wonder if the Japanese Golden Dawn scene might be part of this process as well.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59871247", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-07 02:11 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If Japan can survive the converging crises closing in on it, yes. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59830543", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 03:48 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG:<br/><br/>Last week, you advised another person to maintain a magical practice every day, about 30 minutes.<br/>https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/364211.html?thread=59778739#cmt59778739<br/><br/>I pray first thing every morning, when I get out of bed, to the Almighty Creator and Jehoshua the Masiach. Do I assume correctly that this \"counts\" in a similar way?<br/><br/>Thank you for these Magic Mondays, and for all you do.<br/><br/>- Cicada Grove", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59837199", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 04:42 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's certainly a valid spiritual practice, and one I would recommend to anyone who belongs to the religion you do. The effects won't be the same as if you were practicing meditation and ritual, let's say, but you'll still get the effects -- and yes, sheer pigheaded perseverance in that practice will get you very, very far. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59847183", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 07:42 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you very much!<br/><br/>I shall continue my sheer, pigheaded perseverance. :D<br/><br/>- Cicada Grove"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59832335", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 04:07 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Once you get to the root cause of a problem by journaling, what's the next step? I am working through LRM, and have found that the daily recall reliably triggers a very intense anger, no matter what has happened in the day. I did some journaling, worked out that it was fear under the anger, and have finally worked out the root cause. My parents would blame me for anything that happened, no matter how absurd the contortions of facts, logic, and anything else required to do so, and it was very dangerous when I was a kid to correct them, or even just to contradict whatever insane narrative they had come up with (whether or not I knew it at the time). It was easier to just not remember anything, because remembering was dangerous. <br/><br/>I now know the reason for this issue, and probably for my chronic memory problems, among other issues; but I'm not sure what the next step is. I've tried reminding myself that I'm no longer in that position, and that it is safe to remember things. I've still been doing the exercise this whole time, but even knowing why I'm reacting this way, I'm still finding it hard to overcome this emotional issue. Is there a next step I'm missing, or do I just need to sit with this for a while?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59837967", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 04:47 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Sit with it. Let yourself feel the anger, and recognize that it was appropriate and justified at the time. After a while, you'll start feeling what's under the anger. (Anger is always a secondary emotion; we feel angry because that's less devastating to us, especially in childhood, than feeling intense grief, fear, or shame.) Those primary emotions, down underneath the anger, are the motor driving that whole pattern. Once you can feel them, accept them, and acknowledge that the way you were treated was monstrously wrong and that your feelings were wholly appropriate at the time, you can let them flow out of you and reclaim the strengths you had to lock away from yourself back then. "}, {"id": "cmt59841551", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 05:35 pm", "user": "ivn66", "content": "I have nothing of practical value to add to this discussion, except to sympathize; that is to say, your upbringing sounds, at least in this particular way, to mirror my own. Inasmuch as it was nice for me to see others had a similar experience, maybe you'll appreciate the bit of company as I did. I've long been known as the resident space cadet in whatever circle of friends I find myself. The roots of this are not terribly fun memories but temet nosce and such!", "edit_time": "2026-04-06 05:37 pm (UTC)"}, {"id": "cmt59858703", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 11:05 pm", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "Just wanted to say OP, what you experienced was a form of serious psychological abuse, arguably a form of torture. I think it's important for you to acknowledge that serious violence was done to you, to not downplay it, and work through it from there."}, {"id": "cmt59868431", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-07 01:26 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Im doing this work at the moment as well. Similar pattern - anger and sadness ubderneath due to parental maltreatment. Journal every day and allow yourself to feel all of it until theres no more anger and sadness left, until the charge has dissapered around the issue is my advice. But don't be surprised if the next thing jumps out for healing once this one is done! "}, {"id": "cmt59877391", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-07 03:39 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm also going through the situation where I have anger underlain by extreme grief etc.<br/>Thank you very, very much for your steadying comments on this, JMG, now as well as in<br/>a previous MM (https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/355036.html?thread=58775772#cmt58775772).<br/><br/>My whatever-it-is seeps out a little at a time, every so often. A little at a time seems to be the way to go.<br/><br/>- Cicada Grove"}]}, {"id": "cmt59836175", "title": "Wotan", "date": "2026-04-06 04:32 pm", "user": "degringolade", "content": "Just re-read \"Wotan\" by Carl Jung.<br/><br/>Just wondering aloud here, is Wotan here in the US today, or is there another God who is out and about?  I tend to think that Coyote is more subtle than this, but maybe not.<br/><br/>What are your thoughts?<br/><br/>(I just posted my edit of the essay at my place, I don't think that I am violating any copyright, but if I am, would someone set me straight?)<br/><br/><a href=\"https://degringolade.dreamwidth.org/476682.html\">https://degringolade.dreamwidth.org/476682.html</a>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59838479", "title": "Re: Wotan", "date": "2026-04-06 04:53 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I wrote an essay about that very point some years ago: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/the-kek-wars-part-four-what-moves-in-the-darkness/\">https://www.ecosophia.net/the-kek-wars-part-four-what-moves-in-the-darkness/</a><br/><br/>The short form is that as I see it, the divine archetype moving through the deep places of the American mind these days is the Changer, a figure who appears in many Native American traditions, whose task it is to make the world different. He's not necessarily subtle at all about it!"}, {"id": "cmt59842575", "title": "Re: Wotan", "date": "2026-04-06 05:59 pm", "user": "degringolade", "content": "Thanks, I had forgotten about that one: good lord, has it really been eight years?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59845135", "title": "Re: Wotan", "date": "2026-04-06 06:52 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yep. A long, strange trip! "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59838991", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 04:59 pm", "user": "kylec", "content": "All healing hands requests from last week have been fulfilled. If you'd like to sign up this week, just reply or PM me your name and request. Thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59865615", "title": "Healing Hands with kylec", "date": "2026-04-07 12:47 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello Kyle C,<br/>I would very much like to experience your offering of healing hands. I am continuing to work-out to keep muscle mass and improve my stamina as I move into my 60s. I would very much appreciate anything that would assist me in a little stronger muscle recovery time. Thank you.<br/>Mary"}, {"id": "cmt59869455", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-07 01:40 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yes, I would like healing hands this week.<br/><br/>Thank you very much, as always,<br/>Brad"}]}, {"id": "cmt59840271", "title": "See you there", "date": "2026-04-06 05:12 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Just a note -- in celebration of the current Artemis II space mission, when the spacecraft goes around the far side of our nearest celestial neighbor, I'm going to play the Pink Floyd album <i>Dark Side of the Moon</i>. <br/><br/>;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59857935", "title": "Re: See you there", "date": "2026-04-06 10:53 pm", "user": "scottyc", "content": "Nice!  Timely too as I'm six or so minutes late it seems.  Time for the Floyd", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59862543", "title": "Re: See you there", "date": "2026-04-07 12:08 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Definitely time for the Floyd! "}, {"id": "cmt59862799", "title": "Re: See you there", "date": "2026-04-07 12:17 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Just took a moment to check the news. Artemis II went through its 40 minutes of radio silence while the Moon was between the capsule and Earth, and is back in contact with ground control. I suppose you had to be there during the Apollo years to remember just how nervewracking that silence was back in the day, when space travel was brand new and nobody had much idea what might be behind the Moon. <br/><br/>So they're on their way back. Whew. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59869199", "title": "Re: See you there", "date": "2026-04-07 01:37 am", "user": "scottyc", "content": "Thanks for this and the erudite soundtrack suggestion.   Except for your post I would have missed this event and the chance to focus on positive news for a change. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59841039", "title": "Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-04-06 05:25 pm", "user": "ecoprayer", "content": "<a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/tag/prayerlist\">At this page</a> is the full list of all of the non-faith-specific requests for prayer that have recently appeared at <a href=\"https://ecosophia.net\">ecosophia.net</a> and <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org\">ecosophia.dreamwidth.org</a>, as well as in the comments of the prayer list posts (<a href=\"https://drive.google.com/file/d/1k1MLUovBKzARQYliiEYp26ddsPOvkRgo/view?usp=drivesdk\">printable version here</a>, current to 3/13). Please feel free to add any or all of the requests to your own prayers.<br/><br/>If I missed anybody, or if you would like to add a prayer request for yourself or anyone who has given you consent (or for whom a relevant person holds power of consent) to the list, please feel free to leave a comment below.<br/><br/><center>* * *</center><br/>This week I would like to bring special attention to the following prayer requests, selected from the fuller list.<br/><br/><div style=\"\"><br/><br/>May a safe and happy home environment be enjoyed by Laurelmirror, her daughter, and her mother, as well as protection from evil influences. May their family situation be resolved in such a way that Laurelmirror's mother will get a chance to recover physically and mentally from the stresses it has caused; may mother be blessed and invigorated.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1732.html?thread=20676#cmt20676\">Bob W of Lake County, Ohio's</a> treatment for cancer go well so that he may heal and recover as quickly as possible.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/360870.html?thread=59415974#cmt59415974\">Open Space</a> be filled with the strength he needs to heal quickly from his current bout of Chicken Pox; may his will remain strong, that he does not scratch; may he be healed completely, and suffer no scarring in its wake.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/november-2025-open-post/#comment-149490\">Bob Ralston (aka Rasty Bob)</a>, who is in hospice care in Buckeye AZ, and who just lost his wife Leslie Fish, be blessed and find relief from his pain and discomfort; may Bob's heart remain strong. <br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1732.html?thread=18372#cmt18372\">Princess Cutekitten</a>, who has made no comments on any of the Ecosophia blogs for a year now, and hasn't responded to attempts at contact, be blessed wherever she is and in whatever form she may exist.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/359082.html?thread=59206570#cmt59206570\">Cathy N. of St. Marys, Ohio</a> heal and recover from injuries caused by a fall.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=15906#cmt15906\">Dustin, a relative of Brenainn</a>, be healed of a recently discovered heart condition.<br/><br/>May 1Wanderers's partner Cathy, whose cancer has returned, be given the physical and mental strength to fight it, and tolerate the treatment, and may she enjoy a full and permanent recovery.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=14882#cmt14882\">Jule from Iserlohn, Germany</a>, who is experiencing complications in her pregnancy due to an influenza infection, recover and have a pleasant pregnancy and birth.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1314.html?thread=12322#cmt12322\">Larry Mulford</a>, who has entered hospice after a year battling with pancreatic cancer, pass in the smoothest possible manner, and may his wife be enveloped in our love.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/1160.html?thread=12168#cmt12168\">Marko</a> have the strength to seize the opportunities.<br/><br/>May Pierre's young daughter, Athena, be healed from her fatigue and its root causes in ways that are easy, natural, and as holistic as possible.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18134.html?thread=452566#cmt452566\">5 year old Max</a> be blessed and protected during his parents' contentious divorce; may events work out in a manner most conducive to Max's healthy development over the long term.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecoprayer.dreamwidth.org/514.html?thread=2562#cmt2562\">Lydia G. of Geauga County, Ohio</a> heal and recover from prolonged health issues.<br/><br/>May both <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/347398.html?thread=57920774#cmt57920774\">Monika and the child she is pregnant with</a> both be blessed with good health and a safe delivery. <br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/338828.html?thread=56777612#cmt56777612\">Mary's sister</a> have her auto-immune conditions sent into remission, may her eyes remain healthy, and may she heal in body, mind, and spirit.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/18134.html?thread=455382#cmt455382\">Trubujah's best friend Pat's teenage daughter Devin</a>, who has a mysterious condition which doctors are so far baffled by necessitating that she remain in a wheelchair, be healed of her condition; may the underlying cause come to light so that treatment may begin.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/16429.html?thread=392237#cmt392237\">Kevin’s sister Cynthia</a> be cured of the hallucinations and delusions that have afflicted her, and freed from emotional distress. May she be safely healed of the physical condition that has provoked her emotions; and may she be healed of the spiritual condition that brings her to be so unsettled by it. May she come to feel calm and secure in her physical body, regardless of its level of health.<br/><br/>May <a href=\"https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/312140.html?thread=53408588#cmt53408588\">Frank R. Hartman, who lost his house in the Altadena fire, and all who have been affected by the larger conflagration</a> be blessed and healed.<br/><br/></div><div><br/><br/><center>* * *</center><br/>Guidelines for how long prayer requests stay on the list, how to word requests, how to be added to the weekly email list, how to improve the chances of your prayer being answered, and several other common questions and issues, are to be found <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/6373.html\">at the Ecosophia Prayer List FAQ</a>.<br/><br/>If there are any among you who might wish to join me in a bit of <a href=\"https://tunesmyth.dreamwidth.org/1986.html\">astrological timing</a>, I pray each week for the health of all those with health problems on the list on the  astrological hour of the Sun on Sundays, bearing in mind the Sun's rulerships of heart, brain, and vital energies. If this appeals to you, I invite you to join me.</div>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59844623", "title": "Re: Ecosophia Prayer List", "date": "2026-04-06 06:49 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this as always. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59841295", "title": "Horary astrology: resumed", "date": "2026-04-06 05:33 pm", "user": "ivn66", "content": "Hello, JMG, and hello, Ecosophians!<br/><br/>My lingering computer issues have been fixed. To the two among you to whom I owe answers, expect them today or tomorrow. As for the rest of us:<br/><br/>I'm continuing to offer consultations in horary astrology over on my own dreamwidth page, free of charge, in order to help myself practice and to provide a service to the commentariat, from whose activities I have drawn much benefit over the years. <br/><br/>If you have any nagging question for which you'd like to seek an answer in the Heavens, my door is open - not just this Magic Monday, but every day of the week. If you're seeing this comment after the post has closed and would like to ask a question, you may do so at any time. <br/><br/>Thanks to our venerable host and thanks to you all. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59855887", "title": "Re: Horary astrology: resumed", "date": "2026-04-06 10:17 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do you have any advice on how to learn horary astrology?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59879951", "title": "Re: Horary astrology: resumed", "date": "2026-04-07 07:41 am", "user": "ivn66", "content": "[after midnight - JMG, please delete this if desired. Apologies]<br/><br/>Yes. Pick up a copy of John Frawley's <i>The Horary Textbook</i> (as well as William Lilly's full <i>Christian Astrology</i>) and read it a million times. It'll help to have some knowledge of astrological fundamentals going in. From there, just trust your own common sense and make sure you're referring to the text in any doubtful case while you practice, practice, practice. ", "edit_time": "2026-04-07 07:42 am (UTC)"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59842063", "title": "Ariel Moravec Series", "date": "2026-04-06 05:51 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello John,<br/>I arrived a little late to the party regarding your Ariel Moravec books. I have just finished the first two and my library, that had to get them for me through Inter-library loans, has ordered the Carnelian Moon. They are very good, delightful really, and I can see young people enjoying them as well. I  especially like the interaction between Ariel and her grandfather. <br/><br/>Thanks for hosting MM and thanks for the good reads.<br/><br/>Mary", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59844879", "title": "Re: Ariel Moravec Series", "date": "2026-04-06 06:50 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you! I'm delighted to hear this -- and thank you for encouraging your library to get a copy. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59845647", "title": "Ogham Interpretation", "date": "2026-04-06 07:11 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you, as always, for MM.<br/><br/>I am teaching myself to read the Ogham.  I am curious to know if you or the commentariat determined the best way to interpret a yes or no question.<br/><br/>My ability is improving and this question has me a little stuck.<br/><br/><br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59848719", "title": "Re: Ogham Interpretation", "date": "2026-04-06 08:05 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I always did it intuitively, with an eye toward the details of the question. I know that probably doesn't help you at all! "}, {"id": "cmt59851279", "title": "Re: Ogham Interpretation", "date": "2026-04-06 08:32 pm", "user": "jprussell", "content": "I also found this somewhat challenging and usually tried to follow JMG's approach for the most part. I also tended to interpret reversed cards as more likely to mean \"no\" and upright to mean \"yes.\"<br/><br/>In <i>The Runecaster's Handbook</i>, Edred Thorsson recommended an approach with Runestaves for yes/no questions: set out a cloth with a central ring with a diameter of ~8 inches marked on it (or visualize such a ring), take up the staves, think about your question, close your eyes, and let them fall on the cloth. Looking only at the staves that fell in the ring, count the number that are face up (\"bright\") and the number that are face-down (\"murky\") - more brights than murkies means \"Yes,\" and vice versa means \"no.\" Thorsson cautions that this approach works better if you've already gotten comfortable with the Runes for more interpretative questions, so it's not purely a matter of mechanics. I've had some success with this approach, but I almost always lean towards asking more interpretative questions, as I've found that to work better for me, even if a nice, straightforward yes or no would be appreciated.<br/><br/>I mention this because it occurs to me that you could adapt it to the Ogham fairly straightforwardly, especially if you use sticks instead of cards (I've thought about making a set out of popsicle sticks, which I did for my daughter's first Runestaves). Even with cards, though, you could pick a set number of cards to draw (say, five to fit with the symbolism of the Ogham), then interpret more uprights than reverses as \"Yes.\" Like Thorsson said about the Runes, it might be that you have to have a good \"feel\" for your sticks/deck before this would work. I haven't tried this, though, so I don't know whether it would work at all!<br/><br/>Cheers,<br/>Jeff", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59870479", "title": "Re: Ogham Interpretation", "date": "2026-04-07 02:00 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you.  I will try this approach.  <br/><br/>Rooby"}]}, {"id": "cmt59867663", "title": "Re: Ogham Interpretation", "date": "2026-04-07 01:01 am", "user": "slclaire", "content": "The way I ask a yes/no question is to announce to the cards of any deck I am using, before I shuffle them, what the question is and that an upright card equals yes, a reversed card equals no. Then I shuffle as usual, cut the deck as usual, and turn over the top card. If it's upright, the answer is yes; if reversed, it's no. I interpret the card itself as telling me why the answer is yes or no.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59870735", "title": "Re: Ogham Interpretation", "date": "2026-04-07 02:03 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you.  <br/><br/>Sometimes I find myself drawing a card without clearly thinking through the question I am seeking to answer and then I start over.<br/><br/>Thank you for this answer. <br/><br/>Best,<br/>Rooby"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59849743", "title": "Blessing of gardens amd orchards", "date": "2026-04-06 08:17 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "So, yesterday, on Eadter, I planted 3 fruit trees and this year's garden. Do you know any rituals specifically focused on bringing forth agricultural blessings? I have experience in the Modern Order of Essenes system and a good relationship with Jupiter, sky father, Gaia, earth mother, and Mercury, the divine child and intelligence, and can call on theor blessings. <br/><br/>Any specific steps or rituals to ensure the success of this agricultural endeavor would be appreciated. Any blessings you can give would be appreciated - I know you mentioned in one of these magic mondays that you have secret knowledge and rituals you cant share as part of lodges you joined, and mentioned you know how to uncurse livestock. So if there's any rituals to bless orchards and gardens you can't share, then send some of that good energy my way! I'm due south of you, and not too far, if you need to know what direction to send this in.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59863311", "title": "Re: Blessing of gardens and orchards", "date": "2026-04-07 12:22 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Positive energy en route. <br/><br/>Since you've trained in the MOE system, there's a very effective working you can do. Take a bowl of water and charge it with your healing hands, concentrating on the healing energy going into the water. Then sprinkle it on the garden and the roots of the trees. Do this once a week all through the growing season and the results will be excellent. <br/><br/>If you've practiced the Bridge of Light technique from the Essene Master Healer teachings, that's also a very potent method of blessing. Don't neglect the simple methods, though. If you simply bless your trees and plants whenever you go out into the garden, that'll benefit them greatly. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59851791", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 08:58 pm", "user": "kenkyuusha", "content": "Hello JMG! I have several questions so will send them separately to have independent threads. Thank you for this! <br/><br/>if the true will is what leads the soul to seek some experiences and not others, is it fair to say that people who want to kill/rape/hurt other people - they do it because their true will thinks this is what is needed to advance them on their path of spiritual evolution? meaning that there is no way they advance further without first experiencing that? Or they just are not in connection with their true will? I am generally thinking a lot about what we perceive as “evil” - does every soul at some point of its development commit all the evil acts from all the cultures of the world to, kind of, \"collect\" full set of all possible experiences available on Earth by the time it completes its cycle here?", "edit_time": "2026-04-06 09:42 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59863567", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-07 12:26 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, that's a common misunderstanding that Dion Fortune discusses in <i>The Cosmic Doctrine</i> among other places. We encounter evil impulses not so that we should fall in with them, but so that we can use them as \"thrust blocks,\" sources of resistance to allow us to climb above them. If you have an evil desire, that's a form of negative evil, and by knowing the desire and then refusing it you grow in strength and wisdom. If you submit to it instead, that becomes positive evil, and then you generate bad karma and get to suffer the consequences. You have to experience the desire, but you don't have to act on it! "}]}, {"id": "cmt59852047", "title": "on money", "date": "2026-04-06 09:00 pm", "user": "kenkyuusha", "content": "I experience really crazy problems with money for the past year or so, and i feel really stuck. It deteriorated during the last 6 months even more, leading me to situations sometimes where I do not have money to buy food on some days. Mars is afflicted in my cart and Chris Warnock recommended planetary charity. i have completed it. doing 100 affirmations daily “i see many opportunities to resolve my financial situation - for the greater good of everyone concerned”. i do a lot of stuff on the material plane: look for projects, talk to my network etc. and nothing. what is even more strange, even when friends and family decide to support me by offering some money or lending it, for some reason it takes a lot of effort to physically get this money to me. the debt grows and nothing sustainable just comes my way. i wonder if that is just a transition of some sort which i need to accept or could be some curse? as i am at the stage in LRM where i perform the Middle Pillar daily and LBRP is a part of it, I guess it would improve any “bad influence” if that was the case? I do not know if this is relevant, but in all other domains of life things are going quite good for me, I would even say extraordinary good! ", "edit_time": "2026-04-06 10:50 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59863823", "title": "Re: on money", "date": "2026-04-07 12:28 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I would encourage you to do a lot of journaling and meditation on money and the roles it plays in your life and emotions. Very often, if most of life is fine but there's one important area that just doesn't work, that's a message that you've gotten something tangled and wrong in that part of your life and it won't come right until you figure it out. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59852303", "title": "on nickname for magic", "date": "2026-04-06 09:01 pm", "user": "kenkyuusha", "content": "W. E. Butler in his book “the Magician, his training and work” in the chapter 9 on names and sounds writes that it might be very profitable for occult and magical work to use our own name, but then goes on to saying that this is not the name given by parents, but a “nickname” we kind of have to get. the passage does not specify how exactly is this nickname to be obtained and i was wondering where i could learn on how to get my name that i can use for magical work as well as how exactly (in what rituals) to use it. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59864079", "title": "Re: on nickname for magic", "date": "2026-04-07 12:29 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Butler was one of the first occult authors I studied but I don't recommend him these days, and things like this are the reasons why. I've never found this business about a \"magical nickname\" to work, for me or for anyone I've worked with. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59871759", "title": "Re: on nickname for magic", "date": "2026-04-07 02:14 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not OP<br/><br/>What are the other reasons you don’t recommend W. E. Butler anymore? I have read some of his stuff before, and I don’t recall noticing anything that seemed particularly bad, though admittedly I’m not really an advanced occultist.<br/><br/>J.L.Mc12", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59872783", "title": "Re: on nickname for magic", "date": "2026-04-07 02:26 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't own his books any more -- I got rid of them before this most recent move -- so I can't cite you chapter and verse. I simply don't find most of his advice useful, and there are better sources such as Dion Fortune, Gareth Knight, and Israel Regardie. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59852559", "title": "on daily rituals", "date": "2026-04-06 09:01 pm", "user": "kenkyuusha", "content": "i am now dating a girl, and sometimes she stays at my place or i stay at her place. i have mentioned to her that i am studying occultism and \"doing some practices”, nothing more specific than that. she has never seen me actually performing QC, LBRP or MP and vibrating the names out loud. she also has a dog. however i usually perform the rituals in the morning, and she is around as well as her dog. what should be my strategy here? should i just do it as i do alone and let her witness it? or should i just postpone it till later in the day when we stay at each other’s places? i read in the Butler’s book that if two people work together, the effect is greater than 10 people working individually, so maybe i could just get her to practice with me? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59864335", "title": "Re: on daily rituals", "date": "2026-04-07 12:33 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "This is a question that's on my mind these days, as I start thinking about dating again! I'd start by talking to her about it, and giving her a little more of an idea of what your practices amount to. Then the two of you can discuss how to handle this, and it'll benefit the relationship. If she decides she's interested, by all means point her to the books and help her learn, but the choice must always be hers -- it's ***NEVER*** a good idea, or an acceptable one, to push someone else into magical training. Each person has to make that choice himself or herself. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59875343", "title": "Re: on daily rituals", "date": "2026-04-07 03:05 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "It really is never a good idea or an acceptable one to push someone else to do anything. Wish that a lot of activists on both sides of the political spectrum can learn that lesson and spend less time getting other people to do X activity and more time doing X activity themselves. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59876111", "title": "Re: on daily rituals", "date": "2026-04-07 03:30 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Granted! But magic is especially subject to that, since it's such a loaded topic for anyone in our culture, and since blowback from negative magic is so nasty. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59853071", "title": "Aphantasia", "date": "2026-04-06 09:10 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Apologies if you have answered this previously, if there is a way to go about searching past Magic Monday topics it has escaped my notice. I am wondering if you have any input regarding aphantasia, the inability to form mental images. For quite some time now I have considered myself to have aphantasia, as I fit the criteria of being generally unable to bring any kind of imagery into mind. That being said, my mother recalls my having been quite imaginative as a child, and I my experience of dreaming does involve an impression of visual imagery, so I am wondering if perhaps it is less of a constitutional lack of capacity and more of a muscle which has suffered atrophy. Regardless, in my reading so far of your work, it seems that imagination holds quite an important place among the tools of occult practice. Have you encountered any practicing occultists who share such a difficulty, or who have overcome such? Do you know of any methods for strengthening one's ability to visualize? Thanks in advance for your assistance!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59864847", "title": "Re: Aphantasia", "date": "2026-04-07 12:44 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Okay, this is complicated. First, a lot of people think they have aphantasia because they can't create mental images as vivid as a movie on a screen. Very, very few people can do this. Think about your bedroom. Do you remember where your bed is, and where the window or windows are. Think about the place where you work. What does it look like out front? If you can remember these things your imagination is strong enough to do magic. <br/><br/>Second, visual imagery isn't the only kind that matters. Bring all the imaginary senses into play. One trick I learned long ago is to feel, as well as see, the symbols I'm drawing in the air. I imagine a pentagram as being made of five bars of golden metal, cold to the touch and very smooth, which I feel with my fingertips as I slide them over the surface. (My pentagram rituals became dramatically stronger when I started doing that.)<br/><br/>Third, most people's imaginations have atrophied badly because they spend so much time staring into screens. Regular practice will fix that. Think about a red rubber ball. Don't \"visualize\" it, just think about it. Imagine yourself bouncing it off the floor; think about what it feels like when it hits your hand, and the sound it makes when it hits the floor. Do other exercises like that. Imagine yourself walking into the kitchen, getting a beer, and coming back to your chair. Come up with plenty of others. You'll do fine. <br/><br/>For what it's worth, I had a very poor visual imagination when I started doing this work; I naturally think in spoken language, not in imagery. Regular practice did the trick. "}, {"id": "cmt59879695", "title": "Re: Aphantasia", "date": "2026-04-07 05:28 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi OP,<br/><br/>it sounds like we're similar when it comes to visual imagery/aphantasia. I worried about this too starting pathworking, but here is what I did: Take it slow. You'll have good days when images come and other days when they don't. Don't expect anything or be over critical - I could always sense concepts (as in \"there is a rock ahead of me\") but not always see them. Occasionally I get flashes of things or my immediate surroundings. Very rarely I get to see as if with my material senses. The first time that happened was amazing! Good luck :)"}]}, {"id": "cmt59856655", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 10:32 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What is the benefit of balancing the four elements within oneself? Franz Bardon's work seems to place emphasis on this and I wondered how important it is in other systems and how its approached in ritual magic, especially the practices in your books. Does any of your material end up with something like \"elemental equilibrium\" or is this a bad comparison?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59865103", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-07 12:45 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's useful because elemental balance brings mental and physical health. In the systems I teach, ritual methods are used for this; one of the main points of daily practice of the Sphere of Protection ritual, for example, is that it fosters elemental balance. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59856911", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 10:38 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG!<br/>Hope you are well!<br/>I was wondering for a time: (In the GD tradition or any other therefore),<br/>if a ritual fails (for instance a planetary invocation), will there be just no effect, or can it also happen that it turns over completely and has the opposite (or a negative) effect?<br/>Can I guard against this, if that is a possibility?<br/><br/>Thanx in advance...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59865359", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-07 12:46 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Under normal circumstances all that happens is that you get no effect. It takes considerable power, combined with great stupidity and very bad ritual design, to get an opposite effect."}]}, {"id": "cmt59857679", "title": "Tree of Life", "date": "2026-04-06 10:50 pm", "user": "seakingwisdom", "content": "Dear JMG,<br/><br/>I would like to thank you as well as your fellow co-writers—Clare Vaughn and Earl King Jr.—of Learning Ritual Magic. I am currently going through the beginning of the book and enjoying it quite a bit. For the reading and study exercise of the second lesson, I have extracted seven sentences from the first chapter of Paths of Wisdom. This chapter and exercise are my first exposure to the Cabala and its Tree of Life (outside of the brief introduction in lesson one of LRM). I have a few questions about the Tree of Life that I think I can combine into one: Do stones and thoughts dream?<br/><br/>It will be interesting to see where this all leads! (This is my first Magic Monday question.)<br/><br/>Thank you for being so generous with your time.<br/><br/>Sincerely,<br/>SW", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59865871", "title": "Re: Tree of Life", "date": "2026-04-07 12:47 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Earl King Jr.?  A great name; shades of Goethe.  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59866639", "title": "Re: Tree of Life", "date": "2026-04-07 12:53 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "it is indeed. He's still alive and hasn't chosen to make his occult activities public, so I won't blow his cover here. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59866383", "title": "Re: Tree of Life", "date": "2026-04-07 12:52 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're most welcome! \"Claire Vaughn\" was a pen name used by my late wife Sara -- she was responsible for a great deal of the material in that book, and she was always delighted to hear from people who had benefited from it. <br/><br/>As for your question, that's a good one. Stones are in a state of consciousness like very deep sleep; if they dream at all, their dreams are slow and imageless, more like slight shifts of mood than anything else. Thoughts, by contrast, can be said to dream when they aren't reflected in the consciousness of a thinking being, and wake up when they find themselves a mind that will think them. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59873807", "title": "Re: Tree of Life", "date": "2026-04-07 02:45 am", "user": "seakingwisdom", "content": "Thank you Sara!! And thank you too! <br/><br/>My impression is that a great deal of care has gone into constructing Learning Ritual Magic. For instance, I think I've gone deeper into a meditative state while performing the daily recollection exercise than I have in my many attempts at meditating, which is intriguing to say the least and does not feel like an accident. It feels like the right book for someone like me who is at the very earliest stages of this type of development. <br/><br/>That is a fascinating answer to the question! I'll have to think about it and maybe ask a follow-up next Monday. Thank you! ", "edit_time": "2026-04-07 02:52 am (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59877135", "title": "Re: Tree of Life", "date": "2026-04-07 03:38 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The three of us worked our rumps off designing the original course for a magical lodge we led many years ago, and then reworked things on the basis of our experiences. It's been very rewarding to hear from people who've benefited from it. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59858191", "title": "Emile Cohl", "date": "2026-04-06 10:57 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello,<br/><br/>Do you happen to know if the French caricaturist Emile Cohl was involved in occult studies, specifically Crowleyite groups?<br/><br/>Thank you", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59866895", "title": "Re: Emile Cohl", "date": "2026-04-07 12:53 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I have no idea. Anyone else? "}]}, {"id": "cmt59859215", "title": "werewolves/lycanthropy", "date": "2026-04-06 11:24 pm", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "In previous discussions, we've worked out the origin of mummies, vampires and pretas/hungry ghosts -- namely the etheric revenant tradition, or remnants thereof. It's useful to know the occult backstory of these spooky fixtures of popular culture (even if pretas are much more eastern).<br/><br/>So that leads me to wonder, what about werewolves? I've done some research on this, indicating that one possible root is a Germanic warrior tradition of donning wolf-skins as an initiation ritual; but it could also go further back to the Greco-Roman festivals of Lupercalia &amp; Lykaia. But that may not be the whole story.<br/><br/>So what is the occult explanation of werewolves, and their connection to the full moon? It seems like there's some kind of ancient lore encoded in there, but I'm not certain.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59867151", "title": "Re: werewolves/lycanthropy", "date": "2026-04-07 12:59 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oddly enough, one of my more popular posts from 2023 was about that: <br/><br/><a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/our-werewolves-ourselves/\">https://www.ecosophia.net/our-werewolves-ourselves/</a><br/><br/>I also put that into the third of my Ariel Moravec novels, for what it's worth. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59869967", "title": "Re: werewolves/lycanthropy", "date": "2026-04-07 01:47 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "Good stuff, I'll be sure to delve into this, ty."}, {"id": "cmt59875855", "title": "Re: werewolves/lycanthropy", "date": "2026-04-07 03:28 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "ahh, I should've known that the ancient Indo-European koryos would play a key role in this. Also interesting was your observation of the more recent koryos of gangs and internet culture, which parallels observations made by this Barsoomian article:<br/><a href=\"https://barsoom.substack.com/p/dei-the-dispossessed-generation-and\">https://barsoom.substack.com/p/dei-the-dispossessed-generation-and</a><br/><br/>The bit at the end about silver/moon/feminine energy explains the whole thing of silver bullets, quite an insight. But still I wonder, why exactly do they transform in the full moon? There must be something to it. Is it feminine energy bringing on puberty? Or the general \"lunacy\" of lunar influence?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59876879", "title": "Re: werewolves/lycanthropy", "date": "2026-04-07 03:37 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "From a magical perspective, it makes perfect sense. Eliphas Levi argued that the loups-garous in early modern France practiced etheric projection -- their ordinary bodies went into trance while a nearly physical body, able to affect matter directly, roamed the night. The etheric tides are always at their height when the Moon is full. <br/><br/>It's occurred to me that the older tradition may have involved taking on an etheric body surrounding the material one -- that would make sense of the ulfedhnar and berserkr warriors who were seen as terrifying, shadowy half-animal figures. A full moon would be less necessary but still very helpful for that. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59878415", "title": "Re: werewolves/lycanthropy", "date": "2026-04-07 03:48 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "I see, thanks! That also explains why the full moon is seen as a time of energetic strangeness in general.<br/><br/>I searched before asking, and while I didn't find that article, I found another which is relevant, and elaborates on that last point: <a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/the-doctrine-of-high-magic-chapter-14/\">https://www.ecosophia.net/the-doctrine-of-high-magic-chapter-14/</a>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59878927", "title": "Re: werewolves/lycanthropy", "date": "2026-04-07 03:55 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Levi was the writer who set me on the trail of what was actually going on in lycanthropy. His chapter on the subject is well worth reading. "}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59859471", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-06 11:33 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,<br/><br/>What magical methods do you recommend to turn around projected ill fortune? I'm planning a trip to cultivate some important business contacts and my divination for the event is looking bad (Tarot Wheel of Fortune inverted, Last Judgment inverted, 9 of Swords) but cancelling would be a worse problem. I have experience with planetary charity, making talismans and gamahes and doing common candle workings. My goal would be to channel positive influences counteracting problems that might occur. For this kind of purpose do you think a ritual like planetary charity makes more sense, or to consecrate a protective token like a gamahe that I can carry on the trip? Or is there anything specific you would suggest given the outlook per the tarot reading? Thanks.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59867407", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-07 01:00 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In your place I'd do planetary charity, since that has a long and well-earned reputation for averting misfortune, and I'd also make a gamahe or talisman for the same purpose. "}]}, {"id": "cmt59868943", "title": "Divination on the future", "date": "2026-04-07 01:31 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I would love to know on how to divine on the future, specifically the fate of the world in the next 2 or 3 years. Because divination on queries on the future are possible, initially I thought to seek out tarot readers for hire who may agree to this but there is practically no way to verify the readings.<br/><br/>John Michael Greer, I've seen you say that a glimpse into the future is possible for a powerful occultist. Daniel from the Old Testament was able to do exactly this.<br/><br/>How is this done?<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59872015", "title": "Re: Divination on the future", "date": "2026-04-07 02:16 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Well, actually, no -- the Book of Daniel was written many centuries after the events that it chronicled, and it used the setting of the Babylonian captivity to conceal a set of prophecies aimed at encouraging Jewish resistance to the Greek Seleucid government. There have been remarkable prophecies of the future, including some in the Christian tradition, but that's not one of them. <br/><br/>More broadly speaking, you've got two options, the way of the prophet and the way of the diviner. Prophets get their messages from gods, and the gods decide to send the message -- the prophet doesn't get to choose. Diviners do choose, but there's one simple but profoundly difficult requirement for good political divination: you have to stop caring about the outcome. As long as you have any emotional investment in how things are going to turn out, that's going to distort your vision, and you'll end up along with all those astrologers who predicted a Kamala Harris victory in the long, long list of people who got the future wrong. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59874831", "title": "Re: Divination on the future", "date": "2026-04-07 02:54 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Reminds me of how the astrologer Carter predicted peace in Europe on the eve of World War II because of his sympathies towards the Nazi racial ideology. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59876623", "title": "Re: Divination on the future", "date": "2026-04-07 03:32 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's an example that's been much on my mind since I found out about it. It took astrology a generation to recover from that embarrassing failure. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59871503", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-07 02:13 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG. I hope you can relate to this since you're also seeking a relationship.<br/><br/>I have a deeply rooted fear that I may never be able to get married, at least not until a very late age, due to a total lack of success in life where I may have to say goodbye to the idea of healthy babies. I have never been in a relationship. I come from a country where relationships are not allowed in public, and people only marry through suitors, so they never get the chance to experience relationships.<br/><br/>I am shocked to say that the extremely high rising costs of living our country has been experiencing since 2022, have now shifted us to a category of below replacement level births rates.<br/><br/>Also I've noticed that younger women of my generation have zero situational awareness on how to navigate basic relationships unlike their predecessor generations of women. What's going on? The men of my generation are more or less the same but I'm noticing that the women are completely clueless regarding what they want.<br/><br/>Our government is completely dead silent on this issue unlike the near constant coverage countries like Japan and S Korea get for the same issues.<br/><br/>What's going on and what will become of our GenZ generation?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59872527", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-07 02:24 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The Earth has eight billion people on it, and it can support one to two billion for the long term. In most species of animals, overcrowding trips various odd hormonal and behavioral triggers to shut down breeding. I'm pretty sure that the same process among humans is what's causing so many countries to tip over into population contraction. The collapse of relationships is part of that. <br/><br/>The interesting thing is that in some places that process is already beginning to balance out. A recent poll has shown that among American Gen-Z women, for example, more want to become mothers and wives than to become successful in business or other public fields. Young couples with new children are starting to become a common sight again in certain venues, such as churches. That'll slow the decline down, though it probably won't stop it. <br/><br/>For young people who want to get married and raise a family, it's still a rough road, because the population still has to contract considerably. I hope to marry again because I'll be looking for a woman in roughly my own age cohort -- but we'll see.  ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59874063", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-07 02:46 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Wel at least the crop of women in your age group are likable in many ways. I've spoken to women in their 40s and 50s and they're so simplistic, sweet and full of life. They told me they merely met their now spouse in highschool or college and got married \"whereas you youngsters make it so difficult on yourselves that you suffer every relationship you try to flee from\". But if you debate with them on politics, the emotions come out crying in full.<br/><br/>Whereas the women of my generation are extremely quirky, combative, disrespectful, apathetic, lying, manipulative and relying on every response to treat it as a death sentence if we didn't say a word right. It's reflected in their choice of music as well.<br/><br/>They've caused themselves so much depression, anxiety and burnout because of these behaviours that ultimately cause the men they seek to flat out reject them. My smartest friend is convinced that he won't be putting the ring on a woman of his own race and country, preferring the Asian women to his own calling himself a 'passport bro' as his European passport allows it though even he won't any effort to initiate contact.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59877647", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-07 03:41 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, I know the political thing is going to be a land mine when I start dating. We'll see how it works out. As for the women of your generation, er, I think your description fits a lot of the guys as well..."}, {"id": "cmt59878671", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-07 03:53 am", "user": "xcalibur_djs", "content": "Neither male nor female are entirely to blame for the current mess. We're both affected, just in different ways.<br/><br/>I can totally understand why the passport bros seek out a different cultural context, with women who better fit the traditional role. There's alot of factors involved, which I won't get into, but for them it's an escape hatch.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59879183", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2026-04-07 03:57 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Understood. It's a bitterly tangled mess on all sides, and <a href=\"https://www.ecosophia.net/cognitive-collapse-a-first-reconnaissance/\">cognitive collapse</a> driven by social media has a lot to do with it.<br/><br/>", "edit_time": "2026-04-07 03:57 am (UTC)"}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt59873039", "title": "The Agate & the Lake", "date": "2026-04-07 02:26 am", "user": "cs2", "content": "Thank you for advising me on leaving my iron-red agate near the lake where it came from. I want to reiterate that I think there's a god in this lake. She has been a good friend to me and I will miss her. I've said goodbye and told her where I'm going. If you or any of the commentariat who pray to the Welsh or Greek gods would be willing to pray for my safe passage on Wednesday and Thursday this week, I'd appreciate it. <br/><br/>Last greetings from Lakeland. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59873295", "title": "Re: The Agate & the Lake", "date": "2026-04-07 02:28 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Positive energy en route! "}]}, {"id": "cmt59874575", "title": "A Wistful Wish", "date": "2026-04-07 02:52 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I hope/wish that when you get your new hosting service, they and your old host would be able to port the comment threads over to the new place.<br/>There's gold in them thar comment threads, particularly the Magic Mondays.<br/>I had fond hopes of going back and reading through all the Magic Mondays after I retired and had the time, but I'm sure not going to be able to retire before June 1!<br/><br/>- Cicada Grove", "replies": [{"id": "cmt59877903", "title": "Re: A Wistful Wish", "date": "2026-04-07 03:43 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm certainly going to try to arrange that. "}]}]}];